<HEADLINE>
ETHICS PANEL GIVES RARE REBUKE TO HOUSE REPUBLICAN WHIP 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House ethics committee has given a rare private
rebuke to Rep. Tom DeLay of Texas, the Republican whip, for
badgering a lobbying organization over its hiring of a Democrat as
its president, House aides said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The aides said DeLay was chastised for complaining to the
Electronic Industries Alliance last October about its hiring of
Dave McCurdy, a former Democratic congressman from Oklahoma. At the
time, DeLay complained to Speaker Newt Gingrich, and later, at a
meeting of the House Republican leadership.
</P>
<P>
   An aide to DeLay said on Thursday night: ``We got a letter, yes.
We're pleased the matter has been disposed of.'' The aide declined
to comment further on the matter, which was reported on Friday in
The Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
   The Post reported that the letter sent to DeLay was essentially
the same as a memorandum the committee gave House members, officers
and staff this week warning them about linking their official
actions to partisan considerations.
</P>
<P>
   That memorandum was said to have been prompted by DeLay's
pressuring of the electronics trade association last autumn, and
the fallout. Soon after DeLay complained of McCurdy's hiring, and
to show their displeasure at the association's failure to hire
retiring Rep. Bill Paxon, R-N.Y.,, the House leaders postponed
votes on an international treaty the association wanted.
</P>
<P>
   The private rebuke of DeLay was a rare instance in which the
ethics committee, officially the Committee on Standards of Official
Conduct, acted without receiving a formal complaint. Long at the
center of embarrassing episodes involving lawmakers' ethical
lapses, the committee is known to be trying to keep a lower
profile.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
