<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAQ PUTS NUMBERS WHERE HIS MOUTH IS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Give this much to Shaquille O'Neal. He backs up his
boasts.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the week, he was declaring himself an ``all-purpose big
man.'' And through the first two games of the Los Angeles Lakers'
playoff series with Houston, he has indeed done it all.
</P>
<P>
   The 27.5 points and 10.0 rebounds per game were predictable. But
it's the 5.5 assists and 4.5 blocked shots that have made O'Neal a
baseline-to-baseline wrecking ball. He averaged only 2.3 assists
and 1.67 blocks in the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   His passing in particular has impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, it's just a testament to who he is and what he is and
what he wants to be,'' coach Kurt Rambis said. ``He wants to be a
champion, he wants to be a team ballplayer. He understands that in
order to make his game easier, to make us better as a team, to give
us the best chance to win, he has to be able to do that and he has
to be able to do that effectively, and he does that. . . . If they
come and trap him, then you see that he's passing the basketball
out.''
</P>
<P>
   But O'Neal's assist totals don't reflect the true number of
scoring chances he's creating.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the time when the ball comes out, it comes to a guy
who then swings it to another guy who gets a shot,'' Rambis said,
``so Shaq never really gets anything out of it. But if it was
hockey, he'd end up with a lot of (assists) out of that. Even
though numbers-wise he may not get the assist, he is completing the
great offensive play by getting that first pass out when they
double-team him.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Horry said O'Neal's point-guard-like assist totals are an
outgrowth of the Lakers' offensive improvements, particularly
better spacing among players.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're spread out in a way that he can find us now,'' Horry
said. ``It's not all clogged up with people in the middle that he
can't see what's going on. Right now he can see cutters, he can see
guys spotting up. It's a lot easier situation for him. . . . He was
looking to pass all along, but the floor looked so congested he
couldn't get it out.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Return to sender: The NBA's all-defensive teams were
announced Thursday and Horry was shocked to see Utah forward Karl
Malone on the first team _ especially in the wake of the Sacramento
Kings' two straight victories over the Utah Jazz.
</P>
<P>
   ``They need to recount them damn votes for that all-defensive
team, and take his butt off that team,'' Horry said. ``I would put
(Philadelphia's) Theo Ratliff in there before I put him in there. I
think he's a lot overrated on the `D' because he's Karl Malone.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the Jazz's struggles, the Lakers will admit no joy at
seeing their postseason nemesis falter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't do anything for me right now,'' Horry said. ``I
don't even watch other series. The only one I will watch is San
Antonio, because that's our next opponent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
