A6606 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-PORK-1STLD-W     05-14 1424
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-PORK-1STLD-WRITETHRU-885&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO AND TORNADO RELIEF COMES AT A PRICE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to update in 2nd graf, reflecting actual reaching of
agreement; changes $14.6 million to $14.7. Clarifies last sentence
of 3rd graf re ``waste rock and cyanide-treated ore.'' Inserts new
12th and 13th grafs, beginning: The decision is part ... Adds 10
grafs, including optional trim, at end of original text.) (sw/mk) 
 By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK with TIM WEINER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ On the face of it, the seven-year battle over a mining
company's petition to blow a 900-foot hole in a mountain in
northern Washington state and extract the gold inside would seem to
have nothing to do with an emergency bill in Congress to aid war
refugees in Kosovo and victims of the recent Midwest tornadoes.
</P>
<P>
   But that is only on the face of it. In fact, before House and
Senate conferees reached agreement Thursday night on the emergency
spending bill, negotiations were bogged down by the efforts of
lawmakers to cut deals, trade favors and insert pet projects. The
agreement they reached Thursday evening more than doubled the
amount President Clinton had sought for war and disaster relief, to
a total of $14.7 billion, and included a host of non-budget
provisions.
</P>
<P>
   That is where Buckhorn Mountain, in the Okanogan Highlands of
north-central Washington, comes in. So far, Washington's senior
senator, Slade Gorton, a Republican who is running for re-election
next year, has succeeded in attaching language to the spending bill
that effectively overturns a Clinton administration decision to
deny a permit for the mine. The administration has said that mining
would leave far too much waste rock and cyanide-treated ore on
federal land at the mountain, near the Canadian border.
</P>
<P>
   The pro-mining measure, or rider, is just one that members of
Congress from all over the nation are attaching to to the spending
bill. Also included are hundreds of millions of dollars in farm
aid, loan programs for the steel, oil and gas industries, and a
host of other measures.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Richard Shelby, R-Ala., fought unsuccessfully for language
to force the White House to keep the Alabama sturgeon off the
endangered species amendment. Sen. Ted Stevens, R-Ala., did succeed
in adding $3 million for commercial reindeer herders.
</P>
<P>
   Legislation, of course, is often made in ways that are not
pretty, and riders have been around almost since the dawn of the
Republic. But many involved in the fight in the Capitol say they
find something particularly distasteful about the way that this
bill, also intended to provide help for victims of last year's
Central American hurricanes, has been delayed by matters affecting
so many other people whose interests are, to say the least, less
urgent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is about as low as it goes,'' said Marty Hayden,
director of policy and legislation for the Earthjustice Legal
Defense Fund, an environmental group that opposes the Buckhorn
Mountain mining project. ``The supporters of these efforts are
cynically taking advantage of a very real human tragedy, by
including this provision and others like it in a bill meant to aid
victims of natural disaster and war.''
</P>
<P>
   But supporters of the provisions are equally resentful. Gorton,
for instance, who huddled with a mining lobbyist late Wednesday
night outside a Capitol basement conference room, reviewing
proposed language, said that including the rider in a bill that is
unlikely to be vetoed was a perfectly acceptable way of overturning
the administration's decision to block the mine.
</P>
<P>
   The mining company, Battle Mountain Gold of Houston, and a
partner, Crown Resources Corp. of Denver, have spent years and an
estimated $80 million on the permit process, and have obtained
permits from lower agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Gorton criticized the decision by the Interior Department to
block the mining project.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just immoral,'' he said. ``This is not how an honest
government deals with its citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision is part of the administration's effort to overturn
a century-old mining law that has allowed companies to extract
billions of dollars of minerals from federal land and pay no
royalties.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the president is pressing for speedy passage of any
package that will allow the United States and its NATO allies to
fight the war in Yugoslavia and aid refugees, a White House
spokeswoman held out the possibility of a veto and blamed Congress
for ``trying to take advantage of emergency needs in Kosovo and
Central America by loading up this bill with everybody's pet
projects.''
</P>
<P>
   Gorton has strongly defended the project as an economic boon for
a depressed area of Washington, Okanogan County, which has an
unemployment rate of about 11 percent, more than twice the state
average.
</P>
<P>
   Some residents of the area are enthusiastic about Gorton's
support of the mine project, which could employ 140 people for
about 10 years and yield as much as half a billion dollars of gold.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had several bad years in a row in the apples market; the
timber industry is down,'' said Jimmie Dale Walker, the mayor of
Oroville, a town of 1,500 people near Buckhorn Mountain.
</P>
<P>
   Others, including the Confederated Tribes of the Colville Indian
Reservation, whose members live near five streams with headwaters
on Buckhorn Mountain, are bitterly opposed. Many of the critics say
the mine threatens the spectacular qualities that have made tourism
an important part of the local economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people have this kind of star in their eyes that they're
going to get rich on the gold mine, instead of looking at the
natural beauty all around them and working with that,'' said Dave
Kliegman, executive director of the Okanogan Highlands Alliance, a
local environment group.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   For Gorton, the legislative maneuver is consistent with his
strong support for mining and logging companies in his 17-year
career in the Senate. Such moves have earned him the enmity of
environmental groups, including the Sierra Club, whose Northwest
regional director, Bill Arthur, said Thursday that the senator's
``latest back-room deal continued a long line of shameless acts on
behalf of corporate interests to run roughshod over America's
environmental laws.''
</P>
<P>
   The senator's actions on behalf of Battle Mountain Gold have
also inspired ire in his home state, including that of one Seattle
Post-Intelligencer reader who recently wrote to the paper: ``Three
senators from Texas and only one from Washington is surely
unconstitutional.''
</P>
<P>
   In the conference committee, Gorton has so far succeeded in
obtaining language that overturns the Clinton administration's
decision on the mining project, which hinges on a reading of the
1872 law.
</P>
<P>
   That law, signed by President Ulysses S. Grant to encourage
Western development in the pickaxe-and-mule era of mining, still
allows mining companies broad access to federal land for just a few
dollars an acre. Critics, including the Interior secretary, Bruce
Babbitt, say it amounts to a huge giveaway of public resources and
has left a dangerous legacy of 500,000 abandoned mines across the
West.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the debate over the 1872 law is the question of whether a
measure blocking the administration's decision belongs in an
emergency spending bill.
</P>
<P>
   Gorton's Senate colleague from Washington, Patty Murray, a
Democrat, said late Wednesday that his rider was ``the wrong
manner'' to debate the mining law.
</P>
<P>
   ``To address this in the middle of the night in an emergency
bill that seeks to address the Kosovo issue is wrong,'' Murray
said.
</P>
<P>
   And nearly two dozen House Republicans, led by Rep. Sherwood
Boehlert of upstate New York, signed a letter earlier this week
urging that the spending bill be kept free of ``extraneous
provisions'' and riders.
</P>
<P>
   ``The supplemental bills address serious and urgent matters,
including emergency aid for farmers and money for our troops in
Kosovo,'' the letter said. ``Controversial policy decisions ought
to have a full airing on the House floor, and should not be added
into must-pass bills during conference negotiations. This is
particularly true in the case of these supplemental bills, which
address genuine emergencies.''
</P>
<P>
   But other members of Congress seemed prepared to stretch the
definition of what belonged in the bill. ``The question of whether
it's an emergency or not,'' said Sen. Harry Reid, D-Nev., ``is in
the eye of the beholder.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
