<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIRACLE-RECOVERY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMING OUT OF COMA, CRASH VICTIM HEADED HOME TO HEAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY ROBERT MONROE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Keith Mullins shuffled around the halls of the
acute rehabilitation unit at Valley Presbyterian Hospital in the
Van Nuys community of Los Angeles' San Fernando Valley and looked
forward to going home.
</P>
<P>
   To his family, his small steps are nothing short of a miracle.
</P>
<P>
   To Mullins, they are a gift from God _ a second chance at life
after doctors held out little hope he would ever awaken from a
coma.
</P>
<P>
   ``He asked me if I wanted to go with him. I said I wanted to
stay,'' Mullins said of his encounter with the Almighty.
</P>
<P>
   The 55-year-old president-elect of the Mid Valley Chamber of
Commerce suffered massive injuries Jan. 15 when a pickup truck
veered after being cut off and smashed into his Mercedes-Benz.
</P>
<P>
   For six weeks he lay in a coma, family members all but giving up
on prayers that they would ever talk with Mullins again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been at this 20 years. I've seen people wake up out of
comas after a week or two. He was six weeks,'' said Dr. Mark
Romoff, an internist who treated Mullins.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of February, with his wife, Marilyn, at his bedside,
Mullins suddenly came out of the coma and grabbed a photo of the
couple out of her hand.
</P>
<P>
   Then, he kissed it. And the family's hope of recovery was
reborn.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just started off with `There's a glimmer of hope here.' And
it just builds and builds,'' said Marilyn Mullins, 53, who works in
the gift shop four floors below the ward where her husband is
recovering.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone said, `Just sit back and watch the miracle,' and it is
a miracle.'''
</P>
<P>
   Mullins is preparing to go home Saturday, exactly four months
after the crash that nearly cost him his life.
</P>
<P>
   He will take a wheelchair to the hospital front door and plans
to walk the rest of the way with help.
</P>
<P>
   Mullins' family had all but given up hope he would emerge from
the coma, approving a recommendation by the hospital not to
resuscitate him if he should fall into cardiac arrest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't even imagine putting him in that state. You're
being told every day, `It doesn't look good. It doesn't look good.'
At that point we really didn't know,'' said his daughter Theresa
Mullins, a Studio City resident.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Mullins sustained what's called ``brain shearing'' in
which a whiplash action ruptures blood vessels in the brain. That
triggered a stroke.
</P>
<P>
   Mullins has recovered a great deal since the day he grabbed the
photo from his wife. But he still has a long way to go.
</P>
<P>
   Directions like ``shave'' and ``brush teeth'' hang on signs at
the foot of his bed.
</P>
<P>
   Mullins' speech remains somewhat clipped and often ends in
emotional stammers.
</P>
<P>
   In the darkest period during the coma, Mullins said he believes
he saw God, who gave him a choice to live or die.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Mullins and the couple's three adult children prayed, as
did his friends.
</P>
<P>
   Romoff, who oversaw Mullins' treatment, recommended
do-not-resuscitate status to the family.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked about if we needed to do something else to keep him
alive, that we shouldn't do that because I thought there was going
to be no meaningful quality of life,'' Romoff said.
</P>
<P>
   Family members visited Mullins every day, first at Northridge
Hospital Medical Center, where he was in intensive care for six
days, then at Valley Presbyterian.
</P>
<P>
   The kiss led to other milestones. Keith Mullins' hand took a
brush to his hair. One day, he yelled his first word: ``nurse.''
</P>
<P>
   The firsts have continued since. He was moved from custodial
care to the acute rehabilitation unit and relearned more movements,
more words.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn gives credit for her husband's recovery to the faith of
hundreds of well-wishers, prayers and a special Mass said for him
at St. Elisabeth's Church.
</P>
<P>
   Nurse Manager Jamie Terrence credits the constant stimulation
his family gave him for pulling him out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another family, this wouldn't have happened, no way,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Mullins will continue to receive physical therapy on an
outpatient basis. And the chamber is holding open the seat to which
he was elected before the crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he went through this, we just wanted to support him,''
said chamber Executive Vice President Nancy Hoffman. ``We didn't
want to throw in the towel.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
