<SLUG> BC-BBA-CLARK-RANGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLARK STILL DISAPPOINTED ABOUT DEPARTURE FROM RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The once-anticipated return of first baseman
Will Clark went largely unnoticed last night at The Ballpark in
Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   The 15-day disabled list _ no stranger to Clark _ will do that.
</P>
<P>
   Clark remains sidelined with a fracture to his left thumb
suffered April 18, yet another injury stings Baltimore's
35-year-old infielder.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers hurt his pride.
</P>
<P>
   Clark, who spent the previous five seasons with the Rangers,
never wanted to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's no secret at all,'' Clark said yesterday afternoon
while sitting in the unfamiliar surroundings of the visitors'
clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Clark became expendable once the Rangers signed Rafael Palmeiro
on Dec. 1, and that still gnaws at the productive-when-healthy
player.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I got,'' said Clark, who later signed a two-year
contract with the Orioles worth $11 million. ``I was trying to get
a deal done pretty much from the start. I kept getting, `Wait.
Wait. Wait.' I waited to file for free agency until the very last
day, pretty much the last hour for that matter. Then, I was told to
wait until Randy Johnson signed.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers failed in their pursuit of the left-hander for their
rotation, and Palmeiro made his bid to return the next afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Randy signed on Monday,'' Clark recalled. ``Rafael signed on
Tuesday, and I have yet to meet with Doug Melvin after all that
waiting.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers general manager acknowledged regret about how the
events unfolded, but Melvin and then club president Tom Schieffer
called and explained their reasoning to Clark, Melvin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a real tough phone call, and I told him why,'' Melvin
said. ``I think he was obviously hurt, and he had a reason to be
mad.''
</P>
<P>
   Melvin planned to meet with Clark's representative, Jeff Moorad,
the day after signing Palmeiro.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he owed me the courtesy to sit down with me,'' Clark
said. ``All that does is just illustrate that this is not a game.
Baseball is a business. I understand that.''
</P>
<P>
   Disappointed? Yes, Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   Bitter? No.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not bitter,'' Clark said. ``I understand that this is a
business.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark, who was hitting .370 before being placed on the disabled
list, expected a warm reception upon his return to The Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   ``How could they not? I laid my blood and guts out there for
them,'' Clark said. ``They don't make 'em like this anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   The physical injury robbed him of even that.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
