<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOGGERS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOGGERS NEED COURT TO SETTLE RUNNING FEUD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS FISCUS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GILBERT, Ariz. _ It sounds like a Dr. Seuss book, which told of
a north-going Zax and a south-going Zax bumping into each other and
both refusing to budge.
</P>
<P>
   But this isn't a children's story. Or is it?
</P>
<P>
   Meet the plaintiff: Brenda James. The 42-year-old loves to run
in the Islands community in Gilbert.
</P>
<P>
   Meet the defendants: the husband-and-wife team of Rhett and
Barbara Muller. They also run in the Islands, in the opposite
direction.
</P>
<P>
   When James and the Mullers have met on the street, all have
refused to budge.
</P>
<P>
   So one got a court order against the others.
</P>
<P>
   The Mullers have to stay 10 feet away while James runs, or they
can be arrested.
</P>
<P>
   James told the court that the couple runs side by side and
refuses to move over, or to run single-file, to allow her to pass.
She said they force her into the street.
</P>
<P>
   There have been some elbows exchanged, and some words. She says
she's been spit on.
</P>
<P>
   James went to Gilbert Municipal Court and was granted an
injunction against harassment. The Mullers can't contact her by
phone or in writing.
</P>
<P>
   Or when she's running.
</P>
<P>
   The defendants ``shall not come within 10 feet of plaintiff
while she is running,'' according to the April court order, which
is good anywhere in the United States for one year.
</P>
<P>
   The runners also were ordered to run against the flow of
traffic, which could keep them on opposite sides of the street or
running in the same direction.
</P>
<P>
   If the Mullers violate the order, they could be arrested and
prosecuted for interfering with judicial proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Judge David Phares granted the injunction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ideally, I'd like them to sit down on the lawn, drink their
Gatorade and work out a solution,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If that isn't possible, he prefers they come to court for
mediation or a ruling by a judge ``rather than having people handle
these kind of debates physically.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our courtroom is not THAT crowded,'' he adds.
</P>
<P>
   The tiff seems out of place in the Islands.
</P>
<P>
   The Gilbert community near McQueen and Warner roads is built
around man-made lakes, where ducks strut along the water near fancy
homes with perfect lawns and nice cars.
</P>
<P>
   The streets and sidewalks are wide. Bike paths are plentiful.
</P>
<P>
   Numerous calls seeking comment were not returned. Notes left at
the Muller and James homes went unanswered.
</P>
<P>
   While the court order is recent, the feud has been running for a
while.
</P>
<P>
   In court records, James said that on March 22, James said
Barbara Muller was ``running towards me forcing me into traffic''
and James says she accidentally hit Muller.
</P>
<P>
   On April 1, the couple were running toward her and wouldn't
move, ``forcing me into traffic and Rhett and I hit each other in
passing.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Another injunction had been issued in September and served to
the Mullers by Gilbert police. James told the court at the time
that on two different days she was screamed at. Once, she said, one
of them spat in her face.
</P>
<P>
   The court had asked what harm could occur if the injunction was
not granted.
</P>
<P>
   James wrote: ``more yelling and screaming and spitting, maybe
physical hitting or tripping.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; An October hearing was set; the judge sent the three to
mediation. Terms were worked out where James would essentially be
left alone, but she says those terms were violated, so she went
back to the court.
</P>
<P>
   The injunction is now in effect for a year.
</P>
<P>
   And jogging is supposed to be relaxing.
</P>
<P>
   John Crawford is an associate professor specializing in conflict
resolution in Arizona State University's Department of
Communication.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pointless, relatively childish act,'' he said of the
dueling joggers. ``Absolutely childish.''
</P>
<P>
   He also calls the case ``absolutely fascinating.''
</P>
<P>
   He likened the dispute in some ways to road rage, where a minor
act can erupt into a case of ``I'll teach you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like two little boys pushing each other in the shoulder .
. . pretty soon there's blood on the wall,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   To Crawford, the case also reflects a problem with society:
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're running to the law and running to outsiders
increasingly rapidly. `I'm going to tell the cops on you.' `I'm
going to tell the courts on you.' It's another very bad sign of
things we're doing badly'' as a society.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Appleton of Tempe runs every day. He sometimes comes across
teens walking on the sidewalk who won't make room for him, or cars
whose drivers don't give him the right of way.
</P>
<P>
   But the fact that the dispute is with fellow joggers, he said,
is a shock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Typically, you go by, you lift up your hand, you say `hi,' you
do something,'' he said, and the natural thing would be for the
couple to fall into single file. ``It's really kind of that
runners' code.
</P>
<P>
   ``Runners aren't hockey players,'' he adds. ``They're nice,
gentle people.'' &QL; 
Chris Fiscus can be reached at (602) 444-7942 or by e-mail at
chris.fiscus(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
