<HEADLINE>
X'S AND O'S IMPORTANT, BUT GALAXY SHOULD FOCUSON W'S
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; If some Galaxy players think new coach Sigi Schmid's X's and
O's are better than former coach Octavio Zambrano's, they had
better start showing it soon. Dominating games and creating more
scoring chances are nice, but unless you win, game plans and
strategies mean nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's 2-1 loss to Kansas City wasn't embarrassing in
itself, but the situation made it so. The Wizards were 0-7 and had
scored only two goals while giving up 12 before their victory over
the Galaxy.
</P>
<P>
   Galaxy players, who have scored a mere four goals going into the
Kansas City game, talked all week how they were on board with the
game plan. Ever since Zambrano was fired, the players have praised
Schmid for his communication skills, his adjustments and his
game-simulated practices.
</P>
<P>
   But what is hard to fathom about this 4-4 team is why the
players would praise Schmid in a way as to suggest that Zambrano
wasn't worthy of such compliments.
</P>
<P>
   One thing is clear after speaking with players and front-office
people: Zambrano wasn't a communicator. Not all the players thought
that, but several did. The knock on Zambrano is that he didn't have
a game plan, didn't adjust well and didn't get along with the
foreign players.
</P>
<P>
   At least on the record, those were some of the reasons Galaxy
president Tim Leiweke gave for Zambrano's firing three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Respect? Adjustments? If those are the reasons, then the players
need to answer a few questions:
</P>
<P>
   __ If Zambrano's preparation and strategy were so poor, how did
the team manage to win 24 games and score 68 points _ a MLS record
_ last season? And just how did the Galaxy score a league-record 85
goals?
</P>
<P>
   __ And if his halftime adjustments were so bad, how did the
Galaxy finish with the league's top-rated defense last year?
</P>
<P>
   This isn't to downgrade Schmid, because enough credible people
believe if anybody can turn this team around, it is him. But it has
to make you wonder why the players suddenly feel better coached
now, or better prepared now. It seems the players should be more
concerned with before than now.
</P>
<P>
   As in: Why don't they score more goals as before or win games as
they did before?
</P>
<P>
   __ Cup talk: As part of the MLS's qualifying for the 1999 U.S.
Open Cup, the final two ``play-in'' games are scheduled for
Saturday, when New York/New Jersey faces Miami and the Galaxy hosts
Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado was the first team to play its way into the tournament
by defeating Kansas City on April 17. The loser of the three
``play-in'' games with the most MLS points as of June will also
qualify.
</P>
<P>
   __ Gotta be the stadium: The only chance soccer has to rival
other pro sports in this country is to build soccer-specific
stadiums similar to the one Columbus will introduce Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The Crew, which previously played at Ohio Stadium, built the
first soccer-only venue in the U.S., fittingly named ``Columbus
Crew Stadium.''
</P>
<P>
   The 22,500-seat venue is built so fans will feel on top of the
field, similar to many stadiums in Europe. There will not be much
space between the touchline and the fans, which should make for
good television, especially when the stadium is filled to capacity.
</P>
<P>
   The first game at Columbus Crew Stadium will be televised by
ESPN2 at 4:30 p.m. on Saturday. The Crew hosts the New England
Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   __ Looking for help: Galaxy public relations coordinator Luis
Garcia confirmed that the team is inviting strikers Alejandro
Sequiera and Mickey Trotman to training camp next week.
</P>
<P>
   Sequiera, formerly of Tampa Bay and a Costa Rica native, could
replace seldom-used El Salvadoran Jaime Caicedo as the Galaxy's
fourth foreign player. Trotman, released by Dallas, has shown signs
of becoming a talented scorer in MLS.
</P>
<P>
   Schmid said he likes Caicedo, but carrying him is more of a
burden than an asset.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a talented player, but he's only 18,'' said Schmid.
``When you're only allowed four foreign players, it's important
that all those foreign players are making an impact on your team.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Tough times: It was easy to attribute the Galaxy's success
last season to Welton and Cobi Jones. Jones led the team in scoring
with 19 goals and 13 assists. Welton finished second with 17 goals
and 11 assists.
</P>
<P>
   One can just as easily attribute the team's slow start to the
same duo. Welton is scoreless and Jones has just one goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're more disappointed than anybody,'' Schmid said.
``I'm sure Cobi and Welton would like to have more goals at this
point. Welton had two good chances and Cobi had one very good
chance last week against Kansas City.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
