<HEADLINE>
POLICE RESUME SEARCH FOR MISSING TEEN AFTER TIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BENITA Y. WILLIAMS  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Police resumed their search Thursday for a
missing girl after receiving an anonymous tip that her body was at
a Kansas City area lake.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star received written information indicating
that Crystal Kipper's body was under high water near a bridge. The
information was given to police.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City detectives and officers from the Clinton County
Sheriff's Department, the Missouri Water Patrol, Missouri
Department of Conservation and Clay County Park Rangers were
involved in a five-hour search Thursday that yielded nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're trying to do is take our best guess and get it
narrowed down to two or three areas and then start looking,'' said
Kansas City Police Sgt. Tim Witcig.
</P>
<P>
   Officers Thursday said the tipster's description fit at least
five areas at Smithville Lake including some dry spots flooded
recently by heavy rains.
</P>
<P>
   Witcig said that without more details police will have to wait
for the lake to recede to resume the search.
</P>
<P>
   Witcig said it was unclear whether the tip meant Kipper's body
was in the lake or buried on a flooded area that once was shore.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could be out here for nothing,'' he said. ``Just as soon as
we don't check this out, that will be where she is.''
</P>
<P>
   Police have received countless tips on Kipper. They have
conducted several searches. They had never searched Smithville
Lake.
</P>
<P>
   Kipper, 18, vanished Feb. 24, 1997, after her car broke down on
Interstate 29. Platte County authorities have classified the case
as a homicide, though no body has been recovered.
</P>
<P>
   The only suspect in the case, John E. Williams, was found hanged
in his Jackson County, Mo., jail cell on April 24. Prosecutors said
they were days away from charging Williams with Kipper's murder.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-14-99 0018EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990514.0009 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 00:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6615 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-SARAZEN-HNS &LR;      05-14 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-SARAZEN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EDDIE SEFKO  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING _ Byron Nelson had grown to love his annual meetings with
Gene Sarazen on the first tee at Augusta National.
</P>
<P>
   On the morning of the first round of the Masters, Nelson and
Sarazen would act as ceremonial starters, hitting the first swats
off the tee. It had become tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember the year when Gene turned 90 and he told me that
was the last time he was going to do it,'' Nelson said Thursday.
``Then this year, he's 97 and still doing it. He was like an old
fire horse. He was always ready to go.''
</P>
<P>
   One of golf's original thoroughbreds in spite of his slight
build, Sarazen died Thursday from complications of pneumonia. The
man who hit the most famous shot in Masters history _ a double
eagle on No. 15 in 1935 _ had been talking with friends in the golf
business as recently as last week before suddenly falling ill.
</P>
<P>
   Sarazen died peacefully in Naples, Fla., members of his family
said in a statement released through the PGA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   Sarazen, who is credited with the invention of the sand wedge,
won 38 tour titles and seven major championships. He was the first
player to complete the career Grand Slam _ winning all four of
golf's major championships over the course of 13 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got to meet him a couple of times at the Masters and sat
next to him for a delightful lunch one day this year,'' said Tiger
Woods. ``It's a sad day because he was such a great man and a great
ambassador of golf. To have two great men of golf leave us in a
two-year stretch (Ben Hogan died in July 1997) is tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Sarazen was one of the last remaining links to golf's early
roots in America. Nelson, 10 years Sarazen's junior, said he will
never forget the times when he was considered the young pup on the
golf scene during the 1940s.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were four players of history in golf back in the early
days,'' Nelson said. ``You had (Walter) Hagen, (Francis) Ouimet,
Sarazen and (Bobby) Jones. So that's an end of that era. And that's
a nostalgic thing to think that Gene has had good enough health to
be here this long. He almost made it for one whole century.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first became interested in golf and was hacking it
around, his name was very prominent. When I learned to play, I kind
of started the new, modern type of playing where you use the feet
and legs, like they do today. And Sarazen played the old school of
hitting against a stiff, straight left leg.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before I ever met him, Gene said, `Nelson is never going to
make a good player because he uses his feet and legs too much.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, some people might say I played all right. But years
later, we met and became good friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Sarazen is a charter member of the World Golf Hall of Fame and
was the first winner of the PGA Tour Lifetime Achievement Award in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   Sarazen will be remembered as a golfer. But he also was a
straight shooter who never left it unknown where he stood on any
subject. Nelson remembered a vignette from the 1945 PGA
Championship at Moraine Country Club in Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   ``In those days, you kind of got paired according to the gallery
and so forth,'' Nelson said of what was then a match-play
tournament. ``And Gene said he wanted to play Nelson in the first
round because he either wanted to stay all week or go home on the
first day. So unfortunately for Gene, he went home on the first
day.''
</P>
<P>
   Sarazen's wife, Mary, died in 1986 after the couple had been
married 62 years. They are survived by two children, Mary Ann, of
Marco Island, Fla., and Gene Jr., of Delray Beach, Fla., seven
grandchildren and six great-grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Sarazen lived the last years of his life on Marco Island. A
funeral Mass will be held at the San Marco Roman Catholic Church on
Marco Island at 10 a.m. Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The comforting thing about it, as far as I'm concerned, is
that Gene went on and on and then he was gone,'' Nelson said. ``I'd
like to think that my life could be like that _ not having to go
through any illness or long seizure of cancer or whatever.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I think a lot of people should feel happy that it happened
this way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
