<SLUG> BC-Watch-Seniors-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROGRAM HELPS POLICE SERVE SENIORS, OTHERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MALCOLM GARCIA  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Kansas City Police Officer Everett Babcock
knocked gently on Ruby Franks' door on East Sixth Street, just
below the sign: ``Do not pet my dog. If you pet her I will give you
paper towels to clean her puddles off the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have your sticker,'' Babcock said when Franks answered the
door in her wheelchair. He rubbed a sticker marked ``SENIOR WATCH''
on a pane of glass near the doorknob, stepping carefully around a
dachshund sniffing his feet.
</P>
<P>
   Franks, a 68-year-old multiple sclerosis patient, was one of
several people Babcock visited recently as part of the Senior Watch
program sponsored by the Police Department's East Patrol Division.
</P>
<P>
   Program members such as Franks provide police with their phone
numbers, medical histories, family contacts and the names of people
nearby who can let police into their homes in emergencies. The
information, entered into a computer, is accessible only to police.
</P>
<P>
   ``I needed to join,'' Franks said. ``I'm in this chair. I'm by
myself. There may come a time I'll need some help.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite its name, the program is not limited to seniors. People
of all ages with serious medical problems may participate.
</P>
<P>
   Members are given small stickers for front doors. The stickers
have identification numbers that correspond to the members' names
in the database. Police can get immediate medical and contact
information by calling the station.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get a lot of calls to do resident checks on the elderly,''
said Babcock, who started the program in January. ``A neighbor
calls and says they haven't seen Mrs. So-and-So and sends for us.
We knock on the door and no one answers. Or we kick it in, which
causes one more problem for the occupant. Or we leave and if they
need help they could die.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be so frustrating to be there and you can't get in
and you don't know the first thing about them. All you needed was
information. This gives us the information.''
</P>
<P>
   Since January, 280 persons have joined the program, and the
Police Department is considering implementing the program citywide.
</P>
<P>
   ``The response has been really good,'' Babcock said. ``It's been
talked about on Internet chat rooms, and we've gotten calls from
out of state. We've had to turn people away who don't live in East
Patrol.''
</P>
<P>
   The Metropolitan and South Patrol divisions recently picked up
the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``In two days we had 200 people verbally commit to the
program,'' said Officer Lindy Belton of South Patrol. ``I can't
find anybody who is not interested. One man called for himself, his
wife and three neighbors. Now we can protect people who are really
alone with just a phone call.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, police have used the program a few times in nonemergency
situations.
</P>
<P>
   One concern the department had when starting the program was
whether the stickers would alert criminals to vulnerable people.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a 50-50 kind of deal,'' Babcock said. ``The sticker helps
the resident, but if someone comes to the door they'll know. That's
why we kept it (the sticker) small.''
</P>
<P>
   The ages of those in the East Patrol program vary widely. The
oldest member was born in 1902, the youngest in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good idea,'' said Marla Moore, administrative
coordinator for Minute Circle Friendly House, an agency that works
with the elderly on the city's east side. ``This is a very
drug-infested area. Most of the seniors we work with don't have
family. It's just them. With the police working with them, it can
only make things better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-14-99 0021EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
