<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 00:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6618 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEN-UNIBEAT-COLUMN-LA     05-14 0535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-UNIBEAT-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERIENCE COUNTS FOR HUBER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If there appears to be a maturity in Ditta Huber's game and
confidence in her step, it's because USC's top singles player has
been there.
</P>
<P>
   She's 23, which is almost ancient by tennis standards. She will
be among the elderly when the Trojans step onto their home court
for Saturday's NCAA Regional at 2 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The women's regionals begin Saturday at various national sites,
including USC, UCLA and Pepperdine. (UCLA also is hosting a men's
regionalthat began Friday and continues Saturday.) Huber is one of
the area players to watch.
</P>
<P>
   Seven years ago (or a lifetime ago, as she says), Huber won a
Junior National doubles tournament with partner Lindsay Davenport
and beat Davenport to win the Southern California sectionals. She
also won the prestigious Easter Bowl by defeating Annie Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Davenport is ranked in the world's top 10. Miller was ranked as
high as 41st before quitting the tour to attend college at
Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Huber's teen-age success prompted her to attempt her dream of
playing on the women's professional tour (as an amateur). She
played mostly qualifying and satellite events in places like
Midland, Texas, and Mexico, Singapore, Thailand, China and Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was enjoyable. I had a good time,'' she said. ``But it's a
struggle. It's a very different lifestyle.''
</P>
<P>
   USC is ranked 10th. If the Trojans defeat Drake on Saturday,
they move to Sunday's final, possibly against San Diego, whose top
singles player, Zuzana Lesenarova, is the ITA's top-ranked singles
player.
</P>
<P>
   Each regional champion advances to the NCAA Championships in
Gainesville, Fla. Here are other area players who could lead their
teams to Gator country:
</P>
<P>
   __ Amanda Basica and Annica Cooper, UCLA:For three years the
Bruins wanted Basica to be their top singles player, but a severe
shoulder injury has prevented her from taking that role. Cooper has
stepped forward, but the two remain the top doubles team.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper, a junior, has been only too happy to take over the No. 1
spot, saying the better competition has made her a better player
since coming to UCLA from Chicago and starting her career at No. 3
singles.
</P>
<P>
   This season has been rocky for Cooper. Working on a new
one-handed backhand cost her some early-season victories. Now,
``I'm catching up with the other girls.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA, ranked seventh, opens against Western Michigan on Saturday
at 9 a.m. A victory sends the Bruins into Sunday's final with
either South Alabama or Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   __ Angela Lawrence, Pepperdine: The senior, the No. 8-ranked
Waves' top singles player the past two years and top doubles player
her entire career, is trying to become the school's second
four-year All-American, following Janna Kovacevich (1988-91).
</P>
<P>
   So far, Lawrence is ranked 31st in singles and seventh in
doubles with Ipek Senoglu. She defeated Lesenarova on April 25 in
the West Coast Conference championships.
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine opens Saturday against Boston University at 11 a.m.
The final is Sunday at noon against either Louisiana State or Ohio
State.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
