<SLUG> BC-ADOPT-CHINA-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUPLES DEPART CHINA DEMONSTRATIONS WITH NEWLY ADOPTED CHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PHILLIP O'CONNOR  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Leawood, Kan., residents Scott and Kim Tucker
could interpret only one of the slogans being shouted by the mob
demonstrating on the streets below their 14th floor hotel room
earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``American killers. American killers. American killers.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple had traveled halfway around the world to Guangzhou,
in southern China, on a mission of love _ to meet and experience
the culture of their first child, Lillie Gwynne Tucker, before
returning with her to America.
</P>
<P>
   But in the process, the Tuckers and 12 other adoptive families,
including Damon and Joyce Sickel of Kearney, found themselves
temporary prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   Outside their hotel, tens of thousands of demonstrators filled
the streets and surrounded the adjacent U.S. Consulate to protest
the NATO bombing of the Chinese embassy in Belgrade, Yugoslavia.
NATO called last week's bombing which killed three Chinese
officials accidental.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Tucker at times videotaped the demonstrators, many of whom
arrived in buses. The state-run Xinhua News Agency reported that
the demonstrations in Guangzhou involved tens of thousands of
students from more than 10 universities who converged on the U.S.,
British, French, Italian and Dutch consulates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty tense,'' said Scott Tucker, who was eventually
warned by hotel staff to stay away from the windows. ``We really
didn't know what was going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting information was difficult.
</P>
<P>
   The couple watched Chinese news reports on television but found
the language barrier insurmountable. The hotel staff couldn't
provide many answers.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with the adoption agency also were in the dark.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, someone saw a CNN report about the bombing. They also
saw video of Chinese protesters attacking the U.S. Embassy in
Beijing and setting fire to a building in the U.S. consulate
compound in Chengdu.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that point, we were pretty nervous,'' Tucker said.
</P>
<P>
   Confined to the hotel, the Tuckers whiled away the hours talking
by telephone to relatives back home and enjoying Lillie.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until someone with the adoption agency contacted
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright that things began to move.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the consulate came to the hotel to give the
families visas.
</P>
<P>
   The group eventually fled the hotel in a bus with covered
windows and drove to the airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a bit unnerving to say the least,'' Scott Tucker
recalled Thursday afternoon, moments after arriving at Kansas City
International Airport. The Sickels arrived at KCI on a later flight
with their new daughter, Jasmine.
</P>
<P>
   When the Tuckers appeared at the airport, Kim Tucker held
1-year-old Lillie close to her chest while relatives and friends
reached out to touch the latest addition to the family. Lillie,
dressed in a silky red robe and pants, seemed unaffected by the
cheers, balloons and television lights.
</P>
<P>
   She quickly warmed to her 4-year-old cousin Kylie Burfeind who
grabbed Lillie's hand and wouldn't let go.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good to be home,'' Scott Tucker said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
