A6621 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Quake-KCK-KAN &LR;      05-14 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Quake-KCK-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINOR EARTHQUAKE RATTLES KANSAS CITY, KAN. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK WIEBE  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ An earthquake briefly shook parts of Kansas
City, Kan., at 9:18 a.m. Thursday, jangling some nerves, damaging
one structure, forcing the evacuation of several buildings, but
injuring no one.
</P>
<P>
   By California standards, it was a small earthquake. But in this
area, where earthquakes are rare, the tremor triggered dozens of
phone calls to police, news agencies and Wyandotte County's Unified
Government.
</P>
<P>
   It was, after all, the first earthquake in many years that
caused noticeable tremors in the Kansas City area, according to Don
Steeples, a geophysics professor at the University of Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's quake might not have been felt outside of Kansas
City, Kan. Dispatchers at the Johnson County Emergency
Communications Center and the Kansas City Police Department
communications unit didn't receive any reports of tremors.
</P>
<P>
   Steeples said area residents had little reason to worry about
earthquakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know what's going to happen,'' Steeples said. ``But
statistically, I have a great deal of confidence that there are
going to be a hundred times more earthquakes in Los Angeles than in
Kansas City over thousands of years.''
</P>
<P>
   Steeples said a 1961 earthquake measured nearly 4.0 in
magnitude. Its epicenter was about 20 miles northeast of Kansas
City, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, seismographs recorded two earthquakes near Kansas
City International Airport in the mid-1980s, he said, but no one
felt those.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the U.S. Geological Survey in Golden, Colo., notes
that in 1968, an earthquake centered in southern Illinois
registered a magnitude 5.3 and was felt in this area.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, people across the central and south-central parts
of Kansas City, Kan., reported feeling tremors. Desks shook at the
Board of Public Utilities at Seventh Street and Minnesota Avenue.
Books fell off of a shelf at the main branch of the Kansas City
Kansas Public Library a block from the BPU.
</P>
<P>
   All in a matter of seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, hmm, an earthquake,'' said Claudia Baker, director
of development at Heart of America Family Services, 626 Minnesota
Ave. ``I just kept working. So did everyone else. If it had
continued, everybody would have left.''
</P>
<P>
   Others, like Dan Schenkein, president of the Kansas City Kansas
Area Chamber of Commerce, also on Minnesota Avenue, felt nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Within a minute or two, seismographs in several states started
to record the initial shaking, which was followed by an aftershock
about 90 seconds later.
</P>
<P>
   A geophysicist with the Oklahoma Geological Survey said that
three seismographs in that state indicated the earthquake had
reached a magnitude of 2.8. An official with the U.S. Geological
Survey in Golden reported that eight seismographs in eight states
recorded average readings of 3.0 in magnitude.
</P>
<P>
   Steeples said Thursday's tremors were probably the result of
movement along a small fault _ a fracture in underground rock _
somewhere in Kansas City, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   Steeples said seismograms _ charts generated by the seismograph
_ indicated that the tremors could have been compounded by the
possible collapse of a closed limestone mine. However, he did not
rule out the possibility that the collapse precipitated the
earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   The mine lies beneath two medical buildings at 46th Street and
Orville Avenue, just south of Indian Springs Marketplace,
Interstate 635 and State Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after feeling the tremors, about 100 medical staff and
patients in the west medical building were evacuated. They were not
allowed to re-enter because the building had moved and developed
cracks, and the earth had pulled away from part of the foundation,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, an 8-foot-deep fissure opened in the parking lot of
the two-story building.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt like someone hit the building with a truck,'' said
Sandy Storms, a medical assistant.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were yelling, `Get out, get out!' '' Storms said, and
they ran out of the building as fast as they could.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Bond, the Unified Government's chief building inspector, and
Bill Blackwell, the structural engineer, surveyed the area and
declared it unsafe. Mayor Carol Marinovich arrived at the scene
about 11 a.m. and was briefed.
</P>
<P>
   City building inspectors examined a handful of other buildings,
but did not find any with structural damage, said Assistant Fire
Chief Bill Hollander.
</P>
<P>
   At least four buildings were evacuated, including Kaw Valley
Children's Center, 759 Vermont Ave.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because we are a children's organization, we felt that anytime
something like this happens, you err on the side of caution,'' said
Marilyn Alstrom, vice president of human resources and development
for the center, which is responsible for foster care in eastern
Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   Steeples said the seismogram indicated that the tremors came on
suddenly, possibly indicating that Kansas City, Kan., had
experienced a tectonic earthquake, caused by a slip on a fault.
</P>
<P>
   The collapse of a mine could cause an earthquake, he said, but
had that happened, the seismogram probably would have shown the
tremors coming on gradually.
</P>
<P>
   Because reports of tremors came in a relatively limited area,
the earthquake's epicenter had to be somewhere in Kansas City,
Kan., Steeples said. However, geologists will probably have a hard
time pinpointing exactly where the epicenter was because the
nearest seismograph station is more than 250 miles away. At best,
he said, geologists probably will come only within two to three
miles of the exact site.
</P>
<P>
   The tremors were not, he stressed, the product of a larger
earthquake that occurred elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are scores of faults in this area,'' Steeples said.
``Most of them are small and harmless in the sense that the
earthquakes that occur on them are small. Nevertheless, they're
there....Occasionally they just slip a bit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
