<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-ORIOLES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS' GLOVES, BATS COME UP BIG
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Dransfeldt to McLemore to Stevens just
doesn't have the same iambic rhythm as Tinkers to Evers to Chance.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is the Rangers' makeshift double play combination likely to
produce three Hall of Famers or even have a poem written about
them. But last night at least they were as good as the Chicago
Cubs' revered infield of long ago and much better than the
Baltimore Orioles' shoddy glovework.
</P>
<P>
   The stark difference in defense, on a night when pitchers on
both teams needed all the help they could get, made the ultimate
difference in allowing the Rangers to hold off the Orioles, 15-7,
at The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our infield defense did an outstanding job tonight,'' manager
Johnny Oates said. ``We haven't played well defensively. Tonight is
more indicative of how we can play.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' offense stood out by tying a season high for runs
scored on a night when Juan Gonzalez was sidelined with a strained
right hamstring muscle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Juan's been there for us all year,'' outfielder Rusty Greer
said. ``We realize his big bat is out of the lineup but we still
have to take the same approach, day-in and day-out.''
</P>
<P>
   The defense came through early when shortstop Kelly Dransfeldt,
second baseman Mark McLemore and first baseman Lee Stevens turned
four double plays in the first four innings, keeping pitcher Mike
Morgan from total collapse.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's big,'' Rangers coach Bucky Dent said. ``Double plays
are a pitcher's life-saver, it shuts the inning right down. Those
were big.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates praised the work of Dransfeldt, a rookie called up to
replace the injured Royce Clayton. Oates went as far as to compare
him to Cal Ripken Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ``He reminds me of Junior,'' Oates said. ``He never rushes.
Catch the ball. Throw the ball. He's either going to be out or
safe. He doesn't even bobble a ground ball.''
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles' defensive collapse soon followed, starting in the
fourth when Roberto Kelly's grand slam, a three-run homer by Rusty
Greer and Rafael Palmeiro's solo shot brought home eight runs and
gave the Rangers a 9-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   For all the Rangers' muscle, the inning might have turned out
differently if second baseman Delino DeShields, with runners at
first and second, had been able to handle a one-hop potential
double play grounder hit by Lee Stevens. Instead he fumbled it for
an error and left the bases loaded for Kelly's blast off losing
pitcher Scott Kamieniecki.
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles then killed their chances for a dramatic rally with
four more errors in the sixth. They had cut the Rangers lead to 9-7
by finally getting to Morgan before giving away three runs that
inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers scored three more in the eighth, allowing them to
tie their season high in runs scored. Another footnote: Kelly's
grand slam and the one Rusty Greer hit Tuesday in Chicago marked
the first time in club history the Rangers have hit grand slams in
consecutive games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously it was an embarrassing pitching performance for both
teams,'' Orioles manager Ray Miller.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' failure to put the Orioles away after taking a 9-1
lead forced Oates to use reliever Jeff Zimmerman for two more
innings. He retired six straight hitters.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan got his sixth victory, second only in the American League
to Boston's Pedro Martinez, despite allowing 12 of 23 batters to
reach base. He allowed nine hits and three walks and might have
been showering even earlier than usual if it weren't for the double
plays.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
