<SLUG> BC-RAC-ANTLEY-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTLEY TAKES AIM AT TRIPLE CROWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK C. GIRARDOT  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ A CNN camera crew waits patiently to speak
to Chris Antley. But the jockey who won the Kentucky Derby earlier
this month aboard Charismatic isn't ready. He wants to dispense
investment advice first.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hang on a sec,'' he says to a member of the crew. ``I'll be
right with you.''
</P>
<P>
   Then comes the hot stock tip:
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's my Triple Crown,'' Antley says. ``AOL, Yahoo, CMGI. Buy
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Antley, in high demand for both his riding abilities on the race
track and his investment advice on the Internet, hopes to win the
Preakness aboard Charismatic on Saturday. A victory there would put
him within one of achieving something only a handful of jockeys
have ever done _ win horse racing's Triple Crown.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, he's a guy who takes his investment advice as seriously as
any ride he might get at the track. Perhaps it foreshadows
something momentous; his stock market tips were winners earlier
this week.
</P>
<P>
   At 14, Antley got his first ride and discovered the love of his
life _ horse racing. By age 17, he was riding at Pimlico. There, he
had his first taste of victory aboard Vaya Condonero. That year,
1983, Antley was a sensation on the racing circuit. During a 30-day
meet at Monmouth Park, he rode 172 winners.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 31, 1987, Antley was the first jockey to win nine races
in one day. He did it at Belmont and it's an accomplishment of
which he is still proud.
</P>
<P>
   Riding came naturally; life was a bit tougher. Antley tested
positive for marijuana and cocaine in 1988 and surrendered his
riding license in '89 because of substance abuse. He won his
license back in 1990 and rode Strike the Gold to victory in the '91
Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   But a new substance problem arose _ food. Keeping the weight off
became a daily battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to keep myself together,'' Antley said. ``I tried to
challenge the body, but you always end up in the same spot and it's
not a good place to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Antley was burned out by 1997. He was tired of the diets that
didn't work and the daily trips to the box, a sauna jockeys use
daily to sweat off excess weight. So he packed his bags, returned
home to Columbia, S.C., and moved in with his father, who was
selling propane.
</P>
<P>
   He was out of racing and rumors of his demise circulated at race
tracks and in Internet discussion groups devoted to horse racing.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it was on the Internet that Antley began building another
following with his timely investment advice. Every morning at 2
a.m., he would rise to compile ``The Antman Report'' and e-mail it
to anyone interested.
</P>
<P>
   Deep inside, he yearned to return to racing. Being out of work
was no picnic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually weighed 147,'' Antley said. ``I got on the scale
and it hit me. So that's when I started running.''
</P>
<P>
   He ran miles every day, watched his diet and half-jokingly
promised his father he would win the Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know it started out with sarcasm,'' Antley said. ``We
started to make it like a routine, where I was getting near getting
back. We were making jokes about it, but I kept thinking, the
Derby's in May and I sure would like to be a part of it and
wouldn't it be neat to win it?''
</P>
<P>
   A slim, trim Antley resurfaced in Southern California during
Santa Anita's winter/spring meet. At 118 pounds, he's getting the
most out of every horse he rides.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's riding better than I've ever seen him,'' said veteran
handicapper Jack Karlik. ``It's really something.''
</P>
<P>
   Charismatic's trainer, D. Wayne Lukas, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent the spring with Chris and saw an intensity in him I'd
never seen before,'' Lukas said on Derby Day. ``I just thought he
was a great fit.''
</P>
<P>
   Antley's drive to be a success on the race track again appealed
to Lukas.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's hungry and has a passion to get back into the upper
echelon of this sport,'' Lukas said. ``He's also won the Derby
before, he finishes well and he's very confident. I loved the way
he looked right at me and said, `We'll get it done.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Until the Derby, Antley had never seen Charismatic in the flesh.
And perhaps he didn't have to actually meet the horse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was our day,'' he said. ``You know how it is when you are
in that kind of situation? You can't try to figure out how lucky
you were or how it happened. You just take it all in and let it
soak in.''
</P>
<P>
   Antley recognizes that while his riding career has had many ups
and downs, nothing compares to the experience of coming back to win
the Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the first time I had ever really been proud of
myself,'' he said in his soft Southern drawl. ``Not just proud of
an accomplishment because I happened to be in the right place at
the right time, or because it was the best horse or this and that.
This was something that was a feeling. . . . I knew I got back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
