<HEADLINE>
`SEXUAL PREDATOR' LAW IS UPHELD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By VICTORIA HARKER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ An Arizona law that allows the indefinite
hospitalization of `'sexual predators'' like Harold Vroman Ray _
who hogties, tortures and sodomizes his victims _ was upheld
Thursday by the Arizona Court of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   In a 2-1 decision, the court said that the law not only is
constitutional but goes above and beyond other states' because it
guarantees treatment for predators.
</P>
<P>
   In affirming the law, the judges said the law serves two
purposes: protection of the public from sexually violent persons
and treatment of those persons so that they may return to society.
</P>
<P>
   They said the law is not punitive even though defendants are
committed to the state hospital after having completed their prison
terms.
</P>
<P>
   It is a civil, not a criminal matter, similar to an individual
being committed to the state hospital for a mental illness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any confinement . . . is to allow treatment and to protect the
public, not to punish for past crimes,'' wrote Judge Rebecca White
Berch. Judge Sheldon Weisberg concurred.
</P>
<P>
   In the sole dissenting opinion, Judge Thomas Kleinschmidt argued
that the law is unfair because most defendants were not told they
could be detained for life when they signed plea agreements. The
law did not go into effect until 1995.
</P>
<P>
   He also cited Arizona's dismal record for treating the mentally
ill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not willing to trust the state on this point,'' he wrote.
``The state's record in caring for and treating the mentally ill is
not a good one.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the defense attorneys representing 13 clients who filed
the special action, called the ruling ``disappointing'' but
predictable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, the judges think this is an unattractive
population,'' attorney Barbara Spencer said. ``They're certainly
not going to take any political risks to try and uphold the
constitutional rights of these defendants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their civil rights and constitutional rights are violated and
will continue to be violated as long as this statute is in
effect.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1995 law allows prosecutors to seek confinement in the state
hospital for sexual predators who are about to be released from
prison. In order to be labeled a predator, a defendant must be
convicted at least once for a sexual crime and be diagnosed as
having a mental disorder that makes him likely to engage in sexual
violence in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Similar laws in other states have been upheld, and the U.S.
Supreme Court has even upheld laws that do not provide for any
treatment, said Cindi Nannetti, bureau chief of the sex crimes unit
for the Maricopa County Attorney's Office.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say there is a certain group of sex offenders that
treatment is not going to do any good,'' Nannetti said.
</P>
<P>
   More than 40 men have been confined as predators, she said. Some
are contesting their confinement. Others, like Derick Martin, are
requesting confinement and treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutor Nannetti said Arizona's law provides added
protections for sexual predators, including annual reviews to
determine whether they are still a threat to society.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona also has ``least restrictive alternatives'' that allow
some predators in treatment to work during the day with electronic
monitoring bracelets.
</P>
<P>
   But lawyer Spencer said she and others likely will appeal the
ruling to the state Supreme Court because their clients are being
treated like prisoners, not patients.
</P>
<P>
   Her clients have been subjected to searches with dogs, must wear
special clothes that identify them from other patients, and are
placed in handcuffs and shackles when taken to court, she said. &QL; 
Victoria Harker can be reached at (602) 444-8058 or at
victoria.harker(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
