<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SULLIVAN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS NEED TO RESIST PULL OF JULY 31 CURE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fernando Tatis could easily be playing for the National League
All-Star team this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Think about that on July 31 when the Rangers are in contention,
their starting rotation still has serious problems and general
manager Doug Melvin is under severe pressure _ again _ to come
riding to the rescue.
</P>
<P>
   The scenario is very plausible, especially considering it comes
around every summer. A prolonged winning streak could change that,
but a killer June schedule could easily raise the panic level and
push Melvin toward the annual quick fix at the farm system's
everlasting expense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping we don't have to do that,'' Melvin said. ``It gets
expensive for your farm system. I'm hoping we do play well enough
where we can get a big lead and all we have to do is fine-tune the
club. Maybe this is the year where we try to win without making a
trade that hurts our farm system.''
</P>
<P>
   Melvin knows the Rangers' farm system is close to being
productive again. The problem is resisting the pressure both he and
former general manager Tom Grieve have had to face every summer
when the team is in contention and the public starts screaming for
pitching help.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin succumbed last year on July 31, when the Rangers were one
game behind the Anaheim Angels. Melvin sent third baseman Tatis,
pitcher Darren Oliver and minor-league outfielder Mark Little to
the St. Louis Cardinals for pitcher Todd Stottlemyre and shortstop
Royce Clayton.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, to fill the hole created at third base, he
traded minor-league pitcher Daniel DeYoung and infielder Jose Santo
_ two quality Class-A prospects _ to the Marlins for Todd Zeile.
</P>
<P>
   The deals were lauded for giving the Rangers a much better
chance to win the division and compete with the Yankees in the
playoffs. Turns out the Rangers did win the division _ a dubious
proposition without the trade _ but got swept in the playoffs by
the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Rangers may end up in the same position again. They
clearly have a good chance of winning the division. It is also
clear they have no better than the third-best team in the American
League, a distant third at that behind the Yankees and the
Cleveland Indians.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure to swing a deal mounts.
</P>
<P>
   Surely, they don't trade Ruben Mateo. How about Mike Zywica?
Kelly Dransfeldt? Ryan Glynn? He's 3-0 with a league-leading 1.64
earned-run average at Triple-A Oklahoma. There is also the Double-A
Tulsa staff of Derrick Cook, Doug Davis, Corey Lee, Ted Silva and
Danny Kolb. Tulsa has the lowest team ERA in the Texas League.
</P>
<P>
   For who?
</P>
<P>
   The obvious choice is Curt Schilling, if he is available. But
it's still questionable if adding Schilling could pull the Rangers
even with the Yankees or the Indians. Kenny Rogers? He left his
last start with the Athletics with a bad back.
</P>
<P>
   One long-held view is that when a team has a chance to win, it
should go all out to do so, because the chance might not come again
for a long time. But the Rangers have been in competition almost
every year without clearing the final hurdle. It's time to try
something different.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers should try leaving the farm system alone for just
one summer and see if what they sow reaps greater benefits then
what they've been getting. What they've been getting hasn't been
all that much.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
