<SLUG> BC-GREENFIELD-OBIT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEG GREENFIELD REMEMBERED WARMLY IN BOTH WASHINGTONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Meg Greenfield, 68, editorial page editor of The
Washington Post and a part-time resident of Bainbridge Island,
Wash., died Thursday in Washington, D.C., after a lengthy bout with
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Greenfield was a Seattle native who attained an insider's perch
in Washington, D.C., but brought to it independence and detachment.
</P>
<P>
   She moved late in life to reestablish ties with the place where
she grew up, buying a home on Bainbridge that became a meeting
place for business, political and journalistic figures from both
Washingtons.
</P>
<P>
   ``She felt this is where her roots were. She wanted to get back
here,'' said William Ruckelshaus, former U.S. Environmental
Protection Administration director and another Seattle-area
returnee.
</P>
<P>
   Retired University of Washington President William Gerberding on
Thursday summed up a quality that drew people to Greenfield, and
gave force to her writing. ``She was witty and wise and deeply
immersed in big-time politics,'' he said. ``She managed to have a
wry, detached perspective on power while being right in the middle
of it.''
</P>
<P>
   On Bainbridge, Greenfield was renowned for her July Fourth
parties and the people who would get to know each other. She
introduced billionaire investor Warren Buffett, a house guest on
Bainbridge, to Microsoft founder Bill Gates.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was very proud of bringing people from the East Coast out
to Bainbridge Island so they could see the other Washington. She
introduced a lot of people to this state,'' said Rep. Norm Dicks,
D-Wash.
</P>
<P>
   Greenfield wrote a biweekly Newsweek column for the past 25
years, and was The Post's editorial page editor since 1979. A Post
editorial writer since 1968, she won the 1978 Pulitzer Prize for
editorial writing with editorials on civil rights, international
relations and the press.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she wanted to retire out here, but she had a terrible
time retiring,'' said Ruckelshaus.
</P>
<P>
   Greenfield was renowned for her entertaining, whether it was
Washington D.C., guests like Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, a New
York Democrat, discoursing around the circular dinner table of her
Georgetown home, or lifelong Seattle friends enjoying her garden on
Bainbridge.
</P>
<P>
   Greenfield was born in Seattle on Dec. 27, 1930. She was the
daughter of Lewis James Greenfield, an antique furniture dealer,
and Lorraine Nathan Greenfield. She graduated from the Bush School,
went on to graduate summa cum laude from Smith College, and earned
a Fulbright scholarship which she spent at Cambridge University
studying the poetry of William Blake.
</P>
<P>
   She was identified early with liberal politics, working for
Democratic presidential nominee Adlai Stevenson in 1956, and moving
on to The Reporter. She stayed with the magazine until it stopped
publication in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   At The Reporter, she gained renown for such articles as one
titled ``Richard Nixon's Prose Style,'' which schooled readers on
how to interpret language used by the future president. Whenever
Nixon claimed to be taking a daring stand or going against his
advisers, Greenfield wrote, an untruth was sure to follow.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was a fairly traditional liberal at the outset,'' said
Gerberding, ``but she underwent a period of change as she grew
older, and liberal verities came into question.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of her onetime associates became neo-conservatives. A
lot of those people joined the Republican Party and became fans of
Ronald Reagan. It didn't happen to Meg. Her political trajectory
was more confined. She ceased being a party line liberal _ whatever
that means _ but she didn't become a neo-conservative.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenfield sounded fairly conservative themes during a 1992
Seattle talk. She questioned the wisdom of broadly written hate
crime laws. She urged members of the audience to ``fight like
tigers against government attempts to substitute its judgment for
ours.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenfield was also a critic of attack TV, sound-bite politics,
and the increasingly confrontational atmosphere of life in the
nation's capital. A 1989 column wondered about the blizzard of
petty accusations.
</P>
<P>
   ``All day long around here, we... go around implying that the
other fellow is lying, trimming, gouging, feathering his nest,
murdering the innocent and otherwise violating everything that
upright people hold dear,'' she wrote. ``The effect of this
constant play is that we lose the ability to recognize a genuine
moral dereliction when we see one.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Greenfield was appreciated by friends in both
Washingtons.
</P>
<P>
   Gerberding recalled her generosity to the University of
Washington, where she set up a scholarship in classics to honor her
late brother. She ``cared deeply about this state,'' Dicks added.
</P>
<P>
   Greenfield once lamented that she was ``a passionate, failed
gardner'' but the self-description was disputed Thursday by the
University of Washington's longtime lobbyist, Dr. Jack Lein. ``The
garden (on Bainbridge) was a masterpiece,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pete Milius, an editorial board colleague at The Post, described
Greenfield as the best editor he ever encountered. Her
craftsmanship with words was ``a little like being at the eye
doctor, where he drops lens after lens until the right focus
appears in front of your eyes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Greenfield was ``incorrigibly funny,'' Milius added. ``She loved
nothing more than to deflate. It is a useful impulse to have in
this town.''
</P>
<P>
   A Seattle memorial service for Greenfield will be held at 11:30
a.m. Monday at Temple De Hirsch Sinai in Seattle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
