<SLUG> BC-FBC-COLLEGE-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS STATE FOOTBALL REGROUPING FROM LATE '98 SWOON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Out front, center stage, Kansas State suffered as public a
pratfall as any team in recent memory.
</P>
<P>
   In December, the Wildcats were 15 minutes of football from
playing for a national championship before Texas A&AMP;M rallied for a
shocking 36-33 overtime victory in the Big 12 Conference
championship game. Instead of playing in the Fiesta Bowl, Kansas
State wound up in the Alamo Bowl, where it suffered a desultory
37-34 loss to Purdue.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the scenes, Kansas State football also has been torn
asunder. When former Wildcats assistant Bob Stoops was hired at
Oklahoma, he quickly hired Kansas State assistants Mike Stoops (his
brother) and Brent Venables.
</P>
<P>
   Both of those hirings came after the A&AMP;M loss and further
depressed a program that had watched its dream season turn
nightmarish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Timing is everything, isn't it?'' Kansas State coach Bill
Snyder said. ``It was not an easy task to work our way through
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, a few days after the Purdue loss, assistant Mark Mangino
left the Wildcats' staff to join the exodus to Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   Wait. It gets worse. Snyder hired Rex Ryan, who was Oklahoma's
defensive coordinator last season. But in February, Ryan left to
take an NFL assistant coaching job.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan's decision came close to signing day and presaged another
body blow. Mostly because of the hiring of Mike Stoops and
Venables, running back James Mozee of Blue Springs, Mo., changed
his mind and signed with Oklahoma instead of Kansas State.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are always concerns when things like that happen,''
Snyder said. ``But stuff happens. It's part of the business.''
</P>
<P>
   Staff turnover can be expected, especially at a program that has
been successful. But replacing four assistants _ that's typical of
a program mired in losing that's trying to find the right
combination.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder, though, says that the coaching staff transition has been
eased in that his four new assistants are all coaching veterans.
Defensive coordinator Phil Bennett, for instance, has coached at
TCU, Texas A&AMP;M, Iowa State, Purdue, LSU and Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder and his assistants must replace eight offensive starters,
including do-it-all quarterback Michael Bishop. But while Snyder
wasn't pleased with his team's spring progress, he didn't sense any
hangover from his team's last two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last December was a difficult time, particularly the first
loss,'' Snyder said. ``Getting ready for the Alamo Bowl was a
tremendously difficult task. Hindsight would tell you we probably
should have packed our bags and waited for a better day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've all put that behind us. Youngsters are pretty
resilient. It's us old guys that sometimes don't bounce back as
quickly.''
Briefly
</P>
<P>
   The Bowl Championship Series has had preliminary discussions
about adding a fifth bowl to its lineup. The idea would be to
create two more at-large bids for deserving teams that wind up
losing late-season games (see: Kansas State, 1998). The earliest a
fifth bowl could be added would be after the 2001 season.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Chryst, who was named Mid-American Conference commissioner
this week, is a former Southwest Conference assistant commissioner.
He's leaving the Atlantic Coast Conference, where he's assistant
commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night in Oklahoma City, Oklahoma State and Oklahoma
staged a benefit baseball game to raise money for tornado victims.
An estimated $55,000 was raised as 10,172 showed up to watch the
Sooners beat the Cowboys, 10-9.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
