A6645 &Cx1f; tth-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOEING-CUTS-SPI &LR;      05-14 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-CUTS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING TO CUT UP TO 7,000 JOBS IN ST. LOUIS JET FIGHTER PLANT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Having lost out on a key contract to defense rival
Lockheed Martin, The Boeing Co. announced Thursday that it will
eliminate as many as 7,000 jobs at its St. Louis fighter aircraft
plant between now and mid-2001.
</P>
<P>
   That's about 35 percent of Boeing's work force in St. Louis,
headquarters of its Military Aircraft and Missiles group.
</P>
<P>
   With those cuts, the Seattle-based aerospace giant could end
next year with about 53,000 fewer workers companywide than it had
at the peak of employment in July 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing previously announced it would eliminate 43,000 to 53,000
jobs by the end of the 2000. That would reduce employment
companywide to between 185,000 and 195,000, from a peak of 238,000
last July.
</P>
<P>
   The job cuts in St. Louis fall within Boeing's earlier
forecasts, Boeing spokesman Peter Conte said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This does not change our projection,'' he said. ``But we will
definitely be at the lower end (185,000) by the end of 2000. Beyond
that, it's unclear.''
</P>
<P>
   As of May 1, Boeing's employment companywide was 217,000, of
which 88,600 jobs were in Washington state.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing the job cuts in St. Louis, Boeing said it will
halt production, at least temporarily, of its F-15 fighter line
once the last plane now on order is delivered to the U.S. Air Force
in early 2000. The company previously said it would halt production
in mid-2000 of its F-18C/D line.
</P>
<P>
   The two fighter programs were acquired by Boeing in the 1997
merger with McDonnell Douglas. Both have been highly profitable,
but Boeing has been unable to win news orders. The F-15 and F-18
are being widely used in the air war against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The St. Louis announcement was not entirely unexpected in the
wake of last month's decision by Greece to buy F-16s from Lockheed
Martin rather than F-15s from Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   But union leaders there said they were shocked by the size of
the layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew there would be layoffs, but not of this magnitude,''
said Rick Smith, president of District 837 of the International
Association of Machinists and Aerospace Workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they lost the sales, we all expected something to happen,
but not this quickly and not this big. These are all good,
relatively high-paying jobs. It's not going to be pretty.''
</P>
<P>
   About 5,000 workers in St. Louis are involved in the F-15
program.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1972, more than 1,500 F-15s have been built for the air
forces of the United States, Israel, Saudi Arabia and Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing had been counting on Greece to order up to 35 F-15s,
which could have extended production of the fighter for another two
years. Instead, Greece chose the new Eurofighter and the F-16 built
by Lockheed Martin.
</P>
<P>
   At about $60 million, the more advanced F-15 cost twice as much
as the F-16.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing still hopes to win new F-15 orders from Israel, though
published reports say Israel has decided to buy fighters from
Lockheed Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's air force reportedly recommended in a closed-door
meeting Thursday that the government award the $2.5 billion
fighter-plane contract to Lockheed Martin.
</P>
<P>
   But Defense Minister Moshe Arens, who chaired the Tel Aviv
meeting of top defense officials, put off choosing between Lockheed
and Boeing at least until next week, making a decision unlikely
before Israel's general election Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Defense experts say the air force wants the F-16 because Israel
can get twice as many planes at the same price.
</P>
<P>
   There is still a remote possibility Israel could split the
order, those experts say.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Israel ordered 25 of the most advanced version of the
Boeing fighter, the F-15I. The last of those planes recently was
delivered. The only F-15s still in the production line are
replacement planes for the U.S. Air Force and the last of a
72-plane order for Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Boeing won new orders from Israel, deliveries would not
begin until 2001, and that means a break in the F-15 line when the
last plane now on order is delivered early next year, Boeing
spokeswoman JoAnne Davis in St. Louis said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's decision will not affect Boeing's plans to eliminate
6,200 to 7,000 jobs in St. Louis by mid-2001, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we completed an assessment of our business environment
based on the April 30 decision by the government of Greece, we
decided to let our team and the community know as soon as possible
what to expect for the foreseeable future,'' Jerry Daniels,
Boeing's vice president and general manager for its St. Louis
operations, said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   As of May 1, Boeing employment in Missouri was 20,150.
</P>
<P>
   The F-15 line has been an important source of revenue for
Boeing. The company will deliver 38 of the fighters this year.
Costing an estimated $60 million each, the 39 deliveries mean about
$2.3 billion for Boeing in 1999. And that is nearly 20 percent of
Boeing's projected 1999 revenue of $12 billion for its entire
Military Aircraft and Missiles unit.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing might have to take a one-time charge to pay for parts it
ordered, expecting to win the Greek order. Because of the long lead
time in getting parts, Boeing had no choice but to order parts so
it could be ready to continue F-15 production.
</P>
<P>
   Longer term, the new F-18E/F Super Hornet that Boeing has just
started building for the Navy will more than make up for lost F-15
revenue, but it will take time for the program to become as
profitable as the F-15, which has been in production since the
early 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the 5,000 or so St. Louis employees working on
the F-15 program, some 6,000 to 7,000 build the F-18C/D Hornet and
the new F-18-E/F Super Hornet.
</P>
<P>
   Production on the Hornet line will stop in mid-2000. Just like
with the F-15, production of the Hornet could be restarted if
Boeing gets additional orders. But potential Hornet orders from
countries in Latin America
</P>
<P>
   and Central Europe have been de-
</P>
<P>
   layed.
</P>
<P>
   The F-15 line was shut down once before, then was restarted with
the order from Saudi Arabia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
