u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REFUGEES-KOSOVO-SPI &LR;      05-14 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFUGEES-KOSOVO-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGENCIES READY TO DO WHAT THEY CAN FOR KOSOVO REFUGEES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GORDY HOLT  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Puget Sound-area rescue agencies say they expect and
can accommodate an estimated 250 to 500 Kosovo refugees as the
region's share of about 20,000 who have been promised shelter in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   They could be arriving at any time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to help these people become as fully independent
and self-sufficient as they can be,'' said Cindy Koser, director of
refugee resettlement for Catholic Community Services in Seattle.
``But we will offer only what they will be able and willing to
accept.''
</P>
<P>
   Koser said the ethnic-Albanian Kosovars are expected to arrive
with little more than the clothes on their backs. But because of
their war experiences, they will be packing plenty of emotional
baggage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't expect the fears of these people will go away
easily,'' Koser said. ``But with the help of mental-health
professionals, we'll try to alleviate them.''
</P>
<P>
   Basic needs will come first. Housing, food, furniture and
medical care top the list. Refugee children will be integrated into
local schools. English-language lessons will be available for
adults and children.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, programs are available to aquaint the newcomers
with community assets and culture. Employment assistance and/or
welfare benefits also are offered.
</P>
<P>
   Koser's agency is among a handful locally given federal money to
help resettle refugees who arrive without private support. Included
are the Episcopal Migration Ministries, the Lutheran Refugee
Project, World Relief and the International Rescue Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Rescue Committee Director Bob Johnson said Thursday word of the
refugees' arrival remains ``up in the air.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The first groups are now being processed at Fort Dix, N.J.,''
he said. ``Beyond that, we've only been asked how many can we take,
and we've provided that information.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Holter, the World Relief spokesman in Spokane, said his
organization will be able to place between six and 10 families
through churches there. Holter said he was told to expect the
newcomers within the next six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   By all indications, however, those who eventually arrive in the
Northwest will be a fraction of Kosovo's refugees. According to the
United Nations High Command for Refugees in Geneva, Switzerland,
more than 750,000 ethnic Albanians have been chased from their
homes to seek shelter in neighboring states.
</P>
<P>
   By the United Nation's reckoning, nearly 4,000 have been
accepted by countries beyond the Balkans, including the 1,861 who
have arrived in the United States so far, including 482 who arrived
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Most spent months in ill-equipped refugee camps in Albania and
Macedonia where there has been little clean water, virtually no
sanitation and few services.
</P>
<P>
   According to the United Nations organization, another
million-plus refugees are thought to be homeless and hiding inside
Kosovo under even worse conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Van Dinh Kuno, director of Snohomish County's Refugee and
Immigrant Forum at Everett Community College, said the United
States, again, will be a willing host, especially at the local
level, where offers of help are pouring in.
</P>
<P>
   Individuals as well as groups such as Our Savior's Lutheran
Church in Everett, Wash., have responded, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Our Savior's pastor, the Rev. David Parks, said helping refugees
is part of his congregation's 100-year-old history.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've already raised $2,000 and we've formed a committee,'' he
said. ``But right now we can only wait to see what happens next.''
</P>
<P>
   Kuno was among the so-called ``boat people'' who fled Vietnam a
quarter-century ago. In her case, she sailed with 300 others in a
boat jammed so tightly there was barely room to sit. Her passage
took her to the Philippines, but her journey extended from there to
Guam and on to a military base in Arkansas. Eventually she was sent
to Minnesota where two churches came to her aid.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-four years later, she has made the best of it, earning a
degree in biochemistry at the University of Minnesota, and, after
determining that refugee work was more to her liking, got a
bachelor's degree in human services from the University of
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Kuno said education was her leg up over the barriers she faced
as a refugee. The same will prove true for this latest wave, she
predicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first year or two everything will be overwhelming,
like it or not,'' she said. ``They'll have to do what it takes to
survive. But we hope to be ready to help.''
</P>
<P>
   Depression is expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the people I work with suffer from it,'' she said.
``There is guilt over leaving loved ones. Here they'll have plenty
of food and a roof over their heads. Eventually, they will begin
losing hope that they'll ever see home again, and from there,
mental-health issues will surface _ lost sleep, no appetite, some
may even hear voices.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will all want to go home. All refugees do,'' Kuno said.
Unlike immigrants, she said, refugees don't plan to come here and
never had a chance to say goodbye to loved ones.
</P>
<P>
   For Hungarian-American Paul Juhasz of Seattle, more than 54
years have failed to dim memories of refugee life in Europe and
America following World War II.
</P>
<P>
   With the certainty of his 85 years, Paul Juhasz can see the
future for this latest group, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who come will be lost to Kosovo, that is for sure,'' he
said. ``But what Kosovo drains, the U.S. gains, especially with the
young people. This is a rich country. They will find a better
future here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
