<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ANGELS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS SHUT OUT YANKEES, 2-0 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The sheen of invincibility the Yankees donned last
season is gone, the last of it peeled away on Thursday night by the
Anaheim Angels, who completed a three-game sweep at Yankee Stadium
with a 2-0 shutout, the first visiting team sweep since July 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Torre, the Yankees' manager, told his players in spring
training that they should forget about trying to live up to the
great expectations created last year, that 1998 was an incredible
season that would be virtually impossible to re-create. The '99
Yankees are 20-13 _ they didn't suffer their 13th loss last year
until June 21 _ and now they can fully understand what Torre meant.
</P>
<P>
   Forget about '98. Focus on what they are in '99, which is a
well-above-average team that is capable of losing streaks, mental
mistakes and erratic fielding. The Yankees are a slumping team
starved for hits and runs, and stuffed with frustration.
</P>
<P>
   Hideki Irabu pitched superbly for seven innings, as David Cone
did Wednesday in a 1-0 loss. Irabu held the Angels scoreless until
Mo Vaughn homered in the sixth inning, but the Yankees could not
push across any runs. They have gone scoreless for 19 consecutive
innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our offense right now is sputtering,'' said Don Zimmer, the
Yankees' interim manager. ``Who knows, we might score nine runs
tomorrow. But we've watched this for two days.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels arrived four days ago devastated by injuries, their
active roster stacked with journeymen and burdened by a four-game
losing streak. But Chuck Finley shut New York out for eight innings
Wednesday, and Omar Olivares did the same for six and two-thirds
innings on Thursday night, as the Yankee hitters began swinging
anxiously.
</P>
<P>
   Paul O'Neill's current plight is a microcosm of the team slump.
He goes through an evolution when he is struggling: at the outset
of any string of poor at-bats, he talks to himself after passing
first base, his head sometimes turning with each syllable. When the
slump deepens, he can explode with anger, throwing helmets and bats
and batting gloves.
</P>
<P>
   Now he is in the third stage of his evolution _ despair, which
was on full display Thursday night. When the game began, O'Neill
was without a hit in his last 14 at-bats with runners in scoring
position, a streak dating to May 1. With runners at first and third
and two out in the third inning, O'Neill grounded out. After
crossing the base, O'Neill's head dropped, his shoulders shrunk,
and he quietly pulled off his batting gloves and placed them in his
helmet resignedly.
</P>
<P>
   Two innings later, O'Neill had a significant opportunity to end
his despair. Bases loaded and one out, the game scoreless. Olivares
appeared to be wilting, ripe for O'Neill to pounce, as he had done
in previous meetings. Going into the game, O'Neill had 7 hits in 17
at-bats (.412) in his career against Olivares. But O'Neill weakly
slapped a grounder to second baseman Randy Velarde, who initiated a
rally-killing double play, and O'Neill's body language emanated
pure self-loathing as he crossed first base.
</P>
<P>
   ``You try and make it all happen at once, on one pitch,''
O'Neill said. ``I'm speaking for myself.''
</P>
<P>
   He could have been speaking for everybody. Chuck Knoblauch is 0
for 12 since he was roll-blocked last week in Minnesota. Tino
Martinez went 0 for 4. Bernie Williams is averaging 3.11 pitches
for each plate appearance, the fourth-lowest figure in the American
League, and he is on a pace to draw 35 walks, after drawing 74 last
year. He is hitting about 20 percent more grounders than in 1998,
at least partly accounting for his decrease in extra-base hits.
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Posada, the catcher, cannot remember slumping worse than
he has this year. Going into the game, the switch-hitter was
batting .182 over all, but while batting left-handed, his average
was .146 with 21 strikeouts in 48 at-bats. He often appeared lost
at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday night, Posada showed signs of breaking out,
hammering a double off the top of the fence in left-center field in
the fifth and hitting the ball hard in his other at-bats. Posada
was stranded, however, when O'Neill hit into the double play.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the five Yankees to bat in the sixth inning reached
base, and they could not score. Williams was caught stealing with
one out, and after Chili Davis walked and Shane Spencer ripped a
single, Scott Brosius grounded into a forceout to close the inning.
</P>
<P>
   In the eighth, the Yankees had runners at first and second and
one out, and Spencer and Brosius could not deliver, prompting most
in the crowd of 40,619 to leave Yankee Stadium. The Yankees are
without a hit in their last 17 at-bats with runners in scoring
position, dating to the third inning of Tuesday's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've just got to keep playing hard,'' Williams said. ``Good
things are going to happen, sooner or later.''
</P>
<P>
   Good things always happened in 1998. But it's not 1998. The
Yankees know that, now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
