<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 01:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6656 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-REDWINGS-AVALANCH     05-14 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-REDWINGS-AVALANCHE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AVALANCHE CRUSH RED WINGS, 6-2 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ The Stanley Cup reign of the Detroit Red Wings is in
jeopardy because of injury and ineffectiveness in goal. The injured
goalie is Chris Osgood, who has not played since the first round of
the playoffs because of a sprained right knee. The ineffective
goalie is Bill Ranford, who played so well in the first two games
of this second-round series, both won by Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday night, Ranford was pulled for the second consecutive
game, this one a 6-2 Colorado Avalanche victory before a grumbling
crowd at Joe Louis Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``It rocks your confidence; no doubt about that,'' Ranford said.
``But it's still 2-2; we'll have to go back to Colorado and steal
another one.''
</P>
<P>
   The result evened the four-of-seven-game Western Conference
semifinal series at two victories apiece. All four games have been
won by the visiting team. The round will resume on Sunday with Game
5 in Denver. Game 6 will be in Detroit on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Although Osgood has resumed practice and seemed more agile in
recent days, it was not known on Thursday if he would be able to
play on Sunday. Even if he plays, it is difficult to predict how
sharp he will be after missing more than two weeks. And even if
Osgood is at his best, it is no sure thing that he can pull the Red
Wings out of their nose dive. Last spring, Detroit won its second
consecutive Stanley Cup championship despite Osgood's tendency to
allow the occasional soft goal on long shots.
</P>
<P>
   Scotty Bowman, the Detroit coach, said Osgood ``wasn't 100
percent'' when he worked out on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's close,'' Bowman said. ``He hasn't had a full workout. A
lot will depend on how he does in the workouts.''
</P>
<P>
   Detroit's opponent at the other end of the ice will again be
Patrick Roy, who stopped 31 of 33 shots on Thursday night and
showed the old confidence and cockiness that helped his teams win
the cup in Montreal in 1986 and in Colorado in 1996. After stopping
pucks, Roy would sometimes swat them away with his big paddle or
flick his wrist while securing them in the big glove on his left
hand.
</P>
<P>
   Ranford gave up a goal just 88 seconds into the game, on a
rebound by Chris Drury. Then he was replaced by Norm Maracle at 14
minutes 4 seconds of the second period after Milan Hejduk scored on
a power play to give Colorado a 3-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Bowman said he replaced Ranford not because of that goal in
particular but because his team was behind by three. ``I thought we
needed to get some kind of boost,'' he said. ``Tonight did not look
too even.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game is well done; it's finished. Next game we will try
to put the pressure on them.''
</P>
<P>
   Although many goalies might have stopped the low shot between
the skates, Ranford was not the only Wing to blame on this one.
Chris Chelios and Ulf Samuelsson, two veteran defensemen obtained
at the trading deadline on March 23, were skating pirouettes behind
their goal line as the Colorado attackers eluded them and worked
the puck toward the crease.
</P>
<P>
   Like them, Ranford was obtained at the deadline to bolster a
championship team that had slipped to mediocrity during the regular
season. The fourth veteran obtained that day was Wendel Clark, also
ineffective on Thursday night as the teamwide slump spread through
the home team like a virus. The Wings had swept Anaheim in four
games in the first round. Colorado needed six games to eliminate
San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an embarrassment,'' Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   Adam Deadmarsh scored twice for Colorado. Valery Kamensky and
Peter Forsberg got the others. Slava Kozlov ended Roy's shutout
with two goals late in the third period as the game took on the
sloppy character of an exhibition. The Avalanche played a
disciplined style with tight checking and avoided the unprovoked
penalties that had marred its style in the first two games.
</P>
<P>
   One factor bolstering the Avalanche in the last two games has
been the return of Kamensky from a broken arm.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about Kamensky, Roy said: ``I think Kamensky coming
back is huge. It let us put Deadmarsh on the third line and gave us
a solid third line.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he could explain his team's pattern in this
series, Roy replied: ``Nope. Now, the question is if we can build
confidence in our own building.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wings have been hurt by the loss of Igor Larionov, who has
missed the last two games with a cast on his left hand to cover
what the Wings say is a dislocated finger.
</P>
<P>
   Bowman said of Larionov: ``He's a good setup player. You miss a
solid playmaking type of player.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Hartley, the Colorado coach, said of Roy: ``Patrick gave us
the big saves at the right time. Every time we're forced to face
adversity, we've responded well.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
