A6663 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-FINANCIAL-SERVIC     05-14 0530
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-FINANCIAL-SERVICES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A SHIFTING FINANCIAL LANDSCAPE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Friday, May 14:
</P>
<P>
   While the politicians in Washington have squabbled endlessly
about how to regulate financial services companies, the financial
architecture of the country has changed even as the laws have not.
It is now entirely possible that the restructuring will be
completed while Congress argues _ and in a way that seriously
compromises the ability of the most important federal regulators to
supervise major financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
   A significant new element in the debate was injected last week
by Gov. George Pataki of New York, who proposed state legislation
that would allow financial institutions to offer a full range of
financial services including banking and insurance. In the
byzantine structure of financial regulation in America, that
proposal, if enacted, would allow any New York bank to restructure
in a way that would leave it regulated by a variety of regulators
but not by the Federal Reserve Board or the Comptroller of the
Currency.
</P>
<P>
   More than 60 years ago, Congress separated banking and brokerage
firms via the Glass-Steagall Act. But after a series of regulatory
and court decisions, the only meaningful barrier left is one that
keeps insurance underwriters from engaging in banking. That is
important to many companies, among them Chase Manhattan and Merrill
Lynch. Citigroup has only a temporary exemption allowing it to own
Travelers Insurance, and needs a change in the law.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed New York legislation would provide a way around
that by letting Citigroup set up a New York bank that would engage
in everything except retail banking. It would then set up a thrift
to provide its retail banking services. The difference would be
invisible to consumers, but not to regulators, and that could be
important in a crisis.
</P>
<P>
   One of the fights that has prevented congressional action has
been a turf war between the Comptroller and the Fed over who will
regulate new large financial entities. The Fed has tried to keep
all of that for itself, freezing out the comptroller. The Pataki
proposal should serve as a warning to the Fed to back off and let
the comptroller continue to share in such regulation, out of the
fear that both will lose if major banks go the New York route.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate last week passed a bill in this area that is not
adequate. Besides siding with the Fed in the turf war, it also
unreasonably reduces the obligations of banks under the Community
Reinvestment Act, which mandates that banks serve poor communities.
In addition, Arthur Levitt Jr., the chairman of the Securities and
Exchange Commission, has warned that the bill would leave bank
customers with significantly less protection than is enjoyed by
customers of brokerage firms not part of banks. That is clearly
unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   It is up to the House to come up with a better bill. It and the
Senate should find a way to pass an acceptable measure quickly, or
they will risk seeing the act become meaningless as New York, and
other states, pass their own legislation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
