</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-GARDENS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: MISS M'S DIVINE INTERVENTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Friday, May 14:
</P>
<P>
   There are many people who deserve praise for saving 112
community gardens that were due to be auctioned by New York City
for other purposes. The gardeners themselves have earned a nod for
weeding and cleaning and watering these odd-sized plots for years.
The Trust for Public Land began earnestly negotiating a few months
ago to try to buy some of the gardens. Activists planted lawsuits
in recent days, stalling the date of the auction long enough to
allow for a deal. Protesters converted themselves into ladybugs or
sunflowers and marched off to jail for a good green cause. Even
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's administrators, the very ones readying
these patches for auction to the highest and perhaps unsympathetic
bidder, deserve thanks for agreeing to sell the land to those who
wanted to develop little more than grassy triangles, bordered by
nasturtiums or tomato plants.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the clincher was a last-minute Saturday-matinee-style
rescue by Bette Midler. The organization that she founded in 1994,
the New York Restoration Project, agreed Wednesday to put up about
$1 million to buy the less desirable gardens not covered in the
Trust for Public Land's offer of $3 million for the better plots.
The combined package saved the 112 gardens and may make it more
difficult for the city to bulldoze other gardens in the future. The
self-proclaimed Queen of Trash, known for her exuberant music,
movies and costumery, this week adds another title _ the Queen of
Green.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
