<HEADER>
A6668 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBD-ELWAY-LADN     05-14 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBD-ELWAY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELWAYS CENTER OF ATTENTION IN MEETINGS ABOUT L.A. FRANCHISE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY STEVE DILBECK  
 c.1999 SAN BERNARDINO SUN  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ How does John Elway, NFL team president and
part-owner sound?
</P>
<P>
   Elway, who retired after a legendary career with the Denver
Broncos less than two weeks ago, has suddenly become the golden boy
in the battle between the two competing groups bidding to earn the
NFL's Los Angeles franchise.
</P>
<P>
   In separate meetings Thursday, Elway listened to both groups,
and each discussion included not only a minority ownership
possibility, but that of running the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it wasn't Los Angeles, and professional football, and the
opportunity of management at a very high level _ possibly the
president _ this wouldn't be a consideration,'' said Marvin Demoff,
his agent. ``It is a unique opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Elway, his wife, Jan, and Demoff met first with Ovitz for
approximately an hour, and then later for about the same time with
Eli Broad and Los Angeles Mayor Richard Riordan in Century City.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, this is the most exciting news I could have ever heard,
that John Elway would be interested in being the president of a
team in Los Angeles,'' Riordan said. ``I think it's a magical way
to make all this work very quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Elway, however, decided to keep his thoughts on the meetings
private. Not wanting to show favoritism between the two groups, and
being careful not to offend Denver, he opted out of the scheduled
press conference.
</P>
<P>
   Demoff said Elway, a former star at Granada Hills High School in
Los Angeles' San Fernando Valley, still had much to digest before
making a decision whether to join one of the Los Angeles groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the level of interest in Los Angeles, while
flattering, caught John off-guard,'' Demoff said. ``We were looking
at broadcasting opportunities, Denver Bronco opportunity, some
business opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``And in the last 10 days, Los Angeles presented itself, and
it's exciting to him. He truly doesn't know enough to even start to
make an informed decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Elway has a standing offer to become a minority owner with Pat
Bowlen with the Broncos. But Bowlen plans to continue to run the
team for an additional 10 or more years, and if Elway wants to
direct his own team, he will have to go elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he would be a great member of the Coliseum partners
team,'' Broad said. ``We need someone of his caliber to run the
franchise if it's awarded to us.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't discuss percentages, but we prefer whoever is in
management to also be an owner. We like linking ownership and
management.''
</P>
<P>
   NFL owners are next scheduled to meet May 25-26 in Atlanta.
Broad said he and partner Ed Roski Jr. plan to present financial
and parking plans at that meeting, and are hopeful a Los Angeles
owner will be chosen to meet their September deadline.
</P>
<P>
   But Demoff said he doesn't expect Elway to align himself with
either group by the May meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is such a unique opportunity, it's important for him to
explore it fully and this is really just the very beginning of
that,'' Demoff said.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday did allow Elway to make it clear to both Ovitz and
Broad that he wanted to actively run the team. And it allowed both
potential owners to embrace the possibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``John made it clear he doesn't want to be just a celebrity,''
Broad said. ``He wants to start a new career and he said in my new
career, I want to be as successful as I was in my last career. And
I believe he can do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not made an offer. We did not say, John, we want you
to become president at these terms. We said, We want you. We think
you'd be a great asset to this franchise. It would help us create a
type of excitement we need here and hopefully help us create a team
that in the not-too-distant future will be looking at some Super
Bowl rings.''
</P>
<P>
   Broad also used Thursday's press conference to take a page out
of Ovitz's book. Broad said he would be broadening his ownership
group in the next few weeks to include members of the entertainment
industry.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
