<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 01:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6670 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      05-14 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PAYTON EQUATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Reflecting upon the season, Paul Westphal knew it was
the superstar that was his undoing.
</P>
<P>
   ``My opinion on him was that he is exactly as advertised,'' he
said. ``He had a great upside with a certain amount of baggage. To
hold that against him is unrealistic.''
</P>
<P>
   That didn't stop the Phoenix Suns from firing Westphal, and
trading Charles Barkley.
</P>
<P>
   Oh. Were you thinking the Sonics and Gary Payton?
</P>
<P>
   Excuse the misunderstanding. The situations tend to look alike.
</P>
<P>
   The turbulence around Payton is a major element in the Sonics'
unpleasant early obituary. But in 1996, Westphal as Suns coach had
in Barkley a similar dilemma. There, it cost him his job.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Phoenix, management and I had a different opinion of
Charles's value and the appropriateness of his role with
teammates,'' Westphal said. ``Here, I'm on the same page with
management about Gary.''
</P>
<P>
   What does that page say about superstars and their teammates?
</P>
<P>
   ``To the extent that (teammates) tolerate the idiosyncrasies as
much as they embrace the stars' strengths, there will be peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``To the extent they can't, there will be problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds kinda highfalutin. Whaddyamean?
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me put it this way,'' he said, smiling. ``Gary and Charles
... they ain't changin'.''
</P>
<P>
   Therein lies the crux of the Sonics' millennium remake. Payton
is going to be his usual caustic, belligerent, demanding self.
Anyone who thinks that lipstick will help this pig of a situation
hasn't been around Payton and the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   With four years left on his $87 million contract, the Sonics are
not about to deal him, if for no other reason than superstar trades
rarely work out for the team surrendering them.
</P>
<P>
   Or, for that matter, look at what happened when Phoenix in '96
traded Barkley to Houston for Robert Horry, Chucky Brown, Mark
Bryant and Sam Cassell. The Suns haven't advanced beyond the
playoffs' first round since, including Portland's 3-0 sweep this
week.
</P>
<P>
   These guys are rare talents, however infuriating they can be
from time to time.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you sat Gary down, he probably would tell you himself he's
difficult to get along with,'' Westphal said. ``That difficulty
also makes me a big fan, because it's part of his supercompetitive
nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you can curb it, but you can't instill it. When you
find someone who has it, you build on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Finding the parts to fit around Payton is a major trick, one
that will determine the future of club president Wally Walker. It
was plain this year that Payton and Detlef Schrempf were nearing
the end of their tolerance for one another. Same for Payton and
Dale Ellis. Sam Perkins wasn't sorry to leave Payton's company, and
even good pal Vin Baker was stung deeply by Payton's criticisms.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the word for years on Barkley around the league is
that he eventually wears out everybody he's around. Then again, in
the four years Barkley and Westphal were together in Phoenix, the
Chuckster averaged 23.4 points and 11.5 rebounds in the regular
season, and 26 points and 12 rebounds in the playoffs. He also
helped make Westphal in 1992-93 the winningest rookie head coach in
NBA history.
</P>
<P>
   So wear me out, Westphal is saying.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest similarity is that Gary and Charles are
strong-willed, unique individuals,'' he said. ``You must be very
confident and mature to flourish with them as teammates.''
</P>
<P>
   Egad. A player has to be mature? In the NBA? Good luck, Wally.
</P>
<P>
   When asked this week about potential roster changes, Walker
would confirm only that he wanted his core back. When pressed as to
the identity of the core, Walker mentioned only Payton and Baker,
with some approving nods thrown to the three rookies, Rashard
Lewis, Jelani McCoy and Vladimir Stepania.
</P>
<P>
   It must be presumed that everyone else is in play, either via
trades or free agency. But whoever is brought in has to get along
with Payton.
</P>
<P>
   Westphal doesn't believe that is impossible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever you don't rise to people's expectations, the
microscopes come out,'' Westphal said. ``Some of the same problems
are there when you win, but when you lose, they're magnified.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't ever recall a team that always had smooth sailing.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Westphal also doesn't want another repetition of his last
year in Phoenix, where his previous seasons of 62, 56 and 59 wins
were forgotten in a 14-19 start tainted by perceptions that Barkley
had run him over. He wants Payton to give some, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Gary has to shoot as much as he did, especially
as many threes,'' he said. ``His best role is to play a little
less, distribute the ball a little more and have more scoring
help.''
</P>
<P>
   Given Payton's messianic tendencies, is that likely?
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a summer to plan and piece things together that will
give us a much better chance to succeed,'' he said. ``I think Gary
and I came a long way. We have a chance this summer to go
further.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing like the optimism of the coach who has lived again after
being killed by a coach-killing player. Dying that way once
inspires the victim to avoid repetition.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
