<HEADLINE>
SWEEPLESS IN HOUSTON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Two straight wins and one devastating rout had the
Lakers poised to sweep a Hall of Fame trio out of the first round
of the playoffs. And then an obvious truth set in: Old legends
don't go down that easily.
</P>
<P>
   Scottie Pippen, all but left for dead after two ineffective
games, morphed back into the multitalented, end-to-end weapon that
won six rings in Chicago. And he left a stunned Lakers team in his
wake, scoring a career playoff-high 37 points to lead the Houston
Rockets to a 102-88 victory Thursday at Compaq Center.
</P>
<P>
   When Pippen wasn't dunking and driving and hitting open
3-pointers, Charles Barkley was backing into the basket, scoring 30
points and grabbing 26 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets' victory cut the Lakers' series lead to 2-1, with a
chance to tie it Saturday at Compaq.
</P>
<P>
   All the Lakers could do afterward was tip their hats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's disappointing,'' coach Kurt Rambis said.
``They're a talented ballclub, they've got great players on their
team. At the beginning of the series, if we thought we were gonna
waltz through this thing and just win three straight, we were only
kidding ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won two _ we were very fortunate to come away with a win in
Game 1, we did what we had to do in Game 2. They're back home, they
played well.''
</P>
<P>
   Really well. The Rockets showed all of the energy, hustle and
poise the Lakers had in Game 2, while the Lakers showed only
glimpses of it.
</P>
<P>
   Houston owned the boards, outrebounding the Lakers 54-42. The
Rockets took 19 offensive rebounds, converting them into 20
second-chance points. They had three times as many steals (9 to 3)
and forced 14 turnovers, leading to 15 points.
</P>
<P>
   And the Lakers kept misfiring under the frenzied pace. They hit
just 37.8 percent of their field goals, and Shaquille O'Neal (26
points, 10 rebounds) was the only Laker who made an impact _ and
even then, he missed 13 of 22 shots.
</P>
<P>
   Kobe Bryant got in early foul trouble guarding Pippen and
finished with 13 points on 5-of-17 shooting. Glen Rice had a
seven-point first quarter, then faded, finishing with 13 points on
5-of-13 shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their effort was a little better tonight, their energy was
better,'' Derek Harper conceded.
</P>
<P>
   And for Pippen, who slumped through the first two games and was
immediately torched by the local media, there was redemption. In
addition to his career-high in points, Pippen got 13 rebounds, four
assists, a steal and a blocked shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel great. I knew I had to lay it all on the line,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen went to work early, turning to his post-up game to get in
the flow. Bryant, so effective against him in the first two games,
suddenly seemed overmatched. Rice and Rick Fox fared no better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got some quick and early fouls on (Bryant), and he was just
at my mercy at that point,'' Pippen said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets, who had never led by more than seven points in this
series _ and had never led at halftime _ took a 10-point lead into
the intermission behind the suddenly rejuvenated tandem of Pippen
and Barkley. They scored 15 each in the half and combined for 17
rebounds, while the Lakers, after a fast start, struggled mightily.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal had 12 points by halftime, but Rice scored just seven _
none in the second quarter, and Bryant had six. More irritating,
however, was the Lakers' sudden onslaught of the drops _ they
turned the ball over nine times, leading to 13 points for the
Rockets. Houston scored 10 off of fast breaks, while the Lakers'
defense created few running opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers held an eight-point lead three minutes into the
second quarter, but the Rockets went on a 10-2 run to tie the game
for the first time, 36-36, with 5:30 to go, and a minute later took
their first lead at 40-38. Othella Harrington sparked the run,
scoring seven points in three and a half minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen then shredded the Lakers singlehandedly, scoring 10
points in a 12-2 run to close out the half.
</P>
<P>
   It was clear from the opening tip that the Rockets would do
everything possible to ignite Pippen, their dormant superstar who
was averaging just 8.5 points in the series. They fed Pippen on
their second possession, letting him post up against Bryant. Pippen
missed the shot, but the agenda had been set.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
