<P>
   CONGRESS-PORK (Seattle) _ On the face of it, the seven-year
battle over a Houston-based mining company's petition to blow a
900-foot hole in Buckhorn Mountain and extract the gold inside
would seem to have nothing to do with an emergency bill in Congress
to aid war refugees in Kosovo and victims of the recent Midwest
tornadoes. But that's only on the face of it. In fact, the spending
bill has become bogged down by a numbing series of attempts by
lawmakers to add in pet projects and other provisions that could
drive the final cost to more than twice the amount originally
sought for war and disaster relief by President Clinton. By Sam
Howe Verhovek and Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   SARAZEN-OBIT (Undated) _ Gene Sarazen, whose stylish, effective
swing and dogged demeanor made him one of the finest golfers of the
1920s and '30s, died Thursday in Naples, Fla. He was 97. By Larry
Dorman.
</P>
<P>
   GREENFIELD-OBIT (Undated) _ Meg Greenfield, the editor of The
Washington Post's editorial page, who brought a combination of
sharp-eyed analysis and wry wit to bear on a generation of the
nation's policy makers and politicians, died Thursday morning at
her home in Washington.She was 68. By Felicity Barringer.
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-GAMES (Los Angeles) _ In the aftermath of the shootings at
Columbine and schools elsewhere, video game makers, whose products
are increasingly coming under fire for excessive violence, have
their annual meeting in Los Angeles. By Andrew Pollack.
</P>
