<P>
   SALEM-TRAVEL (Salem, Mass.) _ Stand by the second-story window
of the nearly two-century-old Custom House here and you will find
yourself gazing over a waterfront that once linked the young United
States with the world's farthest corners. All's quiet now. But the
place once saw ships in such numbers _ en route to or from China,
Europe, the West Indies, the South Seas _ as to rank Salem among
the nation's most cosmopolitan and wealthy cities. Salem is
probably most closely linked in the public imagination with the
1692 witchcraft trials, but it contains much more of interest. By
Gustav Niebuhr.
