<DOCNO> NYT19990514.0050 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 02:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6700 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     05-14 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
BETWEEN them, the officials and Shaquille O'Neal conspired to make
Hakeem Olajuwon appear small and insignificant Thursday night.
Olajuwon has probably never made less of an impact in a crucial
game in the 15 seasons he has worn a Rockets uniform.
</P>
<P>
   And, amazingly, it didn't matter one bit.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets, as you know, have three superstars, and the other
two picked up sufficient slack to more than negate Shaq. As a
result, Houston's season will last at least 48 additional minutes,
and Scottie Pippen's season can't yet be judged a complete failure.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen still has a ways to go to undo the damage he did to his
image and his credibility in the first eight quarters of the
Rockets-Lakers series _ never mind his tepid regular season _ but
at least redemption remains a possibility.
</P>
<P>
   If the Rockets do come off the mat to beat LA, then go on to
claim the NBA championship, few people will remember his shameless
finger-pointing after Game 1 or his shameful shooting in Game 2. He
will probably even be judged worthy of his $14 million salary by
the Houston fans.
</P>
<P>
   As for Charles Barkley, if he doesn't score another point or
grab another rebound and the Rockets go down in four to the Lakers,
we can still safely say he has already earned his paltry million
bucks.
</P>
<P>
   Every darned penny.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley, the Rockets' ranking warrior on a regular basis all
year, had nothing to prove to anybody this night. Nonetheless, he
proved it anyway, cutting loose for 30 points and 23 rebounds in
the 43 minutes he spent on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   His was a hugely magnificent effort, no two ways about it,
particularly since, in his spare time, he was also asked to
pinch-hit defending O'Neal, seven inches taller, 50 pounds heavier
and almost a decade younger.
</P>
<P>
   Sir Charles measured up to every challenge.
</P>
<P>
   And Pippen, his turncoat buddy, decided to aid and abet him, for
a change.
</P>
<P>
   Scottie, of course, had questioned Barkley's smarts for fouling
O'Neal, an impossibly inept free-throw shooter, in the waning
seconds of the series opener, and he did so after his costly
turnover had cost the Rockets any chance of winning. Barkley nodded
and grinned, saying nothing. He took the high road, even taking
Pippen out for dinner that evening.
</P>
<P>
   Deep down, though, he was hurt, very hurt. After all, he has
been in Pippen's corner all season, working behind the scenes to
get the ex-Bull comfortable in a vastly different system while
subverting his own deservedly extra-large ego to feed Scottie's. It
was a case of total selflessness.
</P>
<P>
   More admirably, when Scottie stunk things up so badly in the
second game, missing every shot he put up and doing his best to
disappear from the radar screen, the Chuckster kept his mouth shut
_ not always the easiest thing for him to do.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley took the high road because to do anything less would
have torn the Rockets completely apart and possibly assured them of
being summarily swept into the offseason by LA. For public
consumption, at least, he stayed in Pippen's corner, never mind
that his loyalty had heretofore been a one-way street.
</P>
<P>
   And Scottie, glory be, would thus apologize in the most
productive, constructive way possible Thursday evening by
contributing a personal playoff best of 37 points _ plus 13
rebounds of his own _ in the Rockets' survival-mode 102-88 victory.
</P>
<P>
   We're tempted to say it's about time, but why get grumpy on such
a celebratory occasion? The Pip was outstanding, so let's give him
his due and hope he has a few more of these monster games in him.
For the Rockets to survive the Lakers he must, since it appears
Olajuwon, at 36, has more than met his match against Shaq.
</P>
<P>
   Especially since the order-keepers with the whistles around
their necks have concluded he is no longer worthy of their respect.
The rinky-dink fouls that stuck Olajuwon on the bench for all but
nine minutes of the first half and knocked him off his rhythm for
the entire game were appalling.
</P>
<P>
   That the Rockets could get by with Hakeem missing 10 of the 12
shots he took, receiving just one free throw and being held to six
rebounds tells us how different a team they have become. He remains
their center, but he's no longer the center of their universe.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen should be, for what he's taking to the bank. However,
Barkley, more often than not, has been the man. As to who takes the
lead the rest of the way, it makes no difference, as long as one or
the other does.
</P>
<P>
   We were again reminded how much experience matters in the second
season. The hotshot Houston rookies, Cuttino Mobley and Michael
Dickerson, would again be rendered virtually impotent, combining
for all of five points between them.
</P>
<P>
   Well, I say combining. Mobley scored all of the five as
Dickerson, who appeared to be a stud in the making at the end of
the regular season, took a second consecutive bagel. He's learning
the hard way about how the playoffs are different.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets can probably live with Dickerson's disappearing act.
But should Pippen go back into hiding, they're dead. While he put a
new load of pressure on himself by rising to such heights _ we're
going to expect it now _ it's the least he could do to help win
back the Chuckster's affection.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, Pippen has six rings to Barkley's none. Scottie owes
it to Chaz to keep the pedal to the metal, to try to get him one.
This was a fine start, but that's all it was _ a start.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-three games after the fact.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-14-99 0237EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990514.0051 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 02:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6701 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LAKERS-ROCKETS-HN     05-14 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-ROCKETS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
It was not artistic. It was not smooth, neat or pretty. And that
made it beautiful.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Rockets beat the Los Angeles Lakers 102-88 on Thursday night
at Compaq Center the hard way. In a game for playoff survival, the
Rockets were bloodied, battered and floor-burned but would not be
beaten.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told my guys before the game,'' Rockets coach Rudy
Tomjanovich said, ``I'd been in this situation a lot of times
before and I've never had to give a Knute Rockne speech. If I did,
I had the wrong guys in the locker room. They went out there and
played their hearts out. We talked about leaving it out on the
floor. That's what the Rockets did tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   They did what they could not in Los Angeles. They found a way to
win _ many ways unexpected, difficult and almost all based on
effort. Unlike Game 1, when they shot well to take control but let
the win slip away, they extended the series to Saturday's Game 4 by
willing themselves past the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   They made just 40.2 percent of their shots but dominated the
boards. They were in almost constant foul trouble, center Hakeem
Olajuwon limited to 28 minutes, five points and six rebounds, but
the Rockets took turns on Shaquille O'Neal until the committee of
big men, including Charles Barkley, held him in check.
</P>
<P>
   And they got sublime, determined performances from Barkley and
Scottie Pippen, who carried the Rockets through the fourth quarter
with indefatigable efforts. Barkley banged inside with everyone
from Robert Horry to O'Neal and still had to carry the offense
through the fourth quarter. Pippen played all 48 minutes with
determination and aggression he did not have in LA.
</P>
<P>
   They got a huge and necessary lift from reserve Brent Price,
whose manic, body-sacrificing intensity _ more than his 10 points,
seven assists, four rebounds, two steals and one blocked shot _
seemed to drive the Rockets through the rough spots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wow, that was a game,'' Barkley said. ``I was very proud of my
team. We got off to a bad start (falling 11 points behind) but hung
in there. Scottie played great. I was very proud of Brent Price and
Sam Mack giving us a lift. Determination comes out in a game like
this. Nobody wants to get swept. They really kicked our butts in
Game 2.''
</P>
<P>
   Pippen rose from his LA haze to have one of the greatest playoff
games of his playoff-filled career, scoring 37 points and grabbing
13 rebounds. He helped hold Glen Rice, averaging 21.5 points in the
series, to 13 points on 5-of-13 shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I have a down game, it's not the end of my career,''
Pippen said. ``I wanted the ball and the opportunity to post up. I
have to come out and just play hard. I'm going to be aggressive.
I'm not letting up.''
</P>
<P>
   Barkley, driving himself until he had to be wrapped in
ice-water-soaked towels during timeouts, had 30 points, grabbed 23
rebounds and spent crucial minutes matched up eye-to-chest on
O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy was just phenomenal,'' Tomjanovich said. ``I don't
know how he had the energy to play offense, holding up that big guy
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Barkley and Pippen scored every Rockets point in the fourth
quarter, their first 20, until a Mack free throw with 31.6 seconds
left.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers' last chance ended when, after a flagrant foul on
Pippen gave the Lakers two free throws and the ball with 38.8
seconds left, guard Derek Fisher missed his second free throw,
leaving the Lakers eight back, and Kobe Bryant missed a 3-pointer
from 26 feet.
</P>
<P>
   After Mack's free throw, the Lakers missed four shots on their
next possession, and the Lakers, who had checked out of their
hotel, could begin looking for a place to stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``You saw the intensity,'' Rockets center Antoine Carr said.
``We were running back, even when they scored. We were banging
people. We were a whole lot more active. We have to play with
heart. If we don't play with heart, it's over. We just decided if
we're going to go down, we'll go down with our guns blazing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets began the fourth quarter with Barkley tipping in a
missed shot, then passing to Pippen for a jumper to an 81-69 lead,
then their largest of the game. Having found a formula that worked,
the Rockets worked it hard. Barkley controlled the offense, posting
up inside on almost every trip down the court, and it worked almost
every time.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley scored six of the Rockets' next eight points until, with
4:23 left and the Lakers having cut a Rockets lead that had reached
13 to seven, he found Pippen alone outside. Pippen swished his 3
for a 92-82 Rockets lead, giving him 33 points, by one a playoff
career high.
</P>
<P>
   But the difference in the Rockets was clear much earlier. Price
forced jump balls with J.R. Reid and O'Neal, grabbed an offensive
rebound and redirected it to Barkley inside. He dove into the crowd
for one loose ball and face-first into Barkley's head for another.
In Barkley's five first-half minutes on O'Neal, the Lakers center
had one field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Olajuwon's immediate foul trouble, the Rockets worked
enough bodies onto O'Neal to limit him to 9-of-22 shooting for 26
points. He had 10 rebounds. And the Rockets attacked defensively,
scrambling in and out of double teams and rotations until the
Lakers could make just 37.8 percent of their shots and just four of
22 (18.2 percent) of their 3s.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't come close to laying down,'' Lakers guard Derek
Harper said. ``They played like a desperate team would play.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
