<DOCNO> NYT19990514.0052 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 02:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6702 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     05-14 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
PICK a play, almost any play.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Charles Barkley using Robert Horry like a yo-yo on a
string down in the low post, backing him along the baseline and
then whirling into the lane for that falling-away,
how-does-he-do-that little push shot that seems to chin itself over
the front rim and then snuggles into the net.
</P>
<P>
   Or smashing like one huge bowling ball into a set of tenpins,
mangling so many limbs and sending bodies flying as he wraps those
mitts around misses and turns them into big opportunities for
offensive-rebound hoops.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Scottie Pippen turning himself into a one-man version of
the Brian Setzer Orchestra, jumping, jiving and wailing all over
the court like it was his own personal dance floor. Flashing across
the baseline for the niftiest peekaboo reverse move, keeping his
feet alive to tap in his own little jump hook, spinning past Kobe
Bryant like he was just another teen-ager without a date at the
senior prom for a tomahawk dunk. The only thing missing was a zoot
suit and a long, gold watch chain.
</P>
<P>
   Pick a play, any play from the Rockets' 102-88 win over the
Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe a foul-plagued Hakeem Olajuwon taking another early seat
on the bench and Antoine Carr coming in like the hungriest Big Dawg
in the neighborhood, slamming himself into Shaquille O'Neal,
setting himself up in the passing lanes and even taking his aging
body down to the floor for loose balls.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Sam Mack coming in with a six-shooter that wasn't firing
straight, but keeping himself on the floor by chasing, bumping,
pushing, pulling, shoving, harassing Bryant up and down the court.
Taunting him, even, with a word that rhymes with witch.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Brent Price. Oh, yes, definitely Brent Price, who exploded
like a firecracker in the silverware drawer and let everybody in
the house know this wasn't a weekend in LA anymore.
</P>
<P>
   This was a night when the Lakers, using $2 motivational tactics,
checked out of their hotel rooms before the game.
</P>
<P>
   This was the game when the Rockets finally checked into the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   It was hot, intense, fiery, emotional. Everything the Rockets
were not in the last time out Tuesday night at the Forum.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley strode through the hallway of the Laptop and entered the
locker room barely 45 minutes before the opening tap, looking natty
in a suit of emerald green.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every night's a good night for the Chuckster,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And it was. He sank his teeth into 30 points and gobbled up 23
rebounds _ joining Olajuwon, Moses Malone and Elvin Hayes as the
fourth player in Rockets history to hit the 30-20 plateau in a
playoff game _ and then he was probably taken straight to the
doctor for a rabies shot.
</P>
<P>
   He went around J.R. Reid. He went through Horry. He went over
Bryant, and he even went toe-to-toe on the defensive end for long
stretches with Shaq, giving away nearly a foot in height but
nothing in fight. He did just about everything except foam at the
mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Are there any more questions about who is leading this team now?
Is there anybody left who wants to shove him out the door just
because they don't like the way he runs his mouth?
</P>
<P>
   This was the Pippen that Houston has been waiting to see since
the stretch limo dropped him on the doorstep back in January. Alert
and alive and arcing like a live wire at both ends of the floor. He
put up 27 shots, and he nailed an even dozen for a playoff
career-high 37 points and also managed 13 rebounds and four
assists.
</P>
<P>
   Let's see now. That's one for the season at $14 million. Would
the Rockets have had to pay him $742,000,000 to get the same
production for the first 52 games?
</P>
<P>
   Pippen and Barkley were the Dream Team reunited as they held off
the Lakers in the second half. Until Mack finally broke their
string with a free throw in the final 31 seconds, they had scored
30 consecutive points in taking on LA like Batman and Robin.
</P>
<P>
   If necessity is the mother of invention, then Olajuwon's foul
trouble turned Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich into the
reincarnation of Thomas Edison in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets went to a small lineup and played so big. But nobody
was so big, so huge, so gargantuan as Price. He has waited for
three years to make this kind of contribution, and he gave until it
hurt. In the second quarter alone, Price scored five points, dealt
six assists, made two steals and tied up both Shaq and Reid for
jump balls.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley and Pippen were the engines that drove the machine, but
Price was the spark in the ignition. Pick a play, almost any play,
and the machine finally hummed.
</P>
<P>
   One game that gave the Rockets hope.
</P>
<P>
   One night that gave the Lakers the unexpected _ room service.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
