<DOCNO> NYT19990514.0053 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 03:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6708 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ET-SEARCH-SFCHRON &LR;      05-14 0662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ET-SEARCH-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 COMPUTER USERS EVERYWHERE INVITED TO JOIN SEARCH FOR ETS  &HT;     By DAVID PERLMAN 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERKELEY, Calif. _ Tens of thousands of computer users from
around the world are being enlisted to participate in an ambitious
effort to detect radio signals from extraterrestrial civilizations.
</P>
<P>
   The project, called SETI &LR; home, is based on a software program
that uses idle computers around the globe to automatically analyze
data in search of oddly strong or repetitive radio signals from
distant space.
</P>
<P>
   If ET has called, scientists involved in the project hope,
someone somewhere will catch the signal.
</P>
<P>
   One doesn't have to be a brilliant hacker to participate in the
project. Almost anyone with access to the Internet can play _ and
it's the start of what will surely be the biggest mass computer
hunt in the brief history of cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning on Monday, scientists at the University of
California's Space Sciences Laboratory in Berkeley, where the
project is based, will make the free SETI software available as a
screen-saver to every computer user who visits the SETI &LR; home Web
site. The address is http://setiathome.ssl.berkeley.edu/.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 400,000 people from 96 countries have already expressed
interest in participating in the search.
</P>
<P>
   The radio buzzing and crackling that fills all of space all the
time are constantly received by the powerful radio telescope at
Arecibo in Puerto Rico. The data embedded in that noise is what
will be broken into chunks and automatically transmitted to all
computers in the global SETI &LR; home network.
</P>
<P>
   Versions of the project's free software have been developed for
Windows, Macintosh and 30 varieties of Unix operating systems, and
it can all be downloaded from the same Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever a computer equipped with the software is idle, it will
receive a chunk of data, crunch it automatically, and then send the
results to Berkeley through the Internet. The computer will then
automatically acquire a fresh chunk of data.
</P>
<P>
   Already some 12,000 people around the world have volunteered to
test the system and have racked up about 200 years of free
computing time, said computer scientist David Anderson, the
SETI &LR; home project director. And already volunteers have translated
the software instructions into 30 different languages besides
English.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm amazed at the extreme eagerness of people to use this,''
Anderson said. ``Every day I'm getting e-mail in all languages
saying `Give me the software NOW!'''
</P>
<P>
   SETI, as millions already know, stands for the Search for
Extra-Terrestrial Intelligence, and its primary focus is at the
nonprofit SETI Institute in Mountain View. The original funding for
the worldwide computer project came from the Pasadena-based
Planetary Society, whose president, Louis Friedman, called the
venture ``a grand experiment _ in science, in technology and in
society _ a global cooperative effort at the frontiers of
knowledge.''
</P>
<P>
   The project is also a new experiment in a technology called
``distributed computing,'' in which a large and complex problem
demanding huge amounts of computation is broken down into small
chunks that can be handled by many small computers distributed
anywhere in the world and linked to the main center _ in this case,
UC Berkeley's Space Sciences Laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of linking computers with many different operating
systems into a global network came from David Gedye, a UC Berkeley
graduate student in computer science.
</P>
<P>
   ``SETI &LR; home is a way of harnessing all the idle computers to
increase our computing capacity and our chance of finding
extraterrestrials,'' said Daniel Werthimer, the project's chief
scientist.
</P>
<P>
   Werthimer and his colleagues at Berkeley have been operating
several other SETI projects, including a 20-year-old quest known as
SERENDIP, or the Search for Extraterrestrial Radio Emissions from
Nearby Developed Intelligent Populations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
