<SLUG> BC-SPIN-THE-BOTTLE-STEPASHIN-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KREMLIN'S MUSICAL CHAIRS: HOW STEPASHIN CHANGED SEATS  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This timely 600-word ``separate buy'' article is from The
Independent newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By HELEN WOMACK  
 c.1999 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ ``So...'' growled Boris Yeltsin and the pause seemed to
last for an eternity before he continued: ``You are not sitting in
the right seats. Stepashin is the First Deputy. Sergei
Vladimirovich, move up.''
</P>
<P>
   The ginger-haired and, by all accounts, modest Sergei V.
Stepashin, appointed days earlier as First Deputy Prime Minister,
blushed so deeply that his ears and neck went red and changed seats
with a lesser official at the top of the table.
</P>
<P>
   On the instructions of Yeltsin's press secretary, Russian
television has cut scenes of the president rambling incoherently.
But it did show this game of musical chairs that the Kremlin leader
unexpectedly played last week in the middle of a planning meeting
supposed to be devoted to celebrations for the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Ordinary Russians took it as further evidence that their
unpredictable president was going senile. Experienced Kremlin
watchers saw it as a sign that Stepashin, who has had an up and
down career, was about to rise again.
</P>
<P>
   And indeed Wednesday Yeltsin appointed him acting prime minister
in place of the ousted Yevgeny Primakov.
</P>
<P>
   Stepashin, 47, has been dubbed by the Russian media ``the
rosy-cheeked hawk.'' Before his promotion Wednesday, he combined
the job of first deputy prime minister with that of interior
minister, which put him in charge of thousands of internal troops
and over a million police.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt Yeltsin had that in mind when he sacked Primakov, a
move he knew must enrage the communists and nationalists in the
State Duma.
</P>
<P>
   To them, the appointment of Stepashin is little short of a
Kremlin coup.
</P>
<P>
   If political passions boil over and the confrontation between
president and parliament becomes physical, as it did in October
1993, Yeltsin now has not only a loyal prime minister but also a
man who can command the tank drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Stepashin, born to a military family on a then-Soviet base in
China, began his career as a ``politrabotnik'' (political
activist), the Communist equivalent of a chaplain in the army.
</P>
<P>
   He also lectured at a military academy and wrote a doctorate on
``Party leadership in Leningrad's fire brigades during World War
II.''
</P>
<P>
   Mikhail Gorbachev's perestroika reforms gave him a better
opportunity to use his qualification as a lawyer and he became a
parliamentary deputy, known for his liberal tendencies.
</P>
<P>
   In March 1994, six months after the failure of the parliamentary
uprising against him, Yeltsin appointed Stepashin to head the FSB,
the successor to the KGB secret police. Here he gained a reputation
for being calm.
</P>
<P>
   He lost his cool, however, during the ill-fated war against
Chechnya, which Yeltsin was later to regret as his greatest
mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated by hostage-takers, who kidnapped Russian civilians in
the town of Budyonnovsk, Stepashin applied too much force, which
only increased the number of casualties, and had to resign in
disgrace in June 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin brought him back from the political wilderness in 1997,
giving him the Justice Ministry, where one of his main tasks was to
improve conditions in Russia's notoriously overcrowded and
disease-ridden jails.
</P>
<P>
   He became interior minister last March after Yeltsin sacked
Viktor Chernomyrdin's entire cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   Now Yeltsin, who Wednesday criticized Primakov for allowing
stabilizing policies to turn into stagnation, is hoping that his
protege will revitalize Russian economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
   At a cabinet meeting where Primakov said goodbye to his team,
Stepashin was blushing again as he said he had ``honestly'' not
known that he was about to he promoted over his boss's head.
</P>
<P>
   Primakov said that he wished him well. The awkward body language
gave away what the two politicians were really thinking. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this timely 600-word article, it must be purchased from
the New York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT
at 732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
