<P>
   &UR; NATO'S WAR IS NO MISTAKE _ IT'S A CRIMINAL ACT &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Hard-hitting Commentary) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By ROBERT FISK, The Independent of London &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Alas, how much longer must we endure the folly of NATO's
hopeless, cowardly war in the Balkans? Or, more specifically, how
much longer must we endure NATO?
</P>
<P>
   How soon can this vicious American-run organization be
deconstructed and politically ``degraded,'' its pontificating
generals put back in their boxes with their mortuary language of
``in-theatre assets'' and ``collateral damage?''
</P>
<P>
   In just 50 days, the Atlantic alliance has failed dismally in
everything it set out to do. NATO troops are not willing to die for
Kosovo. So what the hell is the point of NATO? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (ATTN. EDITORS: Article offers THREE helpful OPTIONAL TRIMS,
totaling 500 words: at 375 (200), 675 (75) and at 1,000 (225).
Total uncut is 1,400.) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-KILL-NATO-COMMENTARY-FISK-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HAIR-TRIGGER YELTSIN SHOOTS HIMSELF IN THE FOOT _ AGAIN &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By PHIL REEVES, Independent of London &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Boris Yeltsin Wednesday tried hard to persuade the
world that the reason he fired his prime minister and the cabinet
was because they failed to do enough for Russia's emaciated
economy.
</P>
<P>
   But his true motives for plunging the country into fresh
political chaos, and picking a perilous fight with parliament, have
more to do with pique, personal rivalry and the erratic whims of an
autocratic and unwell president...
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin has _ yet again _ dropped a bombshell.
</P>
<P>
   With a war in Europe and economic gloom at home, Russia is
without a government... &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (ATTN. EDITORS: Story can stand in 775 words; total uncut is
925) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
