<P>
   &UR; IF ONLY SOMEONE HAD BOUGHT A `FODOR'S YUGOSLAVIA 1999' &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By RUPERT CORNWELL, The Independent of London &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LONDON _ The bonehead air strike against the Chinese embassy in
Belgrade confirms the first law of those who adhere to the screw-up
theory in life: the more sophisticated the means at hand (in this
case the intelligence-gathering capability of the CIA), the more
elementary is likely to be the inevitable mistake (in this case, it
would appear, relying on an out-of-date map).
</P>
<P>
   Alas, if only someone had bought a Fodor's guide... &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (NOTE: Two helpful optional trims _ totaling 575 _ at 600 and
1,000. Total uncut version is 1,300 words.) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
