<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 07:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6845 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-NUKE-2NDLD-WRIT     05-14 0376
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-NUKE-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: development program. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The American intelligence community has suspected that China
stole W-70 design information from Lawrence Livermore since the
early 1980s, according to officials. The FBI investigation,
code-named Tiger Trap, never led to any arrests. But officials said
that the scientist who was fired as a result of the investigation
made a series of trips to China after he left the laboratory in
1981.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the idea that the stolen W-70 design technology was being
applied by China for use in its new generation of small warheads
for the DF-31 was a subject of intense controversy within American
intelligence agencies until recently.
</P>
<P>
   Some officials say that it was not until last month's
government-wide damage assessment report on Chinese nuclear
espionage that many intelligence analysts began to connect the
theft of design secrets with the evidence gathered on the DF-31 and
the ongoing modernization of China's nuclear arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   The DF-31, a solid-fuel missile, would be the first Chinese
inter-continental ballistic missile that would be moved on roads.
China test-fired its rocket motor last July, and the missile was
scheduled to be flight tested last December, The Washington Times
has reported.
</P>
<P>
   The development of the missile has apparently been slower than
that of its warhead, officials believe. China conducted six or
seven tests of the two-stage warhead the United States expects to
be deployed on the DF-31, and completed that testing in the early
1990s. U.S. officials now believe the DF-31 will carry only one
warhead.
</P>
<P>
   Once the DF-31 and other advanced missiles are deployed, China
is expected to begin to phase out its older and less accurate
ballistic missiles that carry large, bulky warheads. ``The DF-31
ICBM will give China a major strike capability that will be
difficult to counterattack at any stage of its operation, from
pre-flight mobile operations through the terminal flight phase,''
the 1996 Air Force intelligence report predicted. The ``road
mobility'' of the DF-31, the report adds, ``will greatly improve
Chinese nuclear ballistic missile survivability and will complicate
the task of defeating the Chinese threat.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
