<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 09:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6883 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS13-TAKE     05-14 1735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS13-TAKE2-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: In two takes _ take 2)
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I'm curious about the host of CNN's ``Moneyline News Hour
With Lou Dobbs.'' What is his background?
</P>
<P>
   A: Dobbs, 54, has a degree in economics from Harvard University.
So it came as a surprise to friends and family when he announced
his intention to pursue a career in journalism.
</P>
<P>
   He began his broadcast journalism career as a police and fire
reporter for KBLU-AM in Yuma, Ariz., and was a copy editor for the
Los Angeles Times before joining Seattle's KING-TV as a financial
news reporter. While there he caught the eye of CNN, which hired
him in 1980 as the network's chief economics corresponent and
anchor of ``Moneyline.'' Four years later, Dobbs became vice
president and managing editor of ``CNN Financial News,'' and in
1992 was named senior vice president of CNN.
</P>
<P>
   He was named CNN's executive vice president in May 1995 and was
responsible for the launch of CNNfn _ the first network to launch
simultaneously on TV and on the Internet _ in December 1995. In
addition to being responsible for CNN Financial News, Dobbs anchors
``Moneyline News Hour With Lou Dobbs,'' ``Business Unusual'' and
the weekend program ``Managing With Lou Dobbs.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: A program on the History Channel the other day showed the
launching of a Navy ship named the Carole Lombard. I've never heard
of it. Do you know anything about it?
</P>
<P>
   A: It wasn't a Navy vessel, said John Reilly of the Navy
Historical Center in Washington. The Carole Lombard was a Liberty
ship, one of the mass-produced merchant ships built for the Federal
Maritime Commission. It's a common misconception that ``anything
that floats'' during wartime is believed to be a naval vessel,
Reilly said, but Liberty ships had nothing to do with the Navy.
</P>
<P>
   Actress Carole Lombard, Clark Gable's wife, had been killed in a
1942 plane crash in Nevada while participating in a bond drive for
the Hollywood Victory Committee, Reilly recalled. So, he said,
someone in authority decided it would be appropriate to honor her
memory by naming a Liberty ship after her.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly said anyone interested in such vessels can find a wealth
of information in the book ``The Liberty Ships,'' by L.A. Sawyer
and W.H. Mitchell. It can be found at many libraries.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Did the taxpayers pay the cost of the trip to Europe for the
delegation led by Rev. Jesse Jackson? Was the group flown over on
U.S. military aircraft?
</P>
<P>
   A: No on both counts. The Jackson delegation's trip was
privately funded, said James Gomez of Rainbow/PUSH Coalition's
Washington office, and its members flew on commercial aircraft. The
White House press office said that as a privately funded
humanitarian mission, the group would not have been able to use
military aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Q: It was reported recently that 751 people were contacted for a
nationwide poll. That amounts to about three people per million.
How could that be called accurate?
</P>
<P>
   A: The poll-takers call the process ``probability sampling'' and
say it's the fundamental basis for all survey research. The Gallup
Organization says the basic principle is that a randomly selected,
small percentage of a population of people can represent the
attitudes, opinions or projected behavior of all of the people, if
the sample is selected correctly.
</P>
<P>
   For national Gallup polls, the objective is to present the
opinions of a sample of people which are exactly the same opinions
that would have been obtained had it been possible to interview all
adult Americans in the country. That not being possible, a sample
is taken. If every member of a population has an equal probability
of being selected, then the sample will be representative of the
population, Gallup contends.
</P>
<P>
   The 751 people you refer to is a bit smaller than Gallup's
preferred range. Gallup says the current adult population in the
continental United States is 187 million, and the typical sample
size for a Gallup poll designed to represent this general
population is 1,000 adults.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Q&AMP;A told us how to get into the lottery for Masters practice
round tickets for next year. My question: Are those of us who were
able to get tickets for this year's practice rounds automatically
in the drawing for next year, or do we have to resubmit?
</P>
<P>
   A: You'll be included in next year's drawing, said Glenn
Greenspan at Augusta National Golf Club, so don't submit your name
again. For recorded information about the 2000 Masters and practice
rounds, call 706-667-6700.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I heard something on TV about a study by Harvard or its
medical school proving conclusively the importance to children of
eating breakfast. Do you have any information about this?
</P>
<P>
   A: The latest in a series of Harvard research studies basically
affirmed just what parents have been telling their children for
years: Eating a nutritious breakfast is associated with improved
performance in school.
</P>
<P>
   The findings were reported at a U.S. Department of Agriculture
Symposium on breakfast and learning in children. Dr. Robert
Kleinman, a Harvard Medical School researcher, coordinated a series
of research studies sponsored by the Kellogg Co. ``The body of
evidence is still growing, and it points to the fact that children
who eat breakfast perform better in school,'' Kleinman reported.
``Breakfast positively impacts children's cognitive, emotional and
psychosocial behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   What to feed them is as simple as cereal, milk and fresh fruit,
the researchers said. Tracy Fox of the American Dietetic
Association said alternatives can be a peanut butter and jelly
sandwich or leftovers from the night before, and they can be eaten
either at home or at school. Whatever the food is, she concludes
that ``breakfast is the most important meal of the day'' for
children.
</P>
<P>
   Q: It was reported recently that Rep. Bob Barr (D-Ga.) was the
top House member taking privately financed ``fact-finding'' trips
last year. The item said Reps. Maxine Waters (D-Calif.) and John
Conyers (D-Mich.) were second and third, but gave no details on
their travels. Can you shed some light on this?
</P>
<P>
   A: As reported initially by The Hill, the Capitol Hill
newspaper, Barr took 25 privately funded trips last year. Many were
sponsored by conservative organizations and some by news
organizations, such as NBC, that invited him to be interviewed
about the House impeachment proceedings against President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Waters and Conyers both spoke frequently at the expense of
African-American interest groups. Waters ranked No. 2 on the list
with 17 trips last year, The Hill reported. Her husband, Sidney
Williams, former U.S. ambassador to the Bahamas, often joined
Waters on her trips. Essence Communications, on whose board Waters
sits, sent her on a three-day jaunt to the Bahamas for a music
festival empowerment seminar. Conyers came in third with 16 trips.
Most of his travel was for speeches to minority groups, The Hill
said, but he also attended the birthday of Lionel Hampton courtesy
of the jazz musician's foundation.
</P>
<P>
   These were among 790 expense-paid trips taken by members of
Congress last year at the expense of corporations, nonprofit
organizations and other interest groups. While critics contend that
the interest groups involved in such trips get a golden opportunity
to give members of Congress a skewed view of the facts, the
invitees defend the trips as invaluable learning tools.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A newspaper sports section graded the NFL draft. The text on
each team began with the word ``skinny.'' What does that mean?
</P>
<P>
   A: In this context, it's slang for ``inside information.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Q&AMP;A recently outlined the years when the new quarters
celebrating the nation's 50 states will be issued. Where can we get
these coins?
</P>
<P>
   A: The 50 state quarters will be produced at both the
Philadelphia and Denver Mints and distributed by the Federal
Reserve through the commercial banking system nationwide, just as
regular circulating quarters are today. Consumers can expect to
receive the state quarters as change when conducting normal
commercial transactions. Some already are appearing routinely in
change, and the Mint says more should be in general circulation by
late summer.
</P>
<P>
   The Mint also is selling special collector sets. Call
202-283-2646, the U.S. Mint Customer Care Center, to receive more
information about them. Information also is available on the
Internet at www.usmint.gov
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who were the people accompanying the Rev. Jesse Jackson on
his Yugoslavia trip?
</P>
<P>
   A: Delegation members: Rep. Rod Blagojevich (D-Ill.); John Wyma,
chief of staff for Blagojevich, Washington; the Rev. Dr. Joan Brown
Campbell, National Council of Churches, New York; Bishop Dimitrios
of Xanthos, Greek Orthodox Diocese in America, New York; Dr. Nazir
Uddin Khaja, American Muslim Council, Los Angeles; the Rev. Leonid
Kishkovsky, Orthodox Church in America, New York; Rabbi Steven
Bennet Jacobs, Los Angeles; Father Raymond Glen Helmick, Boston;
Mark Schlansky and Charles McLean, UPLIFT International,
Springfield, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the Rev. Roy Thomas Lloyd, National Council of Churches,
New York; Bishop Marshall Meadors Jr., United Methodist Church,
Jackson, Miss.; Pastor James Trent Meeks, Salem Baptist Church,
Chicago; Virgalem Tadesse and Marie Nelson, Rainbow/PUSH Coalition,
Washington; Landrum Bolling, Conflict Management Group, Cambridge,
Mass.; the Rt. Rev. Kodic Mitrophan, Eastern American Diocese,
Sewickley, Pa.; the Rev. Irinej Dobrijevich, Serbian Orthodox
priest, Cleveland; Dr. Zoran Svetislav Hodjera, St. Luke's Serbian
Orthodox Church, Bethesda, Md.; and Obrad Kesic, ICN
Pharmaceutical, Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I frequently hear comments about how hard it is to get
tickets to the Masters golf tournament. I've even heard that some
people bequeath their tickets to heirs as part of their will. Does
it actually happen, or is that just another urban myth?
</P>
<P>
   A: If a ticket-holding spouse dies, the surviving spouse then
can use the ticket, said Glenn Greenspan of Augusta National Golf
Club. But that's it. ``There's no leaving it in wills, no
bequeathing it,'' he added. ``That's a legend like the one saying
we pack ice around azaleas to keep them at their peak. It doesn't
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Endit
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
