   WHO'S OUT THERE?
</P>
<P>
   BREAKTHROUGHS IN SCIENCE
</P>
<P>
   These are stories that clients of DISCOVER NEWS SERVICE recently
received.
</P>
<P>
   DISCOVER NEWS SERVICE, which is available through The New York
Times Syndicate, captures all the wonders of discovery in the
environment, medicine, prehistory, space and technology.
</P>
<P>
   Each week, Discover News Service delivers fascinating,
trustworthy coverage in two tightly edited features (available in
Spanish, too). Plus superb color art brings all the discoveries to
life.
</P>
<P>
   The features described below are available for ONE-SHOT PURCHASE
by contacting Debra Weydert by phone, (732) 390-4480, or fax, (732)
390-4697.
</P>
<P>
   -------- ALL THE ART IS FREE OF CHARGE! --------
</P>
<P>
   The breakdown ...
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO'S OUT THERE? &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; THREE COLOR SLIDES ARE AVAILABLE FREE &QL; 
 &UR; (1,000 words) &QL; 
 &UR; By JEFF GREENWALD &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The search for intelligent life in outer space is going so well,
scientists need a little help from you and your home computer.
Astrophysicist Dan Werthimer is looking for aliens, or more
precisely, he is listening for them via a modified screen saver for
a personal computer. His brainchild called SETI(AT)home is a
data-saving software program that masks as a screen saver and will
allow amateur computer jockeys to receive and collate chunks of
data from outer space from the privacy of their own homes.
</P>
<P>
   slugged: BC-LISTENING-FOR-ALIENS-NYTSF. Sent to category codes
``a'' general news and ``l'' lifestyle news.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BREAKTHROUGHS IN SCIENCE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; THREE COLOR SLIDES ARE AVAILABLE FREE &QL; 
 &UR; (1,000 words) &QL; 
 &UR; By THE EDITORS OF DISCOVER MAGAZINE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   This month's news from the science front includes a Discover
dialogue with NASA astronaut and biochemist, Shannon Lucid; a
potential cure for spinal-cord injuries; a Yale astronomer's
discovery that nearby stars that closely resemble our sun shoot off
powerful flares; and an overview of NASA's 10 centers and their
specific missions.
</P>
<P>
   slugged: BC-ADVANCES-IN-SCIENCE-NYTSF. Sent to category codes
``a'' general news and ``l'' lifestyle news.
</P>
<P>
   Both stories are also available in Spanish.
