<HEADER>
A7025 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET     05-14 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Friday, May 14, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Friday. If
you have questions, please call Mark Helm at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-BUDGET (Sacramento, Calif.) _ Gov. Gray Davis is proposing
to spend $1 billion on public works projects _ including prisons,
streets and public transit _ in the largest cash investment to
repair California since the go-go years of the late Gov. Edmund G.
``Pat'' Brown. By ROBERT SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   POLICE-HARASS (San Antonio) _ Several police officers have
testified this week in a federal court trial here that they were
ordered to keep downtown streets tourist-friendly by harassing
human ``eyesores'' that included youths and the homeless. By MARO
ROBBINS.
</P>
<P>
   STOP-SIGN-FINE (Sacramento, Calif.) _ The ``California stop'' _
gliding through an intersection without actually stopping _ could
result in a $270 fine under one of several measures that have been
green-lighted by the Legislature. Last year it boosted fines for
running red lights to $270. Now it's going after stop-sign running.
By ROBERT SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   BOY-HERO (Colonie, N.Y.) _ Patrick Gavin-Brynes, 11, of Lake
George, N.Y., has over the years raised thousands of dollars for
charity through walk-a-thons, car washes, raffles, hot dog sales
and foot races. Now he's been honored by the American Red Cross as
a hometown hero. By JAY JOCHNOWITZ.
</P>
<P>
   UC-UNION (San Francisco) _ Capping a 16-year organizing drive
which generated three strikes, graduate teaching assistants at the
University of California at Berkeley have voted to unionize. By
ERIC BRAZIL.
</P>
<P>
   FORBES-SITE (Undated) _ In search of politics that swim against
the tide? This may be the Web site for you: www.forbes2000.com.
This is the virtual land of conservative politics and the national
online headquarters of Steve Forbes, the multimillionaire magazine
publisher who is seeking the Republican nomination for president
for the second time. By GEORGE RAINE.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TV-JOAN (Undated) _ Here is a question posed by ``Joan of Arc,''
the engrossing four-hour miniseries starting Sunday on CBS: If a
person is the embodiment of a myth, can that myth in fact be a
reality? Or is that person just a fraud, since a myth is merely a
morally relevant fictitious tale that can't come true? By MARK
McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-MIDSUMMER (Undated) _ You have to hand it to
Shakespeare. Any playwright who'd name one of his characters Bottom
and then turn him into a long-eared ass has a profound appreciation
for vulgar word play. That down-and-dirty playfulness is one of a
few things going for ``William Shakespeare's A Midsummer Night's
Dream,'' a whizzy, uneven take on the old fairy romp. By AMY
BIANCOLLI.
</P>
<P>
   ATOMIC-TRAIN (Undated) _ The NBC mini-series ``Atomic Train''
would be a quintessential 1959 B-movie, best viewed from the back
seat of a Chevy Bel Air convertible. Sure, it's cheesy, but it is
fun cheese. By MARK McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-CONFESSIONS (Undated) _ In Ingmar Bergman's
``Private Confessions,'' his gift for laying bare the human heart
is given haunting, sometimes lacerating, form. This is a film about
people talking to each other, with the classic Bergman themes front
and center: the painful, perhaps futile search for love, God,
freedom, truth and meaning. By WALTER ADDIEGO.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-CASTLE (Undated) _ There is nothing in movies more
crowd-pleasing than the little guy, tired of being pushed around,
getting angry enough to fight the system. The bare-bones Australian
movie, ``The Castle,'' cashes in on that theme. By EDVINS BEITIKS.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COFFEE-TABLES (Albany, N.Y.) _ Coffee tables, which have been in
use for centuries, are both useful and enhancing to a room. We
trace the evolution of their use since they originated shortly
after the mid-16th century. By FRANCES INGRAHAM. (For release
Sunday.)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS NEWS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   RAC-LUKAS (Baltimore) _ D. Wayne Lukas has trained winners of 11
Triple Crown races in a Hall of Fame career, but he's still waiting
for that exceptional 3-year-old who can win all of them in the span
of six weeks. Lukas, who will be enshrined in the Racing Hall of
Fame in Saratoga Springs, N.Y., in August, has another opportunity
with Charismatic in Saturday's 124th running of the Preakness at
Pimlico Race Course, the second jewel in the Triple Crown. By MATT
GRAVES.
</P>
<P>
   GLF-WOODS (Undated) _ Come Aug. 2, from 8-11 p.m., the sporting
world as we know it will take one giant step forward for humanity
and/or the almighty dollar. David Duval is going to take on Tiger
Woods. No. 1 in the world golfing order vs. No. 2.
Clubhead-to-clubhead. By STEVE CAMPBELL.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ Ah, democracy. What was it
Churchill said? It's the very worst form of government _ except for
all the other forms of government. He had a point. The relentless
political fundraising on the part of legislators is distasteful to
watch _ especially when you realize that few people attend these
events out of political conviction. By DAN LYNCH.
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ I have no friends. I have
colleagues, neighbors, people I talk to on the phone and nodding
acquaintances at the grocery store.Like many modern Californians, I
have a diaphanous social network of people I see regularly and
often have stimulating conversations with, but whose names I keep
forgetting. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
