<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: How-to for Hollywood
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you've ever thought you wanted to be a movie star, here's a
how-to book just for you _ one that's funny, informative and
entertaining: ``Hollywood, Here I Come!'' by Cynthia Hunter.
</P>
<P>
   You remember Cynthia Hunter. No?
</P>
<P>
   Boy, I sure do.
</P>
<P>
   We became great friends several years ago when I was on
assignment in Los Angeles for a series of stories on the weird,
weird ways of Hollywood. Cynthia, whom I met through a mutual
friend, knew the ropes as well as the yarns. We had a fun time.
</P>
<P>
   Now she's written this great book, billed as ``an insider's
guide to a successful acting and modeling career in Los Angeles,''
outlining most every aspect of a career, from your image to your
income taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia arrived some 16 years ago, having sold her car for a
ticket to stardom. Since then, she has appeared in 160 episodes of
a soap opera, six movies, 12 TV shows, 63 commercials, five cartoon
series (she does the voices) and countless training films and
modeling jobs.
</P>
<P>
   And she tells great stories. ``Hollywood, Here I Come!'' is a
whole book full. I'm going to recount just one that she told me
when we first got to know each other ...
</P>
<P>
   Holly (let's call her) wanted movies to be her life. So far it
had been the other way around.
</P>
<P>
   Naive young woman meets war hero, marries and lives dream life.
Yachts and limos. Lots of money and excitement. In the end, lots of
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   What kind of trouble?
</P>
<P>
   ``Every kind,'' Holly would say, smiling a sweet smile.
</P>
<P>
   After seven years, she decided to divorce him. Easier said than
done.
</P>
<P>
   He told her if she ever tried to leave, there'd be a new patio
in their back yard, the kind made of pea gravel. But one of those
pebbles would be the tip of her nose.
</P>
<P>
   She went into hiding for six weeks. He disappeared into South
America. She hasn't heard from him since. Knock on wood.
</P>
<P>
   Growing up, Holly had always wanted to be a movie star. When she
came out of hiding, she came to Hollywood. Along the way, a lot had
changed. Her name, her hair color, her nose, her voice. Her dream
was still the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what I want, to be an actress,'' she told her friends.
``Even if I'm never a success, I'll still have some part of it.
Something is better than nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   When she first came to Hollywood, she knew hardly anyone. There
was one man she met, who was very respectable. He was a banker. He
invited her to his house one evening. They were supposed to make
cookies.
</P>
<P>
   He'd made a special cookie for her.
</P>
<P>
   She didn't wake up until the next morning. She tried to never
let herself think about what happened to her.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing ever happened to him. He denied everything, said she'd
gotten drunk. He was still a banker. She was no longer the dreamer
...
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia, even back then, was giving advice to anybody,
especially women, who wanted to come to Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no longer the casting couch that we used to hear
about. That went out with the big studios. For the independents,
making a film is a business. But there's still plenty of sleaze
around the edges of the industry. Check everybody out. Never talk
to anyone who won't talk to your agent.''
</P>
<P>
   There's plenty more where that came from _ some 350 pages of
good advice that fills Cynthia's book. The price is $19.95. The
publisher is Yellow Deer Press, P.O. Box 7309-103, Santa Monica,
Calif., 90406; e-mail: 4dreams(at)iname.com.
</P>
<P>
   My advice: Don't leave for Hollywood without it.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(at)lcc.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915.; web page,
http://www.geocities.com/SoHo/Bistro/7147.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
