<HEADER>
A7062 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BORDERS-COLUMN15-COX     05-14 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Figuring out what will survive me
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ A depressing yet exhilarating thought
occurred to me the other day while putting the finishing touches on
a curved-back English garden bench that has dominated my spare
hours for the past two months. Of everything I've done, written or
photographed over nearly 30 years of earning my living as an
ink-stained wretch , what will survive my passing the longest are
these modest pieces of furniture I build.
</P>
<P>
   When I'm dead and gone (or now, for that matter) people won't
sit around and reread the more than 1,000 columns and 2,500
editorials I've written thus far to pay the mortgage and buy braces
for the kids. Oh, maybe my children, or past and present wives will
drag out the scrapbooks every once in a while and show the
grandkids what their long-gone patriarch used to do for a living.
But not often, and not for long.
</P>
<P>
   And who could blame them? I deal in a disposable commodity,
where yesterday's paper becomes today's fishwrap or recyclable
material. I have no ambition to do any more than try to entertain
you for a few moments while you eat breakfast on Sunday morning, or
settle back after church to finish reading the paper. I'm happy
enough to do that, along with writing editorials that provoke
readers to think, to write nasty letters, or to maybe try to change
the way things are. It's a great way to make a living. But it's not
literature, at best a modest rough draft of history in our little
town and in my modest life.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's why I turned to making furniture as a pastime. Let
me hasten to note that I am not particularly good at this hobby.
I've gotten better at it over the past months, but this won't be a
second career. Friends are polite, but I see the flaws and resolve
to do better.
</P>
<P>
   To date I've built:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A cabinet to hold cassettes.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A few jewelry boxes given away as presents.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Two Adirondack chairs and a matching table.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The aforementioned garden bench.
</P>
<P>
   If I had to put a price, including labor, on the bench, for
example, I would have to charge about $2,000 to break even. It's
made entirely of red oak that I bought rough cut, planed myself and
cut to size. It's not a bad looking bench, though I see its flaws _
the curve that's not quite perfect, the slight gaps on a few of the
slats, the mortise-and-tenon joints that are off by maybe a
sixteenth of an inch.
</P>
<P>
   You could buy an absolutely perfect, machine-made bench for
about $250 max. I'm going to have to get a lot faster at this to
consider doing it for a post-retirement living.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble is, much as I love working with wood, making the same
thing twice bores the fire out of me. I about had to beat myself to
get through making the second Adirondack chair, though it only took
a third as long as the first one. The joy for me is in creating
something I've never built before. Doing the same thing over and
over is getting too close to drudgery for my
attention-deficit-disordered mind. Nope, best stick to my day job
and hope the 401K does well enough to tide me over in the golden
years.
</P>
<P>
   I wonder sometimes about where these pieces will end up someday,
after I'm stuck in the ground. Our house is filled with antique
pieces of furniture, some of which I picked up here and there over
the years, the rest inherited from my wife's large family. It's
fine stuff: a pie safe refinished by her dad; an old buffet I
bought at the flea market back in college; a one-of-a-kind 1940s
vertical filing cabinet I bought for $50 and have been offered 20
times as much for; a dresser delicately scrolled with intricate
designs; and the 19th century oak desk on which I'm writing now,
which once served as a dining room table for who knows how many
families.
</P>
<P>
   Woodworkers made these pieces. Maybe they did it for a living,
maybe not. Maybe it was a hobby, like it is for me. Like my pieces,
none are perfect, but they're solid, comfortable and will survive
long after a thin veneer-covered piece of particle board has turned
to dust. The Adirondack chairs will provide comfort to someone many
years after I'm gone, as will the garden bench.
</P>
<P>
   The owners might not know the progeny of their furniture as they
sit and sip a cool drink on a summer evening. But maybe they'll
think good thoughts about the woodworker and appreciate the time
and love that went into those pieces. That's reward enough for me.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of The Nacogdoches Daily
Sentinel. E-mail: gborders(AT)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
