A7066 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EXPANDED-NATO15-COX     05-14 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXPANDED-NATO15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. seeks greater role for NATO
 &HT;    By Sharen Shaw Johnson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Allegations of Yugoslav war crimes, ``ethnic
cleansing'' and genocide; controversy over the morality (and
efficacy) of NATO's air war; the Chinese embassy bombing: They
capture our headlines, but history may see them as no more than
sideshows to the main event _ or, at most, its trigger.
</P>
<P>
   Because Dayton has such strong, numerous ties to that troubled
land and because almost every major Dayton industry already feels
pressure to compete internationally, we would be well-advised to
understand said main event. Here is one view: Yugoslavia may be our
first clear look at the new alliances replacing the Cold War's
east-west split.
</P>
<P>
   These alliances are young enough to remain fluid. But generally,
NATO powers are arrayed against a bloc that has both China at its
core and a gravitational pull that attracts U.S. antagonists such
as Iraq. Russia's role? The wild card.
</P>
<P>
   Prevailing in Yugoslavia is vitally important for the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization and its lead player, the United
States; the Clinton administration has flagged that NATO is its
choice to replace the United Nations as top world peace-keeper.
This is relatively new; four years ago, NATO teetered on the canyon
rim of collapse over U.S. reluctance to back the U.N.'s
French-British mission in Bosnia. But China may have made NATO more
attractive to Washington by using its U.N. Security Council veto to
thwart U.S. aims.
</P>
<P>
   So by December, U.S. officials were unveiling the armature they
hoped would support a new, more muscular NATO. When the North
Atlantic Council met in Brussels to set the agenda for this April's
50th-anniversary NATO summit, the Clinton administration announced
that it would propose a NATO clearinghouse for intelligence sharing
by Washington. The theory: More sophisticated intelligence would
produce allies more alert to the world's danger spots and more
willing to help police them. The United States made clear that it
was targeting both rogue states, such as Iraq, and terrorist
groups.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials also began lobbying at this meeting for greater
NATO collaboration to destroy weapons of mass destruction, such as
Iraqi leader Saddam Hussein's suspected biochemical arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   NATO and U.S. officials fleshed out this view in speeches and
events leading up to NATO's historic admission of former East Bloc
members Poland, the Czech Republic and Hungary on March 12:
</P>
<P>
   _ On March 8, NATO spokesman Jamie Shea told Radio Free Europe
the alliance would update its mission statement at its anniversary
summit to help ``cope with future threats. . . proliferation of
weapons of mass destruction, including nuclear, biological and
chemical weapons; the emergence of 'rogue' states; and the access
of terrorist organizations to 'designer weapons.' ``
</P>
<P>
   _ On March 10 in London, Deputy Secretary of State Strobe
Talbott told British military leaders NATO must be better able to
deal with the ``challenges that we are more likely to face. . .
ethnic strife, regional conflict, weapons of mass destruction and
missile proliferation.'' He reassured them that the White House had
no blueprint for a ``global NATO'' but added that the alliance
``has always had broader political functions,'' such as helping
keep Greece and Turkey at peace.
</P>
<P>
   _ On March 12, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright told Polish
Public TV, ``There are many new threats that are much harder to
describe. We don't have a single enemy. That is why it is so
important to keep NATO vibrant and relevant, to be able to deal
with the new threats, which are weapons of mass destruction, ethnic
conflicts, divisions over borders.''
</P>
<P>
   The stage was set _ but then Yugoslavia erupted. NATO's 50th
anniversary, in Washington on April 23-25, was overshadowed by the
immediate drama of its controversial new war. Still, the leaders
held a solemn ceremony in which each signed a ``vision statement''
that would expand NATO's role as Albright and Talbot outlined.
</P>
<P>
   The term _ ``vision statement'' _ was significantly informal: It
differs enough from NATO's current mission that were it considered
a treaty, the leaders arguably would have to return to their
governing bodies for reratification. And in a series of muddled
votes about the Yugoslav air war, the Republican Congress has
indicated its unhappiness at the extent of U.S. involvement with
NATO.
</P>
<P>
   That's unfortunate: The Clinton administration's vision for an
expanded NATO makes sense. We need look no further than Baghdad or
Belgrade to realize that the Cold War nuclear threat has been
replaced by the almost greater terror of rogues with poison-packed
warheads. The United Nations has shown itself inherently incapable
of containing such threats. And halting as NATO intervention has
been against atrocities in Bosnia and Kosovo, it at least
acknowledges that those nations with
</P>
<P>
   Sharen Shaw Johnson is an editorial writer for The Dayton Daily
News. E-mail: sharenjohnson(AT)coxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
