<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SILVERSTEIN-POEM15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Silverstein's time a lesson in rhyme
 &HT;    By Brian Colligan
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, N.C. _ Here is a poem dedicated to author and
songwriter Shel Silverstein, who died on Monday:
</P>
<P>
   How can one try
</P>
<P>
   to measure a life,
</P>
<P>
   That mixture of laughter, of fear and of strife?
</P>
<P>
   It may be awards or achievements bestowed,
</P>
<P>
   Or perhaps walking down a number of roads.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps by the number of those mourning the loss,
</P>
<P>
   Thinking for hours about society's cost.
</P>
<P>
   But it's probably those who simply just smile
</P>
<P>
   And think of the joy you brought for a while
</P>
<P>
   And in that spirit think long and then strive
</P>
<P>
   To do what they can to keep your spirit alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's easy,'' you say from your new perch above
</P>
<P>
   ``Talk to your children with nothing but love
</P>
<P>
   Help them to learn to reach and to grow
</P>
<P>
   Teach them there's nothing that they shouldn't know
</P>
<P>
   That's how I'll know that I've done something well
</P>
<P>
   For the benefits reaped will be unparalleled''
</P>
<P>
   The children, you know, were the point of it all
</P>
<P>
   They all learned from him, the big and the small.
</P>
<P>
   Shel Silverstein graced this world for a time,
</P>
<P>
   Filling blank pages with magical rhyme.
</P>
<P>
   We lost him on Monday _ a terrible day
</P>
<P>
   And though he was silenced, he left more to say.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Light in the Attic,'' and ``The Giving Tree,''
</P>
<P>
   His books were a journey, and something to see.
</P>
<P>
   For a good many years he polished his craft,
</P>
<P>
   He was good for a lesson and good for a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   But words are forever and in that spirit he lives,
</P>
<P>
   And the messages written will continue to give.
</P>
<P>
   And though the loss is like that of a friend's
</P>
<P>
   We will meet again where the grand sidewalk ends.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Colligan writes for The Daily Reflector, Greenville, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
