A7068 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARC-REVIEW15-COX     05-14 0464
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARC-REVIEW15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Searing Sobieski lends fire to `Joan of Arc'
 &HT;    By Kevin D. Thompson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Talk about girl power!
</P>
<P>
   Joan D'Arc, that army-slaying peasant girl, had more clout than
500 Spice Girls. That's what happens when you see angelic visions,
boast a direct hot line to God and help save a wartorn France.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Joan of Arc,'' CBS' lavish and beautifully filmed
miniseries, our 16-year-old heroine (Leelee Sobieski) is the
embodiment of steely courage and doe-eyed innocence. In fact,
Sobieski, who resembles a younger Helen Hunt, gives a star-making
turn as France's doomed savior.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joan of Arc'' tells the age-old tale of a young girl chosen by
God to help pry France from England's iron grip. As Joan is told by
a caring nun (Olympia Dukakis), she has a gift. And that
touched-by-an-angel gift enables her to see religious visions and
hear the voices of St. Catherine.
</P>
<P>
   But Joan doesn't understand her gift. Teens, you know, have a
tough enough time getting through life without hearing voices.
Since the gods tend to desert Joan when she needs them most and
aren't always that specific about her destiny, you can't blame the
poor lass for being a tad confused.
</P>
<P>
   But when the mission becomes clear, a courage-filled Joan sets
out to lead a violent revolt against the cursed English.
Unfortunately for Joan, it was a thankless job. At age 19, she was
burned at the stake after being charged with heresy.
</P>
<P>
   At $21 million, CBS didn't skimp on what is the centerpiece of
the network's sweeps programs. With wonderfully drab costumes and
even drabber sets, the producers faithfully re-created 15th-century
France in the Czech Republic.
</P>
<P>
   Christian Duguay's (''The Assignment'') artful, sure-footed
direction gives ``Joan of Arc'' a sweeping, epic look. The
super-slow-motion battle scenes are especially stunning. While four
hours is a bit long for most miniseries _ unless it's ``Roots'' or
``Rich Man, Poor Man'' _ ``Joan of Arc'' stays interesting despite
a few slow spots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joan of Arc'' also features a wealth of inspired performances.
An all grown-up but still boyishly charming Neil Patrick Harris
(Doogie Howser M.D.) is at his slimy best as King Charles, the
ruler who ultimately betrays unsuspecting Joan. Peter O'Toole gets
to chew half the scenery as a hard-charging bishop. The always
menacing and gravelly voiced Robert Loggia, however, is woefully
miscast as a kind-hearted local priest.
</P>
<P>
   But this film belongs to Sobieski. And her searing performance
gives ``Joan of Arc'' its strength _ and heart.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin D. Thompson writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
