A7069 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CASTLE-REVIEW15-COX     05-14 0430
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CASTLE-REVIEW15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MOVIE REVIEW: A devoted father defends his abode from bulldozers
 &HT;    By Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ It is reassuring to know that certain
deeply held beliefs are universal. That folks on the other side of
the world also have contempt for government, distrust of lawyers,
anger at powerful corporations and affection for any simple soul
who can triumph against all odds to protect his home.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, yeah, and an appreciation of a well-written comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Direct from Australia, the land that gave us such cultural
milestones as ``Babe'' and ``Crocodile Dundee,'' make way for ``The
Castle.'' No, not a medieval costume drama but an enormously
audience-friendly comedy about one man's battle to keep his
ramshackle abode from being bulldozed. Who wouldn't root for the
Kerrigans to bumble their way to victory?
</P>
<P>
   True, the house is in the Melbourne airport landing path,
beneath a forest of high-power towers and over a toxic landfill.
But to Darryl Kerrigan, a tow-truck operator who dotes on his wife
and four children, his home is a castle. A castle about to be
``compulsorily acquired'' for airport expansion, until Darryl
stands his ground and fights his way through the Aussie legal
system.
</P>
<P>
   From the fable-like tongue-in-cheek tone that first-time feature
director Rob Sitch concocts, the resolution is never really in
doubt. The fun is getting there, laughing at thick-headed but
incredibly well-meaning Darryl and warming to his daft but
endearing family exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   Lovingly, he compliments wife Sal for her rudimentary cooking
creations (``What do you call that?'' ``Chicken . . . with
seasonings.''). Like big-time wheeler-dealers, he and son Steve
mull the second-hand bargains advertised in the Trading Post,
weighing the just price for, say, jousting sticks. And you'll never
convince Darryl that imprisoned son Wayne is truly guilty of
robbing that bank.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's overcooked-shrimp-on-the-barbie dry humor comes from
Sitch and his longtime comedy collective _ Santo Cilauro, Tom
Gleisner and Jane Kennedy. They're fixtures of Australian
television, now jumping into the feature-film pool. Even though
they have begun at the shallow end, when you compare their results
to the sledgehammer-obvious, gross-out comedies Hollywood has been
serving up, ``The Castle's'' wry style is a welcome breeze from
Down Under.
</P>
<P>
   Hap Erstein writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
