<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 11:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7071 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOAN-OF-ARC-SPELL15-C     05-14 1327
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOAN-OF-ARC-SPELL15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Under the spell of Joan of Arc
 &HT;    By Michael Browning
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Leelee Sobieski, the 16-year-old actress
who plays Joan of Arc in the upcoming TV miniseries, told Parade
magazine that, to prepare for the part, she read Mark Twain's
``Joan of Arc.''
</P>
<P>
   It was an amazing statement. Nobody reads Mark Twain's ``Joan of
Arc.''
</P>
<P>
   The book was panned when it was published in 1896 and has been
panned over and over again since. It is universally deplored, even
ridiculed, as the worst novel Twain ever wrote. His own close
friend, William Dean Howells, spoke of ``Joan of Arc'' with pity
and regret.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish he had frankly refused to attempt it at all,'' Howells
said.
</P>
<P>
   When the book came out, one reviewer said only one person in the
world had read it clean through, and it was he, the reviewer. He
urged everyone else to give it a miss, because of its ``egregious
dullness.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the novel, with all its flaws and outright silliness, is one
more feather in Joan's cap _ Twain has her wearing an absurd cap
with floppy feathers in some scenes _ one more proof that the Maid
of Orleans has the power to bewitch even the clearest intellect,
make believers of agnostics, make scoffers pray. Mark Twain had
ridiculed Mormons and Christian Scientists. He toured the Holy Land
with a brilliant, lucid wit in ``Innocents Abroad,'' his very first
novel.
</P>
<P>
   He fell headlong at the feet of Joan of Arc.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is easily and by far the most extraordinary person the
human race has ever produced,'' he wrote in a 1904 essay, years
after his book had been damned by critics. He couldn't get over
Joan.
</P>
<P>
   We cannot get over her either. She had her first vision at the
age of 16 in her hometown of Domremy. At 17, she was besieging
cities and commanding the armies of France. She was captured at the
siege of Paris, tried by a French court friendly to the English,
found guilty and burned at the stake as a witch, aged 19. A second
trial rehabilitated her posthumously.
</P>
<P>
   When she was canonized by Pope Benedict XV in 1920, a squadron
of World War I vintage biplanes flew high over her statue in Rouen,
the town where she was combusted. It was one of the first
``fly-overs'' in parade history.
</P>
<P>
   She is today the patron saint of France and of all French
soldiers who are Catholic. A chapel where she prayed has been
brought, stone by stone, to a university in Minnesota. The name of
the bishop who prosecuted her _ Cauchon _ is an insult in French
even today.
</P>
<P>
   Enormous Internet Web sites have sprung up around her. Modern
feminists, gays and lesbians claim her as one of their own (one of
the charges brought against her at trial was that she wore pants).
You can even call up a ``magic eye'' image of Joan on your computer
at http://www.stjoan-center.com/p00591.jpg _ a stereogram. You can
stare at it until she appears to you, emerging from a sea of
autumn-colored pixels, red and gold.
</P>
<P>
   She lived from 1412 to 1431, but her cult, her spell, is very
much alive. Each generation has to come to terms with Joan, her
purity, her incredible career, her supernatural strangeness.
</P>
<P>
   In the run-up to her being declared a saint in 1920, liberals
and conservatives in France both supported canonization, but for
different reasons. Conservatives thought she would reinforce
Catholic morals and values. Liberals and socialists saw her as a
firebrand revolutionary against the entrenched power of the state.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, to the French, who in World War I had lost 895,000
soldiers in action, along with another 420,000 who died of wounds
or disease, Joan of Arc was something talismanic, a symbol of
France, victorious even amid the flames.
</P>
<P>
   But one keeps coming back to Twain. What was it about Joan of
Arc that so fascinated the cynical, skeptical humorist who saw so
clearly through all the folly? Modern scholars have suggested Twain
modeled Joan after his beloved daughter, Susy Clemens, who died
suddenly of spinal meningitis, aged 24 in 1896.
</P>
<P>
   Twain's grief over the loss of his daughter may have spilled
over into Joan of Arc. The book is at times almost incoherent, shot
through with strange lights and shadows, flights of rhetoric and
bizarre asides.
</P>
<P>
   Chapter 19 has absolutely nothing to do with Joan of Arc. It
contains a ghost story, in which the narrator and some companions
spend the night in a haunted house, tormented by screams and
gibberings. When a wall is broken down, a hidden chamber is
revealed. On its floor are two objects: ``a rusty sword and a
rotten fan.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now you know all that I know. Take the pathetic relics and
weave about them the romance of the dungeon's long-vanished inmates
as best you can,'' Twain writes. It's as if he is sleepwalking.
It's as if he doesn't care if the reader can follow him. It's as if
Joan of Arc drove him half-mad.
</P>
<P>
   The frontispiece of Joan, in the 1899 Harper's edition of
Twain's collected works, is a bizarre iconic work by an otherwise
unknown artist, F.V. DuMond, which makes her look like a cross
between a saint and a steel robot, like something out of the
Terminator movies, or Fritz Lang's Metropolis.
</P>
<P>
   She is clad in shining metal, her lethally spiked, metal-shod
feet rest on the head of the English King Henry V, the man who
dared beat the French at the battle of Agincourt in 1415. She wears
the crown of martyrdom. She grasps a sword, a staff with a
fleur-de-lis and a spear. Her armored legs seem welded, bolted,
riveted shut, in a stern denial of any conceivable sexuality.
</P>
<P>
   Cooler-headed historians have pointed out that the real Joan
enjoyed combat almost too much.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fever of battle had entered her blood,'' writes Will
Durant in ``The Reformation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Acclaimed as inspired and holy by half of France, she almost
forgot now to be a saint, and became a warrior. She was strict with
her soldiers, scolded them lovingly, and deprived them of the
consolations that all soldiers hold as their due; and when she
found two prostitutes accompanying them, she drew her sword and
struck one so manfully that the blade broke and the woman died.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Twain doesn't explore this side of Joan. For him, the
French girl is perfection incarnate, a lily in a degenerate world.
Twain himself detested the oozing wealth of the 1890s in the United
States, an era he called scornfully ``The Gilded Age.''
</P>
<P>
   So, in a curious way, his view of Joan strikes a chord in our
own times, when large corporations merge and enlarge themselves,
laying off thousands of workers in the process.
</P>
<P>
   Is this such bad writing?
</P>
<P>
   ``She was truthful when lying was the common speech of men; she
was honest when honesty was become a lost virtue; she was a keeper
of promises when the keeping of a promise was expected of no one;
she gave her great mind to great thoughts and great purposes when
other great minds wasted themselves upon pretty fancies or upon
poor ambitions; she was modest, and fine, and delicate when to be
loud and coarse might be said to be universal; she was full of pity
when a merciless cruelty was the rule; she was steadfast when
stability was unknown, and honorable in an age which had forgotten
what honor was; she was a rock of convictions in a time when men
believed in nothing and scoffed at all things; she was unfailingly
true in an age that was false to the core; she maintained her
personal dignity unimpaired in an age of fawnings and servilities;
she was of a dauntless courage when hope and courage had perished
in the hearts of her nation; she was spotlessly pure in mind and
body when society in the highest places was foul in both . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   Now she is back, this troublesome paragon: Back to rebuke us
again, back to remind us there is more to life than life itself.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Browning writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
