<HEADER>
A7072 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIDSUMMER-REVIEW15-CO     05-14 0613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDSUMMER-REVIEW15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MOVIE REVIEW: `Dream' no scream, but laughs fly fast in fairy
fable
 &HT;    By Gary Schwan
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Perhaps only ``Hamlet'' among
Shakespeare's plays has gotten stranger treatment than ``A
Midsummer Night's Dream.'' The interpretations have often had a
Freudian bent.
</P>
<P>
   So would the new film version of the quirky comedy turn out more
weird than whimsical? A mean sexual nightmare, for example, rather
than a fanciful tale of romantic mischief and misalliances?
</P>
<P>
   No. While the movie has been relocated to 19th century Italy, it
hasn't been re-interpreted in light of the 19th century Austrian.
As directed by Michael Hoffman (''Restoration''), it is a visually
beautiful romp, largely faithful to The Bard, full of very broad
gags, moonshine and fairy dust.
</P>
<P>
   What it isn't is magic. And this story requires an hypnotic
charm to make us drop our hip cynicism and get into the spirit _
or, should we say, spirits _ of things.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to say why the filmmakers decided to place the story
in 19th century Tuscany, unless it was to grab the chance to let
folks wander an enchanted forest on bicycles, and fill the
soundtrack with operatic arias.
</P>
<P>
   Although it's jarring at first to hear Elizabethan English
spoken in this setting, we get used to it. But it may also take
some time to follow the plot for those not used to the play:
</P>
<P>
   Hermia (Anna Friel) loves Lysander (Dominic West). But her
father has ordered her to marry Demetrius (Christian Bale), and the
Duke (David Straithairn) reluctantly backs up papa.
</P>
<P>
   So the frustrated lovers elope. However, Helena (Calista
Flockhart) is also in love with Lysander, and warns Demetrius of
the plans. He takes off after the pair, with an exasperated Helena
pedaling along behind.
</P>
<P>
   They wind up in a moonstruck forest that could pass for Hugh
Hefner's backyard. It seems that even the fairies are having a
tough time in the love department. Oberon (Rupert Everett) is mad
at Titania (Michelle Pfeiffer), and uses his impish servant Puck
(Stanley Tucci) to play mischief on everybody, fairies and humans.
</P>
<P>
   As it happens, also wandering the forest is a group of workmen
from town, who want to rehearse an amateur play. Led by Bottom,
(Kevin Kline) these bumblers also get caught up in the confusion.
</P>
<P>
   Will everything work out? Will the right lovers pair off, and
will the actors pull off their silly play? Will the ``dream''
affect reality? It's another play, but will it be a case of ``all's
well that ends well?''
</P>
<P>
   The cast is fine, including the flighty Flockhart (Ally McBeal
). The play is less famous for its soliloquies than its one liners,
such as ``What fools these mortals be.'' But except for a rather
screechy Friel, the actors present less familiar dialogue with
clarity.
</P>
<P>
   But it must be admitted that the film works best when the comedy
is presented in a thoroughly contemporary manner, and the audience
can take its cues as to when to laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Tucci is irrepressible as the ironic Puck. But Kline steals the
movie as a hammy Bottom, the town joke with a romantic soul. It's a
sight when he's turned into a donkey, and the gorgeous Pfeiffer
murmurs words of love to this braying jackass.
</P>
<P>
   When the workmen finally get to put on their play, the shtick is
straight out of early television _ so lousy and full of mishaps
it's almost charming.
</P>
<P>
   Just like the film itself _ almost, but not quite, charming
enough to make us believe in fairies.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Schwan writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
