<HEADER>
A7073 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-MUSSOLINI-REVIE     05-14 0605
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-MUSSOLINI-REVIEW15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MOVIE REVIEW: Odd, expatriate ladies ignore Mussolini's big, fat
boot
 &HT;    By Gary Schwan
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ ``Tea With Mussolini'' is a quaint title
for a quaint movie about quaint people. Oh, let's be honest.
Eccentric people. They're Brits.
</P>
<P>
   This charming, sentimental flick is about a gaggle of old gals
keeping their lips stiff in Fascist Italy. It's soap opera,
drenched in atmosphere. But how many sudsers can boast a cast of
Joan Plowright, Judi Dench, Maggie Smith, Lily Tomlin and Cher?
</P>
<P>
   Or Franco Zeffirelli as director? His romanticism, put to good
use in bravura adaptations of operas, becomes a tad mushy in this
case. And the film eventually loses some steam, turning predictable
and occasionally clunky.
</P>
<P>
   But Zeffirelli has an eye for beauty. He should, since the
Florentine is filming his native Tuscany. Indeed, the movie is
adapted from the director's autobiography.
</P>
<P>
   The English flocked to Italy. It was cheap, sunny and full of
art. This made up for the fact that Italy was also full of
Italians. British culturati nestled in cities such as Florence,
soaking up the atmosphere while remaining very John Bullish.
</P>
<P>
   English such as the ``Scorpioni'' _ the scorpions. That's what
the Italians call a hardy band of older ladies noted for their
sharp tongues. The film opens in Florence in 1935. There's a
foreshadowing of political trouble, but Mussolini seems to be
simply a pomposity with a knack for train schedules.
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, we observe the Scorpioni through the eyes of a boy
named Luca (Zeffirelli's alter ego.) Born out of wedlock, his
mother is dead, and his Italian father wants as little to do with
him as possible. The ladies take him under their wings, especially
gentle Mary Wallace (Plowright). She introduces the lad to
Shakespeare and the possibilities of a life of art.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Luca leaves for school, returning as war breaks out
and the Scorpioni are interned as enemy nationals, much to the
chagrin of bossy, bigoted Lady Hester (Smith). The widow of a
former ambassador, she has it in her head that she possesses a
special relationship with Mussolini, with whom she once had tea.
(Thus, the film's title.)
</P>
<P>
   Danger, or at least degrading circumstances, face the Scorpioni,
including two Americans _ a butch archaeologist (Tomlin) and a
rich, Jewish, ex-Ziegfield girl (Cher). Luca (attractive newcomer
Baird Wallace) is now on the verge of manhood, and he's called on
to make a mature decision in a life-or-death matter involving
Cher's character.
</P>
<P>
   Beautifully filmed, the movie captures the languor of lazy,
art-filled days in prewar Florence. The multi-talented Zeffirelli
could also have been a designer. Witness the icy marble hallways of
Il Duce's chilly headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Plowright, whose face has become more and more lumpy and lovable
with age, is especially poignant as Luca's wise surrogate mother.
Smith is nicely pursed-lipped as the haughty, self-appointed leader
of the Scorpioni. Dench has a lesser role as an eccentric, would-be
artist, but we know what she can do with lesser roles.
</P>
<P>
   Cher mixes warmth and theatricality as a flashy rich woman with
a heart of gold. Tomlin is all dry sarcasm as the bemused observer
of The Scorpioni and their foibles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tea With Mussolini'' may have a few too many lumps of sugar.
But the quiet film often cuts through the sentimentality to touch
the heart.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Schwan writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
