<P>
   RELIGION-FLAKES - The Rev. Floyd Flakes, one of the leading
figures in the black church, will be in Atlanta May 18 to speak at
New Birth Missionary Baptist Church. Flakes, a former congressman
and now pastor of Allen African Methodist Episcopal Church in New
York, will talk about achieving your dreams, a topic he explores in
the just published ``The Way of The Bootstrapper''
(HarperSanFrancisco, $23, 253 pages), which details his rise from
poverty to Congress. (Blake, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 12.
</P>
<P>
   MILITARY-WITCHES - KILLEEN, Texas - The robed high priestess
turned her back to the fire, faced a makeshift outdoor altar and
blessed the essentials of life: water, bread and salt. ``Great
goddess Freya, bless this creature of the Earth to your service,''
she recited, after placing the shiny blade of her dagger over a
small bowl of salt. ``May we always honor the blessed Earth, its
many forms and beings.'' This gathering of witches celebrating the
vernal equinox didn't take place some hidden glen but on Fort Hood,
the largest military base in the United States, and the witches
were active-duty Army. Three years ago, Fort Hood's top brass
recognized Wicca as a legitimate faith, and the post became the
first U.S. military installation to allow space for neo-pagan
rituals. Now other U.S. military bases worldwide are following
suit, and the chaplain at Fort Hood is considered the Army expert
on the unorthodox religion that is growing rapidly in the military.
The chaplain fields calls from colleagues around the world and even
the chief chaplain's office at the Pentagon. The biggest problem
with Wicca, he says, is other people's ignorance. (Perkes, Austin
American-Statesman). MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   WICCA-BELIEFS and WICCA-HISTORY sidebars. (Perkes, Austin
American-Statesman) ALSO MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
