<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRIENDSHIP AT THE END OF THE MILLENNIUM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ I have no friends. I have colleagues, neighbors,
people I talk to on the phone and nodding acquaintances at the
grocery store.
</P>
<P>
   That's it, the perfect arrangement for a columnist.
</P>
<P>
   This dawned on me the other day when I saw a new doctor and had
to fill out the form on whom to notify in case of emergency.
</P>
<P>
   My wife, my best and only friend, wouldn't want to hear the
news. My editor might.
</P>
<P>
   There wasn't anybody to call in case I lapsed into a coma
reading old Smithsonian magazines in the waiting room.
</P>
<P>
   Like many modern Californians, I have a diaphanous social
network of people I see regularly and often have stimulating
conversations with, but whose names I keep forgetting.
</P>
<P>
   One thing you can say for these low-maintenance relationships:
You never have to invite these people to dinner.
</P>
<P>
   The downside (or upside) of that is less housecleaning.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; -- &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Just this week I had a nice conversation at Tully's coffeehouse
on Fillmore Street with a guy who was hanging out with his young
son before going to work in his home office.
</P>
<P>
   This home-office worker and I compared notes on growing up back
East in ethnic neighborhoods where kids knew the old-fashioned joys
of family, food, friends and beating the bejabbers out of kids from
other ethnic neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   See, maybe that close-knit neighborhood stuff isn't so great.
</P>
<P>
   Reminiscing about it is better, and you can make up better lies
if you're reminiscing with a low-maintenance coffeehouse buddy.
</P>
<P>
   I have scads of coffeehouse buddies whose names I always forget.
With one coffeehouse buddy who's a musician, I talk about music, a
subject I know barely enough about to last one non-grande coffee.
</P>
<P>
   Another coffeehouse buddy is a distinguished psychologist, and
over a latte she'll give me a psychological profile of Bill Clinton
she'd never give me over the phone.
</P>
<P>
   A coffeehouse is also one of the few places a graying fogey like
me can make eye contact with a young woman with a nose ring, even
if she doesn't smile when the fogey tips her.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; -- &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Let's see, who else is in my low-impact social network?
</P>
<P>
   There's the homeless guy on the corner who always rocks back and
forth and says thank you, even though my commitment to him is about
one quarter a month.
</P>
<P>
   I've got about a dozen maitre d's and restaurant owners I really
like, but don't see often enough because of the mortgage lenders
I've never met.
</P>
<P>
   My garbage man and mailman are terrific, and I try to tip them
every Christmas, or at least wave when they're blocking my car.
</P>
<P>
   I've come to like the contractor who has been putting an
addition on the house across the street for longer than it takes to
build the average high-rise. He's very considerate, and did some
great repairs on my driveway his cement trucks turned into talcum
powder.
</P>
<P>
   I've liked a lot of local bus drivers, but for some reason I
never get to see them again. Of course, when you have 3,000 drivers
and only five working buses, the odds of seeing the same driver
twice are small.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; -- &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fleeting conversation. That's the perfect level of social
commitment for the Bay Area of Y2K Minus One.
</P>
<P>
   Think of these interactions as chat rooms where you don't have
to type and you get to see faces, without seeing smiley faces.
</P>
<P>
   Look, I know the idea of low-maintenance community may seem
cynical and twisted, but it's not a bad option in an age where
people wear Sony Walkmans so you can't talk to them, and then shout
into their cell phones so you can't hear yourself think.
</P>
<P>
   What, after all, are the Bay Area neighbors of 1999? For most
people, a neighbor is someone whose trees grow to block your view.
The word ``neighborhood'' most often modifies ``dispute.''
</P>
<P>
   The word ``community'' is long gone. Nowadays it doesn't mean a
group of people living together. It means a group of people who
don't know each other and are ticked off at everybody else.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; -- &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For many Americans, traditional family and neighborhood ties
have come undone. Something has to take their place. What's more
American than on- and-off Velcro attachments?
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of shoes, the sport of soccer blossomed in America so
parents could get out of the gated community and gather around the
field on picnic blankets _ as far as I can tell as a non-soccer
non-dad.
</P>
<P>
   Do you believe parents are doing all that chauffeuring just for
the kids? I've watched a few of those games, and the gossiping
parents seem to have a lot more fun than the puffing kids.
</P>
<P>
   That's one good reason to have a kid. You get a lot of low-
maintenance relationships, for the price of the highest-maintenance
relationship of all.
</P>
<P>
   But I digress. In case of emergency, call Tully's coffeehouse on
Fillmore. Tell whoever answers the phone that the guy who always
has a large decaf, but still talks too much, won't be in.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
