<SLUG> BC-BC-KAN-BUDGET-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY STAR BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of Saturday,
May 15. If you have any questions, please call The Star's News Desk
at (816) 234-4720.
</P>
<P>
   SAM _ Kansas Sen. Sam Brownback has found himself well-placed
for a publicity coup. As a critic of violent song lyrics, the
conservative Republican is now the talking head in demand when talk
turns to culture. A Senate hearing and White House meeting are
helping him gather steam. David Goldstein. 25.
</P>
<P>
   ENERGY: Private contractors of the Department of Energy -
including AlliedSignal and Midwest Research Institute of Kansas
City - are doing little to curb excessive travel costs, a recent
government audit shows. The 32 contractors failed to meet the
department's 1995 goal to cut $35 million a year in travel.
Altogether, we footed $250 million for their travel last year. Some
firms show little interest in containing costs - paying $1,000 + on
airline tickets they could get for less than half that amount and
spending $300 a night on hotel rooms. Oddly, the Department of
Energy is tightening its own travel belt, but contractors are not.
The General Accounting Office says contractors should have a
conscious and that the department should set travel cost targets.
Kevin Murphy. 28 inches.
</P>
<P>
   PARK _ On a bluff with a good view of the Mississippi River, a
statue of Jefferson Davis stands tall in the middle of Confederate
Park in Memphis, Tenn. Appropriately, his back is turned to the
river and instead he peers east into downtown. It was here that
Memphians gathered June 6, 1862, to watch the Battle of Memphis in
the river below. The Yankee ironclad gunboats quickly whipped the
southerners. But this week, the Confederacy _ or its great-great
grandsons _ won one. The Memphis Park Commission retreated from a
plan to oust the rebel president and rename the 90-year-old park.
The new name would have been familiar to Kansas Citians: the
Richard and Annette Bloch Cancer Survivors Park, similar to the one
west of the Plaza here. 38. Photo. Keith Chrostowski.
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN: Peggy Nothnagel of Kansas City finally decided to go back
to college when she realized she'd never make a decent living
without one. Women need some college to earn what a male high
school graduate can make in the workplace and that's one of the
realities fueling a national trend. Women are greatly outnumbering
men on college campuses and are earning most of the college
degrees. Men's share of bachelor's degrees declined from 81 percent
in 1900 to just 45 percent today. In Missouri and Kansas, those
percentages are slightly lower. Some people celebrate women's
success at earning college degrees as payback for years of
exclusion from higher education. But others bemoan the trend,
saying men are losing out in a changing world that often requires a
college diploma for good careers. Lynn Franey. 45. Photos and
graphics.
</P>
<P>
   HIGH (with WOMEN): An especially worrisome aspect of this trend
is the dearth of black men in higher education (women earn about 64
percent of all college degrees awarded to African-American
students). Franey. 20. Graphic.
</P>
<P>
   MOLEG: Missouri legislators will spend their final day trying to
seal deals on tax cut and pension plans that meet with the approval
of the governor. Anything that's not wrapped up by the official 6
p.m. deadline today will automatically die. Will Sentell and Kit
Wagar. 25-30. Photos
</P>
<P>
   ROADS: State and local officials meet in KC today with
representatives of the U.S. Dept. of Transportation to try to
resolve the halt to road construction stemming from air pollution
violations. They may release a more complete list of Johnson County
and other Kansas projects affected. Mike Mansur. 20.
</P>
<P>
   ORGAN: Sam Beckett is the Kansas City Royals new organist. It's
been eight years since an organist has been at the K to play for
the team. Fans, in their surveys, have consistently asked for an
organist to return. We profile a man and his music, plus talk to
fans about Sam. Ruth Igoe. 15-20. Photos.
</P>
<P>
   PIZZA: A $6 dispute over a pizza has landed in federal court in
Kansas City. Mark Morris. 8.
</P>
<P>
   BOWKER: We meet Betrenia Watt Bowker, an octogenarian who lives
east of The Paseo, who was also one of our first female
journalists. She first worked for the WPA guide and she came of age
as a journalist in Missouri. Joe Popper. Photos.
</P>
<P>
   KEN: Trial of Kenneth Demarrias provides look at youth violence
and what's being planned to stop it. He is charged with two counts
of first-degree murder for killing a 17-year-old and a 15-year-old
over a basketball game at Winner Park. The murders last year
outraged a city trying to come to grips with rising juvenile
homicides. In response to last year's murders, the Partnership for
Children and 25 other agencies will soon release a series of
recommendations to curtail youth violence in KC. An official with
the partnership says it's necessary to intervene earlier in
children's lives. Demarrias was 18 at the time of the killings and
faces life without parole if convicted. Joe Lambe. 20. Photos,
graphics.
</P>
<P>
   WELL. Folo on the baby in the well; were there lessons learned
in Midland, Texas, that helped rescuers this time? John L.
Petterson.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K _ Y2K column. David Hayes, Finn Bullar
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
