<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-BUDGET </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIF. GOVERNOR PUSHES $1 BILLION PLAN FOR REPAIRS IN THE STATE 
</HEADLINE>
 -HNS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ Gov. Gray Davis is proposing to spend $1
billion on public works projects, such as prisons, streets and
public transit, in the largest cash investment to repair California
since the go-go years of the late Gov. Edmund G. ``Pat'' Brown.
</P>
<P>
   The money would be used to build a maximum security,
4,500-inmate prison in Kern County and start planning for a second
prison in San Diego County.
</P>
<P>
   California houses 158,000 inmates in three dozen state prisons,
but it will need space for 50,000 more by 2003, prison officials
say.
</P>
<P>
   Davis also wants to give cities and counties an unprecedented
amount of cash to improve streets, public transit, flood control,
port operations, sewage and trash facilities, and parks.
</P>
<P>
   The governor would do that by dumping $425 million into
California's newly created infrastructure bank, allowing cities and
counties to leverage the money with low-cost financing that could
total $2 billion in civic improvements.
</P>
<P>
   Other investments range from $6 million to buy ferries for the
San Francisco Bay area to paying for about half of all the urgent
park improvements in the state. The parks list includes repairing
lifeguard towers, restrooms, trails and, among other things,
sprucing up historic buildings on Angel Island.
</P>
<P>
   The money for bay ferries comes as a task force is urging
lawmakers to raise bay area bridge tolls to $3 to pay for a $2
billion, 40-terminal system of high-speed ferries. The plan is to
attract 40 million to 50 million new water-transported passengers a
year.
</P>
<P>
   Davis hasn't taken a position on that proposal but has proposed
spending $6 million on any publicly run ferry service in the bay
area.
</P>
<P>
   The $1 billion investment announced Friday comes from an
expected $4 billion budget surplus. California's purring economy is
requiring more and more people to pay higher taxes on their
steadily increasing pay and bonuses, giving Davis and the state
legislature unanticipated spending money.
</P>
<P>
   Friday marked the start of final negotiations on the state's
total budget of $77.5 billion, which the legislature must approve
and Davis must sign before July 1, the start of the fiscal year.
Davis is pressuring lawmakers to approve the document by the
deadline, even though the budget has been late 9 of the last 10
years.
</P>
<P>
   Republican lawmakers are arguing for a tax cut, saying the state
can afford to return some of the windfall to California taxpayers.
They want to accelerate the next round of cuts in the state's car
registration fee, which could punch a $500 million hole in the
budget.
</P>
<P>
   Davis has said his top three priorities for the extra money are
schools, increasing the state's reserve fund and giving state
workers a pay raise. The infusion of cash for prisons, ferries,
parks and other construction projects was leaked Thursday by
administration sources and was unexpected.
</P>
<P>
   The new spending recalls the era of Pat Brown, who as Democratic
governor from 1959 to 1967 launched the country's most ambitious
public works program, including 1,000 miles of freeways, 11
university campuses and the huge California water project.
</P>
<P>
   Brown triggered the massive government spending to meet the
needs of a state growing almost a third to 19 million people during
those years.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Hauck, president of the California Business Roundtable,
said, ``Business leaders will be very encouraged by the governor's
level of funding to the infrastructure bank.''
</P>
<P>
   Corporate groups have been continually calling for more money to
improve roads, sewers and other civic projects.
</P>
<P>
   Some Democrats, however, were caught off guard by Davis' plan to
build a new $335 million Kern County prison. Davis also wants $20
million to plan a San Diego prison and $2.3 million to hire more
prison staff.
</P>
<P>
   Senate President pro tem John Burton, a Democrat from San
Francisco, said of Davis' prison-building plan, ``Not having heard
about this except through the press, I don't think much about it.
We ought to figure out some punishment options that are cheaper
than sending nonviolent offenders back for 18 months because they
don't pass a urine test.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
