A7124 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      05-14 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAKING THE POLITICAL MONEY TREE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ There were three of them. They were pleasantly
smiling women sitting at a table outside a meeting room in the Omni
Hotel the other night. One by one, elegantly dressed men walked up
to the table where the women sat. Names were checked off a list.
</P>
<P>
   Then, their wallets lighter to the tune of $150 apiece, the men
went inside the meeting room to join a few dozen other elegantly
dressed men. Most of these guys were lobbyists. They were there to
grab a quick drink, down some finger food and watch a New York
assemblyman shake the money tree.
</P>
<P>
   They couldn't stay long, though. They had other stops to make.
Further down State Street Hill, at LaSerre restaurant on Green
Street, another assemblyman was also shaking the money tree. A
state senator had a similar gathering going west of the Capitol, at
the Fort Orange Club. And, out at the Desmond in suburban Colonie,
the Democratic Assembly Campaign Committee was throwing its annual
``Spring Fling.''
</P>
<P>
   If you wanted to fling along with the Assembly Democrats, you'd
better have $125 in your pocket. Of course, that was less painful
than the 500 bucks a head the Republican Assembly Campaign
Committee had charged the night before at the University Club, at
their ``Prelude to Summer'' soiree.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, democracy. What was it Churchill said? It's the very worst
form of government _ except for all the other forms of government.
He had a point. This relentless political fundraising on the part
of legislators is distasteful to watch _ especially when you
realize that few people attend these events out of political
conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Except for legislative employees, who kick in as an unspoken
prophylactic against unemployment, you see the same people running
from fundraising event to fundraising event all through the state
legislative session. Lobbyists tend to be equally respectful of
both parties, since each controls its own house of the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   And the money goes to a good cause _ namely, to crushing
opposition in the legislator's home district. It goes to pay
campaign staff, take polls, produce campaign literature, to buy
advertising and _ in no small measure _ simply to intimidate
potential opponents who lack their own money tree.
</P>
<P>
   Incumbent legislators virtually never lose, unless they run into
a little bad luck in primary elections. Why not? The money, that's
why not. Unless a legislator is confronted by a well-financed
candidate who enjoys name recognition, he or she is generally
golden back in the home district. That's the time-honored Albany
way.
</P>
<P>
   This year, with the state six weeks late in deciding how to
spend its money and no resolution in sight to this intractable
budget battle, the money tree is vibrating like a tuning fork. In
all of last year, New York's lawmakers threw a 201 fundraising
events. That was nearly two dozen more than the year before that.
</P>
<P>
   This year, they're already up to more than 150 or so
fundraisers, and it's still early. They're throwing roughly twice
the number of money tree-shaking sessions they threw just four
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   What's most disturbing about this is that most of these
shakedown sessions are held at Albany restaurants and hotels, only
blocks from the ornate building where the laws are actually made.
All three lawmakers who were picking pockets the other night
represent districts far away from Albany. They were, essentially,
peddling their influence instead of raising money from loyal
constituents back home.
</P>
<P>
   The solution to a problem like this? Simple. Forget about public
financing. It'll never pass anyway. Just limit political
contributions in state legislative campaigns to gifts from
constituents who actually live in the lawmaker's district. And, by
the way, do the same thing with Congress. That would slow the flow
of special interest money.
</P>
<P>
   On second thought, forget that nutty idea. It might be illegal.
Besides, they would never pass that either.
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Times Union, Box 15000,
Albany, N.Y. 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
