A7130 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-WOODS-HNS &LR;      05-14 0664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-WOODS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIGER WOODS VS. DAVID DUVAL ISN'T A HISTORIC RIVALRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEVE CAMPBELL  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's no need to get out a calendar and circle the date. The
sheer magnitude of the event undoubtedly will make the date stick
in the mind as indelibly as the Fourth of July, Christmas and New
Year's Day.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, April Fool's.
</P>
<P>
   Clear the schedule. Make sure the television _ now might be the
time to take the big-screen plunge, if you haven't already _ is in
working order.
</P>
<P>
   As luck would have it, we're getting plenty of notice. Come Aug.
2, from 8-11 p.m. EDT, the sporting world as we know it will take
one giant step forward for humanity and/or the almighty dollar.
</P>
<P>
   David Duval is going to take on Tiger Woods.
</P>
<P>
   No. 1 in the world golfing order vs. No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Clubhead-to-clubhead.
</P>
<P>
   Live. On network television. For stakes so high, it makes a
check for winning the Masters, the U.S. Open, the British Open or
the PGA Championship look like chump change.
</P>
<P>
   Woods and Duval haven't been able to create that sort of
spectacle on merit, so the International Management Group and ABC
decided to intervene. IMG, which represents Woods and Duval,
brokered a winner-takes-most-of the $1.5-million-on-the-table
match.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a chance where David and I can compete head-to-head, beat
each other's brains out, walk away and say it was great for the
game of golf,'' Woods said, as if he were promoting a
``Wrestlemania'' sequel.
</P>
<P>
   What would really be great for golf would be for Woods and Duval
to both bring their A games to a tournament that matters. Since a
12-shot victory in the 1997 Masters, Woods has been a fringe major
player. Though Duval has won 11 times since the fall of '97, his
next major championship will be his first. Until Woods and Duval
actually get into contention at the same major, this will have to
do for intrigue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't a rivalry make,'' Duval said. ``But it might be a
good start.''
</P>
<P>
   No, a good start would be for Woods and Duval to lay the
groundwork for a storied rivalry the old-fashioned way. By bringing
out the best in each other at the biggest moments. Let's put Woods
and Duval in historical perspective: They have combined to win half
as many majors as Andy North.
</P>
<P>
   A rivalry is Jack Nicklaus vs. Arnold Palmer, Lee Trevino, Tom
Watson and all other challenges. Wilt Chamberlain vs. Bill Russell.
The New York Yankees vs. the Brooklyn Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Duval and Woods belong in that group like Tony Bennett in Kiss
makeup. That could change over time _ the way Michael Jordan made
the transformation from showman to champion. At the moment, the
Woods-Duval match belongs somewhere between Billie Jean King vs.
Bobby Riggs (harmless fun) and Foolish Pleasure vs. Ruffian
(harmful fun) in the food chain of made-for-TV sporting spectacles.
</P>
<P>
   King struck a minor blow against male chauvinism by beating a
65-year-old man. Ruffian broke an ankle in a $350,000 challenge
race and had to be destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Life usually has a way of going on, though, no matter how cheesy
the sporting spectacle. One generation's Roller Derby is another
generation's American Gladiators.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Namath wore _ ugh _ pantyhose on TV. Ahmad Rashad _ groan _
proposed to Phylicia Ayers-Allen on a 1985 National Football League
Thanksgiving Day telecast. Now Tiger Woods and David Duval are
coming to prime time on the network that created The Women
Superstars, Challenge of the Sexes, Celebrity Challenge of the
Sexes, The Battle of the Network Stars.
</P>
<P>
   The $400,000 of the prize money from the Woods-Duval match that
will go to charity is some consolation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would love to see it become a series,'' Woods said, ``where
we could have more special events like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Conservative calculations indicated that the audience for such a
thing will grow at least 525,600 every year. One sucker, born each
and every minute of every day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
