A7137 &Cx1f; gen-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-WASHINGTON-NAT     05-14 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-WASHINGTON-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        TILTING AT OBELISKS: A WASHINGTON COVER-UP
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By C.J. Karamargin  
 &HT;    c. 1999 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON - In a city well-known for cover-ups, this story is
different.
</P>
<P>
   This is the story of a keep-it-covered-up.
</P>
<P>
   Keep it covered is what Chad Allen wants to do with the
Washington Monument, the 555-foot marble and granite obelisk that
rises from the National Mall in honor of the nation's first
president.
</P>
<P>
   The monument has been sheathed in scaffolding since December as
part of a $6.5 million restoration project. Designed by the
internationally renowned architect Michael Graves, the scaffolding
was intended to be practical and attractive - but temporary.
</P>
<P>
   That last part is key. The scaffolding is scheduled to be
dismantled and removed when the restoration is completed in the
summer of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   But Allen, the managing editor of an on-line travel service,
likes Graves' work. He likes the scaffolding better than the
monument itself. And in what can only be a called an example of
someone tilting at obelisks, Allen thinks it should become
permanent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a more modern look,'' said Allen, a native of Kalamazoo
who has lived in Washington for nine months. ``There are times when
it makes sense to update our symbols, to make a gesture that we're
moving forward.''
</P>
<P>
   For Allen, that time has arrived. To promote his admitedly
quixotic cause, Allen is using that most modern of weapons, the
Internet. He has created a Web site - www.keepitcovered.org - where
he urges potential signers of an ``e-petition'' to ``join the
cover-up.''
</P>
<P>
   Among Allen's top ten reasons to keep the scaffolding in place
is that ``the covered monument is an apt metaphor for the need for
greater discretion in personal conduct among politicians.''
</P>
<P>
   But Allen, the holder of a master's degree in philosophy from
Western Michigan University, is more concerned about aesthetics
than politics. In his view, the scaffolding simply makes the
111-year-old monument a more interesting piece of architecture.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just it looks better, especially at night with the
lights,'' he said. ``I guess I just don't have this overwhelming
nostalgia for a big piece of stone.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem for Allen is that many people do. Washington is a
city that takes its monuments seriously. Suggestions to fiddle with
them do not go over well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not something we endorse,'' said Jen Larson, a
spokesperson for the National Park Service Foundation, the
non-profit organiztion spearheading the restoration fundraising
dirve. ``The scaffolding is going to come down.''
</P>
<P>
   And that is exactly what Graves intended. Tom Rowe, an architect
with Graves' Princeton, N.J. firm, said the scaffolding was not
designed to be permanent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very flattering on the one hand,'' said Rowe. ``On the
other, what we designed technically can't last.''
</P>
<P>
   Now at work designing a $70 million addition to the Detroit
Institute of Arts, Graves designed the scaffolding to mimic the
grid pattern of the monument's mortar joints. Transparent netting
attached to the scaffolding allows visitors to watch work crews
scaling the monument's facade, inspecting, cleaning and repairing
the giant stone blocks.
</P>
<P>
   At night, the scaffolding-enveloped monument evokes the Eiffel
Tower, the 984-foot wrought-iron icon of Paris that surpassed the
Washington Monument as the world's tallest structure in 1889.
Normally illuminated by a battery of floodlights shining up from
its base, the monument now is illuminated by 500 light fixtures
attached to the scaffolding.
</P>
<P>
   The image, Allen is convinced, is worth preserving. And, he
said, he's not alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just picking up the vibe from the street, I sense that other
people think it looks better (with the scaffolding) too,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A handfull of supporters have signed his petition, but Allen
admits that the battle to preserve the scaffolding might require a
general of Washington's skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see it as a grassroots thing,'' he said. ``It's just a
matter of building momentum.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
