<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIONEER-GOLD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIONEER COUNTS ON POT OF GOLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; BOSTON -- Placing your nest eggs in different baskets might be
a good strategy for individual investors, but it can be a lousy one
for investment management companies.
</P>
<P>
   Take Pioneer Group Inc., the mid-sized mutual fund firm with an
unusually motley collection of businesses _ and a tarnished record
at making them work. Once lauded as innovative for launching
overseas commodities and financial ventures as a hedge against
downturns in US stocks, the Boston-based company faces growing
scrutiny from shareholders over its money-losing projects.
</P>
<P>
   Pioneer is ``a first-class mutual fund business and distribution
outfit with some awful, awful diversification,'' said investor
Mario J. Gabelli, whose fund firm, Gabelli Funds Inc., is Pioneer's
third-largest shareholder, with an 8.9 percent stake.
</P>
<P>
   After a weak first quarter following a year of steep losses, a
management shakeup, and even loose talk on Wall Street of a
possible sale of the company, Pioneer is finding its biggest
international assets the most difficult to dump.
</P>
<P>
   Having worked for months to drum up interest in its Siberian
timber project, which has never made a profit, the company has
still not found a partner to share the costs and risk.
</P>
<P>
   But the grand deadweight is its gold mine in Ghana, a
once-profitable venture now dulled by low bullion prices and
management missteps.
</P>
<P>
   Investors who gather on Tuesday for Pioneer's annual
shareholders' meeting are looking for signs that plans to sell the
mine, known as Teberebie Goldfields, will help restore the bottom
line at Pioneer and improve the company's depressed stock price.
</P>
<P>
   ``The gold mine sale will be the key determinant of
profitability,'' said analyst Bruce R. Brewington, who follows the
company for Putnam, Lovell, De Guardiola &AMP; Thornton in San
Francisco. Pioneer lost $20.6 million last quarter, with the gold
mine accounting for nearly one-third of that total. After years of
profits, the company, whose core business is mutual funds, reported
1998 losses of $33.5 million, with the mine accounting for 60
percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen G. Kasnet, head of global strategic investments at
Pioneer, said only that the company, which has hired Salomon Smith
Barney for the mine sale, was talking to several buyers, and a deal
would be completed in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But already there are questions about Pioneer's chances of
getting a good price for Teberebie, which the company developed
from the ground up. Citing steps by Ashanti Goldfields Co. Ltd., a
Ghana-based mining company, to shut down its nearby Iduapriem mine,
Douglas Donald, a former Scudder Investments gold fund manager who
is now an independent consultant, sees only one potential buyer for
Pioneer's property: South African miner Gold Fields Ltd., which is
expanding output at its Tarkwa mine, an open pit adjacent to
Teberebie.
</P>
<P>
   Fewer buyers, Donald said, means less price negotiation leverage
for Pioneer, whose property by some estimates could fetch up to $1
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Pioneer originally had expected to unload Teberebie by the end
of March. But late last year, it ran into unexpected difficulties
when it reached harder ore, making it tougher and more expensive to
recover gold through its heap-leaching process. Recent analysis of
the problem led Pioneer to revise downward its estimate of
Teberebie's recoverable reserves to 3.8 million ounces from 4.9
million _ a drop of 22 percent _ and switch to a costlier milling
process.
</P>
<P>
   The setback, which industry analysts say may have spooked some
potential buyers, forced Pioneer to delay the sale by several
months while it reformulated a prospectus for the property.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, gold's depressed price has also hurt matters. The
lowest bullion prices in 20 years _ the product of the precious
metal's waning status as an investment and slack demand in hobbled
Asian markets _ has caused Pioneer to rework its production cost
forecasts, which were initially predicated on an average market
price of $340 an ounce. Gold now fetches around $279 per ounce.
</P>
<P>
   But Pioneer's woes were not caused by exogenous factors only. By
most estimates, Pioneer made several missteps on Teberebie. First,
it declined to hedge, or lock in a future price, for mined output _
a move that would have buffered against low prices. At one point it
had executives with coal-mining expertise involved in the project,
according to Donald _ a choice that may have hampered production.
And it ordered new ore-hauling trucks to replace an old fleet but
scrapped the old ones before the replacements arrived, resulting in
production delays when the delivery was late.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not pros in the gold-mining business,'' Kasnet admitted.
</P>
<P>
   That statement reflects a dramatic shift _ begun eight months
ago and still unfolding _ in Pioneer's philosophy. Reluctantly
letting go of its old-economy vision of gold as a solid investment
and admitting defeat with most of its diversification strategy,
Pioneer cracked down last September, reshuffling executives and
business units and taking a new, harder line on its operations.
</P>
<P>
   The change strikes at the heart of the company, one of the
nation's oldest fund firms but also one of its most eclectic. While
a few money management companies have diversified their businesses
with varying degrees of success _ mutual fund giant Fidelity
Investments has newspaper and limousine units, and John Hancock
Mutual Life Insurance Co. has international logging operations _
few have been as bold as Pioneer.
</P>
<P>
   When asked to describe Pioneer's new strategy, John A. Boynton,
the company's chief financial officer, said, ``I would primarily
describe it focused on financial services and asset management.''
</P>
<P>
   Pioneer has already taken steps to pare its assets. It recently
sold its US-based venture capital unit to a private competitor,
Connecticut-based Landmark Partners Inc. After years of high-flying
profits from its Moscow financial services unit, it has all but
exited Russia, where economic and political collapse broadsided its
brokerage business and an investment in a Moscow bank went awry
when Russian executives fudged accounts. It also sold a 30 percent
stake in its Polish pension company subsidiary to Nationwide Global
Holdings Inc.
</P>
<P>
   While timber prices have recently improved, Pioneer's
Forest-Starma timber production unit in the Russian Far East is
still too cost-intensive for the company to justify going it alone.
But there have been no takers, even though export markets in Japan
and Korea have recovered.
</P>
<P>
   At its peak, the Teberebie mine was handsomely profitable, full
of soft, easily extractable ore that contributed an average 56
percent of Pioneer's profits from 1993 _ its second year of full
production _ through 1996. Pioneer president John F. Cogan Jr., who
purchased rights to the mine in the high-inflation, depressed stock
market era of the late 1970s, saw the far-flung property as a
natural hedge for Pioneer's core fund business. Indeed, many
investors once bought the company's stock on the strength of
Teberebie, whose market value in earlier years outstripped the
company's market capitalization.
</P>
<P>
   The drop in recoverable reserves isn't Pioneer's first problem
with Teberebie. A 1995 plan to sell a 20 percent interest in the
property and list the shares on London and Ghanaian stock exchanges
flopped twice on weak bullion prices. And in recent years Pioneer
reportedly turned down a handsome offer for the asset from miner
Santa Fe Gold Corp., now part of Newmont Mining Corp.
</P>
<P>
   On the domestic front, where Pioneer is now concentrating its
efforts, things are somewhat brighter. Pioneer's core mutual fund
business ``is getting better all the time,'' Brewington said,
referring to the company's success in getting other firms to
distribute its products (Pioneer does not sell its funds directly
to investors).
</P>
<P>
   ``While they made a number of monumental tactical mistakes in
their diversification strategy,'' said R. Bentley Offut from Hunt
Valley, Md.-based Offut Securities, ``they still have a very
valuable investment management group.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Pioneer had net redemptions for its equity funds last
quarter _ its first net outflows in seven quarters _ after record
sales of $961 million in 1998, according to Financial Research
Corp. Two high-profile funds with poor performance, Pioneer II and
Pioneer Capital Growth, were the main problems.
</P>
<P>
   The tumult, which analysts attributed to investor confusion over
the company's internal reorganization, meant Pioneer's total assets
under management fell to $22.9 billion in the first quarter from
$23.4 billion at the start of the year _ all at a time when the Dow
Jones industrial average was soaring and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index posted good gains.
</P>
<P>
   Since last September, at least eight portfolio managers have
resigned or been asked to leave. Just three funds _ Pioneer Fund,
Pioneer Equity-Income, and Pioneer Growth Shares _ now account for
the bulk of sales.
</P>
<P>
   Although Pioneer announced Thursday a new arrangement for a unit
of insurer Aetna Inc. to distribute its three most popular funds,
the dampened fund returns and flows could crimp plans to expand
distribution further. In a recent report, Financial Research wrote
that Pioneer ``has fallen into a position where it is now critical
to its sales efforts that it put highly competitive product on the
shelf.''
</P>
<P>
   As if that weren't enough, the company has to contend with a
downturn in its stock price after years of heady gains. Pioneer
shares fell 25 percent last quarter after losing 29.8 percent in
1998. Having closed at 18 1/8 Thursday, they are down 8.2 percent
so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   Brewington, who has a buy rating on the stock, said that
``generally, the prognosis is good'' for Pioneer as it refocuses
its efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' he added, ``we need to see success in their sales
channels and with the mine sale.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-14-99 1326EDT &QL; 
