<HEADER>
A7207 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BAILEY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      05-14 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAILEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIMING IS EVERYTHING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just once in my life, I'd like to really screw up, resign, and
be handed a $25 &UR;  &LR; million check to go away. But then I'm not a CEO.
I'm not Abe Gosman.
</P>
<P>
   If he had walked away a couple of years ago, Gosman could have
gone out on top as the Michael Jordan of the health-care industry.
Instead he's just another guy with bum knees bouncing around the
CBA, albeit a very rich one.
</P>
<P>
   Gosman is hardly the only great man to have been wrong at the
end of a career; An Wang and Ken Olsen come easily to mind. And
Gosman has been good to me over the years: I've been down to his
incredible Palm Beach mansion; he's suggested snappy headlines for
stories about him; and, more than anything, he's returned my calls
on deadline (a sure way to be my friend).
</P>
<P>
   So I was disinclined to kick him when he's down _ until he took
the $25 &UR;  &LR; million payout at Meditrust Cos., a payout that showed up
this week as a huge charge to the Needham company's earnings.
Haven't Meditrust's shareholders paid enough for Gosman's mistakes?
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Gosman built a reputation as an astute investor
who makes people money. That rep has taken a big blow.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Meditrust, the real estate investment trust, have
fallen 63 percent in 1 1/2 years. Gosman's CareMatrix Corp., the
assisted &UR;  &LR; living company, has been cut in half. His PhyMatrix
Corp., which was designed to buy physician practices, has collapsed
from $15 to a buck and change.
</P>
<P>
   Add in the $2 million Gosman and his son Andrew lost in
investing in little companies like Palomar Technologies Inc. and
NUKO Information Systems Inc. and it has been an ugly run for the
man with the golden touch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a lot of money for shareholders, a lot of money,''
Gosman told me Thursday. But he declined to discuss the Meditrust
settlement, citing legal restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   Abe Gosman is a terrific story. He grew up poor in a three-story
walk-up in Manchester, N.H., the only child of Russian immigrants.
His mom saved for his college education by tossing the winnings
from penny poker games into a blue box on the kitchen shelf; his
dad was an alcoholic.
</P>
<P>
   After college, Gosman started a business selling laminated
snakeskin before jumping into the nursing-home business that would
put him on the Forbes list of richest Americans. Gosman made his
fortune and reputation at the Mediplex Group, the nursing-home
company he built, sold, repurchased, and resold.
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, we should have smelled trouble when Gosman
started touting his ``Wheel of Fortune'' strategy. At 68, Gosman
launched the most ambitious gambit of his career. The idea was to
take Meditrust, which operated retirement communities, and surround
it with a range of barely related ventures.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out to be his Wheel of Misfortune.
</P>
<P>
   Gosman spent $383 million to buy Santa Anita Cos. He was not
after the faded race track, but a rare legal status providing the
favored tax treatment of a real estate investment trust without the
strings that are usually attached. The so-called paired-shared REIT
was to allow him to build his wheel of fortune, and he quickly
spent $1.6 billion for a hotel chain and $241 million for a
golf-course operator.
</P>
<P>
   Timing and instinct are what made Gosman rich and famous, and
they were also what failed him in the end. Soon after Meditrust
introduced its diversification strategy, Congress pulled the rug
out from under Gosman, ending the paired-shared benefits. Timing?
Instinct? Live by the sword, die by the sword.
</P>
<P>
   Since leaving Meditrust, the 70-year-old Gosman has taken over
as joint chief executive of struggling PhyMatrix and chief
executive of CareMatrix. Son Andrew, formerly CareMatrix president,
has been relegated to vice chairman; number one son Michael has
been shuttled off to a new consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   To be fair, Gosman and his family were also shareholders and got
hurt in the collapse of Meditrust, CareMatrix, and PhyMatrix. But
the $25-million payday should help cushion the blow. And he had the
muscle to wrestle a $2-million settlement out of Smith Barney for
his sour investment in Palomar and NUKO; little investors haven't
been so lucky.
</P>
<P>
   It's a great country. For some people.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steve Bailey is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
