<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV16-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WELL-PLANNED PORTFOLIO FALLS INTO THE INFLATION TRAP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, May 16, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Enclosed is a list of the investments of myself and my wife.
The total value is now $461,940. We want to retire five years from
now when she will be 56 and I will be 55. We are currently
investing $500 a month in IDS New Dimensions fund, Class A, and a
similar amount in IDS Diversified Equity Income, Class A. Do we
have enough invested to retire and draw approximately $40,000
annual income from our savings?
</P>
<P>
   M.S., Desert Hot Springs, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes, I think you will have enough saved to attain your goal,
but there's some question whether you will have enough to protect
yourselves from the likely ravages of inflation in the later years
of your retirement. Here's the math: If you continue your $1,000
monthly contributions to the accounts and achieve 8 percent
portfolio growth during the next five years, the pool would be
$751,796 at retirement time. Presuming you could achieve a 6.5
percent average yield from a fixed-income portfolio, you would need
about $615,000 thus invested to support $3,333 monthly withdrawals
without erosion of capital. That would leave you with $136,796
which you could leave in growth-oriented investments to deal with
later inflation. In all likelihood that would suffice, but for an
ultra-secure retirement package, I would rather see that number at
about $300,000. Remember, the earlier you retire, the more you
should worry about the effect of future inflation on your
retirement assets.
</P>
<P>
   How might you get from here to there? Well, if you continued
saving at your present rate, it would require average annual
returns of about 12.53 percent to reach $915,000. Pretty unlikely,
in my opinion. If you achieved average annual investment returns of
10 percent, you'd have to boost monthly savings to $2,231 to reach
the target. Or if you achieved average annual returns of 8 percent,
you'd have to boost savings quite dramatically -- to $3,236 a month
to reach a $915,000 pool.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, it seems to me most likely that the third projection is
the most likely. First of all, nearly 24 percent of your current
portfolio is in fixed-income investments, and the fixed-income side
of holdings such as IDS Mutual would boost the fixed-income side
higher still. Second, I just don't think the stock market
investments which dominate your portfolio will have the legs to
continue the strong growth of recent years. And third, since you
should be moving the portfolio toward more conservative holdings as
you approach retirement, the prospect of high growth will be
accordingly reduced.
</P>
<P>
   My suggestion would be to begin this process immediately by
diverting your ongoing contributions from IDS New Dimensions and
IDS Diversified Equity Income funds to fixed-income options. To
make this move, I would leave IDS, partly because it's not
particularly strong on the fixed-income side, but moreso because
the Class A funds you have been buying from IDS carry 5 percent
front-end sales charges. I see no good reason to pay and
substantial sales charge for a fixed-income fund; the effect of the
sales charge is simply too much for even a talented fund manager to
overcome when the bottom line is compared to the results of no-load
funds. My suggestion would be to look at funds such as Vanguard
GNMA, AARP GNMA and US Treasury, or Fidelity Mortgage Securities
for your ongoing contributions.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am a 52-year-old woman who hopes to retire at about 65. I
have the following IRA mutual fund accounts: $9,406 in Franklin's
Mutual Beacon Z, $4,086 in Fidelity Puritan, $10,431 in Fidelity
Growth and Income, and $35,489 in IDS New Dimensions. Through my
present employer I have $4,000 in a 457 deferred compensation
program, with 60 percent of it in Janus Twenty and 20 percent each
in Janus Worldwide and Fidelity Growth and Income. I add $50 a week
to this account. I also have $10,593 in a 401(k) program with a
previous employer, and I would like to reallocate this money. How
should I reallocate these holdings? I feel I should probably have
some money in a bond fund and some in a small-cap fund. I have
looked at Baron Small Cap fund, but I really hate to have holdings
with so many companies. What do you suggest?
</P>
<P>
   N.M., Nashua, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   A. I think both categories you're suggesting make sense,
although you may be a few years early in establishing a heavier
bond position (remember that about a third of the Puritan portfolio
is on the fixed-income side). If you want to continue with the fund
families you're now using, I suggest you take a look at Janus
Venture fund as a small-cap holding, and at Fidelity Mortgage
Securities fund for your first all-bond holding. Other than that,
the only imbalance I see is the concentration in large-cap domestic
holdings, represented by the stock side of the Puritan, and all of
Fidelity Growth and Income, IDS New Dimensions, and all of Janus
Twenty. My suggestion for a final diversification would be to move
half of the money that's in the Fidelity Growth and Income IRA into
Fidelity Select Health Care. Other than that, it seems to me you're
doing fine.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am 33 years old, married, and have a four-year-old
daughter. I currently earn approximately $42,000 a year as a
federal employee, and 10 years from now can retire at half of my
base salary for the rest of my life. All of my savings is in mutual
funds, allocated as follows: $50,000 in Vanguard Windsor II,
$32,000 in Janus fund, $25,000 in Fidelity Magellan, $20,000 in an
IRA invested in T. Rowe Price International Stock fund, $12,000 in
Janus Twenty, and $2,500 in a money market account. In addition, I
invested $3,000 in American Century Twentieth Century's Giftrust
fund for my daughter. I have been adding $166 a month to the T.
Rowe Price IRA account, and I also add $100 a month to the Janus
fund account. My goals are to save for my daughter's education and
to retire comfortably at age 65 (after working another job after
retiring from the military). I am considering starting a Roth IRA
account for my wife in Janus Worldwide fund and investing $100 a
month in Vanguard's Index 500 fund. With the latter investment, the
account would be in my name, but would be earmarked for my
daughter's education. I would then stop the monthly contribution to
Janus fund. Do you think I have too many funds? Am I
over-diversified? The Giftrust account has performed very poorly
over the last two years, but the contract requires that I keep if
for at least 10 years. Do I have any options here? I am also
hearing that this was not a wise investment because children are
expected to contribute higher percentages of their assets to
educational expenses than children. Is this basically true? My hope
with the Vanguard Index 500 idea is to keep both expenses and taxes
down. Finally, is it prudent for both me and my wife to have IRAs
invested in the international sector?
</P>
<P>
   T.P., Arlington, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Starting with the last question, I see no problem right away,
but if you continued putting all your retirement savings in world
or international funds, you would soon enough find that sector
represented too much of the retirement savings. Right now, your
position in T. Rowe Price represents 15.5 percent of your portfolio
(excluding the Giftrust account). It wouldn't take very many years
of contributions to the two IRA accounts before that sector would
get beyond 20 percent, which is where I would place the limit.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of going with Janus Worldwide, why not look to funds
that would take a different path to getting you better diversified.
The biggest problem I see is that more than 80 percent of the
portfolio is in domestic large-cap stocks. So I suggest you divide
your wife's IRA money between Janus Enterprise, a mid-cal growth
fund, and Janus Venture, a small-cap fund. Both are rated
three-star, or average, by Morningstar, but when you look at the
ratings in those fund sectors, you'll discover that three stars are
excellent in these two sectors, which have been taking their lumps
in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   The story on Giftrust is even worse than you fear. According to
Morningstar Mutual Funds, the contract for this fund's owners
requires that the investment be held for 10 years or until the
owner reaches the age of majority -- whichever comes later.
</P>
<P>
   So there's nothing you can do but stick with it -- and, of
course, refrain from making further contributions to the account.
You are correct that it's best to keep your daughter's college
money in your name, and index funds such as Vanguard Index 500 tend
to be relatively tax-efficient, so that seems a good choice for
that account.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send letters, including your name, address and telephone number,
to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
