<HEADLINE>
11-YEAR-OLD BOY, A WHIZ AT CHARITY DRIVES, IS NAMED HOMETOWN HERO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAY JOCHNOWITZ  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLONIE, N.Y. _ When he was six, Patrick Gavin-Brynes went to a
5K run with his mom. He didn't know much about the charity it was
for, but he sure liked all those bright ``trophies and stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the next year, the Lake George, N.Y., boy worked at getting
sponsors of his own for a walk-a-thon, aware that his little legs
weren't quite up to a full-fledged race. He came to the contest
with $3,200 in pledges.
</P>
<P>
   ``I beat everybody else and got my little dream,'' he recalled.
</P>
<P>
   His budding philanthropy didn't stop. Over the last five years,
he raised $14,000, breaking his original record the last time
around by hustling hard and getting a commitment from Wal-Mart to
match his pledges up to $2,000. With $3,000 of his own pledges,
that brought in $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   The efforts by the busy 11-year-old _ who also plays piano,
trumpet, French horn and soccer and attends Boy Scouts, school and
chorus _ didn't go unnoticed.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Patrick joined seven others here honored by the
American Red Cross as a Hometown Hero. The award is given to people
who go above and beyond the call of duty or personal responsibility
to benefit others.
</P>
<P>
   The money Patrick raises goes to Operation Santa, a year-round
program set up by his uncle, Frank Munoff, to provide food and
clothing to the needy. Patrick has raised funds through car washes,
raffles, hot dog sales and, now that he's a little older, getting
into the 5K run. ``I sort of suffer through it, but it's worth
it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He now has his sights set on raising $10,000 through the help of
an anonymous mortgage agent, who has pledged to give him $50 from
every closing fee the agent earns.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Patrick has gotten his trophies, he says he'd like next
to appear on the ``Rosie O'Donnell Show.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I like her and her personality,'' he said, adding that if he
gets invited to the talk show, he hopes to inspire other people to
do charitable work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
