<HEADLINE>
NU PITCHER HOPES TO STRIKE OUT SCOUTS' HEALTH CONCERNS 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHIRA SPRINGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The scouting report on Greg Montalbano has an
inch-thick addendum. Inside an ordinary manila envelope,
Montalbano's medical records are carefully packaged for his
prospective employers. The weightiest of the five sections begins
with a letter of introduction from Montalbano's oncologist and
proceeds to document every doctors appointment, every test, every
scan taken the past three years.
</P>
<P>
   Montalbano's mother, Sharon, handed out several envelopes of
medical history between games of a recent doubleheader. She
continues to accommodate all requests from baseball scouts for
medical information. Her son, the lefthanded ace of the
Northeastern pitching staff, has nothing to hide. He has a major
league fastball clocked in the low 90s, great command of the strike
zone, the lowest earned run average among Division 1 pitchers, and
a medical history that includes cancer, two courses of
chemotherapy, and 5 1/2 surgical procedures since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   This year, for the first time in his Northeastern career,
Montalbano's health has not interfered with a season. Scouts have
become a regular presence at his games. They file a one-page,
type-written report that details the obvious talent. Three good
pitches that he spots well. Can mix speeds. Knows how to put
hitters away. Good frame. The page gets sent to teams along with
the much bulkier medical history in the manila envelope.
</P>
<P>
   As the June 2 draft approaches, Montalbano's status is difficult
to predict. The measure of his potential must take into
consideration the weighty prose of the medical experts and the
simple sentences of the baseball experts. The Montalbano story is
incomplete without both.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cancer is always going to be an issue, but I'd like to
think the way things are going kind of puts it to rest,'' said
Montalbano. ``I'd like to think that with the way I'm pitching
people are going to stop saying, `Oh this is the sick kid.'
Hopefully, they're going to say, `Oh there's the lefty.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Montalbano has done everthing within his power to erase the
specter of testicular cancer found and surgically removed in
February 1996. This season, he has managed a one-man campaign from
the mound. After a preseason uninterrupted by medical concerns,
Montalbano is proving each start that he can dominate opponents and
maintain a high level of consistency when healthy. Those scouts who
come to contests questioning his stamina are pleasantly surprised
by his complete-game performances.
</P>
<P>
   The lefty pitched a no-hitter in the season-opener against
Niagara, striking out 12 and walking just three in seven innings.
He threw a one-hitter with nine strikeouts against Hartford. Just
two weeks ago, Montalbano set school and America East conference
record for strikeouts in a seven-inning game with 15 K's in the
first game of a doubleheader against Hofstra.
</P>
<P>
   It was after the record-setting performance that scouts went
clamoring for the envelopes with Montalbano's medical history.
Representatives from Cincinnati, Milwaukee, Boston, Toronto, Tampa
Bay, Anaheim, Philadelphia, Colorado, Cleveland, and Arizona have
been spotted at games.
</P>
<P>
   When they come to watch, the scouts see a poised lefthander with
a lanky 6-foot-2-inch frame. He still appears thin, though he has
regained the 20 pounds lost as a result of chemotherapy and stands
at 192. He believes his body can carry another 15-20 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Montalbano's arms look disproportionately long and extend
halfway down his thighs. The pitcher's physique translates into a
long arm delivery that gives hitters trouble. The chest-high kick
of his right leg balances the long reach of his left arm as
Montalbano uncoils to the point of release. The ball whistles by
with speed.The motion appears fluid and effortless, his dangling
limbs the only distraction from the continuous flow.
</P>
<P>
   Medical history aside, Montalbano possesses the physical
attributes of a classic lefthanded pitcher. The package wrapped in
Husky red and black and wearing No. 30 comes close to the ideal
when measurements and statistics are discussed.In the scouting
venacular, he has ``the tools'' and ``the makeup.''
</P>
<P>
   The tools are a fastball clocked at 88-91 miles per hour, a
major league curve that he practiced last summer as a reliever with
the Wareham Gatemen of the Cape Cod League and the makings of a
major league changeup. Those three pitches _ though credit belongs
primarily to his fastball _ have kept Montalbano's ERA below 1.00.
His 7-1 record comes with the lowest ERA in the country at 0.68. No
other pitcher stands below 1.00, with Florida hurler Ben Grezlovski
the closest at 1.71. He ranks 20th in strikes-per- nine-innings
pitched with 11.3.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost impossible for a player to perform better than
Greg has performed this year,'' said Northeastern coach Neil
McPhee.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But this year's statistics only begin to reveal the mental
toughness that has always been a part of Montalbano's competitive
personality. The moment that defined his focus came during the 1997
America East championship game. The lefty entered the game against
Vermont with the title hanging in the balance. Seventh inning.
Bases loaded. No one out. Northeastern ahead, 5-1. He struck out
the side in the seventh, then fanned two in the eighth and two in
the ninth. He recorded three scoreless innings and earned his third
save of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a savvy pitcher,'' said one scout. ``He knows his way
around the mound. On top of that, he has great fight to him. He
battles hitters and that's a testament to his character. The fact
that he was sick and battled back, that just shows his courage and
his fight. He doesn't let that get the best of him. You can tell he
loves to pitch. He loves the competition.''
</P>
<P>
   On an afternoon when he did not pitch, Montalbano watched
intensely as his teammates faced Harvard at Friedman Diamond. He
looked straight past the pitcher's mound, keeping his line of sight
above the treetops, and could see the hospitals that constitute
Boston's medical district. The distance from the diamond to Brigham
and Women's Hospital is no more than a mile. Montalbano had his
last medical procedure at Brigham and Women's and spent five days
in the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
