<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990514.0154 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7228 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBC-MONTALBANO-2ND &LR;  &UR; T     05-14 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBC-MONTALBANO-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 BOSTON: ... in the hospital.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I like the view better from here,'' said Montalbano the sun on
his face and the sound of baseball in the background.
</P>
<P>
   The endless schedule of doctors appointments, catscans, MRIs,
blood tests, and hospital visits began in the winter of 1996.
Doctors found a cancerous tumor in Montalbano's right testicle and
removed it on Feb. 1. He was 18 years old.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought my kid was going to die,'' said nurse Sharon
Montalbano about the moment she learned of her son's cancer. ``When
I studied it in school, you died from it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How can you think about that?'' said Greg. ``I'm 21. I'm not
ready to think about that stuff. I can't say it was never in the
back of my mind. You wonder because it can happen, but I didn't
worry about it happening to me. I always thought of the
positives.''
</P>
<P>
   For the next three years, the good news would be coupled with
bad news.
</P>
<P>
   A committee of doctors called the tumor board reviewed
Montalbano's case after the initial surgery and discovered a nodule
in his right lung. Two sessions of chemotherapy were prescribed.
Each session lasted three weeks. At the start of the second
session, Montalbano lost his hair and lost weight. With
chemotherapy in February and March, baseball was not an option, and
Montalbano was a medical redshirt his freshman year.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his college career, Montalbano would be plagued not
with a recurrence of the cancer, but with the appearance of tumors
called teratomas. A patient with Montalbano's history of cancer
must have any growth monitored carefully and removed if there's a
concern about malignancy. The timing of the surgeries always
interfered with baseball season and prevented Montalbano from
participating in a full season until this year. And each time he
came back from a surgery, Montalbano battled soreness and the
frustration of spending time away from the game.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the highly invasive nature of the many surgeries that
would follow as a result of the teratomas, his doctors made every
attempt to preserve his body for pitching.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I would speak with Coach McPhee he would say, `Do they
have a clue Sharon? Do they know what's really going on?' '' said
Montalbano's mother. ``When they read through Gregory's medical
notes, it says he's a pitcher and he's concerned about being able
to play baseball afterwards. I would always start out saying, `His
life is the most important thing to us.' Don't get me wrong, but
this child also has a talent.''
</P>
<P>
   His doctors understood and made every attempt to take his future
as an athlete also into consideration, while placing a priority on
curing him.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Before the end of 1996, Montalbano would have two more surgeries
to remove teratomas. The most difficult was a right thoracotomy in
September 1996 to take out two tumors in his right lung. In order
to reach the tumors, Montalbano's lung was collapsed and doctors
made an incision that stretched from his spine to his sternum.
Recovering from the surgery, Montalbano would have trouble
breathing when rolled onto his side so the incision could be
cleaned.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he pitched the following spring, saving the confererence
championship game in dramatic fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Surgery No. 4 followed in August 1997. Surgery No. 5 in February
1998, when multiple teratomas were removed from his pelvic area.
Last November, he underwent cryotherapy at Brigham and Women's to
disolve yet another teratoma.
</P>
<P>
   When a recent medical exam revealed no new growths, Montalbano
called it a ``big step.'' It was an important sign, especially
considering the upcoming draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``After a certain point, it really does affect your chances,''
said Montalbano of the constant removal of teratomas. ``If
something else were to happen, then that's where the scouts and the
major league teams might start to say, `Oh well, that's the one.
That's too many. We can't take a risk on this kid.' That's fine. If
that's the way it is, that's the way it is. I don't necessarily see
it that way.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the Anaheim Angels didn't see it that way, either. They
selected lefthander Scott Schoeneweis in the third round of the
June free agent draft. During his career at Duke, Schoeneweis had
testicular cancer and shoulder surgery. Montalbano is widely
considered the No. 2 college prospect in New England. And while
some have projected he'll go in the later rounds, the fourth or
fifth round seems more than reasonable for such a lefthanded
talent.
</P>
<P>
   Montalbano understands baseball is a business and that teams
invest in players. There are two approaches organizations can take
with his case. They can decide he presents too big a risk to take
early and wait to see if he's available later. They can also weigh
his medical history against his potential and decide he presents a
tremendous upside. With all of his surgeries and medical
treatments, Montalbano missed critical periods of development.
There is no doubt his body will mature and more experience will add
needed polish to his pitching.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been told that I have stuff to get picked pretty high,
but there's also 45 rounds and I've got all the baggage to go
late,'' said Montalbano. ``Granted I think I bring a lot more to
the table than other players do as far as the mental edge and
sharpness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not doing this to say,`Hey, I told you so.' I'm doing this
because it's my dream. This is what I want to do with my life. I
really don't think I have anything to prove to anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   There are two big packages up for grabs. The manila envelope
documents the past. The 6-2 lefty represents the future.
</P>
</TEXT>
