<HEADER>
A7229 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV1     05-14 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV16-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOODBYE SLIDERS, HELLO CURTAINS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, May 16, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I want to take off my shower sliders. They are messed up and
I'd like to replace them with a curtain. Are they difficult to
remove?
</P>
<P>
   D. P., Brookline, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Not really, but it might be a bit tedious. That should not
deter you from getting rid of the doors; many of the inexpensive
ones don't work very well, and all are miserable to keep clean.
And, if you have young kids that need bathing in the tub, the
sliders, which open half way, can make it difficult, if not
hilarious, to try to grab a soapy kid who has escaped to the wrong
end of the tub.
</P>
<P>
   I think curtains are the best way to go, because modern curtains
have many styles and colors, they don't stiffen like the old ones
did, are inexpensive and easily replaced, and can be washed in the
washer to remove mildew.
</P>
<P>
   To remove the slider, take out the doors. Remove any screws that
are holding the frame to the tiled walls, and push and pull the
frame off the tub rim. The frame has been caulked (or should have
been) so it will take some pretty hard prying with a chisel or
other prying instrument to get it off. Remove glue residue from
tiles and tub by scraping and treating with a solvent: rubbing
alcohol, paint thinner, dry cleaning fluid or chemical paint
remover. Or, try heat from a hair dryer to soften the glue for
scraping.
</P>
<P>
   Fill the screw holes in the tile with joint compound or sandless
grout; paint to match.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My back yard is a tiny area that is muddy in winter and dusty
in summer. I'd like to install a pavement as a broad walkway and
also space to park a car. Are the concrete ``brick color'' concrete
pavers (6 inches square) any good to use? The whole area is only 20
by 15 feet; I'd like to pave an area 8 by 12-15 feet.
</P>
<P>
   FLORA HAAS, Arlington, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Pavers will hold up well because modern ones are made of
high-pressure concrete, which is stronger than standard, and are a
far cry from ordinary concrete blocks. There are more varieties
than the 6-inch by 6-inch one you have in mind. The colors may
fade, the concrete will endure. And, they will stand up under a
car. An alternative is real paving stones, chunks of cut granite in
various shapes; the granite, being granite, will last forever.
</P>
<P>
   To install, set the pavers in 2 inches of stone dust or sand,
which really can be tamped firm enough so the pavers will not sag
or sink. Of course, you will have to excavate to keep the pavers at
the proper level.
</P>
<P>
   If the area is so small, why not pave it all, or leave a strip
of earth for growing flowers. If you pave it all, you can buy
whiskey half barrels and other containers and grow your flowers in
them. There should be some relief from all that paving, as good
looking as it will be.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am finishing a hardwood floor after taking up a rug and the
nailing strip, but several big-headed common nails were driven into
the wood and I cannot pull or countersink them. A cat's paw to pull
them would gouge the wood. How can I conceal or remove those nail
heads?
</P>
<P>
   TOM ANGUISH, Holliston, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Try cutting the heads off with a hacksaw blade. You can buy a
handle that holds just the blade so you can get under the head. You
will have to cut into the wood to get a bit below the surface to
get to the shank so you can cut off the head, but it can't be
helped. Countersink the nails and fill the holes with wood filler,
sand and finish.
</P>
<P>
   Or, slip a narrow chisel under the head and pry up enough so a
hammer claw can grab it. You will ruin the chisel doing this, so
use a cheap chisel. Be careful of flying chips when you pry; wear
safey goggles. You will also cut some of the wood, but not much.
</P>
<P>
   Another way: tap the top of the nail head with a nailset to
create a pilot hole, then drill a hole into the head, repeating the
drilling until you've drilled the head right off. Countersink the
shaft and fill with wood filler or a dowel.
</P>
<P>
   If the floor is on the first floor and the ceiling in the
basement is exposed, before doing anything, check to see if you can
see those big common nails coming through the floor boards. If so,
drive them up and pull them out or cut off.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My deck is peeling like crazy, but the wood is intact. I
bought the house with the deck already built, so I don't know if it
is paint or what kind of wood it is. What finish can I use that
won't peel, and protect the wood?
</P>
<P>
   ANTHONY COSTELLO, Melrose, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. The wood, at least the floor boards, might be
pressure-treated, mahogany, or cedar. It might possibly be fir, but
that is unlikely. Only the fir needs protection. The solution is to
sand the deck (floor) to the bare wood and apply a semitransparent
house stain. This is not designed for decks, but it will work,
provide color and protection, and last for three to five years. If
it is pressure-treated wood, sand carefully, wear a dust mask and
collect the dust for safe disposal. All the old finish must be
removed for the semitransparent stain to penetrate.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
