<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-FRINGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SINGLE-ISSUE PARTIES ADD SPICE TO ISRAEL RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALIZA MARCUS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEL AVIV _ Ezra Tissona is sure that legalized gambling will
solve Israel's problems. Reuven Zelinkovsky thinks meditation is
the answer. Boaz Wachtel says the best thing is to sit back and get
high.
</P>
<P>
   And these are just a few of the new faces on Israel's political
scene.
</P>
<P>
   When Israeli voters go to the polls on Monday to elect a new
prime minister and parliament, they will choose among 32 different
parties ranging from the right-wing to the fairly offbeat.
</P>
<P>
   Take Zelinkovsky and his Natural Law Party. The retired army
officer believes that Israel's biggest problems _ from conflict
between secular and religious Jews to the stalled peace process
with the Palestinians _ can be best addressed by mass meditation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to train and enjoyable to practice _ when groups of
people are practicing meditation, there is a strong influence on
the surroundings,'' said Zelinkovsky, 55, vice chairman of the
International Meditation Society of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   But the Natural Law Party could face tough competition from
Wachtel's Green Leaf Party, which wants to see cannabis for
personal use legalized as a way to promote, among other things,
spirituality.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are being attacked by conservative forces in Israel who try
to diminish our existence in a variety of ways _ but I smoke pot
and there's no addiction, only great love,'' said the 40-year-old
Wachtel, who graduated from the Hebrew College in Brookline.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear whether this will be enough to grab voters. With a
national unemployment rate of nearly 9 percent, an overburdened
health care system, and a stalled peace process with the
Palestinians, Israelis may have more than spirituality in mind when
they go to the polls.
</P>
<P>
   That's where Tissona thinks he has the edge. His Casino Party
has a simple answer to almost every problem _ legalize gambling in
Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Israelis must leave the country if they want to place a bet.
Since last year, this often means an hour's drive to the
Palestinian-controlled city of Jericho, where an Austrian-managed
casino has proven to be a financial windfall for its Palestinian
and foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
   Tissona probably represents the view of more than a few Israelis
when he says he does not see why the Palestinians should get all
the money. ``If we open a casino, we're going to have a few million
tourists _ we are going to have Israelis _ if we have all this it's
going to make Israel much stronger,'' said the 53-year-old
businessman, an avid gambler.
</P>
<P>
   These political novices may be more astute than their party
platforms appear to reflect. It takes 1.5 percent of votes cast to
make it to the 120-seat parliament, meaning that a political party
can win a seat with about 55,000 votes.
</P>
<P>
   This is good news for small parties, but many analysts complain
that the voting system encourages fractionalization and makes it
difficult to put together a working coalition. Under the system,
voters cast two ballots, one for prime minister and one for a
political party.
</P>
<P>
   When the system was first applied in 1996, 11 of the 21 parties
made it to parliament and Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu ended
up with what proved to be an unwieldy coalition that mixed his
right-wing Likud party with Orthodox and other parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``The little parties make it hard to form a coalition, and it's
damaging to the system, because people get into sectoral
politics,'' said Janet Aviad, Israel director of the Charles R.
Bronfman Foundation, which works on issues of coexistence.
</P>
<P>
   Among those registered for Monday's elections are three parties
representing Russian immigrants, one party of Bukharan Jews,
another founded by Romanian Jews, and a party for the Negev desert
region. Then there are the more established parties that represent
not just nationalists, moderates, and centrists, but Arab Israelis,
religious Jews, and secular Jews.
</P>
<P>
   But leaders of the new small parties said that Israelis had
nothing to fear from a parliament that could include the Power to
Pensioner's Party for the elderly, the Green Party for the
environment, or the Rights of Man in the Family Party to protect
men's rights after divorce. They plan to be loyal to anyone who
works for their interests.
</P>
<P>
   The Casino Party chairman, Tissona, said there was no point in
asking him about the peace process. ``I don't like to get involved
in politics, the one who is elected will decide these things and I
will support whoever is elected.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If he goes for peace, I go for peace, if he goes for war, I go
for war, it's not my problem,'' he said. ``I just go for the
casinos.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-14-99 1337EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990514.0157 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 13:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7231 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      05-14 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIFE IN THE CAMPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Volunteering in Tirana to help the American Refugee Committee
set up on the ground to help minister to hundreds of thousands of
Kosovar refugees, Peter Lucas promptly discovered what was most
needed in the primitive 1,000-person camp at Golem on the Adriatic
coast: ``frozen chicken and ladies' underwear.''
</P>
<P>
   It was part Frank Perdue, and part Victoria's Secret, but it
worked. Red tape, inefficiency, ethnic rivalries, and desperate
shortages of everything from good roads to adequate transport make
it hard to shuffle supplies to those most in need. So the veteran
Boston-born journalist-turned-bureaucrat, one of the first
Americans of Albanian descent to re-enter the tiny nation after its
half-century-long isolation from the West under communism, played
his hole card: the plastic one.
</P>
<P>
   ``With my friend, Agim, I went to the American Express office in
Tirana, gave them my credit card, and eventually got $2,000 in
traveler's checks. I turned that into dollars. Then on the black
market I turned that into about 400,000 leks, the local currency.
Then we hit the market, an open-air bazaar.''
</P>
<P>
   With cash and a truck to collect his booty, he paid for 50 boxes
of frozen chicken parts for the Kosovars, mostly women and
children, who had been denied protein for three weeks or more.
``The labels on the boxes said the chickens had been packed in
Gainesville, Ga.'' He has no idea how it got to Albania.
</P>
<P>
   Next stop: the section of the market where he bought ``4,000
sets of women's cotton underwear made in Turkey _ all sizes.'' On
his first visit to Golem, he had heard refugee women and girls
lament a lack of underclothes; most had fled on short notice. After
a month of rough living, their garments were tattered.
</P>
<P>
   Think global, act local. Adopt a village, was Lucas's practical
response to the sight of hundreds of NGO workers thrashing around
in the confusing melee of relief work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Albania is an ecological disaster,'' Lucas matter-of-factly
recounted for a Boston audience of two dozen Wednesday, which also
heard from two other Bay State natives freshly returned from the
war zone. Dr. Tom Durant of Massachusetts General Hospital, an ARC
board member, and Morton Dean, the fall River native and Emerson
College alum who was ABC's man on the scene for 31 days in
Belgrade, nodded assent as Lucas explained the refugee plight.
</P>
<P>
   Gangs of feral boys, orphans scavenging for food, turn the
roadsides into grotesque pantomimes of ``Animal Farm.'' Lucas:
``There's rubbish in all the camps, beside the roads. Come summer,
and the heat, without adequate water or food, there'll be cholera,
tuberculosis, and everything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Durant: ``There are 800,000 people living in tents or shelters.
The tents are saunas in two weeks, and refrigerators on Oct. 1.''
Lucas, who covered the Vietnam War for the old Boston Herald, said
Tirana's airport reminded him of the US military presence in
Saigon. Durant said that what refugees run into everywhere, whether
in Somalia, Cambodia, or Kosovo, is ``the four B's _ bureaucracy,
baksheesh, bribery, and bugs.''
</P>
<P>
   Durant voiced skepticism about Clinton's ability to deliver on
his pledge to Kosovars that they will one day go home. ``How you do
that short of sending ground troops, I have no idea.''
</P>
<P>
   A month in Belgrade reporting from the Serb capital convinced
Dean that ``most Serbs don't care what happens to the Kosovars, or
to Milosevic,'' but they fear the bombing, hate NATO, and blame
America for the rising toll of bomb damage. ``Serbs look down on
Kosovar Albanians as lazy;they say `they don't want to work,' ''
said Dean, and are locked in the prism of the revenge of history.
``They give you the history lesson: `In the year 1369, here's what
happened . . ..' ''
</P>
<P>
   Serb television does not show pictures of the Kosovar refugees,
said Dean, whose own video reports, screened but not altered by
Serb government censors, were transmitted out of the TV station
damaged by a NATO missile attack.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas, who has visited Albania 15 or 16 times in the last
decade, is on a first-name basis with most of the Albanian
leadership. That government hangs on the thin thread of hope that
the US will redeem President Clinton's pledge to see the Kosovar
refugees safely home. ``I back the NATO bombing, and I back
Clinton,'' said Lucas in a later interview.
</P>
<P>
   Like many Americans of immigrant stock, he has a deeper
understanding of his own good fortune when he sees how the old
country is faring. ``The way I look at it, I've hit the lottery
twice in my life. First, in being born. Second, in being born an
American. That's no bull. When you come back out of there, that's
how you think.''
</P>
<P>
   As to the eventual outcome, Lucas thinks US and NATO policy will
ultimately prevail, and that Clinton, a politician often denigrated
as an opportunist, will be redeemed by backing a policy that looked
like a political loser at the outset.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Clinton will pull this off, the refugees will go back,
and this will save his presidency _ that this is what he'll be
remembered for.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
