</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-DANCING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DANCING IN THE DARK' TRACES A WOMAN'S WANDERLUST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN CLEGG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
DANCING IN THE DARK 
Romance, Yearning, and the Search for the Sublime 
Barbara Lazear Ascher 
Cliff Street/HarperCollins, 228 pp; $24 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When she turned 50, Barbara Lazear Ascher wanted some edge in
her life _ the kind of voyage out that is rarely granted doting
mothers and dutiful wives. ``Why are the boys having all the fun?''
she muses in ``Dancing in the Dark,'' an eloquent collection of
essays that makes up her fourth book. ``William Least Heat Moon.
Peter Matthiessen. Paul Theroux. They do that sort of thing in real
life. Girls do it in fiction.''
</P>
<P>
   So Ascher sets out on her own quest, seeking ``passionate
connection, something beyond love affairs and official business.''
Whether she is in Madrid gazing at a Hieronymous Bosch triptych in
the Prado or lusting after Woody Allen's typewriter in an office
supply store in Manhattan, Ascher is able to find a sort of
everyday bliss.
</P>
<P>
   ``The romance is in the quest. That a hand may never close on
the object of desire or that facts learned do not necessarily
reveal answers sought doesn't dissuade. The romantic, undeterred by
mystery, enters it with enthusiasm and reverence as though entering
a cathedral.''
</P>
<P>
   Onetime author of the ``Hers'' column in The New York Times and
apparent Renaissance woman (the book is a worthy read for the
bibliography alone), Ascher begins in her own backyard: Central
Park. Ignoring the plaints of her daughter, who asks if this is
``another menopause thing,'' Ascher determines to test Henry David
Thoreau's theory that ``it takes a man of genius to travel in his
own country, in his native village; to make any progress between
his door and his gate.''
</P>
<P>
   She joins a band of birders and stalks a long-eared owl that
sleeps in a spruce tree near the 79th Street traverse and the
canyons of success on Fifth Avenue. The birder seem perched at the
exact intersection of nature's wild bramble and the hemmed-in
hustling city. Like 19th-century Romantics and Transcendentalists,
she writes, the birders have ``open minds, sharp eyes, uninhibited
imaginations and available souls.''
</P>
<P>
   Ascher notes: ``They heeded the cry of their mentor Goethe,
whose Faust, finding himself imprisoned by intellect, sought
experience as an escape from institutional learning into vaster
knowledge. `You must escape from this confining world!' '' Ascher
sanctifies the mundane: owl, tree, life; faith, mystery, surrender.
</P>
<P>
   Although it begins with nature, ``Dancing in the Dark'' doesn't
neglect the more civilized pleasures and patterns in places like
Madrid and Venice. Some of her adventures owe more to the
journalists' trade than the philosophers', but they keep the book
from being too heavy. Her day with the pastry chef at Le Cirque in
Manhattan serves as kind of an intermezzo, amid musings on Keats,
Virgil, and the Barbizon painters.
</P>
<P>
   Ascher also gives glimpses of her own rich family life. When she
travels to Los Angeles to interview director Sydney Pollack, ``the
king of foreplay,'' it is partly at her daughter's behest.
(``Enough about Thoreau!'') She attends a birthday bash in the
Rainbow Room for her brother-in-law, magazine editor Dan Okrent,
and finds desire and yearning in the enduring calm of a long
marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Singer Andrea Marcovicci is flown in for the party; for Ascher,
the lyrics of Ira Gershwin and Jerome Kern recall a golden age. If
her quotes from Hesiod feel a little forced, her larger point seems
to hold true: Cole Porter's tunes bring us closer to paradise than
the postmodern ethos of ``do it till you're satisfied.''
</P>
<P>
   Ascher's supple prose and catholic tastes certainly entertain.
But she also understands what it means to be an outsider, forever
trying to apprehend the mysterious order of things.
</P>
<P>
   ``Romance is structured yearning,'' she writes early on. ``In
the romantic moment, we gather and focus that yearning in order to
connect with something outside ourselves, believing against all
odds that such connection is possible, knowing paradoxically that
romance is born in the space between our reach and our grasp.''
Sometimes, a long gaze at the thing apart unlocks a few sweet
secrets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-14-99 1341EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
