<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990514.0160 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7235 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-MUSSOLINI-BOS &LR;      05-14 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-MUSSOLINI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STYLISH ACTING IS SERVED WITH `TEA WITH MUSSOLINI' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
TEA WITH MUSSOLINI 
Directed by: Franco Zeffirelli 
Screenplay by: Zeffirelli and John Mortimer (from Zeffirelli's
autobiography) 
Starring: Cher, Judi Dench, Joan Plowright, Maggie Smith, Lily
Tomlin, Charlie Lucas, Baird Wallace, Massimo Ghini, Paolo Seganti,
Claudio Spadaro 
Running time: 118 minutes 
Rated: PG (thematic elements, language, brief nudity and some mild
violence) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Tea with Mussolini'' is a pretty long tea and a pretty diffuse
one, but it's carried by its generous helpings of warmth and period
flavor. Essentially, it's Franco Zeffirelli's semiautobiographical
homage to a gaggle of eccentric British ladies and two expatriate
Americans residing in Florence between the wars. When they're not
turning Italy's cultural glories into the 20th century's first
theme park, they help a boy orphaned by the death of his unwed
mother and abandoned by his father, a Florentine dealer in British
textiles. The ensemble piece gives Maggie Smith, Joan Plowright,
and Judi Dench the chance to unfurl high feelings and high style
against which Cher's showgirl turned rich art collector and Lily
Tomlin's lesbian archeologist more than hold their own.
</P>
<P>
   The youthful Zeffirelli surrogate (Charlie Lucas as a boy, Baird
Wallace as a teen) understandably fades into the background, given
the formidable women. Even more formidable is the Tuscan
architecture, including the Renaissance orphanage from which
Plowright's gentlewoman plucks the orphan and installs him in her
own pensione. Because she must earn her living, she's the most
reality-oriented. But Dench's art devotee is no less humane and
helpful to the boy, if less well defined. Smith's snobby widow of a
diplomat, who refuses to entertain even the possibility that the
impending turbulence about to be ushered in by Mussolini will in
any way disturb her comfortably blinkered routine, mostly holds
center stage, treating it as a natural habitat.
</P>
<P>
   This gives her something in common with Mussolini. Yes, there is
a tea. Shamelessly milking her late husband's connection, she
elbows her way into the dictator's company with the other ladies in
tow, as well as a newspaper reporter. For the sake of public
image-buffing, Claudio Spadaro's thuggishly polite Mussolini
reassures the Englishwoman that she may consider herself under his
personal protection. It's all she needs to hear. But of course it
isn't true. As the Black Shirts step up their terrorism, the women
find their insulated lives knocked out from under them, culminating
with the throwing of their tea tables off the balustrade of the
Ufizzi Gallery and, once war is declared, their internment.
</P>
<P>
   The obtuseness of Smith's character slides into caricature after
a while. Dench's character never is allowed to take on much depth,
unlike that of Plowright, who is as warm as she is shrewd. Cher
makes a strong impression as the headstrong wife of an absent rich
man, and Tomlin impresses with her easy authority, too. Perhaps
inevitably, the film becomes a vehicle for the women rather than
the fully dimensioned emotional experience it could have been by
including the Italians. The celebration of the ladies' eccentricity
and character sweeps before it any attempt at a deeper take on the
emotions detonated by the war. Zeffirelli is content to allow his
younger self to stand back and the let the women carry the film.
It's more a portrait gallery than the rich landscape it could have
been. Still, it's impossible not to savor the veteran actresses'
style and finesse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-14-99 1342EDT &QL; 
