<HEADER>
A7241 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCGRORY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      05-14 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCGRORY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEEHAN SHOULD KEEP HIS WORD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Admittedly, we have come to expect a lot from Marty Meehan, the
congressman with the delightfully ordinary personality and the
extraordinary ability to drive pivotal issues onto the national
stage. Perhaps, it now seems, we expect too much.
</P>
<P>
   In six years in Congress, he has emerged as the savviest, most
significant member of the state's congressional delegation. He has
been lauded by President Clinton for his work on tobacco regulation
and campaign finance reform. He is already a looming force in the
2002 gubernatorial race _ his prospects second only to Joseph
Kennedy and far ahead of Governor Paul Cellucci, who appears
unintentionally committed to serving a single term.
</P>
<P>
   But now, in the last week, it has become painfully apparent that
too much of Meehan's politics is born of convenience rather than
conviction, that he is not a man of his word, that he has rendered
himself just another untrustworthy politician in an age when a dose
of trust is so urgently needed in the body politic.
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1992, when he defeated an incumbent from his own
Democratic Party, Meehan rode the trendy term limits issue for all
it was worth, pledging that, if elected, he would serve just eight
years in the House. ``It's bad to have members of Congress who are
absolutely desperate to get reelected,'' he told voters. ``I want
to do my job and do it well and then get out.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem is precisely this: He did his job and did it well,
but now he refuses to get out. Rather than adhere to a promise that
helped him win election, he reversed course last weekend and said
he plans to seek a fifth two-year term in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``People will realize that someone can change their mind or make
a mistake,'' he said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Meehan, at 42, has tasted power and glory, and like so many
thousands of congressmen who have come before him, has decided he
can't get enough. He has, in short, become the politician against
which he once railed.
</P>
<P>
   In deciding to break his promise, he has committed intellectual
back-flips. He claims not to have realized the crucial role of
seniority in the House, even though it would have been obvious to
him when he worked for Representative James Shannon in the early
1980s. He now says his success mandates his continued tenure.
</P>
<P>
   His decision has been met with curious support among a community
of political followers who have grown absurdly tolerant of lies and
broken pledges. His hometown paper, the Lowell Sun, ran an
editorial this month pleading with him to run. Two of my esteemed
colleagues on the Globe's op-ed page lauded his decision in
Sunday's paper. This newspaper published an editorial in January
urging him to break his promise, saying he should ``show the
independence and common sense voters have come to expect of him.''
Independence from those pesky commitments?
</P>
<P>
   Truth is, term limits, especially unilaterally imposed ones, are
a profoundly foolish idea. The conveniently converted Meehan is
right when he recently said it is voters who should have the right
to decide who their representative should be.
</P>
<P>
   Equally truthful is this: Meehan's been a terrific congressman,
both for his district and for the national causes that he's
championed. His name stands on the seminal campaign finance reform
bill of the decade. Though it has failed in the House, it spurred a
national conversation on the dire need for fundamental change in
the way candidates raise money.
</P>
<P>
   But that's irrelevant to the issue at hand. Meehan made a
promise in the heat of a political campaign because he thought it
would help him win. He repeated it often, even signing a gimmicky
letter of resignation four years ago postdated to January 2000 that
haunts him today.
</P>
<P>
   As he made his decision last week, trust in politicians could
not have been lower, thanks to a president who treats the truth as
he treats his wife, which is to say with no respect at all.
</P>
<P>
   Meehan could have decided to keep his word to re-instill a
measure of trust between the nation and politicians. He could have
stood down for two years then run again. He could have begun the
spadework for a statewide campaign. He could have entered the
private sector.
</P>
<P>
   But he didn't. He succumbed. The temptation of power is
overwhelming. The Democrats may recover control of the House next
year. Meehan may need his congressional perch to pad his $1.1
million war chest for a gubernatorial race.
</P>
<P>
   Meehan may yet be governor or senator. God knows, he has the
talent and ambition. But I'll always think of what else he could
have been. He could have been a man of his word at a time when we
needed one most. He'll never be that again.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Brian McGrory's e-mail address is mcgrory(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
