<SLUG> BC-POSTHUMOUS-MEDAL-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR KOREAN WAR HERO, AN HONOR LONG OVERDUE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GLORIA NEGRI  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- In a murderous attack on three American outposts in
Korea in March 1953, 3,500 communist Chinese forces virtually wiped
out 120 Marines trying to hold three hilltop positions northeast of
Seoul.
</P>
<P>
   On one of the hills, a Navy hospital corpsman from Dorchester,
Joseph Francis Keenan, continued to treat casualties, though he had
been blinded and struck by shrapnel four times within four hours.
</P>
<P>
   Keenan, who had just turned 20, died while caring for others on
that dusty hill thousands of miles from home. His superior officer,
Dr. William Beaven, a battle surgeon, nominated him for the
congressional Medal of Honor, the nation's highest award.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy sent Keenan's body home in a flag-draped coffin, and it
arrived the ``day of the 1953 Worcester tornado,'' his younger
brother, Mike Keenan, remembered. But, though he had received a
Purple Heart for his injuries, the Medal of Honor never arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen years ago, Mike Keenan, an elevator repairman from
Hanover, set out to win his beloved big brother the recognition he
deserved. He searched records, researched military documents,
interviewed veterans who had been in Korea with him, and gathered
letters his brother had written his parents 46 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   He brought his case to the Navy. After a six-month
investigation, the merit of the case was confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   Friday (May 14) Mike Keenan's persistence was rewarded. At
ceremonies at the Marine Corps barracks in Washington, his country
honored Hospital Corpsman 3d Class Joseph F. Keenan with the Navy
Cross, the second highest military award the nation bestows.
</P>
<P>
   The family is content Joe Keenan is finally being remembered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel pretty wonderful about this,'' Keenan said Thursday.
``The beauty of this award is not that it is just my brother, but
all the people he served with.''
</P>
<P>
   To this day, no one knows for certain why the Navy failed to
award the medal. And nobody has been able to locate the original
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Polley of Georgetown, Ky., a corpsman who was temporarily
blinded in the same battles as Keenan, Thursday remembered the
confusion and casualties that marked the end of the Korean War.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had about 78 percent casualties,'' said Polley, who was
also awarded the Navy Cross. ``About 10 or 15 people got
battlefield decorations every day. Joe's brother fought very hard
for this and Joe certainly deserves it.''
</P>
<P>
   Even after receiving word from the Navy about Joe's death, the
Keenan family was not sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Navy telegram said he was dead, but two of his buddies
wrote us that he had been wounded. My parents finally got
confirmation (of Joe's death) from the office of John F. Kennedy,
who was then a senator.''
</P>
<P>
   Keenan recalled the day the telegram came.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother called my father at work. We lived on Mather Street
in Dorchester, about a block from the T station, and I could see
the tears in my father's eyes as he walked home.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Keenan began his labor of brotherly love in 1982 when he
received the letters Joe had sent from Korea to their parents. He
did other things. He went to reunions in Washington of Fox 25, the
Marine unit Joe had served with.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of them mentioned my brother's name,'' he said. ``Another
said he had seen a card file of people who had received the
congressional Medal of Honor. There was a card with my brother's
name, but nothing else on it. I wrote to Dr. Beaven in Saudi
Arabia, and he said he had nominated my brother for the medal.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Keenan had only been in Korea a month when he was killed. A
letter to his parents on Feb. 25, 1953, was prophetic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I arrived here on Feb. 13,'' he wrote. ``It's a good thing I'm
not superstitious. Many boys here will awake tomorrow with either
both arms or legs missing. They asked for a volunteer corpsman to
go up to evac. some patients. I said I'd go but didn't realize what
I said till after I was in the halftrack, but then I got scared. I
went up the hill but when I got there it was too late so I came
back to the aid station. I loaded eight or nine cases on the
`copters' bay. They sure are life-saving machines.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the Keenan family and former war comrades of Joe Keenan at
the ceremony Friday was the nephew named for him, Joseph F. Keenan,
33, of Cohasset.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a kid, I always looked up to my brother, Joe,'' Mike Keenan
said. ``He'll always be my hero.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
