<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENNOCHI-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF MEEHAN BREAKS HIS TERM-LIMIT PROMISE, WHO CAN TRUST HIM? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN VENNOCHI  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Power is an aphrodisiac. At its most seductive, it causes you to
fall in love with yourself.
</P>
<P>
   How else to explain Marty Meehan's love affair with Marty
Meehan?
</P>
<P>
   Meehan is the Democrat who last week notified his Massachusetts
constituents he will run for a fifth congressional term despite his
pledge to serve only four two-year terms. He made the pledge when
he first ran for Congress in 1992 and reiterated his commitment
numerous times since, even putting it in writing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Should I be elected to serve more than two additional terms in
the US House of Representatives following the 104th Congress, by
this letter I hereby resign and direct you to remove my name
permanently from the roll of the members,'' Meehan wrote in a 1995
letter filed with the House clerk.
</P>
<P>
   Again in 1998, it was reported by the organization US Term
Limits that Meehan had reaffirmed his term-limit pledge.
</P>
<P>
   Why the change of heart in 1999?
</P>
<P>
   Well, more than one political operative believes Meehan's change
of heart came long before 1999. The reform candidate for Congress
took the pledge, realized soon enough he would ultimately break it
and should have stamped the letter sent to the House clerk with the
words: ``Return to sender. This is filed for publicity purposes
only and should not be taken seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, that is not Meehan's view. He calls his promise
``boneheaded'' and a mistake but one he gave in good faith. He also
says it was never intended to be a central part of his 1992
campaign. As for his decision to reiterate it in writing, he
describes that action as a drastic step taken to force the
Republican leadership to take an up-or-down vote on term limits.
</P>
<P>
   His disingenuousness is distressing.
</P>
<P>
   Let's face facts. Political expedience shaped Meehan's decision
when he first ran for Congress just as it shapes it now. Meehan
wants us to view his pledge as the misjudgment of a political
neophyte. But it is clear he made it with absolute calculation,
opting to tap into the tide of public opinion at a given point in
time to benefit his own ambition.
</P>
<P>
   As he acknowledged last week in a letter to constituents:
(itals)``In response to overwhelming sentiment,(unitals) I
developed a campaign that focused on job creation, deficit
reduction, and congressional reform.''
</P>
<P>
   Barney Frank, the veteran Democratic Massachusetts congressman,
recently told The Wall Street Journal that breaking a term limits
promise is ``the worst kind of lie to the people _ you have traded
this pledge for their vote.'' Frank was talking about a cast of
Republicans who have made term-limit vows. Later, when asked
specifically about Meehan, Frank said Meehan, too, should abide by
his pledge.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever Meehan's original intent, it is obvious that for a
while now he has been looking for a way to break his word as
painlessly as possible. Over the past year or so, he made the
rounds in Massachusetts asking for advice, support _ and, as
always, for money. With $1.1 million in his campaign fund, this
champion of campaign finance reform is considered the most
aggressive fundraiser in the Massachusetts delegation.
</P>
<P>
   More than one person told Meehan privately to keep his pledge
and leave Washington. It would make him a true national political
story: a politician whose word is good.
</P>
<P>
   But like legions of incumbents before him, Meehan now considers
himself too important to leave. After four terms, he can't imagine
Congress without him in it and points to his experience and
seniority as pluses for his constituents. Now he believes members
of Congress need at least two terms ``to learn the ropes.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, when he won election in 1992, Meehan was the guy who
challenged and defeated incumbent Representative Chester Atkins,
who at the time was the ranking Democrat on the House Ways and
Means Committee. Meehan was the guy who said, ``It's bad for the
country to have members of Congress who are absolutely desperate to
get reelected. I don't want to spend 20 years in Washington. I want
to do my job and do it well and then get out.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Meehan is the insider sticking around Washington. His
decision raises an array of questions.
</P>
<P>
   Why can't he at least be honest about the political decision he
made in 1992 and the one he is making now?
</P>
<P>
   If seniority is good for Meehan and the constituents of the 5th
Congressional District, is it still bad for others? Are only
liberals entitled to the benefits of seniority?
</P>
<P>
   If he does not want to hurt his constituents by depriving them
of the services of a veteran congressman, how much time does he owe
them now? How will he explain a decision to abandon the district
and run for another office, such as governor?
</P>
<P>
   And finally, when should voters take him at his word?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Joan Vennochi is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
