<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWSUITS IN STEREO: BOSE V. KLOSS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They're the same age, and enjoy the same ``power ranking'' on
Boston magazine's current list of 100 most powerful Bostonians. But
the magazine forgot to mention one thing: They're always suing each
other.
</P>
<P>
   The men in question are audio bigwigs Henry Kloss (the K in KLH,
stereo of choice for '60s-era stoners) and Amar Bose, founder of
the Bose Corp. Kloss is the founder of Newton's Cambridge
SoundWorks, which Bose sued five years ago for claiming that its
speakers were ``better than Bose at half the price.'' That suit was
settled. Since then, Bose has hauled CSW into court for alleged
patent violations. Late last month, CSW counter-sued, claiming that
Framingham-based Bose is making false advertising claims when it
hypes its Wave table radio as the best-reviewed in its field. CSW
insists its own Model 88 is superior, etc., etc.
</P>
<P>
   How much do these two legendary entrepreneurs dislike each
other? ``There's no personal edge at all,'' Kloss assures me.
``Amar has a history of litigiousness.'' Kloss recalls that Bose
pursued a suit against Consumer Reports for 14 years, all the way
to the Supreme Court, ``largely for egotistical reasons as far as I
can explain.'' (The suit concerned a review that criticized Bose's
901 speaker system. The Supreme Court threw out a libel award Bose
won in a lower court.) When it comes to suing, Bose ``has the
money, he has the ego, and he has a competent attorney'' _ that
would be Fish &AMP; Richardson lawyer Charles Hieken _ Kloss says. ``We
call (the company) junkyard dogs.''
</P>
<P>
   But remember, there's nothing personal about this.
</P>
<P>
   Bose does have a reputation for suing. In a forthcoming
commentary on the Bose-CSW lawsuits in the Boston Audio Society's
newsletter, audiophile David Moran writes: ``You might think
veteran Bose legal watchdog Charles Hieken might get tired of such
predictable snarling after 30 years of it, but the obnoxious Bose
style remains indefatigable.'' A few years ago, Bose threatened to
sue a tiny Peterborough, N.H.-based publisher called Audio Amateur
over an alleged patent violation, then backed off. ``We were sort
of hoping they might do it,'' says company president Ed Dell, whose
lawyers advised him that the Bose suit was meritless. ``It would
have put us on the map.''
</P>
<P>
   On legal matters, Hieken runs interference for his MIT
classmate, longtime colleague, and friend Amar Bose. Accusations of
predatory litigation ``are unfair,'' Hieken says in a faxed
response to my inquiry. ``Bose attempts to resolve disputes
amicably.'' He correctly notes that the Supreme Court did not
disagree with Bose's claim that the Consumer Reports review was
damaging; the court held that Bose could not prove it had been
libeled. Concerning its latest anti-CSW action, Hieken writes that
``Bose tried to amicably resolve the . . . case before bringing
suit.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Random notes
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Is there such a thing as nice payback? I think so. Or perhaps it
is just coincidence that an unnamed Boston Globe music critic makes
a cameo appearance in Vikram Seth's new novel, ``An Equal Music.''
Globe music critic Richard Dyer reviewed Seth's previous novel, ``A
Suitable Boy,'' and liked it a lot . . . Why does the already
famous, well-connected, and terrifying Robert Popeo of Mintz Levin
want to be head of the 8,300-member Boston Bar Association? Popeo
is starting the wearisome climb through the BBA hierarchy. Having
served as BBA secretary, he is now seeking the association's vice
presidency. There are still two rungs above him: president-elect
and president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not doing this for me,'' says Popeo, who points out that
his eventual assumption of the BBA presidency is not a sure thing.
``Lawyers from major firms should participate in a leadership role,
or organizations like the bar association lose prestige and
influence.'' Perhaps, like John Curtin and the late Robert Meserve
before him, Popeo will use the BBA as a springboard to the
presidency of the American Bar Association. Stranger things have
happened.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
`Star Wars' haiku
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You're history, George
</P>
<P>
   It's now clear to all _ the Force
</P>
<P>
   Is with Keanu
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Alex Beam's e-dress is beam(at)globe.com.)
</P>
