<HEADER>
A7262 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-CASTLE-BOS &LR;      05-14 0426
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-CASTLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILY, LAWYER CONQUER ALL IN `CASTLE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
THE CASTLE 
Directed by: Rob Stich 
Screenplay by: Stich, Santo Cilauro, Tom Gleisner, Jane Kennedy 
Starring: Michael Caton, Anne Tenney, Stephen Curry, Anthony
Simcoe, Sophie Lee, Tiriel Mora, Charles Tingwell 
Running time: 85 minutes 
Rated: R (language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It sits on a toxic waste dump alongside Melbourne's airport
runway, and as for its decor, don't ask. It's not much of a house,
really. But it's all the home Darryl Kerrigan (Michael Caton) and
his family need. When the local government wants to bulldoze the
Kerrigans off it to expand the airport, the ordinarily cheery
Darryl gets mad and decides he's not going to take it. That's all
the premise that's needed to launch Rob Stich's ``The Castle,'' a
winning Aussie mix of Frank Capra and John Waters.
</P>
<P>
   First, the airport dealmakers try bribery. Then they try
intimidation. Then they find themselves sneering down their noses
in court at Darryl, who goes to bat for his family and neighbors,
but with an endearingly, hilariously inept lawyer (Tiriel Mora)
who's the first to admit that he's in over his head. To argue his
case, he doesn't cite legal precedents, relying instead on what he
takes to be the vibes underlying Australia's constitution.
</P>
<P>
   But ``The Castle'' is too resolutely benevolent to leave it at
that. It brings in a ringer who meets Darryl on the sidewalk
outside the court, takes a liking to him, and turns out to be a
constitutional law authority much better equipped to do battle with
the well-heeled establishment on behalf of the little guys. You'll
likely like Darryl too, if only because it's difficult to imagine
anyone disliking him. He's a loving family man, warm and sunny and
filled with admiration at his wife's mastery of such mouthwatering
staples as meatloaf.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Castle,'' in short, is a film that has only one big
moral-esthetic decision to make, and it resoundingly makes the
right one. It must have been tempting to get snide about the
Kerrigans' plasticized decor, souvenir beer mugs, oversize TV
antenna, and other lapses in taste. But ``The Castle'' isn't the
film to equate good taste with goodness, and its celebration of
happy family closeness makes it easy to buy into its feel-good
mode. It would rather err on the side of sentimentality than
snobbery. Led by Caton's undentable optimism as Darryl, it's got
just the cast to convince you there was no other way to go.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-14-99 1356EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
