<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-SEASONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THREE SEASONS'' POSTWAR VIETNAM TREADS GENTLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
THREE SEASONS 
Directed and written by: Tony Bui 
Starring: Don Duong, Ngoc Hiep, Tran Minh Cuong, Harvey Keitel, Zoe
Bui, Nguyen Huu Duco, Minh Ngoc, Hoang Phat Trieu 
Running time: 113 minutes 
Rated: PG-13 (thematic elements) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tony Bui's ``Three Seasons'' paints a delicate picture of the
grueling lives of four inhabitants of modern-day Saigon. The first
American independent feature to be filmed in present-day Vietnam,
it's a four-track look at the lives of a prostitute, a cyclo
driver, a young boy working as a street peddler and a young woman
working as a lotus harvester. Although it was American-produced and
Harvey Keitel, who helped produce it, stars as an ex-Marine driven
by conscience to seek out the daughter he fathered years ago,
``Three Seasons'' doesn't present Vietnam as a product of the
Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   Although the fissures opened by that conflict still can be felt,
it suggests the lives of working-class Vietnamese have always been
arduous. While teeming and steeped in poverty, the streets of Ho
Chi Minh City, nevertheless, seem less meaner than their American
equivalents. Part of it is Bui's inclination to tread lightly, with
visuals that emphasize the subtle sunset tints, shots through rain
and proverbial lotus-blossom gentleness. Actually, it's the last
that ushers in the closest thing to shock theater, as Ngoyen Ngoc
Hiep's harvester in a lotus pond owned by a reclusive poet, learns
his story after being ushered into his intimidating presence in a
beauty-and-the-beast replay.
</P>
<P>
   In less discreet hands the love story between Don Duong's ardent
cyclo driver and Zoe Bui's sad prostitute would disintegrate into
cliche, and the Dickensian chapter built around the stolen
merchandise of the street kid (Nguyen Huu Doc) would dissolve in
sentimental bathos. So would the quest of the ex-Marine driven by
guilt and a belated surge of paternal feeling. There's much that's
absorbing in this film starring mostly Vietnamese actors, but the
film in the end seems a bit like the Marine's quest, vague and
rudderless, in search of an imperative, or even a narrative, to
give it shape and purpose. It's great on atmosphere, but it seems
in the end no more than a screenful of the ingredients of a
compelling film, never quite combined to become the film it could
have been.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-14-99 1357EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990514.0172 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 13:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7268 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-SINATRA-BOS &LR;      05-14 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-SINATRA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE MORE FOR THE ROAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When I was 17, it wasn't an overly good year until I discovered
a singer named Sinatra.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that I was a raging rock 'n' roll fan. Frank Sinatra,
who died a year ago today &UR;  &LR; (May 14), had captivated me with the
voice that said so much. And there was that ring-a-ding-ding,
world-on-a-string persona, too. I bought my first-ever long-playing
album, ``Songs for Swinging' Lovers'' (I, of course, was anything
but). Then I bought ``In the Wee Small Hours'' and played it until
it was all skips and scratches. Who knew that these two albums
would be the foundation of a collection that one day would grow to
gargantuan proportions?
</P>
<P>
   When I was 21, I had accumulated a small but significant
collection of Sinatra LPs, including more of his magical Capitol
albums, some of his earlier songs on Columbia, and an album or two
on the new label that he founded, Reprise.
</P>
<P>
   When I was 35, I may have been less enchanted with the Sinatra
lifestyle but was more captivated than ever by the music. That's
because audiocassettes and eight-track tapes had come on the
market. Whatever their faults, they didn't scratch. So I began
replacing some of my favorite Sinatra LPs (and by now they were
many), mostly with cassettes.
</P>
<P>
   Now that I'm in the autumn of my years (well, maybe the late
summer) and pristine-sounding compact discs are the recordings of
choice, I've done what I had to do: quietly accumulated virtually
everything Sinatra officially recorded _ some 1,500 different
tracks.
</P>
<P>
   That, to my knowledge, is all of his authorized studio vocal
recordings on all of his major US labels and all of his officially
released live songs. Also in the collection are a couple of dozen
discs of sometimes muddy quality and dubious legality, adding a
couple of hundred songs culled from Sinatra's radio and TV
broadcasts and stage shows.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, that's a lot of albums; yes, there are also several
repeats; yes, there are different versions of the same song; and
yes, there are flaws in a few. Some may consider this extreme, and
I can't deny it.
</P>
<P>
   How did I do it? One of the wonderful things about compact discs
is that they have inspired record labels to release box sets of an
artist's complete recordings. After Sinatra died, an incomplete
collection seemed, well, just not complete. I already had all of
the chairman's Capitol albums (16 discs, 255 songs, his best work)
except a couple in which he only conducts. But now available were
his complete recordings with Tommy Dorsey on RCA (5 discs, 120
songs), all of his Columbia studio recordings (12 discs, 285
songs), his V-Discs, recorded for those serving abroad during World
War II (2 discs, 53 songs), all of his Capitol singles (4 discs, 96
songs), and all of his Reprise records (20 discs, 450 songs). My
checkbook was cringing.
</P>
<P>
   And how do I play so many records? With a 60-disc Panasonic
stereo that holds most (but hardly all) of my collection. Almost
every night, when the non-Sinatra fans are fast sleep, I turn on
the stereo and press the ``random'' button, which selects a song or
two from all the albums in no particular order. There's a young,
thin, silky-voiced Sinatra singing with the Harry James and Tommy
Dorsey bands. There's a slightly older but still skinny Sinatra,
warbling the tender tunes that made the girls go gaga at the
Paramount. There's the fedora-wearing Sinatra of the 1950s, his
rich baritone letting you in on the sorrows and joys that
accompanied his fall from popularity and his return to the top of
the heap. There's the older and heavier Sinatra, past his peak but
nonetheless sounding better than any other pop singer. And finally,
there's the old man, the pipes badly rusted but the singer still
worth listening to because he is, after all, still Sinatra. Through
it all, there are the marvelous musicians behind the man: Stordahl
and Riddle, Costa and May, Ellington and Basie.
</P>
<P>
   This is the music of my life and so many other lives. I regret
none of the time spent accumulating the records, tapes, and discs,
and none of the expense. There is one thing, though: My wife
doesn't fully realize the extent, and thus the cost, of my
collection. If she reads this article, the title of an early
Sinatra song will be most appropriate: ``I'll Never Smile Again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-14-99 1358EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
