<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-ROCK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARTING THE `PARTY' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ Timing is everything, or so they say. And
Boston's Push Stars have waited for just the right moment to
release their major-label debut album, ``After the Party.'' Given
their buoyant, pure-pop sound, the Push Stars knew it had to be a
springtime release.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are out in the spring. They're feeling happy and
upbeat, which is what this record is about,'' bassist Dan
McLoughlin said.
</P>
<P>
   For all you shiny, happy people (no slur intended), get ready
for the Push Stars disc on May 18 from Capitol Record, followed by
a CD release party at the Paradise on May 22, then a national tour
with fellow popsters Better Than Ezra.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of negativity in the music business right now,''
says McLaughlin. ``We feel music should be a completely positive
force. It should be uplifting and therapeutic. If we can get people
to listen to the record and say it makes them feel good, then
that's the ultimate payoff.''
</P>
<P>
   The band accomplishes its purpose on the new CD, which is
sentimental but not treacly. It rocks with an uncommon glee and
breezy intelligence on guitar-stoked tracks such as ``Everything
Shines'' (which first appeared on the soundtrack to ``There's
Something About Mary''), ``Any Little Town'' (the first single),
and the humorous ``Drunk Is Better than Dead.''
</P>
<P>
   The songs were written by Push Stars singer/guitarist Chris
Trapper, who grew up outside Buffalo, N.Y. He writes about boy
chasing girl, sometimes finding girl, sometimes losing girl, but
always with an engaging, indomitable spirit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pretty much all of it is autobiographical,'' says Trapper, who
at 29 is the oldest band member. ``If I tried to write a song just
to be cool, I couldn't do it. It has to be honest. And I'm a white
guy from a country town outside of Buffalo, so that's what I write
about.''
</P>
<P>
   The Push Stars formed nearly four years ago. Trapper had left
another band and was working at the Copley Plaza Hotel as a
purchasing food clerk. His boss saw him writing song lyrics on box
tops and wine cases and told him to try music again. That struck
home with Trapper, who recruited upstate New York friend McLoughlin
(then an engineer at Dreamland Studios in Woodstock) and met
drummer Ryan MacMillan, after a gig MacMillan played at the Middle
East in Cambridge. ``Chris said, `I really like your playing.
You've got a nice feel,' '' notes MacMillan.
</P>
<P>
   The three Push Stars then began playing Tuesday nights at the
Common Ground in Allston, building things up from there. ``We've
played everywhere in town many times,'' says Trapper.
</P>
<P>
   Amazingly, the band never had a rehearsal space, but worked out
song arrangements at shows and soundchecks. ``A band is based on
chemistry and trust _ and we've shared that,'' says Trapper.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, the music stayed simple and concise, so it's no
surprise that the new album follows suit. ``It's a pop record _
three chords and the truth,'' says Trapper.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're confident that we have something,'' he adds. ``And it
feels good to bring that to the public now. More than ever, people
need something positive out there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
