<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-FATHER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRELAND A SOMBER BACKDROP FOR `FATHER' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
THIS IS MY FATHER 
Directed and written by: Paul Quinn 
Starring: Aidan Quinn, James Caan, Jacob Tierney, Colm Meaney,
Donal Donnelly, Brendan Gleeson, Moira Deady, Moya Farrelly, Maria
McDermottroe, Gina Moxley, Eamonn Morriseey, Stephen Rea, John
Cusack, Susan Almgren, Pauline Hutton, Fiona Glascott 
Running time: 120 minutes 
Rated: R (a scene of sexuality and brief language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Compared to most of what we'll see this summer, ``This Is My
Father'' is radically unfashionable. It's a slow, dark, somber but
emotionally solid film that eventually repays the patience it takes
to stay with it. In more ways than one, it's a family film, with
the name Quinn all over it. Paul Quinn wrote and directed, brother
Declan photographed it, and it stars brother Aidan as a
pure-hearted but inarticulate farmer named Kieran. The farmer's
circumstances add up to a textbook case of the reasons young Irish
fled Ireland in the days before the current economic boom and
reverse brain drain.
</P>
<P>
   It's framed by the present-day search of James Caan's burned-out
suburban Chicago high school history teacher for his Irish roots
and, specifically, for the father he never knew. He's spurred on as
well by a need to revive the spirits of his aged mother, recovering
(or perhaps not) from a stroke. For good measure, and perhaps one
story strand more than the film can comfortably accommodate, he
takes his troubled nephew back with him. Before long, they're
installed in Colm Meaney's bed and breakfast, listening to the
proprietor's mother, a treasure trove of local lore, fill in the
blanks in the visitors' history each day at teatime.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the film is given over to the troubled romance of
Quinn's laborer, regarded as a second-class citizen because he grew
up in an orphanage, and the lively young woman, Fiona, who takes a
shine to him. Moya Farrelly, the Irish actress who plays Fiona, is
a real find. She's spirited, beautiful, vivacious, and sincere. The
question is whether Fiona will be allowed to forget she's part of
the village gentry and pursue a romance with a man regarded as her
social inferior by her formidable widowed mother and as her moral
inferior by the fire-and-brimstone clergy, who between them hold
the village in an iron grip.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly the Quinn brothers have called in a lot of favors from
good friends in the business. Such first-rate actors as Donal
Donnelly, Brendan Gleeson, John Cusack, and Stephen Rea fortify the
roster in small but flavorful roles. Caan hardly dominates as the
character whose inquiries set the story in motion. Yet ``This Is My
Father'' is anything but a vanity project. It's deeply felt and
gorgeously, if sometimes diffusely, photographed and acted. Aidan
Quinn gives the film the emotional core it needs as a passionate
but bottled-up man, and Farrelly gives the film its romantic wings.
Prewar Ireland is also a vivid presence in this sometimes ungainly
but always heartfelt and often moving work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-14-99 1401EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990514.0177 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 14:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7274 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-REVIEW-CASTLE-HN     05-14 0608
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-CASTLE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUSTRALIAN MOVIE INSPIRES WRONG KIND OF LAUGHS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDVINS BEITISK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is nothing in movies more crowd-pleasing than the little
guy, tired of being pushed around, getting angry enough to fight
the system.
</P>
<P>
   The bare-bones Australian movie, ``The Castle,'' cashes in on
that theme.
</P>
<P>
   With the possible exception of the cartoonish ``Patch Adams,''
``The Castle'' may be the least subtle beat-the-system film ever
made.
</P>
<P>
   A tow-truck driver and his family have lived happily for years
next to a runway at Melbourne's airport, but their placid lives are
interrupted when airport expansion threatens to take their house
through eminent domain.
</P>
<P>
   The father, Darryl Kerrigan (Michael Caton), decides to fight
the airport through the appeal process, loses, hires a down-and-out
lawyer, loses again, and finally takes his case to Australia's
highest court with the help of a Queen's Counsel he's befriended
(``The kind of lawyer rich people hire.'') Through it all, Kerrigan
is seen as a saint by his youngest son, the narrator.
</P>
<P>
   The acting hits no false notes, from Caton to the mother (Anne
Tenney), a housewife deep into cheesy crafts, to the oldest brother
(Wayne Hope), serving a term in prison for armed robbery.
</P>
<P>
   The middle brother (Anthony Simcoe) searches for bargains in the
paper (``Here's a guy with some jousting sticks, dad''), while the
youngest brother (Stephen Curry) interrupts conversations with
airhead questions and digs holes in the backyard.
</P>
<P>
   The sister (Sophie Lee) graduates from a beauty college and
marries a kick-boxer. The couple honeymoons in Thailand, as
impressed by the airline food as by going to the Orient. Much is
made of her appearance on ``The Price Is Right'' and the fact she's
the only one in the family with a degree.
</P>
<P>
   The father takes pride in everything around him _ his slow
greyhounds, his wife's cooking, a fake chimney on the roof and a
home- made pool room. There's also a powerboat and the family's
jerry-built vacation house by the lake at Bonny Doone (``I reckon
we're the luckiest family in the world,'' Dad keeps saying).
</P>
<P>
   It's the poor white trash lifestyle, seen through a precious
lens, as Kerrigan takes on the government and its preening lawyers.
The movie backs Kerrigan the whole way, but there's a fine line
between laughing at someone and laughing with him. ``The Castle''
constantly crosses that line.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Gleisner, one of four writers on the project, says,
``Australians are very good at laughing at themselves, but it's not
meant as disrespect.'' The movie is supposed to be seen as a
``Capraesque symbol of lost family innocence.''
</P>
<P>
   But ``The Castle,'' unlike the movies of Frank Capra and Preston
Sturges, makes fun of the people at the heart of its story. It
laughs at the Kerrigans' ordinary existence.
</P>
<P>
   As the family sits on the divan, chuckling at the TV, the
youngest son says, ``If there's anything Dad likes better than
`Funniest Home Videos,' it's `The Best of Funniest Home Videos.'''
The family is meant more than anything to be lovable, but the movie
never stops reminding you these folks are borderline dumb.
</P>
<P>
   There are some honestly funny bits, like Kerrigan's midnight tow
truck attack on the people causing him trouble, periodic
neighborhood gatherings, and Kerrigan's lawyer (Tiriel Mora) asking
the appeals court to feel ``the vibe of the thing'' when looking at
the Australian Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the laughs, though, come at the cost of the Kerrigans,
which undermines the movie's basic decency.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
