<HEADLINE>
`PLATINUM' DULLS ROSS-BRANDY PAIRING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
DOUBLE PLATINUM 
Starring: Brandy, Diana Ross, Roger Rees, Harvey Fierstein,
Christine Ebersole, Brian Stokes Mitchell 
Directed by: Robert Allan Ackerman 
On: ABC 
Time: Sunday at 9 p.m. 
Rated: TVPG 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Watching Diana Ross's hair get big-bigger-biggest during the
course of ``Double Platinum'' is a sad reminder of what this
made-for-TV melodrama could have been. If only the rest of the
movie _ the script, the performances, the costumes, the sets _ had
followed the same camp aesthetic, this familiar mother-daughter
story could have been juicy, soapy fun. It could have had the
bloated sentimentality of ``Beaches,'' or the insane emotionality
of ``Mommie Dearest.'' Instead, ``Double Platinum'' ends up as a
safe, middle-of-the-road vehicle for two singer-actresses, one that
tries in vain to fill its dramatic vacuum with a constant flow of
big, generic ballads.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody had the idea: Diana Ross and Brandy star as mother and
daughter singers who are reunited after Ross abandoned Brandy as an
infant to pursue her career. But nobody invested much time in
elaborating on that concept with a fresh script, and so ``Double
Platinum'' runs through all the showbiz cliches as mother and
daughter come to terms with each other and each other's careers.
Brandy's Kayla had always revered the music of Ross's Olivia King,
but when she discovers Olivia is her mother, she is angry and
vindictive. She's not even consoled when Olivia provides her with
connections in the music business, and makes her into a hot new
star. There are absolutely no surprises in the plot, and the
dialogue is ridden with expected lines like ``Please don't play
mom. It's a little late for that.''
</P>
<P>
   It's really a pleasure to see Ross, who doesn't act very often.
But she's too laid back here, unwilling to have some fun and come
off like a true bad guy for a few scenes. Brandy is more moody,
although her sullenness becomes tedious after a while, particularly
when you realize that she's dumped her father and best friend back
in St. Louis as easily as her mother dumped her so many years ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-14-99 1402EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990514.0179 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 14:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7277 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-JOAN-BOS &LR;      05-14 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-JOAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ST. JOAN' SCORES A SURPRISING VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
JOAN OF ARC 
Starring: Leelee Sobieski, Jacqueline Bisset, Powers Boothe,
Olympia Dukakis, Maury Chaykin, Shirley MacLaine, Neil Patrick
Harris, Robert Loggia, Peter O'Toole, Maximilian Schell, Peter
Strauss 
Directed by: Christian Duguay 
On: CBS 
Time: Sunday and Tuesday, 9-11 p.m. 
Rated: TVPG 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It wouldn't be hard for ``Joan of Arc'' to look like a class
act, as it arrives so quickly in the wake of NBC's fickle, phony
``Noah's Ark,'' which managed to reduce the Bible to ``The
Flintstones'' meets ``Waterworld.''
</P>
<P>
   But CBS's two-part miniseries about the 15th-century peasant
girl who helped unite France is definitely more than a relative
success. With a grace and an ambition that are unusual for sweeps
``event'' TV, the movie relies as much on spiritual and religious
themes as it does on a haunting visual style. A few of the
historical twists and battle sequences are confusing, a muddy crush
of horses, swords, French cities, Prince Valiant hairdos, and
violent deaths. And some of the supporting players are wasted, with
Olympia Dukakis's Mother Babette allowed to extend her emotional
range from very maternal to very, very maternal. But ``Joan of
Arc'' contains a handful of wonderful characterizations, most
surprisingly from Neil Patrick Harris as the crafty King Charles
VII, and it manages to build to its fiery climax with restraint and
almost none of the sanctimoniousness you generally find in prime
time's other religious forays. It's never holier than thou.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joan of Arc,'' which airs Sunday and Tuesday nights at 9 on
Ch. 4, leads off with its most drab, least engaging scenes, as
young Joan discovers her one-on-one relationship with God during
her poor childhood in southern France. But once Joan leaves her
hostile father's house for a crusade to save her war-torn country,
the movie gains in pageantry and becomes more politically complex.
If Joan of Arc lived today, hearing the voices of saints and seeing
blazing hallucinations, she'd probably become a street person, and
``Joan of Arc'' would probably be more like ``The Fisher King.''
But in the 1420s people are drawn to her divine visions and
unshakeable faith, and the teenager becomes a mythic heroine for
whom her countrymen would give their lives. This power over the
masses makes Joan a perfect pawn for wily leaders, including Maury
Chaykin's Sir Robert and Harris's King Charles. It also makes her
into a pioneer for women, as she is consistently berated for
wearing men's clothing and engaging in men's pursuits.
</P>
<P>
   As Joan, Leelee Sobieski is all deadpan determination and
asexuality. The 16-year-old actress is low-key enough to hold the
screen for four hours without becoming tiresome, and she manages to
keep her contemporary affect at a minimum. She has the air of God
about her, but she is quite human, and her mission is sometimes
marred by pride. Oddly, Sobieski's biggest liability is her uncanny
resemblance to Helen Hunt. She has a depth and somberness that the
``Mad About You'' star probably couldn't call forth, but the
likeness is surprisingly distracting.
</P>
<P>
   While Sobieski's presence is sober and confident, the other
actors are vibrant and neurotic. Peter O'Toole shines as Charles's
spiritual adviser, Bishop Cauchon. He shakes with cynical intensity
in the face of Joan's claims, urging her not to pretend that any
human can know God's will. O'Toole's a scene stealer, of course,
and the angrier he gets, the more he leans on his syllables: ``The
only guide that will serve you well is mercy.'' He stimulates one
of the movie's central conflicts, as his position in the Church
leads him to fear and doubt a passionate faith that reaches beyond
Church teachings. Shirley MacLaine has a short, memorable role in
Part 2, as the dying Madame de Beaurevoir. Both tough and fragile,
she wants Joan to become her surrogate daughter and to fight for
the Bergundians. She looks a bit like an exhausted Agnes Moorehead,
and in one touching moment you can see her heart breaking as Joan
recoils from her touch.
</P>
<P>
   Harris appears to be having a good time as the foppish, naive,
and, ultimately, duplicitous King Charles. He's come a long way
from his days as the star of ``Doogie Howser, M.D.,'' as he slings
lines like, ``Bishop, don't be so dreary.'' Charles doesn't like
being upstaged by Joan, but he seems familiar with the rules of
fame as we know them all too well in the 20th century _
particularly the business about backlash. Joan doesn't like being
famous, but she knows it can help her cause, even if it finally
destroys her, which, of course, it does.
</P>
<P>
   Even when the noble Joan is burned to death for heresy, ``Joan
of Arc'' resists undermining its story of faith by trading in
manipulative schmaltz. It's the sort of TV movie that has something
more than tears at stake.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
