<P>
   COURTS-HEARST (Washington) _ Most Americans give state and local
courts high marks for upholding justice, but many feel they don't
act quickly enough and that taking a case to court is unaffordable,
according to a survey funded by the Hearst Corporation. Frank A.
Bennack Jr., Hearst's president and chief executive officer, tells
officials attending a national conference on public perception of
the judicial system that the courts came out ``just OK on average''
in the survey. Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist also addresses
the group. By DAN FREEDMAN and JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN.
