<HEADER>
A7293 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-REVIEW-CONFESSIO     05-14 0603
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-CONFESSIONS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INGMAR BERGMAN IS BACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WALTER ADDIEGO  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The human face is the starting point for our work,'' Ingmar
Bergman once wrote. So it is in ``Private Confessions,'' in which
his gift for laying bare the human heart is given haunting,
sometimes lacerating, form.
</P>
<P>
   This is a film about people talking to each other, with the
classic Bergman themes front and center: the painful, perhaps
futile search for love, God, freedom, truth and meaning.
</P>
<P>
   The story is simple and sparely told. A spirited young woman has
a revealing series of conversations with the three men who are most
important to her _ an elderly priest, her husband and her lover.
Both of the latter are theology students. The tale begins in 1925,
and the woman happens to be Bergman's mother.
</P>
<P>
   This is the third film in which Bergman, the son of a Lutheran
minister, has tried to come to grips with complex family issues
(1982's ``Fanny and Alexander'' and 1992's ``Best Intentions'' are
the others). All were made for Swedish TV.
</P>
<P>
   The director is Liv Ullmann, but this is in every other respect
a Bergman movie. Although he retired from film directing in 1983,
he has continued to write for the stage and screen, often drawing
on autobiographical materials; Ullmann, of course, is Bergman's
longtime star and protege, and the actors here, Pernilla August and
Max von Sydow, are also Bergman stalwarts.
</P>
<P>
   The picture was even photographed by Bergman's celebrated
cameraman, Sven Nykvist.
</P>
<P>
   The film is broken into five ``conversations'' of varying
lengths.
</P>
<P>
   (The film's European title is ``Private Conversations,'' which
we're told was Martin Luther's term for his version of the
sacrament of confession.)
</P>
<P>
   In the first, Anna (August), a young married woman, tells her
pastor, Jacob (von Sydow), of the affair she's been conducting with
Tomas, a divinity student and friend of her husband. Though clearly
anguished, she describes her joy in the liaison and declares she
won't break it off.
</P>
<P>
   Jacob, who has known her since her confirmation (she calls him
``uncle''), tells her she must end all communications with her
lover and inform her husband. He's moved to reveal his own complex,
deeply held beliefs: ``We act out many roles, mostly to protect
ourselves, then we imperceptibly lose whatever is not a role. . .
.Only poets, musicians and saints have handed us mirrors where we
can discern the unfathomable. It consoles me to think of the
sanctity of man and the mysterious immensities surrounding us.''
</P>
<P>
   These remarks provide a context for the remaining talks, which
take place both before and after the first conversation. We watch
Anna inform her weakling husband of the affair, then observe her
and her lover on a tragic, stolen weekend. Two more talks with
Jacob follow, one during his final illness, the other when Anna is
a teenager.
</P>
<P>
   The marvelous August, her visage plain and wholesome as a
Puritan's, played the same character in ``Best Intentions.'' (She
has a modest role in the upcoming ``Star Wars'' prequel.) In
``Private Confessions,'' the drama is played out not only in
Bergman's words but on her radiant, sublimely expressive face.
</P>
<P>
   Out of respect for these two powerful forces, Ullmann uses the
most austere directorial means: essentially a sequence of talking
heads that you might mistakenly label ``static'' if this were
lesser material. Von Sydow is magisterial. His gaunt face and
rumbling voice have become, for me, impossible to distinguish from
Bergman's own.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-14-99 1411EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990514.0183 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 14:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7296 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-COLU     05-14 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S RESEARCH, I SWEAR IT IS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I find myself suddenly deluged with porno
e-mail on America Online. I am curious how I became the recipient
of such drivel. My only Internet usage has been for e-mail and for
searching medical literature through the Library of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   _ Spammee
</P>
<P>
   DEAR SPAMMEE: Well, where do you think congressmen keep all
their dirty books? No wonder you're getting those solicitations.
And I wasn't aware that the latest copy of ``Big Buxom Babes'' was
considered ``medical literature.'' I'm more of a National
Geographic man myself.
</P>
<P>
   Don't think you're special just because some scumbucket is
filling your mailbox every morning. Spam is a fact of life. Who
knows how you got on the list? It could have been that time you
typed in the wrong keyword or visited the American Urological
Association home page or downloaded pictures of farm animals for
your kid's school project. There are slimeballs out there who spend
their whole day trolling AOL and a hundred other places for
potential suckers.
</P>
<P>
   About all you can do is set your mail controls to accept letters
only from a pre-approved list of other AOL members and Internet
addresses. And nobody says you have to read any of the crud you
receive. Delete it all and go back to your research, unless you
actually think a letter with a subject line of ``Free XXX pics''
could be from dear old Aunt Mabel. And that's just plain sick.
Maybe you should run for Congress.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I just read an article that when you visit a
Web site, you provide information about yourself, including your
viewing habits, search terms, etc. What is the truth?
</P>
<P>
   _ Not So Anonymous
</P>
<P>
   DEAR NOT: Are you kidding? They even know if you're wearing
clean underwear. The people who build Web sites are fond of pulling
every little trick out of the book when it comes down to figuring
out who you are and why you'd like to buy their products or enjoy
their muck-laden spam. Weren't you paying attention during the last
question?
</P>
<P>
   Sure, they get all the normal stuff, like what browser or
Internet provider you're using. But every time you click on a link
or search a site, there's the potential some Web weasel just earned
a commission. And if you fill out any questionnaires? Well, duh.
What did you think they were going to do with that information?
</P>
<P>
   Here it is: If you do anything at all on the Internet, then
somebody else probably knows what it is. In fact, I can tell what
you're doing right now. And you'd better stop it.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I don't understand how a program like Yahoo!
Pager knows that a particular person is online.
</P>
<P>
   _ I'm Not Here
</P>
<P>
   DEAR I'M: Isn't anybody listening to what I've been saying? If
you're on the Net, somebody somewhere knows you are there. Programs
like Pager and AIM and ICQ compound the exposure. They log you in
to a server with all the other people running those programs. When
you put people on your notification list or vice versa, the
insidious little things actually query that server to see who's on.
</P>
<P>
   Call me paranoid, but sometimes I'd like to check out that hot
urology page the first guy was looking at without everybody in the
world knowing I'm hooked up. But that's just me.
</P>
<P>
   (Noted computerologist Dr. Emilio Bombay has never done anything
on the Internet he would be ashamed to talk about with Jerry
Springer for the right fee. He can be reached at
drbombay(at)star-telegram.com, via snail-mail at Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth 76101, or fax: (817) 390-7257.
His real name is Michael Gerst, editorial systems manager for the
Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services
on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
