<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990514.0188 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 14:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7307 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEACHER-PAY-$ADV16-CO     05-14 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEACHER-PAY-$ADV16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    STARTING PAY FOR TEACHERS STAYS LOW
 &HT;    590&AMP;adds. With TEACHER-PAY-DATA. For release Sunday, May 16.
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As the nation's public schools gear up to hire
millions of new teachers over the next decade, they are offering
salaries far below what most of this year's college graduates can
expect.
</P>
<P>
   A report to be issued this summer by the American Federation of
Teachers (AFT) shows that the average newly licensed teacher with a
bachelor's degree earned $25,735 in the 1997-98 school year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a disgrace,'' said AFT President Sandra Feldman.
``Ultimately, if we plan to find a way to fill what will be
something like two million teacher slots over the next decade,
we're going to have to raise salaries.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with adjustments for inflation, starting pay for teachers
remains below what is being offered to new graduates in other
fields.
</P>
<P>
   The typical college graduate with a bachelor's degree is being
offered between $33,900 and $37,200 a year, according to a national
study by Phil Gardner, director of career services and placement at
Michigan State University.
</P>
<P>
   Most dramatically, in the red-hot, worker-short field of
technology information, even a two-year associate degree in
computer science routinely leads to offers of between $32,900 and
$35,200.
</P>
<P>
   ``Education is in a bind unless we come up with more money,''
Gardner said. ``I had an education major working for me who gave up
teaching and started her own Web site development company. It's
creative work and she can make more money that way.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the report provided to Cox Newspapers by the AFT,
state averages for new teachers in the last school year were above
$29,000 in only three states: Alaska ($33,162), Connecticut
($29,506) and Pennsylvania ($29,581). The averages were below
$21,000 in four states: Mississippi ($20,630), South Dakota
($20,340), Idaho ($20,248) and North Dakota ($19,146).
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody goes into teaching for the pay. It's something in your
soul,'' said Linda Koutoufas, an veteran teacher at Woodstock
Elementary School in Virginia Beach, Va. ``But I know of no new
teacher, not a one, who does not work two jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Chase, president of the National Education Association, said
schools need to find a lot more qualified teachers in math,
science, history and special and bilingual education. In addition,
he said, some states and districts face shortages caused by
``teacher retirement, population mobility, increasing birth rates,
immigration and a trend toward smaller class size.''
</P>
<P>
   In union and non-union school districts alike, starting pay is
held down by the custom of raising all salaries at all levels in
lock-step percentages, rather than in response to changing demands
for new teachers or for certain specialties, such as science and
math.
</P>
<P>
   AFT data show that in the 10 years that ended in 1998, both the
new teachers and experienced teachers received pay raises that
averaged about 4 percent a year before inflation.
</P>
<P>
   That meant that while pay for experienced teachers (including
increases for seniority or graduate degrees) rose by $1,126 a year,
the pay for beginners rose by only $718 annually.
</P>
<P>
   ``That particularly hurts in the competition for the most
academically able students,'' said Susan Moore Johnson, academic
dean of the Harvard Graduate School of Education. ``Most of today's
young people don't see themselves as choosing a lifetime career
when they take that job after earning their degree; they're
comparing what they can make right now in investment banking with
what they can make in teaching.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   To get new teachers, many districts are recruiting people who
earned teaching certificates but never did teach, or who left the
profession to raise families. Most states also offer special
regulations and courses that help people in middle management or
the military switch to teaching at mid-life.
</P>
<P>
   Those mature recruits could fill as many as half the vacancies
expected in the decade ahead.
</P>
<P>
   However, the competition for younger applicants is fierce:
</P>
<P>
   _ Detroit, short 1,000 teachers, pushed its starting pay above
$35,000, and offers a $1,000 signing bonus to those who sign a
five-year contract.
</P>
<P>
   _ Massachusetts is offering bonus of $5,000 a year for four
years to the top 50 applicants in a new quality-teacher hiring
program.
</P>
<P>
   _ California offers education courses on the Internet to help
the more than 20,000 uncertified teachers working with
``emergency'' credentials in that state qualify for permanent
teaching jobs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Applicants in states as different as Alaska, Georgia,
Maryland, Mississippi and South Carolina can get daily updates on
almost all of each state's job openings, salary schedules and
incentive programs on Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   _ In Maryland, Howard County offers a $1,000 bonus for those
signing one-year teaching contracts, and Baltimore offers $5,000
toward closing costs on the purchase of a home within the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're certainly not going to object to people getting that
kind of additional money,'' Feldman said. ``But ultimately what you
have to do to keep people on the job is to pay them a professional
salary.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Magi (cq) D. Shepley, a special education teacher, says she left
her first teaching job in Baltimore to take a better-paying job in
a suburban district because ``I owe $26,000 in student loans, and I
only made a bit more than that'' a year.
</P>
<P>
   To keep teaching in public schools she must earn 24 to 33 hours
of graduate credits within seven years. She estimates this will
cost her $11,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``My 'teacher shortage area' deferment (for teaching in
Baltimore) runs out in six months, at which time I'll start paying
$259 per month on those undergraduate loans, not counting what I'll
be paying back to my credit union for grad school,'' Shepley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I work over the summer, while taking graduate classes,'' she
said. She commutes in a car which has more than 209,000 miles on
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very soon I'll be forced to buy a new car,'' she said. ``It's
a tight squeeze.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
