<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATOMIC-TRAIN-$ADV16-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ATOMIC TRAIN' IS CHEESY FUN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, May 16)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK McGUIRE  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A freight train laden with nuclear waste and _ gasp _ a
contraband Soviet nuclear bomb, armed of course, rumbles toward
Denver. Then . . . no brakes! And it's all downhill.
</P>
<P>
   Our hero jumps from a helicopter to try to stop the locomotive,
almost succeeds, but no. Fire lights up the skies. Coloradans flee
toward Kansas. Too late! Cue mushroom cloud.
</P>
<P>
   All this . . . and Rob Lowe, too.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is that Cold War-era title, ``Atomic Train.'' The
four-hour miniseries airs tonight and Monday (9 p.m. EDT on NBC).
Oh, the humanity of it all. Paging Ed Wood, paging Ed Wood.
</P>
<P>
   Put all these elements together, and this recipe-for-a-disaster
flick seems like a recipe for a disaster. Then comes the biggest
shocker of them all: It ain't that bad.
</P>
<P>
   A tad slow in the first half, at times thrilling in the second,
this is a film made for the wrong venue. ``Atomic Train'' would be
a quintessential 1959 B-movie, best viewed from the back seat of a
Chevy Bel Air convertible. Sure, it's cheesy, but it is fun cheese.
</P>
<P>
   While the special effects are there, including a train crash
just a notch or two below the standard set by ``The Fugitive,''
``Atomic Train'' has an old-time feel, especially when Lowe _ as
National Traffic Safety Board investigator John Seger _ is
scampering onto, in and around the locomotive. Lowe says he is
comfortable around trains, but did that mean he really had to do
many of his own stunts?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what my wife asks. I'm glad she was not on location,''
Lowe said in a recent interview. ``This is a genre that needs every
element to elevate it above something we've all seen before.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowe is getting good as this Armageddon thing (remember him as
Nick Andros in the 1994 Stephen King miniseries ``The Stand''?). He
has recovered from his late-'80s videotaped career implosion and is
carving out a solid niche for himself as a secondary character in
movies. In ``Atomic Train,'' he proves he can still handle the
lead. Well, co-lead.
</P>
<P>
   The real star, at least in Part I, is the train, a vehicle that
traditionally on screen is a character unto itself rivaled only by
the 1930s gangster sedan with running boards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most guys love them,'' Lowe said. ``There is something
genetically imprinted into Americans (about trains). Cinematically,
they are great characters. I've never seen a train movie I didn't
love.''
</P>
<P>
   A subplot to the movie is Seger's effort at melding a new family
with second wife Megan (Kristin Davis, of HBO's ``Sex and the
City''), her young son and his teenage daughter.
</P>
<P>
   That's right, Lowe, 35, former teen idol, plays the dad of a
teenage daughter in the movie. ``Nobody was more worried about the
believability than me,'' said Lowe, who is the father of two young
sons. More surprising than him playing a dad is that halfway
through you forget about the narrow age gap.
</P>
<P>
   Complicating the new arrangement is Megan Seger's ex, a gung-ho
cop named Mac played by Esai Morales (``The Burning Season'').
Morales comes off as a heavy-handed macho clown, but you realize
soon enough he is just a blundering father trying desperately to
connect with his kid.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you liked `The Hunt for Red October,' if you liked `Crimson
Tide,' you will love this movie,'' Lowe said. ``It is a nonstop
roller-coaster ride where the characters have tremendous humanity.
This is an action movie that takes its time and services
humanity.''
</P>
<P>
   There was some talk within NBC of temporarily shelving the
project after the school attack in Littleton, Colo. But while this
story does involve a bomb and takes place in Colorado, the
similarities end there.
</P>
<P>
   While the network was right to raise the question of whether
such a film was appropriate, it was equally right to go ahead and
air the two-parter. The Denver NBC affiliate has chosen not to air
the movie.
</P>
<P>
   In a laden Sunday night of television, all three of the alphabet
networks have special offerings. All are worth watching to varying
extents, depending on what you are looking for:
</P>
<P>
   Historical: ``Joan of Arc'' (Sunday and Tuesday at 9 p.m. EDT,
CBS.) Excellent drama.
</P>
<P>
   Sentimental: ``Double Platinum'' (Sunday at 9 p.m. EDT, ABC).
The ABC movie pairs Diana Ross and Brandy as a mother and daughter,
both singers, who are reunited. And, in the end, it feels so good
(Yeah, yeah, I know: It's Peaches and Herb).
</P>
<P>
   Action: ``Atomic Train.'' Plus, it's real fun to say over and
over and over. Try it.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the Albany, N.Y., Times Union TV/Radio writer
and can be contacted at 518-454-5467 or on e-mail at
mmcguiretimesunion.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
