<HEADLINE>
UNIVERSITY OF CALIFORNIA TEACHING ASSISTANTS AT BERKELEY UNIONIZE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC BRAZIL  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Capping a 16-year organizing drive which
generated three strikes, graduate teaching assistants at the
University of California at Berkeley have voted to unionize.
</P>
<P>
   The California Public Employment Relations Board, or PERB,
announced Thursday that the vote by members of the Association of
Graduate Student Employees for unionization was 833-293.
</P>
<P>
   The 70 percent turnout of the campus's 1,000 teaching assistants
in the election, which was conducted April 27-29, was the second
highest in the UC system's history, said association spokesman
Scott Prudham.
</P>
<P>
   Graduate assistants will be represented for collective
bargaining purposes by the United Auto Workers. ``We expect to
start bargaining pretty soon,'' said Prudham, a graduate student in
energy and resources.
</P>
<P>
   UC-Berkeley is the second campus at which graduate assistants
have voted for unionization. The UCLA unit, which voted March 9-11,
has just begun bargaining.
</P>
<P>
   Graduate assistants at UC-Berkeley are paid $1,200 to $1,400 per
month during their five-month appointments and receive partial
health insurance and partial fee remission. They must re-apply for
their positions at the end of each five-month work period.
</P>
<P>
   The UC administration long resisted the unionization campaign on
the grounds that graduate assistants were not, technically
speaking, employees covered by the PERB.
</P>
<P>
   The board ruled last year that the graduate assistants were
within its jurisdiction and ordered elections for all eight of the
UC campuses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-14-99 1436EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
