<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990514.0192 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 14:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7321 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-REVIEW-MIDSUMMER     05-14 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-MIDSUMMER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MIDSUMMER NIGHT'S DREAM' WITH ALL THE FAIRY DUST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WESLEY MORRIS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   All the women in Michael Hoffman's ``A Midsummer Night's Dream''
look guiltily ravaged, sexually harassed and newly turned on _ like
they've wandered into the film's sun-dried 1920s Tuscan locales
from the wrap-party of an NC-17 Prince video.
</P>
<P>
   Their tendrils look more wrangled than done, their costumes are
almost on straight and their desire is barely in disguise, but
``necklines are high'' as the intro tells us, so there's not much
more in the way of dirty-mindedness than the implication that each
of the Shakespearean ladies that appear on-screen emits that
getting-it-on-in-a-cul-de-sac glow, even if it's not altogether
true.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman fools with the playwright's love farce with a
relaxed-fit, corsets-be-damned glee that, while truncating the
intricacies of the play's character relations, unleashes copious
amounts of fairy dust, body glitter and innocuous lust.
</P>
<P>
   That and Kevin Kline standing on the tip-toes of his softly
riotous jester-with-an-XL-IQ powers. As Bottom, the haplessly
grandiose leader of an actor's troupe, Kline pirouettes through the
film like a clumsy reject from some dance company smart enough to
say ``no.''
</P>
<P>
   Save an overjoyed quickie by the madly emotive Sam Rockwell as
Flute, the ``boy'' in Bottom's troupe, Kline is the most astral
creature in a constellation lit up by a pack of actors who manage
to strike even when they're wearing their characters as if they
were plucked from a hanger in wardrobe: one-outfit, one-note
persona.
</P>
<P>
   But it's fun, for instance, to realize that Calista Flockhart is
that missing link in the degrees of separation between ``Ally
McBeal'' creator David E. Kelley and William Shakespeare.
</P>
<P>
   Flockhart's foppish, neurotic Helen is a lovesick rag doll of
ruthlessly lonely proportions, humiliated, rejected, embarrassed
and in constant search of a pratfall to clarify exactly how
pathetic she is. ``I am your spaniel . . . ,'' she tells Demetrius
(Christian Bale).
</P>
<P>
   Whoa, Helen! One more self-flagellating confession like that and
you may as well be cat-fighting your rival in a waist-deep mudbath.
Huh? Oh that's right: She does pull hair and get dirty with Hermia
(Anna Friel) over two men. The other suitor, Lysander (Dominic
West), finds himself smitten with Ally _ doh! Helen! _ after a
spell is sprinkled on him in his slumber. The spellbinder is the
magically inept Puck (Stanley Tucci) and the soap opera on a yo-yo
is by Oberon's (Rupert Everett) design.
</P>
<P>
   Oberon's romantic machinations with the deity Titania (Michelle
Pfeiffer) are clipped at the expense of the 
Helen-wants-Demetrius-who-wants-Hermia-who-wants-Lysander-who-wants-
Helen-who-is-suddenly-wanted-back-by-Demetrius love rhombus.
</P>
<P>
   Though maybe Hoffman had something in mind, considering that
Everett carries on in a doldrums deadpan and Pfeiffer, who hasn't
looked this ravishing since swiveling all over Jeff Bridges'
Steinway, doesn't act so much as susurrate and respire like a
pixie-diva cum window fan made of God's own heavenly cardboard.
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons Pfeiffer, who's cameoed here, seems
particularly indifferent is that we're supposed to believe in the
spell under which she's been accidentally placed that makes her not
mind being in love with Bottom after he's transformed into an ass
(the beast of burden sort).
</P>
<P>
   She's inviting but school-play-lite, which is perfectly aligned
with the makeshift splendor of Lucianna Arrighi and Gianni
Giovagnoni's forest set. It's a sylvan, playpen-bound Oz where the
sprites and satyrs fondle 12-inch opera LPs and build bicyclettes
when they're not combing each other's hair.
</P>
<P>
   The leafy, nectar-soaked atmospherics and the horseplay that
abounds are the exuberant, eye-candy cortex of the ``Shakespeare in
Love'' brain: undaunted by being anything more than what it is _ a
gorgeous sliver of grown-up ambrosia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
