r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     05-14 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILL BUSH FLAME OUT? DON'T BET ON IT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's really nothing to dislike about George W. Bush. He's a
nice guy. He's sincere. His political philosophy is conservative in
the best sense of the word, which is to say that his ideas and
policies are thoughtful, responsible and decidedly unthreatening.
</P>
<P>
   And yet there are people who apparently loathe the Texas
governor _ people who seem determined to leave no stone unturned in
their crusade to derail Bush's fledgling presidential candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   We're talking about an extremely small minority here, but it's
an adamant minority. Any time that I say a kind word about Bush in
the newspaper, for example, I can count on getting a phone message
or two in which the caller pronounces Bush a worthless bum and
pronounces me a pitiable idiot for supporting him.
</P>
<P>
   To these readers I reply: I may be an idiot, but that's not why
I'm a Bush supporter. The fact is, Bush is a terrific public
servant and an outstanding politician who is on the verge of
proving himself more than worthy of the front-runner status he has
achieved in an election that is nearly 18 months away.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's what the anti-Bush crowd is ticked off about _ that
the son of former President George Bush could so casually grab the
lead in the 2000 sweepstakes without even stepping into the
starting gate. He has not, after all, made an official announcement
that he's a candidate, and yet he consistently and convincingly
trounces all the other would-be presidents _ Republican and
Democrat _ in every public-opinion poll that comes along.
</P>
<P>
   There has to be more to it than that, though. Some of this
anti-Bush sentiment showed up during his 1998 campaign for
re-election as governor.
</P>
<P>
   Hardly a week went by last summer and fall that I failed to get
a call from some Bush-basher who demanded: ``What in the world has
this guy done to deserve being re-elected? Name one thing. Name
just one darn (actually, the adjective was usually stronger than
that) thing that he's done.''
</P>
<P>
   Those calls were easy to answer, of course, since Bush had done
any number of things to deserve being re-elected.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, he had kept every promise he made during his 1994
campaign _ a spectacular and virtually unheard of accomplishment by
any politician. Most of them start breaking promises at least two
weeks before they take the oath of office.
</P>
<P>
   Bush promised plenty in that first campaign for governor:
welfare reform, tort reform, education reform, revision of the
juvenile justice code, property tax relief. By developing a spirit
of cooperation and mutual interest with a state Legislature that is
notorious for ignoring the wishes of governors, Bush managed to
deliver every one of the promised improvements.
</P>
<P>
   And now he is working hard to push his 1998 campaign promises
through the Legislature before hitting the presidential campaign
trail next month.
</P>
<P>
   And while the governor tends to the job that he promised to give
top priority before seeking any other, the critics relentlessly
take potshots.
</P>
<P>
   They bash Bush for what he says, what he doesn't say, what he's
thinking, what he might be thinking, what he might have thought if
he had given any thought to whatever it is that his critics think
he ought to be thinking about.
</P>
<P>
   The critics can be found mostly in the media, of course, not
among the general public. Out here in the heartland, the few
Bush-bashers willing to weigh in seem to be the same ones who've
been bashing him for years.
</P>
<P>
   As for the media, well, it's only a matter of time until they
see that the Bush-for-president phenomenon is real, that the Bush
bandwagon is fueled up and ready to roll _ that the
self-destructive flame-out that they so eagerly anticipate is not
going to happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Enjoy the sun while you can, Governor,'' Newsweek's Howard
Fineman wrote in the magazine's May 17 edition. ``After months of
pursuing his stay-at-home, low-profile campaign, Bush is about to
step into the maelstrom.''
</P>
<P>
   Maelstrom, my eye. The only thing Bush is about to step into is
the fast lane to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
