<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 14:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7327 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FORBES-SITE-HNS &LR;      05-14 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORBES-SITE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORBES' NEW WEB SITE IS A VIRTUAL LAND OF CONSERVATIVE POLITICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GEORGE RAINE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In search of politics that swim against the tide? Had it up to
here with the mainstream media and Stone Age politicians tripping
on the front steps of the information age? This may be the Web site
for you: www.forbes2000.com.
</P>
<P>
   This is the virtual land of conservative politics, both fiscal
and social, and the national online headquarters of Malcolm S.
``Steve'' Forbes, the multimillionaire magazine publisher who is
seeking the Republican nomination for president for the second
time.
</P>
<P>
   Here you will find, for example, a contrary view of Robert
Rubin, the Treasury secretary who was credited in most newspapers
this week with shaping economic policy in a time of gleeful
prosperity and no-show inflation. Rubin is resigning and will be
succeeded by Lawrence Summers, the deputy secretary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Promoting Larry Summers to be U.S. Treasury secretary is like
sending Typhoid Mary into a maternity ward,'' reads a posting from
Forbes, who criticizes fiscal advice the United States has given
abroad in Latin America, Russia and the Pacific Rim because he says
it contributed to currency collapses.
</P>
<P>
   The Rubin news was breaking as Forbes arrived in San Francisco
to give a speech Wednesday, an especially appropriate day for him:
Tax Freedom Day, the symbolic line of demarcation for taxes _ all
income that the average worker earned this year, before that date,
would equal that worker's tax bill (paychecks thereafter can be
used for other purposes).
</P>
<P>
   ``The tax burden is the highest since World War II,'' said
Forbes, 51, the president and editor in chief of Forbes, the
business-oriented magazine his grandfather founded in 1917.
</P>
<P>
   He proposes, as he did in his 1996 candidacy, a flat tax of 17
percent and a form that could be filed on a postcard. There would
be no federal income tax on earnings under $36,000 in the Forbes
plan, one that appeals to 60 percent of Americans, according to a
recent Louis Harris poll.
</P>
<P>
   The flat tax always starts a fight, however, particularly
because key deductions for home mortgages and charitable donations
would be eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   It would ``devastate property values,'' said Rep. Tom Campbell,
R-Calif., who favors the option of a national sales tax and who
also favors Elizabeth Dole in the GOP presidential primary race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can at least make the case with a straight face and more
than a clean conscience that a national sales tax would not
devastate property values,'' said Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   Said a senior Clinton administration official who asked not to
be named: ``If you are not interested in collecting the same amount
of revenue we collect now, then you have to deal with the possible
consequences of throwing the federal budget out, back into
deficit.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes insists his themes will resonate, particularly in
California, where he said he will compete vigorously before the
March 7 primary and where he has installed former state GOP
Chairman John Herrington as campaign director.
</P>
<P>
   ``What will resonate is the idea of the rebirth of freedom,
certainly out here, where there is the potential of the Internet
and the expansion of bandwidth, and having more control over your
life,'' said Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having more choice will resonate, whether it is suppression of
the tax code, health care _ issues the Democrats think are theirs.
Shouldn't we be able to choose any doctor we want?'' asked the
advocate of HMO reform. ``Why should we have to go through a
gatekeeper or bureaucracy?
</P>
<P>
   ``And schooling! Why should a mother have to send her child to a
crummy school?'' asked the advocate of vouchers for private
schools.
</P>
<P>
   He also advocates individuals' ability to invest Social Security
funds in private retirement accounts similar to IRAs or 401(k)
plans. ``People love that because they are in charge of it, not
Washington,'' he said, noting that if individuals die prematurely,
their heirs receive none of the Social Security funds they paid
except for a small survivor benefit.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have nothing for a lifetime of work, but with this system
you do,'' he said. ``More young people believe in UFOs than believe
the Social Security system will be there when they retire.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, Forbes has emphasized his conservative anti-
abortion social agenda, thereby seeking to broaden his appeal
beyond fiscal conservatives to social conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   He also says he'll be helped by the Internet. ``In the old days
you had physical precincts, but now you bring people on
electronically. You mobilize them that way,'' he said, adding that
13,000 campaign volunteers have signed on at www.forbes2000.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
