<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-JOAN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`JOAN OF ARC' IS AN OLD STORY WORTH RETELLING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK McGUIRE  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is a question posed by ``Joan of Arc,'' the engrossing
four-hour miniseries starting Sunday on CBS:
</P>
<P>
   If a person is the embodiment of a myth, can that myth in fact
be a reality? Or is that person just a fraud, since a myth is
merely a morally relevant fictitious tale that can't come true?
</P>
<P>
   What is true is a simple but devout teenage farm girl inspired
and led her people into battle from 1428 to 1430, only to be
betrayed and burned at the stake in 1431 as a heretic. In the eyes
of the church, acknowledging her would be to acknowledge her power
_ and challenge its own.
</P>
<P>
   More than a half a millennium later, Joan of Arc remains a
powerful and everlasting symbol, raised to sainthood by the
Catholic Church that condemned her. A medieval feminist whose life
had a Christ-like parallel (sans the pacificism), hers is a story
that still resonates.
</P>
<P>
   CBS has gathered the most star-studded cast of the May sweeps
for this miniseries (Sunday and Tuesday at 9 p.m. EDT). In the lead
of Joan of Arc is Leelee Sobieski, portraying a teen who believes
she is empowered by the word of God through direct conversation
with saints to unite the people of France against England.
</P>
<P>
   Peter O'Toole, Olympia Dukakis, Maximilian Schell, Peter
Strauss, Jaqueline Bisset, Powers Boothe, Robert Loggia, Neil
Patrick Harris, Chad Willett and Shirley MacLaine in a cameo also
star in this historical drama.
</P>
<P>
   Was Joan, an illiterate from Domremy in the South of France, the
mythical Maid of Lorraine foretold by the wizard Merlin? Her power
to inspire and lead France on its way to victory in the 100 Years'
War says yes. Her piety and devoutness say yes.
</P>
<P>
   But the church and the king she helped install recognized the
danger of the power she had, as myth and person. Her death was
pre-ordained.
</P>
<P>
   Sobieski first garnered widespread attention and praise for her
starring role in the 1998 Merchant-Ivory production ``A Soldier's
Daughter Never Cries.'' She was also in, among other films, ``Deep
Impact,'' and will appear this summer in ``Eyes Wide Shut,'' the
Stanley Kubrick/Tom Cruise/Nicole Kidman film.
</P>
<P>
   Sobieski, who has a passing resemblance to a younger Helen Hunt
with a little bit of Jewel mixed in, plays the complex Joan
brilliantly, at times the confident leader emboldened by the
saints, at other times a confused girl who does not know her role
in God's plans.
</P>
<P>
   As magnificent as Sobieski is, it is O'Toole who gives the most
stunning performance as Bishop Cauchon, who first advises the
French King Charles (Harris), then serves as Joan's prosecutor in
her church trial on heresy charges.
</P>
<P>
   O'Toole's character struggles throughout, between the vanity of
holding onto his role as the king's adviser and his powerful
position in the church, to finally believing that executing Joan is
the only way to save this girl's soul. In the end he realizes, too
late, that he was also fighting for, and losing, his own salvation.
</P>
<P>
   Filmed in the Czech Republic, the battle scenes star not Joan,
nor the other soldiers, nor swords, nor horses, catapults, ladders
knocked off parapets, hand-to-hand combat, nor men dying _ although
all are there.
</P>
<P>
   No, the featured player, a character really, is the mud. Weapons
change throughout the history of warfare, from the rock to the
spear to the gun to the B-2 bomber. But mud, brown and black and
rivers of red from battle, mud has remained the constant.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Joan of Arc,'' engulfing ground coupled with a gray sky
capture the brutality of war better than any graphic gore.
</P>
<P>
   Thankfully, the miniseries does not attempt to trot out fake
French accents (a French accent, from Powers Boothe? I don't think
so), which could have created a Kevin Costner-as-Robin Hood
scenario where the dialects somehow get lost halfway through the
movie. And this production, directed by Christian Duguay and
written by Ronald Parker and Michael Miller, is too good to fall
into that trap.
</P>
<P>
   As flames lap at Joan, who is tied to the stake, she looks
toward heaven and says repeatedly: ``Thank you. Thank you.'' In a
lackluster television season, you may say the same after watching
``Joan of Arc.''
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the Albany, N.Y., Times Union TV/Radio writer
and can be contacted at 518-454-5467 or on e-mail at
mmcguiretimesunion.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
