<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DOUBLE PLATINUM' ALL GLITTER AND NO SUBSTANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Double Platinum'' had the good sense to cast a diva and a
diva-in-waiting as a mother-and-daughter tandem, and even better
sense to put them in front of a microphone as many times as humanly
possible.
</P>
<P>
   Overplayed with teary emotion by Diana Ross, Olivia King is a
pure-voiced careerist singer, forced to soul-search when she
realizes that she has everything except the daughter she walked out
on some 18 years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Brandy is the abandoned Kayla Harris, now a teen-ager with a
nice little voice of her own. She's living in St. Louis, working
part-time at the dry cleaners owned by her dad (Brian Stokes
Mitchell), the jilted, abandoned, very unforgiving hubby. Kayla's
dream: to become a superstar like Olivia King, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Now an international sensation, Olivia wants a parental do-over,
and she re-enters Kayla's life. The daughter hates the mother for
leaving _ especially this rich, famous mother she thinks ``is the
bomb!''_ but not enough to turn down Olivia's offer to come to New
York and meet the right music-biz folk.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could be a star,'' mother says to daughter, who, while
packing her bags, growls something along the lines of, ``But I
don't wanna owe you nothin'.''
</P>
<P>
   Since you probably know where this is headed, it gives nothing
away to admit that mother and daughter fight, make up, break up,
fight again and reunite in a tear-filled, triumphant duet shortly
before the end credits. Lots of tears, lots of overacting in
between. Thin dialogue, the usual suspects in characterizations:
the uptight agent (Roger Rees), the funny manager (Harvey Fierstein
in a cameo), the sexy but oh-so-sleazy record executive (Allen
Payne).
</P>
<P>
   Movies don't come more simplistic and manipulative than ``Double
Platinum,'' a two-hour music video cleverly designed to do what
music videos do: sell records. This movie should do wonders for the
albums of the two singers, especially Ross' just released CD.
</P>
<P>
   The performers' songs are all from their albums, and most seem
to be played in their entirety.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a revelation that the musical performances are the
better moments of ``Double Platinum,'' and that the writers decided
not to spend a whole lot of time coming up with anything to get you
from one tune to the next.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since ``Lady Sings the Blues,'' Ross has played the woman
hurting from the inside out. Crying and spewing I'm-so-hurt
dialogue. It's old, and it's not very good. Brandy won't become a
good actress until she realizes how severely limited her abilities
are. Ego can trip you up that way. (But she's young, so there's
hope.)
</P>
<P>
   It should also be noted that Brandy, Ross and Brandy's mother,
Sonja B. Norwood, are part of a five-person executive producing
team. Boy, to have been a fly on the wall in those tug-o'-war
meetings.
</P>
<P>
   I say this because as premises go, ``Double Platinum'' has a
pretty good one. But as in many Hollywood projects, artistic merit
went soaring out the window the moment Ross and Brandy _ their
managers, their agents and their record companies _ began
negotiating who'll do what and when.
</P>
<P>
   ABC is expecting sizable ratings for this movie, even up against
the first night of the far-superior ``Joan of Arc'' on CBS. And
they'll get those ratings. Viewers won't be able to resist seeing
Brandy and Ross together.
</P>
<P>
   Look, I tapped my feet while singing along with Brandy. (Ross'
music in the past 20 years hasn't moved me, so I elected to use
that wonderful fast-forward device). But I have to say: Shortly
after watching the tape of ``Double Platinum,'' I caught two of
Brandy's music videos on Black Entertainment Television. They had
more of a dramatic kick.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere this week:
</P>
<P>
   ``City at Peace'' (6:30 p.m. Thursday, HBO) Barbra Streisand and
Cis Corman executive-produced this 90-minute documentary about what
happens when 60 teens from various backgrounds discover they have
more in common than they thought. It's a rich look at how social
and racial differences can be overcome when we set aside some of
our psychological baggage. The kids connect and learn about their
lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``City at Peace'' focuses on eight cast members, including a
high-school dropout whose past includes selling drugs, a girl who
struggles to keep togerher her suburban family, and a girl whose
parents are having difficulty with a gay, HIV-positive son.
</P>
<P>
   This is a well-crafted production which, if it doesn't entertain
you, at the very least will give you hope.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kperkins(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
