<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 15:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7354 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LABBE-COLUMN-TEX     05-14 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABBE-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOTS OF ROOM UNDER FIRST AMENDMENT'S UMBRELLA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By J.R. LABBE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nude dancing. Flag burning. Political campaign contributions. A
Ku Klux Klan rally. Internet threats against abortion providers.
Voter initiatives. ``The Jenny Jones Show.'' Doom, the video game.
``Hustler'' magazine.
</P>
<P>
   At first blush, these appear as disparate issues. Yet at the
core of each sit the First Amendment and the right to free
expression for all Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The First Amendment: 45 simple words that continue to fascinate
_ and sometimes frustrate _ folks across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congress shall make no law respecting an establishment of
religion, or prohibiting the free exercise thereof; or abridging
the freedom of speech, or of the press, or the rights of the people
peaceably to assemble, and to petition the Government for a redress
of grievances.''
</P>
<P>
   Penned by James Madison more than 200 years ago, and ratified as
part of the Bill of Rights in 1791, the First Amendment is perhaps
the most widely known of the 10 amendments, although an
unscientific survey of people on the street recently revealed an
obvious gap in knowledge about just how many rights the amendment
covers. Many of the people could cite the speech, religion and
press components; assembly took some coaxing; forget about
petition.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, everyone who was asked knew the Second Amendment _
the one that addresses the right to keep and bear arms _ which is
getting a lot high-profile attention these days as Congress and the
lawmakers in various statehouses wrestle with crafting more
gun-control legislation in the wake of the tragedy in Littleton,
Colo. But that, as they say, is another story for another day.
</P>
<P>
   First Amendment considerations are also on Congress' mind. This
session is seeing yet another attempt to pass a constitutional
amendment to prohibit the desecration of the U.S. flag. At the risk
of alienating the affections of our nation's fine military veterans
_ men and women who served under the majestic banner of Old Glory _
Congress must see beyond the emotional hurt it will cause honorable
people and defeat the effort again.
</P>
<P>
   Government doesn't get to pick and choose which types of
expression are protected while making others unacceptable. Granted,
forms of speech do exist that can be actionable by law. You can't
threaten the president. Don't joke about having a gun or a bomb in
an airport. Most folks cite yelling, ``Fire!'' in a crowded
theater, although I've heard vigorous debates about whether that's
a First Amendment issue or one of inciting a public danger.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign finance reform has been stymied in part because of
First Amendment considerations. Attempts to regulate contributions
have passed court challenges, but not attempts to limit the amount
that a candidate can spend. Electoral spending facilitates
political speech, and that must remain unfettered. Government
doesn't get to single out a specific form of expression for
regulation, even if the form takes the shape of a
multimillion-dollar advertising buy.
</P>
<P>
   The recent $25 million jury verdict in the Jenny Jones civil
trial will undoubtedly be challenged on First Amendment grounds. As
reprehensible as her kind of televised garbage is _ setting up a
man to meet his secret admirer, and the admirer turns out to be
another man _ Jones, Warner Bros. and Telepictures Inc. did not put
a gun into Jonathan Schmitz's hands and force him to kill Scott
Amedure. The jury's disgust with the cesspool that is TV shock
shows was apparent, but the way to change television is to boycott
the sponsors or turn off the idiot box completely, not to trample
all over the First Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   The connection between speech and action is a tenuous one and
will continue to be tested in court, particularly as lawmakers get
sucked into the maelstrom of what role movies, videos and music may
play in influencing violent teen behavior.
</P>
<P>
   When I was growing up, I often heard two contradictory phrases
uttered by friends and siblings when play took an ugly turn: ``Them
are fightin' words'' and ``Sticks and stones may break my bones,
but words can never hurt me.'' Little did I know that the same
First Amendment that protected my right to be a childish horse's
patoot then would one day protect my right to be a professional
horse's patoot now.
</P>
<P>
   (Jill ``J.R.'' Labbe is a senior editorial writer and columnist
for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. She can be reached via e-mail at
jrlabbe(at)star-telegram.com or by phone at (817) 390-7599. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
