<HEADER>
A7374 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILLENNIUM-WOMEN-BABI     05-14 2889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIUM-WOMEN-BABIES-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 BABY in a BOX  
 &HT;     (This article has already moved to Centerpiece and Millennium
Plus partnership clients. To publish as a one shot _ and for
millennium rates and packages _ please contact one of these New
York Times Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089.  By NATALIE ANGIER  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 For release: May 16 or thereafter  
 c.1999 The New York Times Magazine  
<TEXT>
 &UR; Editors: See THE LOCAL ANGLE box below &LR;  &QL;
<P>
   A month shy of giving birth to her first child, Laura Pouzer, a
college chemistry teacher, reclines on a padded table at Johns
Hopkins University, the luxuriousness of her belly and her wit on
equal display as she takes the infamous Stroop stress test.
</P>
<P>
   Lists of words flash on a screen, each of them specifying a
color _ blue, yellow, white, purple _ but each printed in a color
other than the color it signifies. It is Pouzer's assignment to
call out, as quickly as possible, the colors the words appear in,
rather than the color they specify.
</P>
<P>
   I look at the slides over her shoulder and feel my brain lurch
and creak. I see the word ``blue,'' I think the word ``blue,'' the
tint it's written in be damned.
</P>
<P>
   Pouzer, though, is acing the Stroop, flying through the lists
without missing a beat or flubbing a shade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perfect, perfect,'' says Kathleen Costigan, a researcher and
obstetrical nurse. ``You're awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   As Pouzer barrels along, transponders taped to her belly reveal
two things: first, that she is enviably relaxed, her heart rate
slow and skin-conductance response flat; and second, that the
36-week-old male fetus within her is sleeping soundly. It is as
though the purity of the mother's mental concentration has lulled
the baby into long-wave bliss.
</P>
<P>
   The test over, the 28-year-old Pouzer nudges her eyeglasses up
her nose and shrugs. ``That wasn't too bad,'' she says to Costigan
and Janet DiPietro, a developmental psychologist. ``Much easier
than the last time.''
</P>
<P>
   A moment later, thump, jab, squirm. Her fetus is awake.
Something about his mother has changed, and he is practically
knocking on the door of her uterine chamber to find out what it is.
</P>
<P>
   Half a world away, in the laboratory of Yosinori Kuwabara and
his colleagues at Juntendou University in Tokyo, a fetal goat
floats in a clear acrylic tank the size of a large toaster oven,
bathed in eight quarts of artificial amniotic fluid kept at body
temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Its umbilical cord is threaded to two machines that jointly
perform the nuts and bolts of a placenta, pumping in blood, oxygen
and nutrients and cleaning out waste. The fetus is almost 20 weeks
old, weighs about six pounds and has been living in its eerie
fishbowl of a universe since it was removed from its mother by
Caesarean section several days earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The creature behaves like any other prenatal goat, blinking its
soft black eyes and kicking its slender white limbs. Should it
survive for two more weeks, to the full 21-week goat term, it will
be ``born'': lifted out of the tank and its umbilicus cut.
</P>
<P>
   Kuwabara and his co-workers are striving to create a viable
artificial womb, a system to sustain a developing infant when the
real womb won't or can't do. So far, the researchers have managed
to keep their goats-on-a-rope alive for up to 10 days, and they are
getting closer to understanding why the artificial environment
eventually fails its charges.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists hesitate when asked when their experimental
uterus will be ready for human use, but others happily speculate
for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of difficult technical problems to be
overcome,'' says Malcolm Levene, professor of pediatrics and child
health at the University of Leeds in England. ``But I see them as
being soluble in the next 5 to 10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   In vivo, in vitro, the womb in two views: one, the mother's
belly, the sum of humanity's yesterdays, the umbilicus the original
apron string that yokes us all to the body's throbbing loneliness
and joy; and the other, the acrylic baby bumper, an embryonic
technology that has the seductive flash of the eternal tomorrow, of
the airplane foil, the computer screen, the crystal ball.
</P>
<P>
   Yet as polarized as the two vignettes of the uterus initially
appear, they are both, in the end, about the future. Tales of
reproduction and birth have always been about the future, about
extending the shelf life of your longings and fantasies beyond your
personal expiration date.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe my child will revolutionize art; maybe my child will help
colonize Mars. People have always dreamed of consorting with gods
and bearing immortal progeny, or suckling at the breast of the
Virgin Mary to attain eternal salvation.
</P>
<P>
   Being the natural currency of tomorrow, the topic of human
fertility lends itself to the wildest sci-fi spasms and millennial
speculations. And as though to oblige our fixation on big round
numbers, our high priests and priestesses of fecundity, our
reproductive endocrinologists, embryologists, gynecologists and
geneticists, lately have pipetted up an unceasing supply of
millennialist material.
</P>
<P>
   Postmenopausal women have gestated their daughters' eggs and
given birth to their own grandchildren. Congenitally infertile men
can have their dysfunctional sperm mechanically rammed into the
body of an egg, and thus sire sons who inherit the once
uninheritable: the fathers' sterility. An older woman's fading egg,
and the chromosomes it enfolds, can be rejuvenated through the
addition of the rich, viscous cytoplasm from a younger woman's egg.
</P>
<P>
   If that chimeric gamete is then fertilized and transferred into
the womb of a third woman for gestation, the resulting child can
claim three biological mothers: chromosomal mom, cytoplasmic mom
and gestational mom.
</P>
<P>
   Once a little couplet said it all: mother's baby, father's
maybe. Now DNA tests can pretty well settle the question of
biological paternity, while the issue of biological maternity has
been sufficiently muddied to demand the regular intercession of
judges.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're being forced to rethink the whole concept of
motherhood,'' says George J. Annas, chairman of the department of
health law at the Boston University School of Public Health. ``I
never thought that would happen in my lifetime.''
</P>
<P>
   These goggle-eyed tomorrow scenes are already today's tomorrows,
if not yesterday's. There are more to come, of course, many more.
Most of them can't be predicted or described in any detail, but
each will surely force us to think better and harder than we're
used to about two mighty piers of life's foundation: power and
love.
</P>
<P>
   How much power can we have over the timing and circumstances of
our reproduction? And does that power give us greater freedom, or
does it deprive us of one of life's most unsung freedoms: the
freedom to have things happen on their own?
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people don't choose to have children, they just get
pregnant,'' says R. Alta Charo, professor of law and medical ethics
at the University of Wisconsin in Madison. ``Reproductive
technologies cumulatively reduce the range of events that happen by
serendipity and increase the range of events that happen by active
planning. This changes the texture of life. One of the rights we
have is the right to not have to make choices.''
</P>
<P>
   The new fertility fetishes also bring us face to face with our
concept of love, and what it means to love our children, and what
inspires that love or sullies it. Can we love a child who is
genetically unrelated to us? Of course; every parent of an adopted
child knows as much.
</P>
<P>
   Yet infertile couples go to extraordinary lengths to give birth
to a genetically related baby, and their hunger to see their
chromosomes represented in the next generation has inspired many of
the new reproductive manipulations. But does the quest to have
genetically related offspring mean that we are delighted with
ourselves, our spouses, our extant genomic kin?
</P>
<P>
   ``When I talk to people who say how important it is that their
children be theirs, and who think of adoption as a terrible last
resort, I say to them, `Oh, you must be so close to your parents
and your siblings,''' says Barbara Katz Rothman, a sociologist at
the City University of New York. ``They say, `No, I haven't seen my
brother in three years _ he's a real jerk.' So I reply, `What makes
you think it will be different for you and your genetically related
children?'''
</P>
<P>
   Two of the emerging technologies exemplify the profound tension
and interdependency between power and love, between our hopes and
nattering fears for tomorrow, as medicine does what we demand that
it do, and plays the stork through any kind of outrageous weather.
</P>
<P>
   The artificial uterus is one technology: In this we see the
ultimate attempt to control gestation, which means to control
ourselves, the personal plant. The other is genetic enhancement,
the attempt to improve or select some of an embryo's traits _ that
is, to control our children.
</P>
<P>
   They are both coming, if not in 10 years, then in 15 or 50. If
we can tinker, we will tinker, and when it comes to our kids, we'll
hammer ourselves deaf, bent and bruised, until we hammer ourselves
away for good.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty years ago, the feminist Shulamith Firestone wrote in
``The Dialectics of Sex'' about the need for an artificial uterus,
a way to remove the act of reproduction from the female body and
thus free women from what she saw as the source of their biological
servitude.
</P>
<P>
   Kuwabara and his colleagues are not working on the artificial
uterus as a nod to female liberation, of course. They're doing it
with the hope of helping extremely premature infants, those born
before 22 or 23 weeks of gestation, the current outer limit of
salvageability, when the fetus is meant to be an aquatic animal,
suspended in solution, its fragile gelatinous flesh shielded from
the brutality of air or touch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Artificial wombs will begin as a response to the needs of
women who are unable to carry a baby through to term,'' says
Marshall Marinker, a visiting professor of general practice at the
University of London. ``But like so many things in medicine, what
begins as a response to illness may become a lifestyle choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Look at Viagra, he says. It began as a drug for clinical
impotence and now is seen as a recreational means to megapotence.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, horrors, the mother who would choose to turn her fetus over
to a burbling laboratory broth!
</P>
<P>
   Mary B. Mahowald, a professor at the MacLean Center for Clinical
Medical Ethics at the University of Chicago, believes that the
demand for an artificial uterus will be negligible and that most
women view pregnancy as a whole-body thrill, one of life's few
genuine odysseys.
</P>
<P>
   She published a study in 1997 in the Journal of Women's Health
in which she asked women the following question: If you could
either gestate a baby using a donor egg or have your own egg
gestated by a surrogate mother, but couldn't do both, which would
you choose? A slight majority opted for gestation with donor egg.
``Many women feel that there's a relationship you can develop with
the fetus during pregnancy that men are not privy to,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe. But when I posed Mahowald's question to a dozen friends
and colleagues, some of them mothers, some of them not, a slight
majority opted for having their personal eggs baked in a surrogate
womb. ``The idea of being pregnant seems noxious to me,'' explained
one woman, a childless professor at the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology.
</P>
<P>
   When I further told my respondents to imagine that they had had
a hysterectomy but wanted a child and asked if they would prefer to
have their eggs gestated by a surrogate human mother or in an
artificial womb, a sizable majority opted for the artificial womb.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously the thought of a fake Frankenstein-ian uterus was not
as disturbing to them as the prospect of dealing with a genuine
surrogate mother, who might get drunk or smoke while pregnant or
demand visitation rights after birth.
</P>
<P>
   If we cannot blithely assume that every woman who wants to have
children wants to be pregnant _ if some women, like many men, find
the prospect noxious _ then we are left to wonder just how bad it
might be for a fetus to spend much of its tenure in a box.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the artificial uterus may be reasonably proficient at
performing the basics of nutrient delivery and the exchange of
blood gases. But what of the rest, the spectacular rest that is the
maternal-fetal dyad, an exquisite push-me-pull-you relationship
millions of years in the forging?
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to DiPietro's country, the land of blinkered darkness.
DiPietro is one of the only scientists in the world who are
studying the relationship between maternal and fetal behavior.
Doctors have spent a lot of time tracking how the fetus grows and
when its various organs and sensory capabilities mature: the fetus
as an independent operator, the free-floating homunculus at the end
of ``2001: A Space Odyssey.''
</P>
<P>
   DiPietro herself was performing such an orthodox study about 10
years ago. She was electronically monitoring the progress of a
fetus that happened to be gestating in the belly of a nurse who
worked in a neonatal intensive-care unit.
</P>
<P>
   Just to be conversational, DiPietro asked the woman if it
bothered her to be around desperately sick newborns while she
herself was pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said, `Not really, except once,''' DiPietro recalls.
``That was when her office was used as a temporary morgue for the
newborns that had died.''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, DiPietro's monitors detected a big surge in heart
rate. ``At first, I thought it was the nurse's heart rate going up
at the memory,'' she says. ``But then I realized it was the fetus's
heart. It was racing. It was an instantaneous reaction.'' The nurse
remembered that she had felt a suffocating grief, and her fetus
fairly keened in reply.
</P>
<P>
   In short order, DiPietro changed her focus from tracking
prenatal development to the study of the behavioral interplay
between mother and fetus. She wanted to know whether a woman's mood
or temperament or stress level had any impact on her fetus. If so,
how, why, when, to what end? If not, why not?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ridiculous _ the questions just haven't been asked,'' she
says. ``Women have their ideas. Anecdotes abound. There are
references in the Bible and in Shakespeare about how a mother's
emotions affect the fetus. But our scientific knowledge is utterly
crude.
</P>
<P>
   ``A mother's emotions have to affect an infant's temperament,
they have to,'' she says, at once earnest and matter-of-fact. ``A
fetus is bathed in maternal hormones, chemicals, peptides, at just
the time when its brain is forming.''
</P>
<P>
   But personal conviction is one thing; proof is another. And so
DiPietro studies pregnant women and their fetuses and puts women
like Pouzer through stressful quizzes to see how they and their
babies react and interact.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're learning, what is a new scientific finding, is
that, yes, the fetus does respond to its mother's emotions,'' she
says. ``Sometimes the reaction of the fetus, in terms of heart rate
and movement, is even more pronounced than the reaction of the
mother. That reactivity is not necessarily a bad thing. The arousal
must be doing something to its nervous system, perhaps helping to
drive brain development, but we don't know that yet for sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mother provides such a complex, labile environment for the
fetus. She gets up, she sits down, she shifts position. She eats
something different, it affects the amniotic fluid. When she
laughs, she shakes the baby around really vigorously.'' DiPietro
waves her arms in the air to demonstrate. ``Who knows? That could
be why we like roller-coaster rides _ and why they make us laugh
even while we're screaming.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Natalie Angier, who writes about biology for The New York
Times, is the author of ``Woman: An Intimate Geography.'') &LR; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; THE LOCAL ANGLE: Here are a few ideas to localize this piece: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. Find out who's saying what about bioethics in your
circulation area. A good source is the American Society for
Bioethics and Humanities  &QL; http:www.asbh.org &QR;  with a comprehensive
listing of academic centers and programs in the U.S. and Canada.
Headquarters in Glenview, IL. Phone 847-375-4745.
</P>
<P>
   The National Reference Center for Bioethics Literature
 &QL; http://www.georgetown.edu/research/nrcbl/ &QR; , telephone
1-800-MED-ETHX, provides a wealth of background.
</P>
<P>
   2. How have babies been birthed over the millennium? Talk to
midwives about what's changed and what hasn't. The American College
of Midwives  &QL; http://www.midwife.org/find/ &QR; , telephone
1-888-MIDWIFE, can point you to midwives and birthing centers near
you.
</P>
<P>
   ------------- &QC;
</P>
