<HEADER>
A7383 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TREK-LIAM-NEESON-IN-S     05-14 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TREK-LIAM-NEESON-IN-STAR-WARS-ADV31-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATTN: CALIFORNIA 
 INSIDE TREK &AMP; SCI-FI 
 A KNIGHT TO REMEMBER: LIAM NEESON IN `STAR WARS' 
</HEADLINE>
  (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Inside Trek, a
weekly science-fiction column with color and black-and-white art.)
 Includes a color slide and a black-and-white photo of Liam Neeson
in ``Star Wars: The Phantom Menace.'' 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Some days Liam Neeson spends his time working with Oscar-winning
actors like Ben Kingsley, Meryl Streep and Debra Winger.
 &HT;    Other days, he's playing opposite Jar-Jar Binks.
 &HT;    Actually, Neeson says, the challenge of playing a character like
his Oscar-nominated role in Steven Spielberg's acclaimed 1993 drama
``Schindler's List'' isn't that different from playing Jedi knight
Qui-Gon Jinn opposite the computer-generated Jar-Jar in ``Star
Wars: The Phantom Menace.''
 &HT;    ``At the end of the day, you still have to act,'' Neeson says.
``There's still something you have to convey and share, be it
`Where's the nearest spacecraft? Let's get out of here' or whatever
other line you can think of.
 &HT;    ``You can't take it lightly or try to overplay it.''
 &HT;    Neeson brings genuine warmth and humanity to his ``Phantom
Menace'' role as mentor to Obi-Wan Kenobi (Ewan McGregor) and
protector to young Anakin Skywalker (Jake Lloyd). But he says he
signed on not for the chance to wield a lightsaber or intone ``May
the Force be with you'' _ though he admits that that was ``cool'' _
but to work with the franchise's very own Yoda, writer/director
George Lucas.
 &HT;    ``George is the ultimate Jedi master,'' Neeson says during a
conversation at the Regency Hotel in Manhattan. ``You know that his
knowledge of cameras and his competency at making movies and
telling stories on celluloid is extraordinary, but he never forces
that on you _ it's just a given.
 &HT;    ``His direction was just perfect for what we were doing,'' the
actor says. ``Eight times out of 10 his direction would be, `Speak
a little faster on that line' or `When you turn, pick him up with
your right hand instead of your left.'
 &HT;    ``What he does is employ you because you're a good carpenter,
because you're a good actor, because you're a good scenic
designer,'' Neeson concludes. ``And then he lets you get on with
it.''
 &HT;    His performance as Qui-Gon, the Irishman reveals, combined
elements of Lucas and of Alan Ladd as the lone gunslinger in the
classic 1953 Western ``Shane,'' with a bit of Alec Guinness's regal
turn as a Jedi elder in ``Star Wars'' thrown in for continuity's
sake.
 &HT;    As for the lightsaber duels with the lethal Darth Maul (Ray
Park), Neeson benefited from the training he received years ago as
a top-ranked amateur boxer. The broadsword style he learned for the
1995 period epic ``Rob Roy'' didn't hurt, either.
 &HT;    Neeson spent much of the shoot acting in front of blue screens
and ``reacting'' to special effects and computer-generated
characters that would be added long afterward. Many actors are
thrown by this sort of thing, but Neeson says it doesn't make that
big a difference.
 &HT;    ``Acting is a leap of the imagination,'' he says. ``It's
`Imagine you're a king' or `Imagine you're a fairy.'
 &HT;    ``As wonderful as the technology _ the hovercrafts and the
machines _ was on `Star Wars,' it was the actors who sold it with
their nonchalance,'' he adds. ``To them, it was everyday stuff.
Mark Hamill jumps into his speedster and _ phooooph! _ he's off.
 &HT;    ``He sold it as much as the magicians did afterwards, and I
tried to do the same.''
 &HT;    While the faithful revel in ``Star Wars'' mania, slurping soda
from Qui-Gon cans, stockpiling Queen Amidala action figures and
seeking to find deep meaning in the apparently immaculate
conception of Anakin, Neeson is still pondering the whole
phenomenon.
 &HT;    ``It is just a film, but maybe for some little 9-or-10-year-old
boy it's something else,'' he says thoughtfully.
 &HT;    ``The whole culture around `Star Wars' is fascinating and kind
of strange to me,'' the actor says. ``It has something to do with
the psyche of all of us as human beings that we recognize these
incredible mythological stories, these fairy tales. Fairy tales
exist to bring a very complex world into an understandable form
that helps us through life.''
 &HT;    Neeson's next role is as a ghostbuster in Jan De Bont's horror
movie ``The Haunting,'' opening on July 23. Then he'll play a
neurotic spy opposite Sandra Bullock in ``Gun Shy'' and, he hopes,
star in an adaptation of ``Asylum'' with Natasha Richardson, his
wife and the mother of their two young sons.
 &HT;    And who knows, you may spot him at your neighborhood multiplex,
taking in ``The Phantom Menace.'' He does plan to catch it again,
he says.
 &HT;    ``I've seen it once,'' he says. ``It was like being very hungry
and having somebody bring in a tray of all your favorite foods _
but you only have time to grab the French fries before the tray is
taken away.''
 &HT;    Neeson laughs.
 &HT;    ``So I need to see it a few more times just to digest it all.'' 
 c.1999 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
