<P>
   NEW-THINKTANK (Washington) _ In Thinktankland, both conservative
and liberal groups have competed for years to convert their ideas
about taxes, foreign policy, the environment or whatever into
policy in the real world. But since the beginning of this year, a
new entry, the New America Foundation, has been trying to change
the think tank landscape. New America seeks to introduce younger
voices, break out of the traditional liberal and conservative
categories and produce unconventional ideas. Yet no matter how many
innovations New America offers, none may be as brilliant as the one
associated with its founding: getting money from the cyberbarons of
Silicon Valley. By Neil A. Lewis. (1000 words)
</P>
<P>
   ELLISON-JUNETEENTH (Undated) _ Ralph Ellison will not have it
easy in death, just as he did not have it easy in life. The author
of ``Invisible Man'' (1952) has been accused of being an ``Uncle
Tom'' and a careerist producing ``obsequious bleatings of white
appeasement.'' Such accusations have faded, but there are still
rumblings of discontent about Ellison's persistent defense of
American ideals and his ``elitist'' esthetic demands. And matters
are bound to become still more complicated when Random House
publishes ``Juneteenth'' next month _ a novel posthumously
constructed out of 40 years' accumulation of notes and excerpts. By
Edward Rothstein. (950 words0
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
