<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COURTS-HEARST (Washington) _ Most Americans give state and local
courts high marks for upholding justice, but many feel they don't
act quickly enough and that taking a case to court is unaffordable,
according to a survey funded by the Hearst Corporation. Frank A.
Bennack Jr., Hearst's president and chief executive officer, tells
officials attending a national conference on public perception of
the judicial system that the courts came out ``just OK on average''
in the survey. Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist also addresses
the group. By DAN FREEDMAN and JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN.
</P>
<P>
   US-KOSOVO (Washington) _ President Clinton seeks to clear the
way for the quick insertion of a U.S.-led combat force into Kosovo
to help ethnic Albanians return to their homes after a peace
settlement is reached. He again apologizes for the mistaken bombing
of China's embassy in Belgrade in a telephone call to Chinese
President Jiang Zemin. The gesture is essential to avoid China's
veto of the peace force in the U.N. Security Council. By STEWART M.
POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-FUNDING (Washington) _ Balkans supplemental shows that
not even a war can stop congressional log-rolling, although coal
and energy lose out in House-Senate conference. By GREG MCDONALD
</P>
<P>
   GUNS-SENATE (Washington) _ In reversal, Senate votes for
buyer-checks at gun shows. But President Clinton says the measure
is faulty, and Republicans say they'll consider additional changes.
By JOHN HENRY
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CHINA (Washington) _ President Jiang finally accepts
call from Clinton who expresses profound regret. NANCY MATHIS
</P>
<P>
   INDIAN-TRUST-FUNDS (Washington) _ Under pressure to clean up a
controversy over $3 billion in missing or unaccounted-for money in
Indian trust funds, Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt unveils a new
$60 million computer accounting system. A report by the General
Accounting Office, Congress' key investigative arm, says the system
may not work. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ABORTION-TEXAS (Austin, Texas) _ House committee votes out
compromise parental notification bill, which could go to the full
House as soon as Monday. Gov. George W. Bush supports the
compromise bill despite sniping by anti-abortion activists. By
POLLY ROSS HUGHES
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WORKING-COLUMN (Undated) _ Many employers help to pay the
college bills of their employees. Congress allows favorable tax
treatment _ up to $5250 each year is considered tax free income for
employees, and employers don't have to pay employment taxes on the
money either. There is a bill pending in Congress to extend that
favorable tax treatment that is set to expire next year and include
graduate level education too. But Texas Congressman Bill Archer is
reportedly opposed to it and he can derail the legislation. By L.M.
SIXEL.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-COLUMN (Undated) _ The market for video cards and 3-D
graphics cards has heated up beyond the boiling point. By DWIGHT
SILVERMAN
</P>
