<HEADER>
A7428 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV16-     05-14 0987
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FERTILIZER MACHINE FUELED BY DIRT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, May 16)  
(lh) 
 By CASS PETERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The uneven surfaces of my concrete sidewalk and driveway gather
pools of water after a heavy rain, and most times each pool has a
couple of earthworms in it. The worms look dead, or dying, and I
used to think it was unfortunate that they came to the surface to
escape their flooding burrows only to expire in these temporary
ponds.
</P>
<P>
   Then I learned that earthworms can survive several weeks under
water, and actually were coming up from their subterranean homes to
make whoopee. All those earthworms you see after a rain are there
because they can move easily over wet surfaces without drying out,
and mates are easier to find on the open ground than down in that
labyrinth of worm tunnels.
</P>
<P>
   So I am glad for the rain, not just because it means that I can
avoid the watering chores for a day or two, but also because it
promises to enhance my precious population of earthworms. It's a
rare gardener who does not know that earthworms are beneficial.
Cleopatra was so impressed with their work that she declared them
sacred. They are the best cultivators of the soil. They actually
eat it, as well as any organic matter mixed with it. The soil
passes through their soft, tubular bodies and comes out as fecal
matter called castings. Worm castings are the richest, most perfect
plant-growing medium I know.
</P>
<P>
   Worms distribute their nutrient-rich castings evenly as they
tunnel through the ground, and their tunnels help aerate and drain
the soil. They can bring up trace minerals and other nutrients from
8 feet below the surface, a better reach than even deeply rooted
plants like alfalfa and clover, which farmers often grow to draw up
subsoil nutrients and to improve aeration.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Darwin estimated that good soil has about 53,000 worms
in each acre. Taking that down to the garden scale suggests that a
10-by-20-foot backyard garden patch with decent soil has about 250
earthworms. Each worm is capable of producing, over the year, a
third of a pound of castings, which works out to 80 pounds of
top-quality fertilizer being added to that garden plot every year.
It's free fertilizer, requiring no transportation from the garden
store and no work on the gardener's part.
</P>
<P>
   If the soil is very rich, with plenty of organic matter for
worms to eat and sufficient moisture to keep them active and
healthy, there may be two or three times that many worms in
residence and two or three times that much fertilizer being
produced.
</P>
<P>
   Earthworms are so closely associated with fertile soil that it
seems unthinkable that good soil could exist without them. But the
earthworms common in North America were introduced from elsewhere,
like Japanese beetles and gypsy moths (and, for that matter,
honeybees).
</P>
<P>
   Any native North American species were probably wiped out by the
last ice age. Our current earthworms arrived with European settlers
in the 17th and 18th centuries, as worms or eggs in soil clinging
to the roots of plants brought by the colonists or in mud stuck to
shoes. They spread across the continent in the same way _
hitchhiking.
</P>
<P>
   The garden is usually host to two main types of beneficial
earthworms: night crawlers and field worms.
</P>
<P>
   Night crawlers (Lumbricus terrestris) are the big guys (up to 10
inches long), and tend to hang out in meadows or lawns where there
is a living cover of organic material. In backyard gardens, which
are usually surrounded by lawns, mulched beds or some ground cover,
the night crawler is the most common species.
</P>
<P>
   Field worms (various species of Allolobophora caliginosa) are
smaller and can survive on less organic matter. They are more
common in large farm fields, where the nearest grassy patch may be
a very long crawl away.
</P>
<P>
   A third type of earthworm might be in the yard if you have a
compost pile: the manure worm or red wiggler. This kind is often
offered for sale in garden catalogs. It is useful for digesting
organic materials in compost or manure piles, but requires such
high levels of organic matter that it cannot survive in the garden.
</P>
<P>
   You can buy night crawlers (at bait shops if necessary) to add
to the garden, but it's far easier and cheaper to encourage them to
reproduce on their own. Keeping high levels of organic matter in
the garden is the most important step. Artificial fertilizers do
not provide food for earthworms, and may repel them because of
their high soluble salt content.
</P>
<P>
   Worms also need moisture. In dry periods, they retreat far below
the surface, where the soil is wetter and cooler. If the soil dries
out too deeply, as in intense droughts, the worms will die.
</P>
<P>
   A few earthworms may be chopped up in tilling the garden,
although night crawlers can regenerate from pieces. But the real
danger to earthworms from excessive tillage is that it aerates the
soil, drying it out and reducing the organic matter that they need
to survive.
</P>
<P>
   Earthworms are a favorite high-protein snack for some birds, as
well as moles and skunks. Robins are champion worm hunters. When
they cock their heads as they hop across the lawn, they're looking
for the slight movement of a worm sliding through the grass. The
hunting is best in the mornings, when the worms are heading home
after a night of dewy debauchery.
</P>
<P>
   People, too, can eat earthworms, which are said to be relatively
tasty baked up into earthworm-chip cookies. Personally, I prefer
chocolate. I can eat chocolate without guilt. Eating an earthworm
would be like eating my seed potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, I feed them with mulch, compost, grass clippings and
whatever other organic materials I can find. And these days, when I
see one exhausted and turning pale in a pool of water after a heavy
rain, I scoop it out and toss it onto the grass to recover, hoping
it's had a good time.
</P>
</TEXT>
