<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STYLE-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
 Attn: Style and Leisure Editors:  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following articles
from the Style section for use Sunday, May 16, and thereafter. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRINCETON-IVY-CLUB (Undated) _ To get into Ivy Club, the oldest,
most expensive and most patrician eating club at Princeton
University, candidates must sit for 10 one-on-one interviews with
members, whose attempts to plumb their souls touch on what their
parents do, where they spend summers and who their friends are.
Then the entire century-old club votes on prospects in all-night
sessions. By Monique P. Yazigi. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SHOP-LEELEE-SOBIESKI (New York) _ While most 16-year-old girls
might have headed for the mall on a rainy spring afternoon to try
on tankinis at Club Monaco, a recent downpour gave Leelee Sobieski
other ideas. Ms. Sobieski, a Manhattan-born actress, stepped into a
limousine provided by 20th Century Fox, one of the movie studios
she has been working for lately, and cruised a few blocks from her
parents' apartment to Allan &AMP; Suzi, a vintage designer shop on
Amsterdam Avenue that specializes in clothes from the 1970s. By
Nancy Hass. Photo. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MELLON-FASHION-JOURNAL (New York) _ Last Tuesday's guide at
Costume Institute of the Metropolitan Museum of Art was a lively
lady with a short gray flip, a pony-print purse and black-framed
glasses. Polly Mellen, a fixture in fashion journalism for some 40
years, a woman known for her forceful opinions and eccentric
personality, was, at the behest of the institute, giving a one-shot
tour as an outside expert with inside information. By Michael
Musto. Photo. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MASON-AUTHOR-NITEOUT (New York) _ I can't really believe I'm
here,'' said Richard Mason, a novelist and Oxford University
student, as he toured the book party thrown for him at the offices
of The New Yorker magazine last Monday night. Mason, 21 and not
that far removed from a daydreaming Eton schoolboy, has landed
inside New York's velvet ropes. His debut novel, ``The Drowning
People,'' written when he was 18, has just been published with all
the promotional muscle of Warner Books, which acquired the novel in
a two-book deal for more than $800,000. By Douglas Century. Photo. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FLAMENCO-LESSONS (Undated) _ About halfway through my first
flamenco class, when the instructor, Jorge Navarro, said, ``Lift
your arms like the world is on them,'' I figured I was home free.
That's how I feel all the time, anyway. But by the end of the
class, feet throbbing, I was ready to surrender and I am no
stranger to dance. Growing up as an overprivileged suburban child,
I had years of ballet, jazz, even modern dance classes. My summers
were spent _ Heaven help me _ at a camp that taught Israeli folk
dancing. But never had I encountered anything as complex as
flamenco, which blatantly defies three of America's favorite words:
Easy. Now. Young. By Alex Witchel. Photo. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ The uneven surfaces of my concrete
sidewalk and driveway gather pools of water after a heavy rain, and
most times each pool has a couple of earthworms in it. The worms
look dead, or dying, and I used to think it was unfortunate that
they came to the surface to escape their flooding burrows only to
expire in these temporary ponds. Then I learned that earthworms can
survive several weeks under water, and actually were coming up from
their subterranean homes to make whoopee. By Cass Peterson.  &QL;
</P>
