<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 16:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7449 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLAMENCO-LESSONS-ART-     05-14 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLAMENCO-LESSONS-ART-$ADV16-650(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO DANCE FLAMENCO, FIRST FEEL PAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, May, 16)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By ALEX WITCHEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ About halfway through my first flamenco class, when
the instructor, Jorge Navarro, said, ``Lift your arms like the
world is on them,'' I figured I was home free. That's how I feel
all the time, anyway. But by the end of the class, feet throbbing,
I was ready to surrender, and I am no stranger to dance. Growing up
as an overprivileged suburban child, I had years of ballet, jazz,
even modern dance classes. My summers were spent _ heaven help me _
at a camp that taught Israeli folk dancing. But never had I
encountered anything as complex as flamenco, which blatantly defies
three of America's favorite words: Easy. Now. Young.
</P>
<P>
   Which makes it even more surprising that the age-old Spanish
dance of men in tight pants and women wielding castanets has
captured the imagination of the Gap generation. They are packing
places like Alegrias, Navarro's tapas bar at 46 Bedford St.; Xunta
Tapas Bar, at 174 First Ave., and N, at 33 Crosby St., for weekly
performances. Even Joe's Pub, the nightclub of the moment at the
Public Theater, recently featured Noche Flamenco, a company whose
performances proved so successful it is to return this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Menkes, the Spanish manufacturer of flamenco shoes and all
manner of costume and accessory recently opened its first store in
this country at 250 W. 54th St. Its manager, Maya de Silva, says
business is booming with flamenco students, people in search of
stylish scarves and earrings, and also drag queens, for whom Menkes
custom-makes platform boots up to a foot and a half high.
</P>
<P>
   Flamenco classes, too, are proliferating: Steps, on Broadway at
74th Street, now offers two every Sunday, counting between 15 and
30 students a class; Carlota Santana, whose company, Flamenco Vivo
Carlota Santana, recently sold out its weeklong run at the New
Victory Theater, says attendance at her classes at Fazil Studios,
Eighth Avenue and 46th Street, is up. Navarro teaches on Sundays at
the Sandra Cameron Dance Center on Cooper Square and on Saturdays
leads an advanced four-hour class at Music Theater Works, on
Lafayette Street, that includes choreography. He says his students
include increasing numbers of models and actors; the centered
confidence and erect carriage that are essential to flamenco help
them on runways and at auditions.
</P>
<P>
   Many of flamenco's new fans say the dance does not replace their
exercise regimens, but complements them. They consider flamenco a
form of self-expression and emotional release _ the physical
equivalent of poetry for people who speak better with their bodies.
What's surprising is just how popular it is becoming even though it
is the antithesis to the easy/now/young American mindset. Navarro
thinks the attention is due partly to Joaquin Cortes, who packs
venues like Radio City Music Hall with his fusion flamenco, which
adds jazz and modern dance. But the truth is that flamenco means
difficult/later/old. To learn the steps and arms, and for a woman,
the skirt, hands, and hips, all of which do different things at the
same time, takes years. And technique is only half of it. Some
people think women can't effectively dance flamenco until they have
reached middle age. Only then have they suffered enough pain.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. de Silva of Menkes notes: ``Part of its appeal is that as an
art form it's very forgiving. You don't have to be 18 and a slender
stick of a girl to do it. You go to Spain and see an old fat lady
who becomes a goddess when she dances. There is no age or weight
limit. It is an art form that speaks to the emotions.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonnie Metzgar, the producer at Joe's Pub, adds: ``Flamenco is
unique because within an evening you get the flamboyance and
ebullience and festive nature of tango, along with drama from a
place of sadness, a shout-in-the-night esthetic. People respond
viscerally to someone dancing from that place of searching.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, on a recent Saturday night at Alegrias, the audience,
everyone from groups of twentysomethings to older Spanish-speaking
women (all of whom ate tapas and drank pitchers of sangria
throughout) was riveted by Navarro, who is originally from Granada,
Spain, and Antonio Hidalgo, visiting from Cordoba. They were
dancing martinete, a variety of flamenco using canes, a la
``Stomp.'' The dance became a competitive jam session between the
men, with the audience cheering them on.
</P>
<P>
   Then the singer sang an aching song that Navarro later described
as ``very tragic, about how much he loves a woman and how little
attention she pays him.'' The men danced so furiously that just in
keeping up with them the guitarist snapped a string. It was a
performance so infused with drama and urgency, it is easy to see
how people would want to be a part of it. Or think they do. After
this show alone, three people raced to the stage to find out where
they could learn. Navarro, of course, recommends himself.
</P>
<P>
   I attended one of his classes on a Sunday afternoon with six
other students, two men, both somewhat tentative, and four other
women. One was especially proficient, but she has apparently lived
a pain-free life: She danced like a windup doll.
</P>
<P>
   The most experienced student was Joanne Lomanto, 35, who works
as a research associate at an insurance company. ``Flamenco feels
like another world to me,'' she said. ``Ten years ago I saw Jose
Greco at the Joyce Theater, and when it was over my friends said
they had headaches from all that stomping, but I thought it was the
sexiest thing I had ever seen. And Jorge is very patient. He's
like, `If you don't learn it this week, you'll learn it next
week.'''
</P>
<P>
   Watching Ms. Lomanto demonstrate a dance with Navarro was
transporting, the grace of their movements suffused by a sexual
tension and longing that made the steps seem unimportant, though of
course, they are not. I did just fine with the constant repetition
of the Sevillanas step and fine with the constant repetition of the
arms, but when Navarro put them together, I ran into trouble. The
feet are supposed to move in a set, staccato pattern, while the
arms wind sinuously up, down and around. It's like patting your
head and rubbing your stomach at the same time, a talent I do not
have. He also kept saying things like ``Keep your body up and your
shoulders down,'' which for me, at least, is easier said than done.
</P>
<P>
   When the class was over, everyone paid Navarro their $14 (less
if you buy a series), and he stayed to chat. ``I'm 44, and I've
been dancing for 32 years,'' he said. ``In ballet you have to be
very young to accomplish the jumps and stretching. In flamenco it's
a way of expressing your feelings, and like any art, you mature.
When I'm dancing, I compare it with sex. It's something spiritual,
like you're not thinking. You've got an itch inside to express
yourself and the dancing is your partner.''
</P>
<P>
   As I made my way home, I considered whether I would take another
class. Besides my feet, I could feel the strain of the stamping
steps on my hips and calves. But I had been genuinely elated at
even the tiniest victory of matching a complicated movement to the
music.
</P>
<P>
   By the time I was home though, and had fallen onto my bed
exhausted, I was pretty sure I would not go back. Summoning
Navarro's comparison of flamenco and sex, I figured I could look
upon this class as a perfectly satisfying one-night stand _ which I
thoroughly enjoyed and never had to do again.
</P>
<P>
   Ole.
</P>
</TEXT>
