<HEADER>
A7455 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-MACARTHUR-$ADV17-B     05-14 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MACARTHUR-$ADV17-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE THE FLAWS, `MACARTHUR' LARGELY WATCHABLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Monday, May 17)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN KOCH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
MACARTHUR 
Produced and written by: Austin Hoyt 
Directed by: Austin Hoyt and Sarah Holt 
Narrated by: David Ogden Stiers 
On: PBS 
Date: Monday and Tuesday, 9-11 p.m. 
Rating: PG-TV 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most Americans know something of General Douglas MacArthur. His
line, ``I shall return,'' is chiseled into the national
consciousness as is his flamboyant image in braided cap smoking his
outsized corncob pipe. MacArthur himself was outsized, literally
and figuratively, a big, theatrical man with ambitions to match who
valiantly led troops in three major wars and battled his
commanders-in-chief, notably FDR and Truman, who fired the
larger-than-life five-star general for insubordination during the
Korean War.
</P>
<P>
   His story is as winding and episodic as his nature is
contradictory. So any treatment of MacArthur desperately needs an
organizing principle, to serve both as scaffold for the
event-filled narrative and lens for examining his complexity. The
new four-hour American Experience presentation packages MacArthur
as psychohistory.
</P>
<P>
   WGBH producer Austin Hoyt, who wrote and directed ``MacArthur,''
evokes him as a product of his doting mother's exhortations and his
father's lofty military example. ``You must grow up to be a great
man,'' MacArthur recalled his mother telling him as she tucked him
in at night. (Perhaps Hoyt should have noted that it would have
been consistent with MacArthur's vanity to have manufactured the
quote himself.) His father, Arthur, was a great Civil War hero,
deeply embittered by his later treatment at the hands of
politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, for instance, the popular general's bitter feuds with
Roosevelt are seen in terms of his father's rejection as chief of
staff in the McKinley administration. And his sometimes
over-reaching quests for triumph, such as his desire to invade
China during the Korean War, are presumably impelled by his
mother's great-man expectations. Such psychologizing is too
superficial to yield lasting insight, and unfortunately, it isn't
skillfully exploited in the documentary as an organizing tool
either.
</P>
<P>
   However genuinely fascinating a lot of the material is, much of
this sweeping ``MacArthur'' unfolds without a strong, unifying
sense of purpose. Also, swaths of it, notably the long, narrowly
focused segments involving his World War II campaigns in the
Pacific lack an urgency that could have been provided by a wider
perspective on the world conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Still, if you see only one of the two parts of ``MacArthur,''
choose the second, which begins in the heat of World War II with
the general waging twin battles, one against the President, the
other against the Japanese in the Philippines where, earlier, his
forces had been routed. ``I shall return,'' he had vowed, to save
the suffering remnants of troops who had surrendered. To do so, he
politically threatened FDR, selfishly disregarding competing and
vital American campaigns elsewhere in the Pacific and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   There isn't much disagreement among the articulate historians
Hoyt has assembled to comment on MacArthur's actions and character.
He was a daring, dynamic leader and formidable tactician, but so
dangerously egotistical that he often lost sight of larger
interests in the pursuit his own.
</P>
<P>
   In an irony never registered in ``MacArthur,'' the general
seemed most creative in his peacetime roles, especially as the
Supreme Commander of occupied Japan. The often dauntingly episodic
documentary excels on this topic, slowing down enough and providing
sufficient focus and bright detail to tell an important chapter in
the life thoroughly and well.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it was the gentlemanly example set by his father that
prompted MacArthur to stage Japan's surrender as magnanimously as
he did. But ``MacArthur'' has the taste not to over-speculate about
the impulses behind this deft, healing piece of stagecraft or the
remarkable reforms MacArthur introduced into post-war Japan. We
also learn of MacArthur's cynical but effective public
rehabilitation of Emperor Hirohito from war lord (and probable war
criminal) to popular symbol of democracy. Yet, as with so many of
MacArthur's extraordinary achievements, the long-term results were
mixed. While helping to stabilize and democratize Japan, sanitizing
the Emperor, according to one historian, ``poisoned the thinking
about responsibility in general in Japan to the present day.''
</P>
<P>
   Not nearly enough of the panoramic biography equals this
smoothly unfolding segment in which solid facts, not glib theories,
fully reveal its colorfully complex and deeply contradictory
protagonist. Not only does it amply illustrate MacArthur's profound
sense of public duty, but also his sentimental private life,
especially his devotion to his young son Arthur, who led a lonely
life isolated in the American Embassy among military brass.
</P>
<P>
   MacArthur's creative contributions in Japan resembled his
efforts as superintendent of West Point a quarter century earlier,
a useful connection the documentary perhaps should have made. He
considered the academy, where he endured horrific hazing and
finished first in his class, ``a provincial reformatory . . . based
on fear,'' and he tried to make it a ``cosmopolitan university.''
</P>
<P>
   ``MacArthur'' is largely watchable, surviving its many
deficiencies only because its subject is intrinsically interesting.
Imagine a decorated general not only personally leading his troops
under fire, but also, we are told, without benefit of helmet or
weapon. Instead of a gun, MacArthur carried a riding crop. The
renowned warrior considered it his role, according to the film, to
inspire killing but not to do it himself.
</P>
<P>
   Though noteworthy, this is just one of many perhaps defining
peculiarities this thinly psychological ``MacArthur'' teasingly
mentions but fails to probe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
