<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-ATOMIC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ATOMIC TRAIN' CAREENS TOWARD IMPROBABILITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
ATOMIC TRAIN 
Starring: Rob Lowe, Kristin Davis, Esai Morales, Edward Herrmann 
Directed by: Dick Lowry and David Jackson 
On: NBC 
Time: Sunday and Monday, 9 p.m. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The creators of ``Atomic Train'' probably worked pretty hard to
come up with a concept that borrows from every action movie,
including ``Speed,'' ``Deep Impact,'' ``Independence Day,'' and, of
course, ``Die Hard.'' Indeed, they were downright diligent in their
equal-opportunity appropriation, and ``Atomic Train,'' an NBC
two-part event movie, is nothing if not familiar. It's a generic
piece of business about a runaway train carrying a Soviet-made
nuclear weapon careening toward Denver, and it's so loaded with
improbabilities you wonder how it manages to move forward at all.
But it does, it does, filling four hours of prime time with all the
predictable fire and brimstone and a little less than two hours'
worth of plot.
</P>
<P>
   One-time Brat Packer Rob Lowe is the heroic fellow who is
helicoptered onto the brakeless train, to help stop or derail it.
As an action hero, Lowe is suitably laconic and clever, although he
might be less bland if he were allowed a few ironic jokes or snappy
rejoinders. The movie follows his noble, but unsuccessful,
acrobatics on the train, as well as his efforts to protect his
family in Denver, including his new wife, his daughter, and his
stepson. In the background of the action plot, Lowe is trying to
make his new family work, befriending his hostile stepson while his
wife tries to rein in her rebellious stepdaughter. Ah, but there's
nothing like a good old-fashioned nightmare to bring a blended
family together _ ``Stepmom'' recently healed similar rifts with
the help of terminal cancer _ and so the dire events that transpire
in ``Atomic Train'' do their part to create family harmony. Think
of it as disaster therapy.
</P>
<P>
   The two parts of the movie are quite different from each other.
Part one, a high-speed drama in the Colorado wilderness, has more
pacing and oomph. It's silly, but never exactly boring, as the
train keeps a rolling all day long no matter what the authorities
do to stop it. Part two is a slower-paced ground adventure, and it
gets pretty lugubrious as the characters wander aimlessly around
the darkly lit city, which has become an anarchic mess on the order
of the L.A. riots, What both parts share is an almost comic amount
of coincidence, as the movie's main characters keep bumping into
each other in far-flung locations as well as the mass hysteria of
Denver. (Both also contain a misleading premise: nuclear waste is
transported in casks not shown in the film, and nuclear weapons are
transported by truck and disarmed. After preview tapes were sent to
critics, NBC decided to change the movie by tacking on a disclaimer
and replacing all references to nuclear waste with the phrase
``hazardous waste.'')
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, the events in ``Atomic Train'' offer plenty of
opportunities for ordinary heroism, some of them quite gag-worthy.
Lowe's wife, played warmly by Kristin Davis of HBO's ``Sex and the
City,'' risks plenty to save her stepdaughter's long-haired
boyfriend, and her cop ex-husband virtuously tries to impose order
on the urban chaos. Edward Herrmann, the man who was born to play
president, is on hand as the country's compassionate leader,
keeping his faith in a happy ending even while the experts tell him
otherwise. There is a strangely stunted and pointless subplot,
involving a rookie cop and his wife, whose pregnancy is the
occasion for the movie's most naive optimism about the harmlessness
of nuclear radiation. No one seems concerned about the aftereffects
of the disaster in ``Atomic Train,'' unless the moviemakers are
holding on to that story for a sequel. Maybe they'll throw it
together for next year's May sweeps, and call it ``Brain Drain.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-14-99 1638EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
