<DOCNO> NYT19990514.0227 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 16:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7465 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-EXPLOITATION-TEX     05-14 1287
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-EXPLOITATION-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LATEST IN SLEAZE TV FEATURES ADULTERERS CAUGHT IN THE ACT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A talk-radio host once asked me whether Jerry Springer's sleaze
and fisticuffs combo would ever catch on, whether shows that rely
heavily on the voyeuristic pain, misery and titillation of others
would eventually be the rule, and my answer was an emphatic no.
</P>
<P>
   Now I wonder. It's naive to think that Springer and other greedy
purveyors who exploit human frailties for cinematic sport have not
restructured what we see on television.
</P>
<P>
   Let's face it: The more we get the more we can take and thereby
accept within the standards and practices of our personal
television viewing.
</P>
<P>
   And although there has been no shortage of public and media
outcry over the explosion of explicit content, the healthy ratings
of such shows _ and the new ones that keep appearing _ simply don't
jibe with our heartfelt concern.
</P>
<P>
   Pacing our collective viewing these days is this kind of
ratings-rich phenomenon of reality programming, shows promising to
give viewers the real deal with real conflict, real emotion and
real blood. ``Cops'' is quietly celebrating its 10th year, for
example. After initially throwing up our hands about cameras
accompanying police officers into private homes as they settle
disputes, usually with force and often with the innocent, we said
little when the copycats followed, upping the ante.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder Jenny Jones told ``Dateline NBC'' on Sunday that she
expects ratings for her talker to remain healthy despite being
found liable (to the tune of $25 million) last week in the shooting
death of a guest.
</P>
<P>
   To Jones, Jonathan Schmitz, who shot Scott Amedure three days
after the two taped a same-sex crush segment, was a troubled man
who would have harmed Amedure even had the two never set foot on
her stage.
</P>
<P>
   The jury agreed that Schmitz was mentally unstable, but found
Jones' producers negligent in putting him on the show and then
humiliating him.
</P>
<P>
   Jones' most unsettling statement to NBC's Jane Pauley wasn't
that she felt no guilt or responsibility in the death of one man
and the imprisonment of another, but that shows like hers will be
around as long we watch them.
</P>
<P>
   Case in point: The major networks have, in the past three years,
quadrupled their use of reality specials, programs like ``Wildest
Police Videos,'' which Fox aired last month. That show featured a
law enforcement officer being struck head-on by a car, another
being shot, another being attacked by a dog.
</P>
<P>
   In March 1997, you could find only 11 reality-TV segments
totaling two hours of weekly programming on all the major networks
combined. In March of this year, according to the newsletter NewsTV
Reports, there were 118 segments totaling eight hours weekly.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to censor, and you want to believe that viewers
should choose their pleasure or pain,'' says Michael Filberg, a
former professor of media studies who works as a consultant for a
Seattle-based advertising and marketing firm. ``But at the same
time, any responsible human being has to wonder, `So what's next?
How will we top this?'''
</P>
<P>
   Programmers will top it by tweaking the shows that are already
out there. The other day, I viewed a pilot called ``Cheaters,''
which catches adulterers on videotape, and then tapes ``the
confrontation'' in all its gory detail.
</P>
<P>
   In the pilot, which features actors, a woman leaps out of a
surveillance van with a camera crew and tries to wrestle her
``husband'' to the ground. Selling points were the woman sobbing as
she watched hidden camera videotape of her hubby and lover kissing,
and then physically attacking him. In another segment, a gay man
and his lover go through the same tango, with yelling and screaming
and more chaos.
</P>
<P>
   Set to air in the fall as a syndicated program, ``Cheaters'' has
already filmed a number of segments with real people, one featuring
a Dallas woman who was confronted at The Blue Goose restaurant on
lower Greenville Avenue. Her husband walked up to his wife and her
lover and screamed, ``What the hell (are) you doing!?'' Restaurant
patrons looked on; the cameras rolled.
</P>
<P>
   Other incidents so far, in cities like Cleveland, Detroit and
New York City, have included fistfights and riotlike situations, as
bystanders are energized by the TV cameras.
</P>
<P>
   To ``Cheaters'' creator Bobby Goldstein, a Dallas attorney, the
more riotous, the better; he knows that will only enhance the
train-wreck appeal of his series. He admits that ``Cheaters'' was
turned down by the networks after ``heavy'' talks about how they
could get it on air with the least backlash. But judging by the
number of markets (not this one yet) that have already bought the
program, ``Cheaters'' will find a home.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein laughs at the thought of his program humiliating
anyone, instead considering his ``Cheaters,'' which is being
distributed by Los Angeles-based Keller Entertainment, as merely
giving audiences what they crave. Even need.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have the group that's compassionate, who could relate to
the victim or the complainant,'' he says. ``They would watch them
and want to have pain with them. The other (group) is satisfying
their voyeuristic interests in other people. The other is the cruel
element of the human kind that looks to watch other people caught
in something.''
</P>
<P>
   Springer, too, has said in interviews that reality TV will
remain a force because viewers are tired of fiction, of fantasy, of
sitcoms that are silly and unbelievable and dramas that would carry
more dramatic weight if they were real. Scary as it sounds, viewers
have seen so many staged fights and killings, only the ``real''
thing is of interest.
</P>
<P>
   Such programming was inevitable, and that's why shows such as
``Change of Heart'' (where couples berate one another, as well as
the person whom producers set up for their significant other to
date) were conceived. And it's why Goldstein is forging ahead with
``Cheaters,'' believing that reality programming represents ``a
form of truth'' that we can't resist as viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Although reckless, irresponsible talk hosts and reality
programmers have been castigated, the rules have been stretched for
some well-respected series. Certain allowances for language and
adult themes were offered to ``St. Elsewhere,'' ``Hill Street
Blues'' and to such current shows as ``Ally McBeal'' and ``NYPD
Blue,'' which brought seminudity to prime time.
</P>
<P>
   Once these shows claimed new territory in terms of what could be
shown and said, was it any surprise that sleazier programmers saw
an opportunity to pick up the baton and make a dash?
</P>
<P>
   Fox, for example, is the king of reality specials, showing
grisly footage of people hurt in attacks by animals, and it is
fending off accusations of staging or fabricating aspects of those
shows to make them ``more dramatic.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Los Angeles television stations interrupted
children's programming to provide live coverage of a standoff
between police and a man blocking a freeway. He eventually set
himself and his dog on fire, and then, after staggering out of his
truck, put a shotgun under his chin and fired.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-five million is a lot of money, but I don't see Jenny
Jones sweating. She's frustrated, tired, perturbed, maybe. But
tomorrow, she'll tape another segment. And we'll be watching.
Wishing, hoping, for something crazier than the day before.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kperkins(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
