<HEADER>
A7466 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-FERMAN-COLUMN-T     05-14 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-FERMAN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS ROBIN'S SONGS FINALLY FIND A NEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Robin Syler has always been a different sort of blues guitarist.
</P>
<P>
   No question, the 48-year-old Dallas native could always play the
fire out of a six-string; with touches reminiscent of Albert King
and Texan Albert Collins, he's been tearing up bandstands around
Texas since the '60s, at one point in the early '70s sharing guitar
duties with Stevie Ray Vaughan in a band called Krackerjack.
</P>
<P>
   But Syler has never been content to ``just'' play the blues:
He's always thrown a lot of rockabilly, surf and Louisiana swamp
pop into the mix, and had a taste for obscure covers, Link Wray
tunes and the like.
</P>
<P>
   And now, for the first time, all that Syler loves to do is in
one place, on record.
</P>
<P>
   His new tape, the 16-track ``Double Dip,'' is a raw, homegrown,
turn-it-up-and-go trip through a whole lot of rootsy American
barroom boogie _ and exactly the right antidote for the sort of
overproduced, cliche-ridden stuff that masquerades as modern blues.
</P>
<P>
   Recorded last October through this January at Fort Worth's own
Eagle Audio (and available in limited quantities at Record Town on
University Drive across from TCU), ``Dip'' is a hybrid of styles
and influences. Among the covers are Link Wray's ``Steel Trap,''
Buddy Guy's ``Watch Yourself'' and Leroy Washington's ``Wild
Cherry;'' among the Syler originals are ``Ducks,'' a humorous tune
first released on a now impossible-to-find single back in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to go in and do tunes that represent everything I do
and what you'd hear if you saw me somewhere,'' says Syler, who
moved to Fort Worth a decade ago and regularly plays at the Keys
Lounge (5677 Westcreek Drive) on Sunday nights. ``We intentionally
made it sound like an imperfect recording.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Double Dip'' is the brainchild of Wes Race, a fixture on the
Fort Worth blues scene for several years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just thought, `Robin's due _ he's on fire a lot of nights,
and when he is he's practically untouchable,' '' says Race, who is
also a spoken-word poet. ``And I had the money. I thought, `Let's
do it.' I was sort of the cryptic adviser on the whole thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Race is currently shopping ``Double Dip'' to different blues
labels, hoping for a bite.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope he gets signed pretty soon,'' he says. ``But if nobody
picks it up, we'll just put it out ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Some sad news for Fort Worth music fans: Amazing jazz/Western
swing fiddle player Buddy Ray has left Cowtown after 25 years to
move to Waskom, which is east of Marshall and just this side of the
Louisiana border.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's real beautiful out there in those pine trees,'' says Ray,
79, who is best-known in Cowtown as a longtime member of the
Swingmasters Revue, a jump-blues/jazz/swing outfit that has played
swing night at Caravan of Dreams and other local clubs. ``I'm going
to enjoy getting out of the city. I like the atmosphere in the
casinos, watching people play craps and blackjack.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray first recorded in 1937 as part of Houston's Modern
Mountaineers. Two years later, he was part of the Texas Wanderers,
who waxed the Western swing classic ``Pipeliner's Blues.'' He also
appeared in several movies, including ``The Benny Goodman Story''
and 1957's ``Jailhouse Rock,'' which starred Elvis Presley.
</P>
<P>
   Ray says he decided to move to Waskom largely to be near his
daughter Kim and her son, Eric.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's 4 1/2 years old and our pride and joy,'' he says. ``It's
really going to be a gas.''
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman is pop music critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7839, or e-mail:
dfer(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
