<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 16:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7472 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOP-LEELEE-SOBIESKI-     05-14 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOP-LEELEE-SOBIESKI-ART-$ADV16-(800)2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOPPING WITH: LEELEE SOBIESKI 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., May 16)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By NANCY HASS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ While most 16-year-old girls might have headed for
the mall on a rainy spring afternoon to try on tankinis at Club
Monaco, a recent downpour gave Leelee Sobieski other ideas. Ms.
Sobieski, a Manhattan-born actress, stepped into a limousine
provided by 20th Century Fox, one of the movie studios she has been
working for lately, and cruised a few blocks from her parents'
apartment to Allan &AMP; Suzi, a vintage designer shop on Amsterdam
Avenue that specializes in clothes from the 1970s. There, she
plowed past racks of sequined Lycra and tie-dyed organza and
immediately wrapped herself in a floor-length fake-Persian lamb
coat. ``This,'' she said with the confidence of a fashion veteran,
``is really worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   Worth $800? ``Definitely,'' she said. ``It's silk-lined and
everything. Not that I'd pay it. Hey, I'm 16 years old. My parents
would never go for it. And I wouldn't ask them. Where would I wear
it?''
</P>
<P>
   How about to the premiere this summer of ``Eyes Wide Shut,''
Stanley Kubrick's last film, in which she plays the daughter of
Nicole Kidman and Tom Cruise (yes, it is now time to imagine Tom
and Nicole as old enough to be the parents of a teen-ager)? Or to
parties surrounding the broadcast Sunday night of the first
installment of a two-part mini-series, ``Joan of Arc,'' on CBS, in
which she plays the 15th-century French heroine.
</P>
<P>
   ``First time the virgin is really played by a virgin,'' she
quipped.
</P>
<P>
   Spending an afternoon with Ms. Sobieski, it is often hard to
tell if she is playing the role of an ingenue, or just hasn't
adjusted to the fact that she's on the brink of stardom. A study in
quicksilver contradictions, she is from one angle the poised
celebrity with a publicist in tow; from another, a Manhattan
schoolgirl fishing for change from her ratty purse, while her
mother, who's also her manager, looks on. It's clear that Ms.
Sobieski would rather see herself as an average 16-year-old with a
taste for princess-y clothing than as a Hollywood cliche of a
starlet.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, she glides from elegance to awkwardness like a swan
whose down is still damp. At Allan &AMP; Suzi, where she tried on gauzy
gowns and platform heels to the hushed delight of the other
shoppers, the curvy, 5-foot-9-inch Ms. Sobieski was every inch the
movie star, who has been pictured on the cover of Vanity Fair and
in virtually every celebrity-driven magazine. But in a flash she
reverted to the goony adolescent, rolling her eyes back in disgust
at the nonstop rain, and drawing her hair back with a cartoonish
barrette, part woman, part lizard.
</P>
<P>
   What do you expect from a Manhattan private schooler who went to
a recent fashion shoot straight from class still wearing her
uniform? ``The stylist said: `Ooh, I love that skirt. Is it
Prada?''' Ms. Sobieski recalled. ``And I said, `No, it's $25
polyester disgusting.'''
</P>
<P>
   Lately, though, Ms. Sobieski has had a reprieve from the
indignity of inexpensive pleats. She has spent much of her time in
Los Angeles making movies, where she studies with a tutor on the
set. Discovered at 10 by a casting agent looking for talent in the
cafeteria of her Upper East Side school, in just the past couple of
years she has been singled out by film critics for her performances
in ``Deep Impact'' and ``A Soldier's Daughter Never Cries.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little weird sometimes, and I do worry that I'm missing
the regular teen-age stuff,'' said Ms. Sobieski, whose speech is
noticeably free of ``like'' and ``y'know.'' ``I don't get to hang
out with a bunch of friends and shop.''
</P>
<P>
   So, when she is back in town, Ms. Sobieski makes up for lost
time on the retail trail. Though she is an up-and-coming member of
an elite pack of fashion-conscious actresses _ Claire Danes and
Rose McGowan also come to mind _ Ms. Sobieski doesn't care to
borrow clothes from designers. When Giorgio Armani approached her
to wear one of his gowns to the Venice Film Festival, she turned
him down, explaining that the clothes were too grown-up. She would
prefer more whimsical creations, like ones by the Dutch design team
Viktor &AMP; Rolf that she saw in the pages of Italian Vogue. Besides,
borrowing clothes takes the fun out of shopping for bargains.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I've ever spent more than $200 on a dress,'' she
said, smoothing out the folds of the billowy, ankle-length dress
she was wearing with black Hush Puppy loafers, ``and that's for
something really nice, like for a film festival or a premiere or
something. I love looking around in this store, but I never really
buy anything really expensive.''
</P>
<P>
   Her restraint may stem at least in part from the decision by her
parents, Jean and Elizabeth Sobieski, to place the money she makes
in a trust fund that she can't touch until she's 18. For now, she
has an allowance, which she won't disclose. ``It's just what I
need,'' she said. ``And if I really want something, I can go to my
parents and ask. They don't always say yes, but they're pretty
reasonable.'' Generally, Ms. Sobieski puts the brakes on, herself.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``Mom, I love this,'' she said, holding up a $1,000 burgundy
velour halter dress for her mother's approval. ``But it's really
too expensive.'' In a flash, Suzi Kandel, one of the store's
co-owners, offered to cut 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, if I did decide to buy it, exactly how much would that
be?'' Ms. Sobieski asked, cocking her head in an obvious ploy to
get even more shaved from the price. ``Five-hundred? Well, we'll
keep it in mind if I have something special coming up.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sobieski said she gets her sense of style and her eye for a
bargain from her parents. Her mother, also striking, is a writer
who admires Yohji Yamamoto and Vivienne Westwood, but shops mostly
at Century 21. Her father, a French-born abstract painter who
starred in a few Westerns in his youth, wears L.L. Bean around the
house and Cacharel to the occasional art opening.
</P>
<P>
   With such bohemian parents, it is often Ms. Sobieski who has to
figure out what is acceptable clothing for a 16-year-old movie star
with the body of a Botticelli. ``My mother will let me wear a
miniskirt and a blouse with my nipples showing,'' she said. ``And
once there was this black dress that had the sides cut out, and my
father said in his accent, 'Zat lukes gret, rilly sexy.' And I had
to say, `No, it's too sophisticated for me.'''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sobieski lingered a little longer at Allan &AMP; Suzi over a
turquoise chain-mail tank top. ``I wore chain mail in `Joan of
Arc,' but it was like a jillion times heavier,'' she said, before
choosing instead a patchwork jacket from the early '80s _ lots of
satin, velvet and embroidery _ and a pair of skin-tight navy mesh
gloves. The total: $52.
</P>
<P>
   Piling back into the limousine, she said she is happiest buying
lots of small things. She showed off the spoils of a morning trip
to Alphabets, a novelty shop on Broadway near 83d Street: a
mechanical key chain with a shark eating a swimmer, and a pen
decorated with a woman who sheds her clothes when turned
upside-down. ``This is one of the really good ones,'' she insisted.
``Some of the women on those pens are really ugly. But look, this
girl has a really elegant face.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite her own elegant face _ Ms. Sobieski bears a
much-remarked-upon resemblance to Helen Hunt _ like most
teen-agers, she has a feature she says she ``hates'' _ her hair,
which falls in perfect Seventeen magazine-style cascades around her
face. So self-conscious is she about her hair (``horrible and
thin,'' she moaned), that she collects wigs. ``I wear them to
parties or sometimes just out to the corner to get milk,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   She'd been thinking about adding a pink Afro to her collection
of a half-dozen. When the car passed Ricky's, the Lincoln Center
outpost of the Manhattan beauty-supply chain, she shouted for the
driver to stop, and once inside, she darted around like, well, a
kid let loose in a cosmetics store. First she swooned over a
suitcase covered in psychedelic fake leopard print, then she fell
in love with a pair of $6 angular red sunglasses. Eventually, she
made her way to a long row of wigs and hairpieces, many in
fluorescent hues. She spotted the Afro of her dreams, a poufy pale
pink corona of curls. The saleswoman suggested she try an electric
blue pageboy, but Ms. Sobieski could not be swayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This really does it,'' she said, patting the pink wig into
place. Her mother looked on nostalgically. ``I wore a mauve Afro
wig when I was her age,'' she said wistfully.
</P>
<P>
   But before the $27 wig could be folded into a bag, Ms. Sobieski
was engrossed in the revolving racks of temporary tattoos. ``Mom,
I'm going to send this one to Drew, she's so great,'' she said.
Drew is Drew Barrymore, her co-star in ``Never Been Kissed.''
``What do you think?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I think she's already got some real ones, hon,'' her
mother said.``But I'm sure she'd appreciate the thought.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-14-99 1643EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
