<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990514.0232 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 16:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7476 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-OLDIES15-COX     05-14 1672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-OLDIES15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rockers who created classic hits bask in the glory, miss out on
the profits
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Cheer up, Sleepy Jean. There's a kind of hush all over
the world. It's still rock 'n' roll to me.
</P>
<P>
   If any of those phrases send you running to your vinyl record
collection, you're probably among the 45,000 or so people headed
for the Georgia Dome today for the Fox 97 annual Ultimate Oldies
Concert, the largest of its kind in the country. The daylong
carnival of music and wallow-in-it nostalgia features acts that
sold millions of records back when cars were big, hair was long and
skirts were really, really short.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the artists on this year's bill _ including Jerry Lee
Lewis, Bobby Sherman, Mickey Dolenz (of the Monkees) and Tommy
James _ are now in their 50s and 60s. The youngest star on the
bill, Peter Noone of Herman's Hermits, is 51. Still, they'll take
the stage to sing about puppy love and petting in souped-up sports
cars.
</P>
<P>
   The day's acts, and the fans who turn, turn, turn out to see
them, will no doubt be happy together. But what concertgoers may
not realize, as they sing along, is that the oldies business has a
darker side. Behind the scenes, original artists are fighting for
the rights to their names, their music and their money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody back then thought these songs would be big years
later,'' says Greg Lesher, editor of Goldmine Magazine, a
publication for record collectors. ``Most of these groups were just
happy to get a bus ride to New York. Nobody had any money. To them,
if they got paid $300 for the rights to a record, they couldn't
comprehend what that meant long-term. The artists didn't know what
they were doing, but the executives knew the ins and outs.''
</P>
<P>
   Even names are lost
</P>
<P>
   As a result, many of the artists who wrote and recorded hits
that have become oldies staples see little if any money from their
work. Some aren't even allowed to use their stage names, or perform
under the name of their once-famous group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some sold all the rights to their recordings. Take
Steppenwolf, for example,'' says Fox 97 program director Bill
Cahill. ``(Lead singer) John Kay owned the name of the band. Some
of the other members wanted to tour using the name. He said `OK'
under one condition. He wanted to own all the shares to all their
royalties on future reissues.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time, the only Steppenwolf albums you could find sold
for 89 cents and came from the cutout bins at Woolworth's. The band
members signed their lives away,'' Cahill says. ``Kay made a
boatload of money when CDs came out. Now these guys are like, ``Oh
man, what did we do?''
</P>
<P>
   The Steppenwolfers weren't the only ones taken on a magic carpet
ride. The Turtles were another victim. When California teenagers
Mark Volman and Howard Kaylan signed with White Whale records in
the '60s, they apparently didn't read the fine print. The label not
only owned all the masters to their songs (including ``Happy
Together''), it owned the band's name as well. The contract even
forbid the guys from performing under their real names, so the duo
became Flo &AMP; Eddie. When the oldies craze hit, Volman and Kaylan
sued White Whale for royalties that had never been paid and won.
</P>
<P>
   According to Lesher and others, there are more horror stories:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ronnie Spector, lead singer with the Ronettes, can't use the
group's name or sing such hits as ``Be My Baby'' because her
ex-husband/producer Phil Spector owns the rights.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Alex Chilton, the sultry blues singer behind such hits such as
``The Letter,'' can't refer to the Box Tops in any advertising or
promotional materials.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Dennis Edwards, who sang the scorching vocals on ``Papa Was a
Rolling Stone'' and ``Cloud Nine,'' is prohibited from even
mentioning that he was once lead singer of the Temptations.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Florence Ballard, an original Supreme, died penniless in a
housing project in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   What's even more bizarre is that some of the people making
millions off classic Top 40 songs had little to do with the
original music. The world of oldies is peppered with Great
Pretenders. Cahill says one of the biggest challenges in booking
the Ultimate Oldies concert is ``finding people who are
legitimate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, we were trying to investigate to see if the act we
were considering was the original Crystals,'' he says. ``I had no
idea. But we checked it out, and they were the real thing. But you
have to be careful. There's actually a Herman's Hermits out there
without Peter Noone. There's a Shangri Las out there, but I believe
most of the originals are deceased. I can't think of who could
possibly be in that group that would give it legitimacy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, that's like buying a box of Captain Crunch and inside
it's cornflakes,'' says Lesher. ``It's just not the same, and it's
not fair to consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   But some artists are fighting back.
</P>
<P>
   Joyce Moore, wife of Sam Moore (as in Sam and Dave) has founded
a group called Artists and Others Against Impostors dedicated to
preserving ``truth in rock.'' She and a jukebox full of artists _
including members of the Platters, the Supremes, the Box Tops and
the Drifters _ have lobbied the U.S. House of Representatives to
consider legislation that would give performers the power to chase
impostor groups in the courts under federal trademark law. (The
bill is co-sponsored by Georgia Rep. Charlie Norwood.)
</P>
<P>
   Moore says she and her husband became dedicated to protecting
artists' rights after his former partner, Dave Prater, began
touring the country with another ``Sam.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sam and I had heard about this, so we decided to go see for
ourselves,'' she says. ``We went to Las Vegas, where `Sam and Dave'
were doing a show. We plopped down the money, went in, and it was
like watching a Fellini movie. It was totally surreal. It was like
watching a really bad car accident, and you know the people in the
car.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was furious, but for Sam it was worse. We had lost our house
and were living in a motel at the time. We were in really bad shape
financially, and here was Dave working for $3,000 a night. You do
the math.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, it was Moore who owned the name ``Sam and Dave'' and
the rights to most of their material. But copyright laws were
rarely enforced when it came to oldies shows. Joyce Moore estimates
the couple spent close to $200,000 chasing laws that were basically
``catch me if you can'' before Prater died in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``People make comments like, `What does it matter? It's the
music that people love.' But I don't believe that any more than
looking at a Picasso and saying, `It's just the paint,''' Moore
says.
</P>
<P>
   Hard to fool real fans
</P>
<P>
   Cahill says he goes to great pains to make sure the acts at the
Fox 97 concert are the real deal. Although some fans don't mind if
their music is delivered by someone who wasn't on the original
recording, many care passionately.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really have two types of listeners: The ones who are keenly
interested in the music and care about it deeply, and the ones who
just like the song,'' he says. ``But the ones who do care, you
can't try to pull the wool over their eyes. We brought in Creedence
Clearwater Revisited once, and I had people calling and screaming
at me because John Fogerty (the man who sang and wrote the group's
hit songs) wasn't with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds Fox 97 deejay J.J. Jackson: ``The audience wants to believe
that everything is just as they remember it, and the original is
the greatest.''
</P>
<P>
   But, to paraphrase the Stones, time isn't exactly on Fox 97's
side. While tunes such as ``I Get Around'' are timeless, the
reality is that acts are aging. The Beach Boys, who did that song,
are continuing but without any of the founding Wilson brothers.
This year, there are two versions of the Beach Boys on tour. One,
with lead singer Mike Love, plays Chastain Park Amphitheatre
tonight. The other features the somewhat marginal contributions of
bassist Al Jardine.
</P>
<P>
   Which begs the question: How long can the Ultimate Oldies
Concert keep going? The answer: Probably until we're all in
assisted living communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will always be bands that go out and do these songs,''
Cahill says. ``When Mozart wrote his symphonies, he had no idea
they would go on for centuries. How do you know that `Splish
Splash' won't be around for decades? It's become a standard kids'
song.''
</P>
<P>
   Lesher says oldies acts are here to stay. ``I remember a couple
of years ago listening to a radio station, and they were taking
requests for oldies. Somebody called up and said they wanted to
hear `Like a Virgin' by Madonna. I thought `Holy Mackerel.' But,
truth is, everybody likes to identify with their growing-up days.
It's comfortable, like sleeping in your own bed at night.''
</P>
<P>
   NAME THAT TUNE
</P>
<P>
   Oldies songs never die, they just go to movies and television.
Or are remade by fresher groups. Here's a sampling:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Everyday People,'' the hit by Sly and the Family Stone, is
used to sell Toyotas.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Beatles' ``Revolution'' sells Nike shoes.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Woodstock footage sells Tampax tampons.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Tommy James and the Shondells' ``Sweet Cherry Wine'' sells
Coca-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  James' ``Mony Mony'' sells Remington shavers.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  James' ``Hanky Panky'' shows up in the movie ``Forrest Gump.''
His ``Draggin' the Line'' is featured in the movie ``Don't Tell Mom
the Babysitter's Dead.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  James' ``Crimson and Clover'' was covered by Joan Jett. ``I
Think We're Alone Now'' was covered by Tiffany, and Billy Idol
burned up MTV with his version of ``Mony Mony.''
</P>
<P>
   IN CONCERT
</P>
<P>
   Fox 97 Ultimate Oldies Concert
</P>
<P>
   6:30 p.m. Saturday. $5-$15. Headliners include Tommy James and
the Shondells, Peter Noone, Bobby Sherman and Mickey Dolenz.
Limited upper-level seats remain. Georgia Dome, 1 Georgia Dome
Drive N.W. 404-249-6400.
</P>
<P>
   Miriam Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
