<SLUG> BC-WORKING-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TUITION BENEFITS AID MANY WORKERS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By L.M. SIXEL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Debbie Cheney couldn't afford to go to college when she
graduated from high school, so she took a $4-an-hour clerical job.
</P>
<P>
   Once she got married and became a mother, her chances of going
to college seemed even more remote.
</P>
<P>
   But when her employer, Stewart &AMP; Stevenson, offered to pick up
the cost of books and tuition, Cheney jumped at the chance and
enrolled in night classes at San Jacinto College in Houston. She
has 12 credit hours under her belt and is working toward a
bachelor's degree in business management.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't afford to go and get my degree without the help,''
said Cheney, a 38-year-old human resource assistant who is
reimbursed about $1,000 a year by Stewart &AMP; Stevenson. ``It takes
everything we have to pay the bills and take care of the kids and
their needs.''
</P>
<P>
   Many companies, especially large ones, help defray the college
expenses of their employees. It's a good way to get better-educated
employees and offer an important competitive benefit in this tight
labor market.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, Congress allows favorable tax treatment for
undergraduate educational expenses for both employees and their
employers. But that is set to expire next year.
</P>
<P>
   What Congress does next could greatly determine whether people
like Cheney will be able to continue improving their educations.
</P>
<P>
   As it is now, employers can reimburse employees up to $5,250
each year and the money is not treated as income. That's good for
employees.
</P>
<P>
   It's an advantage for employers because they get a break on the
Social Security taxes they pay for employees and they can treat the
tuition like an ordinary business expense.
</P>
<P>
   Two bills in Congress _ one in the Senate sponsored by New York
Democrat Daniel Patrick Moynihan and Rhode Island Republican
William Roth and one in the House sponsored by Sandy Levin, D-Mich.
_ would retain that tax break and extend it to graduate school
tuition.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
EXPANSION DRAWS ARCHER'S IRE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So far, both bills are in committee and face opposition from the
powerful chairman of the House Ways and Means Committee, U.S. Rep.
Bill Archer, R-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Though Archer supports extending the tax break for undergraduate
tuition, he opposes the proposals because they contain the break
for graduate students, says his spokesman, Sean Rushton.
</P>
<P>
   The tax benefits are expensive and the lost tax revenues have to
be made up somewhere, Rushton said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, a lot of the money will go toward people earning law,
medicine and engineering degrees, he said. Those jobs pay well and
students can take out loans or save money to pay for their own
courses.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have to bear this burden on their own,'' Rushton said.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney said if she had to pay taxes on the $1,000 she is
reimbursed for tuition each year, she might not be able to afford
to continue.
</P>
<P>
   Every penny counts, she said, worried the extra dollars would
throw her family into a higher tax bracket.
</P>
<P>
   Without the help, an employee who earns $35,000 a year and
receives a $3,000 annual educational benefit would have to pay an
extra $1,249 in taxes, or $104 more a month, estimated Mike Aitken,
associate executive director of government and external relations
for the College and University Personnel Association in Washington,
D.C.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
EMPLOYERS ARE ALSO TROUBLED &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Congressional opposition to the legislation also is troubling to
employers who offer the tuition help.
</P>
<P>
   It's in the best interests of employers to provide all the
incentives they can to encourage employees to go to school, said
Kathleen M. Fenninger, president of the Houston Human Resource
Management Association. If the tax benefits are taken away,
Fenninger said, she is worried some companies, especially small and
midsized ones, won't be able to offer the benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Not only does the education help the company, it's also a strong
recruiting tool, said Fenninger, who also is senior director of
human resources for Enron Capital &AMP; Trade Resources in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   For some applicants, the educational benefit is more important
than salary, she said. They want to know if the company has a
tuition reimbursement program and will compare companies based on
their programs.
</P>
<P>
   But according to a 1995 survey taken by the National Association
of Independent Colleges and Universities, the annual income of
employees receiving educational help from their employers for
undergraduate and graduate-level courses was $32,859, which is just
slightly above the national average annual wage of $30,946.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
L.M. Sixel can receive electronic mail via the Internet. Address
your comments and questions to lm.sixel(at)chron.com, or call (713)
220-2000 and enter access code 1002. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
