<HEADLINE>
HOW TO DRAW AN ACE PICKING VIDEO CARDS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the most interesting trends in the evolution of the
personal computer is how, occasionally, the development of a
particular component suddenly will take off. The part currently
enjoying one of these growth spurts is the video card.
</P>
<P>
   The makers of video cards long ago conquered the desktop, making
2-D Windows feel snappy and comfortable. But you can scroll through
a Web page or open a folder only so fast. The next frontier is 3-D.
</P>
<P>
   The market for high-end 3-D graphics cards has heated up beyond
the boiling point. Capabilities are improving dramatically, while
prices are dropping drastically. The driver for this is 3-D gaming.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, most of the graphics adapters found on off-the-shelf
consumer PCs leave something to be desired for games. Once users
get hooked on a game that requires lots of performance, they
realize they'll have to replace that sluggish puppy in their PC.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the replacement market has gone into high gear. You
can buy very fast cards very inexpensively, and you probably are
going to be confused by the choices. Reading the boxes or even
reviews written by hard-core techies is probably not going to help
you _ the jargon that surrounds video-card technology is incredibly
numbing.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next few months, I'm going to try to break through some
of the confusion, reviewing some state-of-the-art cards. For now,
let's take a look at the basic things you'll need to know when
shopping for a new video card that excels at 3-D.
</P>
<P>
   First, it helps to understand how many games work. In many
cases, objects in a 3-D game are like wire-frame models with a kind
of ``skin,'' or texture, placed over them.
</P>
<P>
   Textures can be simple or complex, depending on how the game is
designed. For example, a smooth wall or a slick road is simple. But
what about a bumpy wall covered with moss, or a dirt-and-gravel
road? Those kinds of images will use much more complicated
textures.
</P>
<P>
   A quality video card can handle these complex textures, and make
them appear on a screen quickly. When the textures are on moving
objects, the card must handle this as well.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all 3-D graphics cards sold today have sophisticated
features for 3-D, such as Z-buffering (where the card tracks moving
objects, even if you don't see them) and alpha blending (in which
some textures can be seen through others).
</P>
<P>
   However, other things can affect how well a game looks and plays
on a computer, including the speed of the PC's processor; the
amount of memory it has; and how fast information travels between
the processor, the video card and the monitor.
</P>
<P>
   _ Video memory. &UR;  &LR; At a minimum, you'll want eight megabytes of
video memory. Fortunately, this is not hard to find. In fact, many
midrange cards come with 16 megabytes, and higher-end cards have as
much as 32.
</P>
<P>
   With more video memory, a card can store and quickly display
more visual information. With less memory, a game will have to pull
information off files stored on a computer's hard drive, including
textures, lighting data and so on.
</P>
<P>
   More video memory also lets a card display more colors at
greater resolutions. The object is to have as many colors displayed
in as wide an area as possible. For example, it's better to have 24
million colors (often called 32-bit color) at a resolution of
1,024-by-768 pixels than to have just 16.7 million colors (or
16-bit color) at 800-by-600 pixels.
</P>
<P>
   Look for 128-bit video memory. This refers to how much
information can pass into the memory at any given time.
Older-generation cards have 32-and 64-bit memory.
</P>
<P>
   _ Speed. Like the processor in a PC, a video card also has a
chip that runs at a specific speed. The faster the chip, the more
information it can process in a given period of time.
</P>
<P>
   There are two measures of speed on a video card _ the clock
speed of the onboard processor, and the speed at which the image is
converted from digital to analog information and sent to the
monitor. This latter is known as the RAMDAC, and it's often much
faster than the clock speed.
</P>
<P>
   The clock speed, for game-playing, is the most important. The
higher the speed, the better. Next-generation cards run at speeds
of 100 megahertz or higher _ much higher.
</P>
<P>
   _ System bus. &UR;  &LR; Always use the fastest card connection available
in your computer for a new card.
</P>
<P>
   If you have ISA and PCI slots, use the PCI slots. If you also
have AGP slots _ often found in Pentium II-level systems and newer
_ use that connection.
</P>
<P>
   _ OpenGL and DirectX. Nearly all modern cards can display the
two most popular schemes for handling 3-D graphics _ Silicon
Graphics' OpenGL and Microsoft's DirectX.
</P>
<P>
   While almost all cards for Windows machines can work with
DirectX just fine, not all cards have drivers that handle OpenGL as
well. Check with the manufacturer of a card you're considering to
see if OpenGL drivers are available now. If they are still in
development, or have only recently been released, avoid that card.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR;  &QL; 
 &LR; Dwight Silverman can receive electronic mail via the Internet.
Address your comments and questions to
dwight.silverman(at)chron.com, or call (713) 220-2000 and enter
access code 1001. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-14-99 1649EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990514.0235 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 16:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7488 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTER-HELPLINE-HNS     05-14 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-HELPLINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS THERE AN EASY WAY TO SAVE TEXT AND PHOTOS TOGETHER? 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I have been trying to save my son's home page to my hard
drive. He's got a lot of photos on it. When I do a File, then Save
As in Internet Explorer, I can save it as an HTML file. But the
photos don't come with it. I figured out that I can right-click on
the photos and save them separately. Is there any way to do this in
one step, and have everything saved to my hard drive at once?
</P>
<P>
   A: The File/Save As command does indeed only save the text _ not
the images _ in a Web page. But even if you use your right mouse
button to save them, you may not end up being able to see them.
</P>
<P>
   That's because some Web authors put images in a separate folder.
So, if you save the photos to the same folder as the HTML file, but
the author has written the page so the pictures are supposed to go
into a folder called IMAGES, you'll get the familiar ``broken
image'' icon. You'll need to create that IMAGES folder on your hard
drive.
</P>
<P>
   If you save a lot of pages to your drive, this gets very old,
very fast.
</P>
<P>
   You didn't say what version of Internet Explorer you're using,
but 5.0 has a very nice system for downloading and viewing Web
pages.
</P>
<P>
   Just add the page to your Favorites, and then click the ``Make
available offline'' checkbox. Click the Customize button to control
just how much material you end up saving to your hard drive. Be
careful here _ if you allow it to capture too much, you'll end up
grabbing much more than you need!
</P>
<P>
   If you'd like something more powerful, try Blue Squirrel's Web
Whacker, which gives you much more control over the process. A beta
version of Web Whacker 2000 is available from www.bluesquirrel.com.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Here's a tip I'd like to share with your other readers. I
recently installed new video drivers on my computer. I couldn't get
the bootup process to complete _ it would just stop about 75
percent into it. I decided to use the Windows 98 boot-log feature
to see where it was hanging. When I did this, it started just fine,
and the BOOTLOG.TXT file showed no problems. I later had similar
problems with another program. I used the boot-log feature, and
what do you know? It started up just fine. I don't know what this
does, but it seems to ``fix'' certain problems.
</P>
<P>
   A: I, too, have noticed the strangely curative effects of making
a boot log file. It works like this: When your computer starts the
boot-up process (before you see the ``Starting Windows 98 ...''
message) hold down the CTRL key. You'll get a menu of several
different start-up options, including one that lets you set up a
log of every component that gets loaded into the system. Choose
this item and let the boot process continue.
</P>
<P>
   For some reason, I've seen this feature take me past seemingly
insurmountable boot-up problems. Of course, even if it does not,
you'll still get a log file that shows where the process stopped _
look for BOOTLOG.TXT in your C:folder and read it with a text
editor _ that will help you troubleshoot your problem.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My computer has more than enough memory _ I loaded it up with
384 megabytes of RAM when I bought it! However, I find that Windows
still wants to set up a swap file on my hard drive. Why does it
need a swap file when I have so much memory?
</P>
<P>
   A: A swap file is simulated memory created on your hard drive.
Windows 95/98 expands and contracts this file as needed. Since
virtual memory on a hard drive is much slower than real memory, it
would make sense that Windows would not create this file until more
memory is needed.
</P>
<P>
   However, other programs often expect a swap file to be present,
and will call upon Windows to add more virtual memory.
</P>
<P>
   Having more memory will indeed speed up your computer's
operations, but the swap file is an unfortunate necessity.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Got a question about your computer? Dwight Silverman can receive
electronic mail via the Internet. Address your comments and
questions to dwight.silverman(at)chron.com, or call (713) 220-2000
and enter access code 1001. &UR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
