<SLUG> BC-US-KOSOVO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TAKES STEPS TO SMOOTH WAY FOR KOSOVO PEACEKEEPING FORCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton took diplomatic steps Friday to
clear the way for quick deployment of U.S. ground troops into
Kosovo as the vanguard of a peacekeeping force once a truce takes
effect there.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton personally apologized by telephone to Chinese President
Jiang Zemin for a mistaken U.S. bombing of China's embassy in
Belgrade _ the latest gesture to soothe Beijing and avert China's
veto of a planned U.N. Security Council resolution to authorize a
U.S.-led peacekeeping force for Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration continued working with Russia as well
to avert a possible Russian veto of the planned U.N. authorizing
resolution.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott and Russia's envoy to
the Balkans, former Russian Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin,
planned to resume discussions in Helsinki Tuesday on an emerging
blueprint to end the conflict in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The plan is designed to persuade Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic to accept allied conditions and halt his forces'
murderous ethnic cleansing of ethnic Albanians in Kosovo in order
to win cessation of the escalating allied bombing campaign against
Yugoslav forces that has dropped more than 10,000 bombs and
missiles since March 24.
</P>
<P>
   State Department spokesman James Rubin said U.S. officials are
banking that Chernomyrdin will return to Belgrade carrying ``the
clearest possible understanding of what will be necessary for
President Milosevic to agree to, and to accept, so that we can
suspend the bombing.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States is prepared to suspend the bombing campaign
``only if there's a rapid and precise timetable for the withdrawal
of all Serb forces (from Kosovo) and there are verifiable and
demonstrable steps to that end,'' Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   Jamie Shea, NATO's spokesman at headquarters in Brussels,
Belgium, said allied forces are prepared to enter Kosovo within
hours of Milosevic's acceptance of NATO's conditions for suspending
the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If President Milosevic has the good sense to do that tomorrow
... then certainly NATO would be ready,'' Shea said. ``When
Milosevic is ready, we are going to be ready because we won't allow
a vacuum to arise in Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   Combat planners at NATO headquarters and at the Pentagon are
enlarging the size of the peacekeeping ground forces targeted for
duty in Kosovo after a ceasefire goes into effect.
</P>
<P>
   Before seven weeks of combat operations against Yugoslav forces
began, the allies envisioned a 28,000-member peace enforcement
operation, including 4,000 American soldiers, to enter Kosovo in
conjunction with a negotiated peace agreement with Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon conceded Thursday that Pentagon
planners now believe that ``a larger force will be required to go
in as a peacekeeping force.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know whether it will be twice as large or three times
as large or 50 percent as large as we initially planned,'' Bacon
said.
</P>
<P>
   The spokesman at NATO headquarters said Friday that alliance
planners are examining what extra duties may be assigned to
peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
   ``We obviously have to be mindful of the need to look at mines,
look at law-and-order functions, look at the need to return
refugees, perhaps the need for a winterization program so that
those refugees can be returned home before the onset of bad
weather,'' Shea said.
</P>
<P>
   The allies want the international security force to protect the
return to their homes of some 1.4 million ethnic Albanian Muslim
refugees who have fled the Serbian onslaught.
</P>
<P>
   First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton reiterated the allies'
commitment to protecting the return of the refugees to Kosovo
during a visit to a refugee camp in Macedonia on Friday where
23,000 Kosovar refugees are living in tents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to send a message to the refugees that we do not intend
to let the evil which Milosevic perpetrated against these people
keep them away from their homeland and their homes,'' Mrs. Clinton
declared.
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 and via
E-mail: stewart(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
