<HEADER>
A7562 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WILLS-PROFILE-NYT &LR;      05-14 1137
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILLS-PROFILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARRY WILLS TAKES ON SEX AND THE SINGLE SAINT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Conn.)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By DINITIA SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sinners have always loved Augustine, the fourth-century saint,
for he has seemed like such a great sinner himself. He was obsessed
with sex, or so it appeared in his great work ``The City of God.''
He was willing to undertake a rigorous self-analysis in writings
like his ``Confessions,'' giving him an almost contemporary
accessibility.
</P>
<P>
   But now the journalist Garry Wills has written ``St. Augustine''
(in the Penguin Lives series of brief biographies), which tries to
revise the popular view of the saint, and the work may disappoint
some sinners. In the book, Wills says that Augustine wasn't
sex-obsessed at all but concerned with how sexual dysfunction
reflects man's fall from grace; and that the ``Confessions'' was
not a straight autobiography but ``mainly a theological meditation
on his own life.'' ``Revelation is not simply a text outside
life,'' he says. ``Rather it enters your life in the form of your
own experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Could Wills explain then, St. Augustine's relevance to the
modern world?
</P>
<P>
   But Wills will not reduce St. Augustine to ``sound bites,'' as
he puts it. His full, cherubic face often remains expressionless
when he speaks; sometimes there is a thin smile. He is 64 and lives
in a large yellow brick house in Evanston, Ill., where one of the
interviews with him were conducted. He seems impatient with people
who are not as well read as he is. ``He's sort of like a good
boxer,'' said his good friend, Studs Terkel. ``He doesn't waste any
punches.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor does he let down his guard for a moment. Perhaps there are
parallels between him and St. Augustine with respect to Augustine's
quest for self-knowledge? ``There are no parallels with my own
life. That's nonsense,'' Wills said, annoyance coloring his voice.
``Don't try to push that idea. It makes no sense. I have no
identification with him whatsoever.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked how many books he has written, he curtly replied, ``Look
it up in `Who's Who.''' ``Who's Who'' lists 19, including one with
a co-author and one he edited. That would make ``St. Augustine''
his 20th book, and next fall he will publish another, ``A Necessary
Evil'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster), about Americans' fear of government.
</P>
<P>
   More impressive than the number, however, is the range. He has
brought his talent as a scholar to everything from Italian film to
opera, from President Clinton to the Declaration of Independence.
He has a mimetic memory of obscure fourth-century North African
ecclesiastical texts in his book on Augustine, of Homeric boxing
references in an article on Muhammad Ali and of ancient Greek
rhetorical terms in his 1992 book, ``Lincoln at Gettysburg,'' a
study of the Gettysburg address, for which he won a Pulitzer Prize.
</P>
<P>
   Wills said he owes his retentive memory to his Catholic school
education, with its emphasis on recitation. Robert Silvers, his
editor at The New York Review of Books, says the breadth of Wills'
learning sometimes makes him ``a little speechless.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't think of anyone who combines this remarkable range of
interests and abilities,'' Silvers said.
</P>
<P>
   Pressed to identify the common thread in his work, Wills
responds: ``I suppose the study of culture.'' The Presidents he has
written about _ John F. Kennedy, Richard M. Nixon and Ronald Reagan
_ are what he calls ``cultural indicators.'' They ``tell you a good
deal about the America they were in.''
</P>
<P>
   There is another theme that stands out in Wills' writing: the
constant interplay between myth and reality in American life. In
his first big success in 1970, ``Nixon Agonistes: The Crisis of the
Self-Made Man,'' he famously called Nixon a liberal trying to
resurrect ``a web of myths that have lost their magic.''
</P>
<P>
   The Emersonian ideal of hard work has lost its power, Wills
argued, and Adam Smith's notion of a self-regulating market place
hasn't worked. Politicians must give up their atomistic vision for
a more communitarian ideal, he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reagan's America: Innocents at Home,'' continued the theme of
myths. Reagan, Wills wrote, ``is the sincerest claimant to a
heritage that never existed, a perfect blend of an authentic
America he grew up in and of that America's own fables about its
past.''
</P>
<P>
   He embodied ``an American instinct to claim simplicity,'' but
his sunny nature belied a painful Depression-era childhood. He
opposed welfare, but his family received government relief during
the Depression. As president, Reagan claimed to have reduced
government spending, but he actually increased it.
</P>
<P>
   In ``John Wayne's America,'' Wills wrote that Wayne presented
himself as the awkward individualist, the brave warrior, defending
the endless frontier even though he never served in the military.
He played the cowboy but hated horses. He became for Americans ``a
conduit they used to communicate with their own desired selves or
their own imagined past.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Wayne, Wills is a child of the Midwest. He was raised for
the most part in Adrian, Mich. His father, John Wills, sold
appliances. His mother, Mayno, worked for the State Department of
Unemployment. Wills parents were divorced, then remarried.
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by his Jesuit high school teachers, Wills entered a
seminary. But he didn't make it as a priest. ``It was eros
specifically and generally,'' Wills said. Today he is a practicing
Catholic who regularly attends church but says he believes in a
right to abortion, marriage for priests and the ordination of
women.
</P>
<P>
   He went on to get his doctorate in classics from Yale, writing
his dissertation on Aeschylus. While at Yale he sent an unsolicited
article attacking what he called the glib style of Time magazine to
William F. Buckley Jr., the editor of the conservative National
Review. Buckley printed it and began giving him assignments.
</P>
<P>
   When they met, ``he asked me if I was a conservative,'' Wills
said. Wills told him: ``I'm a distributist, like G.K. Chesterton.
Communitarian. Anti-capitalist. Anti-government.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Is that a conservative?'' Wills asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm afraid not,'' Buckley replied.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Wills became one of the young writers of National
Review's golden age, among them Joan Didion, Renata Adler, John
Leonard and Arlene Croce.
</P>
<P>
   But during the Vietnam War his politics began to change. He was
arrested twice in antiwar demonstrations. When Buckley rejected one
of his articles on Vietnam, they parted ways amicably, Wills said.
Today Wills describes himself as a cultural conservative, but when
it comes to politics, ``I'm more a Democrat than a Republican.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-14-99 1734EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990514.0239 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7564 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WILLS-PROFILE-2NDTAKE     05-14 0488
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILLS-PROFILE-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
Undated: than a Republican.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1957 Wills covered the Senate hearings on Jimmy Hoffa for the
National Review. He was on the shuttle from Washington when a
stewardess with ``big and mocking Italian eyes'' noticed he was
reading Henri Bergson's ``Two Sources,'' Wills wrote in
``Confessions of a Conservative.'' ``She said, `Aren't you a little
too young to be reading that?' '' The stewardess was Natalie
Cavallo, and Wills married her.
</P>
<P>
   Even on their honeymoon in England, Wills wasted no time, doing
research for his first book, ``Chesterton: Man and Mask,''
published in 1961. Today Natalie Wills is her husband's first
reader. She takes photographs to aid his memory. She handles the
financial aspects of his career, leaving him time to write in the
mornings at home and in the afternoon to do research at the
library. They have three children, Lydia, 35, a literary agent;
Garry Jr., 38, a film maker, and John, 39, a programmer.
</P>
<P>
   For much of his adult life, Wills has been an academic. At times
he has been accused of having an academic style. ``Garry Wills is a
bright young man who left his Yale doctorate in classics behind him
only to bring the academic vices of preciosity and obfuscation to
his new career as a political journalist,'' one Newsweek critic
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988 Wills gave up tenure at Northwestern University, though
he has remained in Evanston, teaching one course annually. He
prefers living far from Washington and New York, he said. ``I'd
rather be remote. I get more work done.''
</P>
<P>
   Wills said he had long been preoccupied with St. Augustine.
Augustine was born in what is now Algeria in 354. From age 16 to 31
he lived with a woman who bore him a son. He converted to
Christianity and eventually became bishop of Hippo. His doctrines
on original sin, divine grace and free will have influenced every
branch of Christianity.
</P>
<P>
   Augustine wrote frankly about sex in ``The City of God:'' ``At
times, without intention, the body stirs on its own insistent,''
Augustine wrote. ``At other times, it leaves a straining lover in
the lurch.'' At another point he describes the Stoics' wanting to
defy social codes by having public intercourse.
</P>
<P>
   But because they couldn't respond on command, they used clubs to
simulate an erection. Still, despite the almost graphic nature of
some of his writings, Wills said, for Augustine sexual turmoil is
``one sign of the inner dividedness of the human being. Your body
doesn't respond the way you want it to.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Greed, violence and deception were greater concerns in his
sermons,'' Wills writes.
</P>
<P>
   Wills is translating ``Confessions'' from the Latin and writing
a commentary on it. He said he was drawn to Augustine because ``he
has such a questioning mind, such a fresh way of going at
everything.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way the quest for God is a quest into himself,'' Wills
said. ``He's also just a great writer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
