<SLUG> BC-TV-JOAN-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`JOAN OF ARC': A FUTURE SAINT TAKES IT A DAY AT A TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.)  
 (bl)  
 By RON WERTHEIMER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a drama, and maybe even as a history lesson, ``Joan of Arc''
works. This CBS mini-series, which begins Sunday night, manages to
present its 15th-century heroine as a real and fallible young woman
without robbing her story of the required patina of legend. From
Joan's sad little village to her devastating battles to the
inquisition that condemns her, the film follows a course of
emotional authenticity.
</P>
<P>
   There are virtually no laughs, not even many smiles, in these
four hours. But it is a measure of the film's success that it is
never grim. It is, as it must be, the tale of a destiny followed
with courage to its inevitable end.
</P>
<P>
   The movie, which concludes Tuesday, manages to fulfill its own
destiny despite some obvious shortcomings of both conception and
casting. While concentrating all its narrative energy on
16-year-old Leelee Sobieski as Joan, the illiterate French peasant
girl who says heavenly voices command her to lead the King's army,
the drama never makes clear the complex political forces that drive
such actions.
</P>
<P>
   You have the competing interests of the French, not to be
confused with the people of Burgundy, both of them slipping in and
out of treacherous alliances with each other and the English. No
wonder the Hundred Years' War took so long to sort out. Viewers of
this Two Nights' War may be a bit baffled.
</P>
<P>
   As for the featured performers, well, this is a mini-series. So
familiar names and faces are more important than a unified
approach. The names and faces include those of Robert Loggia,
Olympia Dukakis, Maximilian Schell, Jacqueline Bisset and Shirley
MacLaine. And while their performances never seem phoned in, as in
some hastily assembled television productions, their styles and
levels of intensity do not always mesh.
</P>
<P>
   To find a harmony of approach in a pivotal encounter between
Neil Patrick Harris, as the Dauphin Charles, and Peter O'Toole, as
the manipulative Bishop Cauchon, may have taken more divine
intervention than the director, Christian Duguay, could call upon.
(Doogie Howser meets Lawrence of Arabia? Nah.)
</P>
<P>
   Maybe some of the blame must be borne by the writers, Ronald
Parker and Michael Miller. They're the ones who expected O'Toole to
tell Harris with rheumy-eyed conviction, ``As His Majesty's
church-appointed spiritual adviser, I advise His Majesty not to
take lightly the advice of his spiritual adviser.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Ms. Sobieski, who bears a remarkable resemblance to Helen
Hunt, she makes a swell-looking Joan of Arc. She looks terrific in
armor, up on that proud white steed. You'll understand in a second
why thousands gladly follow her to war. And she has a whole array
of facial expressions at her disposal. She can pout. She can
grimace. She can glow with the purest piety.
</P>
<P>
   But when she is called upon to speak, the illusion slips a bit.
Her voice cannot manage the conviction of her eyes. Maybe the
script is letting her down, too. But when, early in her quest, a
nasty nobleman derisively asks whether it's true that Joan wants to
unite ``the poor wretches of France,'' she replies, ``Uh-huh.'' He
finds that funny. Wouldn't you?
</P>
<P>
   Later, when her trusted friend Jean (sensitively played by Chad
Willett) asks Joan, ``Where's all this going?,'' she replies: ``I
dunno. I just take it as it comes.'' Like, that is so not heroic,
y'know?
</P>
<P>
   Still, the film displays strengths enough to ride past these
rough spots. It carries Joan convincingly from her first encounters
with the saints to her willing martyrdom. Along the way it is ably
served by many in the cast, including Loggia, as a kindly priest;
Ms. Dukakis, as a sprightly nun, and Peter Strauss as a grizzled
soldier whose resentment of Joan gives way, gradually but totally,
to respectful affection.
</P>
<P>
   The director and writers must share some of the credit, too.
Their film is bathed in a dull, muddy light that reinforces its
long-ago quality, as if it were written on faded parchment.
</P>
<P>
   Like its heroine, the film is flawed, and perhaps it is not
quite worthy of its lofty ambitions. But like her, the drama knows
where it's going and succeeds merely by getting there.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   JOAN OF ARC
</P>
<P>
   CBS, Sunday night and Tuesday night at 9
</P>
<P>
   (Channel 2 in New York)
</P>
<P>
   First of a two-part miniseries. Ed Gernon, Peter Sussman and
Graham Flashner, executive producers; Peter Bray, producer; Brenda
Friend and Andrew Dean, co-executive producers; Christian Duguay,
director; Ronald Parker and Michael Miller, writers. Produced by
Alliance Atlantis.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Leelee Sobieski (Joan), Jacqueline Bisset (Isabelle),
Powers Boothe (Jacques), Maury Chaykin (Sir Robert de Baudricourt),
Olympia Dukakis (Mother Babette), Neil Patrick Harris (King
Charles), Jonathan Hyde (Duke of Bedford), Robert Loggia (Father
Monet), Cliff Saunders (Bertrand de Poligny), Maximilian Schell
(Brother John), Peter Strauss (La Hire), Chad Willett (Jean de
Metz), Ron White (Dunois), Jaimz Woolvett (Philip, Duke of
Burgundy), Peter O'Toole (Bishop Cauchon) and Shirley MacLaine
(Mme. de Beaurevoir).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
