<SLUG> BC-BROWN-COMPUTER-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROGRAM PROVIDES PARTY DECORATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By LONNIE BROWN   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Summer, with graduations, weddings and holidays, is a party
season. To help put parties together, American Greetings offers
CreataParty!, with more than 100,000 project possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   The Windows-based program (about $25-$30) makes all sorts of
party goodies: invitations and envelopes, banners, place cards,
hats, party favors, T-shirts and napkin rings.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike going to a party store, where items are packaged in sets
that have more items than guests, party throwers can make as many
items as they want. They can also customize party materials with
the names of featured guests or sports teams.
</P>
<P>
   There are dozens of party themes ranging from birthdays (with 20
subcategories including dinosaurs, money and baseball fun) to
special occasions and engagements. Additional art packages can be
purchased online as well, and if there's absolutely nothing that
pleases, users can start from scratch.
</P>
<P>
   Most, however, will find that the best way is to call up a
ready-made party set and use the program's various photo and
text-editing tools to customize what's already in place.
</P>
<P>
   Also included: Forget-Me-Not reminders, which pop up should
there be any important dates in the near future; cropping and
drawing tools; twain support for scanners and digital cameras; the
ability to create borders from ready-made art or photos; and ``year
you were born'' information.
</P>
<P>
   Creating party decorations takes time, and if the party will
include more than a few people, help will be welcome.
</P>
<P>
   For information, visit the parent company's Web site:
www.broderbund.com.
</P>
<P>
   WATCH YOUR BACK
</P>
<P>
   The PC Mirror isn't much of a gadget in the way of high tech.
It's a 4-by-4-inch mirror in a computer-beige frame that attaches
to the side of a computer monitor. It's on a hinge, and can swing
so you see yourself _ should you be particularly vain or curious if
lunch may still be on your chin.
</P>
<P>
   If you're somewhat paranoid, or a former fighter pilot familiar
with the term ``watch your six,'' you can swing it so the rearview
is covered.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Newman, the inventor of PC Mirror and president of Assist
Technologies Inc., said he noticed the need for a high-quality
mirror when he was visiting computer-based clients.
</P>
<P>
   The best thing about it is that it's a flat-surfaced glass
mirror. It's not one of the cheap convex kind, a little bigger than
a matchbox, that sticks on the monitor, makes objects look like
they're in a fun house, and has an image so small that it's
difficult to determine who _ or what _ is reflected in them.
</P>
<P>
   It's sort of like eyes in the back of your head.
</P>
<P>
   The mirrors are $9.95 each, plus $3 shipping for the first
mirror; $1 for each additional. There are four ways to order the
mirror: tollfree, 1-800-655-2911, anytime; fax, 914-228-1765; by
mailing a check or money order to Assist Technologies Inc., 533
Route 52, Carmel Business Center, Lake Carmel, NY 10512; or through
the Web, www.pcmirror.com using Visa or MasterCard.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC COMPRESSION
</P>
<P>
   Music on the Internet is often found in an MP3 file. It's a file
that compresses music, allowing a 30 megabyte song (about three
minutes of music) to be reduced to less than three megabytes with
little, if any, reduction in sound quality. A WinAmp player
(www.winamp.com) is the best way to compress or play such files.
</P>
<P>
   The size reduction is remarkable, but it may become even more
so. A new technology developed by AT&AMP;T offers 16-to-1 compression,
bringing the 30 megabtye file mentioned earlier down to less than
two megabytes.
</P>
<P>
   ShadowMan Entertainment is an Internet record-label based in
West Hollywood. The company uses this new technology in its
Internet marketing, which includes a proprietary e-mail delivery
system, a proprietary entertainment database, and electronic
postcards.
</P>
<P>
   ShadowMan Entertainment is using Kelli Lidell, an urban-country
singer, as its beta-test artist. Her ``Here Today Gone Tomorrow''
was in the Top Five on British recording charts and No. 1 in
Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   Although the music format is labeled MP4, the designation is not
connected with MP3, the computer shorthand for ``open source MPEG 1
Layer 3,'' a company spokesman said. It is based on AT&AMP;T's audio
compression method, a2b.
</P>
<P>
   The music format allows Web surfers to play a 20-second sample
of a song with little waiting for download. It also allows users to
send audio ``postcards'' to friends so artists who can't afford
other promotional methods can have their music heard around the
country.
</P>
<P>
   To sample the features, visit this Web site:
www.urbancountry.com.
</P>
<P>
   (The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla., is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
