<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO CRISIS
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-STRIKES _ WASHINGTON _ The latest Friday on the U.S.-led
NATO bombing campaign against Yugoslavia. The Tanjug
state-controlled news agency, reported 100 civilians in a column of
500 ethnic Albanian refugees heading toward the Albanian border
were killed in a NATO aerial attack. The allies said they could not
immediately confirm or deny the report. Meanwhile, Apache attack
helicopters held their first ``live fire'' exercise. Developing.
(Deans, Cox News Service). 30.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOving in (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-VOTE _ El Al (the Israeli Airline) is offering charter
flights at cut rates, and several Israeli political parties are
sponsoring trips to Israel to bring back Israelis living in America
so they can vote in the May 17 election. Election turnout is
already about 80 percent in Israel and the last election was
decided by less than 30,000 votes of about 2 million cast. There
are around 100,000 Israelis living in America; none can vote by
mail except diplomats so the effort to get them back is intense. We
will speak to at least one Israeli living in Boca Raton about why
he feels it is important to go back, as well as Israeli political
analysts and political organizers in the Miami area. (Belkin, Palm
Beach Post). 15-18. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in the (i) International and (a) General News
categories.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   VONNEGUT-GRADS _ ATLANTA _ Sure, there was pomp. To say nothing
of circumstance. With 140 graduates receiving their diplomas this
morning, Agnes Scott College may have one of the smaller
commencements going. But look at the big fish they reeled in as
their speaker. Born-again pop culture touchstone Kurt Vonnegut, who
set off a flurry of Internet activity two years ago and spawned a
current Top 40 record _ all because of a commencement address he
never gave, delivered his only such speech of the year at the
Decatur college. Senior class President Sandy Miller said the
students selected Vonnegut long before the song, ``Everybody's Free
(To Wear Sunscreen),'' became a hit. No matter, said the author of
the anti-war classic ``Slaughterhouse Five'' and numerous other
novels: ``It's probably made me more famous than anything I've ever
done.'' (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   HAMVENTION _ DAYTON _ You don't have to be American to enjoy
this other-worldy amalgamation of transisters, diodes and dials.
Plenty of people from other nations make annual pilgrimmages to
Hara Arena to pursue their love of amateur radio. Friday is the
first full day of Hamvention. (Bischoff, Dayton Daily News).
</P>
