<SLUG> BC-OCEAN-WHEELCHAIRS-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.) 
ALL-TERRAIN WHEELCHAIRS PUT THE OCEAN WITHIN REACH 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By STARSHINE ROSHELL   
 Santa Barbara (Calif.) News-Press   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA BARBARA, Calif. _ It had been two decades since Rodrianne
Croisdale dipped her toes in the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to walk on the beach all the time,'' said Croisdale,
48, who has multiple sclerosis. She uses a wheelchair and sidewalk
scooter to get around.
</P>
<P>
   From a beachfront office, she advises the city on issues
affecting disabled people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look out these windows and I see people walking up and down
the beach all the time, and I'm terribly jealous,'' Croisdale said.
</P>
<P>
   But her envy ended this week, when Croisdale crossed the sand
and splashed in the sea while seated in one of two new all-terrain
wheelchairs recently purchased by the city of Santa Barbara's
recreation department.
</P>
<P>
   The splashy green chairs with their giant, green,
doughnut-shaped tires are wider, lighter and lower to the ground
than typical wheelchairs.
</P>
<P>
   They are being loaned out for free to the city's 3,000 disabled
residents, as well as to seniors and others who have trouble
trekking across the sand.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the last 20 years, I've been wishing that I could get down
by the water,'' said Croisdale, ``but there's no way unless my
brother would carry me, and that's not really the way I'd want to
arrive.''
</P>
<P>
   Now she can arrive in style. The chairs cost $2,500 each and
were purchased from a New Jersey-based company called Natural
Access, which manufactures various recreational vehicles for people
with disabilities. The city used grant money to buy the chairs.
</P>
<P>
   The beach buggies are constructed of waterproof nylon and
stainless steel, so they can be safely wheeled through the small
waves that lap at the shore. The leg rest can even be brought up
parallel to the ground, like a lounge chair, so sun-worshipping
passengers can put their feet up and catch some rays.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a ball,'' said Croisdale moments after her first ride
through the shallow surf. ``A wave actually had the nerve to come
up and get me good.''
</P>
<P>
   The chairs, which require someone to push them, can be checked
out free of charge for two hours at a time. Users are welcome to
wheel it to any city beach, but they may not want to go too far.
Riding across the sand can be wildly bumpy, and pushing someone
across the sand can be downright tiring.
</P>
<P>
   If the chairs prove popular, the recreation department will
consider buying another. Until then, Croisdale hopes to use the
chairs as often as she can find someone to push her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now what we need,'' she said, ``is a little booth where strong
men hang out.''
</P>
<P>
   (The News-Press in Santa Barbara, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
