<HEADER>
A7580 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELLISON-JUNETEENTH-AR     05-14 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELLISON-JUNETEENTH-ART-words&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FACED WITH `PARVENU' OR `PARIAH,' AN ARTIST STOOD HIS GROUND 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By EDWARD ROTHSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ralph Ellison will not have it easy in death, just as he did not
have it easy in life. In a 1982 letter recently published in The
New Republic, he complained about the harsh treatment he received
``from some of the so-called black radicals during the late '60s
and most of the '30s.'' That included accusations that the author
of ``Invisible Man'' (1952) was an ``Uncle Tom,'' a careerist
producing ``obsequious bleatings of white appeasement.''
</P>
<P>
   Such accusations have faded, but there are still rumblings of
discontent about Ellison's persistent defense of American ideals
and his ``elitist'' esthetic demands. And matters are bound to
become still more complicated when Random House publishes
``Juneteenth'' next month _ a novel posthumously constructed from
40 years' accumulation of notes and excerpts. It simmers with
portentous racial themes; its elaborate miscegenation of ideas and
identities includes a stirring speech about the intricacies of
American identity delivered, eerily, by a racist senator.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month a conference on ``Ellison and American
Culture'' organized by Morris Dickstein, director of the Center for
the Humanities at the City University of New York, raised yet
another set of opposing categories for classifying Ellison: was he
a parvenu or a pariah? Was he, in other words, a social climber
clamoring for the acclaim of white society, willing to sacrifice
his distinctiveness by adopting the values of the majority, or was
he a dissenter whose perspective from the outskirts of society
allowed him to champion its greatest ideals while grieving over its
greatest failures?
</P>
<P>
   The terms parvenu and pariah were introduced at the conference
by Ross Posnock, a professor of English at the University of
Washington. Hannah Arendt had used them to discuss the nature of
Jewish identity in Germany. The parvenu yearned for acceptance; the
pariah accepted a distinction. The notion of parvenu has an aura of
phoniness; being a pariah has come to seem proudly authentic.
</P>
<P>
   These concepts have broad implications because the
parvenu/pariah distinction is at the heart of most contemporary
debates about racial and ethnic identity and American culture. How
much should any group sacrifice for the sake of a hyphenated
identity? Is it necessary to become a parvenu to become American?
Can one remain a pariah and be American?
</P>
<P>
   Those questions haunted Ellison throughout his career. In his
essay ``The World and the Jug'' (1963), he chastised Irving Howe
for suggesting that he was being less true to his racial identity
than Richard Wright or James Baldwin were in their angry attempts
to make literature serve a political purpose. Ellison countered
that this was presumptuous, that individuality and character were
far more important in literature than allegiance to a set of
doctrines. Far from there being a required mode of racial anger,
there are many possible responses; there was even, he wrote, ``an
American Negro tradition ... which abhors as obscene any trading on
one's own anguish for gain or sympathy.''
</P>
<P>
   But similar criticisms are still being made of Ellison and the
acclaim accorded his work. At the City University conference, Jerry
Watts, a professor of American studies at Trinity College, said he
thought there had been excessive veneration of Ellison, that the
work had been treated by black critics and readers as part of a
``quest for respectability'' to be granted by white society.
Barbara Foley, an English professor at Rutgers University, proposed
that Ellison may really have been a parvenu, turning ``Invisible
Man'' into an anti-Communist novel to court acceptance in the
McCarthy era: ``That is a lot of what remains behind Ellison's
reputation.''
</P>
<P>
   Such views suggest that there is a clear definition of what the
authentic American black should do: reject white ``respectability''
and adopt political radicalism. Ellison passionately objected to
such demands. He even objected to being treated as a black-American
writer, just as Saul Bellow bristled at the label of
Jewish-American novelist. The hyphens may be suggestive of shared
experience, but they do not bind or obligate; they serve to
liberate. They provide the particular perspective from which a
broad vision of human life can be constructed.
</P>
<P>
   It may even be that the best literary comparison with
``Invisible Man'' is not a book in the black-American canon like
Wright's ``Native Son'' but Bellow's ``Adventures of Augie March,''
which appeared around the same time as Ellison's novel. The tempers
of the books, of course, are quite different, and Augie March's
identity, while unmistakably Jewish, is far less central to his
picaresque journey. But in both the characters are swept up in an
American maelstrom. In both the issues of self-definition loom
large; in both the characters struggle for an elusive autonomy.
</P>
<P>
   In fact the problem for the main character of ``Invisible Man''
is that he is only seen as an incarnation of his race, being
battered about by both blacks and whites who impose their visions
of racial identity on him. This is just what Ellison himself was
objecting to when answering his critics. In his 1981 introduction
to ``Invisible Man,'' Ellison argued that ``the interests of art
and democracy converge.'' Democracy values the ``development of
conscious, articulate citizens''; art values ``the creation of
conscious, articulate characters.'' Such individuality was for
Ellison a mark of freedom, and it could be earned only outside
politics. Art combines the perspective of the parvenu and the
pariah.
</P>
<P>
   One reason Ellison may have struggled through 40 years of
desertlike wandering without ever finishing his second novel was
that he was seeking some way to reveal the nature of America's
racial trauma without being either political or prescriptive. He
never fully emerged from the racial heart of darkness, but
``Juneteenth'' will be one incomplete trace of his attempt to leave
the parvenu and pariah behind.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
