A7581 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LATHAM-COLUMN15-COX     05-14 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATHAM-COLUMN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Watching a dope deal
 &HT;    By Phil Latham
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARSHALL, Texas _ I saw a dope deal last week.
</P>
<P>
   OK, I'll admit, I'm not 100 percent sure it was a dope deal.
Never having been involved in such a thing myself (regular readers
of this column may have some doubts about that), I could be wrong.
I only see dope deals on
</P>
<P>
   television and in the movies.
</P>
<P>
   So read this story knowing it is possible that the four people
who were walking down Jefferson Road the other day were just out
for a stroll, hoping to commune with nature.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not even sure what caught my eye about the whole situation.
Maybe it was the bright red hair and beard sported by one of the
three white people walking down Jefferson Road in a group. Maybe it
was the singular black man walking toward them. Maybe it was the
look on the faces of the three white people.
</P>
<P>
   Because, at the time, I thought the look was one of anger. I had
the queasy feeling that I was about to see a fight and a
three-on-one fight at that. To be sure, one of the white people was
a woman, but it was one mean looking
</P>
<P>
   woman.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting on that look, I have the feeling now that it might
have been one of determination or maybe even hunger. The look on
the black man's face when he glanced at me as I passed was
unmistakable: Nervousness.
</P>
<P>
   I slowed my car after passing the white group and watched the
scene in the rear-view mirror.
</P>
<P>
   As the white group passed the black man, an exchange was made _
item for item, I was too far away to tell what the items were, but
they were small. The exchange itself was done with an amazing
smoothness. The two people
</P>
<P>
   handing off the ``batons'' _ Mr. Red Beard and the black man _
did not once look at each other. Eyes straight ahead, they slipped
the items to one another and just kept walking.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe I have it all wrong. It could be that these people were
exchanging business cards. Maybe they were giving each other a list
of their favorite authors and books. They could be members of a
literary club.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe in broad daylight I witnessed dope being bought and
sold on the mean streets of Marshall, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   It does not surprise me that such a thing occurs, even during
the day and in public, but perhaps it surprises some.
</P>
<P>
   A newcomer in the health field asked me the other day if people
here understood that Marshall had a drug problem. I told him I
thought so, but perhaps that was the wrong answer. He has an
occasion to see drug testing
</P>
<P>
   and said he sees up to 30 percent of the people with positive
results.
</P>
<P>
   But furthermore, I think there is an incredibly mistaken belief
that drug use is a problem of one particular race or ethnic group.
</P>
<P>
   It simply isn't so. Drug use may be the most fully integrated
activity in the United States. If what I saw was a drug deal,
somebody was the buyer and somebody was the user. Of course, it is
even possible that the buyers were also sellers, or that they also
do that.
</P>
<P>
   There is no way that we can expect the police to stop the kind
of thing that I saw last week. What could they do, stake out
Jefferson Street, stake out every street in Marshall?
</P>
<P>
   No, the drug problem is not just a matter for police, but for
all of us. We have to get involved in saying ``no'' in the first
place, then we have to get involved in reporting what we know is
going on.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Latham is editor and publisher of the Marshall (TX) News
Messenger. His email address is platham(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
