<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, May 16, will move Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   On the dress page:
</P>
<P>
   POST-COLDWAR-REVIEW (Undated) _ For 10 years, the U.S., Russia
and China have agreed that their most vital interests were
economic, and that global cooperation in the pursuit of prosperity
was their paramount goal. That, at least, was how Americans had
understood the new world. But in Russia and China, as events last
week showed, the picture was not quite so straightforward. Whatever
their interests in building new markets alongside the U.S., the
Kosovo crisis has revealed the blinders Americans wear as they
imagine how other countries perceive their own vital interests and
the degree to which former enemies have come to trust Americans. By
Erik Eckholm. (`i' category)
</P>
<P>
   AMY-FISHER-REVIEW (Undated) _ The once-and-future queen of our
tabloid domain was released from a prison last week. After a
seven-year hiatus, Amy Fisher is among us again, and it seems that
since we cannot escape her, we may have no recourse but to pursue,
analyze and perhaps even worship her. By Dan Barry. (`a' category)
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `a' category:
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ENLIST-REVIEW (Undated) _ Notable numbers of young
Americans enlisted to fight Iraq in the gulf war. So far they have
been sitting out the conflict in Yugoslavia. For a few years, the
gulf war stemmed a steady decline in enlistment, in a way that
ethnic cleansing in Yugoslavia has so far failed to do. The dearth
of enlistees raises intriguing questions about attitudes toward
military service and modern warfare, and about the lessons of World
War II. By Diana Jean Schemo.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T-ANTITRUST-REVIEW (Undated) _ Many consumer advocates think
antitrust regulation has been futile. But even supporters of the
AT&AMP;T's cable takeovers can agree that existing antitrust standards
are not well suited to handle telecommunications mergers where
threats to diverse expression trump in importance threats of higher
prices, the ordinary province of antitrust enforcement. Regulatory
authorities are groping for answers. The AT&AMP;T-MediaOne case may
force them to find some before they are ready. By Michael M.
Weinstein.
</P>
<P>
   REALITY-ARTS-REVIEW (Undated) _ Americans are getting more and
more facts, not only in the traditional venue of newspapers and TV
but also in the arts _ `a kind of headlong rush toward more and
more reality,'' says Mark Rosenthal, curator of 20th-century art at
the Guggenheim Museum. The arts are not just imitating reality _
they are appropriating it. By Elin Schoen Brockman.
</P>
<P>
   AIRLINE-MOVIES-REVIEW (Undated) _ After the Colorado school
shootings and the ensuing debate over media violence, a movement
has been formed among parents and educators to persuade airlines
that young children should not be casually exposed to lurid movie
imagery of guns, bombs and mayhem. By Joe Sharkey.
</P>
<P>
   CIVILWAR-REENACT-TEXT-REVIEW (Undated) _ Tips for Civil War
re-enactors. There is a large and growing body books, magazines,
Web sites treating the war and its landscape not only as hallowed
ground but also as fertile soil for levity, fantasy, fringe
scholarship, even romance.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-DESIGN-REVIEW (Undated) _ Auto historians and designers
wonder why today's models have a more masculine, brawny, tougher
look than the more delicate, feminine cars of earlier decades.
Perhaps it's because more women are buying cars. Maybe people feel
less safe, causing them to look to their cars for protection.
Whatever the cause, it is as if Detroit's metal has had a sex
change operation. By Robyn Meredith.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `i' category:
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MAPS-REVIEW (Washington) _ To avert another mishap such
as the bombing of the Chinese embassy in Belgrade, the Pentagon has
announced corrective steps, including speedier updates from
government analysts to the military's so-called `no strike'' list.
But unlike the billions poured into building B-2 bombers or
launching spy satellites, the art of military mapmaking and
analyzing reconnaissance photos has been given short shrift in the
post-Cold War budget battles. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-U.S.-REVIEW (New York) _ There is a five-way contest
going on for prime minister of Israel, and it could end with the
ouster of Benjamin Netanyahu. Yet with the exception of religious
Jews in the U.S. who have long kept closer tabs on Jerusalem than
on Washington, there is surprisingly little interest among many
American Jews about what is taking place in Israel. By Adam
Nagourney.
</P>
