<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-ELECTIONS-$ADV-16-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETANYAHU SCRAMBLES AS POLL NUMBERS WANE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Also see: Israel-Russians and Israel-multiparties) 
(For release Sunday, May 16) 
 
By DEBORAH HORAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, not usually a
politician on the defensive, spent much of the final week leading
up to Israel's elections looking like a man scrambling to hold on
to votes.
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual plea delivered in the closing days of the
campaign, he broadcast an appeal to voters who have deserted him to
``come back home.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he took to the radio waves to deny that a spirit of
defeatism hangs over his Likud Party. ``These are false reports
aimed at demoralizing Likud voters,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the run-up to Monday's elections in which Israel's prime
minister will be directly elected by the voters, political analysts
say Netanyahu's words and deeds reflect a mood of desperation in
his camp brought on by a slip in poll after poll.
</P>
<P>
   Yet if Netanyahu, who claims in public that the polls are wrong,
denies his main challenger, Labor Party leader Ehud Barak, a
majority of the votes and forces him into a runoff June 1, he would
buy two additional weeks to turn his campaign around.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some political analysts and pollsters suspect that
Netanyahu is leading a losing cause.
</P>
<P>
   He ``is a victim of his own success in putting down terror,''
says Efraim Inbar, an analyst at Tel Aviv's Bar Ilan University who
specializes in Israeli domestic politics. ``People take (their own
safety) for granted now.''
</P>
<P>
   In a race that holds the fate of the stalled Arab-Israeli peace
process in the balance, Netanyahu has been trying to remind
Israelis of the acts of terror that followed the original peace
pact negotiated with the Palestinians in 1993 by the previous Labor
government.
</P>
<P>
   One of his campaign commercials, which was later withdrawn after
outcries from his opponents, showed grisly news footage of a bus
explosion by a Palestinian suicide bomber that occurred during the
term of Netanyahu's predecessor, Labor Party Prime Minister Shimon
Peres.
</P>
<P>
   Another spot compared the 1993 Israeli-Palestinian peace
agreement to the appeasement of the 1938 Munich accord _ an
agreement that many Israelis believe led to World War II and the
Holocaust, the systematic destruction of 6 million Jews.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was trying to evoke emotions,'' said Inbar, the Bar Ilan
University analyst. ``He was trailing in the polls.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the ``security'' strategy worked for Netanyahu:
Israelis weary of a string of bus bombings in the weeks before
elections ushered the right-wing Netanyahu into office, choosing
his promises of ``security'' over Peres' ``peace'' platform.
</P>
<P>
   After Netanyahu took office, the peace process with Yasser
Arafat's Palestinian Authority stalled, with his government pushing
ahead with new settlements in the West Bank and Arab-dominated east
Jerusalem and provoking public disapproval from the United States
and others.
</P>
<P>
   But if the polls are any indication this time around,
Netanyahu's appeal to Israelis' sense of security has not been as
effective. For weeks now, the polls have consistently given Barak
about 45 percent of the vote to Netanyahu's 38 percent in a
five-man race for prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   The other candidates _ former Defense Minister Yitzhak
Mordechai, ex-Likud Party stalwart Benny Begin and Arab politician
Azmi Bishara _ are fading or did not catch on, according to the
polls.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the incumbent's defensive campaign, the
challenger's has gone on the attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``Netanyahu tries to scare you because he is going nowhere,''
Barak said in one campaign ad that was aired last week. ``We must
take Israel forward without fear.''
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, though, Barak's ads have concentrated on
people's growing frustrations over the freeze in the peace process,
a downturn in the economy and a cultural rift between religious and
secular Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   Barka has gained a broad appeal, building a coalition called
``One Israel,'' which includes a moderate religious party, a party
of Sephardic Jews of Middle Eastern background and the Labor
Party's traditional supporters, the Ashkenazi Jews of European
backgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, his popularity among new Russian immigrants has gone
up. And last week, two of the country's four Arab parties endorsed
his candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts say credit for Barak's success should go to James
Carville, the U.S. political consultant who, along with three other
well-known American strategists, formed the brains behind Barak's
new image and muscular campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Months ago, political observers chided Barak for being too stiff
and something of a political blockhead who tended to stumble in
public. In a radio interview, for instance, he told listeners that
if he had been a Palestinian, he ``would have been a terrorist.''
</P>
<P>
   After hiring Carville and Co., Barak's image took on a shine. He
became an amicable, well-spoken and decorated military man flanked
at campaign events by army generals who approved of his strategy of
peacemaking with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   He became a champion of a new economic policy that he said would
pull Israel out of its slump and create jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, he became a pragmatic centrist whose left-wing Labor
allies _ namely, Peres and Oslo accord architect Yossi Beilin, who
many Israelis in the political center associate with capitulation
in negotiations with Palestinians _ were nowhere to be found.
</P>
<P>
   ``He camouflaged Labor. He moved his headquarters out, changed
the name (of the party) to One Israel and added religious and
Sephardic parties'' said Shmuel Sandler, a political analyst at Bar
Ilan University.
</P>
<P>
   ``And he's hiding many of his best supporters, like Peres and
Beilin,`` Sandler said. ``The Israeli electorate is not to the
left. It is center-right, so by hiding them, he attracts supporters
of (Netanyahu) who would reject him if they saw Peres and Beilin at
the forefront.''
</P>
<P>
   Sandler, though, cautions against giving too much credit to the
American strategists. Netanyahu also brought in Aurthur
Finkelstein, the Republican campaign adviser, to help his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any adviser who comes from the outside doesn't understand what
makes a country tick,'' Sandler said. ``They can advise him how to
put the message forward, but they can't tell him what the message
should be.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say Netanyahu's lag in the polls reflects not so much
Barak's success at attracting new votes as Netanyahu's failure to
keep the ones he had. Netanyahu, they say, created many political
enemies during his three years in office. Both Mordechai's and
Begin's candidacies split the right wing and take votes away from
Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not Barak leading. It's Netanyahu trailing,'' said Inbar,
who explained: ``Basically, he doesn't have a very good record.
He's made a lot of political mistakes. His allies left him.''
</P>
<P>
   In the final days of the campaign, Netanyahu made a bold pitch
for support from traditional Likud voters who had abandoned him.
One television spot showed a young Likud voter talking about his
decision to dump Netanyahu for Mordechai.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized I would be voting for the Left,'' the voter says,
``so I went back to Netanyahu.''
</P>
<P>
   The strategy still might work. In 1996, Netanyahu stayed behind
Peres in the polls right up to Election Day, and then beat the
Labor leader by just 30,000 votes _ a fact Netanyahu keeps
reminding voters today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always lose in the polls and win the election,'' Netanyahu
said with characteristic confidence last week.
</P>
<P>
   Most analysts cautioned against writing Netanyahu off.
</P>
<P>
   Israelis don't always tell the truth to pollsters. Almost 10
percent of the electorate is still undecided. And the race has
shaped up to be hair-splittingly close.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't count Netanyahu out,'' said Inbar. ``The surprising
thing is he still has a chance.``
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
