<HEADLINE>
SURVEY SHOWS PUBLIC VIEWS STATE COURTS AS `JUST OK' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN and JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ State courts received middling grades in a
nationwide public opinion survey released Friday, with the majority
of respondents giving judges and court systems high marks for
fairness while expressing qualms about delays and the cost of
litigation.
</P>
<P>
   The survey of 1,826 respondents yielded widespread concern that
courts fail to treat diverse racial and economic groups equally.
</P>
<P>
   Eighty percent of respondents said the wealthy get better
treatment than most while 47 percent said African-Americans and
Hispanics are treated worse.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, 49 percent of non-Hispanic whites believe juries are
representative of their communities while only 29 percent of
African-Americans and 33 percent of Hispanics agree.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty-six percent said the courts generally favor corporations
when they are sued by individuals. And 81 percent said judges'
decisions in some degree are influenced by political
considerations.
</P>
<P>
   The survey was sponsored by The Hearst Corporation and the
findings were presented by Frank A. Bennack Jr., president and
chief executive officer, at the National Conference on Public Trust
and Confidence in the Judicial System.
</P>
<P>
   There is ``an overwhelming belief that equal justice under the
law is more equal to some than to others,'' Bennack told the
gathering of 460 judges, court administrators, bar officials, and
members of the League of Women Voters. Overall, ``when all the
(survey's) figures were totaled and all the comments considered,
the courts came out just OK on average,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The American Bar Association, the Conference of Chief Justices,
the Conference of State Court Administrators and the League of
Women Voters sponsored the conference, described as the first-ever
examination of the degree of public trust of the courts.
</P>
<P>
   Bennack said the public wasn't likely to invest political
institutions or the communications media with high degrees of
trust. But trust in courts is essential, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here, society and institution come together in ways that
really define who we would like to think we are as a society _
fair, open and protective of the rights of every individual,'' he
said. ``Politicians can advocate it, the media can comment on it _
but only the courts actually make it happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Bennack noted that Hearst sponsored a public opinion survey in
1983 that was designed to assess public attitudes toward courts.
That survey found a similar pattern of strengths, weaknesses and
inconsistencies _ and what Bennack termed ``a worrisome disconnect
between the courts and the people they are sworn to serve.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 survey was overseen by the National Center for State
Courts, based in Williamsburg, Va. Interviews were conducted in
January and February by the Indiana University Public Opinion
Laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   Interviewers questioned 1,200 respondents at random, as well as
300 African-Americans and 300 Hispanics to insure the views of
minorities were represented. The final sample from which results
were drawn was weighted according to national population statistics
for non-Hipsanic whites (72.1 percent), Hispanics (13.4 percent)
and African-Americans (12.1 percent).
</P>
<P>
   Across the board, judges won praise in the survey. A total of 61
percent said judges do not give cases adequate time and attention,
but 79 percent said they are generally honest and fair. Among
Hispanics, 75 percent agreed; 68 percent for African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, 85 percent said the courts protect defendants'
rights. Seventy-four percent of African-Americans and 82 percent of
Hispanics agreed.
</P>
<P>
   But all respondents expressed concern over the slow pace of
justice. Eighty percent said cases are not resolved in a timely
manner and only 49 percent said courts don't do a good job of
monitoring the progress of cases.
</P>
<P>
   Bennack noted one respondent who commented: ``I think they're
just so overworked and backlogged that they can't get anything
done.''
</P>
<P>
   The high cost of litigation was cited as another cause for
concern. Sixty-eight percent said the cost of bringing a case to
court is not affordable, with 87 percent saying lawyers' fees
contribute ``a lot'' to the high cost of litigation. By contrast,
41.5 percent blamed court fees and 51 percent cited the complexity
of the law.
</P>
<P>
   Respondents did not have a high opinion of media coverage of the
courts. Fifty-three percent expressed some degree of skepticism
over the accuracy of news reporting of court cases. And only 10
percent expressed a ``great deal'' of confidence in the media
overall as an American institutions.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, 23 percent expressed a similarly high level of
confidence in courts while 43 percent gave high marks to the local
police and 45 percent gave them to doctors.
</P>
<P>
   Discontent with courts is an inevitable byproduct of its
adversarial format, Chief Justice William Rehnquist told the
audience. ``In the prototypical lawsuit, one party will win and one
party will lose,'' Rehnquist said. ``Many of the losers will
understandably be disappointed and some may feel they got a raw
deal from the courts.''
</P>
<P>
   There is not much the courts can do to change this perception,
but forcing judges to reconsider decisions simply because they are
unpopular would undermine the nation's tradition of an independent
judiciary, Rehnquist said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Recall of judicial decisions by some sort of a popular mandate
... is too high a price to pay for public approval,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Panels of lawyers and judges later told the conference that the
public's view of courts might improve if judges became more
involved in their communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the basic reasons we have a lack of public trust and
confidence...is because judges have isolated themselves from the
community,'' said Veronica McBeth, presiding judge of the Los
Angeles municipal court.
</P>
<P>
   McBeth said she has spoken to several community groups and
attended several meetings in and around Los Angeles in an effort to
educate the public about the court system.
</P>
<P>
   One problem, McBeth said, is that many judges are reluctant to
make public speeches because they are concerned the public won't
view them as able to make impartial decisions in the court room.
</P>
<P>
   Other panelists said judges need to make themselves more
accessible to lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   W. Seaborn Jones, an Atlanta lawyer and president-elect of the
National Conference of Bar Presidents, said a 10-minute phone call
between lawyers and a judge can save reams of paperwork and time,
helping to more speedily move cases through the court system.
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Freedman and Jennifer Corbett Dooren can be reached at
202-298-6920 and, by email, at dan(at)hearstdc.com or
jennifer(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
