<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, May 15, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Temperatures plummeted to 20 degrees early Friday at Winnemucca,
Nev., setting a new record minimum for the date. The reading was
symptomatic of the cool air mass covering much of the West this
week. With the cool air mass holding steady Saturday, snow will
fall at elevations as low as 5,000 feet in the mountains of Montana
and Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, very warm and humid air will expand northward from
the southern Plains, with afternoon temperatures possibly exceeding
85 degrees as far north as Nebraska. Humidity will also soar as
tropical air streams northward from the Gulf of Mexico. As a
result, the stage will be set for winter in the Rockies to clash
with summer in the Plains, a volatile meeting that will likely
result in severe thunderstorms over the Midwest later Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   With warm, humid air acting as volatile fuel and a cold
upper-level disturbance acting as a match, explosive thunderstorms
will erupt Saturday across Nebraska and northern Kansas. Large hail
and damaging straight-line winds will lash some areas. Tornadoes
are also possible, particularly near the warm front in Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   Farther south, widely separated potent thunderstorms will erupt
from western Kansas to western Texas along a line marking the
boundary between tropical air from the Gulf of Mexico and dry air
from the southern Rockies and northern Old Mexico. Some storms may
reach severe levels.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, showers and thunderstorms will develop in parts of
the Middle Atlantic States in the vicinity of a stalled low off the
Carolina coast.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Atypical Snowfall
</P>
<P>
   Last Thursday, two-tenths of an inch of snow fell at Spokane,
Wash., as a cold and moist flow of air from the northwest blew
across the Pacific Northwest. The tiny accumulation of snow was
large enough, however, to set a daily snowfall record in the
eastern Washington city. But more impressive than the amount of
snow has been the recent frequency of snowfall in Spokane. Since
climate records began in 1881, only nine May days have registered
measurable snow, three of which have occurred during this current
May. The latest date of measurable snow in Spokane is May 14.
</P>
</TEXT>
