<SLUG> BC-MELLEN-FASHION-JOURNALIST-ART-$ADV16-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN `ABSOLUTELY FABULOUS' COMES TO BREATHLESS LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, May 16)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By MICHAEL MUSTO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Last Tuesday's guide at Costume Institute of the
Metropolitan Museum of Art was a lively lady with a short gray
flip, a pony-print purse and black-framed glasses, which she
regularly removed to emphasize pronouncements like, ``I've always
been enamored of Cinderella and rags and shredding!''
</P>
<P>
   Polly Mellen, a fixture in fashion journalism for some 40 years,
a woman known for her forceful opinions and eccentric personality,
was, at the behest of the institute, giving a one-shot tour as an
outside expert with inside information. Ms. Mellen, who brightened
``Unzipped,'' the 1995 documentary about Isaac Mizrahi, with
operatic exclamations on the order of ``This outfit says hello to
me very distinctly!'' promised not to be a tour guide who would
lull her listeners to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   At seventysomething, Ms. Mellen is branching out. For the past
seven years she has been the creative director of Allure magazine,
but Ms. Mellen will leave at the end of August to free-lance, write
a book and presumably have time for new larks like this one. As she
put it: ``I'm very interested in spreading my wings. I want to go
out on my own and see what I get from it. I'm not a negative
thinker!''
</P>
<P>
   That's an understatement; the woman could look at a pile of
provocatively placed dishrags and shriek ``Divine!''
</P>
<P>
   She wasn't dismayed that no one was there for her unheralded
tour at first. At 11:45 in the morning, the institute's director,
Richard Martin, stood with Ms. Mellen at a meeting area on the
museum's main floor and announced ``This is the 11:45 tour'' to no
one in particular. Only the crew for ``Polly Mellen's World Tour,''
a documentary being made about her by Douglas Keeve, the director
of ``Unzipped,'' was there. Undaunted, Ms. Mellen marched
downstairs to the first window of ``Our New Clothes: Acquisitions
of the 1990s,'' an exhibit of clothing ranging from Victorian
summer laces to Hollywood dresses.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a rare bird,'' Keeve said. ``There's no one who gets
that excited about fashion every time.'' As Ms. Mellen said in an
earlier interview: ``I'm a realist, but I'm considered in a fantasy
world because I'm enthusiastic. Enthusiastic people can throw
people off. But along with that energy, I promise you there's a
certain knowledge.''
</P>
<P>
   The tour was not for no one, as it turned out. As Ms. Mellen
held forth, speaking in her signature manner, in which every other
word sounds italicized, a growing group _ mostly women, tourists,
fashionistas and the simply curious _ began to follow her around
the Costume Institute's show as if she were some Pied Piper of
Seventh Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mellen, who apprenticed with the legendary fashion editor
Diana Vreeland at Harper's Bazaar in the '50s, talked
extemporaneously for the whole hour, commenting on outfits as they
caught her eye in a selective, semichronological manner. Her
commentary provided a rare mix of history, observation, gossip and
riff, although she spoke more to the glassed-in displays and the
camera crew than to the tour group itself. Gesturing toward a
window filled with flowing white gowns and robes from the 18th
century, she declared: ``White has to do with pristine, silence, a
certain modesty. And yet you feel that inside these women is a
hothouse!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Were these clothes uncomfortable?'' Keeve asked. Ms. Mellen
explained that the women who wore them knew how to co-exist with
corsets.
</P>
<P>
   But her remarks seemed a little halfhearted; she was clearly
more comfortable with contemporary designers, the ones she has
known personally and cheered from the front row for years.
</P>
<P>
   As the tour moved to a display case filled with dazzling outfits
from the mod '60s to the present, Ms. Mellen went into such
absolute rapture at least one listener didn't know whether to hug
her or douse her with water.
</P>
<P>
   She gushed over a Todd Oldham beaded halter top. ``There's a
feeling of Cleopatra, a feeling of the American Indian, and he puts
her in pinstriped pants that belong to a man!'' She paused,
meaningfully.
</P>
<P>
   Spotting an elaborate Rei Kawakubo dress, Ms. Mellen beamed.
``She dares, she stretches, she cares,'' she said. ``Oh, my. I have
been moved to tears when I look at Rei's collections.''
</P>
<P>
   Of a Charles James design she said: ``His clothes are timeless.
I couldn't afford them, so I used to have them copied.''
</P>
<P>
   And she pointed with her glasses to a pale pink wool Pierre
Cardin coat from 1965 and said: ``It took real adjustment to
understand his clothes at first for me, but once you got it, it was
a springboard to Courreges and Gernreich!''
</P>
<P>
   Simon Doonan, the creative director for Barneys New York, which
sponsored the show, interjected, ``Cardin was what you were going
to wear if you went to the moon.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mellen kept charging ahead, hardly noticing that when she
said, ``Mme. Gres designed a great deal in jersey,'' a few of the
touristy types seemed to think she meant Passaic. Her enthusiasm
clearly rendered her unfazed, and you could practically hear her
gasp in between analyses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you like plaid?'' one of Keeve's companions blurted out in
a real-life ``Absolutely Fabulous'' moment. ``I love plaid!'' Ms.
Mellen said. She alerted everyone to a beaded James Galanos
ensemble that looked positively Nancy Reagan. The designer, she
said, always knew who his clients' friends were ``so you wouldn't
show up in the same dress.'' More excitedly, she spotted an Issey
Miyake dress, a multicolored number with accordion shapes, and
said: ``When I squint, I see a Japanese lantern or Punch and Judy.
If you wear that, you have to really feel for that.''
</P>
<P>
   She clearly felt for it. But suddenly she looked a little lost
in thought, staring at the mannequins' faces instead of their
outfits. ``We're starting to see much less makeup,'' she declared.
``Blue eye shadow _ finished! Women today are more confident in
constructing their faces.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple of tour members who were wearing blue eye shadow
quietly lowered their heads.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   As if to make sure she didn't lose the crowd, Ms. Mellen
immediately segued to the flowing black Versace dress Madonna wore
to a charity ball last year. At the word ``Madonna,'' their ears
perked up. ``I'll never forget Madonna in this dress,'' Ms. Mellen
said, letting the clothes act as memory springboards.
</P>
<P>
   The sight of a Claire McCardell design reminded her of the time
in the 1940s _ on the beach at Fishers Island _ when Miss McCardell
pulled off her dress to demonstrate a new bathing suit right in
front of her: ``She was in a diaper _ a diaper! Shocking, but she
didn't care!''
</P>
<P>
   Two preteen girls tittered, than darted away. They missed the
even racier spectacle of Ms. Mellen pointing out a 1996 Gaultier
jacket with a naked male frame silk-screened on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The body is raised a bit,'' she said, ``and I think that's
because Mr. Gaultier wants you to see the penis.'' Everyone
laughed.
</P>
<P>
   She could probably have gone on all day, but time was up. Ms.
Mellen thanked the crowd, then quickly disappeared into a private
room. Doonan was left to fend off two women. ``Who was she?'' one
of them asked. ``Did you say she was Molly or Polly Mellen?''
</P>
<P>
   He explained, and one of them, casually dressed with
close-cropped hair, balked, ``I've been on many tours,'' she said,
``and this is the first one that wasn't addressed to us. She talked
only to the press. I resent it.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, there's always the movie.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
