<SLUG> BC-TV-PETTY-REVIEW-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BEHIND THE MUSIC': A LOOK AT TOM PETTY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By BILL DEYOUNG   
 The Gainesville (Fla.) Sun  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAINESVILLE, Fla. _ The story of Tom Petty's exodus from Florida
into the belly of the music business beast has been recited over
and over again. Sunday's edition of VH1's rock documentary ``Behind
the Music'' attempts, with mixed results, to tell the tale
definitively.
</P>
<P>
   Petty formed the original Heartbreakers in Los Angeles in 1975,
more than a year after all five of the musicians had left
Gainesville, which was the hometown of Petty and keyboardist
Benmont Tench.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way to tell anybody what you've been through, and
what your eyes have seen,'' Petty, 48, tells VH1. Referring to the
Heartbreakers he says, ``but they were there, and they went through
it, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Petty, Tench and guitarist Mike Campbell are extensively
interviewed, along with bassist Ron Blair, who left the band in
1982, and drummer Stan Lynch, who departed in 1994. The producers
also talk to Howie Epstein, Blair's replacement and still a member
of the group, Petty's manager, and various musical collaborators
and record producers.
</P>
<P>
   In Gainesville, the interview subjects include Petty's father
and his cousin, Sadie Darnell, who is commander of operations at
the Gainesville Police Department. ``He was a long-haired person in
a short-haired world,'' Darnell says.
</P>
<P>
   Petty's rebellion against all kinds of conformity forms the
backbone of this 60-minute program. The familiar stories are
trotted out: His refusal to work until a record company gave the
band a better deal, bankruptcy, legal wranglings, the studio
frustration that led to his smashing his left hand against a wall.
``Pulverized it,'' Petty says. ``Broke it to powder.'' A lengthy
segment documents the 1987 fire that destroyed his Encino, Calif.
home.
</P>
<P>
   Old photos and home movies race by: There's the Mudcrutch farm
in Gainesville, where the musicians played for thousands of friends
and fans; there's Gainesville High School, from which Petty
graduated in 1968. The musicians are shown with long hair and short
hair, with beards and without, with girlfriends, wives and
ex-wives. Clips from television shows _ particularly from the '70s,
when the band was young and still hungry _ are riveting.
</P>
<P>
   After nearly 25 years, however, there's no hunger left in Tom
Petty or the remains of his band. His music today is the polished
work of a craftsman, but it hasn't been sharp-edged, or
particularly challenging, for a long time. The first 45 minutes of
VH1's documentary seem designed as a lead-in to the last quarter,
which is nothing more than a celebratory plug for Petty's new
album.
</P>
<P>
   This series' style: quick-cut editing, music bites and
choppily-edited quotes never longer than 10 or 12 seconds, grows
irritating after a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``Behind the Music: Tom Petty &AMP; the Heartbreakers'' is woefully
short on personal insight _ there's no mention of Petty's recent
divorce, which doubtless had a great impact on his writing _ and
the viewer never gets a sense of the Heartbreakers as friends, or
as individuals. If the producers intended to achieve anything more
than a quick gloss of ancient history, they blew it.
</P>
<P>
   (The Gainsville (Fla.) Sun is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
