<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-MULTIPARTIES-$ADV-16-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOPEFULS FROM 32 PARTIES ADD SPICE TO VOTING 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Sunday, May 16) 
 
DEBORAH HORAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ This year, Israelis who think peace in the Middle
East can be achieved through transcendental meditation have a shot
at sending a representative to parliament.
</P>
<P>
   So do those who want to protect the rights of battered husbands,
light up a marijuana cigarette in the open, protect the environment
or play blackjack for money without breaking the law.
</P>
<P>
   And if none of those sounds appealing, most voters need not
worry about finding their political niches: No fewer than 32
separate parties have signed up to run in Monday's elections, when
voters will choose 120 members to the Knesset as well as a prime
minister.
</P>
<P>
   While most of them are not expected to get the approximately
45,000 votes needed to win a parliamentary seat, their inclusion in
this year's election has added spice to campaigns that in past
elections have centered mostly on issues of war and peace.
</P>
<P>
   There have always been one-issue parties in Israel. But a new
electoral law that gives each voter two ballots _ one for prime
minister and one for a party _ has prompted them to proliferate.
</P>
<P>
   ``With one ballot, they can vote with their brains,'' said
Reuven Hazan, a political analyst at Jerusalem's Hebrew University.
``With the other, they can vote with their emotions.''
</P>
<P>
   And so there are parties for the environment, for senior
citizens, for feminists and for men. One party promises to promote
development of the Negev Desert. Another wants to commemorate
Romanian-Jewish history.
</P>
<P>
   The Casino Party hopes to legalize gambling, while the Green
Leaf Party wants to decriminalize marijuana. And for those into
unconventional ways to bring about world peace, there is the
Natural Law Party. They believe that if the square root of one
percent of the population of the Middle East _ approximately 1,500
people, by their reckoning _ practices yogic flying twice a day,
they will usher in regional peace.
</P>
<P>
   Confused? Surprisingly, most Israelis aren't.
</P>
<P>
   ``Israeli voters are experts in this,'' said Yaron Ezrahi, a
political analyst at Jerusalem's Hebrew University. ``We never had
a choice between two parties only.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say most voters will stick to the parties _ all 11 of
them _ that already hold seats in parliament. But of the newcomers,
polls suggest Pnina Rosenblum's feminist party and Tommy Lapid's
anti-religious party stand a decent chance at capturing a seat.
</P>
<P>
   So does one of the new parties appealing to new Russian
immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   And the others?
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of them only have a few thousand people behind them,''
Hazan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Realistically? They don't stand a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
