u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRINCETON-IVY-CLUB-$A     05-14 1293
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRINCETON-IVY-CLUB-$ADV16-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PRINCETON IVY CLUB, WHERE TOMORROW'S ELITE MEETS TO EAT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga., Ghana)  (ART ADV: Two photes are being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By MONIQUE P. YAZIGI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Should the members of the Ivy Club ever face the withering
scrutiny of a Fifth Avenue co-op board or a Fairfield County
country club, they will be well prepared.
</P>
<P>
   To get into Ivy, the oldest, most expensive and most patrician
eating club at Princeton University, candidates must sit for 10
one-on-one interviews with members, whose attempts to plumb their
souls touch on what their parents do, where they spend summers and
who their friends are.
</P>
<P>
   Then the entire century-old club votes on prospects in all-night
sessions. Like an English men's club, there is a blackball rule: if
one of 130 members vetoes a candidate, he or she is rejected _
``hosed'' in the tart campus vernacular.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, more and more students are being hosed who don't fit
Ivy's image as a haven for Eastern establishment, Social Register
types, what one former member called ``a club full of sons and
daughters of CEO's.''
</P>
<P>
   At Princeton, where more than 80 percent of juniors and seniors
eat meals in one of 11 privately owned clubs on Prospect Avenue,
known as ``the Street,'' the eating clubs dominate social life.
They determine not only the students' dinner partners but also whom
they socialize with on Thursday and Saturday party nights.
Membership can shape a person's social identity for life.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, in the wake of a widely reported 1990 court
decision that forced Princeton's eating clubs to admit women, Ivy
became more democratic and socially open. Not only women, but
students of different races and more diverse social backgrounds
were welcomed during ``bicker,'' the yearly selection process.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember meetings, open discussions about changing the
perception of the club,'' said Sophie Glenn of Princeton's class of
1992, who was one of the first women admitted to Ivy. ``It was
brought up that it would be in the club's interest to be more
diverse, especially in the backgrounds of people, because it was
always perceived as a snotty place for rich white kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a conscious effort to diversify,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But now the pendulum is swinging back, in part a reflection of
increasingly status-conscious, money-conscious times. The race for
credentials and connections like an Ivy membership begins, at least
in places like New York and Los Angeles, with selective nursery
schools, and is egged on by a culture that makes popular heroes out
of Wall Street bonus babies.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Ivy has fewer members from minority groups and public
schools than in the early '90s, present and past members say. Atu
Darko, a senior who dropped out of Ivy in February, was one of four
of seven black members who left the eating club in the last
academic year, citing their discomfort. ``When I first got there,
it was more international, but over the years it became very
WASP,'' said Darko, who is the son of Ghanaian immigrants and
graduated from the Bronx High School of Science. ``It had to do
with the membership's choosing new members. I think less
international kids bickered, or less minorities bickered because
they felt uncomfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   As Ivy swings back to what F. Scott Fitzgerald called a
``detached and breathlessly aristocratic'' club, present and former
Princeton students and faculty members are not surprised.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way the Ivy Club is certainly in tune with current
trends, if not even ahead of the curve,'' said Uwe E. Reinhardt,
the James Madison professor of political economy at Princeton. ``If
you look at American society, in certainly the world Fitzgerald
wrote about, we are divided by class. We are sliding back toward a
society dominated by a corporate society. I think in our corporate
elite, there is a Marie Antoinette complex, and that percolates
down to Princeton.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ivy Club, where membership costs $5,660 a year, is a
three-story brick mansion set behind iron gates. The dining room,
billiard room and library are a procession of red leather club
chairs, mahogany walls and oil paintings of Fitzgerald-era
``lacrosse gentlemen.''
</P>
<P>
   Members eat at long tables covered with white linens and set
with 19th-century Sheffield sterling candelabra, which are lighted
even when daylight streams in the windows.
</P>
<P>
   The formality can unnerve some not to the manner born. Heyman
said that though he is a product of private schools and
professional parents (a lawyer and a doctor), he would have been
mortified a year ago at dropping his knife, as he did at dinner the
other night. He studied the faces around him to see if anyone had
noticed. Luckily, no one had. ``That would have made me more
nervous a year ago,'' he said, quickly retrieving the knife. ``But
I'm much better now.''
</P>
<P>
   When Nat Zilkha, who grew up in Portland, Me., and went to
boarding school at Andover, was accepted by Ivy, his older sister
had one piece of advice: ``Get a tux.'' The club sponsors nearly a
dozen black-tie parties a year, including one during February's
initiation week for new members (which also includes the tradition
of passing newcomers naked down a staircase, modified in the 90s to
allow women to keep their underwear on).
</P>
<P>
   A woman who dropped out of Ivy last winter, because she felt she
was not from a grand enough background, said the club is full of
``people who don't have any concept of money.'' Raised in Atlanta,
she felt uneasy being served four-course dinners by a uniformed
staff. ``If you're not flying off to London on spring weekends,
you'll end up feeling left out,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ivy's current membership of 130 includes Mary Bonner Baker, a
daughter of James A. Baker III, the former secretary of state;
Moira Forbes, a daughter of Steve Forbes, the one-time presidential
candidate, and Mary Firestone, a descendant of the founder of the
tire company.
</P>
<P>
   James Q. Griffin, a 1955 Princeton graduate and president of the
alumni board that governs Ivy, said that in membership, ``I can't
see any difference between the way it is now and 50 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``It's a Jeffersonian democracy, taking the natural
aristocracy, as you were. There's no social pyramid.''
</P>
<P>
   He pointed out that interest in joining the club was at an
all-time high, and ``by that very definition, there is something
that seems attractive.''
</P>
<P>
   In the latest bicker, 130 sophomores and juniors applied to Ivy,
and 67 were accepted. All along the Street, the five clubs that
select their members attracted the most sophomore applicants since
1994, and the six eating clubs that accept anyone wishing to join
attracted the fewest since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The popularity of the bicker clubs frustrates some Princeton
administrators, who have never been entirely happy with the system.
``I think there are problems with selectivity of any kind on the
college campus, because selectivity excludes people,'' said Janina
Montero, dean of student life.
</P>
<P>
   But the administration and the clubs, whose relations have swung
between hostility and accommodation over the years, are in a period
of relative truce in the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   Middle-aged alumni in New York say that for the first time
friends are seeking their help in getting children who are in
private secondary schools into Ivy. ``It's absurd,'' said one
alumnus who was asked to provide references. ``Why don't they worry
about getting their kid into Princeton first?''
</P>
<P>
   He did not want to be identified because he thought it might
spoil the chances for his own son, 16, to get into Ivy one day.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Collectively, Princeton students are more racially and
ethnically diverse than in the past, and as a dress code, the L.L.
Bean styles of a generation ago have been replaced by T-shirts and
baseball caps, a generic geek chic. Ivy, however, is a last bastion
of traditional dress and etiquette.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you see a movie about Princeton _ proper, WASP, preppy,
they dress nice and they are smart and tell you how smart they are
_ that's Ivy,'' said Joe Juliano, a senior, who worked as a bouncer
during Ivy parties, but is not a member. ``Princeton doesn't look
like that anymore, but Ivy does.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the question of members' ethnic and economic backgrounds
is more complex. The membership seems calculated to be a mix of
old-line families, new-money heirs and even a group on financial
aid. ``Of course, there's still diversity,'' one Ivy alumnus said.
``About 20 percent. They are there to make the other 80 percent
show they are democratic and feel more superior.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivy members invariably maintain that the club is diverse. ``We
pick people who are diverse,'' said Zilkha, the social chairman. He
spoke of members who perform in an a capella singing group, play
the guitar and are active in the arts and drama.
</P>
<P>
   ``Exactly,'' responded Darko, one of the four black students who
resigned from Ivy this year. He said the club interprets diversity
to mean members with broad interests, rather than with broad ethnic
and economic backgrounds. ``Diversity to me means seeing different
faces, people with different income brackets and different clothing
styles,'' Darko said.
</P>
<P>
   Darko, a senior classics major who won a Fulbright fellowship
for study abroad after graduation, said that he did not feel racial
bias at Ivy; he simply grew tired of the homogeneity and
closed-mindedness. ``I couldn't identify with the people in the
club,'' he said. ``Everything was the same old same old. Same old
music. Same bad beer. The club is not open to change.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ivy would never play Motown,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Reared in Manhattan by parents from Ghana _ his mother is a
psychotherapist, his father a probation officer _ Darko said that
when Ivy does select blacks, they tend to be from immigrant or
foreign families. ``Being black to the club means being an
international black,'' he said. ``They aren't African-American from
New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to comment about the high number of black dropouts,
Griffin, the graduate board president, said: ``There are plenty of
blacks that do feel comfortable. It's just an individual decision.
The very fact that the people who dropped out were taken in the
first place means what they are implying is not true.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the profile of each new class of Ivy members is
determined by the undergraduates in the club. Current officers did
not respond to repeated requests to comment on their criteria for
admission. ``There is no pattern except the quality of the people
is very high,'' Griffin said. ``The undergraduates have a geometry.
Just because they are young doesn't mean the sociology is any less
complex.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
