<HEADLINE>
SIGNS OF RUSSIAN ECONOMIC RECOVERY ARE REPORTED 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By NEELA BANERJEE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Against the backdrop of Russia's political turmoil, the
economy seems to be gradually reviving from its collapse last
summer, with increased consumer spending and industrial production,
a Moscow research group said Friday in a widely followed monthly
report.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer expenditures rose 1.5 percent in March from February,
the second consecutive month of growth, according to the report,
Russian Economic Trends. Industrial production returned to its
level in December 1997, the highest since the collapse of the
Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   But a government economist and the report's authors at the
Russian European Center for Economic Policy warned that such growth
might be short-lived if a new Cabinet was not installed soon and if
it failed to carry out important systemic changes to encourage
long-term economic development. ``It's very important to have a
Cabinet in place quickly,'' said Peter Westin, an economist with
the Russian European Center, ``because any long, drawn-out process
has a negative effect on the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   The growth in production and spending is the unlikely
side-benefit of the government's decision last August to devalue
the ruble, which has fallen from about 15 cents to the dollar to
approximately 4 cents. As a result, imports that were bought for
dollars and other hard currency became too expensive for most
Russians. Over the last few months, as the flow of imports to
Russia has shrunk, domestic producers have made more to meet
consumer demand.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we've seen is that not so much investment as demand was
needed to get the economy to grow,'' said Vladimir Mau, head of the
Russian government's Center for Economic Reforms, an analytical
agency. He said the data showed that higher consumer demand had
helped to invigorate the economy, at least in the short term. ``But
investment is needed over the long term. This kind of growth can be
exhausted quickly. It's not stable.''
</P>
<P>
   The economists maintain that sustainable growth does not hinge
on one-time events such as a currency devaluation but on the
creation of conditions that allow businesses to thrive and the
government to function efficiently, so-called structural changes.
</P>
<P>
   Russia for years has worked on the edges of such changes without
mustering the political will or momentum to fully proceed with
them, partly because they are sure to alienate various interest
groups.
</P>
<P>
   Structural changes include a new tax code, an effective
bankruptcy procedure, pension reform and banking reform after the
collapse of the banking system last summer.
</P>
<P>
   President Boris Yeltsin said he had dismissed Prime Minister
Yevgeny Primakov because his government refused to push ahead with
such reforms. But any new government may face the same temptation,
especially because parliamentary and presidential elections are
scheduled over the next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fear is that political stability will be bought with
economic instability and giving in to demands of this lobby or
another,'' Mau said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
