<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHERN-EXPOSURE-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP LAWMAKERS OPPOSE THE WAR, BUT NOT THE SPENDING ON IT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By CARL HULSE and SEAN LOUGHLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Dozens of House Republicans want to stop the war in
Yugoslavia, but they evidently don't want to stop the war spending.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the same conservatives who shocked the White House by
voting to halt the ongoing air campaign and withdraw troops from
the region rallied behind the emergency appropriations measure
providing $11.7 billion for defense _ twice what the president
sought.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for this seeming contradiction? The lawmakers argued
the Clinton White House will fund the conflict regardless of their
opposition to it. They say they want to make certain the Pentagon
bank account is not depleted to the point where the military's
overall capability is sacrificed to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The money is going to be spent,'' said Rep. Charles Canady,
R-Fla. ``The question is whether it is going to come out of the
hide of the Defense Department.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jim DeMint, R-S.C., noted the emergency spending measure
contained more than $1 billion for spare military parts, $1.8
billion for military pay hikes and millions more for recruiting and
readiness training.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is time for us to rebuild the strength and dignity of our
military,'' declared DeMint.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats and other critics, however, said the disconnect
between the GOP positions against the conflict and for the funding
shows that Republicans are taking advantage of the conflict to
shower money on the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   Not all Republicans were on board. Rep. Howard Coble, R-N.C.,
said he couldn't support the military spending bill when he doesn't
approve of the administration's policy in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   He said the vote against the defense bill was difficult, but he
wanted to encourage a swift resolution to the crisis. ``The quicker
we get out, the better,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   SENATE SHOOTOUT
</P>
<P>
   The changing culture on gun control in the wake of the Columbine
shootings is becoming evident. The Senate's Southern Democrats, who
tend to be more cautious than other Democrats on the issue due to
the popularity of hunting and shooting in the region, nonetheless
gave their full support to the latest efforts at gun restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats John Breaux and Mary Landrieu of Louisiana, John
Edwards of North Carolina, Bob Graham of Florida and Fritz Hollings
of South Carolina all supported expanding background checks at gun
shows to include sales by unlicensed dealers.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the proposal initially failed due to GOP opposition.
Republicans Jeff Sessions and Richard Shelby of Alabama, Jesse
Helms of North Carolina, Strom Thurmond of South Carolina and
Connie Mack of Florida all fought it.
</P>
<P>
   Sensing a misstep, the GOP retreated and pushed through its own
approach to tightening restrictions on gun show sales. But
Democrats said the proposal left loopholes and they vowed to hold
Republicans accountable for the initial vote.
</P>
<P>
   After that vote, Hollings took to the Senate floor to denounce
the ``stonewalling and influence'' of the NRA, saying the gun
industry had lobbied to defeat a measure that could have helped
keep firearms out of the hands of criminals.''
</P>
<P>
   JURIS IMPRUDENCE?
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Robert Wexler, D-Fla., is a liberal member of the House
Judiciary Committee who earned a reputation as President Clinton's
fierce defender during impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   But his tolerance doesn't extend to President Slobodan Milosevic
of Yugoslavia. During a recent television interview, Wexler offered
his legal prescription for dealing with the strongman.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ought to go in and get him, try him and hang him,'' said
Wexler.
</P>
<P>
   MAMA'S BOY
</P>
<P>
   In their effort to win support for bills, lawmakers often invoke
the names of powerful allies or celebrities to make their point.
Rep. Billy Tauzin, R-La., cited family ties as he called for
cutting taxes and fees on telephone service.
</P>
<P>
   Tauzin said many consumers are unhappy about the expanding
charges ``including my poor 80-year-old mama in Chackbay,'' Tauzin
said, referring to his mother's hometown. In case you missed the
point, Tauzin asked that his colleagues in Congress give this
``sweet old lady'' a break by going along with his bill.
</P>
<P>
   To give consumers a break, Tauzin's bill would slash a 3 percent
federal communications excise tax by two-thirds, a tax that he said
was first imposed by Congress in 1913 to help pay for World War I.
</P>
<P>
   ``If history serves me, that war is over and I think we won it,
but that tax remains,'' said Tauzin, who also wants to prevent the
Federal Communications Commission from imposing other new fees on
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   (Compiled from reports by Sean Loughlin and Carl Hulse in the
Washington Bureau of the New York Times Regional Newspaper Group)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
