<SLUG> BC-MASK-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BLACK MASK': NONSTOP ACTION, RIDICULOUS PLOT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anyone whose lips are exhausted from puzzling through the
nearest comic book can take a respite by eyeing ``Black Mask,'' one
of those dubbed action imports from Hong Kong that is long on
flying bodies, bullets and blood and short on credibility.
</P>
<P>
   The Educational Testing Service may want to winnow the
Harvard-bound from lesser college candidates by using the plot as
the basis for one of its soporific exercises in textual analysis.
But in brief form the story has something to do with Project 701, a
Chinese operation that created a commando force of biologically
enhanced humans, fearless and impervious to pain.
</P>
<P>
   When they got a bit out of hand, efforts were made to obliterate
them. One of their number, in the person of Jet Li, resurfaces in
Hong Kong as a peaceful librarian whose best friend, Rock (Lau
Ching Wan), happens to be a police detective.
</P>
<P>
   When Hong Kong's drug lords begin to meet death in vast, ghastly
numbers, the trail leads to the survivors of 701, led by the
Commander, who resembles a hybrid of Darth Vader, Dr. No and Yoko
Ono. It seems that the Commander and his men are in league with the
Colombian drug cartel in a deal intended to force the Chinese
government to give the survivors an antidote to a blood component
that will kill them all within a year.
</P>
<P>
   Quite a while passes before Rock realizes that the valorous
interloper in various shootouts is his pal, wearing a black eye
mask like Kato in the old ``Green Hornet.'' The resemblance does
not go unremarked. In its inane way, ``Black Mask'' packs enough
action to have nourished a couple of years' worth of yesteryear's
Saturday afternoon serials.
</P>
<P>
   Francoise Yip, as a deadly old friend from the 701 days, lends
glamour to the proceedings, and Karen Mok, as a love-hungry
librarian, furnishes a healthy dose of action comedy.
</P>
<P>
   With its shallow, time-worn characters, ``Black Mask'' doesn't
have anything on its mind besides action. It delivers that in
abundance for those whose tastes run to burned faces, severed
children's limbs and freshets of blood.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `BLACK MASK'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Daniel Lee; written by Tsui Hark, Teddy Chen and Joe
Ma; dubbed into English; director of photography, Cheung Tung
Leung; edited by Cheung Ka Tai; music by Teddy Robin and Ben
Vaughn; produced by Hark; released by Artisan Entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   With: Jet Li (Tsui), Karen Mok (Tracy), Lau Ching Wan (Rock) and
Francoise Yip (Yeuk-lan).
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 90 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Black Mask'' is rated R (under 17 requires accompanying parent
or adult guardian). It includes many forms of physical violence as
well as bondage, simulated sex and uninhibited language.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-14-99 1758EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
