<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-RUSSIANS-$ADV-16-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURTING THE RUSSIANS: 680,000 IMMIGRANT VOTERS BEING WOOED 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Sunday, May 16) 
 
By DEBORAH HORAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASHDOD, Israel _ As the clock winds down toward Israel's
elections, the candidates for prime minister are busily wooing
voters like Yevgeny Derimian, a 22-year-old immigrant from Russia.
</P>
<P>
   He arrived in the country six months ago and, like many Jews
from the former Soviet Union, still doesn't know which candidate to
support.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe Barak,'' he says with a shrug while enjoying the
afternoon at a cafe, referring to the opposition Labor Party
candidate Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
   ``People I know who know the situation, they say Barak is
better. But I'm not sure. I don't have enough information.''
</P>
<P>
   In the run-up to Monday's elections, Israeli candidates are
courting no group more fervently than the 680,000 voters from the
former Soviet Union, known here simply as ``the Russians.''
</P>
<P>
   New to Israel's rough-and-tumble politics and not yet set in
their political beliefs, they are the swing voters who political
analysts predict largely will decide who is the next prime
minister.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing has illustrated this better than the courtship of Natan
Sharansky, a former Soviet dissident who heads the Immigrants Party
and who has yet to throw his political weight behind any of the
five candidates competing for Israel's top job.
</P>
<P>
   Both Barak and Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, the two
front-runners, have bent over backward to woo him.
</P>
<P>
   Both men have said they are considering offering Sharansky the
coveted finance ministry post in the next government. Both have
announced plans for subsidizing Russian immigrants. Both have added
Russian subtitles to their television campaign commercials.
</P>
<P>
   Short, stocky and balding, Sharansky quipped recently that his
political suitors had ``finally understood that I'm a good-looking
man with a full head of curls.''
</P>
<P>
   But so far he has left it up to his followers to choose which
candidate best suits them.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, they overwhelmingly went for Netanyahu. Right-wing when
it comes to questions of peace with the Palestinians, most Russians
believed then that Netanyahu would succeed where Israel's left-wing
had failed on personal-security issues.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't always that way.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, they voted overwhelmingly for Labor because the party
was perceived as the best equipped to help them get settled in
their new land.
</P>
<P>
   This time around, polls indicate that Barak has succeeded in
persuading many to swing back and support a Labor candidate. When
the race for prime minister began this year, polls indicated that
Netanyahu had the support of 70 percent of the Russian vote, while
Barak had only 19 percent.
</P>
<P>
   By May 5, support for Netanyahu had plummeted to 55 percent, the
polls said, and Barak's popularity had skyrocketed to 40 percent.
In the week leading up to the election, those numbers held
constant.
</P>
<P>
   Much of that, say analysts, is because of the way Barak's staff
packaged the Labor leader. In campaign ads, they emphasized that he
is a classical pianist and former army chief of staff with a degree
in systems analysis from Stanford _ qualities most Russians
appreciate.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have published many materials portraying Barak as a
soldier of Israel, Barak as an intellectual,'' says Marina
Solodkin, a sociologist and Russian member of parliament who has
written a book called ``Civilization Discomfort: the Soviet Jewry
in Israel in the Last Ten Years.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that he plays the piano is important,'' she says.
``It makes him more human.''
</P>
<P>
   Polls indicate the decrease in Russian support for Netanyahu has
contributed to the lag behind Barak. If the Russian trend toward
Barak continues, Netanyahu may be in trouble _ even if he keeps a
slight majority of Russian voters in his camp, analysts predict.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Russian vote will be 55 percent for Netanyahu and 45
percent for Barak, then Barak will win,'' says Solodkin.
</P>
<P>
   But at least 15 percent, and maybe as much as 35 percent, of
these immigrants haven't yet made up their minds.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Netanyahu still appeals to many Russians who believe
that security should come first. And his right-wing emphasis on
Jewish heritage and nationalism resonates among immigrants who
traded a life in Russia for one in Israel for precisely those
reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``He talks about Jewish heritage,'' says Boris Yentin, editor of
Vesty, one of four Russian-language newspapers published in Israel.
``He is perceived as strong, as stable.''
</P>
<P>
   But Netanyahu seems to have lost points with Russian voters each
time a political ally deserted him, which has happened often during
his tumultuous three-year rule, usually after a nasty public round
of name-calling.
</P>
<P>
   Many Russians who will not vote for Netanyahu cite what they say
has been a string of lies from his lips.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't trust him,'' says Israel Lerner, a Russian from
Moldova who lives in a posh area north of Tel Aviv. ``He's
arrogant. When you see him he has a little smile in the corner of
his mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   And Barak, more than Netanyahu, seems to have capitalized on a
cultural rift that has pitted Russians, who are typically secular,
against the religious supporters of the ultra-Orthodox Shas Party.
</P>
<P>
   Under Netanyahu, Shas controlled the Interior Ministry _ a
portfolio the Russians' political leaders desperately want. The
ministry has kept many Russians from obtaining Israeli citizenship,
getting married here or bringing relatives to the country by
questioning their Jewishness.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli officials estimate that some 30 percent are not Jewish
according to Jewish law.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu's interior minister, Shas member Eli Suissa, accused
Russians of coveting the ministry because they know the Shas will
prevent ``counterfeiters, con men and call girls'' from staying in
Israel.
</P>
<P>
   During the campaign, the Immigrants Party ran TV commercials
that showed ordinary Russians demanding that Suissa apologize.
</P>
<P>
   Barak scored big among Russian voters, apparently without losing
others, when he hinted he would wrest the Interior Ministry away
from Shas.
</P>
<P>
   Because he favors forcing ultra-Orthodox Jews to serve in the
army, Shas voters are unlikely to vote for Barak anyway. Last week,
the party's spiritual council endorsed Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect that Shas may be a part of Netanyahu's next
government pushes Russian voters toward Barak, said Sharansky.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't want a government that is controlled by the
ultra-Orthodox,'' Sharansky said.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the Russians' immense political clout gained so soon
after their arrival has irked many Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   Some 900,000 Russians have immigrated to Israel since 1989, and
they have established their own subculture in this nation of 5.6
million people.
</P>
<P>
   In towns like Ashdod, 30 miles south of Tel Aviv, people line up
for Russian-language theaters, dine at restaurants that use
Russian-language menus and attend concerts by Russian musicians on
tour from Moscow and St. Petersburg.
</P>
<P>
   Many of Israel's Russians dislike what they consider the
simplistic political categories such as ``religious'' or
``secular'' that other Israelis tend to use to describe themselves.
They believe they are more politically sophisticated.
</P>
<P>
   Many say they don't have time to worry about politics because
they have everyday problems. Unemployment among Russians is higher
than the Israeli average and many others are underemployed or
working at menial jobs despite their higher educations.
</P>
<P>
   Derimian, the 22-year-old Russian who moved to Israel six months
ago, is in many ways typical of the Russian predicament. He studies
Hebrew at a communal farm in the Negev desert and supplements a
$325 monthly stipend for new refugees from the Jewish Agency by
working part time as a waiter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have my own problems,'' he says. ``Of course I think what
will happen in terms of politics, war or not war, is important.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I have more important things to think about than the
elections.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
