<HEADLINE>
(HLW)
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories that New York Times editors are planning
for the Page 1 of Saturday, May 15. The N.Y. Times News Service
supervisor is Henry Louis Warnken. The final FRONTPAGE will move
later in the evening.
</P>
<P>
   For copy info: (888) 346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   For graphics, map, photo info: (888) 603-1036.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ATTACK (Belgrade) _ More than 60 ethnic Albanians were
killed and another 60 badly injured late on Thursday night when
bombs blew apart a village in southwest Kosovo, near Prizren,
Yugoslav officials and journalists at the scene said. By Steven
Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-GUNS (Washington) _ By a squeaker of a vote, Senate
Republicans on Friday passed a measure to promote background checks
at gun shows. Democrats, preferring a more stringent proposal of
their own, almost solidly opposed the measure. By Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   EPA-POLLUTE (Washington) _ A federal appeals court on Friday set
aside new air quality standards issued by the Environmental
Protection Agency in 1997, handing the Clinton administration a
major environmental defeat. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   WELFARE-MILWAUKEE (Milwaukee) _ A decade ago, an eccentric band
of reformers here set out to guarantee every poor person a path
from poverty _ an assured job at a sufficient wage with child care
and health care. But as the program closes its offices this week,
an exhaustive volume of new research offers some disquieting
conclusions. Among the adults, only 27 percent managed to stick
with their subsidized jobs long enough to escape poverty. Their
average annual earnings were just $6,600. By Jason DeParle.
</P>
<P>
   ASSASSIN-GAME (Westport, Conn.) _ Beginning next week, 35 elite
college-bound students from Staples High School plan to arm
themselves with plastic guns with names like Lock `n' Load, Secret
Shot II, and Expand-a-Blast, then stalk classmates through town.
The students, who call the game Assassinations, have elaborate
plans for staying alive, and so expect the contest to last three
weeks. The final two survivors will shoot it out in a town park,
then collect cash prizes. Although life has not completely imitated
art in the students' game, some students have begun to worry about
the issue of real bullets. A handful of Staples students are bowing
out this year, deciding that four weeks after the killings in a
Colorado high school might not be the best time to lurk in bushes
and hide under cars in hopes of knocking off a target, even if it
is with a foam dart. By Mike Allen.
</P>
<P>
   HAWAII-TRUST (Honolulu) _ Developments concerning the Bishop
Estate. The estate, an institution of almost medieval power, was
long been a source of intense native pride, but in recent years it
had come to be seen as the embodiment of Hawaii's brand of inbred,
closed-door politics, as secretive and suspect as it was
impregnable. Most of the trustees were closely connected to the
state's ruling political establishment, so their dramatic ouster _
and the long fight that led up to it _ has led to predictions of a
shakeup in institutions from the Legislature to the state Supreme
Court, whose members used to select the Bishop trustees. By Todd S.
Purdum.
</P>
</TEXT>
