<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7659 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ASSASSIN-GAME-ART-2TA     05-14 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASSASSIN-GAME-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER LITTLETON, STUDENT GAMES MIMICKING VIOLENCE SPUR DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WESTPORT, Conn. _ Beginning next week, 35 elite college-bound
students from Staples High School plan to arm themselves with
plastic guns with names like Lock `n' Load, Secret Shot II and
Expand-a-Blast, then stalk classmates through town.
</P>
<P>
   The students, who call the game A.P. Assassination, have
elaborate plans for staying alive, and so expect the contest to
last three weeks. The final two survivors will shoot it out in a
town park, then collect cash prizes.
</P>
<P>
   The game and others like it have become a rite of spring at high
schools and colleges across the country, apparently inspired by a
1982 movie ``T.A.G.: The Assassination Game.'' In the film, college
students shoot each other with rubber darts, and it's all great fun
until one player begins using real bullets.
</P>
<P>
   Although life has not completely imitated art in the students'
game, some students have begun to worry about the issue of real
bullets in the aftermath of the bloodbath at a Colorado high school
in April. A handful of Staples students are bowing out this year,
deciding that four weeks after the Colorado shootings might not be
the best time to lurk in bushes and hide under cars in hopes of
knocking off a target, even if it is with a foam dart.
</P>
<P>
   The epidemic of bomb scares and copycat threats that followed
the Littleton killings has added to the tension over the toy-gun
sprees.
</P>
<P>
   At a parent-teacher meeting this week, principal Gloria Rakovic
urged parents to try to dissuade their seniors from participating.
``They're symbolically hurting each other, and we have seen that
the discrimination between what's real and what's not can get
fuzzy,'' she said. ``This is a teachable moment to talk to kids
about how their behavior is perceived by others, and whether they
care how people perceive them.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the games vary somewhat from school to school, the
basic elements are these: students draw names of classmates and
then try to shoot their prey without getting shot themselves.
</P>
<P>
   It's Secret Santa, with squirt guns and Nerf assault rifles.
Phony pizza deliveries, pre-dawn stakeouts and after-work ambushes
are all part of the game. Underclassmen sometimes serve as body
guards. Siblings are enlisted as lookouts.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the concerns about Littleton, Colo., the games are to go
on at many schools from California to Virginia, school officials
say. But in a number of cases, the students themselves have altered
or curtailed this year's edition out of a sense of duty and a
precocious instinct for public relations. At Staples, for instance,
a rebel group of seniors is boycotting the game and plans a
barbecue instead. For entertainment, there will be Capture the
Flag.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have 90 kids running around town with toy guns - not that I
wouldn't have fun doing it, but I can't make that sound right in my
head right now,'' said Alex Williams-Resnick, captain of the ski
team and president of the drama club. ``I've never had to deal with
having a gun pulled on me. I asked myself, Am I throwing it in
someone else's face? To do this in the name of fun, am I belittling
the actual violence that goes on in the world?''
</P>
<P>
   For authorities on violence who have argued that society can
stimulate violent outbursts by troubled young people, the
proliferation of assassination games _ and their continuation
despite the Colorado tragedy _ is alarming and even dangerous. Dr.
Robert Butterworth, a child psychologist in Los Angeles who studies
trauma, said he was astonished to hear of the practice, given the
current climate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do they wear trench coats?'' he asked. Butterworth said such
games could help desensitize students to violence. ``We're not
going to change the culture for these deviant kids, but we have to
be careful that we don't make it too easy for them to be ignited,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Many kids scoff at that idea. Jay Liner, a senior who is in the
third week of an assassination game at Northwest Catholic High
School in West Hartford, said it was patronizing to suggest that
18-year-olds cannot differentiate between a squirt gun and an Uzi.
``Nothing has changed from the week before Littleton,'' he said.
``I don't want to sound un-whatever, but that's the way I feel.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the changes being made to the games appear to be token
reactions, while others have been major. At Harvard University,
students called a 19-hour truce in an assassination game that ended
in a furious foam-dart shootout in the courtyard of Quincy House.
``Due to the extraordinary tragedy that occurred,'' organizers told
players in an e-mail message the night after the Littleton
shootings, ``we would ask that people don't carry guns tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   At Conard High School in West Hartford, students officially
changed the name of this year's game from ``Assassins'' to ``The
Game'' (after ``Water Wars'' and ``Soak'' were vetoed as too
corny). Like Westport's, the Conard game is not sanctioned by the
school and is completely run by students. The rules for the games
prohibit shootings on school grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Conard principal Chuck Landroche made a rare special
announcement over the public-address system to encourage students
to discontinue the game in light of Littleton, but to no avail.
</P>
<P>
   After a heated assembly at Sharon High School, about 30 miles
south of Boston, seniors canceled their squirt-gun Assassination
game and are thinking about holding a class cookout or taking a
trip to a water park. Students there admit that the game had been
getting out of hand, anyway. Michael Schindelar, the senior class
president, said that one year the game resulted in five car
accidents.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   And at the University of Nevada-Reno, students wore purple
ribbons in tribute to the fallen of Columbine High School during
``The Assassination Game,'' which this year was played not with the
usual squirt guns but with labels showing the university seal. The
students called it ``Sticker Tag.''
</P>
<P>
   Trenton Johnson, the senior class president, said that although
some students complained that ``we've become even more politically
correct, he believes that the campus will remain more wary of mock
violence and that the Assassination game is dead for good.
</P>
<P>
   One of this year's most furious debates over the game unfolded
this week here in Westport, a town of 25,000 built around the mouth
of the Saugatuck River, where stone mansions with ``Private
Residence'' signs are surrounded by bright boutiques and trendy
galleries that evoke a Yankee Aspen.
</P>
<P>
   In this haven for overachievers, even Assassination is
exclusive. By tradition at Staples, the town's lone public high
school, the game is played only by seniors who have taken
advanced-placement courses, which is college-level work offered in
high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``A.P. Assassination'' begins at midnight after the final
Advanced Placement examination and continues for several weeks _ a
chance for the top pupils, most of whom have already been admitted
to good colleges, to bond and blow off steam in the month left
until graduation.
</P>
<P>
   This year's Nerf war, which is to begin May 22, carries a $7
entry fee. The rules require that the guns fire ``non-spherical
objects,'' such as darts tipped with suction cups.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the game say they expect their protest cookout to
attract about 40 of the roughly 90 students who were eligible for
the game. Matt Cass, a senior, said students were concerned about
their image if they were seen popping out of bushes with toy guns.
But more than that, he said, ``We can see that violence is
society's problem, and not just an individual's problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Donald Cohen, a family therapist who hosts a radio program,
``Kids Are Talking,'' on the high school's station, said students
here have reacted very emotionally to the Colorado shootings, in
part because of the demographics of Littleton and Westport are
similarly upscale.
</P>
<P>
   But supporters of the game think the boycott barbecue represents
a ridiculous overreaction. ``We try to put a little intrigue into
it, but this is basically tag,'' said Dan Lascar, 18, who hopes to
become a physics professor. ``How long have people been playing
cowboys and Indians? If we choose to turn our lives completely
around and upside down because of the gunmen, they truly have
won.''
</P>
<P>
   Yearbook editor Alison Cooke, who organized this year's game,
said that although ``it can look, I guess, somewhat disturbing,
possibly,'' it is, in fact, ``a way to relax and get to know
people.''
</P>
<P>
   She quibbled with the numbers offered by opponents to the game
and said that only 10 people had dropped out after Littleton. But
catching the sociable spirit of the year, she said the assassins,
too, plan a cookout after just one of them is left standing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
