<HEADER>
A7670 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TESTDRIVE-SONATA15-CO     05-14 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TESTDRIVE-SONATA15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hyundai rolls out a new image
 &HT;    By Russ DeVault
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Although Korean automaker Hyundai has totally rebuilt
its Sonata, it's possible to argue that the front-drive sedan's
most appealing and striking features are the papers that come with
it. Here's why:
</P>
<P>
   _ The window sticker shows a base price of $15,799, which
includes air conditioning, a cassette-playing stereo, an automatic
transmission and power locks, windows and mirrors.
</P>
<P>
   _ A warranty good for five years/60,000 miles, bumper to bumper.
It covers the drivetrain for 10 years/100,000 miles and provides
unlimited-mileage roadside assistance for five years.
</P>
<P>
   There must be a catch, right? Well, it's this: Hyundai is trying
to overcome a shaky reputation acquired when the cars it imported
to the United States starting in 1988 proved to have
less-than-ideal reliability and quality.
</P>
<P>
   The monochromatic ``lime moss'' test car, a $15,799 base model
with 2.4-liter four-cylinder engine and four-speed automatic
transmission, seems proof that Hyundai has made progress in one of
its two problem areas. The quality seemed solid, with things inside
and out fitted nicely, although the Sonata can produce tinny
noises.
</P>
<P>
   But the reliability remains a question mark because both the
2.4-liter four-cylinder in the base car and the 170-horsepower,
2.5-liter V-6 engine in the $16,999 Sonata GLS are new.
</P>
<P>
   Some things, however, remain the same. The Sonata is noisy, with
its engine, suspension and the road all to blame. The ride is
totally acceptable most of the time, but the handling is awkward
and the acceleration sluggish for the 3,000-pounder.
</P>
<P>
   The interior _ in terms of space _ is a definite plus. While its
price says ``compact car,'' the numbers and feel declare it's a
midsize sedan. Total length is 185.4 inches _ nearly 16 feet _ and
the new Sonata is about 2 inches wider this year for a total width
of 71.6 inches.
</P>
<P>
   The rounded body and cabin provide family-size room with 39.3
inches of front headroom and 43.3 inches of legroom. Can't stretch
out as much in the rear, though, because legroom drops to 36.2
inches and headroom to 37.6 inches.
</P>
<P>
   Like its predecessors, this Sonata is big on plastic. There's
lots of it _ oodles, if not acres _ surrounding the occupants, and
it's not particularly pretty. The patterned cloth seats, though,
are OK visually and physically, with good adjustments and a form
that encourages an upright driving position.
</P>
<P>
   The center console has storage and a handy lidded two-drink
holder. Controls are basic and simple, with the only real irritant
a console-mounted shifter that seemed determined to slide past
``D'' to ``3'' every time it was pulled into gear. Be inattentive,
and it's possible to drive for a while in third gear (makes for
better expressway performance, however).
</P>
<P>
   The conclusion is that while notably improved and attractive on
paper, the Sonata hasn't caught the targeted Camrys, Accords,
Malibus and other midsize cars. But what used to be a Grand
Canyon-ish gulf is now a gap that's closable.
</P>
<P>
   Test vehicle: 1999 Hyundai Sonata front-drive sedan
</P>
<P>
   Price as tested: $17,052 (base: $15,799)
</P>
<P>
   Safety features: dual front and side air bags, side-impact
beams, height-adjustable front shoulder belts
</P>
<P>
   Powertrain: 2.4-liter four-cylinder engine with 16 valves (149
horsepower), four-speed automatic overdrive transmission with
winter and power shift modes
</P>
<P>
   Options on test vehicle: package with cruise control, 120-watt
stereo with CD player, power moonroof, $1,175; carpeted floor mats,
$78
</P>
<P>
   EPA figures: 21 mpg regular unleaded city, 28 mpg highway
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
