<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-DIARY-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON SURVEYS, RESEARCH AND NEW PRODUCTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, May 16)  
 (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Comparing Old and New In Electronic Publishing
</P>
<P>
   Exercises in valuing Internet-based businesses by traditional
means can end in snapped pencils and thrown-up hands. New
companies, new business models, no profits, no track record, no
equivalent firm for comparison: the litany usually leads back to
``it's worth whatever people will pay for it.''
</P>
<P>
   But not every Internet company is operating in uncharted
terrain. The Net stock enthusiasts who greeted its offering last
week may not like being told so, but TheStreet.com is in just about
the same business as Dow Jones &AMP; Co., or at least its
electronic-publishing wing.
</P>
<P>
   Consider that each operates a financial-information Web site
with original journalistic content; each site generates revenue by
selling advertising and charging users a subscription fee for
access to the best stuff.
</P>
<P>
   So, stacked up against Dow Jones and its electronic publishing
operation (which also includes the Dow Jones Newswires and some
other data services), how does TheStreet.com (in which The New York
Times Co. owns a minority stake) compare?
</P>
<P>
   Taken just as an Internet play, the whole of Dow Jones is more
attractively priced _ and you get The Wall Street Journal for
free. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ PATRICK J. LYONS
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
