<SLUG> BC-BIZ-DIARY-PERSONAL-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON PERSONAL BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, May 16)  
 (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Temptation, Temptation at Auction Houses
</P>
<P>
   Auction houses _ especially their wine departments _ are
outdoing Las Vegas casinos in coddling customers.
</P>
<P>
   To stir interest in its wine sale on Saturday, Sotheby's is
offering a chance to taste some of the best offerings on Friday
night. Similarly, its rival, Christie's, held a dinner at its new
Rockefeller Center quarters the night before its May 6 and 7 wine
sales; according to one executive, the dinner cost about $50,000,
or more than $700 for each of 68 guests.
</P>
<P>
   For Christie's, Charlie Trotter _ the Chicago chef who says ``we
fire customers'' unworthy of dining at the restaurant that bears
his name _ flew in with dozens of assistants. Sellers including
William I. Koch, of the Wichita, Kan., family that owns Koch
Industries, provided the sort of wines usually considered too
costly for anything but auctioning.
</P>
<P>
   As he swirled and sniffed the 1970 Chateau Latour, Christopher
S. Burr, director of the Christie's wine department, said, ``We're
just bringing together willing buyers and willing sellers.''
Bidders, expected to spend about $2.9 million at the sales, offered
$3.4 million instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously,'' Burr said later of the dinner, ``it had some
effect.'' Now other Christie's departments want his help in
entertaining their own bidders.
</P>
<P>
   _ ALLEN MYERSON
</P>
<P>
   That Take-Charge Style
</P>
<P>
   The oppressed secretaries in the movie ``9 to 5'' took the sharp
edges off their autocratic workplace by tying up their
fire-breathing male boss and putting their womanly instincts in
charge. But despite the popular image of women as collegial and
democratic at work, the real-life Boss Who Rules may more likely be
a woman than a man.
</P>
<P>
   Management Research Group, a career planning and consulting firm
in Portland, Maine, asked bosses, peers and subordinates to rate
900 men and 900 women as managers. Robert I. Kabacoff, the
company's director of research, said the results showed that ``men
are more inclined to delegate tasks to others and cooperate with
colleagues'' and that women ``come across as more assertive and
competitive in achieving their goals, while maintaining more
control of their projects.''
</P>
<P>
   Respondents said that men had greater business skills but that
women excelled at people skills like willingness to listen.
</P>
<P>
   If the people who take the orders are correct, democratic habits
may not be so important anyway. Asked who makes the best leader
overall, bosses found the sexes equal, but subordinates and peers
rated women slightly higher. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ SUSAN J. WELLS
</P>
</TEXT>
