<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMARTGIVING-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATAGONIA: WEDDED TO ITS MORAL IMPERATIVES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ANDREA ADELSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FALLEN LEAF LAKE, Calif. _ Here amid the snow-covered pines near
Lake Tahoe, Patagonia Inc. held its fourth annual weekend training
conference last month. In what one participant called a ``summer
camp for tree-huggers,'' community organizers in various
environmental causes came from far and wide to learn how to be more
effective.
</P>
<P>
   David Olsen, chief executive of Patagonia, the trendsetter in
specialty outdoor clothing, told the 70 or so participants, ``We've
invited you here because we want you to raise hell and we support
you in raising hell.''
</P>
<P>
   Known for elegantly simple product design, Patagonia, based in
Ventura, Calif., has long practiced environmental responsibility
quietly, converting its buildings to wind power, eliminating toxic
dyes from its products and making baby clothes from fabric scraps
left over from the adult line. But now the privately-held company's
owners have renounced that reticence. It's their business, and
they've decided to use it as their soapbox, as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came out of the closet,'' said Yvon Chouinard, Patagonia's
president and co-founder.
</P>
<P>
   The company's spring catalog, mailed to 725,000 people
worldwide, takes a stand on an issue way beyond the clothing realm:
removal of dams in five areas around the country, including the
Snake River of Washington. All six of its board members recently
demonstrated to save an ancient redwood forest in Northern
California.
</P>
<P>
   In short, Patagonia is risking its brand name and reputation on
an unusual brand of corporate philanthropy. Rather than just
writing checks to local charities, it is training activists and
taking bold positions.
</P>
<P>
   That can alienate customers, of course. Patagonia's latest
crusade was criticized as a ``biased and misleading diatribe'' by
Francois X. Forgette, an official of the Tri-City Area Chamber of
Commerce in Kennewick, Wash., which could suffer economically if
four dams on the lower Snake River were razed. Forgette called for
a boycott of Patagonia and suggested that the company ``stick to
its knitting.''
</P>
<P>
   Chouinard says it is. He considers environmentalism a
fundamental part of the company's image, and when he saw that
reputation shifting toward rivals, he decided to increase company
efforts. This comes even as some of Patagonia's early innovations,
like spinning fleece from recycled soda bottles, are being
jettisoned by others that had copied them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless Patagonia gets out there and talks about it, they won't
be an exemplar,'' said Chris L. Desser, a Patagonia board member
and a recent appointee to the California agency that regulates
coastal development. ``Most companies are wholly driven by the
bottom line, but Patagonia is not going to sacrifice the
environment for the bottom line.''
</P>
<P>
   Although environmental good deeds would seem to burnish a
company's image with many potential customers, donations to
environmental causes may not rank very high. Among foundations,
grants to such causes make up just 2 percent of all financing,
according to the Foundation Center.
</P>
<P>
   There was considerable soul-searching among Patagonia's managers
over whether the company should seek to use its environmental ethic
as a corporate guide, Chouinard said. ``We don't want to be accused
of green marketing'' _ trying to profit from the appearance of
doing the right thing _ Chouinard said. But a big change swept in a
year ago, after Patagonia commissioned its first customer survey.
Executives were appalled to find Patagonia was seen as dead last
among outdoor companies considered environmental leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the company's environmentalism may not be helping. The
privately held company had sales of $165 million in the fiscal year
ended April 1998. It does not report profits, but there are signs
that they have been flat. The company donates 1 percent of revenue,
or 10 percent of pretax profits, whichever is higher, to local
environmental groups, and that figure has held steady at about $1.2
million for the last three years. The company may also have been
hurt because it failed to capitalize on two popular sports, indoor
rock climbing and snowboarding.
</P>
<P>
   But Olsen, Patagonia's chief, is unconcerned. ``A lot of
environmental things we're going to do whether they give us a
benefit in the market or not,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One thing the company is committed to is the ``tree hugger''
camps. The youthful local organizers paid their own way to the
three-day event, which cost Patagonia about $60,000. Seasoned
organizers shared secrets of fund-raising, marketing and building
membership. Their environmental causes ranged from buffalo herds to
logging.
</P>
<P>
   Patagonia suppliers are also subject to environmental
evangelism, pressed by the company to show ecological gains or risk
losing Patagonia's business.
</P>
<P>
   The idea has met with some resistance from suppliers who
``thought it wasn't a level playing field,'' said Rob C. Koeppel,
vice president of Shawmut Mills, a division of R.H. Wyner
Associates, a maker of laminated fabrics. He said offshore
suppliers could more easily show environmental progress because of
lower standards.
</P>
<P>
   A private company, though, can afford to pursue moral
imperatives since it need not cater to shareholders, an argument
Chouinard said he's heard numerous times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm absolutely convinced everything we do does benefit the
company,'' Chouinard said, before leaving for mountain climbing in
Tibet. ``Most companies give money to the symphony. It's safe. When
other companies see nothing bad comes of it,'' he said of
Patagonia's advocacy, ``they'll be emboldened. It's not going to
come back to bite us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
