<DOCNO> NYT19990514.0291 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 18:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7715 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LYNN-MUSIC-REVIEW-ART     05-14 0635
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYNN-MUSIC-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LORETTA LYNN CONCERT REVIEW: WHEN COUNTRY SANG TO JUST PLAIN
FOLKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By JON PARELES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Loretta Lynn's concert Thursday night at Town Hall,
her first show here in more than a decade, was a reminder of what
country music was like before it embraced video clips, smoke bombs,
power chords and line dancing. It was a homey concert: part shtick,
part spontaneity, trusting in personality rather than spectacle.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lynn chatted with the audience, and she built her set from
whims and requests. ``Anything you want me to sing,'' she
announced. ``Just tell me the first line.''
</P>
<P>
   From the late 1960s through the '70s, Ms. Lynn was a queen of
country music. With her Kentucky drawl, her tightly wound vibrato
and a way of letting a dramatic crescendo leap out of lines that
start casually, Ms. Lynn sang above all about not being taken for
granted.
</P>
<P>
   Her songs, including many that she wrote, were about fighting
for her man and about a neglected woman's temptation to stray; she
demanded respect in songs like ``Don't Come Home a-Drinkin' (With
Lovin' on Your Mind).'' And when ``women's lib'' arrived, she
hitched her inborn feistiness to a broader social current. ``Time
to change and I'm demanding satisfaction, too,'' she declared in
``We've Come a Long Way Baby.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lynn quickly sized up the audience, which was calling for
songs like ``Fist City'' and ``You Ain't Woman Enough.'' This
wasn't a crowd that wanted homilies about true love. Ms. Lynn
followed ``One's on the Way,'' about a pregnant housewife watching
big-city glitter from afar, with ``The Pill,'' about ``tearing down
your brooder house.'' She sang ``Red, White and Blue,'' about a
scorned half-Indian ``half-breed,'' and ``Your Squaw's on the
Warpath,'' about a wife who was fed up.
</P>
<P>
   Not all men were bad in her songs; there was always her father,
celebrated in ``Coal Miner's Daughter.'' And she sang about a
woman's loneliness in ``Somebody Somewhere,'' ``Blue Kentucky
Girl'' and ``When the Tingle Becomes a Chill.'' In her first hit,
``I'm a Honky-Tonk Girl,'' lines like ``I've lost everything in the
world'' sounded utterly bereft, ringing with the sound of a woman
whose broken heart had led her into a hopeless downward spiral.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lynn's voice is still strong; it's less girlish than it is
on her old recordings, yet rich with wounded longing. Her band, the
Coal Miners, seemed ready to cruise through any song in her
repertory; it played with the restrained aplomb of Nashville,
Tenn., professionals.
</P>
<P>
   Between songs Ms. Lynn explained that she was off the road for
five years during her husband's long final illness, but has been
working on a new album. She tried some cornball banter with her son
Ernest Ray. And like the character based on her in Robert Altman's
``Nashville,'' she rambled, taking on subjects like her Las Vegas
years and Sinead O'Connor's shaven head. From an era when country
prided itself on being regular folks' music, Ms. Lynn didn't put on
airs; she just let her songs tell their stories of pride and
desire.
</P>
<P>
   Opening the concert was Brad Paisley, a 26-year-old songwriter,
singer and skillful lead guitarist who shows the smarter, less
bombastic side of current Nashville. His specialty is spurned-lover
songs, from the singles-bar rejection of ``Me Neither'' to the
stalker mentality of ``It Never Would've Worked Out Anyway'' to his
self-pitying hit ``Who Needs Pictures.'' Even his inevitable
soft-rock ballad, ``He Didn't Have to Be,'' had a modern twist: it
was a thank-you song from a single mother's son to his stepfather.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-14-99 1847EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
