<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times plans 2 pages of stories, photos and graphics
on the continuing Kosovo crisis:
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ATTACK (Belgrade) _ More than 60 ethnic Albanians were
killed and scores more badly wounded late Thursday night when bombs
blew apart a village in southwest Kosovo, near Prizren, Yugoslav
officials and journalists at the scene said. No definitive word is
yet available who is responsible. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILITARY (Washington) _ Accounts from the Pentagon and
NATO headquarters of the what happened in Prizren, and other
military activity. By Elizabeth Becker.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATIONS (United Nations) _ China threatens to block all
Security Council action unless a resolution deploring the bombing
of its embassy in Belgrade is approved. By Judith Miller.
</P>
<P>
   (Eds, story will be late.)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-DIPLO (Washington) _ Russia and NATO still differ on key
issues for a peace settlement in Kosovo, but Strobe Talbott, the
deputy secretary of state, and the Russian envoy on the Balkans,
Viktor S. Chernomyrdin, agreed this week on some ways to approach
the Yugoslav leader, Slobodan Milosevic, the State Department said
Friday. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-U.S. (Washington) _ A full week after the NATO bombing of
the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade, President Clinton was finally able
to express his condolences directly to Chinese leaders today in a
telephone call that also touched briefly on Chinese efforts to gain
entry to the World Trade Organization. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MRSCLINTON (Skopje, Macedonia) _ Developments on Mrs.
Clinton's visit: She spent the morning addressing the suffering of
the refugees, and the rest of the day trying to defuse any
anti-American sentiment and to bolster Macedonia's fragile
coalition government, a mix of Macedonian and Albanian parties. By
David Rohde.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-INTERNET (Belgrade) _ Internet enthusiasts were rushing
to send off last minute e-mails at one downtown Internet cafe
today, after word went around that the United States was going to
cut off Yugoslavia off from the world wide web. The net remains the
only means of communication for many in Serbia, and apart from the
short wave radio, provides the only access to independent news in
the country. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEE-CABS (Skopje, Macedonia) _ For enough cash,
ethnic Serb cab drivers in Macedonia will cross into Kosovo and
bring ethnic Albanians out. By David Rohde.
</P>
