<HEADLINE>
CLINTON EXPRESSES `SINCERE REGRETS' TO CHINESE PRESIDENT OVER
BOMBING 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Seeking to mend damaged relations with China,
President Clinton expressed his ``sincere regrets'' Friday to
President Jiang Zemin for the accidental U.S. bombing of the
Chinese Embassy in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang finally accepted a telephone call from Clinton after a
week of refusing to speak to the president. The mistake, made
because intelligence officials used an outdated map, sparked four
days of rock-throwing protests outside the U.S. Embassy in Beijing
in orchestrated demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president once again expressed his sincere regrets and
condolences to President Jiang and the Chinese people concerning
the tragic accident of last week. The president expressed his
desire that we move beyond this tragic accident in our
relationship,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   Relations between the United States and China became strained
when a B-2 Stealth bomber fired three missiles into the Chinese
Embassy on May 7, killing three Chinese journalists and injuring 20
people. The CIA used an old map that failed to identify the
three-year-old embassy.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Jiang took the opportunity to express his views. I
will, obviously, leave it to him to do that,'' Lockhart said,
declining to review Jiang's comments.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart termed the conversation ``constructive.'' The two also
briefly discussed the status of China's request to join the World
Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands of furious Chinese, throwing rocks and paint,
pelted the U.S. embassy this week, trapping U.S. Ambassador James
Sasser, two aides and eight Marine guards inside the compound.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese government repeatedly suggested the bombing of their
embassy was intentional and demanded an investigation by the United
States. The Chinese government also delayed reports of apologies
from the United States and the North Atlantic Treaty Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton on Sunday sent a private letter to Jiang to apologize
for the incident and requested a telephone conversation. Clinton
met with the Chinese Ambassador Li Zhaoxing on Thursday. Li brought
a condolence book for Clinton to sign and told Clinton Jiang would
accept a telephone call.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
