<HEADER>
A7728 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-$ADV16-B     05-14 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-$ADV16-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MITCHELL DESERVES A SHOT AT SOMETHING BIG 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, May 16, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Maine _ In ten months or less, we'll almost certainly
know who'll be the Democrats' next presidential nominee, and very
likely have the GOP nominee in our sights.
</P>
<P>
   The frontloading of delegate-selection and the vast cost of
mounting TV ad campaigns will slaughter or starve all but the most
robust of candidacies. To remain viable, Bill Bradley, the lone
Democrat challenging Vice President Al Gore, will probably have to
win either the Iowa caucuses or New Hampshire's early-February
primary.
</P>
<P>
   Because if the former New Jersey senator _ a sort of taller Paul
Tsongas with a hook shot, with his pro-business, anti-interest
group politics _ cannot win somewhere early, he probably cannot win
anywhere. Then his money evaporates. Gore, so well-heeled an
incumbent VP, so bolstered by unions and Democratic party interest
groups, can survive an early loss or two; Bradley cannot.
</P>
<P>
   On the 11-candidate GOP side, Texas Governor George Bush is as
lopsided an early favorite as Gore, but questions will be raised
about his mettle and staying power until he wins some big-state
primaries and puts the crowded field behind him. But if you had to
pick the likely nominees now, you'd have to say Gore and Bush. So:
who runs with them?
</P>
<P>
   Beyond having suggested previously that Mrs. Elizabeth Dole has
more of a political future as someone else's running mate than she
does as a 62-year old first-time candidate in a party that hasn't
nominated a rookie for the top spot since Eisenhower in '52,
there's no way to get a handle on the GOP second spot.
</P>
<P>
   But I do have a notion for either Gore or Bradley. And that is
to go beyond the traditional ticket-balancing act that tries to
split the difference within your own party's competing interest
groups. There are the traditional yardsticks _ number of electoral
votes in the running mate's home state, acceptance to broad swaths
of the electorate, past positions that do not alienate deep pools
of independent or swing voters, and compatability with the top dog,
and, increasingly important, with the Top Dog's spouse.
</P>
<P>
   It is certainly conceivable that Gore could wind up offering the
No. 2 spot to Bradley, particularly if Bradley departs on a high
note after a gentlemanly campaign of lofty issue-oriented debate
without snotty asides or savage TV spots. But if either Gore or
Bradley cannot stand the other after their mano-a-mano primary
bout, the victor would do well to consider:
</P>
<P>
   George Mitchell of Maine. The former Senate Majority Leader
comes from the wrong end of the electoral vote scale; Maine has but
4, to 54 for the colossus of the west, California, whose senior
senator, Diane Feinstein, is lobbying hard for consideration.
</P>
<P>
   But having raised that, Mitchell has few negatives, and a
hatfull of positives. First and foremost, he is an experienced and
reassuring figure, known to everyone in politics at the national
level, and generally admired by all but the most embittered
Republican insiders, who still blame him for forcing President
George (``Read my lips!'') Bush to raise taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell's role in brokering three years of peace talks in
Northern Ireland put him on the world stage, in Nobel Peace Prize
territory. Mitchell is broadly acceptable to virtually all
Democrats and most independents _ and not a few Republican voters.
The journalism community, save the usual right-wing suspects, has
high regard for his probity and judgment. His moral character is
unquestioned. He's divorced and remarried, with a young son, but
without any hint of tarnish.
</P>
<P>
   Since he has an affiliation with a Maine law firm where one of
my brothers is a partner, I won't rattle on about his career after
15 years in the Senate. But there is one more thing to say before
this letter of recommendation goes into the data base: Mitchell
knows how to run for vice president. He's been there. In 1968, a
disastrous campaign year for Democrats, Mitchell was a young lawyer
who carried the issues briefcase for Edmund Muskie, his political
mentor, a former Senator and later Secretary of State to Jimmy
Carter.
</P>
<P>
   Muskie was Hubert Humphrey's sane and sensible choice for
running mate in the year LBJ resigned, Bobby Kennedy died, Gene
McCarthy flamed out and Nixon won. Paired against Spiro Agnew, the
godfather to Pat Buchanan and William Safire, among others, Muskie
beat the bushes, hitting all the secondary cities that are the
obligatory stops of running mates.
</P>
<P>
   Coaching his man in hotel rooms and on plane and bus rides,
Mitchell barnstormed the nation in a manner known only to national
political candidates and old-line vaudevillians.
</P>
<P>
   I covered that campaign for the Associated Press, as Mitchell
discovered firsthand how a Maine accent, some Down Home jokes, wry
self-deprecation, and a shrewd assessment of the local political
winds can make for a savvy and successful campaign as running mate.
Gore or Bradley could do a lot worse.
</P>
<P>
   When Mitchell spoke here at the Portland Library recently about
his new book on the Irish peace process, he assured the crowd that
after 15 years in the Senate, ``I can speak at any length, on
almost any topic,'' but the ensuing laughter does not erase the
fact that at the level of running for national office, the ability
to project intelligent and articulate political rhetoric is a
godsend.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Quayle didn't have it; Jack Kemp barely managed it;
Geraldine Ferraro never mastered the art. Spiro Agnew was never an
asset. Running mates can't win you many votes, but they can lose
you a ton. When I mentioned to a leading Democratic congressional
figure the possibility of a Mitchell-for-Vice President gambit, he
said: ``I've heard people in Washington talking about George as a
possible Secretary of State.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the right kind of neighborhood from which to pluck a
running mate.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
