<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 19:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7729 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV16-B     05-14 1211
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV16-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE BIG WAVE, COME AND GONE? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, May 16, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the Internet mania in full bloom, stock markets hitting
record levels, and the economic expansion in its ninth year, there
is a lot of talk of a ``new economy.'' Nor is it only talk. Last
week the US economy posted its second consecutive quarterly
productivity gain of 4 percent _ highly welcome after a couple of
decades of much slower growth, and virtually unprecedented for so
late in a business cycle. No wonder central bankers are worriedly
wondering whether the rules of sound monetary policy have changed.
</P>
<P>
   All eyes are on Alan Greenspan.
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, the Federal Reserve Board chairman as much as told
an audience of bankers in Chicago earlier this month that he
thought the rules (itals)had(unitals) changed, somewhat. The Fed's
forecasts of inflation and growth in business activity had been
``generaly off'' in recent years, said Greenspan, inflation on the
high side, growth on the low, apparently because of increasing
efficiency throughout the economy.
</P>
<P>
   The unexpected productivity growth ``reflects _ at least in part
_ a more deep-seated, still-developing shift in our economic
landscape,'' said Greenspan. The rest of the speech is a
fascinating review of the evidence _ ``compelling, if not
conclusive,'' according to the chairman _ ``for a technology-driven
rise in the prospective rate of return on new capital and an
associated acceleration in labor productivity.'
</P>
<P>
   No central banker likes to be understood to say ``it's different
this time'' _ especially one who barely two years ago counselled
against the ``irrational exuberance'' in the markets, when the Dow
was at 6500. So two weeks before his Chicago speech, Greenspan
summoned a couple dozen of the nation's top productivity experts to
Washington to air the issue before the Board of Governors of the
Fed. A lively exchange of views was the result.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad that the expert he most needed to hear wasn't there _
and that the most provocative overview of the productivity puzzle
in a decade wasn't on the Fed's great table.
</P>
<P>
   Robert J. Gordon, professor of economics at Nortwestern
University, is a leading authority on macroeconomics and quality
change _ an expert on, among other things, teasing out of the
Sears, Roebuck catalog over the years fascinating insights into
nature of economic change.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Gordon has been doodling a hand-drawn chart on
whatever page came to hand to make the argument that increased
productivity percolated through the US economy in ``one big wave,''
starting in the first years of the 20th century and petering out at
the end of the 1960s. In a pair of papers written last year,
summarized in a short article in the May issue of the American
Economic Review, Gordon has written down the argument and
illustrated it with a new appeal to the data.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have to explain,'' says Gordon, ``is not why
productivity growth has been slow over the last 25 years, but why
it was so fast between 1915 and 1965.'' The answer, he thinks, is
that there was a ``golden age'' of growth in those years, in
contrast to a slower, more normal situation before and since.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Gordon believes the inventions of the late 19th and early
20th century were ``more fundamental creators of productivity''
than are the devices of the electronic-Internet era.
</P>
<P>
   He classifies these inventions in four clusters, or possibly
five, following his Northwestern colleague Joel Mokyr's argument
that the public health movement (sanitation, vaccination,
cleanliness) had far-reaching economic effects. Gordon also cites
the development of:
</P>
<P>
   _ Electricity (including electric motors, electric light,
consumer appliances);
</P>
<P>
   _ Internal combustion engines (motor transport, air transport,
superhighways, supermarkets, suburbs);
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Rearranging molecules'' (petrochemicals, plastics,
pharmaceuticals);
</P>
<P>
   _ Communications/entertainment (telephone, radio, movies,
television).
</P>
<P>
   Applications of each of these four innovations had the effect of
greatly increasing human capacity to do work, Gordon says. In
contrast, computers so far have failed to have comparable impact
because computers have to interact with human beings. Human beings
are bottlenecks.
</P>
<P>
   For example, there is an increasing mismatch between the
clockspeed of computers and the finger speed of operators who use
them to write documents and create spreadsheets, says Gordon. More
bandwith doesn't mean faster thought. Moreover, he says, they
haven't built the cpmputer yet that can replace a human at any
number of demanding tasks: surgeon, pilot, truck driver,
small-scale assembly of manufactured items.
</P>
<P>
   Much of what we are seeing now is ``second-order'' innovation,
according to Gordon: the VCR, for example, which combines movies
with television but doesn't have the fundamental impact of either
invention. ``Enthusiasts of the Internet might consider that the
computer has not created the paperless society but rather a
duplication of electronic activities, all of which generate paper..
. .''
</P>
<P>
   For most of the '90s, the reigning interpretation of the
expected contribution of information technology has been that of
Oxford University economist Paul David's 1990 paper, ``The Computer
and the Dynamo.'' That extended analogy between the introduction of
electricity and present-day computing argued that a delayed impact
on productivity was to be expected, since while electricity was
widely introduced in the 1880s, it wasn't until the 1920s that
business managers figured out how to effectively harness the new
power with small motors.
</P>
<P>
   It is against that interpretation that Gordon's ``one big wave''
hypothesis will be set. Eventually, new models of ``general purpose
technologies'' developed by economists bent on measuring growth and
``creative destruction'' will help sort out the issues. Most
analysts in the meantime will prefer to work on various
microeconomic issues.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Greenspan has a problem _ rein in the economy or let
it go, in the hope that the next two years will be like the last?
If they are not _ if it turns out that low inflation has less to do
with technological change than it does with widespread belief in
Greenspan's mastery _ then the Fed chairman could make a costly
mistake by buying into the productivity acceleration tale. A couple
of quarters of gains in an ill-understood statistic don't mean much
by themselves.
</P>
<P>
   There are those who believe the Fed has begun to prepare the the
banking structure for tighter money in the fall. Spencer England, a
Boston-based investment strategist, is among them. It's beginning
to feel like 1987, says England.
</P>
<P>
   In the three months preceding the 1987 crash, the market surged
15 percent despite sharply deteriorating liquidity, England notes.
Unlike 1987, wage growth today is moderate, the dollar strong and
the Fed is talking about ``the current wave of technology.'' Then
again, it wouldn't be the first time the Fed said one thing and did
another.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
