<HEADLINE>
MRS. CLINTON VISITS KOSOVO REFUGEES IN MACEDONIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SKOPJE, Macedonia _ Hillary Rodham Clinton swept through
Macedonia on Friday on a visit that illustrated the Clinton
administration's continuing struggle to balance the diverse strands
of its Kosovo policy.
</P>
<P>
   In a refugee camp appearance so carefully scripted that
administration officials chose which refugees Mrs. Clinton would
speak with, the first lady commiserated with Kosovo's expelled
masses. After hearing refugees' accounts of their flight from
Kosovo, she said their plight reminded her of movie depictions of
the Holocaust like ``Schindler's List.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not intend to let the evil Milosevic has perpetrated
against these people keep them away from their homeland and
homes,'' Mrs. Clinton said. ``That is a fundamental goal of the
United States and its allies.''
</P>
<P>
   While expressing sympathy for the refugees, however, Mrs.
Clinton went out of her way to avoid offending Macedonian
sensibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Ethnic Macedonians, who make up roughly two-thirds of this
country's population, generally oppose NATO's bombing of
Yugoslavia. They also fear that if ethnic Albanians _ who made up
roughly one third of Macedonia's population before the crisis _
continue to pour in from Kosovo, Macedonians will be reduced to a
minority in their own country.
</P>
<P>
   So although Mrs. Clinton spent the morning addressing the
suffering of the refugees, she spent the rest of the day trying to
defuse any anti-American sentiment and to bolster Macedonia's
fragile coalition government, a mix of Macedonian and Albanian
parties.
</P>
<P>
   She toured a 16th-century church containing the tomb of Goce
Delchev, the father of Macedonian independence, and met with
President Kiro Gligorov and Prime Minister Ljubco Georgievski.
Although human rights groups have criticized the Macedonian
government for at times blocking Kosovo Albanians from entering its
territory and other callous treatment of refugees, Mrs. Clinton
praised Macedonia for its generosity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important for people in my country and elsewhere to put
themselves in the position of the refugees,'' she said, sounding a
theme she repeated throughout the day, ``but also in the position
of the Macedonian people, who have responded as they have in the
last weeks. I'm very grateful to them as well.''
</P>
<P>
   But for both Macedonians and Albanians, the essential issue
remains when the roughly 200,000 refugees here might return to
Kosovo. When a refugee pressed this issue with Mrs. Clinton on
Friday morning, her answer was both reassuring and vague.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying very hard to permit you to return to your homes
in safety,'' she said. ``That's what my husband, the United States
government and the NATO allies are trying to accomplish.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
