<HEADER>
A7735 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WELFARE-MILWAUKEE-ART     05-14 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WELFARE-MILWAUKEE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUARANTEED-JOB EXPERIMENT YIELDS EVIDENCE OF THE ENDURING NATURE OF
POVERTY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(rm) 
 By JASON DePARLE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ Imagine what would happen if society could guarantee
every poor person a path from poverty: an assured job at a
sufficient wage with child care and health care as well. How many
would take it? How many would prosper?
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago, an eccentric band of reformers here set out to
find the answer, and their discoveries offer an unsettling new look
at the prospects of low-income families at a time of a vast
national exodus from welfare.
</P>
<P>
   The Milwaukee experiment with guaranteed jobs, called Project
New Hope, came to its scheduled close this week. It leaves behind
the most comprehensive study of poor families of the post-welfare
age, with data on everything from parents' earnings to the number
of hours their children watch television.
</P>
<P>
   The program is widely being called a success, and it did have a
modest impact in some statistical terms. But a close look at the
findings, assembled by an independent team of economists,
psychologists and ethnographers, suggests that inner-city poverty
may be even harder to alleviate than is generally understood.
</P>
<P>
   New Hope recruited 677 low-income adults and made them a simple
offer: sign up here, work 30 hours a week and your family will no
longer be poor.
</P>
<P>
   But only 27 percent of the main target group stuck with their
jobs long enough to work their way out of poverty. Their average
annual earnings were just $6,600, statistically no better than a
control group of poor people not in the program.
</P>
<P>
   And despite the conventional view that going to work makes
low-income adults feel better about themselves, New Hope
participants showed no declines in depression and no growth in
self-esteem, when compared with a control group.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, even after two years in the program, the average
participant still registered levels of depression above the
threshold that most psychologists consider cause for clinical
referrals.
</P>
<P>
   The problems that kept people from maintaining steady employment
comprise a catalog of inner-city ills: drug and alcohol abuse;
jealous or violent boyfriends and husbands; conflicts with
employers; unreliable baby sitters and cars, and generally flagging
spirits. In addition, some participants said they preferred to work
less and spend more time with their families, even if it meant
staying poor.
</P>
<P>
   New Hope's admirers acknowledge the persistence of low earnings
and high poverty rates. But they say the program still shows ways
to help low-income families work somewhat more and suffer somewhat
less. New Hope's generous subsidies produced demonstrable, if
modest, gains in access to health insurance and formal child-care
settings. The guaranteed jobs reduced the number of people who
never worked at all. And by complementing paychecks with wage
supplements, New Hope raised total ``earnings-related income'' by
16 percent, to about $8,100 a year.
</P>
<P>
   In a surprise finding, it also appeared to improve the classroom
performance and educational aspirations of its participants'
children, though only among boys. In describing that effect,
evaluators said its statistical magnitude was roughly equal to
adding 100 points to a score on the Scholastic Assessment Test. By
the standards of social experiments, that is an unusually large
improvement, and it has already provoked interest among academics
who study poor children, though they are unsure what caused it or
how long it will last.
</P>
<P>
   Still, for inner-city adults, the main target of the nation's
strict new welfare laws, the news remains sobering. Even with a
guaranteed job at a subsidized wage, 73 percent of the target group
failed to shed poverty without additional support from welfare or a
second earner.
</P>
<P>
   ``People had the opportunity to work full-time, and yet they
didn't do it,'' said Michael Wiseman, an economist at the Urban
Institute, a Washington research group, who served on New Hope's
advisory board. ``We've discovered something new that I think is
distressing.''
</P>
<P>
   The results challenge conventional wisdoms across the political
spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   They suggest that poor people may have less success than
conservatives have predicted in replacing welfare with work. But
they also suggest the reasons many people fail to work stretch far
beyond the economic barriers _ low wages and scarce jobs _ that
many liberals have stressed.
</P>
<P>
   Wiseman said the results particularly ``call into question the
shortage of jobs as the explanation for poverty,'' since
participants failed to work-full time even when subsidized jobs
were assured.
</P>
<P>
   New Hope was not technically a welfare-to-work program since it
included people not on welfare. Indeed, if anything, it offers a
best-case look at the prospects of those now leaving the rolls. It
operated in Milwaukee's unusually strong economy. It worked with
low-income volunteers who had more work experience than the average
welfare recipient. And it offered them unusually generous benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even counting informal work, like baby-sitting or
hair-dressing, the average participant reported working just 27
hours a week, or about 10 percent more than members of a control
group. In a world where anti-poverty programs often produce no
gains at all _ or even bring negative consequences _ these modest
results are being treated, curiously, as resounding good news.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Stewart, who runs the welfare program for Republican Gov.
Tommy Thompson, said it ``validates our belief that a work-based
social contract'' will ``help reduce poverty in the years ahead.''
Olivia Golden, who oversees welfare programs for President Clinton,
said New Hope had brought ``very impressive results in helping
families stay in jobs and improve the well-being of children.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   New Hope grew from a series of conversations in the early 1980s
between David Riemer, a zealous advocate of public jobs, and his
friends John Gardner and Julie Kerksick, husband-and-wife union
organizers then working with the United Farm Workers. Gardner won
election to the Milwaukee school-board and became a prominent
supporter of public-school vouchers. Riemer and Kerksick became
early critics of the welfare system and advocates for public jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Enlisting everyone from the mayor to the head of the gas
company, they raised $17 million from corporate and government
sources. Conservatives liked New Hope because of its anti-welfare
ethos _ participants had to work to keep their benefits. Liberals
liked it because it guaranteed the jobs and subsidized the wages.
</P>
<P>
   New Hope created minimum-wage community service positions, such
as clerical jobs with non-profit groups, for people who could not
find private work. But for anyone working 30 hours a week, either
in private or community service jobs, New Hope added a cash
supplement to lift them above the government poverty threshold. For
a family of three, that threshold is now $12,802.
</P>
<P>
   After years of fund raising, the program began enrolling clients
in August 1994. Participants could keep their benefits for a
maximum of three years. To evaluate the results, New Hope hired
Manpower Demonstration Research Corp., a private group based in New
York City.
</P>
<P>
   Kerksick, the program's director, said its full impact cannot be
seen merely by looking at averages. Some people were too troubled
to respond at all, she said. But for others, the menu of supports _
jobs, wage supplements, child care and health care _ made a marked
difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can look at this and say, `Oh my God, look at all those
people in poverty,''' she said. ``Or we can look at this and say,
`Can you see any difference?' And you can see a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   The research examines the program's findings on two groups.
</P>
<P>
   The largest, comprising two-thirds of the participants,
consisted of those working part-time or not at all when the program
began. This group most closely resembles those now leaving the
welfare rolls.
</P>
<P>
   A guaranteed job did help them work more. Only 6 percent
remained continuously unemployed over a two-year period, compared
with 13 percent of a control group. Likewise, while only 27 percent
of these New Hope participants worked their way out of poverty,
that is still better than the control group, where only 19 percent
did so.
</P>
<P>
   Kerksick noted these official estimates understate participants'
real-world income, since self-employment (like baby sitting) and
the earnings of others living in the same household. And, she said,
earnings are only part of the story. New Hope also reduced the
amount of stress participants reported and increased their access
to health insurance and child care. ``We were able to help people
in other ways that made their lives better,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the modesty of the results illustrates the many
underlying problems. ``This shows it can take people years to
become steady workers, even when they are given a generous package
of jobs and subsidies,'' said Toby Herr, director of Project Match,
a Chicago employment program.
</P>
<P>
   (Begin optional trim)
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Mead, a political scientist at New York University,
said he was particularly struck by the high levels of depression
participants brought with them into the program. That supports the
notion that inner-city poverty is ``rooted in a underlying culture
of defeat,'' he said, rather than in the lack of jobs.
</P>
<P>
   (End optional trim)
</P>
<P>
   New Hope also enrolled a second group: those already employed
full-time when they joined. For them, New Hope actually produced a
decline in total income of about 8 percent, to about $14,100.
Kerksick said this, too, may have been positive, since many entered
the program stressed by 50-hour work-weeks and second jobs.
</P>
<P>
   But others worried that the program may have slowed these
workers' advancement.
</P>
<P>
   After two years, for instance, their average hourly wage of
$7.28 was about 6 percent lower than that of a control group. ``It
conflicts with our hopes for advancement,'' Herr said.
</P>
<P>
   But Herr and many others were impressed with New Hope's apparent
effect on participants' sons. ``That's the big finding,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   When surveyed by psychologists, teachers ranked the New Hope
boys as significantly better behaved and academically skilled than
boys in a control group. And when surveyed themselves, the New Hope
boys were much more likely than those in a control group to say
they expected to attend college.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers are unsure why this occurred. One theory is that the
boys may have benefited from better child care arrangements. With
New Hope's subsidies, the percentage of boys in formal child care
like Head Start or after-school programs grew to 60 percent, from
52 percent in the control group.
</P>
<P>
   (Begin optional trim)
</P>
<P>
   Herr credited the program's caseworkers for helping place
children in structured after-school settings, like scouts and boys
clubs. ``They had a broader vision of child care than most
programs,'' she said. ``This shows the importance of getting kids
into constructive, extra-curricular activities, even as parents
move in and out of work.'' The girls in New Hope families also
spent more time in formal child care.
</P>
<P>
   But they showed no classroom or behavioral improvements, partly
because they were already doing better than their male
counterparts. The program essentially raised the performance of
inner-city boys to the level of inner-city girls.
</P>
<P>
   (End optional trim)
</P>
<P>
   What remains unknown is whether the boys, ages 6 to 12, will
continue their progress as they hit adolescence. ``It's certainly
not an unqualified, `Oh wow, we've solved all the problems,'' said
Aletha Huston, a psychologist at the University of Texas, who
helped evaluate the program. ``But these are striking findings for
the children.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
