<HEADLINE>
INJUNCTION LATEST SHOT IN BATTLE BETWEEN BC, DALY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CINDY RODRIGUEZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Mary Daly, a feminist theologian who refuses to admit
male students to her class, filed a court injunction against Boston
College Friday, asking a judge to bar university officials from
telling people she has retired.
</P>
<P>
   The injunction also seeks to block Boston College from
disseminating the school catalog, which does not list her courses.
</P>
<P>
   Boston College says Daly told them she planned to retire in
January. But Daly calls it a ``bold-faced lie,'' an attempt by the
school to get rid of an ``uppity woman.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is thug behavior,'' Daly says. ``In effect, they're
firing a tenured professor.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest episode in this months-long battle has lined up
feminists who say Daly's teaching style would be compromised by
being forced to teach men in her classes who care more about her
destruction than the feminist theology she teaches. But her critics
call Daly a man-hater who has turned discrimination against men
into an intellectualized art form.
</P>
<P>
   University officials who thought they were close to an agreement
on a retirement package say Daly dropped the ultimate bomb by
taking the issue to court.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very clear to us. She agreed to retire,'' said BC
spokesman Jack Dunn. ``We have no intention of letting her renege
on her commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunn called the lawsuit ``silly'' and said it's Daly's way of
seeking attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that she doesn't have Boston College as the source of her
wrath, she misses the spotlight,'' Dunn said. Daly, he added, seeks
controversy because it helps her sell books.
</P>
<P>
   By the nature of what she teaches, Daly, 70, is controversial.
</P>
<P>
   Described as a pioneer in the radical feminist movement, Daly
believes that since religious structure is male-dominated, it is
abusive to women and, therefore, immoral. Her books _ which
include, ``Gyn/Ecology: The Metaethics of Radical Feminism'' and
``Quintessence . . . Realizing the Archaic Future: A Radical
Elemental Feminist Manifesto'' _ are shocking to some, because Daly
advocates dismantling ``patriarchal'' religion.
</P>
<P>
   Daly has taught women-only classes at the Jesuit college for a
quarter century, but it was never an issue until last fall, when
senior Duane Naquin charged discrimination. Naquin sought the
backing of the Center for Individual Rights, a conservative
Washington, D.C., law firm that has successfully sued to end
affirmative action programs at public universities in Texas and is
currently suing Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with a potential lawsuit, university officials asked Daly
to accept Naquin in her class. Instead, Daly requested a leave of
absence this spring but said she planned to return.
</P>
<P>
   At a Jan. 22 meeting, Dunn said, Daly agreed to retire. Daly
says that's not true and maintains that she has never signed any
retirement agreement. She has submitted her list of course
offerings for the fall semester.
</P>
<P>
   Daly and her lawyer, Gretchen Van Ness, devised a way to get
around accepting male students: She would teach only upper-level
courses restricted to students who have previously taken her
lower-level courses. Since those courses have been taken only by
female students, men would not qualify.
</P>
<P>
   One thing is certain: Daly will not go away quietly. Next
Wednesday, the Unitarian Universalist Association at 25 Beacon St.
will hold a ``speak-out'' from 5 to 7 p.m. to denounce the
university's position.
</P>
<P>
   She is also using other means to make her case public, including
an appearance April 13 on the television talk show ``Rosanne.''
</P>
<P>
   The university cannot get away with essentially firing a tenured
professor without due process, Van Ness argues. ``They have removed
her from the faculty through the back door.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
