<SLUG> BC-BIZ-ECON-COLUMN-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHECKING THE `TO DO' LIST IN THE TREASURY HANDOFF  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 16) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   (italics)Lawrence H. Summers, Deputy Secretary of the Treasury,
was nominated last week to succeed his boss, Robert E. Rubin. When
Summers sits down for the first time at his new desk, he might find
a letter like this from his predecessor.(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dear Larry: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Before you settle in, you might want to run over this list of
unfinished business. For all the talk of my having been the best
Treasury Secretary of the century (shucks), there remain some
explosive problems out there, scattered among the achievements.
</P>
<P>
   Let's start on the plus side. I bequeath to you a strong and
sound banking and financial system. Most of us in the United States
take it for granted these days, but it is nonetheless an absolute
prerequisite for taking advantage of the global economy's
opportunities and weathering its turbulence. Unless you want us to
follow Japan into a deflationary spiral, don't let a credit problem
develop on your watch.
</P>
<P>
   I leave to you a close working relationship with Alan Greenspan
at the Federal Reserve. Fed chairmen and Treasury secretaries
haven't always gotten along, but you and Alan and I have not only
developed a good rapport, but we also basically agree on nearly
every big issue. On one where we don't _ whether Treasury should
cede some of its regulatory authority over banks to the Fed as part
of the financial services bill moving through Congress _ you should
consider conceding the point, as a signal that your partnership
with Alan is more important than a turf fight.
</P>
<P>
   When I took office, we assumed that federal budget deficits
would be with us for a long time. They are gone now, and you will
have a key role in determining how we use the surpluses that seem
likely to mount rapidly in coming years. If you hold the line and
don't allow the surpluses to be squandered, you may even have to
begin planning for something that no Treasury secretary in a
century has had to contemplate: Retiring the national debt,
possibly within a decade if you believe the rosier projections.
</P>
<P>
   Now let's turn to a few really complex issues. I've argued for
years in favor of keeping the dollar strong. It's always been a
tough sell in some quarters _ no doubt Ford, GM and Chrysler will
come a'knockin' again soon _ and it's not getting any easier with
our trade deficit heading rapidly higher.
</P>
<P>
   If that deficit goes totally out of control, there's going to be
pressure from all sides to bring the dollar down. Resist it. The
strong-dollar policy has helped dampen inflation and benefited
consumers by keeping the prices of imports relatively low, and it
has made the United States an attractive place for the rest of the
world to invest. And these days, we need price stability and
capital inflows a lot more than we need a few extra export sales at
the margins.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the stock market. I have no idea whether it will
prove to be a boon or a curse for you. Alan frets over those
stratospheric valuations, but even he says they might just turn out
to be justified _ if the recent surge in productivity turns out to
be lasting. Then again, as Alan said in Chicago earlier this month,
no good thing goes on forever. Remember, my trader's instincts are
very strong, and they told me to get out of Washington while I was
still a hero to the 401(k) brigade.
</P>
<P>
   If all those matters don't keep you busy enough, there are a few
others that could steamroll you if you aren't careful. Russia and
China come to mind immediately.
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to stretch to come up with nightmare scenarios
involving Russia. The good news is that by now, the Russian economy
has been reduced to insignificance, so its collapse probably would
not drag down anyone else with it. The bad news for you is that the
only approach we have to dealing with Russia involves throwing
money at Moscow. Doing that in some kind of prudent way without
enraging Congress is your responsibility now.
</P>
<P>
   China could be even trickier. No doubt you'll have a deal to
bring it into the World Trade Organization within a few months,
once the embassy bombing in Yugoslavia has blown over. But selling
a deal on Capitol Hill was going to be a tall order before we saw
those pictures of our ambassador, James Sasser, peering through the
broken glass in Beijing. It'll be even tougher now.
</P>
<P>
   In the longer run, it's an open question whether China's
leadership can continue to encourage development of a market
economy without releasing its authoritarian grip on power. The
implications for economic development and political stability
throughout Asia could be profound.
</P>
<P>
   Larry, it's probably silly for me to run through these issues,
since you're smarter than just about anyone in Washington.
Congratulations on learning to hide it; nothing irritates
Republicans more than a know-it-all Democrat from Harvard. You know
how to work the policy and political machinery within the
administration. If you can just learn to smile and tell them what
they want to hear on Capitol Hill, you'll do fine.
</P>
<P>
   Never forget that it's your signature on the dollar bill now _
and on that ghastly new 20. I'm going fishing.
</P>
<P>
   Your friend,
</P>
<P>
   Bob &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-14-99 1920EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
