<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7743 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-STUDENTS-BOS &LR;      05-14 1246
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-STUDENTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW STUDENT PROTESTING IN CHINA OVER EMBASSY BOMBING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ They were back on the streets again this week _
screaming, chanting, hurling rocks, and burning flags.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly every decade this century, students have been the match
that lit revolutionary movements or failed rebellions in China _
most recently in 1989, when troops crushed a student-led protest in
Tiananmen Square.
</P>
<P>
   Several revolts began like this week's protests against the NATO
bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade: as rage against foreign
powers. But they turned against Chinese leaders seen as weak or
impotent.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike previous generations of activists, however, Chinese
students today are far more likely to give their government the
benefit of the doubt than to press it for change.
</P>
<P>
   Many students believe ``a movement that wants to change
everything at once could destroy this country,'' declared Jian Yi,
student union chairman at Beijing University, or ``Beida,'' the
birthplace of numerous revolutionary movements this century. ``This
is a big change from before.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the 1989 Tiananmen movement, he said, ``it had no chance
to survive. It was too early . . . Besides, democracy and freedom
are two different things. China will find its form of democracy
only through development.''
</P>
<P>
   Many students, like Jian, are more practical and
career-oriented, less idealistic and radical than their
predecessors. Dozens of students interviewed said they realize that
modernization cannot come overnight, so they are more patient with
the government.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say the new generation is cynical and self-centered,
brainwashed and ignorant of China's painful history, and has sold
out the ideal of political freedom for prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   The shift in attitudes among the new youth reflects an array of
fundamental changes that have washed over China in recent years.
The 1990s brought a second decade of Open Door policies, more
access to foreign products and ideas, rising incomes, and a steady
march toward a market-driven economy. Except for democracy, many
demands of the 1989 protesters have been met _ the right to choose
jobs after graduation, better living conditions, more choice in the
educational system, and an official campaign against corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the 1980 edict limiting families to one child has
spawned a generation of ``little emperors,'' only children whose
newly prosperous parents have showered them with opportunities,
creating China's first generation of ``me-first'' college students.
</P>
<P>
   A Western scholar in Beijing who frequently visits college
campuses said students sometimes classify themselves as red hats,
black hats, or gold hats. Red hats want a Communist Party career,
and today are the smallest group. Black hats want an academic
career, and were probably the dominant group at the time of the
Tiananmen protests. Gold hats want to make money, and not
surprisingly, they are the largest group today.
</P>
<P>
   ``China is different from 10 years ago, so it's natural students
are different,'' said Liu Xiaojun, 26, a student at Beida. ``In the
'80s, students had lots of ideas, but it was just empty words. Now
China is more competitive and people are more practical, not just
sitting around and thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   The attitude of looking-out-for-number-one is tempered, however,
by a deep-seated patriotism and an intense desire to make a weak
China stronger _ a common thread in student movements ever since
the May 4, 1919, protest against the transfer of German colonies in
China to Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nowadays we look at our role differently from previous
students. We think it's important to study harder and make
ourselves more useful. My goal is to get skills so I can be more
valuable for myself and my country,'' said Pan, a 19-year-old
chemistry student at the University of Science and Technology in
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   In the last decade, increased access to foreign education,
travel, and the Internet have broadened students' exposure to
foreign ideas, but it has also made them critical of Western
governments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tiananmen youth didn't know much about the outside world. They
believed the Voice of America and the BBC and were disillusioned
with their government,'' said Stanley Rosen, a political scientist
at the University of Southern California. ``Today's youth are much
more skeptical about the West's motives _ the West is looked upon
as self-serving in its attitude to human rights, and America is
seen as a world policeman attacking countries when it suits them.
</P>
<P>
   ``People pushing democracy in '89 are much more nationalistic
now. And the Chinese government is not distrusted and hated the way
it was then.''
</P>
<P>
   That is largely because the economic and political chaos that
followed the collapse of the Soviet Union is regarded here as a
nightmare scenario of what could have happened if democracy
protesters had gotten their way in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the crumbling of cradle-to-grave benefits and the
job-allocation system has meant that students can choose their jobs
and earn more money. But that freedom has made them more
competitive and goal-oriented, less interested in politics.
</P>
<P>
   That is not to say that a crisis does not get students and
campus organizations riled up. One need look no farther than ``San
Jiao Di,'' the triangle of bulletin boards at Beida that has long
been a window onto the thinking of the country's young elite.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the kiosks were plastered with hundreds of
anti-American and anti-NATO diatribes, as well as a memorial to the
three Chinese killed in the embassy bombing. One 3-D collage had
Coke and Pepsi cups spilling red paint to represent blood, and
called on students to boycott American products. Clinton was
depicted as a devil and denounced in obscenities. Hundreds of
students clustered around taking notes on their classmates' poems
and slogans.
</P>
<P>
   A scene from marches earlier this week was almost comical;
students nodded obediently while police read a list of ``no-nos''
(don't burn anything, don't destroy public property, don't let
non-students join your group), and marched a clearly marked
``parade route,'' chanting from a list of approved slogans. At the
end of the route, they purchased refreshments from an enterprising
woman selling ``Chinese Coke,'' ``Chinese beer,'' and ``Chinese
water.''
</P>
<P>
   The government may be pleased to have a handy bogeyman to
deflect student attention from 10th anniversary of the massacre of
democracy protesters near Tiananmen Square. But even if it were not
for the sudden coalescing of pro-government, nationalistic
feelings, Jian asserts that he knows of no one on his campus who is
preparing for any June 4 commemoration.
</P>
<P>
   But one former 1989 activist, now a graduate student, said that
despite their pragmatism, the students' dreams for the nation
remain the same as those of the May 4, 1919, activists, the first
major student movement of this century.
</P>
<P>
   ``Students have always thought we should destroy the old system
and establish a new way of thinking. But vested interests in China
are very strong, and . . . we're still facing the same problem: how
to develop our country, make it grow, make it more powerful,'' said
the 29-year-old science student at Beida. ``The ideal 80 years ago,
10 years ago, and now is the same. Just the circumstances are
different.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-14-99 1922EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
