<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7745 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABORTION-TEXAS-HNS &LR;      05-14 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEY LEGISLATIVE PANEL APPROVES PARENT NOTIFICATION BILL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By POLLY ROSS HUGHES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A compromise parental notification bill for
teens seeking abortions appears headed to the full Texas House
after gaining approval Friday from a key committee.
</P>
<P>
   The substitute for a measure that passed the Senate in March was
forged during tense and often fragile talks in the past few weeks
that nearly derailed at several bumps along the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would call the situation volatile. This is a passionate
issue,'' House sponsor Rep. Dianne Delisi, R-Temple, said of the
measure's chances with the often unpredictable and emotionally
charged House members.
</P>
<P>
   The committee substitute for Senate Bill 30, which Gov. George
W. Bush backed this week, passed 11-1 in the much-awaited vote by
the House State Affairs Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Caucus leader Ken Marchant of Coppell was absent
while Houston Democrats Sylvester Turner and Kevin Bailey
abstained. Democrat Debra Danburg of Houston, the abortion rights
champion who killed a similar measure two years ago, was the lone
dissenter.
</P>
<P>
   The compromise, drafted by committee Chairman Steve Wolens,
D-Dallas, left activists on both sides of the abortion divide
complaining but won praise from Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thank and commend Chairman Wolens for reporting this
parental notification bill out of committee,'' Bush said. ``This is
an important step in the process, and I look forward to signing a
strong parental notification bill.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting such a measure into law is important to Bush, a GOP
presidential front-runner who had pledged to push for this
restriction on abortion for minors.
</P>
<P>
   The compromise bill would waive a two-day waiting period for
girls brought by parents for abortions, which pleases abortion
rights supporters. However, anti-abortion forces won their fight
that only a judge could decide if there is justification for a girl
not to tell her parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill is as strong as garlic,'' said Wolens, who not only
drafted it but voted for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing else other than the cold, devoid, empty walls
of the courthouse for a minor girl to go to to face a bureaucrat
judge who most likely is going to see this poor girl as another
cause number that he's got to resolve in his long court docket for
the day,'' he added. ``This poor girl is going to be nothing more
than a cause number.''
</P>
<P>
   Abortion foes in various socially conservative groups have never
fully trusted Wolens, and they object to the compromise for
offering doctors legal protections in the event criminal charges
are brought against them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obviously not what we want,'' said Bill Price, president
of Texans United for Life. Yet, in the end, Price and a lawyer for
the National Right to Life Committee did not succeed in convincing
key legislators to kill the compromise or that it is an ``abortion
doctor protection bill.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolens said he simply wanted to make sure a doctor could place a
sworn affidavit in a medical file if he had been told by a clerk at
the court or other official that it was OK to proceed with the
abortion. Having such documentation would prove critical if
criminal charges were filed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not kindergarten conduct that we're talking about,''
he said. ``This is something that will throw a doctor in jail.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolens, a lawyer by profession, said he grew frustrated with the
anti-abortion activists. SB 30, drafted by Sen. Florence Shapiro,
R-Plano, had ``more constitutional holes than a slice of Swiss
cheese,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was appalled in our committee at how little thought had gone
into the bill ... to create legislation that would withstand
constitutional scrutiny in the courts. I have become very impatient
over the last two months when I hear partisan and political
criticism of the way we handled the bill,'' Wolens added.
</P>
<P>
   Danburg said she will keep her ears open to see if a signed
agreement by conservative Republicans to avoid a free-for-all floor
flight on the bill is showing signs of cracking. If that agreement
starts to slip, she said, she will try to hold the bill up in the
Calendars Committee, keeping it from the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not happy with this bill,'' said Peggy Romberg of the
Texas Family Planning Association who said anything could happen.
``The complexity of keeping an agreement _ when you have 150
members _ the odds of a few loose cannons is pretty real.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
