<HEADLINE>
(REPEATING, ADDING ART NOTE)  
 FROM ADDICT TO EDUCATOR IN HARLEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 16)  
 (af)  
 By LAURA PEDERSEN-PIETERSEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Blossom Martin was once bound for college and career. But by
1991, she said, she had become so consumed by alcohol and drugs
that she lost her job, was evicted from her apartment and landed on
welfare. And her two children had been living in foster care.
</P>
<P>
   Coming back was no snap. The course she has followed to
establish a new career, earn a college degree and win back her
children demonstrates both the difficulties and rewards of
recovery. Now, as director of a privately financed after-school
program in Manhattan, her purpose is to help others who are down
and out _ or could become so.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blossom has a lot of valuable skills gained from her life
experience that can help her students,'' said the Rev. Leroy
Ricksy, director of the East Harlem Urban Center, the parent
organization for Ms. Martin's employer, the Booker T. Washington
Learning Center.
</P>
<P>
   When Ms. Martin graduated from Benjamin Franklin High School in
East Harlem in 1974, she wanted to be a doctor. She was accepted by
City College, but, discouraged by what she called bureaucracy and
administrative foul-ups, she never enrolled.
</P>
<P>
   A job as a bookkeeper for an after-hours bar eventually spiraled
into a life of drug and alcohol abuse, she said. The city's Bureau
of Child Welfare placed her two small children in foster care in
1985. Six years later, she had hit bottom.
</P>
<P>
   It was then, at the age of 35, that Ms. Martin decided to
reclaim her life. ``It just gradually occurred to me that I'd
rather spend my money on things other than drugs _ for instance,
paying the rent and buying clothes for my kids.''
</P>
<P>
   She enrolled at Touro College on East 123d Street and entered a
substance abuse program, taking almost two years to fully beat her
addictions. ``Many people still think that addiction can be
overcome in a few weeks or months,'' she said. ``It takes years.
It's a struggle every day.'' After Ms. Martin's second year at
Touro, her children, who had been in foster care for eight years,
were returned to her.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, she earned a bachelor's degree in human services. She
moved from welfare to workfare as a groundskeeper for the city's
Housing Department. Having met and impressed Ricksy, whose agency
ran her drug rehabilitation program, with her work as a volunteer
student counselor, she was hired a year later at the Booker T.
Washington center, on East 101st Street, and left public assistance
entirely.
</P>
<P>
   The center operates a private, all-day preschool, an
after-school educational program for children in nearby public
schools and a full-time summer program. Most of the center's
support comes from New York City businesses like the Dover Corp.
and Lehman Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   All the children receive a big helping of Ms. Martin's tough
love. ``Every child in this community has been affected in some way
by drugs, and as a result they thrive on consistency and
structure,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   When she took over the summer program as well, several months
after her hiring, Ms. Martin informed administrators and students
that its emphasis would be on education, not just supervised play.
</P>
<P>
   ``By coming here for the summer, these children are essentially
going to school all year, and I assure you that they're very happy
to learn every day,'' she said. ``There's plenty of time for fun
and games.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Martin, who is also a volunteer tutor at Public School 50,
visits her learning-center students' parents or other care
providers regularly, to seek their involvement. ``I truly believe
we can turn the public school system around with a more organized
coalition of parents, community organizations and the private
sector,'' she said. ``The school has computers. It has money. What
they need is more community involvement _ not something you get by
shuffling students around.''
</P>
<P>
   She remembers her mother's volunteer work for the Head Start
program in 1968. ``They would go into the homes and see what was
going on and so were able to connect the family with outside
resources and community services,'' Ms. Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   She argues for smaller classes, organized after-school
supervision until 6 p.m. for all students, and year-round
schooling.
</P>
<P>
   If Ms. Martin's own children are proud of her, she is just as
proud of them. Last month her son, Matthew, 15, took part in a
school project, a Web site called ``Harlem Live,'' which recently
became part of a permanent exhibit at the Smithsonian Institution.
Her daughter, Jamilla, 18, is completing the learning center's
computer course.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Martin's next step is to earn her master's degree in
education. She hopes to work eventually as a teacher or an
administrator in the public school system _ as an agent of change. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Laura Pedersen-Pietersen is a Manhattan author and public
speaker. Her column profiling people whose work is their passion
appears the third Sunday of each month. E-mail:
yourmind(AT)nytimes.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
