<SLUG> BC-PRICES-RISE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RISE IN CONSUMER PRICES UPSETS MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The government reported Friday that consumer prices rose at
their fastest pace during the 1990s economic expansion, unnerving
investors and heightening suspense over whether the Federal Reserve
Board may raise interest rates to control inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Investors responding to a 0.7 percent price increase in April
hammered the bond market and drove the Dow Jones industrial index
down 200 points before noon. The Dow never recovered, closing
Friday at 10,913.32, off 193.87 points, or 1.75 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting a very substantial inflation scare here,'' said
Charles Clough, chief investment strategist for Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts do not expect the Fed to raise interest rates when
board members meet on Tuesday. But, they argue, the CPI report
greatly increased the odds the Fed would change its official stance
on interest rates from ``neutral,'' to a tilt toward raising rates
later this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next move from the Fed will be up,'' predicted Lawrence
Horwitz, managing director of Primark Decision Economics in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   A record spike in gasoline prices fueled inflation, as analysts
had predicted. More worrisome, the Labor Department said the
``core'' inflation rate _ minus energy and food prices _ rose by a
stronger-than-expected 0.4 percent. Higher prices for everything
from prescription drugs and cigarettes to clothing helped propel
the overall CPI higher.
</P>
<P>
   The inflation report coincided with other news that the economy
remains strong and inflation looms, including a hefty 0.6 percent
rise in factory output last month and continued buoyancy in
business confidence. On Thursday, the government reported producer
prices shot up 0.5 percent in April.
</P>
<P>
   Inflation is viewed as the single biggest threat not only to the
economy but also to stability of a delicately balanced stock
market. Before slumping Friday, stocks on Thursday broke through
the latest of numerous record highs.
</P>
<P>
   The stock market was led downward by financial companies, which
are hurt by higher interest rates. Citigroup Inc., the nation's
largest banking company, lost 2 7/16 of its value, closing at 71
per share. The technology-heavy Nasdaq stock index declined 2.10
percent, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index fell 2.18 percent,
compared with the Dow's 1.75 percent drop.
</P>
<P>
   Investors are ``trying desperately to sustain these price-equity
ratios but it gets more difficult as bond yields rise and inflation
scares increase,'' said Clough at Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   Fearing higher interest rates in the future, the bond market
tanked, suffering its biggest rout in almost three years. The
benchmark 30-year US Treasury bond fell 2 5/32 points. Yields
surged 17 basis points to 5.92 percent, their highest in a year.
Bond yields are up sharply from the beginning of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ghost of inflation past is starting to haunt the bond and
equity markets,'' said Ned Riley, chief investment officer for
BankBoston Corp.
</P>
<P>
   April's CPI had its biggest monthly advance since October 1990,
marring a near-perfect inflation record during a sustained period
of growth during the 1990s. For the 12 months including April, the
CPI rose at a 2.3 percent annual rate.
</P>
<P>
   The core inflation rate, at 0.4 percent, was markedly higher
than the 0.1 percent rate in the first three months of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Various components that go into the CPI rose sharply. The
largest single factor was energy costs, which rose 6.1 percent in
April. Gasoline prices, which rose 15 percent, had the biggest
monthly increase on record _ bigger even than increases posted
during the 1970s embargo by Middle East oil producers.
</P>
<P>
   Apparel prices rose for the first time since August _ up 1.5
percent in April. Transportation costs, fueled by higher gasoline
prices, rose 2.4 percent. Medical costs, under pressure from
prescription drugs, rose 0.4 percent in April and are up 3.5
percent for the year.
</P>
<P>
   The report provides the clearest evidence to date that
inflationary pressures are intensifying, creating a dilemma for Fed
chairman Alan Greenspan and board members.
</P>
<P>
   The April CPI may be ``a catch up from extraordinarily low
readings we had before,'' said Richard Rippe, a senior vice
president and chief economist at Prudential Securities in New York.
The difficulty, said Rippe, is that it could take a few more
months' data for the Fed to ascertain how big a threat inflation
may become in coming months.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, if the Fed does not act, the inflation pressure-cooker
may heat up, ultimately making it harder to control. If Fed members
do act, they could endanger the bull market, which has soared to
unprecedented highs and fueled consumer spending which keeps the
economy roaring.
</P>
<P>
   ``This (CPI report) complicates their decision next Tuesday,''
Rippe said. Odds the Fed would move to a bias towards tightening _
from its neutral stance _ ``have clearly gone up.''
</P>
<P>
   In another sign of unabated growth, industrial output rose 0.6
percent last month after rising 0.5 percent in March. Previously,
the estimate of March industrial production had been a 0.1 percent
rise.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Minervini, chief investment strategist for Quantech
Research Group in New York, said that though the bond market ``has
fallen out of bed, the stock market so far has held up well,''
given Friday's news.
</P>
<P>
   But, Minervini warned, investors who left early Friday ``need a
chance to digest this over the weekend so let's see what Monday
morning brings.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
