<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-HMO-EARNS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLOW OF RED INK IN BAY STATE HMO BUSINESS CONTINUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- All of Massacahusetts' major health insurers reported
operating losses for the first three months of this year,
continuing the stream of red ink that is washing over the entire
Massachusetts health care industry.
</P>
<P>
   The losses signal steep premium increases ahead for most
consumers in July, when many health insurance contracts are
renewed. Insurers are estimating increases of anywhere from 5
percent to 10 percent, with some customers experiencing far larger
increases.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard Pilgrim Health Care, the largest health maintenance
organization in New England, posted the largest loss of all _ more
thanr $22 million loss on revenue of $703.5 million, compared to a
net gain of $440,000 in the first three months of last year on
revenue of $632.4 million. When $10.8 million in investment income
is taken into account, the Brookline-based HMO's operating loss
balloons to $32.8 million for this year.
</P>
<P>
   Tufts Health Plan, the second biggest HMO in the region, lost
$3.8 million on revenue of $485 million in the first quarter. The
figure includes investment income of $6 million. The loss widens to
nearly $10 million for the quarter once investment income is
withheld.
</P>
<P>
   Tufts, based in Waltham, made money in Massachusetts _ about $5
million _ but lost money in its efforts to expand into Maine, New
Hampshire and Rhode Island, said Richard Hallworth, Tufts chief
financial officer. The losses are expected to continue through
2000, he projected.
</P>
<P>
   Fallon Community Health Plan lost $5.4 million on revenue of
$133.3 million the first quarter, compared to a $873,157 loss
during the first three months of 1998 on revenue of $117.9 million,
according to Jay Egan, co-executive director of the Worcester-based
HMO. Egan said the losses were associated with the HMO's efforts to
expand outside of its central Massachusetts market.
</P>
<P>
   ``These results are dismal, to say the least,'' Susan Connolly,
principal of William M. Mercer Inc., a benefits consulting firm in
Boston, said of the industry's losses.
</P>
<P>
   The one bright spot was Blue Cross and Blue Shield of
Massachusetts, which posted the industry's only net gain. Blue
Cross made $9.2 million on $491.5 million in revenue in the first
quarter, compared to a $29.4 million gain on $502.6 million in the
first quarter of 1998. The figures include proceeds from the sale
of its building at 100 Summer Street in Boston, which yielded $32
million in the first quarter of 1998, and another $8 million in the
first quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   On an operating basis, Blue Cross, however, lost money. This
year, it lost $10.9 million in the first three months. Last year,
it lost $9.2 million in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The losses reflect a general downward trend in the health care
sector as a whole in Massachusetts, which has been struggling with
cuts in Medicare reimbursement and low premium increases. As a
result, negotiations _ between insurers and employers, and between
insurers and health care providers _ are likely to be much more
acrimonious, said Connolly. ``It's going to be a very tough market
this year,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, for example, Apex Health Care Inc. a 210-physician group
in Portsmouth, N.H., announced it was cancelling its contract with
Tufts because of a payment dispute. Apex doctors care for about
16,000 Tufts patients in the Seacoast area of New Hampshire. In
addition, two hospitals associated with Apex, Exeter Hospital and
Portsmouth Regional Hospital, also pulled out of the Tufts network
rather than accept a 10 percent cut in reimbursement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their proposal is just unacceptable,'' said Dr. James Glennon,
Apex medical director. ``Physicians have been living under the same
fee schedule since 1996, despite the fact that our costs have
increased.''
</P>
<P>
   Tufts said it will try to sign contracts with individual doctors
in Apex, whose contract expires July 1. The incident follows a
similar move this month, when 915 physicians affiliated with
Partners Community Health Inc. in Boston said they will not accept
new Tufts patients because of inadequate payment from the insurer.
</P>
</TEXT>
