<P>
   HAWAII-TRUST (Honolulu) _ Developments concerning the Bishop
Estate. The estate, an institution of almost medieval power, was
long been a source of intense native pride, but in recent years it
had come to be seen as the embodiment of Hawaii's brand of inbred,
closed-door politics, as secretive and suspect as it was
impregnable. Most of the trustees were closely connected to the
state's ruling political establishment, so their dramatic ouster _
and the long fight that led up to it _ has led to predictions of a
shakeup in institutions from the Legislature to the state Supreme
Court, whose members used to select the Bishop trustees. By Todd S.
Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   3-column hed.
</P>
<P>
   2-column photo with story.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved; `a' category.)
</P>
<P>
   ASSASSIN-GAME (Westport, Conn.) _ Beginning next week, 35 elite
college-bound students from Staples High School plan to arm
themselves with plastic guns with names like Lock `n' Load, Secret
Shot II, and Expand-a-Blast, then stalk classmates through town.
The students, who call the game Assassinations, have elaborate
plans for staying alive, and so expect the contest to last three
weeks. The final two survivors will shoot it out in a town park,
then collect cash prizes. Although life has not completely imitated
art in the students' game, some students have begun to worry about
the issue of real bullets. A handful of Staples students are bowing
out this year, deciding that four weeks after the killings in a
Colorado high school might not be the best time to lurk in bushes
and hide under cars in hopes of knocking off a target, even if it
is with a foam dart. By Mike Allen.
</P>
<P>
   3-column hed.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved; `a' category.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DUKE-RESEARCH (Undated) _ A four-day-old ban on
federally-financed human experiments at Duke University Medical
Center was lifted on Friday after Duke officials agreed to overhaul
its protections for human subjects. By Philip J. Hilts.
</P>
<P>
   2-column hed.
</P>
