<HEADLINE>
AOL STOCK HAS MAGELLAN FUND LOOKING GOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   America Online, Inc. has done more than any other stock to boost
returns at Fidelity Investment's gigantic Magellan Fund, even
though the mutual fund's manager is generally wary of Internet
stocks and newly cautious about technology issues.
</P>
<P>
   Magellan's skipper, Robert Stansky, credited his decision to buy
more shares in AOL, the nation's biggest Internet service provider
and computer network, with helping Magellan to beat the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index, a broad market benchmark, in recent periods.
</P>
<P>
   His decision, detailed Friday in Magellan's annual report, has
clearly pleased shareholders in Magellan, the nation's biggest
mutual fund with $93.7 billion in assets. Closed to new investors
since September 1997, Magellan recently began attracting a flood of
new cash from existing investors. Magellan was Fidelity's fourth
best selling fund last quarter, raking in a net $1 billion, the
most in three years, according to Financial Research Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Over 12 months through March, Magellan had net sales of $561
million, compared with net outflows of $1.9 billion the year
before, Fidelity said.
</P>
<P>
   Echoing a sober view of Web-oriented stocks, Stansky, 43, wrote
in the report that while he considered the Internet ``the most
exciting business segment of US business, many Internet companies
aren't yet making a profit and their stocks are very volatile.'' He
also provided a rare glimpse into what could be a new stock-picking
style at Fidelity, the nation's biggest fund firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I simply can't analyze the Internet sector the same way I
analyze other sectors,'' Stansky wrote. ``I do use some traditional
fundamental analysis . . . At the same time, I evaluate investor
psychology when it comes to Internet stocks.'' Stansky said his
decision to increase his exposure to Internet and other technology
stocks in the fourth quarter of 1998 to 25.8 percent as of year-end
was due ``at least as much to my feel for the psychology
surrounding thses stocks as it was to any numbers-related
analysis.''
</P>
<P>
   Internet fever has swept many investors off their feet, but over
the first quarter Stansky scaled back technology's share of
Magellan's assets to 20.8 percent as of the end of March.
Magellan's top tech holdings include big blue-chip issues such as
Microsoft Corp. and Cisco Systems, Inc.
</P>
<P>
   In the three years since he took it over, Stansky is widely
credited with having turned a once-troubled Magellan around. The
fund gained 28.5 percent over 12 months through Friday, handily
beating the S&AMP;P 500, which rose 24 percent. Magellan stumbled when
its former manager, Jeffrey Vinik, placed ill-timed bets on bonds
and cash.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity's flagship fund has also benefited recently from
holding popular large-company stocks, including General Electric
Co., now its top holding; retailers Home Depot Inc and Wal-Mart
Stores Inc.; and pharmaceutical giant Merck &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   But Stansky sounded a note of caution about the dominance of
large caps, which have produced most of the US stock market's
double-digit gains in recent years. Magellan, which is concentrated
in the largest issues, could be hurt if the market fundamentally
shifts to favoring smaller companies, Stansky said. He added: ``The
wild card _ in terms of stock performance _ is valuations.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
