<SLUG> BC-RAC-PREAKNESS-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PREAKNESS HOPEFULS KEEP THE FAITH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Choosing a winner in horse races demands foresight
as much as hindsight and imagination as much as crunching numbers.
It is as much an art as a science, this pastime that has consumed
so many for so long.
</P>
<P>
   And ``faith'' is an integral factor in making all decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're finally training this horse the American way,''
trainer Bob Baffert commented after he saw that Worldly Manner had
worked a crisp 1:01 at Churchill Downs Tuesday. This followed a
leisurely 1:02 workout before the Kentucky Derby, a workout done
the European way _ in other words, slow _ and a few American
trainers snickered at the methods of Dubai's Godolphin Racing
Stable.
</P>
<P>
   But Godolphin just may be the most potent racing outfit in the
world. Godolphin will have 15 horses racing in six countries this
weekend, with Godolphin's Worldly Manner racing in Saturday's 124th
Preakness at decrepit, but charming Pimlico Race Course. Worldly
Manner finished seventh in the Kentucky Derby, his first real race
in eight months. Snickerers snickered at the European style.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Bal-mer'' was the home of H.L. Mencken, a man who would be
sure to snicker at the snickerers himself, and of the 12 horses who
have come to Baltimore for the Preakness, Worldly Manner is the
most intriguing. Also, though, he is the horse who most requires a
leap of faith.
</P>
<P>
   Quite simply, it is not known if Worldly Manner gave up the
ghost at the eighth pole in Louisville because 1. he was not
trained sharply enough, 2. he was not good enough, or 3. his mommy
and daddy produced a youngster who just can't run that far. If the
Derby were a mile race, Worldly Manner would have been the winner;
alas, the Derby was a 1 1/4 miles.
</P>
<P>
   So faith is required. Sheikh Mohammed al Maktoum of the
Godolphin blue colors paid $5 million for Worldly Manner, so it
does seem improbable that Worldly Manner is not better than the
common crowd that ran in the Derby. And while pedigree experts can
_ and will _ debate the merits of a mating six or seven generations
back, Worldly Manner does seem to have the blood to run a distance.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, then, the question is whether Worldly Manner just
wasn't fit enough to run the Derby. American horses vying to win
the 3-year-old Classics often are much more seasoned than their
European counterparts trying to win the English Classics; it seems
likely Godolphin's use of a European style of training for the
Kentucky Derby might have been a mistake for a horse unraced in
months.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got a lot out of the Derby,'' said Tom Albertrani, the
assistant trainer for Godolphin. ``We still don't know for sure if
he stays, but we'll find that out (Saturday).''
</P>
<P>
   Alas, it will be too late to wager once that question is
answered definitively. Whether Godolphin actually used the Kentucky
Derby as a prep for the Preakness _ an unsettling thought _ or
whether the Derby was merely Sheikh Mohammed's first lesson learned
in his five-year plan to win America's Triple Crown, no one knows.
</P>
<P>
   So a liberal dose of faith is required. For a human tip,
consider that Sheikh Mohammed is here in Baltimore Saturday and not
in England, Ireland, Germany, Japan, France, or Italy, where
Godolphin horses are running this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   In early Preakness wagering Friday, Menifee was the strong
favorite at 2-1 while Worldly Manner's odds have dropped sharply
from his (strangely-high) morning line odds of 12-1. Charismatic,
the Derby winner, has been dismissed by the crowd and was 7-1.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd believes Menifee had a troubled trip in the Derby and
would have won with a clearer path; the crowd is right when it
looks back to the Derby. But the crowd may not be right when it
looks ahead to the Preakness; the crowd, after all, is seldom right
in any endeavor.
</P>
<P>
   All focus on the Derby has been on the rough-and-wild rodeo
rides that so many horses had, but little focus has been on the
extreme track bias at Churchill Downs May 1. There was an extreme
closer's bias that day in Louisville and speed horses had virtually
no chance. Worldly Manner stalked the lead and then briefly took
the lead at the top of the stretch before fading; the track bias
certainly didn't help him.
</P>
<P>
   The track bias at Pimlico Friday was the exact opposite. Horses
that took the early lead had a huge advantage, especially if they
were to the inside of the track. Worldly Manner should be helped by
1. the race under his belt in Louisville and 2. the bias of
Pimlico, which is likely to be similar Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Even more, the Derby was a bad, slow, dawdling, and plodding
race, the slowest on a dry track in 25 years. Menifee, who missed
winning by a neck, looked good simply because the other horses
weren't good.
</P>
<P>
   It seems certain, though, that Menifee will make the board
Saturday, as will one of D. Wayne Lukas's two horses, Charismatic
or Cat Thief. Charismatic is the better of the two and his odds
will be higher; take Charismatic to be second or third. Baffert's
filly, Excellent Meeting, had a most troubled trip like so many
others in the Derby, and Baffert has been talking her up. But she
can be dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   Worldly Manner can win the Preakness with Charismatic or Menifee
second and either of those two third. Of the long shots, only Badge
may make the board.
</P>
<P>
   It is a leap of faith. But faith often is rewarded.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
