<SLUG> BC-ELDERLY-MITZVAH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINALLY, THEY'LL BE `DAUGHTERS OF THE COMMANDMENTS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- They've waited more than 60 years for a rite of
passage denied them long ago simply because they were girls.
</P>
<P>
   With memories that still sting, they recall the attention,
praise and gifts lavished on their brothers as they crossed the
symbolic threshold into manhood.
</P>
<P>
   The time had come, they decided, for their moment in the sun.
</P>
<P>
   So on Sunday, nine women, ranging in age from 76 to 91, will
finally celebrate their bat mitzvah, becoming ``daughters of the
commandments.'' More than 200 relatives from as far away as
California will come to watch their mothers and grandmothers
achieve a sacred milestone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally, I will feel like a complete Jewish woman,'' said
Dorothy Sockol, 86, sitting in a sun-drenched first-floor meeting
room at Heritage at Cleveland Circle. The nine women live in the
assisted living community in Brighton.
</P>
<P>
   ``My two brothers were educated about the Jewish religion, but I
got no training because it wasn't something that was open to
girls,'' said Sockol, who grew up in Maine. ``It's taken a long
time but I finally earned the privilege to be bat mitzvahed.''
</P>
<P>
   After weeks of intense study Sockol, Violet Katz, 91, Rose
Uchill , 88, Ruth Wineburgh, 89, Sylvia Ewens, 82, Anne Prenovitz,
88, Louis Hyman, 76, Pauline Meyer, 87, and Ida Wolf, 90, will be
called by their Hebrew name to read the Torah in front of their
families.
</P>
<P>
   For the past six months, the nine women have spent dozens of
hours learning Hebrew, studying the Torah and memorizing prayers
preparing to claim a religious right that essentially did not exist
when they were growing up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't something that anyone even thought about,'' Katz
said. ``It was just assumed that this was for the boys, not the
girls so I don't remember anybody raising a ruckus about it.''
</P>
<P>
   But spurred on, in part, by the women's rights movement in the
1960s, Judaism has become more egalitarian over the past four
decades, opening doors to women that had been closed for centuries.
Women rabbis are now common and religious rituals are no longer the
domain of men.
</P>
<P>
   In the Reform and Conservative movement, bat mitzvahs for girls
are the norm _ and an increasing number of adult women eager to
embrace a vital source of Jewish identity also are celebrating the
ritual.
</P>
<P>
   In the Orthodox movement, which has strict rules regarding
gender roles, bat mitzvahs are less common. But even within this
conservative denomination, a growing number of modern Orthodox
congregations are permitting bat mitzvahs.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a young girl, I was the only girl attending Hebrew
school,'' said Wineburgh, who grew up in Utica, N.Y. ``As I watched
the boys become Bar Mitzvahed, I asked my teacher when it would be
my turn. He predicted that someday girls will have the opportunity
to receive this honor. For me this day has finally come in my
golden years.''
</P>
<P>
   The coming of age ceremony celebrated in Judaism for hundreds of
years, the bar mitzvah _ and, today, the bat mitzvah _ is a formal
reminder to maturing youth of their responsibility to uphold Jewish
law and tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Before becoming bar or bat mitzvahed, a Jew must show a basic
understanding of Jewish principles, have enough command of Hebrew
to participate in services and be prepared to assume the religious
and ethical responsibilities of adults.
</P>
<P>
   And while bar and bat mitzvahs are today typically celebrated
among youngsters, there is no age restriction.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we may grow old physically, our sense of faith
doesn't,'' noted Rabbi Maury Levine, rabbi emeritus at Temple Beth
Sholom in Framingham. He will be officiating at Sunday's Bat
Mitzvah. ``I think it's wonderful that these women had the
motivation and desire to renew their ties with the Jewish
tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's ceremony probably wouldn't be happening if Rose Uchill
hadn't spoken up.
</P>
<P>
   Uchill turned 88 on Nov. 16, two weeks after sitting inside
Temple Beth Avodah in Newton watching her grandson, John, become
bar mitzvahed.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, she has traveled to Jerusalem, Hawaii and Denver
to see her children and grandchildren celebrate their bar and bat
mitzvah's. Every time, she listened joyfully as they read from the
Torah in a ritual that binds Jews across time.
</P>
<P>
   After playing the role of proud mom or grandma so many times,
Uchill finally decided this was something she wanted for herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just seemed right to me,'' Uchill said one day last week
after the nine women had finished another afternoon of rehearsing.
</P>
<P>
   So when Nancy Bayer, Heritage's program director, wished her a
happy birthday last November, Uchill said she had just one burning
birthday wish _ to be bat mitzvahed.
</P>
<P>
   Bayer, thrilled by Uchill's request, organized a class, which
eventually evolved into the group of nine women. ``My parents who
are coming to the ceremony, instilled in me a strong sense of
Judaism and because of that I am able to teach others and I can do
this for these women,'' Bayer said.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Calica is coming from San Franciso to watch his grandmother,
Uchill, become bat mitzvahed. ``I think it's wonderful because when
she was growing up girls were treated as a lesser class and she was
this incredibly sharp person,'' said Calica, 35. ``Had she grown up
today she'd probably be something like a scientist. I'm not
surprised she's doing this. She's a real fireball.''
</P>
<P>
   As she prepares the nine women for Sunday's celebration, Bayer
mulls what she will say during the ceremony. ``I'm going to be
praising them for their dedication, interest in learning and
commitment to Judaism,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   As the women approach the Torah, their Hebrew name and that of
their parents will be called out.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, in a bar mitzvah or bat mitzvah, they would be called
to read in the name of their fathers. But the women told Bayer they
also want to be called in the name of their mothers. ``That was
important to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, when the cermony ends, each women will receive a bat
mitzvah certificate that will state: ``Every living soul is a
letter of the Torah.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
