<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-INTERNET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YUGOSLAV INTERNET USERS PANIC ON RUMOR THAT THEY'LL BE CUT OFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ Internet users rushed to send last-minute
e-mails at a downtown Internet cafe Friday, after word circulated
that the United States was going to cut off Yugoslavia from the
World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a rush here and many people heard it was going to be
shut down,'' said Borivoj Ivanovic, 23, a webmaster at the
MultiMedia Center Maverick cafi in central Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd be surprised how many people communicate by email,'' he
said. ``When we had a power cut people were queuing behind the
computers to send email to relatives and friends to say `I am
OK.'''
</P>
<P>
   The loss of internet access is still only a threat, but Internet
providers here are worried that a partial shutdown is imminent. The
net remains the only means of communication for many in Serbia, and
apart from the short wave radio, provides the only access to
independent news in the country. Postal services to and from abroad
have stopped since NATO began its air campaign, and telephone
charges are prohibitive for most ordinary people.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the feared shutdown is a presidential executive order,
signed by President Clinton, that came into force May 1. Updating a
1998 order, the order enforces sanctions to prevent U.S. companies
from dealing in ``goods, software, technology (including technical
services) and services'' with the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Its impact was almost immediate for companies like Informatika,
an Internet provider and software and hardware supplier in
Belgrade. Slobodan Sreckovic, general manager of Informatika, had
just recently expanded his Internet services, organizing a direct
satellite uplink connection with the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But this week he received a letter from Loral Orion, part of
Loral Space and Communications in Maryland, advising him that
because of the order they would have to suspend their satellite
service immediately.
</P>
<P>
   He also received an email from the computer company Unisys,
saying that ``a full embargo is in place and Unisys equipment and
services can no longer be provided to Yugoslavia.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft had not informed the company of their intentions, he
said, but shipments of software teaching materials had stopped,
even though Informatika had paid for the year in advance, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see it right now not as business, but an exchange of ideas
and information,'' said Jakob Salom, assistant general manager and
a board member at Informatika. ``The first result would be to cut
us off from information from the rest of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite its letter, Loral has yet to actually cut off its
satellite service to Informatika. If and when it does, the loss of
United States satellite services would only restrict and slow down
services at Informatika's provider, forcing them to switch to
terrestrial lines and to arrange another satellite link through
East European countries or Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will not be a black-out, that is impossible on the
Internet, it will be a brownout,'' said Alexander Mutavdzic, one of
the company's Internet advisers, and like most of Informatika's
staff, a fluent English speaker. ``The Internet is global,
democratic and practically no one can cut it off.''
</P>
<P>
   Loral Space spokeswoman Jeannette Clonan told the Associated
Press that `We're still not in the clear on this whole thing.''
Loral said it was discussing its obligations under the U.S. embargo
of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration said there was no truth to
allegations that it was trying to cut the flow of information to
Yugoslavia, and said it would not try to limit Internet access for
users in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Full and open access to the Internet can only help the Serbia
people know the ugly truth about the atrocities and crimes against
humanity being perpetrated in Kosovo by the Milosevic regime,''
said State Department spokesman James Rubin, the AP reported.
</P>
<P>
   The National Security Council said earlier that information
services are generally considered exempt from trade embargoes, but
that electronic commerce is affected, the Associated Press
reported. The Internet performs both functions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
