<HEADLINE>
SECOND DRAGGING DEATH TRIAL TO BE HELD IN BRYAN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RICHARD STEWART 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEAUMONT, Texas _ After considering nearly 30 Texas counties _
and being turned down by many of them _ Jasper County authorities
have decided that the second trial of a white man charged with last
June's brutal dragging death of a black man will be held in Bryan.
</P>
<P>
   Testimony in the capital murder trial of Lawrence Russell Brewer
Jr., 32, of Sulphur Springs, is due to begin Aug. 30, state
District Judge Monte Lawlis said Friday in Jasper. Brewer is one of
three men charged with dragging James Byrd Jr., 49, of Jasper,
behind a pickup for almost three miles along country roads early
June 7. Byrd was decapitated when his body hit a concrete culvert.
</P>
<P>
   A jury in Jasper earlier sentenced Bill King, 24, to death. The
trial of Shawn Berry, 24, is scheduled for sometime this fall.
Berry's attorney said he wants his trial to be held in Jasper.
</P>
<P>
   Lawlis first ruled that Brewer's trial would also be held in
Jasper, but agreed to move the case after prosecutors said they
didn't want the location of the trial to be an appeals issue.
</P>
<P>
   District Attorney Guy James Gray said he and Sheriff Billy
Rowles visited almost 30 Texas counties before settling on Brazos
County. Some counties had scheduling conflicts or didn't have
proper facilities for a high-profile trial, but many officials said
they didn't want the trial in their counties. The first trial
attracted scores of reporters from around the world.
</P>
<P>
   During a meeting with officials in Bryan this week, Gray said,
one official stood up and said that while he, personally, didn't
want the trial in his county, he was embarrassed that others had
turned their backs on Jasper.
</P>
<P>
   Bryan, a city of 60,000 near Texas A&AMP;M University, is about 90
miles northwest of downtown Houston.
</P>
<P>
   After Byrd's death, Jasper was visited by Ku Klux Klan and black
militant groups. However, no demonstrations were held during King's
trial, nor were there any serious security problems.
</P>
<P>
   Lawlis said he anticipates issuing an order forbidding any
groups or individuals from having any demonstrations near the
Brazos County courthouse during Brewer's trial. A similar order was
issued during King's trial.
</P>
<P>
   Courthouse renovations in Bryan, due to be finished before the
trial, will increase security at the entrances to the courthouse,
Lawlis said. While the 85th District courtroom _ the largest in the
building _ won't be available until Aug. 30, Lawlis said he
anticipates starting jury selection about three weeks earlier in a
smaller courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
