<DOCNO> NYT19990514.0321 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7773 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ECON-REPORT-ART-960(2     05-14 1035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECON-REPORT-ART-960(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INFLATION RISES FOR APRIL, BUT ECONOMISTS SAY THEIR IS NO CAUSE FOR
WORRY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Inflation, driven in part by rising oil and gasoline
prices, moved up sharply at the consumer level in April, the
government reported Friday, leading some analysts to say that the
remarkable decline in prices over the last several years may be
over.
</P>
<P>
   But at the same time, economists are not predicting that
inflation is taking off. It is just that after the meager 1.6
percent rise in the Consumer Price Index last year, which was due
in a large part to plunging oil prices, inflation is now likely to
return to the 2.3 percent pace of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   On a seasonally adjusted basis, the CPI for April rose 0.7
percent, its biggest monthly increase in eight and a half years.
The so-called core CPI, which excludes the volatile food and energy
components, rose 0.4 percent, the largest monthly increase since
January 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not as bad as it looks,'' said Louis Crandall, chief
economist at R. H. Wrightson &AMP; Associates.
</P>
<P>
   Still the indication of an acceleration in prices was enough to
send stock and bond prices sharply lower and interest rates higher
Friday. The Dow Jones industrial average dropped 193.87 points, or
1.75 percent, to 10,913.32. But the index is still up almost 19
percent for the year. Long-term interest rates jumped to 5.92
percent, their highest in a year.
</P>
<P>
   Stock and bond investors have been worrying about inflationary
pressures for several months because the economy, which has grown
at more than a 5 percent pace over the last six months, has shown
few signs of slowing down to a speed that would prevent the Federal
Reserve from raising interest rates to curb growth and inflation.
Such a move, at least initially, would have a negative effect on
both stocks and bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Because of these concerns, the surge in inflation in April will
focus even more attention on the meeting of Federal Reserve
policy-makers Tuesday. While analysts don't expect central bank
officials to raise interest rates, policy-makers could send the
signal that a rate hike was likely if the April numbers turned into
a trend.
</P>
<P>
   The April surge in the overall CPI followed a 0.2 percent rise
in March and 0.1 percent rises in February and January.
</P>
<P>
   Almost half the April increase was due to a record increase in
gasoline prices, which jumped 15 percent. Overall energy prices
jumped 6.1 percent after a 1.6 percent increase in March.
</P>
<P>
   Food prices were up 0.1 percent after a 0.2 percent decline in
March. The index for fruits and vegetables jumped 1.4 percent after
a decline of 2.2 percent in March.
</P>
<P>
   The more worrisome 0.4 percent jump in the core CPI followed 0.1
percent increases in each of the first three months of the year.
The jump to 0.4 percent was driven by higher apparel, tobacco and
shelter costs.
</P>
<P>
   Apparel prices jumped 1.5 percent, their first increase since
August. Tobacco rose 3.6 percent last month after falling 3.5
percent in March.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, the overall CPI is rising at an annual rate of
3.3 percent, compared to 1.6 percent for all of 1998. However, the
core rate is climbing at a 1.9 percent annual rate, below last
year's 2.4 percent pace.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate economic report Friday, the Federal Reserve said
that industrial production rose 0.6 percent last month after a 0.5
percent increase in March.
</P>
<P>
   One reason economists were relatively calm _ and why the Fed is
not expected to raise interest rates Tuesday _ is that the April
jump in the CPI, so far, seems to be an isolated event. The other
important barometers of inflationary pressure are still in check.
</P>
<P>
   The pace of wage increases, despite the low rate of
unemployment, has been declining this year. Worker productivity,
which jumped a surprising 4 percent in the first quarter of the
year, is rising. The dollar is still relatively strong, meaning
that the prices of imports are in check.
</P>
<P>
   The index for prices at the producer level rose 0.5 percent in
April, but the core rate increased just 0.1 percent. And American
companies still seem to have trouble making any significant price
increases stick.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't remember a time when the CPI, in one report, told you
the trend was changing,'' said James E. Glassman, the senior U.S.
economist at Chase Manhattan Bank. But, still, he is thinking of
raising his CPI forecast for the year. But that is because he is
now forecasting a 1.3 percent increase, based in part on the
assumption that the oil price increase would retreat significantly.
He said if he was revising his forecast now, it would move to
around 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Ian Shepherdson, the chief U.S. economist at High Frequency
Economics in Valhalla, N.Y., said that without the tobacco and
apparel increases, the core CPI would have increased just 0.2
percent, which is what Wall Street was expecting.
</P>
<P>
   He said that the apparel increase was due to retailers marking
up spring clothing after being forced to cut prices on winter
clothes earlier in the year because of the mild winter.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the new calculation method for the CPI appears to
have understated price increases earlier in the year and could be
overstating last month's jump. The tobacco price increases,
Shepherdson said, followed months of discounting by producers. ``I
don't think any of this tells us anything about the underlying
inflation environment,'' he argued.
</P>
<P>
   But there were still some disturbing trends. Medicare care
costs, pushed up by drug costs, rose 0.3 percent and are up 3.5
percent over the last 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   Donald J. Fine, the chief market strategist at Chase Asset
Management, said there were also clear upward trends in hotel,
education and public transportation costs. In addition, there is no
assurance that the recent break in the run-up in crude oil and
gasoline prices mean that those surges are over for the year.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   One of the big questions for both bond and stock investors now
is what happens to interest rates. A move over 6 percent could
become worrisome if it undermined stocks by drawing investors to
the bond market.
</P>
<P>
   But Jeffrey M. Applegate, the bullish chief U.S. strategist at
Lehman Brothers is not worried. ``We are not going to jump the
tracks,'' he said. ``We are not going to change our asset
allocation. This is an outlier,'' he said referring to the April
CPI report. His year-end target for the Dow remains at 11,500.
</P>
<P>
   Abby Joseph Cohen, the market strategist at the Goldman Sachs
Group, said a at conference for clients that the country is not
facing an increase in inflation nor a spike in interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   In trading Friday, the Dow was pulled down in part by sharp
falls in IBM, off 6 3/4 to 239 1/4, and JP Morgan, down 5 13/16 to
140 15/16. Both stocks had jumped sharply Thursday, IBM on Internet
hopes and JP Morgan on takeover rumors. Friday they accounted for
more than a quarter's of the Dow's decline.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index, down 54.14 points, or 2.1 percent,
to 2,527.86, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's index of 500 stocks, off
29.76 points, or 2.2 percent, to 1,337.80, both fell more sharply
than the Dow. Both indexes are loaded with the often overvalued
technology and large growth stocks that investors have shunned
recently. Instead they have flocked to undervalued cyclical stocks,
which have rallied as the economy has shown much more strength than
expected.
</P>
<P>
   In the bond market, the price of the 30-year bond dropped 1
point and 30/32 to 90 22/32 while the yield, which moves in the
opposite direction, jumped to 5.92 percent, from 5.75 percent
Thursday. On Thursday bonds rallied sharply, and the yield dropped,
after the report of the restrained PPI increase and the
announcement that retail sales had cooled off, rising only 0.1
percent in both March and April.
</P>
<P>
   Investors had come to depend on the strong growth but low
inflation story, said Karen Arrese, head of global bonds at Bank
Julius Baer. ``But when you pose a threat to that story the market
doesn't like it,'' she said. She expects that long-term interest
rates will move back over 6 percent. But once that happens, she
thinks bond investors will start buying, pushing interest rates
lower again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-14-99 1939EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990514.0323 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7780 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-PREAKNESS-BOS &LR;      05-14 1161
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-PREAKNESS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM OUT OF THE CROWD, IT'S . . . MENIFEE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Slowly, but surely, Menifee is starting to emerge
from this pack of 3-year-olds, which once was considered tightly
bunched. All the buzz in Baltimore this week has surrounded
Menifee, who gained attention with a rippling run to finish second
in the Kentucky Derby May 1.
</P>
<P>
   Menifee, who looks great and is working well, was 7-1 when he
won the Blue Grass at Keeneland April 10, and 7-1 again in the
Derby. However, the Menifee buzz is building toward a roar, and
he'll be closer to 7-5 than 7-1 for Saturday's 124th running of the
Preakness at Pimlico. He's not only going to be the favorite, he's
going to be a big favorite.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's had a good two weeks,'' said Elliott Walden, who trains
Menifee. ``I'm very happy with the way things are going. I'm
optimistic. He hasn't missed a beat since arriving at Pimlico He's
on top of his game right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Menifee, a son of Harlan, out of Anne Campbell, a Never Bend
mare, is owned by Arthur Hancock and James Stone. Hancock bred
Menifee, a half-brother to Desert Wine _ who was second to Sunny's
Halo in the 1983 Derby _ on his 2,000-acre Stone Farm, near Paris,
Ky. Walden bought Menifee for a bargain $35,000 at the 1997
Keeneland September Sale. Hancock, who liked the colt because of
his intelligence and kind disposition, bought back half of him, and
the other half was sold to Hancock's close friend, James Stone of
New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   The only negative on Menifee's resume was that his sire was
considered a sprinter, and stands at stud at Stone Farm for a
modest fee of $5,000. Menifee's price was relatively low because
horsemen didn't think he had much pedigree. But, Harlan is by Storm
Cat, a noted sire of distance horses. Harlan was the exception that
proved the rule, and there is more of Storm Cat in Menifee than
Harlan.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a big, long-striding horse,'' said Walden. ``He's got a
lot of scope, as we say in the business. With his stride, he goes
like a big horse.''
</P>
<P>
   Menifee broke his maiden easily at first asking at Monmouth last
July, then took a talent-laden allowance at Saratoga, defeating Cat
Thief, who was third in the Derby, and Lemon Drop Kid, who won the
Belmont Futurity in his next race. Menifee captured an allowance at
Gulfstream in February, but suffered his first loss when beaten a
length by Pineaff in the Tampa Bay Derby. Because of the loss at
Tampa, Menifee was a middle-of-the-board choice in the Blue Grass.
Had he not been beaten at Tampa, he would have been undefeated (5
for 5) going into the Derby, in which he weaved his way through
horses after being four-wide, and far back, in the 19-horse field.
Menifee was flying, but he ran out of racetrack and missed catching
Charismatic by a neck.
</P>
<P>
   Walden, 36, is from a racing family, headed by his late father,
Ben, who was a noted farm manager. Elliott grew up on Dearborn
Farm, near Midway, Ky., and is wise about horses beyond his years.
Walden has been training on his own since 1985, has dominated the
standings at Churchill Downs in recent years, and burst on the
national scene when his charge, Victory Gallop, ran second to Real
Quiet in the Derby and Preakness, then denied him the Triple Crown
in the Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Menifee is the horse to beat,'' said Walden.
``Charismatic ran a great race in the Derby, this isn't sour
grapes. Objectively, though, Menifee was made the favorite here
(5-2 in the morning line) because more people than just me think he
could have won the Derby.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years in a row, Elliot has trained the horse who was running
best at the end of the Kentucky Derby, but he hasn't gotten the
roses. All horsemen want to win the Derby, but for one who grew up
playing in the Blue Grass, it is a burning desire. However, Walden,
who is a deeply religious man, as is Menifee's jockey, Pat Day, has
handled the two painful defeats with grace.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lose all the time in this game,'' said Walden. ``The Derby
is the most coveted race of our racing year. I'm disappointed my
horses got beat, I wish they had made it. But I handle it with my
faith. The Derby is not the most important thing in life. As long
as our horses represent us well, that's all I'm hoping for, to live
up to my capabilities as a trainer. As long as I've done all I can
do to prepare them, I'm all right. Both of my horses ran winning
races in the Derby, nothing we did caused them to get beat. I'd
have been a lot more upset if we made a glaring mistake that got
them beat, but that wasn't the case.''
</P>
<P>
   As with most of this group, Menifee is a stalker, which makes it
even more impressive that he adapted to the role of the closer in
the Derby after being knocked back from post No. 18. ``He was taken
out of his game in the Derby.'' said Walden. ``He'll be close in
the Preakness. He had one horse beaten when they straightened away
down the backstretch in the Derby. I give Menifee credit for the
way he ran. Horses get bumped around, but, the bottom line is, good
horse will overcome it, and he did.''
</P>
<P>
   Walden feels that Cat Thief, trained by D. Wayne Lukas, who also
trains Charismatic, is the horse Menifee must beat. He thinks that
both Worldly Manner, who was lightly trained in Dubai before
finishing seventh in the Derby, and the filly Excellent Meeting,
who was beaten up before finishing fifth, could go either way _
very good, or very bad. And he also believes Menifee is the
legitimate favorite.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do feel a little more pressure having the favorite, but I'd
rather have the favorite than not,'' said Walden. ``If I have a
horse at 15-1 or 20-1, I know I'm not in the right spot. The Tampa
Bay Derby was his first race around two turns, but when he lost, it
threw everybody for a loop. He lost an extreme amount of ground in
that race. The lost ground, combined with the fact that he needed
the race, contributed to his defeat. He got tired. If he hadn't
lost the Tampa race, he'd have been 3 for 3 this year, with great
speed figures, going into the Derby. If you're looking for the most
consistent horse, Menifee is the most consistent.''
</P>
<P>
   In 12 Preakness rides, Day has won five times (Tank's Prospect,
1985; Summer Squall, '90; Tabasco Cat, '94; Timber Country, '95;
and Louis Quatorze, '96), and has been second on three occasions
(Easy Goer, '89; Corporate Report, '91, and Cherokee Run, '93).
Day's remarkable record in the Preakness further enhances Menifee's
chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pat has a high confidence level in this horse, and that's
important because Pat has been on a lot of good ones,'' added
Walden. ``I'm very confident. I think if they ran this race 10
times, Menifee would win it the most times. I think he's the best
3-year-old in the country, but I'm not saying he's 5 lengths better
than everybody else. He needs to step up, and (Saturday) is the day
to do it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-14-99 1943EDT &QL; 
