<DOCNO> NYT19990514.0324 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7781 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-STRIKES-15-COX     05-14 1092
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-STRIKES-15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    YUGOSLAVIA CLAIMS ERRANT NATO BOMBS KILL 79 CIVILIANS
 &HT;    EDS: Optional trim at 700
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON Airing grisly footage of charred bodies and burned
out tractors, state-run media in Yugoslavia reported that NATO
bombs killed at least 79 ethnic Albanian refugees early Friday and
wounded scores more in a village in southern Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon and NATO officials did not refute the charges by late
Friday. They acknowledged, however, that NATO warplanes struck at
military targets in the area on the single heaviest day of allied
bombing to date, and said the allegations were under investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Still coping with the diplomatic fallout from NATO's mistaken
bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade a week ago, President
Clinton tried to patch up Sino-American relations in a 30-minute
phone call to Chinese President Jiang Zemin.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to advance diplomatic efforts to bring peace to Kosovo,
the State Department said its top Russia hand, deputy secretary
Strobe Talbott, would meet Tuesday in Finland with Moscow's envoy
to the Balkans, Victor Chernomyrdin.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin was scheduled to then travel to Belgrade for talks
with Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic, on what U.S. officials
hope will be a mission adding pressure on the Serb leader to accept
NATO conditions for halting the air campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going with the clearest possible understanding of what
will be necessary for President Milosevic to agree to and to
accept, so that we can suspend the bombing,'' said State Department
spokesman James Rubin.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're looking for is the acceptance of the unchanging and
unchangeable NATO conditions for a peaceful resolution of this
situation,'' said Rubin, ``and we have not seen that yet.''
</P>
<P>
   In Belgrade, state-run television showed once again gruesome
footage of civilian carnage blamed on NATO bombs.
</P>
<P>
   Survivors of the purported attack were quoted saying they had
recently journeyed out of hiding in nearby mountains to seek refuge
near the village when their convoy was hit by a pair of large
bombs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone was sleeping,'' one dazed survivor, Feriz Emini, told
Serb-run media, the Associated Press reported from Belgrade. ``I
don't know the exact number (killed). Many.''
</P>
<P>
   An AP Television News crew saw dozens of bodies, including two
children, burned beyond recognition and lying near two craters
beside a road. A group of four dozen women and children huddled and
wept in the cellar of a nearby home.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials stopped short of denying the attack. They said,
however, that Yugoslav forces had shelled civilians in the same
area, and they warned reporters to take Belgrade's media reports
with a grain of salt.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did have planes in the area and we were attacking
legitimate military targets and we basically don't know what
happened after that,'' Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon said late
Friday. ``I don't think NATO's going to be finished with its
investigation until tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier at the Pentagon, Air Force Maj. Gen. Charles Wald told
reporters that, based on the televised footage of the purported
scene, it was impossible to tell what caused the pictured vehicles
to burn.
</P>
<P>
   ``The area looks like it was attacked. Whether it was artillery
or a bomb, I don't know,'' said Wald. ``Somebody could have set the
vehicle on fire with a match.''
</P>
<P>
   With NATO warplanes stepping up their attacks on fielded forces
intermingled with civilians across Kosovo, however, Pentagon
officials could not immediately rule out the possibility of another
mistaken attack against civilians.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an environment that is rich for these kinds of
mistakes,'' said Gen. John Jumper, commander general of U.S. Air
Forces in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The attack allegedly took place in the village of Korisa, near
the town of Prizren in southern Kosovo, a province in the main
Yugoslav republic of Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL TRIM FOLLOWS &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The area around Prizren, a hub for Serb troop and police
operations targeting ethnic Albanians, has been the target of
intensive NATO bombing in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   Overnight Thursday, Wald said, U.S. and allied pilots attacked
more than 30 targets in southern Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   NATO bombs have resulted in civilian casualties in at least a
dozen separate instances since the air campaign against Yugoslavia
began March 24.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav officials said Friday the attacks have killed 1,200
civilians and wounded 5,000 more, figures that are impossible to
verify or to reliably refute.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials have admitted, however, that alliance pilots have
mistakenly destroyed a train, a bus, parts of a refugee convoy and
other civilian facilities, in addition to the Chinese Embassy in
Belgrade which was mistakenly bombed May 7.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Clinton apologized for the embassy strike which U.S.
officials blamed on an erroneous intelligence map during a
30-minute telephone conversation with China's Jiang Zemin.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who had already apologized three times in public and a
fourth time in writing, had been trying to reach Jiang since last
Saturday. Jiang refused to take Clinton's calls, however, until
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president once again expressed his sincere regrets and
condolences to President Jiang and the Chinese people
</P>
<P>
   concerning the tragic accident of last week,'' White House
spokesman Joe Lockhart told reporters. ``The president
</P>
<P>
   expressed his desire that we move beyond this tragic accident in
our relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile Friday, First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton traveled to
the Balkans, visiting refugee camps in Macedonia. She compared the
forced exodus of ethnic Albanians to the horrors of Nazi Germany
half a century ago.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. and NATO officials estimate that up to 1.5 million ethnic
Albanians have been forced from their homes over the past two
months by Serb troops, police and paramilitary forces. Roughly half
have fled to neighboring Albania and Macedonia and half are
believed to be on the run inside Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton vowed that all would eventually be allowed to
return.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not intend to let the evil which Milosevic perpetrated
against these people keep them away from their homeland and their
homes,'' she said. ``That is a very basic, fundamental commitment
that is shared not only by those in the U.S. who are committed to
this effort but our allies as well.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
