<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7788 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEWIS-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      05-14 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY:   ON A WING AND A PRAYER?
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   ANTHONY LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It would be hard to find stronger words in condemnation
of Slobodan Milosevic than President Clinton used in a talk to
World War II veterans the other day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Though his ethnic cleansing is not the same as the ethnic
extermination of the Holocaust,'' the president said, ``the two are
related _ both vicious, premeditated, systematic oppression fueled
by religious and ethnic hatred.'' Clinton went on to cite the
hundreds of Kosovo villages burned, the 100,000 men missing, the
rapes and mass executions carried out by Serbian forces.
</P>
<P>
   The question is whether there is in this president the political
will _ the political courage _ to match the moral force of his
rhetoric. The answer to that question will determine how the Kosovo
conflict ends: in the destruction of Milosevic's power for evil or
in a terrible defeat for Western military credibility and Western
values.
</P>
<P>
   Air power is the means on which Clinton has relied to achieve
NATO's declared goal, the return of all refugees to Kosovo under
protection of an effective international force. But the ability of
bombing to accomplish that result has, so far, been based more on
hope than confidence in a military strategy.
</P>
<P>
   The hope first was that, with a few bombs, Milosevic would cave
in. He did not. Then it was that a gradual escalation of air
attacks would force him to give way. That did not work.
</P>
<P>
   The top NATO air commander, Lt. Gen. Michael C. Short of the
United States, indicated last week that he had wanted to hit hard
from the first night at Yugoslavian command centers, electrical
plants and the like. That, he told Michael R. Gordon of The New
York Times, would have sent a signal ``that we were taking the
gloves off from the very beginning, that we were not going to try a
little bit of this and see how you like it.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the last 10 days the bombing has become far heavier. But
there is still profound doubt that air power alone can achieve
NATO's objectives.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in charge of aid to the refugees in camps in Macedonia
and Albania have been told to begin thinking about winterizing the
camps. The implication must be that there is no confidence of
success for the air campaign by September. The refugees are
reported to be losing hope of an early return.
</P>
<P>
   So if NATO leaders are committed to defeating Milosevic, they
have to start moving now toward the use of ground forces. And the
leader who matters is Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   It was Clinton who ruled out ground forces from the start: an
undoubted mistake in military terms, because it enabled Milosevic
to have his 40,000 men in Kosovo kill and rape and expel civilians
without having to worry about defending against a ground attack.
</P>
<P>
   Continuing to rely entirely on the air war may have serious
political and even moral consequences. We may succeed in destroying
Yugoslavia's economy without undoing Milosevic's savagery in
Kosovo. Think what that would do to respect for NATO and the United
States _ and to our self-respect.
</P>
<P>
   NATO has plans for what it calls an opposed ground entry into
Kosovo, and experts are updating them. What is needed now is a
decision to begin a process that will take months: mobilizing the
60,000 to 100,000 troops needed, getting them to the military
theater and training them.
</P>
<P>
   To give that signal would be difficult politically, and not just
for Clinton. The German government is divided, the Italians
reluctant. But if Clinton said yes, his decision would have a
transforming effect on other NATO members. The British and French
publics, according to polls, already favor the use of ground forces
in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   A move toward ground forces would concentrate Milosevic's mind
wonderfully. He is already showing signs of being rattled. His ploy
with Jesse Jackson and peace hints from some of his close
supporters suggest that he wants to find a way out that he could
call a draw _ and that would leave his internal position
unimpaired.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic has bet for eight years that he could outlast and
outmaneuver Western critics. So far he has won. If Clinton's will
matches his words, Milosevic will not win this time. He will end
his political life as an indicted war criminal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
