<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7795 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-CABS-     05-14 1219
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-CABS-515&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRIVERS ARE PAID TO SMUGGLE FAMILIES FROM KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SKOPJE, Macedonia _ Dr. Mustafe Abdyli and his family hid when
they heard a car approaching their house in southeastern Kosovo on
a recent Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The house had already been raided by Serbian soldiers who stole
a car, a tractor and even a pair of used sneakers, and Abdyli said
he and his family ``counted ourselves dead.''
</P>
<P>
   But to their astonishment, a yellow sedan with license plates
from Macedonia rolled into the driveway. The driver, a
mild-mannered man in civilian clothes, politely knocked on the
front door. Fighting an instinct to flee, Abdyli did something that
is extraordinary these days in Kosovo. He opened his door to a
stranger.
</P>
<P>
   ``He introduced himself and gave me a letter my brother-in-law
had written,'' Abdyli, a gynecologist, said. ``It said my
brother-in-law had hired this man to bring us to Macedonia, and it
was safe to go with him.''
</P>
<P>
   The man, who identified himself only by the common Serbian first
name Srdjan, is one of 12 Serbian and Macedonian smugglers in
Skopje who are willing to enter Kosovo, retrieve ethnic Albanians
and take them to Macedonia, at a price. Abdyli's brother-in-law,
who lives in Switzerland, paid Srdjan $2,000 _ half up front, half
on delivery _ to smuggle his mother, his four children, his sister,
his brother-in-law and his nephew out of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   With the border between Macedonia and Kosovo virtually closed
for the ninth day in a row on Friday, a bidding war is erupting for
a small cadre of fearless well-connected smugglers. Their lucrative
daily runs are continuing largely unabated, said border monitors
from the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe and
the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Typically entering Kosovo twice a day, the smugglers carry in
coffee, cigarettes and gasoline to sell to border guards and the
police or simply to bribe them. The smugglers return with their
human cargo, earning up to $5,000 a day, their customers said.
</P>
<P>
   As desperation grows, the cost of freedom is soaring. Abdyli
said Srdjan had become so busy that he was turning down business.
</P>
<P>
   ``The price is going higher and higher,'' Abdyli said. ``There
are a lot of people going to him. I spoke to one man who said he
would pay 10,000 Deutsche marks,'' or $7,000, ``to get his family
out. But he won't even talk to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Although money can be an advantage, even the rich cannot simply
buy freedom in Kosovo. The randomness of the spot executions
described by Albanian refugees shows that the wealthy, as well as
the cautious, can have their lives end at the whim of a person with
a gun. Serbian paramilitary groups have singled out the houses of
Kosovars known to have relatives abroad who send back money.
</P>
<P>
   In a handful of circumstances, like those of Abdyli, wealth is a
decided help. His brother-in-law, Fadil Idrizi, who has lived in
Switzerland for 30 years, said he flew to Macedonia to gain his
family's freedom, no matter what the cost. Dozens of other ethnic
Albanians who live abroad and have returned with money are doing
the same.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At the crossing between Macedonia and Kosovo in Blace on
Thursday, a middle-age Albanian waited anxiously for two smugglers
to return from Kosovo with his family. The man, who insisted on
anonymity, said he had gone to Macedonia from Bern, Switzerland, to
move his family out of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The man refused to say how much he was paying the smugglers, but
said he had heard about their work in Switzerland. ``When I was in
Switzerland,'' he said, ``someone gave me the name and number of
this man in Skopje. They said, `When you go to Skopje, he can solve
your problem.'''
</P>
<P>
   A taxicab driver here who also insisted on anonymity said he
made the hourlong drive to Prizren in southern Kosovo last week to
retrieve the son and wife of a close friend. The driver, an ethnic
Turk with a Macedonian passport, said he agreed to make the trip
after his friend had traveled from Berlin to Macedonia to move his
family out of Kosovo and the smuggler he had hired refused to make
the trip.
</P>
<P>
   The cabdriver's journey went smoothly, he said, until a police
commander seized the 17 cartons of cigarettes and the liquor that
he had planned to use to bribe his way through checkpoints, and he
had to pay a $200 fine. On the way back, at the Macedonian border,
the guards at first refused to allow the group to pass. But a
Serbian diplomat who was passing through helped them cross the
border.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I would go again,'' the cabdriver said. ``If
some good friend comes again that I couldn't say no to, maybe I
would.''
</P>
<P>
   After refugees reach Macedonia, money can buy a better fate.
Those who fled without being robbed of all their money and
possessions have often avoided being relegated to overcrowded
refugee camps.
</P>
<P>
   The Macedonian government considers those who enter the country
in a car to be visitors, not refugees, and allows them to go where
they wish. Refugees who can produce proof that a relative or friend
is willing to accommodate them in a private house are free to leave
the camps. Others bribe their way out.
</P>
<P>
   The exodus of Abdyli and his family began when Idrizi flew on
April 25 from his house in Basel to Macedonia. In a week, he
recounted, he learned from friends and relatives that his family
was still in their hometown, Smira, an hour's drive from the
Macedonian border.
</P>
<P>
   On May 2, he headed for the main border checkpoint in Blace in
search of a smuggler, Idrizi said. Recognizing a Serbian police
officer who was working as a Yugoslav border guard, he described
his plight. The officer gave him the name and telephone numbers of
two Serbian smugglers here.
</P>
<P>
   That night, Idrizi called them, he recalled. Both said they were
busy with other customers. They suggested Srdjan. Idrizi said that
when he met Srdjan that night, he paid him $1,000. The next day
Srdjan returned with the Abdyli family.
</P>
<P>
   At first, some members of the family had to live in a refugee
camp. But they eventually bribed their way out or moved in with
relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Abdyli now lives with 14 people in a two-bedroom apartment here.
He said he was worried about relatives who remained in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   A second effort, to rescue additional relatives, went awry last
week. Srdjan picked up Abdyli's uncle, aunt and other relatives in
their village, but he refused to transport Abdyli's teen-age
cousin, saying he could not guarantee the youth's safety.
</P>
<P>
   When the group reached the border, Macedonian officials, not
Serbs, refused to let the ethnic Albanians pass. Srdjan, saying he
had kept his part of the bargain, left the Albanians in the no
man's land between borders and departed with the $2,000 that he had
been paid so far. The stranded relatives managed to make their way
back to their village, said a neighbor who fled Kosovo several days
later.
</P>
<P>
   Abdyli said that he would not try such a risky rescue again and
that he held no bitterness toward Srdjan or the smugglers. ``It's
better that they go in and get the people,'' he said. ``It's OK
that they are taking money. Life is worth more than money.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
