<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUNS-SENATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE GOP APPROVES LIMITED RESTRICTIONS ON FIREARMS SALES AT GUN
SHOWS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (See optional trim) 
 
By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Trying to counter claims they are controlled by the
gun lobby, Senate Republicans approved limited restrictions on
firearms sales at gun shows, a measure Democrats and President
Clinton described as ``riddled with high-caliber loopholes.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders also indicated they will help pass a
provision to require child-safety locks on all guns sold, a measure
Democrats had pushed with little success before last month's
shooting rampage in Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   The 48-47 vote on the gun-show legislation came two days after
they rejected tougher gun-show sales restrictions and pushed
through a measure to relax laws governing gun-show sales.
</P>
<P>
   Scrambling to contain the political fallout from that vote
Wednesday, the Republican leadership came up with its own version
of gun show restrictions, which the Democrats characterized as rife
with fine-print concessions to the gun lobby. The measure was
opposed by all but one Democrat, Sen. Robert Byrd of West Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Republican senators ``know the public wants gun control, but
they're afraid to offend the National Rifle Association,'' said
Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Under current law, people buying firearms from a licensed dealer
at a store or a show must undergo a background check. Unlicensed
vendors, who sell about 40 percent of the firearms at gun shows, do
not have to run those checks.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, led by Sen. Orrin Hatch of Utah and Sen. Larry
Craig of Idaho, said the legislation passed Friday was designed to
require a background check on anyone seeking to make a purchase at
a gun show. The measure they muscled through Wednesday would have
required only voluntary checks in some cases.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said even the revised measure was flawed, claiming it
contains ambiguities about the gun-show checks, loosens current
regulations on pawnshop gun redemptions, weakens federal law
enforcement checks and record-keeping, and exempts gun sellers from
some civil lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before Friday's vote, Clinton said ``the new Senate
Republican bill is still riddled with high-caliber loopholes.''
</P>
<P>
   The measure sponsored by Hatch and Craig ``won't stop criminals
from buying guns at gun shows. At the same time, it will open up a
new pawnshop loophole that lets convicted felons get guns,''
Clinton said. ``It's actually worse than current law.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatch bridled at the president's assertions. ``The president
doesn't know what's in there,'' the senator said, accusing Clinton
and the Democrats of playing gun politics. ``I hate to speak ill of
my president,'' Hatch said, ``but he hasn't told the truth about
this from day one.''
</P>
<P>
   During Friday's rancorous debate on the Hatch-Craig measure,
which was being proposed as an amendment to a bill to crack down on
juvenile crime, Hatch offered to make corrections to mollify
Democratic critics.
</P>
<P>
   Sensing they had the upper hand politically, the Democrats
refused to allow the Republicans to clarify the proposed amendment,
thus forcing them to vote on a measure open to criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so tired of this stuff,'' Hatch said. ``We're trying to
solve this, others are trying to exploit it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Both Texas Sens. Kay Bailey Hutchison and Phil Gramm voted for
the Hatch-Craig amendment, but for different reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison said lawmakers should ``do all we can to keep guns
from known criminals'' and to ``ensure the law is applied fairly,
so that transactions are covered whether in a store or at a gun
show.''
</P>
<P>
   Gramm spokesman Larry Neal said the senator was ``indifferent to
the amendment because he counts it as inconsequential'' and would
have little effect.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the Senate overwhelmingly approved two other
gun-control measures _ one to prohibit juveniles from possessing
certain semiautomatic weapons, another to outlaw importation of
high-capacity ammunition clips. It was the first time since 1994
that the Senate had approved any gun-control legislation.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the Senate rejected a proposal that would require gun
dealers who peddle weapons over the Internet to comply with federal
licensing laws like most other firearms sellers.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch, a longtime opponent of gun control, said he will
co-sponsor an amendment with Sen. Herb Kohl, D-Wis., to require
anyone selling a firearm to equip it with a safety lock. The
Hatch-Kohl alliance makes passage of the proposal almost certain
when it comes up for a vote Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The various gun-control amendments are being pushed by Democrats
emboldened by public anti-gun sentiment in the wake of the high
school slayings in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Democrats have seized on a political issue, and I
understand that and regret that,'' said Sen. John McCain of
Arizona, a contender for the Republican presidential nomination and
one of a group of senators who helped engineer the GOP's reversal
on the gun shows amendment.
</P>
<P>
   With dozens of contentious, time-consuming amendments awaiting
consideration, Majority Leader Trent Lott, a Mississippi
Republican, threatened to yank the bill off the floor if the two
sides fail to agree on how to wrap up debate and vote on the
juvenile justice bill by Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The sudden burst of gun-control activity in the Senate is
``another step in the effort to outlaw guns by the media and
Democrats,'' Lott said, adding, ``We're not going to let that
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if the bill and its gun-control amendments pass the Senate,
its fate is uncertain when it reaches the House, where opposition
to gun control generally has been stronger.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
