<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990514.0332 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7802 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-GUNS-ART-2TA     05-14 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-GUNS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BY ONE VOTE, SENATE APPROVES REPUBLICAN VERSION OF GUN SHOW
RESTRICTIONS
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(rm) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a squeaker of a vote, Senate Republicans on
Friday passed a measure to promote background checks at gun shows,
one that Democrats, preferring a more stringent proposal of their
own, almost solidly opposed.
</P>
<P>
   In one sense, the Senate seemed like a chamber turned upside
down, with Republicans pressing for a new gun control measure and
Democrats fighting vehemently against it. In reality, the
Democrats, concerned about many details of the Republican plan and
convinced that the political tide on gun control has turned in
their favor, were determined not to let Republicans steal any
credit for seeming to advocate stricter regulations for firearms.
</P>
<P>
   The vote was preceded by intense bickering as members of each
party accused colleagues across the aisle of striking meaningless
poses and putting politics ahead of sound policy. The acrimony
underscored again how potent and volatile the issue of gun control
had become in the three weeks since the school shooting in
Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican gun show proposal passed by just one vote, 48-47,
as an amendment to a juvenile-justice bill whose fate on Capitol
Hill is uncertain. But the extraordinary political contortions
accompanying the gun-control debate made for high drama even this
early in the legislative process.
</P>
<P>
   Only one Democrat, Robert Byrd of West Virginia, joined 47
Republicans in favor, while seven Republicans sided with Democrats
in opposition to it. Four Democrats and one Republican were absent.
Byrd's office did not return calls seeking explanation for the
senator's vote.
</P>
<P>
   Other Democrats immediately lambasted the measure, co-sponsored
by Sens. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, and Larry Craig, R-Idaho, as a
cunningly crafted illusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hatch-Craig amendment has more special effects than the
new `Star Wars' movie,'' said Sen. Richard Durbin, D-Ill.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans said that Democrats were intent on vilifying
them. ``They prefer the gun battle to doing what's right,'' Hatch
said after the vote. ``And I tell you, it's driving me crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatch and Craig said that their measure would require all
vendors at gun shows, whether professional dealers or hobbyists, to
conduct background checks on prospective buyers. It augmented
another amendment by Craig, passed by Republicans on Wednesday,
that merely made it easier for vendors to conduct voluntary checks.
</P>
<P>
   After voting both for the amendment on voluntary checks and
against a stricter Democratic version, a number of moderate
Republicans grew worried that the party had embarrassed itself, and
they urged leaders to put forward a tougher-looking plan. But there
was serious question Friday about whether the new amendment that
Republicans passed was much different from the first.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats looked at the dense thicket of legalese and said that
it created a new category of vendor, neither professional salesman
nor collector, who would be exempt from conducting background
checks. Gun control advocates and Clinton administration officials
concurred with that assessment.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said that Democrats were wrong. But before Friday's
vote, Hatch tried to introduce a clarification that emphasized that
all vendors at gun shows were obliged to conduct background checks.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats rejected its introduction, saying it did not solve
many other problems. For example, the amendment would eliminate the
current obligation of pawn shop owners to conduct background checks
on customers returning to get firearms out of hock.
</P>
<P>
   It would, additionally, give licensed dealers more freedom to
sell guns at shows outside the states in which they are licensed.
And it would shorten, to 24 hours from three business days, the
time that licensed dealers at gun shows are given to conduct
background checks. Licensed dealers are already obliged to perform
those checks, but other vendors are not.
</P>
<P>
   Before the vote Friday morning, Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin
and Attorney General Janet Reno released a statement opposing the
new amendment. President Clinton derided it as ``riddled with
high-caliber loopholes.''
</P>
<P>
   After the vote, Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., said: ``The
Republicans take a step forward and a step back, a step to the
right and a step to the left. They are truly the gang who couldn't
shoot straight.''
</P>
<P>
   But Craig said that the pawn-shop and 24-hour provisions of his
amendment were simply attempts to untangle law-abiding citizens
from unnecessary regulations.
</P>
<P>
   He said he had written his amendment himself, but he
acknowledged having submitted it for legal review to a lawyer for
the National Rifle Association. Craig is on the association's board
of directors.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans who voted against his new amendment included
advocates of gun control, like John Chafee of Rhode Island, John
Warner of Virginia and Pete Fitzgerald of Illinois, all of whom
voted for the Democratic gun show amendment earlier in the week and
obviously found the new Republican alternative insufficient.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican dissenters also included strong opponents of gun
control, like Bob Smith of New Hampshire, Craig Thomas of Wyoming
and Michael Enzi of Wyoming, who clearly thought the new amendment
was too harsh.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Thompson, R-Tenn., also opposed the new amendment,
explaining later that he thought it meddled in matters that should
be left to local discretion.
</P>
<P>
   As the vote came down to the wire, Sen. Trent Lott, the majority
leader, and other Republicans hustled over to Smith and Thomas, who
did not change their negative votes, and to Sen. Richard Shelby of
Alabama and Sen. Conrad Burns of Montana, who did. Those switches
ensured victory.
</P>
<P>
   The close vote suggested that the passage of the juvenile crime
bill itself, which is expected either to proceed to a final vote on
Tuesday or be shelved for weeks or months, was in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   But Hatch and Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., agreed to meet this
weekend to talk about adjustments to the gun control amendment that
might leave Democrats happier.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   There is a separate juvenile crime bill in the House Judiciary
Committee, but it is unlikely to become a similar vehicle for gun
control.
</P>
<P>
   In another vote Friday, senators defeated, 50-43, a measure by
Schumer to prohibit unlicensed gun dealers from selling over the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   But Hatch signed on as a co-sponsor of a Democratic amendment,
to be debated next week, that would require the sale of safety
locks with all handguns. It was yet another sign of Republicans'
eagerness not to be seen as unyielding foes of gun control.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
