</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-SCI-DUKE-RESEARCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUKE CLEARED TO CONTINUE FEDERALLY FUNDED HUMAN EXPERIMENTS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING to change coding; no textual changes)   By PHILIP J. HILTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A four-day-old ban on federally financed human experiments at
Duke University Medical Center was lifted Friday after Duke
officials agreed to overhaul its protections for human subjects.
</P>
<P>
   Duke's license to conduct research on humans was suspended late
Monday, after the federal Office of Protection from Research Risks
found 20 violations of ethics and safety rules at the university
and said that Duke had failed to correct them over a period of
three months.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Ellis, chief of the ethics office, said in a telephone
interview Friday that Duke officials, who flew to Washington on
Thursday to meet with him, had presented a ``satisfactory
corrective action plan.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We will monitor Duke closely over the next year or so to make
sure the plan is fully implemented,'' he said. ``This is the
beginning for Duke, not an ending.''
</P>
<P>
   University officials said they were pleased with the decision
and promised to strengthen its protections of human subjects,
starting with an overhaul of its Institutional Review Board, the
body that reviews each proposed human experiment at Duke.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know action is required of us now, but we are now committed
to developing a model IRB program,'' Dr. Edward W. Holmes, dean of
the School of Medicine at Duke, said in a telephone interview. ``It
will make the university stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged that the resolution produced Friday could and
should have come months earlier, but ``the important point now is
to look forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Duke's plan, the university will have to make a complete
review of at least 274 experiments that had been approved by the
IRB, Holmes said, and possibly more. The university will also have
to retrain and educate each member of the review board, called the
Institutional Review Board, and put all experimenters who work with
human subjects through additional training as well.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis expressed relief that the negotiations went well and that
Duke's proposed plan is ``very good.'' He added that ``four months
of denial by Duke University Medical Center of inadequacies in
human subject protections finally ended this week. It is our
experience that some programs that have had problems like this in
the past have later become the best centers in terms of protection.
That could well be the case with Duke.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Puglisi, at OPRR, said he believed that the most
important part of Duke's new plan is the extensive plans to educate
review board members and scientists. They will not only take
courses, but attended national conferences on human
experimentation, and have regular lectures on human experimentation
and the federal rules that govern it.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble began for Duke late last year when the OPRR decided
to visit Duke University and conduct a routine examination of its
system for reviewing and approving human experiments. There are
about 2,000 such experiments there now, ranging from the testing of
new drugs and medical devices to behavioral research aimed at
improving patients' abilities to deal with illness.
</P>
<P>
   The OPRR, an agency of the Department of Health and Human
Services, monitors all human experiments carried out with federal
financing around the nation. They visited Duke at least partly
because Duke was the only one of the top 15 research universities
that they had not heard from for years. Most universities
periodically call with questions or to ask for advice.
</P>
<P>
   When investigators visited Duke in December 1998, they found an
array of irregular practices, most of them failures of Duke's
review board. The membership of the board was short on citizen
representation, meetings were apparently held and research approved
without most board members present, strict rules were apparently
waived with little discussion. There was no full-time employee at
the university to handle human experiment review. Informed consent
for the patients appeared to be less than the law requires,
investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   But what was most startling to the investigators was that after
a long list of violations were given to Duke, Duke's response
seemed to be less than serious. Investigators pressed the
university several more times, but still got only limited attempts
to come into compliance with the law, investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, on Monday evening, OPRR notified the university that it
was going to suspend the federal government's permission to carry
on research with humans.
</P>
</TEXT>
