<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7822 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORE-COELHO-2TAKES-NY     05-14 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-COELHO-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR GORE, COELHO BRINGS ASSETS, BUT MAYBE LIABILITIES TOO 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In 1981, Ronald Reagan had just become president,
Republicans had taken control of the Senate and Democrats were
desperately hanging on to the House as a last bastion. Tony Coelho,
a young second-term congressman from California, was put in charge
of raising money for House Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next eight years, Coelho revolutionized the party,
placing fund raising above ideology as the Democratic credo,
cultivating ties with fat cats and business interests previously at
odds with Democratic politicians and, in the view of grateful
colleagues, solidifying Democratic control of the House for more
than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Then, 10 years ago this month, having risen to the position of
House whip, the third-ranking post in the Democratic hierarchy,
Coelho abruptly announced his resignation from Congress, saying he
wanted to avoid the agony of an ethics investigation into his
personal finances involving a junk bond investment.
</P>
<P>
   Now, having earned by his own account a fortune on Wall Street,
Coelho (pronounced QUELL-oh) is returning to the center stage of
Democratic politics as the full-time, unpaid chairman of Vice
President Al Gore's campaign for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   He brings to the campaign a reputation as a peerless organizer
and tactician, a compelling performer on television and a natural
leader who can stabilize a team that seemed to be drifting.
</P>
<P>
   But Coelho, 56, also carries the baggage of a Washington
insider, more serious about strategy than substance, who introduced
the Democratic Party to strong-armed fund-raising techniques.
</P>
<P>
   This presents a potential problem since Gore has surrounded
himself with other insiders of a similar ilk and since the way the
vice president himself solicited money in 1996 is an obvious target
of attack from his political opponents. Campaign finance reform is
already a principal theme of former Sen. Bill Bradley, Gore's rival
for the Democratic nomination.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Friday, Coelho said he expected to bring
``enthusiasm, discipline and decision-making'' to the Gore
campaign. ``One of these days, you're going to write that Tony
turned the campaign around,'' he said. ``But that won't be true.
This campaign already is in very good shape, money-wise,
personnel-wise, any way you look at it.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he would not personally be involved in soliciting
donations. Asked for his philosophy on fund raising generally, he
replied: ``Let's make sure we have the right amount of money to run
a campaign. Let's make sure we do it legally and ethically and in a
way that fits in with the campaign. I'm not interested in getting
tobacco money when we're preaching about controls on smoking. I'm
not interested in gun manufacturers' money. I think we're going to
raise the money easily without violating any of these standards.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the leading Democratic politicians who are backing the
Gore candidacy say they are enthusiastic about Coelho's
appointment. House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt, said, for
instance, that Coelho would add much-needed leadership and
structure to the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., chairman of the campaign
committee for Democratic candidates for the Senate, said of Coelho:
``There are very few more effective operators in American politics.
He combines good instincts with a tremendous sense of organizing
and networking.''
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli, who was first elected to the House in 1982 with
Coelho's support, added a thought that was expressed by a
half-dozen other Democrats who served with Coelho in the House and
who were interviewed this week: ``My career would have been
remarkably different if it hadn't been for Tony Coelho.''
</P>
<P>
   But some Gore supporters take a dim view of the appointment.
They worry that the vice president will be tainted by soils on
Coelho's reputation.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, a former congressman who spoke on condition he not
be named said: ``I don't think this is something the vice president
needs. Here is a squeaky-clean public office-holder who needs to
make clear that he is an independent person whose fund raising and
other activities are completely above board. This association with
Coelho has the potential for raising questions that compromise the
candidate in that regard.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem is compounded, some said, by the presence of others
at the top of the Gore campaign whose ethics have been scrutinized
by congressional committees and in some instances the Justice
Department, though no charges have been brought. Those mentioned
include Peter Knight, chairman of the 1996 Clinton-Gore campaign;
Terence McAuliffe, that campaign's chief fund-raiser, and Richard
Sullivan, finance director of the Democratic National Committee in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Curry, who was a political and policy adviser in the
Clinton White House, said: ``Gore's problem is that this crowd of
people whose institutional connections are so strong aren't the
best people to enliven his candidacy, to give it substance and
clarity of purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   When those views were read to Coelho, he responded:
``Ninety-nine point nine percent of American people don't know who
Tony Coelho is. What they care about are Al Gore's views on
education and health and values. He's going to articulate those
things, and no one is going to pay any attention to me.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, Coelho's contribution to the ethos of
congressional politics was to integrate incumbency and fund
raising. It was detailed in a 1988 book by Brooks Jackson, ``Honest
Graft: Big Money and the American Political Process.'' Coelho is
the central figure in the book, but he said he had never read it.
</P>
<P>
   The book documented how Coelho curried favor with and solicited
large donations from shady savings and loan association owners,
some of whom were ultimately convicted of fraud that cost the
government millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The book also showed how Coelho had threatened political action
committees with retaliation if they did not donate money to
Democrats, how he arranged lucrative speaking engagements for
himself and his Democratic colleagues, how he fought against
campaign-finance and tax-reform legislation that might have limited
fund raising or worked to the disadvantage of Democratic donors and
how, after soliciting money from the Teamsters Union, he tried to
intervene with the Justice Department on behalf of the union's
president, Jackie Presser.
</P>
<P>
   In the interview Friday, Coelho said he had no apologies to
make. ``I tried to make campaign finance competitive and prevent
Reagan from taking over control of Congress,'' he said. ``I don't
back away from that at all.''
</P>
<P>
   In the spring of 1989, with the Democratic speaker, Jim Wright,
under fierce attack for ethics violations that led to his
resignation, Coelho came under fire for having profited from a junk
bond in what looked like a sweetheart deal arranged through the
firm of Michael Milken.
</P>
<P>
   Coelho quickly resigned from Congress, saying he did not want to
put himself, his family or his party through the pain of an
investigation. Later, he sought and received a letter from the
Reagan Justice Department clearing him of criminality.
</P>
<P>
   Coelho did not quietly slink out of town like Wright or Gingrich
when they resigned. He threw a big party at the Rayburn Building
with a Dixieland Band, and the next time he surfaced he was on Wall
Street, putting together business deals at the investment house
Wertheim Schroder &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   After Wertheim Schroder broke up two years ago, Coelho started
two companies of his own, an educational technology firm and one
dealing with backroom mortgage loan processing.
</P>
<P>
   He loves business, he said in the interview. Among the
conditions of his accepting Gore's offer of the campaign
chairmanship, he said, were that he would not be paid and that he
would accept no government position should Gore be elected
president. ``I want to go back into business,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While he was on Wall Street, he had one brief foray into
politics. In the summer of 1994, as the congressional election
campaigns were heating up, the White House made Coelho a senior
adviser to the Democratic National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The elections, of course, turned out disastrously for the
Democrats, with Republicans winning control of the Senate and the
House. Coelho said his entire role involved occasional political
meetings at the White House and a few television appearances for
the party.
</P>
<P>
   ``I advised,'' Coelho said. ``They didn't take my advice.''
</P>
<P>
   And what was the advice? ``I never comment on the private advice
I give,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-14-99 2011EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
