<DOCNO> NYT19990514.0340 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7825 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WPA-WRITERS-KAN &LR;      05-14 1128
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WPA-WRITERS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMAN'S VIBRANT SPIRIT BLOOMED WHILE WORKING WITH WPA WRITERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE POPPER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Betrenia Bowker is a petite and dignified
86-year-old woman who once ran with the wolves.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting recently in her pleasant Kansas City home, talking
quietly of old times, she dropped only the faintest hint that in
summer 1936 she fell in with the wildest bunch of writers,
painters, brawlers, poets and raw-jaw radicals who ever knocked
back a boilermaker in Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, that summer in St. Louis was hot,'' is what she said.
</P>
<P>
   And that can be taken two ways. Because it was hot that summer,
literally hot, 100 degrees for weeks on end.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first got to St. Louis, I actually saw the mercury
shoot right through the top of a thermometer on a building,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   She saw other things: Depression homeless sleeping in doorways;
union picket lines and unemployment demonstrations; radical
speakers on almost every corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a revelation.''
</P>
<P>
   And the heat to which she alluded had more than one source.
Fresh-faced and fresh out of Drury College in Springfield,
Mo.,Bowker had unknowingly leaped into a political cauldron.
</P>
<P>
   She had been hired by the Works Progress Administration to help
put out the Missouri edition of the now-famed WPA state-guide
series. The guides were prepared by unemployed writers hired by
President Franklin D. Roosevelt's New Deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the guide was way behind schedule,'' she said, ``and the
people in Washington were getting impatient.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowker saw the problem immediately. Missouri's project
administrators were at war with the guide's writing staff, a group
that included Missouri-born Jack Conroy, already noted for his
classic Depression novel ``The Disinherited.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Conroy and the other writers wanted to produce an honest,
literary portrait of Missouri,'' Bowker said. ``But the
administrators, real political hacks, wanted a sanitized,
chamber-of-commerce tourist guide.''
</P>
<P>
   When Conroy wrote a section on Missouri culture that highlighted
Ozark folk ballads and black music, he was ``reprimanded'' for not
hyping tonier subjects such as the symphony orchestras in St. Louis
and Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``The battle was on,'' Bowker said, ``and it was getting hotter
all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Missouri Writers' Program was based on the ninth floor of
the Civil Courts Building in downtown St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   From there it was a short ramble to the old Mississippi
riverfront levee, where the writers gathered almost nightly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd go down to the river at about 10 p.m. and stay until 2 in
the morning, drinking and talking about writing and politics,''
Bowker said. ``And when all those fascinating, worldly people
discussed their views on social justice, well, they made sense to
me. I became a left-wing New Dealer.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowker had grown up in southern Missouri, one of seven children
in a very proper, very conservative home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had twin sisters, two years older than I was,'' she said.
``And when they turned 16, they each asked for a raisin pie and
permission to say `Gosh.' That should give you an idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Privately, though, Bowker had read of Voltaire and the Age of
Enlightenment, and she dreamed of finding true companions to match
her secret rebel spirit.
</P>
<P>
   She found them on the St. Louis riverfront, eight or nine
kindred souls who made her feel at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fascinating part is that Betrenia was so plain-spoken and
intelligent that she more than held her own with those wild,
hard-living characters,'' said Douglas Wixson, a social historian
and Conroy biographer.
</P>
<P>
   ``She proved tough and savvy, and they all fell in love with
her.''
</P>
<P>
   Conroy was the leader of that literary wild bunch. Raised in a
tough mining camp, barrel-chested, stentorian-voiced, he bellowed
even in private conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd have a beer with him and imagine he was addressing a
huge throng of coal miners,'' Bowker said.
</P>
<P>
   He was bellowing more than usual that summer. In a constant rage
about the state guide, he blew off steam in riverfront saloons.
</P>
<P>
   His regular drinking crew included poet William ``Wallie''
Wharton and other guide writers such as Edwa Moser, Jean Winkler,
Jack Balch and Milton Lomask. They adopted Bowker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said I'd always wanted to see a barroom brawl, and they kept
trying to find me one,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They took me places (strip joints and honky tonks) where women
did things I didn't know human beings could do. We went to bars
with sawdust on the floor and people singing and making speeches
and reciting poetry from on top of the tables.''
</P>
<P>
   She was enchanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this your first cigarette? they'd ask me. Is this your
first shot of whiskey? Of course, they never took me along to the
really rough places where they hung out in East St. Louis. They
were very protective of me.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of showing her barroom brawls, they wrote her about them
after she returned to Springfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fightin', fightin', all night,'' Winkler wrote in one letter
to Bowker. ``One man'd go down and the winner would take on
somebody else.''
</P>
<P>
   And though they excluded her from the harder side of their boozy
nights, they did include her in their almost daily escapades, often
led by Wharton, a brilliant satirist and merry prankster.
</P>
<P>
   ``A men's clothing association was trying to popularize shorts
for men that summer,'' Bowker recalled. ``So they offered free
drinks to any man who walked into a bar wearing shorts. Wallie
walked in wearing his underpants. He got the free drinks.''
</P>
<P>
   Wharton also enjoyed playing a world-weary cavalier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hang on to your pure and lovely innocence, Betrenia,'' he
would intone. ``Oh, if I could just recover mine once more.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you ever recover it?'' she once asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ah, yes, many times, but I just keep losing it again.''
</P>
<P>
   After that summer, Bowker went back to Springfield to work as
the guide's regional editor there. She left the project entirely in
1937, as did most of her friends.
</P>
<P>
   The WPA Guide to Missouri remained mired in conflict. The book
was not published until 1941.
</P>
<P>
   The fears expressed by Conroy and the others proved
well-grounded. Most of their work was edited out and lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not what we would have produced,'' said Bowker, who
taught school for a while, married, moved to Kansas City, raised a
family and became a successful free-lance magazine writer.
</P>
<P>
   In time she lost touch with most of the St. Louis bunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``For years,'' she said, ``1936 seemed long, long in the past.
But recently those memories have been coming back to me. And I've
been thinking more and more about that wonderful hot summer in St.
Louis.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
