<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACKS-INVESTING15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Poll shows black investors growing
 &HT;    By Shelia M. Poole
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In the past three years, Lee Jenkins, a stockbroker
with Raymond James &AMP; Associates, has seen the number of black
clients increase dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say African-Americans are a lot more proactive about
building wealth,'' he said. ``I believe a lot of African-Americans
have realized they need to have their long-term money in the market
instead of the bank or some other place.''
</P>
<P>
   A recent poll commissioned by Ariel Mutual Funds and Charles
Schwab &AMP; Co. Inc. supports that view.
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 Ariel/Schwab Black Investor Survey examines the
spending patterns, upbringing and overall attitudes toward
investing that might keep many African-Americans from investing
with brokerage firms or mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``African-Americans have done more in the past year to better
familiarize themselves with the stock market,'' said Mellody
Hobson, senior vice president of Chicago-based Ariel. ``That's very
significant.''
</P>
<P>
   The study found blacks were more likely than whites _ 58 percent
vs. 46 percent _ to read books about saving and investing; to
attend an investing seminar (28 percent vs. 22 percent); or join an
investment club (10 percent vs. 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet has also served as a way for blacks to find
information.
</P>
<P>
   Among noninvestors, 48 percent of blacks and 34 percent of
whites said they were likely to start investing this year.
</P>
<P>
   The poll, of 813 black households and 816 white households with
incomes of more than $50,000, was conducted by Yankelovich
Partners. The margin of error is plus or minus 3.4 percentage
points.
</P>
<P>
   The study does not address whether the percentage of
African-Americans owning stock has increased. Last year's study
found that 57 percent of blacks owned stocks, compared to 81
percent of whites.
</P>
<P>
   Other findings:
</P>
<P>
   _ Black women are the least likely of all groups surveyed to
invest in stocks, but when they do, are more open to seeking
professional investment advice.
</P>
<P>
   _ When blacks were asked where they keep most of their assets,
44 percent said banks, vs. 31 percent of whites; 17 percent of
blacks said insurance companies, compared to 10 percent of whites;
and 30 percent of blacks listed mutual funds or brokerage houses,
compared to 51 percent of whites.
</P>
<P>
   _ The median amount blacks save and invest every month is $173,
up from $146 a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
