<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLOBAL-USWEST15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Global considers merger with US West
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In yet another sign that stock value can make giants
out of companies that are barely profitable, Global Crossing Ltd.
is reportedly in merger talks with US West.
</P>
<P>
   If the feisty, 2-year-old Bermuda-based company does buy US
West, the deal would produce a $17 billion company. It would also
leave BellSouth as the last of the seven Bells with an identity and
turf unchanged in the 15 years since the Bells were spun out of
AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of Global Crossing and US West declined comment. CNBC
and Bloomberg News reported that talks between the companies were
headed for a merger.
</P>
<P>
   Global Crossing in March announced a $12.5 billion purchase of
Frontier Communications, an acquisition that has not been
completed.
</P>
<P>
   The company's acquisitiveness has been mostly fueled by its
stock value, a tactic that allowed Mississippi-based WorldCom to
buy UUNet, MCI and other smaller companies, turning from a
minor-league long-distance company into one of the world's largest
telecommunications companies.
</P>
<P>
   Leading the charge for Global Crossing is Chief Executive Robert
Annunziata, who had been CEO of Teleport Communications Group.
Global Crossing was founded by Gary Winnick, a former Drexel
Burnham Lambert bond trader.
</P>
<P>
   US West has, like BellSouth, often been mentioned as a spectator
to the series of megamergers sweeping through telecommunications.
US West is profitable, but unlike BellSouth, it is not seen as an
especially attractive target.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Bacurin, an analyst with JC Bradford &AMP; Co., said Global
Crossing might see the deal as a route to a surge of capital.
</P>
<P>
   However, US West is the weakest Bell with a mostly rural region,
and it would not provide the kind of advantages that usually spur a
merger. For example, when Bell Atlantic bought Nynex, it added a
turf that was at its border and could carry millions of phone calls
from beginning to end. Global Crossing wouldn't get that with US
West, he said. ``It makes zero sense to me. I can't imagine you've
got a lot of sheep farmers in Wyoming who want to make calls to
Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
