</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEARS-CHILDLABOR15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sears fined over child labor laws
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The U.S. Department of Labor has accused Sears,
Roebuck &AMP; Co. of violating child labor laws, and the agency said
more investigations of retailers and other employers are on the
way.
</P>
<P>
   The federal probe found that 227 teen-agers were working at
Sears in violation of child labor laws. Sears allegedly violated
child labor laws in 44 stores nationwide. Sears has agreed to pay a
$325,000 fine, audit stores for problems each year and better train
its managers. Under an agreement reached this week, Sears did not
admit any wrongdoing. Sears, the nation's largest department store
and second-largest retailer, has 11,150 workers under age 18.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of Labor Alexis Herman used the announcement of the
settlement to warn employers that she's focused on more crackdowns
as the summer job rush approaches in a tight labor market.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very important that our young people have constructive
early work experiences, but it is equally important that their jobs
are safe and complement their education, rather than compete with
it,'' Herman said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Labor Department investigators in 23 states reviewed
employment records covering two years at 71 of the retailer's 845
department stores. Violations were allegedly found in more than
half of the stores investigated.
</P>
<P>
   In most cases cited, 16- and 17-year-old workers were operating
forklifts, freight elevators and other heavy machinery, which is
prohibited by labor law. In a few instances, 15-year-old employees
were working too many hours. About 60 percent of teen-age workers
have retail jobs, Herman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope this case sends a signal to other employers,'' Herman
said. ``Time and time again, we find that employers don't know the
child-labor laws in detail.'' Federal and state laws have different
requirements, depending on the age of the employee and the type of
work.
</P>
<P>
   In Georgia, child labor violations are rare considering the
large number of employers that rely on teen-agers to fill jobs,
said John Clark, child labor chief for the state Department of
Labor. The department depends on the public to notify it of
possible infractions. It also screens work permits for underage
workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the most part, unless someone calls us, we're not aware of
the problem,'' Clark said. The most frequent complaint stems from
employers who use teen-agers and children for door-to-door sales of
candy, cookies and magazines. In many cases, the youths are too
young to work, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people bring kids to a neighborhood, dump them out and
leave them unsupervised. That's a threat to the safety of the
children,'' Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   State and federal officials said parents should be responsible
for becoming familiar with their children's workplaces and
assessing safety. As part of its agreement, Sears will provide
informational material to parents of workers under age 18.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
