<SLUG> BC-WOMENOWN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    10 Georgia businesses on Working Woman 500
 &HT;    By Staff reports
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Ten businesses in Georgia, all in metro Atlanta, made
the Working Woman magazine 500, an annual list of companies based
on revenue, ownership, and title and duties of the top female
executive. The firms generated $80.7 billion in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Working Woman 500 celebrates entrepreneurship, not simple
affluence,'' the magazine said. For a company to make the list, a
woman must be the largest individual shareholder or must share
ownership equally with a partner or family member and hold a
position as CEO, chair or president.
</P>
<P>
   The highest-ranked company in Georgia is packaging giant
Printpack, at No. 18. Its chairwoman, Gay Love, oversees 4,000
employees and $899 million in revenues. Last year, Printpack also
was No. 18.
</P>
<P>
   Cathy Ellis, president of Atlanta Classic Cars, ranked No. 104,
up from No. 133 last year, said inclusion on the list has been good
for business. ``Women come in alone all the time, buying for
themselves. I tell the guys not to talk to women any differently
than they do a man,'' she said. ``We make it we try to make it easy
for women to do business here.''
</P>
<P>
   Janie McLure, CEO of No. 184-ranked McLure Oil, uses the list
partially to set goals for herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were disappointed because we dropped in the ranking this
year (from No. 130),'' McLure said. ``Our gross revenues are
heavily affected by prices of crude oil, and prices last year
plummeted. This year we'll probably do double we did last year. My
goal is for us to be in the top 100 next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
