<SLUG> BC-Y2K-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILL SEEKS TO CURB Y2K LAWSUITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FINN BULLERS and DAVID HAYES  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: A coalition of watchdog groups is asking consumers to
bombard Washington with protest letters, part of an effort aimed at
blocking legislation approved by the U.S. House this week that
would curb Y2K liability lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers Union, Public Citizen and the U.S. Public Interest
Research Group are leading the protest against the Year 2000
Readiness and Responsibility Act. A similar bill could be
considered by the Senate as early as next week.
</P>
<P>
   The House legislation, backed by the computer industry, the U.S.
Chamber of Commerce and other business groups, passed the House on
Thursday by a vote of 236-190. The legislation would put caps on
punitive damage awards, make potential plaintiffs wait 90 days
before filing suits, encourage mediation and limit class-action
lawsuits relating to Y2K.
</P>
<P>
   A similar bill was pulled from the Senate two weeks ago because
of protests from the White House and some Senate Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill pits the interests of big businesses that do not
want to be held accountable for their defective products against
small businesses and individual consumers who will be the ones hurt
by Y2K,'' said Joan Claybrook, president of Public Citizen.
</P>
<P>
   ``As one commentator has noted, this bill `looks like it was
written by Bill Gates on a napkin while having cocktails with
Donald Trump,''' Claybrook said.
</P>
<P>
   Public Citizen, founded by Ralph Nader, has set up a special
free fax service on the organization's Web site that allows
consumers to fax their senators from the Internet for free.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fax your senator to oppose Y2K immunity for big business,''
the Web site said. The fax site is at
www.citizen.org//faxserver//letter2//step1.htm. ---A couple is
hunkered down in their bomb shelter with a stock of pickled eggs,
kilos of toilet paper, potted meat, and breath spray.
</P>
<P>
   In another spot, hundreds of depositors are milling about a bank
waiting to withdraw their cash before a computer glitch leaves them
penniless.
</P>
<P>
   Claiming that ``Y2K'' actually means ``Yes to Kia,'' the Irving,
Calif.-based Kia Motors America advises consumers in a national ad
campaign now airing on cable not to worry about imminent disaster
as the century shifts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've taken a broad and well-publicized global event and
turned it on its ear,'' said Fred Golldberg, CEO of the San
Francisco firm that created the ad. ``The Y2K issue is full of
intrigue, suspense and fear. The advertising makes it humorous and
familiar.''
</P>
<P>
   The American Bankers Association is not laughing. They insist
Kia should pull the parody ads because they give bankers a black
eye. In a letter to the bankers and federal regulators, the car
maker says the spot, expected to run until June 1, is not intended
to create panic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ... a joke,'' Kia spokesman Monica Miller said. ``But you
know those bankers.'' ---
</P>
<P>
   Kansas National Guard officials learned two things during a
national Y2K communications drill earlier this month: Some
high-frequency radios don't work and those that do should be used
early in the morning or late at night when the signal strength is
best.
</P>
<P>
   As a regional control center, it was the job of Guard officials
in Topeka to send signal tests every hour for 24 hours to command
posts in Arkansas, Louisiana, Missouri, Nebraska, New Mexico,
Oklahoma and Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Some radios flunked the test, said Guard spokesman Joy Moser,
while some radio signals were weak during the middle of the day.
</P>
<P>
   Guard officials nationwide will run a similar test Sept. 1 to
see how prepared state armories are in the advent of a Y2K
communications blackout. Of Kansas' 56 armories, 21 still need
work, said Lt. Col. Mike Miller. The deadline for all work is Sept.
1.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is better to be prepared and not need (the radios), than to
need the capability and not be prepared,'' Miller said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
