<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-FUNDING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKERS SHOW KNACK FOR DELIVERING GOODIES TO CONSTITUENTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (See optional trim) 
 
By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In reaching a final agreement this week on an
emergency measure to finance the air campaign against Yugoslavia,
lawmakers demonstrated that not even a war can stop them from
delivering the goodies for important constituencies.
</P>
<P>
   Although steel and energy-related special interests lost out for
the most part in the compromise bill negotiated by the House and
Senate, defense contractors, Alaska fishermen and the states did
quite well in getting what they wanted out of Washington. The bill
is likely to be passed by both chambers Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison of Texas did better than
most of her colleagues by succeeding in having an amendment added
to the nearly $15 billion spending bill that would prevent the
federal government from sharing in the $246 billion the states have
won in tobacco settlements.
</P>
<P>
   The White House would like to use some of the settlement money
for the reimbursement of Medicaid and Medicare outlays, and
President Clinton had threatened to veto any final emergency
spending bill if it arrived on his desk with the tobacco provision
attached. But it appears that the administration will accept the
provision as long as states pledge to use most of the money for
medical-related programs.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison also got the House and Senate negotiators to include a
provision that would prevent the Interior Department from raising
the wellhead tax on oil and gas companies in Texas and other oil
patch states until at least Oct. 1. The department has been wanting
to change the rules governing the royalties paid by companies to
Washington on oil and gas taken from federal lands and waters.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time Hutchison failed in getting an amendment added
that would have provided millions in federal loan guarantees to
strapped oil and gas companies hard-hit by low prices. But
Hutchison's provision is similar to another measure authored by
Senate Budget Committee Chairman Pete Domenici, R-N.M., that the
Senate and House has promised to vote on later this month.
</P>
<P>
   Domenici's amendment, which would provide $500 million in loan
guarantees to small oil and gas companies in New Mexico, Texas and
other states, was rolled into another measure authored by Sen.
Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., that would provide federal guarantees backing
up to $1 billion in loans to economically-depressed steel companies
hurt by foreign competition.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd's insistence that his provision, which was designed
primarily to help one West Virginia steel company, be added to the
emergency spending measure almost ended up derailing an agreement
on a final bill. Byrd finally backed down and agreed to drop his
amendment after negotiators promised that he and Domenici would get
a separate vote on their measures later this month as ``emergency
status'' legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Both Republicans and Democrats had decried the Byrd steel
amendment, and the Domenici oil and gas proposal, as the epitome of
``pork'' legislation designed to help only a narrow constituency.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's original request to help fund the U.S. portion of the
NATO air campaign through Sept. 30 of this year was $6.05 billion.
But by the the time House and Senate negotiators finished their
work on the final spending measure that figure had nearly doubled
to $11.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   That final figure includes $1.8 billion for a military pay
increase, $2.5 billion for munitions, air operations and equipment
maintenance, and $919 million for refugee relief efforts and aid to
the frontline Balkan nations.
</P>
<P>
   The final bill, which the House and Senate are expected to pass
Tuesday, totals about $15 billion. In addition to the military
funding for the NATO and refugee relief operations, it also
includes nearly $1 billion in aid to Central American countries to
help them rebuild in the aftermath of Hurricane Mitch.
</P>
<P>
   Tornado victims in the United States also got some help as well.
The bill contains $900 million for the Federal Emergency Management
Agency to help replenish its disaster relief coffers in the wake of
the monster tornadoes that demolished parts of Oklahoma, Kansas and
Texas two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   The final bill also includes:
</P>
<P>
   _ $566 million in loan programs to help hog, corn and other
commodities producers hurt by falling prices.
</P>
<P>
   _ $100 million in aid to Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   _ $4.3 million in settlement payments to some Japanese-Americans
now living in South America who were forced into U.S. internment
camps during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   _ $26 million to buy out fishermen and others hurt by federal
limits placed on fishing in protected waters.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the bill contains a provision that would help
Houston-based Battle Mountain Gold Co. by delaying the
implementation of environmental laws designed to force hard-rock
mining companies not to dispose of their milling wastes on public
lands. The provision would specifically prevent the Interior
Department, for the time being, from cracking down on Battle's
Crown Jewel Gold Mine in Washington state.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Losing out in the final bill were families of people who were
killed last year when a U.S. Marine jet cut a gondola wire in the
Italian mountains. The Senate had approved $40 million in
compensation for victims of the gondola accident earlier this year
when it also approved disaster relief money for hurricane damage in
Central America.
</P>
<P>
   But the compensation was stripped out of the final spending bill
approved by House and Senate negotiators.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Chuck Robb, D-Va., called the decision ``regrettable,''
saying that Italy would interpret it as an ``unwillingness'' by the
United States to own up to its responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   The final spending bill, which Clinton is expected to sign, will
be paid for primarily from the federal surplus this year. But
Republicans insisted on paying for about $1.6 billion of the
emergency spending by cutting some unused portions of domestic
program budgets, such as food stamps, public housing and foreign
aid.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
