<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YUGOSLAVS SAY REFUGEES   HIT BY NATO BOMBS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES A. RADIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Yugoslav officials charged that NATO warplanes
attacked a group of nearly 700 ethnic Albanian refugees in pre-dawn
darkness Friday, killing as many as 100 and injuring scores of
others.
</P>
<P>
   Journalists taken to the scene by Yugoslav authorities said
bodies and smoldering tractors were strewn across an area near the
town of Korisa in south-central Kosovo where the Albanians, who had
been hiding in nearby mountains and forests, said they had pitched
camp for the night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometime around midnight, they bombed us from their warplanes
three times. It was a horror,'' said Dostan Rexhaj, 49, from Lodje
Zekaj, part of Korisa village. ``Many people burned up instantly.
We still can't collect all the bodies. They are all around the
place _ in the fields and nearby farms. They have been blown to
pieces.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO and US officials confirmed that heavy bombing had been
taking place in the area, but they said heavy shelling by Yugoslav
artillery was occurring, too. There was no immediate report of
physical evidence that the deaths were caused by NATO bombing.
</P>
<P>
   NATO promised a thorough investigation, and asked journalists
and the public to treat the charge cautiously because it might be
Yugoslav propaganda.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not know what damage may or may not have been done by
NATO aircraft operating in this area,'' said State Department
spokesman James Rubin. ``I would urge everyone to treat Belgrade's
information on this subject with extreme caution until NATO, which
has shown its willingness to admit when mistakes were made, has
been able to complete its assessment of what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday was the 52d day of the NATO bombing campaign, launched in
an effort to stop Serb-dominated Yugoslav forces from persecuting
Albanian residents of Serbia's Kosovo province. There were these
other developments:
</P>
<P>
   --NATO flew 679 sorties, the most sorties of any 24-hour period
in the campaign thus far, NATO spokesman Jamie Shea said. NATO
planes attacked tanks, military vehicles, artillery, and troops on
the ground in the southern Serbian province. The spokesman said the
strikes were particularly heavy around Prizren _ the closest city
to the alleged bombing of the refugee encampment _ during the day
and around Stimlje during the night. Bombing of power stations
blacked out Yugoslavia's three biggest cities and many major towns.
</P>
<P>
   --Support units for US Apache helicopters held their first live
fire exercise, signalling that the heavily armored craft might soon
see action in Kosovo. Two have been lost in crashes during training
exercises.
</P>
<P>
   --Opening a meeting of nine central and eastern European
nations, Ukrainian President Leonid Kuchman stressd his opposition
to the NATO campaign, and complained that his cash-strapped country
was losing $1.2 million a day due to the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   --German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder praised his coalition
partners, the Green party, for strengthening the government and its
determination to prosecute the war for Kosovo by rejecting attempts
at Thursday's turbulent, bitterly divided party congress to condemn
the NATO strikes.
</P>
<P>
   --Hundreds of waving children greeted Hillary Rodham Clinton at
a tent city for refugees near Skopje, Macedonia. Clinton announced
a $21 million aid package.
</P>
<P>
   --Nearly a week after NATO bombs destroyed the Chinese embassy
in Belgrade, killing three persons, President Jiang Zemin for the
first time accepted a telephone call of apology from President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   By Friday night, 79 bodies had been found, the Serb-run Media
Center in Kosovo reported, but said the toll could rise as searches
for bodies continued. Sixty-one people were injured, it said.
</P>
<P>
   Serb TV initially reported the attack was with cluster bombs,
but the media center later said that laser-guided missiles hit the
convoy.
</P>
<P>
   In Moscow Friday the Russian Foreign Ministry accepted at face
value the Yugoslav charges that refugees had been bombed by NATO,
and accused the alliance of a ``new crime.'' But British officials
said any investigation into erroneous airstrikes now include a new
element.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are now reports of Kosovar people being rounded up and
herded under bridges so that when NATO aircraft attack these
bridges, these people can be displayed as civilian casualties,''
British Defense Minister John Spellar said in London.
</P>
<P>
   General John Jumper, commander of US air forces in Europe, at
briefing in Washington, said that NATO is doing a good job of
avoiding civilian casualties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of nearly 20,000 sorties flown by NATO since the attacks on
Yugoslavia began, on 10 or 12 of those . . . we've had collateral
damage that's been an issue,'' Jumper said. ``These are probably
the best results we've ever seen . . . better than the normal odds
would indicate.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubin said that Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott, who
met Friday in Brussels with NATO Secretary General Javier Solana,
would return to Helsinki Tuesday for more meetings with Viktor
Chernomyrdin, Russia's special envoy on the Kosovo crisis, and
Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari.
</P>
<P>
   Ahtisaari, who will soon assume the presidency of the European
Union, and has broad experience in Balkan affairs, appears to be
playing a role in efforts by the Russians to broker a conclusion to
the fighting over Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   An administration official, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
said these meetings are intended to elaborate the positions of NATO
and the Yugoslavs to each other, so that a presumed eventual
agreement in principle will not break down over details.
</P>
<P>
   Thoough Chernomyrdin and the Russians are not in agreement with
the NATO action, Russia has nevertheless acted in ways the US says
are constructive in trying to end the fighting. Ahtisaari, the
official said, ``is connected to Chernomyrdin . . . and his
position meshes with ours. Chernomyrdin thinks he would be helpful,
and we think he would be helpful.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
