<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON PEOPLE AND PERSONALITIES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 16) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Labor vs. Airline: A Split Decision &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Faced with an effort by the International Association of
Machinists and Aerospace Workers to organize its 8,000 baggage
handlers and other cargo workers, Continental Airlines called in a
heavyweight labor specialist. Last month, with a vote pending on
joining the union, the company put up posters that featured Larry
Holmes, the former boxing champion, saying: ``You won the title by
working together. Why let anyone get between you and another
championship?'' He visited with workers in Cleveland, Houston and
Newark on the airline's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   But Holmes didn't stay in the airline's corner for long. Several
pro-union workers as well as R. Thomas Buffenbarger, the machinists
union president, sent e-mail to the champ to complain. He wrote
back that his message had been ``grossly miscommunicated,'' adding,
``My presence was to inform all employees to vote for what is right
for themselves and their families.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Holmes said, ``I'm not pro-union or
anti-union.'' Decades ago, he said, a union rescued him from an
unwarranted firing. ``If not for the union, I wouldn't have had a
job,'' Holmes said.
</P>
<P>
   Continental said that the boxer did not change his tune, which,
it said, was never intended to be anti-union. Ned Walker, a
spokesman for Continental, said, ``The message we were giving out
there was something along the lines of, `Think twice before voting
to change the direction of a winning team because we are already
champions.''' The voters' decision in the match will be announced
on June 4.
</P>
<P>
   Laurence Zuckerman &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Where the Chic Meet the Hip &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To a product line that includes Givenchy couture, Louis Vuitton
luggage and Dom Perignon Champagne, add Trailer Trash and Jail Bait
nail polishes (in silver or pink-and-white swirl). Such are the
brands LVMH Moet Hennessy picked up last week with its purchase of
75 percent of Hard Candy, a Los Angeles cosmetics company founded
just four years ago by Dineh Mohajer and Benjamin Einstein, then
both 22.
</P>
<P>
   The sellers' rationale is clear: They need a sugar daddy. Their
company soared, then slumped, leaving them frustrated and
exhausted. ``I tried for four years to play the role of business
owner, but I am more of a creative person,'' Ms. Mohajer said.
</P>
<P>
   LVMH's courtship of Hard Candy, however, may seem like quite a
culture clash. In fact, LVMH has been looking to buy its way into
the hip, young American market _ just last month it purchased
Bliss, a New York health and beauty spa, and the associated lotions
and potions.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mohajer and Einstein give LVMH access to the sort of
high-spending, fashion-forward 15- to 25-year-old customers who
don't know Givenchy from Guerlain.
</P>
<P>
   The two founders will manage the creative side of the business
while keeping a minority stake. Ms. Mohajer has already learned a
few lessons in corporate diplomacy. Regarding LVMH's purchase of
her company, she said tactfully, ``This is about rounding out their
portfolio.''
</P>
<P>
   Leslie Kaufman &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Will Streeters' Generosity Bloom? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Dow has experienced 11,000, Goldman Sachs has gone public
and mergers and acquisitions abound. But even Wall Street
executives suggest privately that maybe their colleagues could do
more with their fortunes besides expanding them.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it took Bette Midler to rescue the last group of 51
community gardens from the Giuliani administration's auction block.
Ms. Midler pledged the necessary $1.2 million through her New York
Restoration Project.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Wall Street was put off by Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's
description of those who protested his plan to auction off the
gardens to developers. They, he said, are stuck ``in the era of
communism.''
</P>
<P>
   But now Ms. Midler, through a lieutenant, has extended an
invitation to the financiers. ``We need Wall Street big time,''
said Joseph Pupello, the president of Ms. Midler's New York
Restoration Project, which has pledged the money. ``To bring Wall
Street into the community gardens would be a tremendous sign of
good will.''
</P>
<P>
   According to a spokeswoman, Ms. Midler has so far raised only
$250,000 _ none from Wall Street _ of the $1.2 million pledge. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Fuerbringer
</P>
</TEXT>
