<HEADER>
A7840 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-IMPEACH-BOS &LR;      05-14 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-IMPEACH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TENSIONS RISE AS YELTSIN IMPEACHMENT VOTE NEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Angry lawmakers traded insults and the Kremlin hinted
darkly of a ``war'' on Parliament as Russia lurched toward
Saturday's decisive vote on whether to impeach President Boris N.
Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   In a debate that was sometimes raucous, sometimes surreal and
never anything like the solemn legal proceeding it was suppose to
be, the State Duma lower house of the Russian parliament heard
arguments on five counts against Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   Duma leaders said only one of the charges, that Yeltsin
illegally waged war against separatist Chechnya, had a good chance
of gaining the 300 votes in the 450-seat house needed to pass on
the motion for review by Russia's two highest courts.
</P>
<P>
   Few legislators believe their vote to begin the lengthy
impeachment process will result in Yeltsin being forced out of
power. But the authoritarian Russian leader has made it clear that
he will not tolerate a ``yes'' vote on impeachment, and has
threatened to disband the Duma if it ignores him.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, the Kremlin issued a starkly worded statement via the
official news agency that Yeltsin would view any action to remove
him as a ``declaration of war.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin himself kept silent and stayed out of sight, as he did
during the first day of debating Thursday. Odd as it may seem for a
politician fighting the battle of his career, this is what the
aging, ailing Russian president often does during crises.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the statement quoted an unnamed senior official as
saying ``the president's response may be most unexpected.''
</P>
<P>
   That raised the stakes in a government crisis that began when
Yeltsin dismissed popular Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov Wednesday
and proposed as a replacement Sergei Stepashin, the president's
loyal ally and the head of Russia's 500,000-strong Interior
Ministry troops.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's military said it would not get involved, but everyone
here remembers 1993, when Yeltsin forced parliament to disband with
tanks and troops in an assault that left at least 140 dead -- this
is one of the charges against him in Friday's debates.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition deputy Stanislav Govorukhin said removing the man
responsible for these events ``would be the best evidence that the
country is becoming democratic.''
</P>
<P>
   But the chaotic Duma debate seemed instead to expose the rough
spots in Russia's young democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's most passionate defender was ultranationalist leader
Vladimir Zhirinovsky, an ironic twist of fate for the president who
frequently promises to do away with Russian chauvinism.
</P>
<P>
   Zhirinovsky shouted that if Yeltsin is impeached, NATO's
airstrikes in Yugoslavia could turn into ``World War III against
Russia'' next month.
</P>
<P>
   When Duma Speaker Gennady Seleznyov cut him off, Zhirinovsky
rasped: ``We'll pick up where we left off tomorrow, you'll all go
out of your minds.''
</P>
<P>
   Zhirinovsky refused to comment on a rumor that he had been
offered a post in Stepashin's government in return for the votes of
his 59-member bloc.
</P>
<P>
   A senior Communist lawmaker, Alexander Kravtsev, claimed Duma
members were being offered $30,000 to stay away from Saturday's
session.
</P>
<P>
   While these allegations tainted the proceedings, the chaotic
debate threatened to make a mockery of the proceess.
</P>
<P>
   Of some 40 witnesses the Duma called, only five appeared. Among
those who declined to show up was former Soviet President Mikhail
S. Gorbachev, whom the Duma wanted to give testimony on the 1991
breakup of the Soviet Union (another of the impeachable offenses
Yeltsin is charged with committing.) Gorbachev said he received
only a vaguely worded telegram, which he felt was inadequate for a
former head of state.
</P>
<P>
   ``They could have at least phoned me,'' Ekho Moskvy radio quoted
Gorbachev as saying.
</P>
<P>
   One of the witnesses who did appear, aging Soviet-era writer
Vasily Belov, whose speech was one of the stranger moments of the
day, said Yeltsin's guilt over a third charge of ``genocide'' was
self-evident and needed no proof.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched him come to power,'' Belov said in an unsteady
voice. ``It was all preordained.''
</P>
<P>
   One Communist lawmaker suggested sending out Duma security
guards to round up witnesses such as former Defense Minister Pavel
Grachev to answer questions about the 1994-96 war in rebel
Chechnya, or about the charge that Yeltsin destroyed Russia's army.
Duma leaders explained that the house had no right to do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``These proceedings in many ways are just a farce,'' remarked
Vladimir Ryzhkov, leader of a pro-Yeltsin bloc in the Duma.
</P>
<P>
   One lawmaker drew jeers when he ruefully commented that
America's recent impeachment of President Clinton ran smoothly in
comparison.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Americans worked well, the investigators had facts,'' said
Zhirinovsky ally Alexei Mitrofanov. ``They knew exactly when Monica
Lewisnsky called Clinton's secretary, what day, what time. Where
are the records of Yeltsin's conversations?''
</P>
<P>
   Records would have been nice, but it is unlikely they would have
changed anything. Most Duma members think Yeltsin is guilty, a
minority say he is not
</P>
<P>
   Some Duma members guessed the house would vote yes on
impeachment because after that, according to Russia's constitution,
the president cannot disband parliament. Others observed that
Yeltsin will do whatever he wants, and predicted the house would
back down to avoid provoking him.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday we will find out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
