<HEADER>
A7842 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-US-MISTAKES-BOS &LR;      05-14 1481
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-MISTAKES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECRECY CONCERNS MAY HAVE LED TO MISTAKEN ATTACK ON EMBASSY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES A. RADIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Fearful of security leaks, planners of the
disastrous US bombing raid that hit the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade
excluded from their discussions former US embassy personnel in
Yugoslavia who were intimately familiar with the Yugoslav capital
and would have known the location of the Chinese mission.
</P>
<P>
   About 75 professional-level federal employees worked in the
American Embassy in Belgrade before the final deterioration of
US-Yugoslav relations. Some were intelligence operatives; many had
spent years there.
</P>
<P>
   But due to the intelligence concerns about the danger of leaks,
none of these people were included in discussions of bombing
targets, according to a senior administration source. Instead,
people who may have been able to correct sites chosen from outdated
maps were asked to leave planning sessions on the Yugoslav crisis
when the targets were being discussed, the source said.
</P>
<P>
   Only Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright, who did not have
an intimate acquaintance with the potential targets, sat in with
the very small group of high military and intelligence officials
who discussed the targets.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the Pentagon and CIA had made full use of State
Department resources in their planning, State Department spokesman
James P. Rubin would not answer directly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me say that everybody involved has expressed their
apologies,'' he said, ``and everybody involved knows that a tragic
mistake occurred. Mistakes do occur. . . . We will continue to work
with the Pentagon and other agencies . . . and we will try to help
more rather than less.''
</P>
<P>
   The embassy bombing follows a host of lesser-known mistakes and
miscalculations that paved the way to high-profile blunders, such
as underestimating Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic and
overestimating the effectiveness of air power, according to
think-tank and university-based specialists, many of whom are
former US officials and current advisers to the government.
</P>
<P>
   These errors-behind-the-errors, they say, have deeply disturbing
implications for America's capacity to deal with strife and with
renegade leaders in the future.
</P>
<P>
   The American approach to the Balkans has revealed a flawed grasp
of the nature and intensity of ethnic nationalism, a capacity to
ignore well-sourced intelligence that gets in the way of political
policy, a lack of flexibility in the face of changing
circumstances, and a tendency to bluff without knowing what to do
if the bluff is called, the specialists say.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a sense, it was not unreasonable to try bombing to get the
Serbs to the (negotiating) table,'' said Ivo H. Daalder, a National
Security Council aide to President Clinton and coordinator of
Bosnia policy during Clinton's first administration. But before the
bombing started, the calculation was never that at a certain level
of pain Milosevic would come to the table, Daalder said; it was
that the Yugoslav leader thought the Americans were bluffing, and
would negotiate as soon he saw they were not.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not unreasonable to believe he thought we were
bluffing,'' Daalder said. ``We had bluffed before and not followed
through on our threats'' that were made repeatedly from the end of
the Bush administration right up to the launching of NATO attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was clear quite quickly, certainly by the end of the first
weekend, that a little bombing wouldn't do the trick,'' he said.
``The real choice on March 27 was to go in with ground troops, or
quit because it wasn't worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the United States recalculated in a way that
rationalized continuing and intensifying the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   A misreading of the lessons of the war in Bosnia, lack of a
serious effort to understand the Serb perspective, and inattention
to information coming out of Kosovo and Serbia all were apparent as
far back as the signing of the Dayton peace accords that ended the
Bosnian conflict in 1995, specialists say.
</P>
<P>
   ``What went wrong begins with the failure to follow up Dayton
with a full-court diplomatic press to resolve the Kosovo problem
peacefully,'' despite the widespread understanding that Kosovo
would be the region's next flashpoint, said Steven L. Burg, a
Brandeis University professor of politics who sources say is
sometimes consulted by government policy makers regarding the
Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   From September 1996 through early 1997, Milosevic and pacifist
Kosovar Albanian leader Ibrahim Rugova both were ready for a
peaceful resolution, Burg said _ Milosevic because he wanted an
easing of US pressure on his regime, Rugova because the Kosovo
Liberation Army was emerging as a violent force.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are so into the idea that negative incentives work with
Milosevic,'' Burg said, ``but at that moment there was a very good
opportunity for positive incentives (such as a lifting of
sanctions) to succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   In the spring of 1998, the US made a bigger mistake, attempting
to woo the KLA. ``It was a fundamental misreading of the KLA,''
Burg said. ``This was not a bunch of revolutionaries using force to
gain an agreement'' _ the goal sought by Rugova and the United
States _ ``it was a bunch of revolutionaries intent on
independence,'' and this was followed by ``a huge mistake'' when US
envoy Richard C. Holbrooke allowed himself to be photographed with
KLA fighters holding raised Kalashnikov machine guns.
</P>
<P>
   The impression given the Serbs was of US approval of the tactics
of the KLA. Then, that autumn, US negotiators at Rambouillet
refused to identify Kosovo as a part of the territory of Serbia in
their drafts of a peace agreement for the province _ insisting
instead on calling it part of the territory of Yugoslavia. Taken
together, these events convinced the Serbs that the United States
was committed to a policy of separating Kosovo from Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, a grave misunderstanding of the politics and
nationalist sentiments of the region sent policy makers down a road
from which they could not possibly return with an agreement from
the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``They misread the lessons of Dayton,'' said Joseph Nye, dean of
Harvard University's Kennedy School of Government, who was
assistant secretary of defense for international security affairs
in Clinton's first term. ``The price of selling out Kosovo was
higher for Milosevic than the price of selling out the Bosnian
Serbs.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, many analysts say, Milosevic would have had to pay with
his political life for giving up Serbian dominion over Kosovo _ a
price the US should have known he would not pay.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, the Americans took Dayton to mean that Milosevic would
yield to force, when in fact, they say, the Dayton agreement was
possible because of a balance of restrained military pressure
coupled with genuine concessions to Serb political interests.
</P>
<P>
   George Kenney, a former State Department desk officer for
Yugoslavia who resigned in 1992 to protest what he saw as poor US
policy making, said a sensible course has gotten harder to steer
due to the progressive demonization of the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Albright and others at the core of the Clinton foreign policy
team ``gradually talked themselves into a mindset where they lost
all respect for the Serbian positions, and started to think Serbs
were just bullies and cowards, not worth consideration whatsoever.
. . . They thought if we just kicked the Serbs a few times, they
would roll over and do anything we wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Kenney and others say, the American officials were
able to persuade themselves that the Balkans could be reformed in
line with Western democratic ideals _ a gross misunderstanding of
the region's nationalisms.
</P>
<P>
   ``People fear each other too much to live in areas where they
are not in the (ethnic) majority,'' Kenney said, ``and it is not
likely that we will be able to educate them to a different reality
for at least the next several generations.''
</P>
<P>
   MIT political scientist Barry Posen said American policy makers
``failed to recognize the power of the force (of nationalism), and
the particular malevolence of this power in the Balkans.'' As a
result, he said, they are pursuing impossible goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The West keeps trying togetherness solutions, and the only
solutions that are going to work are separation solutions,'' Posen
said. ``The Americans think they can keep (the various peoples)
together and do it our way _ not the way of the Turks or the
communists, who knocked heads together when necessary, but in a
democratic society.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's idiocy, saying we're not at war with the Serbs, we're at
war with Slobodan Milosevic,'' Posen said. ``They are nationalists.
They have a nation. That's the way they want it. The others want it
that way too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
