<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7845 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOSPITAL-DEATHS-BOS &LR;      05-14 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOSPITAL-DEATHS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-VA HOSPITAL NURSE COULD FACE DEATH PENALTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHELLEY MURPHY AND B.J. ROCHE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- A former nurse accused of murdering four patients and
trying to kill three others at a veteran's hospital in Northampton
will become the first person in more than 50 years to face the
death penalty in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Just two months after the Massachusetts Legislature rejected a
bill that would have resurrected the state's death penalty, US
Attorney Donald K. Stern announced Friday that prosecutors will ask
a federal jury in Springfield to sentence 31-year-old Kristen
Gilbert to death if she is convicted.
</P>
<P>
   It was Gilbert's alleged cruelty and cunning that convinced US
Attorney General Janet Reno to recommend a death sentence for the
first time in a federal case in Massachusetts, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Although there are 20 federal inmates on death row and more than
a hundred others awaiting trial in capital punishment cases,
Gilbert is the first woman in recent memory to face the death
penalty in a federal case, according to officials.
</P>
<P>
   Calling the murders allegedly committed by Gilbert heinous and
premeditated, Stern told reporters, ``The patients were murdered in
their hospital beds by a nurse who used her position and her
specialized knowledge to commit the crimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Since there is no death penalty in Massachusetts, if convicted
and ordered put to death, Gilbert would be executed in a state
designated by the court or at a federal facility in Terre Haute,
Indiana, which is equipped with a lethal injection chamber,
according to officials.
</P>
<P>
   In November, Gilbert was indicted by a federal grand jury on
charges that she murdered three veterans at the VA Medical Center
in Northampton in 1995 and 1996 by administering fatal overdoses of
the heart-stimulating drug epinephrine. She was also charged with
two counts of attempted murder involving other patients.
</P>
<P>
   After 37 patients died on Gilbert's ward while she was on duty
in 1995 and 1996, fellow nurses reported their suspicions to
authorities and a criminal investigation was launched.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, a new indictment was unsealed that charged Gilbert with
an additional charge of murder and attempted murder.
</P>
<P>
   If a jury convicts Gilbert of the murders, then prosecutors will
send them back to deliberate on whether she should be put to death.
A unanimous verdict is necessary for the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert's attorney, David P. Hoose, argued against the death
penalty in a closed-door session with federal prosecutors in
Boston, and later in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the biggest things we urged was that this is the type
of case that can never be proved to the level needed to justify the
death penalty,'' said Hoose, citing several cases in the past year
in which prisoners on death row have been released after having
been wrongfully convicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this case, there is nothing that connects her
scientifically to the people who were killed,'' Hoose said. ``No
eyewitnesses can say they saw her do anything to any of the
patients. Therefore, there is the concept of residual or lingering
doubt.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Hoose said he was not surprised at Reno's decision; he
cited the current political climate and the fact that the victims
were veterans as two factors in the decision to seek the death
penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Stern said that after meeting with a team of senior prosecutors
and considering arguments from Gilbert's lawyer, he made a
recommendation to Reno on whether to seek the death penalty. But,
he refused to say what his recommendation was, insisting that ``the
only part that becomes important to the public, to the defendant,
to the jury, to the court''is what Reno ultimately decided.
</P>
<P>
   Families of the victims were reluctant to talk about the case,
citing concerns that too much pre-trial publicity would result in
the trial being moved, said Christine Duquette of Northampton,
whose brother Henry Hudon was allegedly killed by Gilbert in
December 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Cutting, 40, of Leominster died on February 2, 1996 at
7:10 p.m. Forty minutes earlier, Gilbert had asked a supervisor if
she could go home early if Cutting died.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, the Springfield attorney representing Cutting's wife,
Nancy in a negligence suit against the government said his client
supported the decision to seek the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``When she first learned of what had happened, she was horrified
at the circumstances, and it remains her position that the death
penalty is the appropriate sanction,'' Astor said.
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert is also charged with killing Edward Skwira, 69, and
Stanley Jagodowski, 66, a US Army veteran who served during the
invasion of Normandy. She is charged with the attempted murder of
Thomas Callahan, Angelo Vella and Francis Marier.
</P>
<P>
   The last federal execution was in 1963. The death penalty was
rarely invoked until Congress, under pressure to crack down on
drug-related killings and terrorism, made some 60 additional
federal crimes punishable by death in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Henninger, of the National Coalition to Abolish the Death
Penalty, criticized federal authorities for pushing capital
punishment in Massachusetts, one of 12 states that doesn't have a
death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Massachusetts has recognized the death penalty is an
act of vengeance and an act of hatred and the federal government
has no business coming in and trying to impose something that the
state has rejected over and over again,'' Henninger said.
</P>
<P>
   But Massachusetts House Minority Leader Francis L. Marini, a
death penalty supporter, said, ``The federal government certainly
has a right to define its own crimes on its own property and to
establish punishment for those,'' he said. ``The state law never
takes precedence over the federal law.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, federal prosecutors in Vermont, another non-death
penalty state, announced in January that they'll seek the death
penalty in the federal murder trial of an Indiana man accused of
shipping a pipe bomb that killed a Vermont teenager last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
