<HEADER>
A7846 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      05-14 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL NOTES: TENNESSEE, GEORGIA, ARKANSAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Et Tu, Tennessee? Bumps in Gore's Ride
</P>
<P>
   It is an old story.
</P>
<P>
   Sooner or later just about every presidential candidate takes a
ride on the campaign roller coaster. And at the moment it is Vice
President Al Gore's turn.
</P>
<P>
   For many months, he was soaring upward, looking good in the
polls, getting rave reviews in the press, seemingly guaranteed the
Democratic nomination. But now he finds himself on the downhill
side, sliding a bit in the polls, getting sour reviews in the
press, his nomination no longer taken for granted and even in
enough doubt for President Clinton to step in and do a bit of
coaching.
</P>
<P>
   Loosen up, Clinton advised his famously stiff No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   The current Republican front-runner, Texas Gov. George W. Bush,
will take one of these rides too, sooner or later. Bet on it.
</P>
<P>
   But in the meantime, consider some new poll results that are
contributing to Gore's rough ride:
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, a Mason-Dixon poll indicated that even in Tennessee,
his home state, he is struggling. In theoretical general-election
matchups, he bested Bush by only three points, 46 percent to 43
percent, with 11 percent undecided, and then beat a fellow
Tennessean, former Gov. Lamar Alexander, by only nine points, 49
percent to 40 percent, again with 11 percent undecided.
</P>
<P>
   The poll, which surveyed 626 voters and had a sampling error of
plus or minus four percentage points, was conducted April 21-23.
Its director, Brad Coker, called it ``a warning buzzer'' for Gore
and added: ``It's still very early in the season, and Tennessee is
one of those states that can swing Democrat or Republican. But if
Al Gore's got to struggle a bit to win in his home state, then
there's something going on worth keeping an eye on.''
</P>
<P>
   Then came a Fox News poll, released Wednesday, that had a bit of
good news, some very serious bad news and some you-be-the-judge
news.
</P>
<P>
   The bit of good news:
</P>
<P>
   By a ratio of about two to one, most Americans would prefer to
have Gore than Clinton as a friend. And by a ratio of almost three
to one, most would prefer to have Gore than Clinton as their
business partner.
</P>
<P>
   The serious bad news:
</P>
<P>
   In a general election, Gore would trail Bush by at least 20
points and Elizabeth Dole by about 10 points.
</P>
<P>
   The your-call news:
</P>
<P>
   At least five in seven Americans believe Clinton would be ``more
fun to hang out with'' than Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Take the Bullet Train To Georgia as Planned
</P>
<P>
   In a Deep South state like Georgia, gun rights advocates are
particularly plentiful, and many political candidates, whatever
their party, welcome the endorsement of the National Rifle
Association. So when the association helped elect a Democrat, Roy
Barnes, as governor last year, Republicans groused loud and long.
</P>
<P>
   But shortly after the election, NRA officials sought to patch up
the damage, sending word that Wayne LaPierre, the group's executive
vice president, would be happy to travel to Georgia to speak at the
party's annual state convention May 22. Party chairman Rusty Paul
replied that LaPierre would be welcome.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the Colorado school shootings _ followed by second
thoughts about the invitation when the NRA came in for some of the
sharpest criticism ever and polls began to indicate that the
American public was becoming more amenable to tougher gun laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bad timing,'' said state Rep. Mark Burkhalter of Alpharetta of
the impending LaPierre visit, summing up the sudden new concern in
the ranks of Georgia Republicans. He suggested that Paul do the
``prudent thing'' and withdraw the invitation until things cooled a
bit.
</P>
<P>
   Paul weighed his dilemma, worried about whether canceling the
speech or going through with it would cause the most division and
embarrassment within the party, and worried, too, about how to keep
the peace with the NRA.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of days ago he made up his mind and announced:
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to withdraw the invitation.''
</P>
<P>
   Why the hard line, especially at a moment when congressional
Republicans show signs of softening on the gun-control issue?
</P>
<P>
   To pull back the invitation, Paul said, would be tantamount to
blaming the NRA for the Colorado killings.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans Gaining In Democratic Bastion
</P>
<P>
   Chalk up more Republican resurgence in the South, this time in
Arkansas, perhaps the most Democratic state left in Dixie.
</P>
<P>
   The party's gains there have been glacial in recent years,
compared with progress elsewhere, from Virginia to Texas. But
Tuesday there was a major gain, one that left Republicans on the
verge of becoming real players rather than bystanders in the state
legislature.
</P>
<P>
   In a special election to fill a vacant seat in the Arkansas
House, a Republican emerged the winner, meaning that Republicans
now hold 25 of the 100 seats there.
</P>
<P>
   The political point is this: In the Arkansas House, it takes 75
votes, not the usual 51, to pass most appropriations bills. So all
the Republicans need do now is vote as a solid bloc and woo across
a single dissident Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   And that's not all.
</P>
<P>
   Next year, because of term limits, 25 more seats will be up for
grabs in the House _ 22 of them held by Democrats.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
