<SLUG> BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS TOP MANAGEMENT SAFE, OWNER JACOBS SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   No matter what happens in this playoff season with the Bruins,
owner Jerry Jacobs wants his Big Three to remain in place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harry Sinden can stay as long as he wants, even another 27
years,'' said Jacobs with a laugh Friday. ``And Mike O'Connell will
be his successor when Harry decides to make a move. I like Mike a
lot. In some ways, he is even tougher than Harry, and more to the
right of Harry, if that's possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``But just as important, I want Pat Burns to be our Scotty
Bowman. I want him to be a career coach, and not just another stop
along the way in his coaching career. I think he is the perfect guy
to coach this Bruins team.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs feels not enough has been said about how the Bruins have
come from the worst record in the league just a couple of years ago
and are now one of the up-and-coming teams in the National Hockey
League.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think those three guys have done a great job getting us to
where we are,'' said Jacobs. ``I like the way they fit together.''
Jacobs, however, made it clear that he does not intend to spend a
lot of money to make his team a winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``That will not happen,'' he said. ``As long as I own this team,
it will make money. We are a business. I'm not going to go out and
do what some of these owners have done in this league, spend so
foolishly that they have put the league in terrible shape. And this
league is in terrible shape. Lucky for us, we've got a great
commissioner who is trying to jawbone this thing back to reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bruins make money, and will continue to make money. But we
do not make nearly the money people say we do. I am not trying to
make a lot of money with the team, I'm just not going to lose any.
And I'm not going to be foolish like some other owners who spent so
much money on players, they are now losing a ton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pittsburgh is bankrupt. Imagine having a team that can win the
Stanley Cup and maybe having to move it. Colorado was sold because
the owner spent so much money he couldn't afford it anymore. Abe
Pollin is selling in Washington because he lost so much money. And
who knows what Detroit is doing? What is that all about? If I do
what those owners have done, in five years I would have to sell
this team myself. I couldn't afford to be able to keep it. But I'm
not going to sell this team. I like it, and I think we have a great
future with the people we have running the show for me, and the
young players we have.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fred Lynn thinks what he did in '75 and Nomar Garciaparra did
last Monday, hitting three homers and knocking in 10 runs in a
game, was exceptional. But nothing compared to what Marshall
McDougall did last Sunday for Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was unbelievable,'' says Lynn, the former Red Sox
All-Star center fielder. ``You could take a major leaguer down to a
Little League field, let him use a titanium bat, and he couldn't
hit six straight home runs. To do something like that is
incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   McDougall is an infielder for a very good Florida State (43-10)
team. In a game last Sunday in Maryland, he singled his first
at-bat and then homered six straight times, finishing with 16 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are really upset with me down here,'' says Maryland
coach Tom Bradley, a former major league pitcher. ``I've been
criticized for pitching to him his last at-bat. But what was I
supposed to do? Walk him with the bases loaded and force in a run?
No way I was going to do that. Give him credit. My pitcher made a
good pitch down and away, and he went out and got it and hit it
over the center-field fence. I take my hat off to him.''
</P>
<P>
   But the 7 for 7 and 16 RBIs is not the whole story. In his final
two at-bats the day before, McDougall went 2 for 2 with a single
and a three-run homer. So that would make him 9 for 9 with seven
HRs and 19 RBIs in that stretch, unmatched in the history of
high-level baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they came in here for that series, I watched him taking
batting practice, and he hit six in a row out,'' Bradley said. ``I
said to myself, `This kid is swinging the bat pretty good.' And he
was.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynn still remembers his explosive night in Detroit in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   ``That season, and in 1979, I just felt like I could hit
everything they were throwing at me,'' he said. ``In both of those
seasons I was completely healthy and swinging the bat with great
confidence. (Joe) Coleman was pitching that night in Detroit. I
went homer, homer, triple in the first three innings. When you are
in a groove like that, every pitch the ball seems big, and in slow
motion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter who the pitcher is, what the pitch is, or
where he throws it, as long as you see it, you feel you can kill
it. The first homer went into the upper deck. The next one went on
the roof. The triple hit the top of the fence in left field, and
just missed being a homer. Then I lined out to the gap in
right-center, got an infield hit, and then came up in the ninth
with two guys on. We were way ahead and by then most of our
starters had dressed and left the ballpark. I hit a three-run homer
in the ninth.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynn will be back in Boston to celebrate All-Star weekend, with
some other great Red Sox stars of the past.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley was also well aware of Garciaparra's exploits.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was great whenever he played against us for Georgia Tech,''
Bradley said. ``You just knew he was going to be a big-time
ballplayer. I can remember him coming in here, and we would pitch
him away, so he would hit the ball to the opposite field and over
the right-field fence. He could adjust to the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the past month, after nearly two decades of being invisible,
Bill Russell has been all over the media, trying to hustle business
for the tribute in his honor at the FleetCenter, scheduled for May
26.
</P>
<P>
   However, despite Russell's best efforts, as this is being
written, the event is a bomb. The FleetCenter can hold close to
20,000 for an event like this. At present, fewer than 3,000 tickets
have been sold. The high-priced item, which is supposed to raise
most of the money, is 100 tables on the floor near the stage, where
the likes of Bill Cosby, Julius Erving, and Aretha Franklin are
among a brilliant cast expected to pay tribute to Russell.
</P>
<P>
   Russell has been on national television, local radio, been
featured in Sports Illustrated and USA Today, had tremendous
exposure, a ton of paid newspaper ads, and still, great
disappointment. There has been behind-the-scenes talk of calling it
off, or moving to a hotel ballroom or smaller venue, where 3,000
would be a great crowd. After 30 years out of the game, filling
20,000 seats was just too much even for Russell, one of the
greatest ever. This isn't like Larry Bird coming back a few months
after his last game.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of selling, it appears the Boston businessmen trying to
sell luxury boxes in the proposed new stadium in Foxborough are off
to a good start.
</P>
<P>
   Your humble correspondent has been told that all eight $325,000
super boxes have been sold, showing there are heavy hitters willing
to pay box-office numbers to buy in Foxborough. This is a good sign
because it will be the money raised from these boxes, plus
preferred seating, that will ultimately pay for the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, Ray Bourque went to Massachusetts General
Hospital for a complete physical, which he needed for an insurance
policy that would cover his contract. Part of the exam included a
stress test, which would normally have been given to people over 45
who might have signs of impending heart problems.
</P>
<P>
   Bourque finished it, which astonished the people who have given
thousands of these tests over the years. He is the only one ever to
do it in that particular testing room in the hospital. However,
when the test results were sent to Dr. Jim Dineen, one of the very
best in the city, he questioned if Bourque might have emphysema
because his lung capacity was so great, his lungs were the size of
those who belonged to someone who appeared to have difficulty
breathing.
</P>
<P>
   The point of the story goes to Bourque's incredible endurance
for the Bruins. After 20 NHL seasons, and at age 38, he is a
medical marvel, logging nearly 30 minutes a game during the regular
season, and more than that in the playoffs. During the test,
Bourque was told at the 15/16ths mark that he could stop, because
they had seen everything they needed to know. But Bourque, not
knowing he was making MGH history, said he may as well finish
because he wanted to have a good workout.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Celtics general manager Chris Wallace's possible lottery picks
in the upcoming draft, depending upon how many more underclassmen
declare themselves eligible before midnight Sunday, are:
</P>
<P>
   1. Elton Brand, 6 feet 7 inches, Duke; 2. Steve Francis, 6-3,
Maryland; 3. Baron Davis, 6-2, UCLA; 4. Richard Hamilton, 6-6,
UConn; 5. Andre Miller, 6-2, Utah; 7. Wally Szczerbiak, 6-7, Miami
of Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Other possibilities: Lamar Odom, URI; Corey Maggette, Duke;
Jonathan Bender, Picayune (Miss.) High School. Odom and Maggette
have yet to declare, and the Rams' star could be in the top two in
the draft if he comes out.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some mystery surrounds two of the top high school basketball
players to come out of Massachusetts in recent years _ Mike Bradley
and Adam Harrington. Bradley, from Worcester, played center for
Kentucky last year, and told coach Tubby Smith he was leaving.
However, he reportedly told him he was leaving to go to Ohio State,
which is supposed to be illegal. A player transferring is not
supposed to have any contact with another school until after he
leaves the first. Kentucky, supposedly, is waiting to see if
Bradley shows up at Ohio State, and if he does, will launch a
protest with the NCAA.
</P>
<P>
   Harrington reportedly is back in his hometown in Western
Massachusetts, after checking out of North Carolina State after his
freshman year. Harrington started as a freshman, and the word is he
recently visited Iowa. There was speculation he would come back to
the University of Massachusetts, just miles from his home, but
UMass has heard nothing from him.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Todd Hynes gets the bragging rights this week in his Brookline,
Mass. home, from adopted brother Joe Thornton. Todd was named the
outstanding freshman athlete at MIT, where he started in football
and lacrosse . . . Vancouver could have the first pick in both the
NHL (Canucks) and NBA (Grizzlies) drafts this year if things break
right in the lottery. Which was the last city to have two
first-round picks in two pro drafts in the same year? In 1982, the
Patriots had the first pick and took Kenneth Sims, and the Bruins
used the first pick to take Gord Kluzak. Also, only two players
performed on the same team with both Bobby Orr and Wayne Gretzky in
the NHL: Ace Bailey and Bobby Schmautz. Bailey told a friend he
didn't want to pick one over the other because of his relationship
with both, but Schmautz didn't mind. ``The best player I played
with, and the best player I played against, was Bobby Orr. One was
protected (Gretzky), the other was a target (Orr).''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-14-99 2024EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990514.0358 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7851 &Cx1f; ttc-z
