<SLUG> BC-STARWARS-MUSIC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCORE ANOTHER ONE FOR JOHN WILLIAMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
Our rating: 3 stars 
By FRED SHUSTER 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Even if you're immune to ``Star Wars'' on screen,
you've got to hand it to composer John Williams for showing some
growth when he could have simply coasted on past triumphs.
</P>
<P>
   The entertaining score to ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom
Menace'' is a fluid mixture of whimsical and adventurous elements
that actually holds up on its own. Some of the themes are instantly
familiar _ the ``Star Wars'' main title, of course _ but there are
plenty of ambitious new sounds on display.
</P>
<P>
   Williams breaks ground by using synthesizer on some tracks,
making possible jarring moments that crackle across your living
room like the fabulous Pod race you'll see when the film reaches
theaters Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Current radio fave ``Duel of the Fates'' features a dark,
pulsating rhythm that contrasts with other set pieces, such as the
strings-driven homage ``Anakin's Theme'' or ``Augie's Great
Municipal Band,'' with its kids' chorus and whistles.
</P>
<P>
   Some ``Star Wars'' themes have always been derivative of golden
age movie composers like Miklos Rozsa, and the dramatic wide-screen
sweep certainly has paid off: The original album outsold every
other soundtrack in history.
</P>
<P>
   Included in the package _ and if you want to be completely
surprised when you see the film, don't read the plot-spoiling track
listing _ is a tribute to Williams by filmmaker George Lucas.
</P>
<P>
   ``John had to draw upon the signature themes while creating a
new, if somehow familiar, musical galaxy,'' he writes. ``And he had
to visit new emotional territory in Episode I. Once again, John has
exceeded my expectations and produced a lavish, rich, moving and
thrilling score.''
</P>
<P>
   The only drawback: While the package promises a poster, it's
actually about the size of a pamphlet. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
