<SLUG> BC-SENATE-GUNS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICS SWIRL AROUND PASSAGE OF REVAMPED GUN-CONTROL MEASURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOUISE D. PALMER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Amid anger and partisan finger-pointing, the Senate
narrowly approved a Republican gun-control provision requiring
background checks at gun shows, underlining the political potency
of the issue and foreshadowing the skirmishing for the 2000
elections.
</P>
<P>
   The 48-47 vote capped an abrupt turnaround by Republicans, who
Wednesday defeated a Democratic proposal to require background
checks on all people who purchase weapons at gun shows, and instead
backed a voluntary measure. Less than 24 hours later, they reversed
their position, introducing a package that included a provision to
make those background checks mandatory.
</P>
<P>
   The move signaled a growing pressure on gun-control issues after
the April 20 shooting at Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   But the final showdown will come next week, when the Senate has
to agree on dozens of more gun-control amendments before final
passage of the overall bill. Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, a
Mississippi Republican, has pledged to pull the entire juvenile
crime bill, which would crack down on youthful violent offenders,
off the floor if the two parties don't reach an agreement by
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Democrats continued to pound their Republican rivals
for what President Clinton called a ``phony proposal'' riddled with
loopholes and concessions to the gun lobby.
</P>
<P>
   ``It won't stop criminals from buying guns at gun shows. At the
same time, it will open up a new pawnshop loophole that lets
convicted felons get guns at a local pawnshop. That's actually
worse than current law,'' Clinton said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate, tempers flared at times, as the debate over the
role of the National Rifle Association seemed to overshadow the
legislation itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let the Senate and not the gun lobby run this debate,'' said
Senator Patrick J. Leahy, a Democrat from Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   ``The National Rifle Association hasn't had a thing to do with
it, and I don't care whether they accept it or not,'' shot back
Senator Orrin G. Hatch, Republican from Utah. ``I'm so tired of
this stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Senator Larry E. Craig, Republican of Idaho and an NRA board
member, later told reporters that NRA lawyers had reviewed his
draft of the gun-show measure that had passed on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   As Democrats presented a raft of gun-control proposals to add to
the juvenile crime bill, Republicans generally sought to turn the
debate toward violence on television, the movies, video games, and
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   To underscore that, Lott issued a statement critical of
Clinton's weekend fund-raising trip to the West Coast. ``What's the
message to our children? Democrats care about your safety, unless
it's inconvenient to their partners in Hollywood,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans accused Democrats of refusing to negotiate in good
faith, instead turning gun control into a campaign issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is being exploited by Democrats for fund-raising and
political purposes,'' said Senator John McCain, the Arizona
Republican who is running for president.
</P>
<P>
   McCain admitted that loopholes remain in the legislation, but
insisted the Republican measure requiring private unlicensed gun
dealers to perform background checks on all purchases was not one
of them.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats disagreed and refused to accept new language that
would clarify the requirement, insisting the GOP measure includes
vague wording that would allow private dealers to skirt the law.
They said Republicans should have passed the original Democratic
measure making background checks mandatory at all gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``The country wants the gun show loophole closed _ not a
quarter-closed, not half-closed, but 100 percent closed,'' said
Senator Edward M. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Richard J. Durbin, a Democrat from Illinois, added,
``The Republican measure has more special effects than the new Star
Wars movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats also vowed never to support the Republican proposal as
long as it includes a provision that would give immunity to gun
dealers sued in court for providing guns to individuals who should
not be allowed to buy firearms under current law.
</P>
<P>
   And they rejected provisions that would allow individuals to
retrieve guns at pawnshops without going through a background
check, saying felons have been caught buying and selling their guns
at pawnshops. Finally, they rejected a 24-hour time limit for
federal agents to conduct background checks at a gun shows. Under
current law, the FBI has three days to make sure an individual
purchasing a weapon is not a felon, an illegal alien, or mentally
ill.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch and Craig also hardened their stance after the bruising
floor battle, saying a compromise was increasingly unlikely, even
though there was ground for agreement on some provisions, including
requiring child safety locks on handguns.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, Republicans handed gun-control advocates
another defeat by killing a Democratic proposal to regulate
Internet gun sales by a vote of 50-43.
</P>
<P>
   The emotion displayed during Friday's debate over background
checks on all purchasers of firearms at gun shows underscored the
political jockeying by both parties in response to the Colorado
school massacre.
</P>
<P>
   Senate observers say Republicans found themselves in a bind,
trying to balance their opposition to tigher controls, the wrath of
the powerful NRA, and concerns about polls showing increasing
support for gun control.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what's going on is a sea change in Ameican thinking on
guns,'' said Senator Dianne Feinstein, Democrat of California.
</P>
<P>
   Durbin said the votes also indicate the ``mighty NRA fortress is
under siege'' and cited as evidence some GOP defections supporting
some gun-control provisions.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty Republicans Friday voted for an amendment from Feinstein
to ban high-capacity ammunition clips, and another half-dozen voted
with the Democrats on the GOP gun-show measure.
</P>
<P>
   Two staunch conservative Republicans, Senators Richard C. Shelby
of Alabama and Conrad Burns of Montana, switched their votes at the
last minute to maintain party unity, and Republicans who voted
against the GOP proposal said they did so under duress and despite
arm-twisting by GOP leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got out of there because I didn't want a lot of pressure,''
said Senator Peter G. Fitzgerald, a Republican from Illinois who
rejected the Republican measure. Fitzgzerald said Craig was unhappy
with his vote, but he believed Republicans were mistakingly giving
the issue to Democrats.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
