<HEADER>
A7860 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEORGE-LUCAS-2TAKES-L     05-14 1328
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEORGE-LUCAS-2TAKES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUCAS MAKES THE FILM HE ALWAYS ENVISIONED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB STRAUSS  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It's good to be the boss.
</P>
<P>
   But even though George Lucas _ beloved ``Star Wars'' creator,
billionaire independent movie entrepreneur, deified shaper of a
generation's imagination _ spent $115 million of his own mony to
make ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom Menace'' exactly the way
he wanted to, he still has at least eight toes firmly planted on
the drab little planet Earth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is only a movie,'' Lucas says about the prequel to his
'70s/'80s sci-fi trilogy that, in more than a few precincts of
Western civilization, is the most eagerly anticipated event this
side of the Second Coming. ``When you get a situation like this,
where you have so much high expectation, it can't possibly live up
to that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Phantom Menace'' did, however, have to meet Lucas' high
standards. With more than 2,000 computer generated shots (four
times the average used in big movies like ``Titanic''), a
half-dozen fully realized alien worlds, hundreds of new creatures
and fleets of redesigned space, land and even underwater vehicles,
it had to blend animated and live-action elements seamlessly in
practically every frame.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas, who has not directed a feature film since the first, 1977
``Star Wars'' movie, has waited all this time for Industrial Light
&AMP; Magic, the effects outfit he built with the trilogy's profits, to
get up to high-tech speed to accomplish the task.
</P>
<P>
   ILM has been on the cutting edge of movie magic breakthroughs
for two decades. Besides the ``Star Wars'' sequels ``The Empire
Strikes Back'' (1980) and ``Return of the Jedi'' (1983) and the
Lucas-produced, Steven Spielberg-directed Indiana Jones trilogy,
the Marin County firm counts ``Terminator 2'' and the ``Jurassic
Park'' pictures among its numerous benchmark credits. But Lucas'
intricate vision for the ``Star Wars'' universe only became
achievable within the last five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to make movies and I wanted to finish this,'' eternal
child Lucas, slightly bearish and definitely graying at the age of
55, said at a New York press conference last week. ``I had been
very frustrated before when I made the first series because I had
an imagination that created a kind of world that I could never get
on film. It was just technically impossible. I was stuck with
creatures in rubber masks that couldn't move very far, with
environments that extremely limited what I could do.
</P>
<P>
   ``So one part of coming back was to finish the story. But part
of it was the chance to make it more the way it was in my mind when
I created it, have alien creatures give good performances and have
really good personalities and be part of the whole dramatic
experience.'' But even that wasn't a sure thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say I had doubts for, oh, the last 4{ years,'' says a
straight-faced Rick McCallum, ``Phantom Menace's'' producer and
Lucas' right-hand man. ``There was a lot of flop sweat. Even when
we started shooting, we had no idea how we were going to accomplish
half the things in the movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was pretty terrifying. I don't think there's any other
business in the world where you spend so much money and resources
and time and talent to start something, and you still don't know
how you're going to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Unnerving as that may be, it's the core of the Lucas ethic, both
personally and in the message his films impart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Risk-taking is part of life,'' Lucas says. ``It's a central
theme in all of my movies. My first film, `THX 1138' (1971), is
about someone trapped in an emotionless world who takes the risk of
trying to find some emotion and leave that world. A very small
gesture, but a very difficult one for him to make. `American
Graffiti' (1973) is pretty much the same story, about the challenge
and risk of leaving your hometown, leaving your nest and going off
into the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, in my life, that's been very important. At various
points I've taken what I consider great risks, and I don't think
I'd be where I am today if I hadn't done that.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucas likes to view himself as a maverick, and in a way he is.
Even though he's the ultimate purveyor of mass-market,
Hollywood-style entertainment, he's anti-Hollywood to the core.
He's gone so far as to establish his own independent filmmaking
fiefdom _ the state-of-the-art Skywalker Ranch north of San
Francisco _ where only he, and no studio executive, calls the
shots.
</P>
<P>
   The son of a Modesto office-supply merchant, Lucas' early
interest in auto racing was cut short by a crash that damaged his
lungs. Turning to film, he enrolled at the University of Southern
California, where his student project eventually grew into the
existential _ and uncommercial _ sci-fi project ``THX.'' Though the
nostalgic ``American Graffiti'' became a huge hit, Lucas chafed at
studio interference with and lack of enthusiasm for the project.
</P>
<P>
   He made ``Star Wars'' on a frayed shoestring of a budget, had
trouble selling it to a distributor and ultimately made a deal with
20th Century Fox that gave him all sequel and merchandizing rights
to the property in exchange for forgoing a $500,000 directing fee.
It proved to be the deal of the century _ for Lucas. The first
three ``Star Wars'' films have collectively grossed $1.8 billion
worldwide. Toys, books, posters, clothing, video games and hundreds
of other ``Star Wars'' products have wrung up about $5 billion in
sales.
</P>
<P>
   All pretty impressive for a guy who claims to be an independent
filmmaker. But Lucas defends the mass-merchandising of his
``personal'' cinematic vision.
</P>
<P>
   ``The movie and the merchandising are two different things,
although people like to think that they're connected,'' Lucas
insists. ``I make the movies, I'm an independent filmmaker in San
Francisco, and I have to make sure that I've exploited everything
that I possibly can in a movie. It's like when an Indian kills a
buffalo, he has to use everything. We can't throw things away, we
can't leave a dead carcass out on the prairie to rot. I'm a very
small company relative to the studios. They have billions and
billions of dollars, they make billions of dollars every single
year. They can afford to just do whatever they want; I can't.
</P>
<P>
   ``The licensing thing is just something that sort of grew
spontaneously. It certainly wasn't something that anybody
predicted; the first toys didn't come out until a year after the
film came out. It's grown into this big opportunity that has helped
finance the movies for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, one man's independence is another man's power trip.
Lucas comes off as a low-key, even-tempered guy. A divorced father
devoted to his three young children, Lucas eschews the kind of
imperious behavior that has stereotypically characterized
mega-directors from Von Stroheim to Cameron.
</P>
<P>
   Still, if power corrupts ...
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, there's nobody who does anything in the theater,
painting, any art form whatsoever, who doesn't want freedom and
control over his work,'' McCallum says in vigorous defense of his
boss. ``Any artist wants to be in a position not to have to listen
to that person who is only thinking about the bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about a guy who has actually beaten the system,
who is not a part of the machine,'' McCallum continues about Lucas.
``And who, also, does not have a titanic ego, who is not a
megalomaniac, who does not give a s--- about private jets and
boats, who is just a basic guy. That is everything that's repugnant
to us, and we don't want to have anything to do with it. But the
only thing that actually makes that happen at the end of the day
is, unfortunately, you have to have the success and money to be
able to hold it together.''
</P>
<P>
   All that acknowledged, Lucas admits that ``Star Wars' ''
phenomenal success has been a double-edged lightsaber.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``I conceived of `Star Wars' about the time I'd finished `THX,'
when I was getting a lot of pressure from my peers to do something
other than these offbeat, artsy, nonstory, noncharacter movies,''
Lucas recalls. ``They thought I should move into a more socially
acceptable medium. That's when I came up with the idea of doing a
sort of modern mythology, Saturday matinee serial for kids. One was
`Indiana Jones' and the other was `Star Wars.' The thing I actually
hated the most in college is what I've done the most of in real
life. I guess that's the way it works.
</P>
<P>
   ```Star Wars' was a very big, consuming thing,'' he adds. ``It's
like a little tar baby I stuck my fist in 23 years ago. I'm a
little surprised at how big it got; it's sort of dominated my life.
I don't regret it, it's been a very interesting experience and very
rewarding in a lot of ways. But I stopped after `Return of the
Jedi' because I was burned out. It's a nine-year commitment, and
that's a big deal. This'll be fine, it'll be fun, but it's a lot of
work and I do want to go on and do other movies.''
</P>
<P>
   But first, the next two movies in the prequel trilogy
(preproduction began on the second feature last week). Lucas will
direct both, and he's not complaining about it. Having finally made
the picture he's always dreamed about, the satisfaction factor far
outweighs any contradictory creative longings.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first film for which I was able to sit down and,
basically, let my imagination run wild and not be hampered by `I
can't do this and I can't do that,''' Lucas says of his latest
baby. ``I could dream up whatever I wanted and, for the most part,
pull it all off. It's always a little nerve-racking when you take
risks and you don't quite know whether it's going to work or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the whole movie,'' he says of the critically dismissed
``Phantom Menace.'' ``I've taken some chances in the storytelling
and the way I've put it together and, I think, by and large I've
been successful.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
