<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7863 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-ATTACK-ART-2TA     05-14 1068
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ATTACK-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT LEAST 60 ARE KILLED IN BOMBING OF KOSOVO VILLAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(rm) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ More than 60 Albanians were killed and
scores more badly wounded late Thursday night when bombs blew apart
a village in southwest Kosovo, near Prizren, Yugoslav officials and
journalists at the scene said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The attack, in the village of Korisa, was said by Yugoslav
government officials to have been carried out by NATO warplanes. A
Serbian journalist from Agence-France Presse, Alexander Mitic, said
he had found a bomb stabilizer fin with the marking GBU-12, which
would indicate a NATO laser-guided bomb.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials in Brussels, Belgium, said they were
investigating the report and were reluctant to comment before their
work was complete. They said there was Yugoslav shelling in the
region. Earlier, NATO had announced that its planes had made many
strikes near Prizren and Stimlje, near Suva Reka, where the Kosovo
Liberation Army is active. Korisa is about three miles north of
Prizren on the road to Suva Reka.
</P>
<P>
   Casualty figures were also uncertain, with a Prizren police
officer Friday evening telling Radovan Urosevic, the director of
the Serbian Media Center in Pristina, that 79 people were dead and
58 injured. Urosevic said the figures were not complete. The media
center is closely connected to Serbian authorities.
</P>
<P>
   If those figures are accurate, and if NATO aircraft are
responsible, it would represent the largest number of people killed
by a misdirected NATO bomb in the 52 days of the alliance's air
campaign against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   On April 14, Yugoslav officials said 75 Albanian refugees had
died in an accidental attack on a convoy near the southwestern
Kosovo town of Djakovica. NATO acknowledged attacking the convoy,
saying it was hitting military vehicles, but foreign journalists
brought to the scene did not see all the bodies.
</P>
<P>
   In Friday's incident, the official Yugoslav news agency, Tanjug,
said at least 100 people had died, and the Russian Foreign Ministry
immediately condemned the attack, calling it ``a new crime by the
alliance.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mitic, the journalist for Agence-France Presse, and other
journalists based in Pristina said they had counted 48 corpses,
many of them children, in the Prizren hospital morgue. Mitic also
said he saw three large plastic garbage bags filled with body parts
and 16 more corpses still at the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Dragan Softic of the Prizren hospital said 61 people had
been admitted with serious injuries, including five people in
intensive care and another seven who had limbs amputated in
operations.
</P>
<P>
   He said that all the injured had ``blast syndrome injuries,
severe burns and fractures of the spine,'' indicating that regular
bombs, not anti-personnel cluster bombs, had been used.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't bring in those who died on the spot as there was
no time,'' Softic said. ``Therefore, I can't give the exact death
toll because Albanians take their dead away.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who died were part of a group of about 500 Albanian
refugees who were traveling through southwest Kosovo with tractors,
and who had stopped in Korisa for the night, sleeping in what
Urosevic described as a long, low building that could have been a
warehouse. The bombs fell about midnight, survivors said. There was
bombing nearby at about 8:30 a.m. &UR;  &LR; Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters at the scene saw at least two large craters.
</P>
<P>
   While Yugoslav officials said the refugees were ``returning
home,'' they could have been seeking to cross the border into
Albania or Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   Urosevic said he had counted at least 15 burned tractors and
trailers lined up outside the warehouse, while another 15 seemed
less damaged. Mitic said nine charred bodies still lay by the
tractors.
</P>
<P>
   (Begin optional trim)
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav Army Press Center in Belgrade, which authorizes all
media travel outside the Yugoslav capital, did not organize or
authorize a trip to the village Friday by foreign journalists based
in Belgrade, saying that it was too late in the day for the
seven-hour drive and that foreign journalists were already on the
scene.
</P>
<P>
   Some journalists were taken to Pristina Friday on a separate
visit, but Urosevic said they had arrived too late to go to Korisa,
in part because of intensive NATO air activity.
</P>
<P>
   (End optional trim)
</P>
<P>
   A 62-year-old Albanian, Zecir Urimeraj, told Mitic that the
group of refugees had been ``hiding in the forests, but Serb
authorities have assured us we can return to our homes.'' He said
two of his daughters, aged 2 and 3, and his brother-in-law had all
died in the attack.
</P>
<P>
   About 200 other displaced people had spent the night in nearby
houses, where, according to the witnesses, many were injured. Mitic
saw about a dozen damaged houses.
</P>
<P>
   After the explosion of the first bomb, the survivors fled toward
nearby fields, Urimeraj said. ``But the bombing continued there
also.''
</P>
<P>
   Another survivor, Dostan Rexhaj, 49, told a Serb journalist
working for Reuters, Goran Tomasevic: ``We decided to spend the
night here. Some time around midnight, they bombed us from their
warplanes three times. It was a horror.''
</P>
<P>
   Rexhaj added: ``Many people burned up instantly. When news that
they bombed us got through, police rounded up the wounded and took
them to Prizren hospital. But we still can't collect all the
bodies. They are all around the place _ in the fields and nearby
farms. They have been blown to pieces.'' He said he thought more
than 150 people had been killed.
</P>
<P>
   Another survivor, Feriz Ametaj, said at least 100 people had
been killed. ``Numerous burnt bodies have been evacuated since this
morning in bags,'' he told Mitic.
</P>
<P>
   In Belgrade Friday, the Yugoslav government, in a meeting lead
by President Slobodan Milosevic, urged the United Nations to press
for an immediate halt to the airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``International opinion should understand that a halt to the
bombing would mean an immediate return to peace,'' the government
statement said.
</P>
<P>
   But two mayors in Serbia, members of the political opposition,
urged Milosevic to make peace in order to stop the bombing.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Zoran Zivkovic, mayor of Nis, heavily hit by the NATO raids,
urged Belgrade to take the West's latest proposals as the ``basis
for political solution'' for the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``No idea is worth the death of whole population,'' Zivkovic
said. ``Patriotism is not to push the whole nation towards death,
but to ensure the future for them.'' He is a top official in the
Democratic Party of Zoran Djindjic, who has fled Serbia for its
sister republic of Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   Velimir Ilic, mayor of Cacak, 100 miles south of Belgrade, where
four people were killed and 13 injured in NATO air raids on Monday,
called on the authorities to do ``everything to stop the bombing.''
</P>
<P>
   Ilic, a leader of a smaller opposition party, told the
independent Beta news agency: ``Destruction in the country is
great, and there are more and more dead every day.''
</P>
<P>
   In Pristina, the first staff and aid supplies arrived from the
International Committee of the Red Cross since the organization
pulled out of the war zone on March 29, five days after the bombing
started.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Cross said a four-vehicle convoy carrying food and
shelter materials had driven into Pristina from Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Friday, NATO planes again attacked the electricity
supplies of the three largest Yugoslav cities of Belgrade, Nis and
Novi Sad, while insisting that electricity supplies were military
targets.
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO does not strike anything which is not directly connected
with fueling the Yugoslav war machine,'' said the NATO spokesman,
Jamie Shea. ``We want to disrupt the command and control of the
Yugoslav forces.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
