<SLUG> BC-INVEST-DIARY-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTING DIGEST, WITH FUNDS WATCH AND MARKETS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 16) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Queen of the Bulls Still Stays the Course &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For followers of Abby Joseph Cohen, investment strategist at
Goldman, Sachs, it probably seems like a reflex reaction. Bad news
prompts a market selloff. Ms. Cohen, a perennial bull, tells
investors not to fret.
</P>
<P>
   It happened again on Friday as the Dow Jones industrial average
lost 193.87 points on the news that the Consumer Price Index rose
an unexpectedly sharp 0.7 percent last month, fueling inflation
fears. Speaking at a Goldman, Sachs conference, Ms. Cohen said the
concerns were overdone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't believe we are on the cusp of an increase in
inflation,'' she said, adding that excess capacity in many
industries and stable commodity prices will temper price increases.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index is in a trading range of
1,300 to 1,350, and it may get a boost as companies report
second-quarter profits, Ms. Cohen said. ``The direction of the S&AMP;P
will be higher,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Cohen added that she didn't expect a ``significant spike''
in interest rates. For the year, she said, inflation will be 1.5
percent to 2 percent. (Bloomberg News) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Dogs of The Dow, Are Having Their Day &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's hardly news to index watchers that the Dow Jones industrial
average has been on a tear. Since April 8, it has returned 9.1
percent through last Thursday, beating the broader, more
growth-oriented Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index, which has
returned just 3.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But the real winners have been investors who follow the
so-called Dogs of the Dow stock-picking system. Although there are
several variations on the theme, the most popular one calls simply
for buying in equal dollar amounts the 10 Dow industrials with the
highest yield as of year-end, and holding them for 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   Since April 8, the Dog stocks have returned 15.8 percent through
Thursday, according to Richard J. Moroney, editor of Dow Theory
Forecasts, a newsletter in Hammond, Ind. The 1999 Dogs are General
Motors, Philip Morris, J.P. Morgan, Eastman Kodak, Goodyear Tire
and Rubber, Minnesota Mining and Manufacturing, Caterpillar,
Chevron, Exxon and DuPont.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does leave you with a list of stocks that have low
price-earnings, low price-to-book ratios and low price-to-sales,''
Moroney said. ``Apart from J.P. Morgan, these are all kind of
classical cyclical stocks.'' And they are the types of stocks that
have performed best as higher valuation growth stocks have paused.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another thing that's really helped them has been their
exposure to oil stocks,'' he said. The spot price of crude oil has
risen nearly 50 percent this year, as of Friday. In addition to the
big integrated oil companies among this year's Dogs, DuPont has a
big oil exposure, through its big stake in Conoco. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Richard Teitelbaum &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1999 Hasn't Been Stellar For Two Big Hedge Funds &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   George Soros and Julian H. Robertson, the managers of the
world's biggest hedge funds, are losing money this year even as
smaller rivals stage a comeback, according to investors and market
news services.
</P>
<P>
   The Quantum fund, the $6.75 billion flagship of Soros Fund
Management, was down 13.8 percent through May 5, and Robertson's
Tiger Management, with about $13 billion in assets, lost 8.5
percent through April 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have very large pools of assets and it is hard to deploy
all the money,'' said David Horn, a partner at Graystone Partners
in Chicago, which helps wealthy clients place $4 billion with 125
managers.
</P>
<P>
   But Horn said some other hedge funds bounced back strongly.
</P>
<P>
   Omega Overseas Partners Ltd., the $1.2 billion offshore fund of
Leon G. Cooperman's Omega Advisors, for example, returned 12.4
percent through April 30, investors said. It lost about 5 percent
in 1998, in part on wrong-way bets on Russian debt. Cooperman, who
declined to comment, has been sticking to stock-picking this year,
investors said.
</P>
<P>
   Long-Term Capital Management, the biggest bond hedge fund, with
about $4.8 billion in net assets, climbed 11.7 percent through
April 30, investors said, though it has lost 0.57 percent since
February. A spokesman declined to comment. The firm, founded by
John W. Meriwether, a former vice chairman of Salomon Brothers, was
acquired last year by 14 lenders when it collapsed after Russia's
default.
</P>
<P>
   (Bloomberg News)
</P>
</TEXT>
