<SLUG> BC-COURTS-SURVEY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURVEY INDICATES CONFIDENCE IN COURTS DIVIDED AMONG RACES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A new national survey indicates confidence in state
and local courts is divided across racial lines.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, sponsored by the Hearst Corp., found black Americans
far less satisfied with the courts than others, particularly
Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   ``The consensus is that the courts protect our constitutional
rights, and that they are honest and fair. But there is also an
overwhelming belief that equal justice under the law is more equal
to some than to others,'' said Hearst President and Chief Executive
Officer Frank A. Bennack Jr., who released the survey results
Friday at the two-day National Conference on Public Trust and
Confidence in the Justice System.
</P>
<P>
   The conference included remarks by Chief Justice William H.
Rehnquist, who urged federal and state judges to strive to increase
public trust in the court system even as they continue to render
decisions based solely on the law, without regard to popular
opinion.
</P>
<P>
   The survey of 1,826 adults, conducted Jan. 13 to Feb. 15,
revealed that most Americans view judges as honest and fair in
deciding cases and ensuring that litigants are adequately
represented.
</P>
<P>
   But the study, by the Indiana University Public Opinion
Laboratory, also showed that nearly 80 percent of Americans believe
court cases take too long to be resolved and about 67 percent say
it is too expensive to sue.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty-eight percent of blacks surveyed say that ``people like
them'' are treated worse than others in court. Thirty-three percent
of Hispanics surveyed felt that way.
</P>
<P>
   About 42 percent of Hispanics and non-Hispanic whites say they
believe blacks receive worse treatment, the survey indicated.
</P>
<P>
   Among Hispanics, 33 percent say they strongly agreed with the
statement that courts make reasonable efforts to ensure all
litigants get adequate legal help. Twenty-nine percent of
non-Hispanic whites and 27 percent of blacks said the same.
</P>
<P>
   In the survey, 85 percent of participants say courts protect
criminal defendants' constitutional rights, and 18 percent prefer
that a judge ignore the law to ensure a defendant's conviction.
</P>
<P>
   But 81 percent also say they believe judges' decisions are
influenced by political considerations, and 78 percent agreed with
a statement saying elected judges ``are influenced by having to
raise campaign funds.''
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-three percent disagree with this statement: ``The media's
portrayal of courts is mostly accurate.''
</P>
<P>
   Rehnquist said judges can inspire trust and remain independent
if they make their courts more understandable to citizens by taking
such steps as ``giving plain reasons'' for their decisions. These
efforts to educate the public must begin in the local traffic
courts, ``where most people have their only personal contact with
our judicial system,'' the chief justice said.
</P>
<P>
   Rehnquist, however, warned judges that their efforts to inspire
confidence should not come at the expense of the need to decide
cases independently of the will of the people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, of course, it is possible in the name of building public
trust and confidence in the judicial system to say that judges who
have rendered an unpopular decision should reconsider it if a
majority of the public does not agree with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``But whatever such a practice might do to increase public trust
and confidence in the system _ and I think it might be quite
counterproductive _ it would be quite contrary to the idea of an
independent judiciary.''
</P>
<P>
   Rehnquist said the public most effectively voices its criticism
at the federal court level, where judges must first be nominated by
the president and confirmed by the Senate. Rehnquist himself
survived two bruising Senate confirmation battles to become an
associate Supreme Court justice and later chief justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a slow process, but it is the only one consistent with
the idea of an independent judiciary,'' Rehnquist said. ``Whatever
may be the merits or demerits of a poll-driven executive or
legislature, the specter of a poll-driven judiciary is not an
appealing one.''
</P>
<P>
   Sponsors of the conference included the National Center for
State Courts, American Bar Association, League of Women Voters,
Conference of Chief Justices and Conference of State Court
Administrators.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
