</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALLIES DEFEND USE OF CLUSTER BOMBS IN KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ELIZABETH BECKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Pentagon and NATO on Friday defended the use of
cluster bombs in the NATO air campaign over Kosovo, saying the
weapons are as accurate as other gravity bombs and remain effective
against targets like troop concentrations, airfields and other
large military targets.
</P>
<P>
   Belgrade has charged that a NATO warplane fired at the Kosovo
village of Korisa, killing more than 60 civilians in an assault
that bore some resemblance to one caused by cluster bombing.
</P>
<P>
   At a briefing, Pentagon officials said that NATO airplanes were
attacking in the general area, but that they had no evidence so far
that any of the planes had been near that village or that cluster
bombs had been used in attacks in that region.
</P>
<P>
   But the use of cluster bombs was criticized just last week in
the strike on the market in Nis, where Belgrade said 15 people were
killed.
</P>
<P>
   General John Jumper, commander general of U.S. Air Forces in
Europe, emphasized today that cluster bombs have the same accuracy
of other bombs that are not precision-guided weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't mean mistakes don't happen,'' said Jumper.
</P>
<P>
   Both Pentagon and NATO officials said they were reluctant to say
yet who was to blame in the Korisa deaths, asserting that they had
to wait until the investigation is complete.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's good reason to be cautious about the Serb
reports,'' said Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon. ``I would just
urge you to be careful with those reports; don't rush to judgment.
NATO is in the middle of investigating this now, and as soon as
they finish, we will have something to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials said they did not want to repeat the mistakes
made in April when NATO warplanes accidentally hit a refugee convoy
in southeastern Kosovo. At first NATO officials publicly denied
responsibility for the April 14 bombing, suggesting Serbian planes
were to blame. But then, after a series of gaffes, they had to
retract their statements and admit NATO jets had hit two convoys.
</P>
<P>
   Human Rights Watch appealed this week to NATO Secretary-General
Javier Solana to stop using cluster bombs in the air campaign. The
group warned in particular about small unexploded bomblets left by
these cluster bombs. These duds, they said, ``effectively turn into
landmines and like antipersonnel landmines, they kill civilians
even years after the conflict has ended.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The use of cluster bombs, particularly in urban areas or
populated areas, has grave consequences for the civilians,'' said
William Arkin, the author of the Human Rights Watch report. ``In
the short term we've already seen two young kids killed picking up
the brightly colored bomblets and in the long term you'll see they
are a hazard for peacekeepers and rebuilders of Kosovo.``
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon said unexploded ordinances are a hazard in any war,
whether from bomblets from cluster bombs are no worse than the far
larger .
</P>
<P>
   Italy questioned NATO on Friday about hundreds of de-activated
bombs that have been found in fishermen's nets in international
waters in the north Adriatic Sea. The Italian government has been
receiving complaints from fishermen operating out of the port of
Chioggia, east of Venice. Italian airbases host the majority of the
NATO airfleet engaged in the air campaign against Kosovo which lies
directly across the Adriatic.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials confirmed today that ``in rare cases'' pilots are
unloading bombs into the Adriatic Sea when there has been a
technical malfunction of the plane and it can not safely land
without shedding the bomb.
</P>
<P>
   ``We make sure by overflying the area first to see there is
nobody there and then these weapons are jettisoned there,'' said
Major General Walter Jertz, a NATO spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Jertz said that when the pilots jettison their bombs they do not
explode because they are already crippled by the malfunction.
</P>
<P>
   Citizens of Chioggia had complained to the Italian government
that these bombs are washing up on the beaches and could cause
injuries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
