<SLUG> BC-WINE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Budding Fine Wineries Boost the Flow of Profits in Industry
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Peter Sinton &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Wine producers often lament the fact that Americans don't drink
enough wine: Per-capita consumption of table wines grew a measly 2
percent last year, which hardly kept pace with the population
growth rate.
</P>
<P>
   The average adult American drinks about a bottle of wine a
month, and a whopping 70 percent of the drinking-age population
doesn't touch wine at all.
</P>
<P>
   But per-capita figures alone are meaningless, according to wine
industry economist Jon Fredrikson at Schied Vineyard's annual
meeting in San Francisco on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The more important thing is that the 11 percent of the
population who consume 88 percent of the wine continue to spend
more on wine.
</P>
<P>
   The market for premium wines, defined as anything above $7 per
750 milliliter bottle, is exploding. Although premium wines
represent 19 percent of total U.S. production, they account for 44
percent of the total $5.1 billion revenues, Fredrikson noted. As a
sign of their popularity and profitability, these wines dominate
shelf position in supermarkets and wine stores.
</P>
<P>
   Scores of premium wineries have popped up as the favorable
economy, weather conditions, health studies and aging of the Baby
Boomer generation have nurtured California's wine industry.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, average per-capita spending on wine has more than
doubled from $18 in 1990 to $38 in 1998. Although total wine
consumption increased just 2 percent last year, premium wines
priced $7 to $14 were up 15 percent, ``ultra-premium'' wines in the
$14 to $25 price gained 10 percent and ``luxury'' wines priced $25
and up jumped 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of hot-selling varietals such as Merlot soared 34 percent
last year and were up another 28 percent in the first four months
of this year, Fredrikson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The industry has been trained to watch wine volume, not
dollars, but that is a mistake,'' added industry consultant Victor
Motto. Another indication of the robust market for California wines
is that privately owned wineries are being acquired for record
prices. The latest crop of vintners to be acquired includes Geyser
Peak, Sonoma-Cutrer, Simi and Franciscan, and experts expect more.
</P>
<P>
   ``The profit margins of super- and ultra-premium wine producers
is quite strong and buyers know the value of consumer brands,''
said Motto, who believes more acquisitions are likely.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to boost wine consumption in certain parts of this
country, the Wine Market Council in Larkspur has been testing
generic ads in Austin, Texas, and Albany, N.Y. Official results of
the ``Wine _ What are you saving it for?'' campaign will be tallied
next month.
</P>
<P>
   But John Gillespie, president of the council, said it seems to
be working. After the three-month promotional campaign in Austin,
indications are that table wine sales were up 24 percent from the
comparable period last year.
</P>
<P>
   The demand for top wines extends to varietal grapes, which is so
strong that Kendall-Jackson Winery of Santa Rosa announced last
week that it will sell vines as well as wines. Kendall-Jackson will
graft 4.3 million vines on its 70-acre ranch north of Madera in the
Central Valley this year and for the first time will sell them to
other growers and nurseries.
</P>
<P>
   The vintner, which started growing rootstock and grafting on
premium varietal cuttings for its own use six years ago, sees
growing demand as more vineyard land is planted and replanted. A
number of vintners produce rootstock and so-called benchgrafts for
their own use, but Kendall-Jackson says it is the only one to
develop it as a commercial offshoot.
</P>
<P>
   Within a year, it expects to rank fifth in the industry. Major
nurseries Duarte, Sunridge, Sonoma Grape Vines and Vintage together
sell about 35 million vines a year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
