r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WINESIDE-SFCHRON &LR;      05-14 0462
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINESIDE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Vintners Showing MBAs How to Appreciate Wine
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Peter Sinton &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Most mortals who want to sample wines these days have to visit
wineries to get free sips. And increasingly they have to pay for
the privilege.
</P>
<P>
   But some vintners are going out of the way to court a new class
of promising customers _ MBA students at the premium universities.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall-Jackson and Cakebread Cellars not only provide free
tastings and seminars to the next generation of business leaders,
they take their case (and cases) right to the graduate schools of
business at such spots as Stanford, the University of California at
Berkeley, Yale and Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   The average attendance at Kendall-Jackson's seminars is about 65
students, and bottle prices range from $10 to $60. The winery's
executive director of communication, Jim Stanley, figures the
events cost $30 to $50 per student.
</P>
<P>
   Vintners say they feel it is money well spent. After all, MBAs
from top schools often earn $100,000-plus when they graduate. And,
presumably, they also will host a lot of expense-account meals.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall-Jackson of Santa Rosa has visited close to 30 top MBA
schools for each of the past three years.
</P>
<P>
   Cakebread Cellars of Rutherford started its targeted MBA mission
this spring. ``These are the decisionmakers of tomorrow,'' said
owner and CEO Jack Cakebread, who has visited MBA wine clubs at
Harvard, Yale, Stanford and UCLA in the past month and plans to
visit a dozen more top MBA schools by this fall. ``The best place
to do business is over a nice lunch or dinner and it's good to know
you don't order a sauterne with a steak.''
</P>
<P>
   At Harvard, where nearly half the 1,200 students belong to the
wine club, Cakebread served five wines, including the $70 1995
Benchlands Select Cabernet, at two back-to-back seminars and
tastings attended by 60 MBA candidates each.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall-Jackson's program offers similar sessions, which start
with a 40-minute multimedia presentation on wine production, the
market, health benefits and other classroom kind of stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Then comes the ``interactive tasting'' segment, which typically
features four varieties of wine in two different styles so the
students can discern the difference, for example, between a
``crisp, lean, acidic'' Chardonnay and a ``big, oaky, buttery``
Chard. The students also get a taste of winespeak.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; It's hard to quantify the potential financial rewards of
offering wine tastings on campus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Missionary work can be effective,'' said John Gillespie,
president of the Wine Market Council, a nonprofit promotional
organization. ``And there's no question MBAs have promising
potential as wine ambassadors in corporations and their
communities.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
