<SLUG> BC-CHINA-U.S.-570&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON APOLOGIZES BY PHONE TO CHINESE PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mont.)  (lb) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A week after the NATO bombing of the Chinese
Embassy in Belgrade, Yugoslavia, President Clinton was finally able
to express his condolences directly to Chinese leaders on Friday in
a telephone call that also touched briefly on Chinese efforts to
gain entry to the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   News of the phone call was quickly disseminated by the Chinese
news agency and featured on Chinese Central Television, suggesting
that the Chinese government is eager to portray the United States
as having bowed to its demands. It took the government two days to
publicize Clinton's first apology.
</P>
<P>
   While most of the half-hour conversation was devoted to
Washington's regret about the bombing, which killed three Chinese
journalists, Clinton also took the opportunity to say that Chinese
entry into the trade organization would benefit both countries,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the cloud cast by the bombings, and long-standing
concerns in Congress about China, the Clinton administration still
hopes that trade talks can resume within the next month and that
China, which has continued its trade talks with Europe, can join
the world organization this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had been trying to call Jiang Zemin, the Chinese
president, after a mistake led to NATO bombs falling on the embassy
last Friday. But China, which opposed the NATO war with Yugoslavia
from the beginning, went into a public rage when its embassy was
hit, and rebuffed Clinton's overtures _ until Thursday night, when
Beijing signaled a willingness to ease the tensions.
</P>
<P>
   A visit to Clinton at the White House by the Chinese ambassador
on Thursday night led to Friday's phone conversation. The White
House spokesman, Joe Lockhart, described it as constructive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president once again expressed his sincere regrets and
condolences to President Jiang and the Chinese people concerning
the tragic accident of last week,'' Lockhart told reporters. ``The
president expressed his desire that we move beyond this tragic
accident in our relationship,'' he said, adding that both sides
need to ``continue working'' on winning China access to the trade
organization.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said that the Chinese leader ``took the opportunity to
express his views,'' but he would not characterize Jiang's side of
the conversation or say whether he accepted the president's
apology.
</P>
<P>
   The official Chinese news agency, Xinhua, gave no clues to
Jiang's reaction either, saying only that he had ``noticed''
Clinton's apology. Most of its report said that the bombing was an
outrageous act that had shocked the world and created sympathy for
China, but it did not vilify the United States, as Jiang had done
publicly the day before, and did not demand an end to the NATO
bombing, as it has done before.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, the news agency said Jiang repeated China's view that
there was a ``pressing need'' for the United States to conduct an
investigation of the incident and to make the results public. China
had previously demanded that those responsible for the error be
punished, but that was not included in Friday's news report.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the severe strains between the two countries, officials
in Washington and Beijing were exploring when and where trade talks
between the United States and China might resume. U.S. officials
said it would be up to China to determine when a decent interval
had elapsed before putting the trade talks back on track.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Charlene Barshefsky, the U.S. trade representative, said Friday,
``We don't have any specific plans to meet with the Chinese next
week.'' But, she said, ``I do think the Chinese wish to remain
engaged on WTO and indeed wish to re-engage, but we will have to
work out the specific time frame.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Cassidy, the U.S. trade representative's special China
negotiator, had planned to go to China next week. Now, officials
said, that meeting has been postponed for at least another week.
Officials said both countries were searching for some neutral
ground such as Geneva, where the trade organization is based.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the two leaders engaged in their delicate dance toward
easing tensions, the governor of China's central bank signaled his
country's willingness to advance the trade talks. He said Friday
that the United States should stop demanding that China make any
more concessions to join the trade organization.
</P>
<P>
   There has been some question of how much leverage the embassy
bombing might give the Chinese as they try to join the
organization, which would lower Chinese trade barriers and make it
conform with global trade rules.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Sperling, the president's economic adviser, said that the
bombing had not changed the requirements China needed to meet to
join the world body. ``Our approach as we go forward on
negotiations is that China's joining the WTO on solid commercial
terms is strongly in both countries' interest _ not that there's
been some alteration in leverage,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some in Congress also indicated their eagerness. Sen. Max
Baucus, D-Mont., and about two dozen other senators, from both
parties, sent a letter to the president vowing to support permanent
most-favored-nation trading status for China.
</P>
<P>
   This would eliminate China's need to seek annual approval for
its access to U.S. markets _ and would eliminate the grueling
debate that Congress engages in every year when it uses the trade
vote as a chance to criticize China's human rights record. Congress
has become even more leery of China since allegations surfaced that
Beijing has stolen U.S. nuclear weapons secrets.
</P>
<P>
   The president is to make his annual recommendation on whether
China should receive most-favored-nation status _ now called normal
trade relations _ by June 3. Congress then has 90 days to overturn
this opinion. The administration and its allies on Capitol Hill
were hoping that China's entry into the trade group would be
secured by then so that the issue would not spill over into this
fall's political campaigns.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-14-99 2039EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
