<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 20:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7876 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIRLINE-ANTITRUST-ART     05-14 1143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRLINE-ANTITRUST-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: ACCUSING AMERICAN AIRLINES OF PREDATORY PRICING IS A
RISKY TACTIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(DW) 
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   By accusing American Airlines of lowering its prices in a
deliberate attempt to drive smaller competitors out of its hub at
Dallas-Fort Worth International Airport, as it did on Thursday, the
Justice Department has adopted a risky legal strategy.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how obvious American's aggressive tactics may appear
to frequent fliers, the legal hurdles that must be overcome to
prove that American was guilty of the predatory practices charged
by the government are extremely high. William E. Kovacic, a
professor at the George Washington University Law School, said that
the latest case was the first predatory pricing case brought by the
government since the 1970s. ``That was partly the result of
deliberate policy choices made by the Reagan and Bush
administrations,'' he added. ``But it is also a recognition that
these cases are extremely difficult to win.''
</P>
<P>
   While the federal courts have ruled on about 150 private
predatory pricing cases since 1975, Kovacic estimated that those
claiming to be victims won on only a handful of occasions. ``The
success rate has been well under one in 10,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   As American Airlines, which is a unit of AMR Corp., has been
quick to remind people, the antitrust laws are designed to protect
consumers, not competitors. In the last 15 years, the Supreme Court
has overturned virtually all lower court decisions that found
businesses guilty of trying to undermine competitors by lowering
prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cutting prices in order to increase business often is the very
essence of competition,'' the court declared in a 1986 decision.
Thus, mistaken conclusions of predatory pricing are costly, the
court continued, ``because they chill the very conduct the
antitrust laws are designed to protect.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department lawyers agree that they face a tough standard
but they argue that the unique qualities of the airline industry
create fertile ground for predatory practices. They charge that
American's actions in the mid-1990s against three small competitors
were so egregious that it amply meets the current legal tests
established by the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``American crossed a fundamental line,'' said Joel I. Klein, the
assistant attorney general in charge of the antitrust division.
</P>
<P>
   American denied any wrongdoing and charged that the government
was ``overreaching'' the law in a bid to establish a new precedent.
``The government will be hard pressed to find law, facts, or common
sense that supports its position in this case,'' the airline said.
</P>
<P>
   Some antitrust experts agree. ``It's really a novel legal theory
that they are advancing,'' said Mark. C. Schechter, an antitrust
attorney at Howrey &AMP; Simon who led the Transportation, Energy and
Agriculture Section of the Justice Department's antitrust division
from 1988 to 1993. ``It is really a very aggressive application of
the antitrust laws.''
</P>
<P>
   The government's charges focus on American's operations at
Dallas-Fort Worth International Airport. American now flies 70
percent of the scheduled seats out of the airport. Dallas-Fort
Worth accounted for $2 billion of American's $17.4 billion in
overall revenue in 1998, making it the airline's most profitable
hub.
</P>
<P>
   The government argues that by dominating major metropolitan
airports like Dallas, major carriers like American have a monopoly.
Few rivals of equal size would risk spending the money necessary to
challenge a major airline's hold on its hub, leaving only smaller
low-fare airlines as the only viable competition.
</P>
<P>
   The government has accused American of deliberately lowering its
prices and adding more flights on specific routes out of
Dallas-Fort Worth in the mid-1990s to prevent three small carriers
_ Vanguard Airlines, Sun Jet International and Western Pacific _
from gaining a foothold there. Then, after the three upstarts were
forced to abandon the routes, American reduced the number of its
flights and raised prices.
</P>
<P>
   The government said the only reason American would risk losing
money by lowering prices and adding capacity was because it knew
that driving out the small competitors would discourage other
challengers and enable it to earn back monopoly profits at
Dallas-Fort Worth International. That is the very definition of
predatory pricing as defined by the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit draws on internal American documents to show that
the airline estimated in 1993 that the potential encroachment of
low-cost airlines put $3.6 billion worth of American's annual
revenue ``at risk.'' Citing other documents, the government said
that American adopted a deliberate strategy to drive the
competitors out with the intention of making back later whatever
money it lost in the process.
</P>
<P>
   Foreshadowing the arguments that will be heard in court,
American denied that it has a monopoly at Dallas-Fort Worth. The
airline said that it faced ``significant competition'' in the
Dallas market, where low-fare carriers also fly to 62 of the 75
cities it serves. Therefore, American said it was merely responding
to the competition when it lowered its prices. It added more
flights only because the lower fares stimulated more demand.
</P>
<P>
   American also counters that the government's case fails to prove
that it lowered its ticket prices below its variable costs when it
added flights on routes that competed with the smaller carriers.
That is one of the key tests of predatory behavior established by
the Supreme Court. That is where the government's case may run into
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department is not arguing that all of American's
disputed flights were flown below cost. While some were, according
to the government, others simply fell below American's own measures
of what was an acceptable profit. In other words, American was
willing to earn less than it would have by flying its planes on
other routes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The generally accepted standard is that to engage in predatory
pricing one must price the service below the incremental cost of
providing that service,'' Schechter said. ``What the Justice
Department is saying is that it doesn't matter that American's
pricing was below cost. It is very novel.''
</P>
<P>
   But one Justice Department lawyer said the Supreme Court
standard only demands that the price ``has to be below an
appropriate measure of cost.''
</P>
<P>
   That interpretation is sure to spark a debate in court when the
case comes to trial several months from now.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a pretty full battle,'' the Justice
Department lawyer said of the case. ``This is going to be a good
one to watch.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
