<HEADER>
A7881 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOURISM15-COX     05-14 0610
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOURISM15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tourism workers meet world's travel writers
 &HT;    By Marguerite M. Plunkett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Palm Beach County Convention and
Visitors Bureau employees will pitch the county's hotels and
attractions to tour operators and travel writers from all over the
world in the next few days _ and never leave South Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The county tourism promoters will join an estimated 6,000 people
from 71 countries at the Travel Industry Association's
International Pow Wow beginning today at the Miami Beach Convention
Center.
</P>
<P>
   Miami Beach gets the biggest piece of the economic action as
host city to the event. But the visitors bureau and hoteliers from
Palm Beach County also expect to reap future bookings from the tour
operators they meet at the annual international show, the largest
of its kind in the industry. The show was last in Miami in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   A total of $3 billion in business is expected to be conducted at
the show. Miami Beach will feel an economic impact of about $7
million just because of the show, and an estimated $300 million in
future bookings, according to Raul Rego, marketing manager at the
Miami Beach Convention Center.
</P>
<P>
   Hoteliers and organizations representing resort destinations
have appointments to meet with tour operators from overseas,
including Europe and Latin America. They negotiate with the tour
operators to be included in brochures and tour packages that are
sold to travel agents and ultimately consumers, according to
Christophe Dagasson, director of leisure and international sales at
The Breakers hotel in Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   The Palm Beach County Convention and Visitors Bureau has a large
booth at the show, at a cost of $8,000, according to Public
Relations Director Ann Hersley. Three hoteliers _ the Sheraton
Oceanfront of Singer Island, the Colony of Palm Beach, and the
Radisson, Boca Raton _ share the booth as well. Other hotels,
including the Breakers, the Boca Raton Resort and Club and the
Radisson Palm Beach Shores Resort have their own booths. Still
others join the booths set up by their chains.
</P>
<P>
   Hersley couldn't estimate how much the event means for Palm
Beach County in terms of tourist dollars. But it's important enough
to the visitors bureau that they are sending nine people, primarily
to meet travel writers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're meeting with people who I would otherwise have to spend
an exorbitant amount to fly around the world to see,'' Hersley
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Breakers, which does about $1 million in business with
overseas tourists each year, plans to meet with tour operators from
Germany, England, Argentina, Brazil and Switzerland, Dagasson said.
The resort already has contracts with 75 percent of these
operators, but it gives Dagasson the opportunity to present what's
new at The Breakers _ the new spa, beach club and ballroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where we profit from it is we get to welcome some of the
delegates before and after the event,'' Dagasson said. ``We host
some of these top tour operators at the hotel.''
</P>
<P>
   Dagasson said one of the large tour operators The Breakers
contracts with might book as many as 1,700 room nights a year.
</P>
<P>
   Tour operators will try to negotiate wholesale rates for resort
rooms, allowing them to pay travel agents a commission and still
make money, Dagasson said.
</P>
<P>
   Visit Florida, a public-private agency created in 1996 to
promote tourism, hosts tours for operators before and after the
show. But, none are scheduled to visit Palm Beach County, said
Maria Hayworth, director of public relations and promotions.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
