<SLUG> BC-CORRECTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR SATURDAY, MAY 15
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Saturday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-LEMBA-JEWISH-GENES-NYT (moved on Saturday, May 8)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Saturday, May 8,
about genetic research suggesting that some members of the Lemba, a
group of South African blacks, have Jewish ancestry, omitted
attribution for two points. While The Times's account was gathered
independently, The Jerusalem Report was the source of the fact that
one researcher was in Toronto when he began thinking about ways of
tracing Jewish lineage, and the fact that the Lemba number more
than 50,000.
</P>
<P>
   The article also referred imprecisely to an earlier historic
reconstruction using Y chromosomes _ the case of Thomas Jefferson,
and whether he fathered a child or children by his slave Sally
Hemings. The chromosome study in that case corroborated an oral
tradition, short of confirming it.
</P>
<P>
   BC-VIETNAM-FILM-ARCHIVES-NYT (moved on Tuesday, May 11)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, May 11,
about the Vietnamese Government's war film archives misspelled a
surname in some references to an executive with the German company
that is helping Vietnam market the films. He is Alexander van
Dulmen, not van Dulman.
</P>
<P>
   BC-CONGO-FEVER-NYT (moved on Tuesday, May 4)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, May 4,
about the outbreak of a disease in the Congo that has killed at
least 63 people misstated a comment from Dr. Ray R. Arthur of the
World Health Organization about recent cases of hemorrhagic fever
around the world. He said that there had been 50 confirmed cases in
the last two years, not that 50 such cases had been caused by the
Ebola virus.
</P>
</TEXT>
