<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7895 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      05-14 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   South Africa: Rivals Enter Pact
</P>
<P>
   The African National Congress and the Inkatha Freedom Party
signed a pact to ease tension in KwaZulu/Natal province before the
June 2 elections. The parties have agreed to a code that includes a
conflict-resolution mechanism. Since the mid-1980s, more than
12,000 people have died in the struggle between the parties.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   Britain: Nanny's Parents Held
</P>
<P>
   The parents of Louise Woodward, 21, the English au pair
convicted of manslaughter in Boston last year in the death of the
baby in her care, Matthew Eappen, have been arrested by police
officers investigating fraudulent payments from a $500,000 trust
fund set up through public appeal to cover their daughter's legal
costs. Susan Woodward, 42, and her husband Gary, 43, were ordered
to appear in court on July 1. The investigation does not involve
their daughter, now a law student in London.
</P>
<P>
   Britain: Troubled Adolescence
</P>
<P>
   The British Medical Journal said teen-agers in England and Wales
have Western Europe's highest incidence of sexually transmitted
diseases and teen-age pregnancy. A report also said the teen-agers
were more likely to have used illicit drugs than their European
counterparts. The trend was ascribed to poor education, poverty and
lack of supervision by parents, who work the longest hours in
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Scotland: Coalition Formed
</P>
<P>
   The Labor and Liberal Democratic parties in the new Scottish
Parliament signed an agreement in Edinburgh bringing coalition
government to Britain for the first time in more than 50 years. Jim
Wallace, the Liberal Democrat leader, was named deputy to the
legislature's first minister, the Scottish Labor leader Donald
Dewar. Labor was obliged to seek the coalition when it failed to
win a majority in last week's Parliamentary elections.
</P>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS
</P>
<P>
   Geneva: A Fifth Term at Weather Agency
</P>
<P>
   The International Meteorological Organization re-elected its
director general, Godwin Olu Patrick Obasi, to a fifth term. The
secret ballot among member countries gave Obasi, of Nigeria, 105
votes, to 47 combined for his two opponents, a Canadian and a Costa
Rican. By the end of his next term, Obasi, 65, will have served 20
years at the helm of the agency, which tries to predict weather
disasters.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: Indian Leader Shot
</P>
<P>
   Gunmen critically wounded an Indian leader and killed two men
accompanying him on a busy street in Oaxaca. Heriberto Pazos Ortiz,
head of an organization of Triqui Indians, was shot three times at
close range, three days after a federal senator from the same
opposition party was shot in a rural town in Oaxaca state. The
Triquis have been involved in disputes over farmland.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   Syria, Jordan: Easing Drought
</P>
<P>
   Syria began pumping water to Jordan to ease shortages caused by
a severe drought. The move reflects improved ties between the
neighbors, which have been at odds since Jordan signed a treaty
with Israel in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia: President to Run Again
</P>
<P>
   The ruling party, Golkar, chose President B.J. Habibie as its
presidential candidate ahead of a parliamentary election to be held
on June 7. Habibie has held his job for a year, since the forced
resignation of his mentor, President Suharto. Habibie's critics say
that despite the reforms he has championed, he does not represent a
clean break with the past. Following the election, a special
congress is due to choose a new president in November.
</P>
<P>
   Malaysia: a Nonofficial Meeting
</P>
<P>
   The president of the World Bank, James Wolfensohn, met privately
with the wife of the jailed opposition leader Anwar Ibrahim but
insisted that the meeting was purely personal. Anwar's wife, Wan
Azizah Ismail, has emerged since his jailing eight months ago as
his voice and has formed a new political party in opposition to
Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad.
</P>
<P>
   India: Politician Faces Trial
</P>
<P>
   Jayalalitha Jayaram, the actress turned political power broker
who helped topple the government last month, has been handed a
defeat by the Supreme Court, which ruled that corruption cases
against her can be tried by three special state courts in Tamil
Nadu. The charges stem from Jayalalitha's years as the state's
prime minister.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
