</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAMVENTION15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Convention attracts radio hams from across globe
 &HT;    By Laura A. Bischoff
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Yasuo Tokuda spent 24 hours on airplanes and in
airports traveling from Japan to Hamvention, where is shopping for
military radios.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some say we are crazy,'' said Tokuda in broken English and
with a big smile. ``Hamvention is very, very famous. Every time, my
wife says, `Never buy.'''
</P>
<P>
   But Tokuda, who has been to Hamvention half-a-dozen times, buys.
Tokuda says he has more than 1,000 pieces of radio equipment in his
small home.
</P>
<P>
   Tokuda isn't the only ham who travels from afar for Hamvention
at Hara Arena. Join the meandering flow of Hamvention shoppers and
you'll hear Italian, Spanish, Japanese and British accents.
Organizers say people from all 50 states and 50 foreign countries
attend.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father is a radio ham. He loves old radios. He buys
thousands of them. And he finds wonderful bargains here,'' said
Mercedes Reguant, who lives outside of Barcelona, Spain.
</P>
<P>
   The Reguant family traveled through New York City, where they
were mugged, and arrived Thursday at Hamvention. By Friday morning,
Jaime Reguant had already purchased 12 or 14 antique radios,
Mercedes Reguant said.
</P>
<P>
   Mike and Sheila Williams of Southampton, England, spent $1,000
in airfare and built their two-week vacation around Hamvention.
They flew into Washington, rented a car and drove through Amish
country on their way to their first Hamvention.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got nothing like this in England. Ours are one-day
events, very small,'' Mike Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Many amateur radio operators claim nothing beats the prices,
scope and organization of Hamvention, a Dayton-area event for the
last 48 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hamvention is the biggest show in the world,'' said Lucia
Hendriks of Holland.
</P>
<P>
   Inside Hara Arena, manufacturers and dealers display the latest
equipment and gear. Thousands of hams mill about the arena floor to
shop and buy. Outside, 2,800 vendors set up an open-air flea market
where radio and computer equipment _ high-tech, low-tech, old and
new _ is displayed on folding tables and sheltered by tarps. In the
flea market, radio enthusiasts hunt for old parts, collectors items
and bargains.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from a place to buy gadgets and gear, Hamvention is one of
the best places to people-watch. An odd sight at Hamvention is a
ham without a radio tucked in his pocket or hanging off his belt
and a microphone clipped to his lapel or strapped to his head.
</P>
<P>
   Men wearing hats that announce their name and call letters are
common: W4HFB Hugh, KC8NP Steve, KT4SU Norm. Some hats even have
the antenna attached as a sign of a ham who isn't afraid to look a
little, well, goofy. As the hams shop, they fiddle with their
radios and talk into their headsets. Some carry backpacks to hold
their mobile radio equipment. And if hams get separated in the
crowd _ which is expected to be 28,000 over three days _ they just
call one another on their radios.
</P>
<P>
   Walter Pagliarani of Rimini, Italy, has been making a pilgrimage
to Hamvention for 10 years, looking for airplane altimeters and
testing equipment. When asked if Hamvention was worth the trip, he
replied ``Si, si, si. Number one.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
