<DOCNO> NYT19990514.0380 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7902 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STARWARS-PORTMAN15-CO     05-14 1001
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARWARS-PORTMAN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Portman relishes challenge of `The Phantom Menace'
 &HT;    By Dave Larsen
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Natalie Portman was reluctant to take the coveted
role of Queen Amidala in ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom
Menace'' and its forthcoming sequels. The 17-year-old actress
hesitated for two reasons: The length of her commitment to George
Lucas' top-grossing sci-fi series and the impact such colossal
films would have on her personal and professional life.
</P>
<P>
   Portman, who made her screen debut in 1994's ``The
Professional,'' was approached at age 14 to play Amidala. As the
future mother of Luke Skywalker and Princess Leia, she will also
appear in Episodes II and III, the last of which will arrive in
2005. From production of ``The Phantom Menace'' to publicity for
the final film, the teen-ager was looking at a 10-year commitment.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a huge thing to do at any age,'' Portman said during an
interview Sunday at the Regency Hotel. ``And when you're 14 and
don't know what you're going to do the next day, you're not really
jumping on the opportunity to sign away your life until you're 24
or something.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Phantom Menace,'' opening at 12:01 a.m. Wednesday on 5,000
screens, is one of the most anticipated movies of the decade.
``When you do any sort of big film it changes your life because you
become more recognizable,'' Portman said. ``It makes your life a
lot more difficult. But also, it presented so many opportunities
and it seemed like I was going to have the best summer ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Long days of shooting under the hot sun in the Tunisian desert,
while wearing cumbersome costumes and head-pieces, proved more
difficult than she expected. Her makeup and hair took 2 1/2 hours;
getting into costume was another 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have done harder things for money, but it wasn't as big
of a breeze as I thought it was going to be,'' she said with a
schoolgirl giggle. ``I thought it was just going to be this flighty
action movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Amazingly, ``The Phantom Menace's'' female lead never saw the
original ``Star Wars'' until after she was offered the role. ``I
was really excited by it,'' Portman said. ``I think it's a really
fun and entertaining film. And I love films that have meanings on
different levels, depending on what you want to take away from it.
It can just be entertainment or it could be the way of your life,
as some people have made it.''
</P>
<P>
   Portman was born in 1981 in Jerusalem, Israel, and moved with
her physician father and artist mother to Maryland at age 3, and
then to Connecticut at age 7, before finally settling in Long
Island, New York. She was approached at a New York pizza parlor at
age 11 by a Revlon representative, and was soon appearing in their
ads. But Portman didn't want to model; she wanted to act.
</P>
<P>
   Her first film role was as a young girl who allies herself with
a hitman after her parents are killed by a corrupt DEA officer in
``The Professional.'' Portman's performance was hailed by critics
and she received a YoungStar Award, sponsored by The Hollywood
Reporter, for best actress in a drama. Films such as ``Heat,''
``Everyone Says I Love You,'' ``Beautiful Girls'' and ``Mars
Attacks!'' followed, along with her Broadway debut last year in the
title role of ``The Diary of Anne Frank.''
</P>
<P>
   For ``The Phantom Menace,'' Lucas was looking for someone
youthful and strong, along the lines of Leia. ``Natalie is very
intelligent and has a lot of presence and is a very strong
person,'' the director said. ``At the same time, she's very young.
I needed somebody to play a 14-year-old girl who basically could be
elected to rule a planet and make that believable.''
</P>
<P>
   Portman praises Lucas for creating strong female characters for
his films. ``I was thrilled to get to be the really smart and in
control one, and also get to kick some butt at the end of this one,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   Amidala is a great role model for girls, she said, particularly
as a straight-A high school senior who sees her fellow students
lose more and more self-confidence every year. ``It's I think a
teen-age trait in general to be self-conscious, but especially in
girls, we don't have a lot of female leaders to look up to. There
have been very few in reality and very few on film, because film on
the whole has been a reflection of reality. So I think it's really
cool for a girl to see _ even if it's a fantasy _ this young woman
in a very strong and powerful position.''
</P>
<P>
   Portman has been accepted to both Harvard and Yale. Her choice,
like her real last name, the town she lives in and the school she
attends, remains private for security reasons. ``I lead a really,
really regular life,'' she said. ``I go to public school. My
friends are regular people and my parents are not involved in the
industry at all. I lead a really regular life and I'd like to keep
that as much as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   As feared, ``The Phantom Menace'' and its high-profile publicity
campaign might make that more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are a lot more interested in me all of a sudden,''
Portman admitted. ``They care about where I live and who I'm dating
and what I'm wearing a lot more than they ever have. It's a little
strange, but what I always say is you choose to put yourself in the
limelight and I knew what I was getting into. So it didn't surprise
me or anything. It's strange always and I think it will never stop
being strange.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite her initial reservations, Portman looks forward to
shooting the next two ``Star Wars'' films. Unlike most movies,
where everyone works together intensely for three months, becomes
close and then goes their separate ways, Episodes II and III will
be something of a reunion. ``Usually, you don't really have the
chance to work with people again, and I'm really looking forward to
it because I'll get to see the whole crew and many of the cast
members again,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
