<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EPA-POLLUTE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPEALS PANEL THROWS OUT NEW AIR QUALITY STANDARDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: We plan to move a longer version of this file)  (rm) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A federal appeals court panel on Friday threw out
air quality standards that were a cornerstone of the Clinton
administration's antipollution strategy, ruling that they had been
set arbitrarily.
</P>
<P>
   The court also said that in setting the standards, which lowered
the allowable levels of smog and soot, the Environmental Protection
Agency had used powers that Congress had granted it
unconstitutionally.
</P>
<P>
   The decision, by a three-judge panel of the U.S. Circuit Court
of Appeals for the District of Columbia, did not find the Clean Air
Act unconstitutional, but said the Environmental Protection Agency
might choose to ask Congress to re-write it.
</P>
<P>
   The court's 2-1 decision said that the agency must state a
coherent and explicit basis for its standards. If that view
prevails through an anticipated appeal, it could be used to
overturn several pending new pollution standards.
</P>
<P>
   The court's push for a clear basis for new pollution limits
contradicts a long-held legal doctrine that courts should defer to
the discretion of the scientific expertise of administrative
agencies when they are making complex scientific decisions.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer at the U.S. Chamber of Commerce, Robin S. Conrad, said:
``We see this as a big win. The EPA's got to justify its numbers;
it can't pull them out of thin air.''
</P>
<P>
   But supporters of the EPA's standard, which was announced in
June 1997 and is supposed to take effect over the next few years,
said that the court's logic was not likely to survive review by the
whole appeals court or the Supreme Court, the two places to which
it could be appealed.
</P>
<P>
   They cited the dissent by one of the three judges, David S.
Tatel, a Clinton appointee, who wrote that the decision by his
colleagues, Stephen F. Williams and Douglas H. Ginsburg, both
Reagan appointees, ignored the fact that over the past
half-century, the Supreme Court had permitted far wider delegation
of power, like the kind at issue in this case.
</P>
<P>
   The panel's decision said that ``What EPA lacks is any
determinate criterion for drawing lines. It has failed to state
intelligibly how much is too much.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is as though Congress commanded EPA to select `big guys,'
and EPA announced that it would evaluate candidates based on height
and weight, but revealed no cut-off point,'' said the decision.
``The announcement, though sensible in what it does say, is fatally
incomplete. The reasonable person responds, `How tall? How
heavy?''' And the way the EPA read the Clean Air Act, the court
majority said, left it ``free to pick any point between zero and a
hair below the concentrations yielding London's Killer Fog.''
</P>
<P>
   The states of Ohio, Michigan and West Virginia challenged the
EPA standards, along with a trucking group and a variety of
industries; supporting it were the states of Massachusetts, New
Jersey, Connecticut, Vermont, New York and New Hampshire, along
with the American Lung Association and other groups. As is often
the case with challenges to prominent regulations, the case went
directly to a three-judge panel of the appeals court.
</P>
<P>
   The standards at issue set levels of smog and particulates in
the air and were based on new medical studies. Under the new
standards, hundreds of communities around the country were
classified as out of compliance with the Clean Air Act and states
were directed to take steps to reduce levels of these pollutants.
</P>
<P>
   The decision points out what people on both sides of the case
say is a growing contradiction in air pollution policy. Congress
told the EPA to set standards that are ``requisite to protect the
public health'' with ``an adequate margin of safety,'' on the
theory that there is a threshold below which any pollutant is safe.
But some scientific studies now say that for contaminants like
ground-level ozone, known as smog, any amount may be harmful.
</P>
<P>
   Conrad, of the Chamber of Commerce, said it was ``a stunningly
broad decision that goes to the heart of the way EPA promulgates
these standards.''
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, President Clinton's spokesman, Joe Lockhart,
said in a statement, ``We are deeply disappointed by the Court of
Appeals' ruling today on clean air standards, particularly given
the court's explicit recognition that there is a strong scientific
and public health rationale for tougher air quality protections.''
</P>
<P>
   The EPA said in a statement that the standards it had put in
place ``will protect the health of 125 million Americans, including
35 million children.''
</P>
<P>
   The ruling, the statement asserted, ``does not question the
science and process conducted by EPA justifying the setting of new,
more protective standards.''
</P>
<P>
   Proposed tighter rules on automotive emissions, including new
standards for sport utility vehicles, would be among the first
affected and possibly derailed by the new interpretation, some
experts said.
</P>
<P>
   The agency plans an appeal. If that is not successful, the
agency said in a statement, ``Congress must ensure that these
protections are preserved for the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   But some advocates of tighter standards were wary of Congress.
John M. Stanton, a lawyer for the National Environmental Trust,
said of the ruling, ``they're saying, you can always give this back
to the legislative branch, you can always give this back to the
Republicans, who we know are going to overturn these safeguards.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
