<HEADER>
A7910 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-1STLD     05-14 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN SPEAKER PREDICTS IMPEACHMENT OF YELTSIN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: Changes ``The other three impeachment charges'' to ``The
other impeachment charges'' in 8th graf.)  (lb) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ After a day of angry and vivid speeches accusing
Russian President Boris Yeltsin of crimes ranging from treason to
genocide, the Communist speaker of the Russian Parliament predicted
Friday night that the lower house would vote on Saturday to impeach
the president on one of five charges.
</P>
<P>
   As Russia's latest political crisis moved toward its next
critical stage, Gennady Seleznyov, leader of the 450-seat lower
house, said that the anti-Yeltsin opposition _ strengthened by his
sudden decision this week to fire Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov _
would collect more than the 300 votes required to impeach.
</P>
<P>
   The tone of Friday's debate was bitter, heated and at times
incoherent, as parliamentary deputies took turns blaming Yeltsin
for all the ills that have befallen Russia in the last seven years
_ from the collapse of its military to the poverty and decline of
its population.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't you hear all of Russia wailing?'' asked Sergei
Govorukhin, a Russian nationalist and filmmaker. ``They wail and
hold out their hands, begging to free us from him, to save our
children. All Russia except the population of the criminal
megalopolises and some 150 deputies who are always ready to sell
themselves _ all of Russia demands impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   In a rebuttal, Alexander Kotenkov, Yeltsin's parliamentary
representative, accused the president's accusers of staging a
``political and not a legal process'' that was heavy on personal
judgment and weak on legally tenable facts.
</P>
<P>
   The other impeachment charges _ due to be voted on on Saturday
by paper ballots that will be made public _ accuse Yeltsin of
orchestrating the collapse of the Soviet Union in 1991, of storming
the Russian Parliament in 1993 and of waging an illegal war in
Chechnya from 1994 to 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The last charge, which will be supported by a leading liberal
party as well as by the Communists and their left-wing allies, is
expected to pass by as many as 312 votes, Seleznyov said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Although other deputies echoed his prediction, none said Friday
that they expected the charge to survive the tortuous impeachment
process. According to the Russian Constitution, an impeachment must
next be reviewed by the Russian Supreme Court, where in this case,
it is widely expected to be squelched.
</P>
<P>
   Still, given the country's nervous political condition, a vote
to impeach could carry heavy political consequences, as a Kremlin
aide warned Friday. ``The president's decisions may be most
unexpected,'' the unnamed official was quoted as saying by the
Itar-Tass news agency.
</P>
<P>
   According to one popular scenario, the lower house, or Duma, may
choose next week to sidestep another showdown by voting to approve
Yeltsin's prime minister-designate, Sergei Stepashin, a Kremlin
loyalist who now heads the country's main police force.
</P>
<P>
   Thrust into a politically tenuous role, Stepashin held a series
of consultations on Friday with parliamentary leaders, and
potential Cabinet members, in an attempt to restore the shaky
consensus shattered this week by the dismissal of Primakov.
</P>
<P>
   If the Parliament approves Stepashin, Yeltsin will have no
evident constitutional means to dismiss it and call early
elections. Under the Russian Constitution, the president must
disband the Parliament if it votes three times to reject his
nominee for prime minister, Another clause in the Constitution
forbids him to dismiss the Parliament for as long as an impeachment
proceeding is under way.
</P>
<P>
   Given the Constitution's loose language, and Yeltsin's
well-known penchant for political surprises, some on Friday were
saying these legalisms could be interpreted freely by a vengeful
Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there was growing hope on Friday for a solution that
might at least keep the country's current political arrangements in
place until parliamentary elections next December.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   `'The Communists will be happy if an impeachment passes, because
it means they will have been able to punish him,'' said Vladimir
Lysenko, a deputy from Moscow. ``In exchange, they could vote for
Stepashin, which would give them the chance to live calmly until
December.''
</P>
<P>
   Lysenko, 43, once a loyal Yeltsin supporter and fellow
``democrat'' _ a label broadly used to describe Russia's
anti-Communists _ took the podium Friday to urge the 68-year-old
president to resign and spare the country the agony of an
open-ended political crisis that he himself created.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have completely disassociated yourself from the democratic
movement that brought you to power,'' said Lysenko, now a member of
the Parliament's moderate Regional bloc. ``You have hidden yourself
behind the Kremlin walls, and high fences. We, who sincerely
believed in democratic reforms and began them with you, are now
doomed to hear the curses of our compatriots.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Lysenko said Friday that he had planned to vote
against impeachment _ until Wednesday, when Yeltsin fired the prime
minister. Now, he said, he is seriously considering joining his old
Communist foes in what he said has turned into a vote of
no-confidence in a presidency that has gone badly wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a human point of view, I am sorry,'' he said. ``From a
political point of view, I am fed up.''
</P>
<P>
   Lysenko said a straw poll of his district, a liberal stronghold
in northern Moscow, showed his electorate to be almost evenly
divided on impeachment, whereas colleagues from more distant
regions were reporting an overwhelming majority against Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many deputies are required to vote for impeachment or else
they will be out of a job in December,'' said Lysenko.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
