<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-SPEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE GIVES SUPPORT TO MEASURE ON SPENDING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: W.Va., N.M., Texas, Fla., Okla., Kan., Wash.)   (bl)  
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Eager for money to pay for the war in Yugoslavia,
the White House on Friday said it expected President Clinton to
sign a nearly $15 billion emergency spending measure that doubles
what the president had requested for the Balkan conflict, for
Central American hurricane victims and for hard-pressed American
farmers.
</P>
<P>
   The package was completed by House and Senate negotiators late
Thursday night. Republican leaders planned to pass it next week in
an effort to bolster their party's credentials on national security
after the House's refusal in April to give its political support to
the air war.
</P>
<P>
   The president had sought $6 billion for the air campaign and
assistance to Balkan refugees and nations neighboring Yugoslavia.
The Republicans provided $11.8 billion, including money for a
general military buildup and to allow for a pay increase for the
military.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite our differences over the administration's Balkan
policy, this bill sends a strong message to our troops in the field
that the Congress supports them,'' said Rep. C.W. Bill Young,
R-Fla., chairman of the House Appropriations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The spending bill also contained $1 billion for relief and
reconstruction efforts in Central America, long-stalled in
Congress. And the negotiators took care of the needy at home,
approving $900 million for tornado victims, mainly in Oklahoma and
Kansas, and $566 million for financially troubled farmers.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans also used the bill to sidestep a looming
confrontation over the next census that could have risked a partial
government shutdown. The package lifts a provision enacted last
year that would have blocked financing for the Commerce, Justice
and State departments after June 15 because of a dispute over how
the census will be conducted.
</P>
<P>
   Emergency spending bills have become magnets in Congress for
special interest provisions because the legislation is usually
considered too important to be vetoed. Senate Majority Leader Trent
Lott and House Speaker Dennis Hastert tried to hold the line
against a flood of such amendments and riders, although a number
survived.
</P>
<P>
   Across three days of furious bargaining between the House and
Senate, several Republican provisions that the administration had
opposed as anti-environmental were dropped or softened as were some
offsetting spending cuts the administration had opposed. The
negotiators also killed a Senate provision providing $40 million
for the families of victims of last year's accident in Italy in
which a low-flying Marine jet cut the cable of a ski gondola and
sent it plunging in the Alps.
</P>
<P>
   The last obstacle to the agreement was overcome Thursday night
when Hastert persuaded several House negotiators to reverse
themselves and reject a guaranteed loan program for some steel
companies that was sought by Sen. Robert Byrd, D-W.Va. The steel
assistance and a similar program for oil and gas companies
sponsored by Sen. Pete Domenici, R-N.M., was separated from the
bill to be considered later in the session. Such stand-alone
measures are easier to defeat.
</P>
<P>
   The bill still includes language that effectively overturns an
administration decision to deny a permit for a mine in Buckhorn
Mountain in Washington state. And it contains a provision sponsored
by Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, that would block the
administration from using any of the $246 billion the states have
won from a legal settlement with the tobacco industry. Clinton had
wanted to use part of that money for health care and anti-tobacco
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier veto threats, nonetheless, disappeared as the president
finally won long-stalled aid for Central America, $100 million in
aid to Jordan and the money for the Balkan war. ``While the
legislation is not perfect, it accomplishes a great deal and
represents significant progress,'' said Linda Ricci, a spokeswoman
for the Office of Management and Budget. She said the White House
was still reviewing the agreement, but added, ``We expect the
president will be presented with a bill he can sign.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had not wanted to offset the new spending with cuts in
other programs. But the Republicans insisted on offsetting $2
billion of the package's cost, by reducing spending for the food
stamp program and subsidized housing. But the administration agreed
with Republicans that these reductions would not affect the poor,
coming from unspent balances that had not been used because of the
improved economy.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the new spending was to be paid for by dipping into the
federal surplus, which in the current fiscal year is entirely due
to Social Security tax receipts. Republicans have said they are
ready to protect Social Security money from being used for other
means, but they have argued that the military is a special case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
