</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-DIPLO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. AND RUSSIA SEEK FINNISH LEADER'S HELP WITH MILOSEVIC TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Russia and NATO still differ on key issues for a
peace settlement in Kosovo, but Deputy Secretary of State Strobe
Talbott and Russian envoy Victor Chernomyrdin agreed this week on
some ways to approach Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic, the
State Department said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The two diplomats plan to go to Helsinki on Tuesday to confer
with Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari to try to persuade him to
accompany Chernomyrdin when the time is right to talk to Milosevic,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Ahtisaari has yet to accept the task of presenting Milosevic
with NATO's plan for an international security force, the
withdrawal of Serbian forces from Kosovo and its other conditions.
</P>
<P>
   And many details of that plan _ including the makeup of the
force and how much of it would involve NATO forces _ were still
being discussed among the allies themselves and with Russia,
diplomats said.
</P>
<P>
   Washington sees Ahtisaari as a suitable negotiator on Kosovo
because Finland is not a NATO member _ a quality that would appeal
to Milosevic _ and also has ties to Russia. Ahtisaari has been
outspoken against the reported atrocities by the Serbian forces in
Kosovo against the ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Considerable differences still exist between the allies and
Russia on how many Russian troops would be deployed in the force
and where in Kosovo they would be deployed. As well, Russia
remained insistent that some Serbian forces be allowed to stay in
Kosovo after the bombing stopped, a condition that Belgrade has
demanded as its sovereign right to protect its territory, including
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Clouding all of Talbott's talks, in Moscow earlier this week and
Friday in Brussels at NATO headquarters, was the political turmoil
in Russia. A U.S. diplomat present at Talbott's briefing to the
North Atlantic Council _ the chief NATO decision-making body _ said
that the deputy secretary predicted Chernomyrdin would continue as
the Balkans envoy.
</P>
<P>
   But Talbott told the Council that there was only a 50-50 chance
that Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov would stay in his post.
Ivanov has been a chief contact for Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright during the Kosovo crisis. He remains as acting foreign
minister, having been dismissed along with the rest of the Cabinet
by President Boris Yeltsin on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But for all the appearance of diplomatic activity, the main
object of the activity _ Milosevic _ was still waiting to be
approached.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic this week told former U.N. official Yasushi Akashi,
who the Yugoslav leader knew from many negotiating sessions during
the Bosnia war, that he would only accept a lightly armed U.N.
mission in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But NATO has demanded that as part of a settlement, Milosevic
must agree to a well armed international force with NATO at its
core, that he must withdraw his army, police and paramilitaries
from Kosovo, and accept an international civil administration that
would govern the ethnic Albanian refugees on their return.
</P>
<P>
   In Moscow, Talbott and Chernomyrdin established working groups
to work out these issues so that a common front could be presented
to Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   When Milosevic's views would be tested was not clear, Clinton
administration officials said. But one thing was plain, said State
Department spokesman James Rubin on Friday: Talbott would not be
going to Belgrade. This would be left to Chernomyrdin and
presumably Ahtisaari at a later date.
</P>
<P>
   In the Netherlands on Friday, Ahtisaari met with U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan. The Finnish leader said he would meet
with Chernomyrdin and Talbott ``to try and see if we can enlarge
the common ground that would facilitate the negotiations.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the points that were under discussion in Moscow in detail,
according to Rubin, were: the composition of the force, what
constituted a ``rapid and precise'' timetable for withdrawal of
Milosevic's forces and how the withdrawal could be verified. The
shape of the civil administration over Kosovo, which would most
likely be run by the United Nations, was also discussed.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin said that an important part of Chernomyrdin's mission when
he went to Belgrade would be to explain ``what will be necessary
for President Milosevic to agree to and to accept, so that we can
suspend the bombing but only if there's a rapid and precise
timetable for the verifiable and demonstrable steps to that end.''
</P>
<P>
   Since NATO arms mistakenly hit the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade
last Friday, these demands have come under increased pressure.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese and the Russian governments, both of which are
permanent members of the United Nations Security Council, were
likely to work together to try to get NATO to be more flexible,
several administration officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The administration and its major NATO allies have said they
would seek a Security Council mandate for the international
security force.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
