<HEADLINE>
FRANK STANTON, 78, DEVELOPER AND ENTREPRENEUR 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds., name Domna, 2nd graf, is CQ)  
 (bl)  
 By WILLIAM H. HONAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Frank Stanton, an entrepreneur and real estate investor who
developed an early videocassette, died May 9 at his home in Water
Mill, N.Y. He was 78.
</P>
<P>
   He died of complications from Parkinson's disease, said his
wife, Domna C. Stanton.
</P>
<P>
   Stanton conducted most of his business and real estate dealings
in partnership with his brother, Arthur, who died in 1987, and
Victor Elmaleh, through World Wide Holdings, the company they
established in Manhattan. It was created for trading in surplus
goods left scattered around the world in the aftermath of World War
II. With a foothold in North Africa, the company became the largest
importer of sugar into Morocco.
</P>
<P>
   It was later involved in importing Volkswagens, Porsches and
Audis into the United States. Later, the company engaged in toy
manufacturing and movie distribution.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1960s, World Wide Holdings joined forces with Avco
Corp., a high-technology manufacturer, to found Cartridge
Television, a company that produced a videocassette and player that
anticipated later developments in the field.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, World Wide Holdings branched into real estate, and
was frequently in partnership with William Zeckendorf Jr. in such
projects as the $300 million Holiday Inn Crowne Plaza-Manhattan, a
46-story hotel on the west side of Broadway between 48th and 49th
Streets, which was designed to light up like a giant jukebox.
</P>
<P>
   The partners were also among the backers of World Wide Plaza, a
residential and business structure at the site of the old Madison
Square Garden at Eighth Avenue and 50th Street. That project helped
push midtown Manhattan development activity to the west.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his wife, he is survived by two sons, James, of
New York City, and Michael, of Stamford, Conn.; a daughter,
Alexandra, of New York City, and two grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
