<SLUG> BC-AIDS-FALSE-REPORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRED REPORTER ADMITS SHE LIED ABOUT AIDS, TOO  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ky.)   By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The 33-year-old reporter in Kentucky who was fired on Monday
after revealing that she had lied in her newspaper columns about
having cancer to cover up the real diagnosis, AIDS, now says that
she has never been treated for AIDS, either.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with the reporter, Kim Stacy, published Friday
in the newspaper that fired her, The Owensboro Messenger-Inquirer,
Ms. Stacy said that all her illnesses had been fabricated, but that
she believed she had been suffering from symptoms compatible with
AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Stacy's first fabrication took place in 1995, when she told
her co-workers at The Appalachian News-Express in Pikeville, Ky.,
that she had stomach cancer. Her picture was later featured in an
article in that newspaper about cancer survivors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know where the idea came from,'' Ms. Stacy said in
Friday's article in The Messenger-Inquirer. ``At the time I was
having trouble with my blood sugar and going to the doctor a lot,
and everybody was real nice to me, real concerned. It seemed like
they made an effort to be friends with me.''
</P>
<P>
   When Ms. Stacy arrived at The Messenger-Inquirer in 1998, she
told her editors that she no longer suffered from stomach cancer;
she told them she had brain cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Her columns on cancer, one of which was distributed by The
Associated Press in Kentucky, were richly detailed. In one, she
described the thrill of hearing about a new kind of laser surgery
that would remove her brain tumor. In another, she described how
she had befriended an 8-year-old leukemia patient who later died.
``He had been battling a rare form of leukemia for three years and
had just finished his latest round of treatments,'' she wrote. ``He
knew every detail of his illness and, unlike me, was not afraid to
talk about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Stacy told her editors early this week that she was not
suffering from brain cancer, but believed she had AIDS, and chose
not to reveal it because of the stigma associated with the disease.
</P>
<P>
   The only signs of illness Ms. Stacy has right now, she says, are
an upset stomach and a rash, which she attributes to stress. Her
father, Monroe Stacy, said in Friday's Messenger-Inquirer that she
is a diabetic.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Ashley, the editor of The Messenger-Inquirer, said:
``Tragic and embarrassing are two words I would use to describe
this situation. It was embarrassing to have to acknowledge that we
published false newspaper columns. But we've debriefed and gone
around a dozen times, and I don't think, looking back over it, that
we could have avoided it. This is clearly a person who is quite
troubled.''
</P>
<P>
   Ashley said that Ms. Stacy had submitted to an AIDS test and
that he was ``highly skeptical'' that the test would result in a
positive diagnosis.
</P>
<P>
   In a column published early this month about her supposed
cancer, Ms. Stacy wrote: ``I'm not so foolish as to deny it or
pretend my illness doesn't exist. But I also know that the
impossible can happen. That is the power of hope. I choose to live
with hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Ashley said, ``I hope she can find a job somewhere.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
