<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEARS-CHILD-LABOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LABOR DEPT. FINES SEARS $325,000 FOR CHILD LABOR VIOLATIONS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The U.S. Department of Labor announced a $325,000 fine against
Sears, Roebuck &AMP; Co. Friday after investigators uncovered child
labor violations at more than 60 percent of the Sears stores they
visited.
</P>
<P>
   Federal inspectors found 227 teen-agers working in violation of
child labor laws at Sears, the nation's second largest retailer.
The most common violation found was that 16-year-olds and
17-year-olds were operating power-driven equipment. Federal law
bars children from running such hazardous equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of Labor Alexis Herman said department investigators
found child-labor violations at 44 of the 71 Sears stores they
visited in 23 states. Investigators found that more than 200 Sears
employees under 18 were illegally operating power-driven paper
balers, freight elevators and forklifts _ all machines the Labor
Department has declared hazardous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I quite frankly hope this case will send a signal to other
employers so that we don't have more cases like this,'' Ms. Herman
said at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing the violations, Ms. Herman also said Sears had
agreed to put into effect a corporate-wide program to assure
compliance with child labor laws at its 850 department stores,
where nearly 11,000 of its 200,000 workers are under 18.
</P>
<P>
   Sears agreed to pay the fine, but it did not admit liability.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that retailers employ 60 percent of teen-agers under 18
who are working, Ms. Herman promised rigorous monitoring of
retailers around the nation to check whether they are obeying child
labor laws.
</P>
<P>
   In the agreement it signed with the department, Sears said it
would appoint a manager to oversee child-labor compliance and said
it would audit all its stores to ferret out child-labor violations.
Sears officials also pledged to provide more information to the
parents of employees under 18 and to improve its training of
managers and teen-age workers to increase compliance.
</P>
<P>
   Jan Drummond, a Sears spokeswoman, said, ``When Sears was made
aware of the Department of Labor's audit, we saw it as an
opportunity to create a unique program that is designed to insure a
safe work environment for teens.''
</P>
<P>
   Herman said, ``We believe Sears' commitment to corporate-wide
compliance and its new child labor program can be a model for other
corporations to build upon.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-14-99 2111EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
