<HEADER>
A7920 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXLEGIS-ABORTION15-C     05-14 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXLEGIS-ABORTION15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Narrowed abortion bill fight goes to Texas House floor
 &HT;    By Dave Harmon
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A bill requiring pregnant girls to notify their
parents before getting an abortion cleared a House committee Friday
and is on its way to the House floor, where lawmakers will duel
over whether to add other relatives to the list of adults who could
be notified.
</P>
<P>
   As it stands now, the committee substitute for Senate Bill 30
requires doctors to notify the parent or guardian of any female
patient under 18 who wants an abortion. The bill gives pregnant
teens just one option to bypass parental notification: go before a
judge and plead your case.
</P>
<P>
   That's stricter than an earlier version that would have let
pregnant minors go to a judge, mental health professional, or state
child welfare officials to bypass parental notification.
</P>
<P>
   After the House State Affairs Committee passed the substitute
bill in an 11-1 vote, committee chairman Steve Wolens (D-Dallas)
said he wasn't crazy about this version _ he wants a teen-ager's
relatives to be another option for notification _ but he wanted to
get it to the House floor, where he expects it to be altered.
</P>
<P>
   One potential change, according to committee member Debra
Danburg, a Houston Democrat who cast the lone ``no'' vote, will
come in the form of an amendment to allow other relatives to be
notified of a girl's abortion instead of her parents. Danburg said
a handful of key lawmakers involved in shaping the bill has agreed
not to engage in an amendment war on the House floor. The group
agreed only to propose the amendment adding relatives to the
notification list, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The right-wingers will knock down the right-wing amendments,
the left-wingers will knock down the left-wing amendments,''
Danburg said. ``I told them if they wouldn't add any right-wing
amendments, I wouldn't propose any liberalizing amendments.''
</P>
<P>
   Danburg said the lawmakers, who include Wolens, also have an
understanding with Gov. George W. Bush's office that the governor
won't lobby against including relatives in the notification section
of the bill, and will sign the bill with or without the amendment.
</P>
<P>
   Not so fast, said Linda Edwards, a spokeswoman for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``As Governor Bush said (Thursday), he always reserves the right
to veto a bill,'' Edwards said. ``His position is he wants parents
to be involved, and if there is some extenuating circumstance where
the parents cannot be involved, then he supports the option of
taking it before a judge. He does not support that amendment
(adding other family members).
</P>
<P>
   ``Our office has been very involved working with legislators
throughout the session on this issue, which is one of the
governor's top priorities,'' Edwards added.
</P>
<P>
   Another House member involved in the negotiations over the bill,
Rep. Dianne White Delisi (R-Temple), said she was part of the group
that agreed to keep the bill ``clean'' and not offer amendments.
</P>
<P>
   But Delisi, whose own bill died in committee, said that doesn't
mean she will let relatives be added to the notification bill
without a fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will fight it with everything I have,'' she said. ``That is
not the purpose of this bill, to call an aunt who lives in North
Dakota or to write a grandmother in a nursing home in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I will prevail,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   Wolens said he hopes the final version of the bill includes a
little more compassion. He said he disagrees with the idea in the
current bill that a doctor can go forward with an abortion without
parental notification if the girl could die or suffer serious
injury without an abortion _ but a young woman's emotional anguish
over revealing a pregnancy isn't considered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pretty much this bill says that if a girl is going to commit
suicide (if she has to tell her parents), have at it,'' he said.
``It is very harsh in that respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
