u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VONNEGUT-GRADS15-COX     05-14 0359
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VONNEGUT-GRADS15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Agnes Scott grads to hear Vonnegut original
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Sure, there'll be pomp. And you can't beat this
circumstance.
</P>
<P>
   With 140 graduates receiving diplomas this morning, Agnes Scott
College in Decatur may have one of the area's smaller commencement
ceremonies. But look at the big fish they've reeled in as speaker:
born-again pop cultural touchstone Kurt Vonnegut.
</P>
<P>
   The same Vonnegut whose classic 1969 novel
``Slaughterhouse-Five'' became required read-and-be-seen-reading
material for Vietnam War protesters and other '60s archetypes.
</P>
<P>
   And the same Vonnegut who unwittingly set off a flurry of rumors
two years ago, which in turn, spawned a current hit record _ all
because of a commencement speech he didn't deliver.
</P>
<P>
   ``That probably made me more famous than anything else I've ever
done,'' Vonnegut joked by telephone from New York earlier this
week.
</P>
<P>
   Thank (or blame) the Internet. Two years ago, an e-mail
careening through cyberspace reprinted Vonnegut's commencement
speech at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, beginning,
``If I could offer you only one tip for the future, sunscreen would
be it.''
</P>
<P>
   All very amusing, except the ``speech'' was actually a column
written by the Chicago Tribune's Mary Schmich, and Vonnegut hadn't
even spoken at MIT. Still, sometime movie director Baz Luhrmann
turned it into a song, ``Everybody's Free (to Wear Sunscreen),''
which currently plays about 20 times per week here on radio station
Star 94.
</P>
<P>
   Agnes Scott senior Class President Sandy Miller said that
today's students still appreciate Vonnegut _ the class requested
him before ``Sunscreen'' ever hit.
</P>
<P>
   As for Vonnegut, he gives but one commencement speech each year,
each a ``custom job.'' His subject at Agnes Scott: ``What it must
feel like to be a woman graduate and go out into the world as it is
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing, meanwhile, about ``his'' hit song?
</P>
<P>
   ``Mary and I are getting no royalties,'' Vonnegut sighed. ``And
it's gone platinum.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
