A7943 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-CUBS15-COX     05-14 0377
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-CUBS15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chicago nope: Cubs' Lieber prescribes shutout for Braves
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO - A slumping team with a man on the mound possessing a
1-4 record and 6.05 ERA in his career against the Braves was
supposed to spell a little relief on this tumultous trip.
</P>
<P>
   But not these Cubs, and not Jon Lieber. They extended the
Braves' misery to five losses in the past seven games with a 9-0
victory as Lieber pitched his first career shutout in front of a
sold-out Wrigley Field crowd of 40,046.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team has given me fits. It's great to win the way we
did,'' Lieber said.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs, who had won only two of their previous seven games,
have beaten the Braves six consecutive times in regular-season
games.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves will send Greg Maddux against Steve Trachsel today
looking for their first win at Wrigley since July 22, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The last time a Braves starter won was Tom Glavine's previous
start on May 8. This time around he wasn't nearly as sharp. He
allowed seven hits and five runs _ two runs on a two-out single by
Henry Rodriguez and two on a Sammy Sosa home run _ and lost for the
first time since April 23. The control and the quality of pitches
he'd had over his past three starts wasn't there this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a pitcher after you have three or four good games, in the
back of your mind you wonder when things aren't going to quite
click,'' Glavine said. ``Today was one of those days. I wasn't able
to battle through it.''
</P>
<P>
   Glavine, who'd allowed only two earned runs in his previous 20
1/3 innings, needed only one inning to reach that mark on Wednesday
on the Rodriguez hit.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves' offense has been in a hibernation of its own. In
five losses on this trip the Braves have scored a total of five
runs and been shut out twice in the past five games.
</P>
<P>
   An idea of how it's been going? Brian Jordan just missed a home
run when the ball curled foul down the left-field line in the sixth
inning. On the next pitch, he grounded into a double play.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to do too much,'' Jordan said. ``One person is
trying to pick up the whole team. We're overswinging.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
