<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-GLOVER15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Top scout says Glover isn't ready
 &HT;    By J.C. Clemons
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Dion Glover's decision to make himself eligible for
the NBA draft drew a rebuke Friday from Marty Blake, the league's
director of scouting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's making a big mistake,'' Blake said. ``My
recommendation to him is to explore his options, and then return to
Georgia Tech.''
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-5 Glover, who would be a redshirt sophomore next
season, has decided to enter the June 30 draft despite missing all
of last season after injuring his left knee the first day of
practice and undergoing reconstructive surgery. Glover averaged
18.4 points a game during his first season, 1997-98, the
third-highest scoring freshman in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Glover, who considered turning pro a year earlier, had the third
highest-scoring season (608 points) ever recorded by a Tech
freshman _ behind Kenny Anderson and Stephon Marbury _ and tied the
freshman school scoring record with a 33-point effort against Seton
Hall in the National Invitation Tournament. Anderson, Marbury and
Dennis Scott are the only three to leave as underclassmen during
coach Bobby Cremins' tenure at Tech.
</P>
<P>
   Glover and Cremins could not be reached for comment, but in a
statement released through the school, Glover said: ``When I was
first injured in October, Coach Cremins explained this option to
me, and I want to take full advantage of the rules to get an idea
of what the pros think of me.''
</P>
<P>
   Glover could maintain his eligibility by withdrawing his name 72
hours before the draft. Also, if he goes through the two-round
process without being picked, he has 30 days to request that his
college eligibility be restored, as long as he hasn't signed with
an agent or accepted any money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will do all I can to help and guide Dion through this
process,'' Cremins said in the statement. ``Dion has assured me he
will abide by all NCAA rules.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
