<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 21:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7945 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WTO-APPOINT-520&AMP;ADD-N     05-14 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WTO-APPOINT-520&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERIOUS ISSUES BEHIND DIVISIONS AS WTO SEARCHES FOR A LEADER
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ELIZABETH OLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ Anger and betrayal have colored the World Trade
Organization's deadlocked talks to choose a new leader, but behind
the emotions are three substantive issues _ the interests of
workers, farmers and the environment _ that have polarized the
134-nation group, producing odd alliances of rich and poor, big and
small.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever is picked as director-general of the organization that
sets rules for global commerce will have an important impact on
whether it tries to impose some labor and environmental protection
rules on everyone, and tries to clear away some existing domestic
protections for agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   Such changes, on the surface, seem fair and reflect the global
forum's commitment to level playing fields in the competition to
sell goods and services across borders. But they represent threats
to countries heavily dependent on agriculture, farm imports or the
use of inexpensive labor. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   These issues have factored into the reasons why member countries
are refusing to compromise over the two finalist candidates, Mike
Moore of New Zealand and Supachai Panitchpakdi of Thailand.
</P>
<P>
   The deadlock, now entering its third week, has left the
organization leaderless since the four-year term of Renato Ruggiero
of Italy expired May 1.
</P>
<P>
   The choices of Japan and the United States, the two giant
trading powers, particularly reflect concerns over these issues.
</P>
<P>
   The United States wants Moore, who is seen as a strong advocate
of better worker treatment and free trade in agriculture. Japan
favors Supachai because he is viewed as more sensitive to the
interests of farmers who worry that they cannot compete with
inexpensive imports.
</P>
<P>
   The United States' preference rests partly on concerns that
Supachai would not advocate environmental and labor issues. ``It
became clear that these issues would take a back seat, as far as
Supachai was concerned,'' a U.S. official said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   American environmental setbacks in trade organization decisions,
most notably an overruling of U.S. safeguards for endangered sea
turtles caught in shrimpers' nets, contributed to Washington's
concern that a new trade leader be attuned to such issues.
</P>
<P>
   Japan and the United States also differ on which candidate would
serve each nation's interest best in agriculture. The Americans
view Moore as a forceful advocate of ending subsidies for farmers
that keep prices artificially high. The Japanese say such a
position is unfair to countries that want to protect small,
family-run farms.
</P>
<P>
   Yoichi Suzuki, Japan's envoy to the trade organization, said,
``Politically speaking, it is not very easy to accept someone from
a country which is a free trader in agriculture.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Thailand, too, is a large agricultural exporter,
especially of rice, a sensitive commodity in Asia, as well as being
a member, along with New Zealand, of a major pro-free trade group.
So why would Japan back Supachai? ``He is viewed as having a more
receptive attitude to the Japanese view that agriculture is a
pillar of rural life, of the environment, of conserving old ways,''
a Japanese negotiator said. &QL;
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Not every country with big agricultural interests has based its
decision on agriculture alone. France, with entrenched farm
subsidies and a powerful farmers lobby, supports Moore. ``This is a
case where the labor forces who fear low-wage competition have won
out over the agricultural interests,'' a European diplomat said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other European countries have also split between the two
candidates, leaving the 15-member European Union with no unified
choice for director-general.
</P>
<P>
   Although Washington favors Moore, it has remained conspicuously
silent. This has created resentment among a number of trade
diplomats in Geneva, who are convinced that American trade
officials are maneuvering clandestinely to ensure that Moore wins.
</P>
<P>
   Resentment is also fueled by a belief among many developing
countries that they have not benefited yet from current free-trade
rules, that liberalized agricultural trade and higher labor
standards would hurt them. Many are also convinced that a
representative from a developing country, such as Thailand, should
lead the organization. Among the most vocal advocates of Supachai's
candidacy are India and Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a strong feeling, right or wrong, that the United
States has prolonged this race to influence the outcome,'' one
envoy from a developing country said. ``That has upset a number of
delegates, and entrenched positions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
