A7947 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EPA-DOCTRINE-NYT     05-14 0353
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EPA-DOCTRINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPEALS COURT REVIVES ARCANE DOCTRINE IN EPA CASE
</HEADLINE>
 (Sidebar with EPA-POLLUTE) 
(bl) 
By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In overturning a clean air standard Friday, a
federal appeals court panel here focused on the ``nondelegation
doctrine,'' invoking a phrase with an unfamiliar ring. Indeed, the
notion that Congress can violate the constitutional separation of
powers by delegating too much legislative-like authority to another
branch of government has essentially been a non-issue since the
early days of the New Deal.
</P>
<P>
   Twice in the mid-1930s, the Supreme Court struck down federal
laws as delegating too much power, in those cases not to
executive-branch agencies but to private organizations. In the
National Industry Recovery Act, Congress gave authority to private
industry groups to establish codes of competition, and in the
Bituminous Coal Conservation Act, Congress had delegated to the
coal industry the job of setting wage and hour regulations.
</P>
<P>
   But since striking down those laws, the justices have
consistently upheld broad congressional delegations of authority
and have shown no appetite for reviving the old doctrine. The issue
received its most extended recent discussion in a 1989 Supreme
Court case, Mistretta vs. United States, which upheld the federal
sentencing guidelines. The guidelines had been challenged as
delegating too much legislative authority to a new judicial branch
agency, the U.S. Sentencing Commission.
</P>
<P>
   In that ruling, all nine justices rejected the delegation
challenge. Writing for the court, Justice Harry Blackmun said the
court's current view of the delegation question was based on ``a
practical understanding that in our increasingly complex society,
replete with ever changing and more technical problems, Congress
simply cannot do its job absent an ability to delegate power under
broad general directives.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the flame has never quite died among conservative
legal scholars and judges, who view administrative agencies with
even more suspicion than they regard Congress.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
