<HEADER>
A7960 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-USWEST-GLOBAL-ART-760     05-14 1281
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-USWEST-GLOBAL-ART-760&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAST-GROWING PHONE CONCERN SAID TO DISCUSS U S WEST DEAL
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz., Calif., Colo., Minn., N.D., Ore., S.D., Wash.,
Wyo.)   (Skedded on the front page as PHONE-MERGER) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphics clients. Non-subscribers may make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By LAURA M. HOLSON and SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Proposing what would be a formidable challenge to regulators,
Global Crossing Ltd., an acquisition-hungry communications upstart,
is in talks to merge with U S West Inc., the smallest of the Baby
Bell local phone giants, in a stock swap valued at more than $30
billion, executives close to the talks said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   While the negotiations are far from over and talks could fall
apart at any time, the two companies could announce a deal as early
as next week. Executives close to the companies said the boards of
both concerns planned to meet this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Global Crossing, a startup with headquarters in Bermuda, aims to
build and operate a worldwide fiber optic telecommunications
network and had ambitions of rivaling MCI Worldcom. A merger with U
S West, which has been left out of the consolidation trend among
the Baby Bells, would help Global Crossing establish the American
foothold it needs to compete against the communications industry's
behemoths.
</P>
<P>
   The two companies have been discussing a merger for about three
weeks, the executives said. But the talks hit a stumbling block in
recent days after the Frontier Corp., the No. 5 long-distance
company, which agreed in March to be acquired by Global Crossing
for $12 billion, learned about Global Crossing's discussions with U
S West.
</P>
<P>
   The deal between Frontier and Global Crossing has not been
finalized, and Frontier's agreement with Global Crossing gives
Frontier the the right to veto any sizable acquisition by Global
Crossing, said one executive close to the talks.
</P>
<P>
   Because the combination of U S West and Global Crossing is being
billed as a merger of equals _ with the combined company to be
equally owned by shareholders of Global Crossing-Frontier on one
side and and U S West on the other _ the executive said Global
Crossing might not need Frontier's approval. Still, if Frontier
does not bless the transaction, it could lead to a legal tangle.
</P>
<P>
   No matter the financial details, a full-blown merger between
Global Crossing and U S West would face immense regulatory
obstacles. In fact, some analysts and communications industry
executives said Friday that it would be highly unlikely that
federal regulators would approve such a deal at all.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, nothing is simple about this deal, least of all the new
company's proposed structure. The U S West and Global Crossing
combination would comprise two tracking stocks: one for the
traditional telephone company assets for Frontier and U S West, the
other for the higher-growth Internet and data assets.
</P>
<P>
   U S West shareholders would swap their shares for stock in
Global Crossing, with each company's original holders owning 50
percent of the combined company. Investors would have the option to
receive shares in either tracking stock.
</P>
<P>
   The two companies would also have significant cultural issues to
overcome, and most analysts agree that executives from Global
Crossing would really run the show. Solomon D. Trujillo, chairman
and chief executive of U S West, would be expected to be named
co-chief executive along with Robert Annunziata of Global Crossing
in a combined company.
</P>
<P>
   Trujillo would probably move to Beverly Hills, Calif., where
Global Crossing's main offices are located, from U S West's Denver
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Global is a fast-paced entrepreneurial firm, the other a
traditional phone company,'' Richard Klugman, a telecommunications
analyst at Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette Inc., said. ```Any time you
introduce two different cultures, there is likely to be a clash.''
</P>
<P>
   There are serious regulatory hurdles as well. The
Telecommunications Act of 1996 says the Bells may not sell
long-distance service in any state within their traditional regions
until they convince the Federal Communications Commission that they
have opened their local phone networks to potential competitors.
</P>
<P>
   No Bell has yet passed that test, and U S West is seen by most
communications analysts as being farther away from winning
long-distance entry than any of its Bell brethren.
</P>
<P>
   Frontier, meanwhile, has long-distance customers all over the
nation, including some within U S West's region, which includes
Phoenix, Denver, Portland, Ore., Seattle and Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   While Frontier may have a disproportionately small number of its
customers in U S West's territory, which also includes many rural
states including Wyoming and the Dakotas, a merger between U S West
and a company that includes Frontier would appear to be a clear
violation of the communications act, many communications experts
said Friday.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``U S West is farther behind any of the Bells in being able to
get relief from the FCC, and realistically it's at a minimum a year
out and probably a lot longer,'' said Scott Cleland, a
communications policy analyst in Washington for the Legg Mason
Precursor Group. ``There aren't any states in U S West territory
where regulators think they're close.''
</P>
<P>
   There are moves that could potentially solve the problems, such
as selling all of Frontier's long-distance customers in U S West's
territory. And regulators may look more kindly on a U S West deal
than they did on the abortive merger talks in 1997 between AT&AMP;T and
SBC Communications because U S West is the smallest Bell; a deal
with Global Crossing could allow U S West to compete against the
communications industry's behemoths.
</P>
<P>
   But what appears to be a more workable deal would be for U S
West to take a mere 10 percent interest in Global
Crossing-Frontier, the limit stated in the law. Earlier this year,
SBC Communications Inc. agreed to acquire up to 10 percent of the
Williams Companies Inc.'s communications unit, a long-distance
upstart, while the BellSouth Corp. agreed to acquire 10 percent of
Qwest Communications International Inc., another new long-distance
carrier.
</P>
<P>
   In such a deal, Frontier could also sell U S West its far-flung
local phone properties, which are scattered in 13 states.
Frontier's local businesses, which have about 1 million customers,
are close to stagnant and have been a drag on the company (though
they do provide needed cash).
</P>
<P>
   The 1 million local customers could be expected to command
perhaps between $2 billion and $3 billion, while 10 percent of a
combined Global Crossing-Frontier would have a market value of
about $3.6 billion. To pay a price of $6.6 billion (or higher, if
the 10 percent stake merits a premium), U S West could assume some
of Global Crossing-Frontier's debt and, even better for Global
Crossing, put up some cash to help Global Crossing pay for its
continued network construction.
</P>
<P>
   In such a deal, Global Crossing would get an anchor tenant for
its network (U S West can currently sell long-distance calls as
part of its less-regulated operations, such as wireless service). U
S West would be assured of low-cost long-distance capacity to meet
its needs for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   Global Crossing's shares gained $1.375, closing at $61.375 in
Nasdaq trading after CNBC, the cable network, said it was in talks
with U S West. Shares of U S West closed at $62.25, up $2.25, while
shares of Frontier lost $2.75 to close at $56.125.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
