<SLUG> BC-ALCOHOL-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS SENATOR'S MOVE KILLS ALCOHOL MEASURES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JAMIE STOCKWELL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A Houston senator killed a House measure Friday
that restricted drinking, including a ban on open containers of
alcohol in vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Mario Gallegos, D-Galena Park, ``tagged'' three bills on
the Senate floor, making it impossible to amend them for 24 hours.
Faced with a midnight deadline to be voted out of Senate
committees, the bills were effectively killed.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the-open container issue, one of the bills included
amendments that would ban alcohol from topless bars and ban minors
from entering bars.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure to kill the legislation came from abortion rights
groups, who feared that anti-abortion legislators would succeed in
amending some bills so that an unborn fetus could be defined as a
living person.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are ways that amendments could be tacked on that would
lay the groundwork for abortions to be deemed illegal,'' said Peggy
Romberg, executive director of Texas Family Planning Association,
who said she asked Gallegos to tag the bills.
</P>
<P>
   Romberg feared that a senator could have added an amendment to
the bill that would stiffen the penalties against someone who
drives drunk and kills a pregnant woman, allowing the driver to be
prosecuted for the death of the mother and her unborn baby.
</P>
<P>
   Also killed was a bill sponsored by Rep. Fred Hill,
R-Richardson, that also would have banned open containers but which
included fewer exemptions and potential loopholes. Hill's bill was
proposed in an effort to avoid the loss of federal transportation
funds.
</P>
<P>
   Without an open-container law in place by Oct. 1, 2000, the
state will face harsh penalties. Texas would be forced to divert
about $40 million in highway construction funds to safety and
education programs. In 2002, the amount would double, and would
continue to increase for every year the state fails to comply with
the federal law.
</P>
<P>
   But Gallegos said his primary concern is not the highway funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue here is not the dollars (being lost) and the issue
is not open containers,'' he said. ``The issue is this: I'm not
going to allow others to have a chance to put language in that
would be a vehicle for pro-life legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
