<HEADER>
A7968 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDONESIA-SALIM-ART-3     05-14 1157
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-SALIM-ART-3TAKES-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YEAR OF LIVING DANGEROUSLY FOR A TYCOON IN INDONESIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo and a graphic of the holdings of the Salim family,
Indonesia's biggest businessmen is being sent to NYT graphic
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 16)  
 (af)  
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ A year ago this week, Anthony Salim looked
out from his 19th-floor office and watched his hometown go up in
flames. Angry mobs rampaged through the streets, looting and
torching cars, motorcycles, shops and anything else in their path.
Plumes of smoke rose from Jakarta's Chinese quarter, where the
crowds turned their rage on the terrified residents.
</P>
<P>
   In his wood-paneled perch, Indonesia's leading ethnic Chinese
tycoon could almost feel the flames at his feet.
</P>
<P>
   At 11:30 on that Thursday morning, Salim learned that his
family's home had been burned to the ground. Rioters had dragged
out and slashed a portrait of his father and spray-painted the
words ``Suharto's dog'' on the gate. Reluctantly, Salim caught the
next flight to Singapore.
</P>
<P>
   ``If your house is already burned, the next thing they would try
to do is get the people,'' Salim explained in a rare interview
here. ``You don't want to get caught in the middle of something
like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Salim, 49, is back in the middle of things. And while he
may not fear for his life, his fortunes are hardly more secure than
they were during those stormy days. Salim is fighting to save the
family empire that he and his father, Liem Sioe Liong, built over
six decades _ an empire, devastated by Indonesia's economic
collapse, that is lurching under $5 billion in debt.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia, moreover, is still a dangerous place. Fresh violence
may erupt next month as the country holds its first multiparty
elections in four decades. Ethnic Chinese merchants are preparing
to board up their shops, fearful that if crowds take to the
streets, they will again be victimized.
</P>
<P>
   As the richest of the Chinese families _ one whose wealth was
founded on its close ties with Indonesia's fallen president,
Suharto _ the Salims are a lightning rod for both ethnic and
economic resentment.
</P>
<P>
   ``They could go after him for everything,'' H.S. Dillon, a
prominent economist here, said of Salim. ``He would be a very good
symbol to crucify. He is the most vulnerable of the cronies.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Salim Group, the family's network of businesses, has
proved remarkably resilient. Its stubborn survival shows how deeply
crony capitalism has taken root here.
</P>
<P>
   If, as many people believe, Salim can hold his empire together,
it will say a lot about the limits of reform in a country where
conglomerates still dominate the economy _ and where the cost of
unraveling the biggest ones may be more than anyone is prepared to
pay.
</P>
<P>
   For now, at least, Salim is making a vigorous case for the
status quo. After remaining in Singapore for a month after
Suharto's ouster, he returned here and began chipping away at the
mountain of debt that looms over the Salim Group. It has been a
grueling, painful and humbling exercise.
</P>
<P>
   Salim was forced to cede control of his flagship asset, Bank
Central Asia, to the government. He also handed over stakes in
dozens of companies, ranging from flour mills and cement factories
to palm oil plantations and office towers. And he is selling other
assets in a desperate effort to raise cash.
</P>
<P>
   His goal is to raise enough money to pay off the $5 billion he
owes the government for its bailout of the bank. If he has enough
left over, he wants to buy back a stake in BCA, which despite its
huge debts is still Indonesia's largest private bank, with 760
branches scattered across this vast archipelago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing is to weather this period _ ``not to
be wiped out by the big wave coming in,'' Salim said.
</P>
<P>
   Remarkably _ given the tsunami that engulfed him last year _
most analysts, bankers, and government officials agree that Salim
will survive and may even prosper. With $20 billion in sales, 500
companies, and 200,000 workers, the Salim Group is so embedded in
the commercial tissue of this country that its breakup, economists
say, would cause severe disruptions in major industries like food
processing, construction and banking.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the Salim Group, like America's Chrysler Corp. a
generation ago, may be too big to fail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoever rules Indonesia will have to do business with the
Salims,'' said Wilson Nababan, the president director of CISI Raya
Utama, a credit-rating agency in Jakarta. ``They still have so many
valuable concessions and they own assets in virtually every part of
the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Salims have also hedged their bets by building a sizable
offshore empire during the last two decades. About 35 percent of
the group's revenues come from holdings outside Indonesia, like the
First Pacific Co., a Hong Kong conglomerate that owns real estate
and telecommunications properties.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy will never be wiped out,'' said Suryo Sulisto, the
chairman of a trade association that represents pribumi, or
indigenous Indonesian business executives. ``He's got his money
salted overseas.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many native Indonesians, Sulisto resents the favorable
treatment the Salims and other ethnic Chinese enjoyed under
Suharto. Such treatment, he said, helped them accumulate a
disproportionate share of the country's wealth. Although they make
up only 3 percent of the population, ethnic Chinese control as much
as 70 percent of Indonesia's private economy.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, according to Sulisto, the most powerful Chinese tycoons
made loans recklessly and lacked accountability, which he said
turned the devaluation of Indonesia's currency, the rupiah, into an
economic calamity.
</P>
<P>
   President B.J. Habibie, he added, should confiscate the Salim
Group's assets and auction them; other critics say Salim should be
put on trial for corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Anthony Salim about that hostility and he responds in a
matter-of-fact tone that suggests that he came to grips with it a
long time ago. Even before the riots, Salim's family lived in
Singapore, and he commutes there every weekend. Two of his children
are in college in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without personal safety, everything else is gone,'' Salim said
quietly. ``It's unrealistic that you're not calculating every
single event or every single possibility. But if you keep worrying,
you do no work.''
</P>
<P>
   A cordial, soft-spoken man with tousled hair and a tuft of
whiskers on his chin, Salim works hard to project a nonthreatening
image. In this, he is like his father and other Chinese tycoons in
Southeast Asia. Educated at a technical college in London, he wears
batik shirts to the office and looks very much like a product of
the central Javanese town of Kudus, where he was born.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Although Salim has pushed to expand the octopus-like reach of
the Salim Group, he says he is not interested in building a
glittering monument.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am neither IBM nor Shangri-La,'' he said, referring to the
luxury hotel chain. ``I have to understand my limitations and
compensate for my weaknesses. What I am good at is trying to
package products and services.''
</P>
<P>
   That subdued style worked to his advantage in his arduous
negotiations with the Indonesian Bank Restructuring Agency, which
nationalized BCA and represented the government in its debt talks
with Salim.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we started this process, everyone was skeptical,'' said
Farid Haryanto, the deputy chairman of the agency. ``But Anthony
Salim focused on the problem. What dragged us together was a common
belief in the future of the private sector in Indonesia.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Salim has won respect for tackling his financial
problems, the real durability of the Salim Group may owe more to
Liem Sioe Liong, his father. By extending his family's reach into
almost every corner of the Indonesian economy, Liem created a
virtually indestructible machine.
</P>
<P>
   Born to a poor family in Fujian province in China, he immigrated
to Indonesia in 1937. At first, he labored in obscurity, selling
cloves, peanuts and bicycle parts in Central Java.
</P>
<P>
   But in the 1950s, Liem made the contact of his life, meeting a
young army lieutenant colonel named Suharto _ and began supplying
the military base that came under Suharto's command.
</P>
<P>
   During this period, Liem adopted an Indonesian name, Sudono
Salim. While his son Anthony took the Salim name, the 83-year-old
patriarch _ who now divides his time between homes in Los Angeles,
Singapore, and Jakarta _ is still widely referred to by his Chinese
name.
</P>
<P>
   Liem's fortunes rose along with Suharto's. When Suharto forced
out President Sukarno in 1966, Liem was ready to help the new
leader develop the country's economy _ one of the cherished goals
of the Suharto ``new order.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon, Liem won a monopoly license to import cloves, the key
ingredient in Indonesia's distinctive sweet-smelling cigarettes. It
was the first of dozens of licenses, franchises and concessions
that would make Liem a baron in coffee, rubber, sugar, wheat,
flour, noodles, rice and cement.
</P>
<P>
   When Suharto wanted Indonesia to expand into new industries,
Liem obliged by opening factories or planting fields. When Liem
needed favors _ a waiver of securities law of restrictions on
satellite transmissions _ the president happily complied.
</P>
<P>
   Liem's ties with Suharto went beyond back-scratching. Two of the
former president's daughters owned d stakes in Bank Central Asia.
And one of Suharto's cousins, Sudwikatmono, is a member of a group
of businessmen who invest in many of the Salim Group's ventures.
</P>
<P>
   By the early 1990s, the Salim Group was a leviathan, accounting
for 5 percent of Indonesia's economic output. In the United States,
that would be like the combined output of Exxon, General Motors,
IBM and AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   Liem was scarcely exaggerating when, in the group's most recent
annual report, he wrote, ``Our companies are intimately involved in
the day-to-day lives of literally millions of Indonesians.''
</P>
<P>
   Would that Liem had earned all this by sweat and guile. Instead,
he was other tycoons were beneficiaries of subsidies and sweetheart
deals that turned Indonesia into an exemplar of emerging-markets
cronymism.
</P>
<P>
   The Salim Group's dominance of the Indonesian flour business
provides a case study of its methods. In 1969, Suharto granted Liem
a monopoly on the importation, milling and distribution of flour.
That enabled his company to build the world's largest flour mill,
Bogosari.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the arrangement, Indonesia's state logistics
agency, known as Bulog, imported wheat and sold it to Bogosari at a
subsidized price. Bogosari then milled the wheat into flour and
sold most of it back to Bulog, tacking on a fee.
</P>
<P>
   Nor were Liem's advantages confined to milling. Bogosari kept a
portion of the flour, which its parent, the Salim-controlled
Indofood Sukses Makmur, processed into instant noodles. The
arrangement helped make Indofood a dominant food producer, with 90
percent of the noodle market in this country, which has 210 million
people.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia deregulated the flour business in March. But
Bogosari's vast size gives it a commanding edge over potential
competitors. The mill, which sprawls along Jakarta's waterfront and
processes 10,000 tons of wheat a day, is 50 percent larger than the
next largest in the world _ one also owned by the Salims, in the
Indonesian city of Surabaya.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia's parliament recently passed anti-monopoly legislation
that analysts say could force the Salim Group to spin off Bogosari.
Cesar dela Cruz, the chief financial officer of Indofood, said the
parent company would be willing to sell up to 60 percent of the
mill to a group of investors, a deal that analysts say could raise
$420 million.
</P>
<P>
   To this day, Anthony Salim defends the roots of the family's
empire.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never broke the rules,'' he said. ``Whether it was a
monopoly or not, those were the rules of the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Salim was eager to make changes when he joined the family
business out of college in 1972. By 1992, when Liem named his
youngest son chief executive of the Salim Group, Anthony Salim set
about transforming the group from an old-fashioned trading house
into a sophisticated global conglomerate.
</P>
<P>
   Liem had built his business through a intricate web of
partnerships. His bank, for example, was run by Mochtar Riady, who
later started the Lippo Group and became enmeshed in the
campaign-finance scandal in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Salim slowly phased out these partnerships and recruited
professional managers to run companies like First Pacific and
Indofood.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was eager to embrace modern ways of doing things,'' said
Robert L. Meyer, an American who was a co-founder of First Pacific
and was a director until last year.
</P>
<P>
   Salim said the Salim Group, with the rapid development of the
Indonesian economy, had moved from a government-dictated strategy
to a market-based approach. Now, he said, it has to move again, to
a standard of greater financial disclosure and adherence to
international legal standards.
</P>
<P>
   It was a lack of regulations and transparency that put the Salim
Group in jeopardy. During the 1980s and early-1990s, most
Indonesian conglomerates financed their capital needs with loans
from their own banks. Although Indonesia's Central Bank limited
such intercompany loans to 20 percent of the bank's portfolio, few
tycoons paid much attention to the rules.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Salim Group was no exception: BCA made as much as 50 percent
of its loans to other Salim companies. Many of those loans were
denominated in American dollars, which meant that when the rupiah
crashed in late 1997, BCA was suddenly shouldering $2 billion in
debt.
</P>
<P>
   The bank also became a target during last year's riots. Dozens
of its branches were looted and burned. And nearly three million
panicky depositors besieged the bank to withdraw their money.
Within a week, BCA lost 42 percent of its capital, forcing a
bailout by the government at a cost of an additional $3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   In hindsight, Salim regrets the profligate lending, but he puts
the loans in perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course it was the wrong thing to do in the sense of prudent
lending,'' Salim said. ``But on the other hand, everybody was doing
the same thing. We just fit into the prevailing climate.''
</P>
<P>
   The debt crisis ultimately gave the government the leverage to
cut a deal with the Salims. By hinting that Salim could be
prosecuted over the lending excesses, the Bank Restructuring Agency
persuaded him to turn over stakes in 104 companies, including
publicly listed giants like Indofood, Indocement and First Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   The government is holding the stakes as collateral to offset its
bailout of BCA. Salim's future depends on how much money he can
earn from selling other assets to pay down the debt. He is not
unlike a homeowner rummaging in the attic for things to sell in a
yard sale.
</P>
<P>
   So far, though his yard sale has been a stop-and-go affair.
Salim recently sold his Singapore property arm for $183 million,
but only after a previous deal had fallen through. And he announced
the sale of 60 percent of Indofood to First Pacific, in which the
group holds a minority stake, and a Japanese food company, Nissin
Food Products _ only to have Nissin pull out because of doubts
about obtaining approval from its banks.
</P>
<P>
   That cut the value of the deal in half, to $285 million. And it
made Salim vulnerable to accusations of self-dealing, since the
remaining investor, First Pacific, is controlled by his family.
</P>
<P>
   Despite these setbacks, Salim has had some good fortune. Stock
markets in Asia have rebounded sharply in the last four months,
driving up the value of his publicly listed companies, particularly
Indofood and First Pacific. While each is still worth about 40
percent less than its value before the Asian crisis, they have
climbed back from having lost 80 percent to 95 percent of their
market value.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts also speculate about further deals, including a
possible investment by the Ford Motor Co. in the Salim Group's auto
maker, Indomobil. The Indonesian government is also keen to lure
foreign banks to invest in BCA. Citigroup and ABN Amro are both
mentioned as potential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The wild card in all this is Indonesian politics. Foreign
investors have generally shunned the country out of fear that the
parliamentary elections next month could prompt a new spasm of
violence. Few analysts think Salim will make great strides with his
asset sales until the elections are over.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, a setback for Habibie's party could have a profound
effect on Salim's prospects. Although the president has endorsed
his government's efforts to drive a hard bargain with Salim, he has
not confiscated Salim assets or prosecuted him for corruption.
Other politicians, particularly those with stronger ties to the
Muslim business community, might be more hostile.
</P>
<P>
   With Suharto in retirement, the Salim family's most obvious
political alliance has gone up in smoke. But that does not mean the
family has given up trying to influence events. A former government
official here said Salim has made large donations to Habibie's
governing party, Golkar.
</P>
<P>
   Salim responded that he did not have spare money to lavish on
politicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Indonesia, you shouldn't participate in politics,'' he
said, ``But you can't be immune from politics either. You watch and
observe.''
</P>
<P>
   Salim said he had even visited Suharto, who lives in a
well-guarded house on a leafy Jakarta street. But he was quick to
add that the Salims were not helping the former president,
financially or otherwise. Antipathy toward Suharto runs deeps here,
and Salim does not need to make any new enemies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Indonesia is like a room with oxygen,'' he said. ``We'll be
here as long as there is enough oxygen to survive. If there is no
longer enough oxygen ... .''
</P>
<P>
   With that, Salim's voice trailed off and his gaze drifted to the
window. The skyline of Jakarta shimmered in the tropical haze _ as
ever, a city of promise and peril for Indonesia's ethnic Chinese.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
