<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   U.S. THREATENS TO IMPOSE PUNITIVE DUTIES IN BEEF WAR
</P>
<P>
   The United States escalated a trade war with the European Union
by threatening to impose $202 million in punitive duties on the
trading bloc for banning imports of American beef from
hormone-treated cattle.
</P>
<P>
   Charlene Barshefsky, the U.S. trade representative, said
Washington remained open to talks to resolve the decade-old
dispute, but added, ``We will absolutely protect our rights and we
will without question retaliate if the EU persists in disregarding
the rules.''
</P>
<P>
   HEALTHEON MAY BE BUYING WEBMD
</P>
<P>
   Healtheon, the medical record-keeping Web site started by Jim
Clark, Netscape Communications' founder, is expected to announce
Monday that it is buying WebMD, a privately held Internet provider
of medical information, for over $3.5 billion in stock.
</P>
<P>
   DELAY LIKELY ON DERIVATIVES RULE
</P>
<P>
   The United States' accounting rule makers, the Financial
Accounting Standards Board, may delay the date when companies must
begin following a controversial new rule that requires them to
record the value of derivatives in their financial statements.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA'S ECONOMY ON THE UPSWING
</P>
<P>
   Despite political turmoil in Russia, the nation's economy seems
to be recovering from its collapse last summer. Consumer spending
rose 1.5 percent in March, and industrial production has returned
to the level of December 1997, a Moscow research group reported.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. FINES SEARS ON CHILD LABOR
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Labor announced a $325,000 fine against Sears,
Roebuck &AMP; Co. after investigators uncovered 227 teen-agers working
in violation of child-labor laws at 44 of the 71 Sears stores they
visited in 23 states. The most common violation found was that
16-year-olds and 17-year-olds were operating power-driven equipment
like paper balers, freight elevators and fork lifts. Federal law
bars children from running such hazardous equipment.
</P>
<P>
   JUDGE TONES DOWN ENERGIZER BUNNY
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge ruled that the Energizer Bunny cannot go on
torching, crushing and pummeling rival batteries on television. In
the finding for Gillette, the judge said that Energizer's
manufacturer, Ralston Purina, must at least temporarily pull the
plug on its attack-bunny battery advertising campaign. The ads,
developed for Ralston Purina by the advertising agency TBWA
Chiat/Day, appear on all major TV networks, on the Internet and in
print.
</P>
<P>
   COURT REJECTS ANTI-POLLUTION RULES
</P>
<P>
   A federal appeals court threw out new rules on soot and smog
developed under the Clean Air Act, which is considered one of the
most important government pollution standards of this decade.
</P>
<P>
   THREE ISSUES DOMINATE TRADE GROUP
</P>
<P>
   Behind the World Trade Organization's deadlocked talks to choose
a new leader are the interests of workers, farmers and
environmentalists. The issues have polarized the 134-nation group,
producing odd alliances.
</P>
<P>
   PITFALLS ON THE ROAD FROM WELFARE
</P>
<P>
   A close look at the decade-old Milwaukee experiment with
guaranteed jobs, called Project New Hope, which is scheduled to
close this week, suggests that inner-city poverty may be even
harder to alleviate than has generally been believed. Although the
project has been hailed as a success, an independent team of
economists, psychologists and ethnographers found that even with a
guaranteed job at a subsidized wage, 73 percent of the main target
group failed to work their way out of poverty without additional
support from welfare or a second earner.
</P>
<P>
   HICKS, MUSE IS ACQUIRING HILLSDOWN
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas-based investment firm Hicks, Muse, Tate &AMP; Furst
agreed Friday to buy Hillsdown Holdings, a British food company
whose products include Typhoo Tea, for 464 million pounds ($752
million).
</P>
</TEXT>
