<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7973 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-LOUIMA-TURETSKY-62     05-14 1174
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LOUIMA-TURETSKY-625&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICER WHO BROKE CODE OF SILENCE IN TORTURE CASE DEFIES LABELS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID BARSTOW   and KEVIN FLYNN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After giving damning evidence to Internal Affairs
investigators, Eric Turetzky, a rookie New York City police
officer, emerged from an interview room at the 70th Precinct
station house in Brooklyn. It was not yet dawn on Aug. 15, 1997,
six days after a handcuffed defendant, Abner Louima, allegedly was
tortured in a bathroom at the precinct.
</P>
<P>
   The mood was tense. Some officers muttered angry words at
Turetzky for cooperating with Internal Affairs. But one burly,
towering officer approached Turetzky, and, as Internal Affairs
investigators braced for a confrontation, the officer said in a
loud, clear voice: ``I wanted to let Eric know he is doing the
right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The incident revealed the stinging rejection _ and unexpected
acceptance _ that Eric Turetzky has found within the New York City
Police Department since that day, two years ago, when he became one
of the few officers to break the code of silence that often impedes
investigations of police misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   Again this week, this conflicting response was on display as
Turetzky _ since promoted to detective _ testified in a U.S.
District Court in Brooklyn against five of his former colleagues
from the 70th Precinct. During some four hours of testimony,
Turetzky was forced to publicly confront the central question about
him: Is he a selfless hero or a selfish rat?
</P>
<P>
   From the witness stand, he refused to be placed in either
category. He portrayed himself as a flawed officer who wanted to do
his duty, but also agonized about turning in friends. But the
debate about Turetzky, and his motives, is far from over.
</P>
<P>
   His testimony is critical for prosecutors who are attempting to
prove that one officer, Justin Volpe, thrust a stick into Louima's
rectum. Turetzky testified that he saw Volpe, moments after the
alleged assault, swinging a broken broomstick as if it were a
sword.
</P>
<P>
   Friends, neighbors and family members spoke about Turetzky this
week with extraordinary warmth. ``If you need to find a most honest
and upstanding person, you'd be looking for Eric,'' said Dr. Ellen
D. Panzer, who has know Turetzky since he was a boy.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the five officers, however, contend that Turetzky is
concealing darker elements of his personality. They have questioned
whether he cooperated because he was scared of being implicated in
the case, or because he was jealous, or because he felt picked
upon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't it true, detective, that what you did in this case was
operate out of your own self-interest?'' one defense lawyer,
Stephen C. Worth, asked him on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Hero or rat, there is no disputing one point: that August
morning marked a turning point for Turetzky, 28. For as he left the
precinct station house, he was also leaving behind the dream he
held for his future in the Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing that Eric loved more than anything else was being a
beat cop, working with the other officers and being in the
community,'' said one investigator involved in the Louima case.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Turetzky found himself under police protection. He
spent months doing little more than desk work for the Internal
Affairs Bureau, where he now works as a detective investigating
possible crimes _ by fellow officers.
</P>
<P>
   Turetzky, who lives with his mother and grandparents in
Canarsie, Brooklyn, declined to be interviewed. ``Right now he's
not ready,'' his grandmother, Anne Rosenblum, said.
</P>
<P>
   She did, however, describe him as being at peace with his
decision to testify this week, and unruffled by attacks on his
character. ``He's not uncomfortable about it,'' Mrs. Rosenblum
said, adding that her grandson has found new friends and new goals
while working in Internal Affairs.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Rabbi Alvin Kass, who will preside at Turetzky's upcoming
wedding, said the officer believes in the Talmud's message that a
civilized society rests on truth, justice and peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prerequisite to justice and peace is integrity,'' said
Kass, who is a Police Department chaplain. ``I've discussed these
beliefs with him, and he always struck me as someone who takes
these values seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   By his own account, though, Turetzky's commitment to Talmudic
principle has wavered on the street. In a chilling admission at
trial, he described how, during the melee outside a nightclub
before Louima's arrest, he threatened to kick a pregnant woman in
the stomach if she did not move on.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a foolish statement,'' he told jurors this week, adding
that he felt scared and nervous when he made the comment.
</P>
<P>
   Turetzky was born in Brooklyn and raised in Canarsie by his
mother and grandparents. His parents divorced when he was an
infant, and his father did not play an active role in his
upbringing, family members said.
</P>
<P>
   About 15 years ago, Morty Panzer, an assistant principal at John
Wilson Junior High School in Brooklyn, was looking for a student to
be his office monitor, someone he could rely upon to run errands
and trust around sensitive school records.
</P>
<P>
   He thought immediately of skinny Eric Turetzky. ``One of the
nicest kids I ever met,'' said Panzer, 66, who is the father of
Ellen Panzer.
</P>
<P>
   He had a curious, agile mind. As a 12-year-old, Eric Turetzky
offered his services to the Canarsie Volunteer Ambulance Service.
Why? Because he was impressed by the way emergency technicians
treated him when he crashed his bike. Starting with minor clerical
tasks, he later was fully trained as an emergency medical
technician and for a time he considered a career in medicine. At
age 14, he volunteered at a hospital in Brooklyn. In the 10th
grade, he apprenticed with a local dentist.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, he graduated from Canarsie High School, where his
mother, Lois C. Turetzky, is a secretary. That fall, he entered the
State University of New York at Stony Brook, where he concentrated
on social science.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving Stony Brook in 1992, Turetzky found work as a
campus police officer at SUNY Farmingdale. A few years later, he
joined the New York City Police Department. His first assignment
was the 70th Precinct. Records show that he has made four arrests.
</P>
<P>
   Turetzky has testified that the decision to come forward was
agonizing. It took two days after he learned of Louima's
allegations for his sense of duty to override his sense of loyalty,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   During those two days, defense lawyers pointed out, his
sergeants were being questioned, and other superiors were being
transferred, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani was visiting Louima in the
hospital and Commissioner Howard Safir was calling on officers to
cooperate.
</P>
<P>
   ``All this is happening before your sense of duty makes you come
forward, right?'' Worth asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Objection, argumentative,'' a prosecutor called out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overruled,'' said the judge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, sir,'' said Turetzky.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
