<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-PREAKNESS-CHARISMATIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HANDICAPPERS SHOW DERBY WINNER NO RESPECT, SEND HIM TO THE
PREAKNESS AT 5-1 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A graphic is being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JOSEPH DURSO  
(DW) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ On the day before the Preakness, a wide-open race
with no sure favorite and a dozen contenders, only one thing seemed
certain Friday: Charismatic, the long shot who won the Kentucky
Derby two weeks ago at odds of 31-1, was still something of a long
shot to make it two straight in the Triple Crown series.
</P>
<P>
   As his trainer, D. Wayne Lukas, said in a ringing
understatement, ``There will be doubters.''
</P>
<P>
   Doubters? There are skeptics, critics and outright nonbelievers.
They start with the Pimlico linemaker, Clem Florio, who made
Charismatic third choice at 5-1 behind two horses he outran in the
Derby. If the filly Silverbulletday had not been scratched to run
in the Black-Eyed Susan Stakes, Charismatic would have been the
fourth choice.
</P>
<P>
   Is that any way to treat the winner of the Kentucky Derby?
</P>
<P>
   It happens on rare occasions. In 1971, it happened when Canonero
II won the Derby but then was listed at 6-1 for the Preakness two
weeks later. He won. He is among the 27 Derby winners who came back
to win the Preakness, including Silver Charm and Real Quiet in the
last two years. But the handicappers and linemakers say it will not
happen this year with Charismatic, who ran as a claimer only three
months ago but was not claimed by anyone willing to risk $62,500 on
his future.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a much better horse than people think,'' Lukas said
without great conviction. ``He's a horse who could move forward off
the Derby.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, sounding like a man searching for answers to his own
questions, Lukas said:
</P>
<P>
   ``This horse completely fooled me. I just didn't have any grasp
of where I was with him. I kept changing and doing different
things. I felt there was something I was missing all the time. I
would watch him train in the morning, and say, `This is a better
horse than I'm getting in the afternoon.' I felt I just wasn't
pushing the right buttons.''
</P>
<P>
   Lukas was chagrined at Charismatic's poor start to his racing
career. He had put up $200,000 to buy Charismatic, a chestnut son
of Summer Squall and the mare Bali Babe, when the colt was a
weanling. The money was paid by Beverly and Bob Lewis of Los
Angeles, who earlier owned Timber Country, winner of the 1995
Preakness; Serena's Song, who led the Kentucky Derby for one mile
the same year before tiring, but came back to win the Black-Eyed
Susan, and Silver Charm, who won the Derby and Preakness in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   But then, Charismatic lost eight of his first nine starts and
twice was entered in claiming races for $62,500. Nobody claimed
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least,'' Bob Lewis said with a smile, ``we would have got
back one-third of our investment.''
</P>
<P>
   But Charismatic turned a corner last month when he started
racing every two weeks, with startling results.
</P>
<P>
   On April 3, he ran fourth in the Santa Anita Derby. On April 18,
he won the Lexington Stakes at Keeneland. On May 1, he won the
Kentucky Derby at Churchill Downs. On May 15, whatever the smart
money says, he will shoot for the Preakness at Pimlico.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a two-week horse,'' Lukas quipped. ``You know, he doesn't
have the look of a chiseled athlete. He's got smoother muscles,
something like Paul Hornung and Merlin Olsen had in football. But
don't overlook him. It would be dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts think it would be dangerous to overlook the second
colt Lukas is running in the Preakness _ Cat Thief, who ran third
in the Derby behind Charismatic and Menifee. Both colts warmed up
for their next performance by galloping this morning and drew raves
from Lukas.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've both responded well in training since the Derby,'' he
said. ``They're doing great. Charismatic always has to have a
little more work than Cat Thief. I have him gallop a little more
and usually work a little longer. He's strong, and he needs to do
more.''
</P>
<P>
   Like win the Preakness. One thing about Charismatic, he is a
work horse, maybe an iron horse. He has run more races than any
other horse in the Preakness, 15, winning four, running in the
money nine times and earning $1.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   But on the eve of battle, Charismatic was being offered to the
betting public as third choice behind Menifee, who just missed
winning the Derby by a neck and was quoted at 5-2 in the early
line, and Excellent Meeting, the filly who finished fifth, who was
9-2. After that, you might find Wayne Lukas and the claimer who won
the Kentucky Derby. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
