<SLUG> BC-GLF-NELSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WOODS-GARCIA CONFRONTATION COULD BE UPSTAGED BY PATE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Spain)   By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Tiger Woods held a share of the lead,
19-year-old Sergio Garcia held a share of third place, and the
weekend at the GTE Byron Nelson Classic held intriguing
possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   After a windy day that was far more challenging than Thursday's
opening-round birdie barrage, Woods and Steve Pate shared the lead
at 12 under par (128), one stroke ahead of Garcia and Jeff
Gallagher. Woods and Pate equaled the 36-hole tournament scoring
record, set by Woods when he won here in 1997, and matched by Lee
Rinker that same year.
</P>
<P>
   While many golfers remained in contention, a Woods-Garcia
weekend confrontation is what most fans want to see, and the two
talented young players are keeping a close eye on each other.
Garcia and Woods crossed paths just once Friday as Woods was
standing on the 10th tee and Garcia was on the adjacent 16th tee.
Woods nodded at Garcia and Garcia returned a smile. They practiced
together on Tuesday, but this weekend the stakes will be much
higher. A first-place check of $540,000 and a chance for bragging
rights are on the line in what could be a budding rivalry.
</P>
<P>
   For Friday, both players were glad to be in contention and they
were looking forward to the final 36 holes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sergio's playing great, and I want him to keep it going,''
said Woods, who shot a three-under-par 67 at the TPC of Las Colinas
Friday after tying the Cottonwood Valley Course record Thursday
with a 61. ``I have to keep hitting the ball well and give myself
chances. I'm putting well. I just need to give myself chances.''
</P>
<P>
   For Garcia, who also shot a 67 at Las Colinas, Friday was
another example of his ability to adapt to changing conditions
despite his youth. With wind gusts of 20 miles an hour making club
selection and ball-flight control more difficult, Garcia made just
two bogeys and avoided any major blunders.
</P>
<P>
   Already a celebrity in his native Spain, Garcia will undoubtedly
be a crowd favorite this weekend, trying to win in his first
appearance as a pro on the PGA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I win this week, I'd like to dedicate this victory to Gene
Sarazen's family,'' said Garcia, referring to the golf legend who
died Thursday. ``I met him in Naples like two years ago and he was
really, really nice with me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's condition was really tough, a lot of wind, changing
all the time, going different directions. So I think it was a
pretty good round. Maybe I have a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Those with early tee times had an advantage, finishing most of
their holes before the wind reached its peak. Gallagher, teeing off
in the day's first group at Las Colinas, shot himself into
contention with a 62, the day's best round, as he turned heads by
shooting seven under par through his first seven holes, including
five birdies and an eagle. Gallagher eventually cooled off, making
a bogey at No. 8, then not making another birdie until No. 17. But
on the front nine, some thought Gallagher might be on his way to a
59.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I made my putt on No. 7, Dan Forsman was like,
`Fifty-nine, fifty-nine,''' said Gallagher, referring to one of his
playing partners. ``I just tried to stay focused. I mean, it takes
a lot of pressure off when you're seven under after No. 7. It was
my best round ever. I've never gotten off to a start like that
before.''
</P>
<P>
   Pate, who shot a 65 at Las Colinas, continued his strong 1999
play, and at age 37 he has already enjoyed a career-best year in
winnings ($1,010,215). A serious car accident in 1996 forced Pate
off the tour for a year and threatened his career, but since
returning he has been a more patient and more appreciative player.
</P>
<P>
   ``After sitting at home for a year, I started watching my
friends go to the same place every day for work and realized that
this isn't too bad,'' Pate said. ``I got a reality check.'' Asked
what else motivated him to return, Pate joked, ``Ten months at home
_ my wife realized she didn't want me around that much.''
</P>
<P>
   All the attention focused on Woods and Garcia may help Pate,
Gallagher and the five players tied for fifth place at eight under
par _ Lee Janzen, Andrew Magee, Loren Roberts, Michael Bradley and
Steve Lowery. But Pate had to laugh when asked if he felt old.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could be Sergio's father,'' said Pate, who will be paired
with Woods in Saturday's final group. ``But I don't care. I turn 38
in two weeks, and I don't really feel any different than I did 15
years ago. I'm 25 pounds heavier and a little more tired at the end
of the day.''
</P>
<P>
   But Woods and Garcia were probably ready to play another 18
holes, and they were definitely looking forward to the weekend.
Asked if he missed being at home with friends in Spain, Garcia
said: ``Probably, but the guys in Spain are missing this. So I
wouldn't change things.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
