<SLUG> BC-THQ-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIDEO GAME MAKER TO BUY SOFTWARE DEVELOPER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY BEN SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALABASAS, Calif. _ Video &UR;  &LR; game maker THQ Inc. said Friday it
will pay about $13 million to acquire Pacific Coast Power &AMP; Light
Co., a small Northern California game developer.
</P>
<P>
   The news came one day after THQ successfully launched three new
titles at Electronic Entertainment Expo, or E3, the video &UR;  &LR; game
industry's largest annual gathering &UR; , &LR;  which was held this week in
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The privately held Pacific Coast, formerly known as Don Traeger
Productions Inc., is located in San Jose. Company founder Don
Traeger will continue to manage the firm as its president, THQ
said, and Dennis Harper will remain its vice president of product
development.
</P>
<P>
   THQ is increasingly focusing on developing in-house content.
Friday's proposed deal would give it a considerable increase in
development management strength. Traeger spent 10 years at THQ
archrival Electronic Arts, while Harper was with Atari Games for 17
years developing arcade games.
</P>
<P>
   In related news, THQ said it has signed a deal with MTV to
develop and publish MTV Sports video games. The four-year contract
gives THQ rights to the MTV property for all current and future
game platforms from Sony, Nintendo and Sega, and for the personal
computer. The first games are due out this winter.
</P>
<P>
   THQ also said it signed an agreement with the Professional Rodeo
Cowboy Association to publish and distribute pro rodeo games for
the PlayStation and PC worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   None of Friday's news was enough to lift THQ shares in the face
of a wide sell-off of stocks that sent most indexes down sharply.
THQ shares fell 6.12 percent, or $1.6875, to $25.875.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
