<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7984 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      05-14 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PETER MAURIN, THE CATHOLIC LEADER WHO WAS CRAZY IN HIS OWN CRAZY
WAY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By PETER STEINFELS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is 50 years ago Saturday since the death of Peter Maurin, one
of the unlikeliest figures ever to ignite a religious movement. He
died poor, as he had lived, and was buried in a donated suit and
laid in a donated Brooklyn, N.Y., grave. But there were obituaries
in Time magazine, on the front page of the Vatican's L'Osservatore
Romano and in the Chicago paper of the remnant Wobblies _ the
Industrial Workers of the World, the radical labor movement of the
early 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   What Maurin helped ignite was the Catholic Worker movement, that
mix of pacifism, anarchism and identification with the poor that
has had an immeasurable impact not only on American Catholicism but
also on social and religious radicalism of all sorts.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1932, Maurin had suddenly appeared in the crowded
New York apartment of Dorothy Day. George Shuster, one of the lay
Catholic editors at Commonweal magazine, had sent him, he
explained. ``Also, a red-headed Irish Communist in Union Square
told me to see you,'' he added. ``He says we think alike.''
</P>
<P>
   Day was then 35, once a crusading journalist for Socialist
newspapers but for the last four years a convert to Roman
Catholicism and not sure exactly how to direct her undiminished
passion for social justice. Maurin was 57, half-scholar, half-hobo,
stocky and wearing a suit that, to Day, ``looked as though he had
slept in it.'' As she found out later, he had.
</P>
<P>
   Maurin had a vision of a better society, ``where it is easier
for people to be good.'' He had a proposal for Day: start a
newspaper. Five months later The Catholic Worker, a monthly selling
for a penny a copy (still its price in 1999), was born. Day was the
paper's founder, and became the leading spirit of the movement
until her death in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   That Maurin proved the essential catalyst in Day's life has
puzzled many, but she insisted that this was so, to the point that
some people have shrugged off her account as a womanly attempt at
self-effacement. Certainly they were different. She was a radical
American-style: combative, practical, urban, ready to feel and stir
outrage. He was a Frenchman of peasant stock, rooted in the land,
once a teaching brother in a Catholic religious order, later an
emigrant and failed homesteader in Canada, then a wandering laborer
and ultimately a kind of lay philosopher-monk who carried a
portable monastery in his mind.
</P>
<P>
   His vision was the Green Revolution, a program that foreshadowed
the back-to-the-land movement of the 1960s: a society of farming
communes _ ``agronomic universities,'' where labor, study and
discussion would mix _ plus small factories owned and operated by
artisans.
</P>
<P>
   Manual labor, simple living, hospitality to those in need: with
these guiding principles, he believed, a new society could be
quietly built in the shell of the old. People simply had to clarify
their ideas, render the good ideas plain enough, repeat them often
enough and then just do it rather than wait for government reform
or wholesale revolution.
</P>
<P>
   He translated these principles into his Easy Essays, punchy
little lessons written in short, sometimes repetitive rhythmic
lines, sometimes bouncing phrases around like billiard balls,
setting up a thesis or a problem like a riddle and bringing it to a
close with a thump.
</P>
<P>
   Maurin inspired The Catholic Worker's devotion to round-table
discussions. Unfortunately his own idea of a discussion was most
people's idea of a monologue. He declaimed his Easy Essays, or he
just talked, with no interruptions allowed.
</P>
<P>
   ``From long practice on the debating fields of Union Square and
Columbus Circle, Peter had learned never to breathe between
sentences,'' John Cort recalls in the current issue of The Catholic
Worker. Cort was a recent Harvard graduate when, in 1936, he first
met Day and Maurin, an encounter that led to his lifetime of
activity in the Catholic Worker movement, the labor movement,
interracial efforts in Boston and the Peace Corps overseas.
</P>
<P>
   Dorothy Day herself, although always protective of Maurin's
image, once recalled that what had first struck her about him ``was
that he was one of those people who talked you deaf, dumb and
blind, who each time he saw you began his conversation just where
he had left off at the previous meeting, and never stopped unless
you begged for rest, and that was not for long.''
</P>
<P>
   Cort offers another story about Maurin's unswerving zest for
discussion, this tale once frequently told by John Cogley, a
onetime Catholic Worker who later reported on religion for The New
York Times:
</P>
<P>
   ``One night,'' Cogley would relate, ``when Peter was staying in
a cheap hotel, a young woman knocked on his door and asked, `Want
to have a good time, honey?'
</P>
<P>
   `` `Come in, come in,' he cried, and when she did he inquired of
her: `Now, what would you say a good time means exactly? Let's
discuss it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Cort nor Cogley exudes the reverence often accorded
Maurin in Catholic Worker circles. But Cort still remembers how
struck he was when, in 1935, he first read bits of Maurin's Easy
Essays. One of those bits defined a leader:
</P>
<P>
   A Leader is a fellow &QL;
</P>
<P>
   who refuses to be crazy &QL;
</P>
<P>
   the way everybody else is crazy &QL;
</P>
<P>
   and tries to be crazy &QL;
</P>
<P>
   in his own crazy way. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``At The Catholic Worker,'' Cort concludes, ``Peter helped
several generations of the young and the not-so-young to be crazy
in their own crazy way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
