Suzuki VL1500 Intruder offers a 45-degree V-twin engine,
liquid-cooled and tuned for peak torque at very low engine speeds.
The engine uses dual-downdraft 36-millimeter carburetors and
hydraulic valve adjusters for minimal maintenance. (New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) UNDATED -- May 14, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 16 --
ABOUT-MOTORCYCLES-7, 5-14 -- With a base price of $10,499, the
Yamaha Road Star is the most Harley-like of all the Japanese
cruisers, and its mechanical formula is simplicity itself. It uses
a 1,602cc 48-degree overhead-valve V-twin engine, the largest in
the industry. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) UNDATED -- May 14, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 16 --
ABOUT-MOTORCYCLES-6, 5-14 -- With a base price of $12,995, the
Polaris Victory V92C is the first motorcycle from Polaris, a
company famous for its snowmobiles and personal watercraft. Built
along very traditional but very clean lines, the deep-fendered
Victory uses a 1,507cc V-twin engine with the cylinders splayed at
a 50-degree angle. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) UNDATED -- May 14, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 16 --
ABOUT-MOTORCYCLES-5, 5-14 -- With a base price of $11,499, the
Kawasaki Drifter 1500 is a cruiser designed to look like the
venerable Indian Chief last produced in 1953. The Drifter's 1500cc
V-twin engine has four valves and two spark plugs per cylinder and
uses digital electronic fuel injection. There is a counterbalancing
shaft and rubber engine mounts for smoothness. (New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) UNDATED -- May 14, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 16 --
ABOUT-MOTORCYCLES-4, 5-14 -- With a base price of $12,799, the
Honda Valkyrie uses the ``flat,'' or horizontally opposed, 1,520cc
six-cylinder engine from the huge Gold Wing touring bike, only with
more power and torque. The Valkyrie is the quickest and fastest
cruiser you can buy. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) UNDATED -- May 14, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 16 --
ABOUT-MOTORCYCLES-3, 5-14 -- With a base price of $15,065, the
Harley-Davidson Road King features the all-new Twin Cam 88, a
45-degree V-twin engine of 88 cubic inches that produces 82
foot-pounds of torque. The engine is mounted indirectly to minimize
vibration and is linked to a five-speed transmission and a quiet,
reinforced rubber-belt drive system. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) STENKOVEC, Macedonia -- May 14, 1999 --
KOSOVO-MRSCLINTON, 5-14 -- A line of laundry is held out of the way
as first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton walked with young ethnic
Albanians at a refugee camp during her visit on Friday. Mrs.
Clinton talked with refugees Friday and announced a $21 million
U.S. aid package, a measure designed to support both ethnic
Albanians forced from Kosovo and the Macedonian people who have
given them refuge. (Tyler Hicks/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) UNDATED -- May 14, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 16 --
ABOUT-MOTORCYCLES-2, 5-14 -- With a base price of $17,995, the
Excelsior-Henderson Super X comes with a 1,386cc 50-degree V-twin
engine with overhead cams, four valves per cylinder and electronic
fuel injection. There is an exposed coil spring leading-link front
suspension; the forks go right through the fenders, just like those
on the 1931 Excelsior. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) UNDATED -- May 14, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 16 --
ABOUT-MOTORCYCLES-1, 5-14 -- With a base price of $14,500, the
R1200C uses BMW's traditional horizontally opposed
1,170-cubic-centimeter fuel-injected engine - the company's
largest, most powerful ever. The smallest engine in the senior
cruiser group, it produces more than 70 foot-pounds of torque with
a five-speed transmission and BMW's time-tested shaft-drive system.
(New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) WASHINGTON -- May 14, 1999 -- CONGRESS-GUNS, 5-14 --
Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., gives a thumb up to his Democratic
colleague from California, Sen. Diane Feinstein, as Sen. Frank
Lautenberg, D-N.J., looks on during a news conference being given
by Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., left, on Friday. The Senators were
commenting on the passage in the Senate of a measure to promote
background checks at gun shows. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- May 14, 1999 -- USWEST-GLOBAL, 5-14 -- Sol
Trujillo, chief executive officer of US West, outside his New York
hotel on Friday. US West, the regional telephone company, and
Global Crossing, an upstart company that operates a worldwide fiber
optic network, are in talks over a $30 billion merger. (Angel
Franco/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) WESTPORT, Conn. -- May 14, 1999 -- ASSASSINS-GAME, 5-14
-- Mark Johnson, a senior at Staples High School, holds his newly
purchased dart gun over fellow students, from foreground, Sandra
Engstrom, Alison Cooke and Bryan McCarthy. Begining next week, in
what has become a rite of spring in high schools across the
country, the students will join their schoolmates in a game called
A.P. Assassin where they will hunt each other down and assassinate
their opponent by firing darts. Following the shooting at Columbine
High School, many students are uncomfortable with playing the game.
(James Estrin/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK -- May 14, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 16 --
SHOP-LEELEE-SOBIESKI, 5-14 -- Leelee Sobieski trying on an outfit
at Ricky's. Ms. Sobieski, a Manhattan-born actress, has the
starring role in a two-part mini-series, ``Joan of Arc,'' on CBS.
``First time the virgin is really played by a virgin,'' says Ms.
Sobieski, 16. (Frances Roberts/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- May 14, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 16 --
MASON-AUTHOR-NITEOUT, 5-14 -- Richard Mason at his book party, with
Clementine Hambro. ``I keep expecting that at some point I'm going
to wake up and be a 12-year-old back at boarding school,'' says
Mason, 21, whose debut novel, ``The Drowning People,'' written when
he was 18, has just been published with all the promotional muscle
of Warner Books, which acquired the novel in a two-book deal for
more than $800,000. (Frances Roberts/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- May 14, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 16 --
MELLEN-FASHION, 5-14 -- When Polly Mellen, far left, gives a tour
of the Costume Institute's show at the Metropolitan Museum of Art,
histrionics are the norm. ``We're starting to see much less
makeup,'' declares Ms. Mellen, a fixture in fashion journalism for
some 40 years. ``Blue eye shadow - finished!'' (Barbara Alper/New
York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) PRINCETON, N.J. -- May 14, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 16
-- PRINCETON-IVY-CLUB-2, 5-14 -- The candelabra is always lit for
dinner at Princeton University's Ivy Club, the most patrician place
to eat. At Princeton, where more than 80 percent of juniors and
seniors eat meals in one of 11 privately owned clubs on Prospect
Avenue, known as ``the Street,'' the eating clubs dominate social
life. (Rebecca Cooney/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) PRINCETON, N.J. -- May 14, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 16
-- PRINCETON-IVY-CLUB-1, 5-14 -- Student members during a party in
Princeton University's Ivy Club. At Princeton, where more than 80
percent of juniors and seniors eat meals in one of 11 privately
owned clubs on Prospect Avenue, known as ``the Street,'' the eating
clubs dominate social life. (Rebecca Cooney/New York Times Photo)
LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- May 14, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 16 --
FLAMENCO-LESSONS, 5-14 -- Learning flamenco on Lafayette Street
with Jorge Navarro, who says ``When I'm dancing, I compare it with
sex.'' The age-old Spanish dance of men in tight pants and women
wielding castanets has captured the imagination of the Gap
generation, but mastering the steps is just the beginning. (Rebecca
Cooney/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) WASHINGTON -- May 14, 1999 -- GORE-COELHO, 5-14 -- Tony
Coelho during an interview on Friday. Coelho, who 10 years ago was
House whip, is returning to the center stage of Democratic politics
as the full-time, unpaid chairman of Vice President Al Gore's
campaign for the presidency. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) LINTHICUM, Md. -- May 14, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 16
-- INVEST-AIRLINE-UNION, 5-14 -- Stephen Sleigh, a strategist for
the International Association of Machinists and Aerospace Workers,
had the idea for I.A.M. Shares, a mutual fund that invests mostly
in companies that employ the union's members. ``When I did it, it
was easy for people to say, 'Steve is cooking the numbers,' ``
Sleigh says. ``But when State Street did it, it really opened
people's eyes.'' (Marty Katz/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- May 14, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 16 --
BIZ-FIRST-JOB, 5-14 -- Blossom Martin working with students at
Harlem's Booker T. Washington Learning Center. ``Many people still
think that addiction can be overcome in a few weeks or months,''
says Ms. Martin, 43, who 8 years ago was drug-addicted and on
welfare before reclaiming her life. ``It takes years. It's a
struggle every day.'' (Carrie Boretz/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- May 14, 1999 -- ELLISON-JUNETEENTH, 5-14 --
Ralph Ellison, author of ``The Invisible Man'' outside his
Manhattan home in 1986. Random House plans to publish
``Juneteenth'' next month; a novel posthumously constructed out of
40 years' accumulation of notes and excerpts from Ellison's work.
(Keith Meyers/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) EVANSTON, Ill. -- May 14, 1999 -- WILLS-PROFILE, 5-14 --
Journalist Garry Wills is the author of ``St. Augustine'' which
tries to revise the popular view of the saint. In his book, Wills
says that Augustine was not sex-obsessed at all but concerned with
how sexual dysfunction reflects man's fall from grace. Wills also
writes that Augustine's ``Confessions'' was not a straight
autobiography but ``mainly a theological meditation on his own
life.'' (Steve Kagan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) CHICAGO -- May 14, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 16 --
BIZ-PROFILE-HOENIG, 5-14 -- Jonathan Hoenig's common-sense advice
and fraternity-style wit have helped him move up in the ranks of
financial celebrities. ``This is not a hard sell,'' Hoenig, 23,
says of his Capitalist Pig media operation, which now consists of a
monthly newsletter, Capitalist Pig Report; T-shirts; a Web site;
syndicated columns; television and radio programming and even his
mom's pig-shaped cookies. (Steve Kagan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) BOSTON -- May 14, 1999 -- MUSIC-COURTNEY, 5-14 --
Courtney Love performs with her band Hole at the Boston Orpheum
Club. It was after the suicide of her husband, Kurt Cobain, in the
spring of 1993 that Love's star shot into the stratosphere just as
Hole's second CD, ``Live Through This,'' came out. The album
spawned a slew of hits, including ``Miss World'' and ``Doll
Parts.'' (Thomas James Hurst/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) HANOVER, Mass. -- May 14, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 16
-- POSTHUMOUS-MEDAL, 5-14 -- Michael Keenan holds a picture of his
brother, Joseph Francis Keenan, a Navy hospital corpsman third
class killed during the Korean War. Through Keenan's efforts, his
brother will be honored with a posthumous Navy Cross during a
ceremony at the Marine Corps barracks in Washington. (Jonathan
Wiggs/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) BOSTON -- May 14, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 16 --
BBC-MONTALBANO, 5-14 -- Greg Montalbono, the lefthanded ace of
Northeastern University, loosens up before a game. Montalbono has
major league potential, but a medical history that includes cancer,
two courses of chemotherapy, and over five surgical procedures
since 1996. ``The cancer is always going to be an issue, but I'd
like to think the way things are going kind of puts it to rest,''
said Montalbano. ``I'd like to think that with the way I'm pitching
people are going to stop saying, 'Oh this is the sick kid.' (John
Tlumacki/Boston Globe Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) JERUSALEM -- May 14, 1999 -- ISRAEL-POLITICS, 5-14 --
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu greets the crowd at the
Merkaza Harav Party, supportive of Jewish settlers in the West Bank
and Gaza, during a rally on Friday. As Mr. Netanyahu fights for his
political survival, the ultra-Orthodox Jewish community remains
nearly unanimously by his side, with rabbis and religious parties
issuing last-minute endorsements of his ailing candidacy. (Rina
Castelnuovo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- May 14, 1999 -- BKN-HEAT, 5-13 -- Pat Riley,
coach of Miami Heat, heads to a news conference on Thursday. Riley,
the coach with the highest winning percentage in the National
Basketball Association, face the New York Knicks, the team he once
coached, in game 4 of the NBA playoffs. (Ozier Muhammad/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
