propell the Knicks into the second round of the playoffs. (Barton
Silverman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT40) GLENDALE, Ariz. -- May 14, 1999 -- SWEETONIONS-FOOD-AZR,
5-13 --Ken Gablin, relishing a sweet onion in a Glendale field, is
coordinator of Arizona's Sweet Onion Festival. ``I don't think most
people know what a sweet onion is,'' says Gablin, who hopes to see
Grand Canyon Sweet Onions become as well known and as popular as
Vidalias. (Michael Ging/Arizona Republic Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT39) PHOENIX -- May 14, 1999 -- FOODART-AZR, 5-13 -- Virginia
Sardi's exhibition at the Barlow &AMP; Straker Gallery in Phoenix
simulates a marketplace. Many of the artist's works are
food-related. (Suzanne Starr/Arizona Republic Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT38) MILWAUKEE -- May 13, 1999 -- WELFARE-MILWAUKEE, 5-13 --
Julie Kirksick, director for project New Hope after a visit with
project participant and board member Corrine Brown. The Milwaukee
experiment, started a decade ago by a band of reformers who wanted
to provide the poor with guaranteed jobs and other benefits, closes
its doors this week. But the experiment, called Project New Hope,
leaves behind the most comprehensive study of poor families in the
post-welfare age. (Nicole Begiveno/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT37) NATICK, Mass. -- May 14, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 16
-- INTERNET-INVESTORS-2, 5-14 -- Spyridon Ganas, 18, became
interested in the markets by watching the ``Nightly Business
Report'' on PBS as he worked in the kitchen at his familyUs
pizzeria. ``I am a member of the new generation of investor Q young
and willing to take huge risks,'' says Ganas, who put $1,000 into
an ETrade account when he turned 18. (Ed Quinn/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT36) BLAIRSVILLE, Ga. -- May 14, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY
16 -- INTERNET-INVESTORS-1, 5-14 -- Bev Waldrip, 57, and her
husband live in Blairsville, where they share eight acres with
horses. After they retired, he started buying and selling the
horses while she took an equal amount of money to invest in stocks.
``I like placing the order and checking late at night to see if one
went through,'' she says. ``I can go outside and work in the yard
and make money with my stock act at the same time.'' (Alan S.
Weiner/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT35) SANTA BARBARA, Calif. -- May 14, 1999 --
OCEAN-WHEELCHAIR, 5-14 -- Rodrianne Croisdale enjoys a ride on the
surf on East Beach in an all-terrain wheelchair being pushed by May
Forbes. The city of Santa Barbara bought two of the chairs to loan
to local residents who are disabled in order for them to enjoy the
surf. (Steve Moloney/Santa Barbara News Press)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT34) CLARK COUNTY, Nev. -- May 14, 1999 -- NEV-GUN-LOVER,
5-14 -- Participants in the Front Site Training Institute practice
firing their machine guns at targets during a promotional class. By
the fall, this baked land 50 minutes west of Las Vegas will hold 12
shooting ranges, an armory, video simulators, tunnels, defensive
driving courses, a SWAT tower and a landing strip. If construction
moves right along, by next year, the area will be an incorporated
village that will be named Front Sight, for the part of a gun you
focus on to hit a target. (Monica Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) HONOLULU -- May 14, 1999 -- HAWAII-TRUST-2, 5-14 --
Richard Wong, a trustee of the Bishop Estate during a court
appearance. A state probate court judge ordered the ouster of the
estate's trustees on the heels of an investigation into their
alleged mismanagement and self-dealing. (David Scull/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) HONOLULU -- May 14, 1999 -- HAWAII-TRUST, 5-14 --
Supporters of Judge Margery Bronster's efforts to remove the five
trustees of the Bishop Estate bow their heads during a prayer near
a portrait of Princess Bernice Pauahi Bishop, the last direct
descendant of King Kamehemeha I, the 18th-century king who had
unified the Hawaiian islands. The state probate court judge ordered
the removal on the heels of an investigation into mismanagement and
self-dealing by the trustees. (David Scull/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) MARIETTA, Ga. -- May 14, 1999 -- WORKSHOP-PONDS-2-COX,
5-13 -- Creating a pond for your yard is as simple as buying a
fiberglass shell and filling it with water. Of course, it also
requires a little digging and a vision of what you want the
completed pond to look like. The borders of the pond are lined with
plants and rocks for a finished look. (Jean Shifrin/Atlanta
Journal-Constitution Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) MARIETTA, Ga. -- May 14, 1999 -- WORKSHOP-PONDS-1-COX,
