<SLUG> BC-HEALTHEON-WEBMD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTHEON EXPECTED TO MERGE WITH WEBMD IN STOCK SWAP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ga.)  (lb) 
 By LAURA M. HOLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Healtheon Corp., the medical record-keeping Web site based in
Santa Clara, Calif., that was started by the founder of Netscape
Communications Corp., Jim Clark, is expected to announce Monday
that it is merging with WebMD, a privately held Internet provider
of medical information.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is expected to be valued at more than $3.5 billion,
with WebMD shareholders receiving Healtheon shares. The boards of
both companies are expected to meet this weekend to approve the
transaction.
</P>
<P>
   Clark, chairman of Healtheon, would be the chairman of the new
company, which is expected to have headquarters in Atlanta, where
WebMD is based. The chairman of WebMD, Jeffrey Arnold, would be
chief executive of the new company, and Healtheon's chief
executive, Michael Long, would be chief operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   As with any negotiations, the talks could falter at the last
minute. A spokesman for WebMD declined to comment on a possible
deal. Healtheon executives did not return telephone calls seeking
comment. Shares of Healtheon spiked on Friday, up $10 on reports of
a possible deal, to close at $57 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Healtheon was started in 1995 by Clark and David Schell, a
Harvard-educated doctor who was also a partner at the venture
capital firm of Kleiner Perkins. The merger would give Healtheon
access to more consumers. It currently focuses mainly on doctors,
hospitals, insurers and other institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Healtheon has been an active acquirer, having bought ActaMed, an
electronic-data concern, in 1998, and Metis, a Web-site developer
of Internet-based health-care information services, also in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Healtheon called off a planned initial public offering last
July, citing the temperamental market for Internet stocks then. The
company went public earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   WebMD was set to go public itself, but last week filed a
statement with the Securities and Exchange Commission canceling its
$55 million public offering. The company was founded in October
1998, but was earlier named Endeavor Technologies.
</P>
<P>
   It was founded by Arnold, an Atlanta native, who in 1994 _ when
he was 24 years old _ started Quality Diagnostic Services, which
describes itself as a cardiac-arrhythmia monitoring company, with
his wife, Meg. Arnold holds a bachelor of arts degree in
communications from the University of Georgia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
