<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;  New York Times Votechart
</P>
<P>
   States News Service
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON WATCH VOTE CHART Questions regarding this
transmission should be directed to 202-628-3100, ext. 224.
WASHINGTON, May 14 -- The following chart shows how senators and
representatives voted on key bills and amendments within the last
week. A ``Y'' means the member voted for the measure; an ``N''
means the member voted against the measure; a ``?'' means the
member did not vote; and a ``P'' means the member voted
``present.''
</P>
<P>
   SENATE VOTES:
</P>
<P>
   1) BILL NUMBER: GUNS
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Wednesday failed to pass a measure that would have
made background checks at gun shows mandatory. Voting 51-47, the
Senate tabled, or set aside, the proposal offered by Sen. Frank
Lautenberg, D-N.J., as an amendment to a larger juvenile crime
bill. Supporters said it is easy for criminals to buy firearms at
gun shows because of the lack of background checks. Opponents said
that most of the dealers at gun shows are licensed, and requiring
background checks on private sales would infringe on individual
rights. A ``yes'' vote favors setting aside the measure.
</P>
<P>
   2) BILL NUMBER: VOLUNTARY
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Wednesday approved, 53-45, a measure that called
for voluntary background checks on private sales at gun shows. The
amendment was offered by Sen. Larry Craig, R-Idaho, as an amendment
to a larger juvenile crime bill. Supporters said private dealers
would be encouraged to do the background check in order to be
protected from liability if a customer uses the gun in a crime.
Opponents said the measure did not do enough to prevent criminals
from acquiring guns at gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   3) BILL NUMBER: FCC
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Thursday failed to pass a measure that would have
asked the Federal Communications Commission to limit broadcasts of
violent programs to times when children are not likely to be in the
audience. Voting 60-39, the Senate tabled, or set aside, the
proposal offered by Sen. Ernest Hollings, D-S.C., as part of a
larger juvenile crime bill. Supporters said there is too much
violence on television when children are watching. Opponents said
the measure would be too much regulation of the television and
satellite industry, and infringe on First Amendment rights. A
``yes'' vote favors settting aside the measure.
</P>
<P>
   4) BILL NUMBER: TEENS
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Thursday approved, 96-2, a measure that would
prohibit juveniles from owning semi-automatic assault weapons and
high-capacity ammunition clips. The measure was introduced by Sen.
John Ashcroft, R-Mo., as an amendment to a larger juvenile crime
bill. Supporters said it would correct the disparity between
handguns, which juveniles need parental permission to own, and
assault weapons, which they need no permision to own. No one spoke
in dissent. A ``yes'' vote favors the bill.
</P>
<P>
   5) BILL NUMBER: AMMO
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Thursday passed a measure that would ban
importation of high-capacity anmmunition clips. Voting 59-39, the
Senate failed to table, or set aside, the measure introduced by
Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., as part of a larger juvenile crime
bill. Immediately after, the Senate passed the motion on a voice
vote. Supporters said it would close the loophole that bans the
domestic manufacture of high-capacity ammunition but allows their
importation from other countries. Opponents said it would undo a
provision in the law and do nothing to control crime. A ``yes''
vote favors setting aside the bill.
</P>
<P>
   VOTE : 1 2 3 4 5
</P>
<P>
   --- --- --- --- ---
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE VOTES:
</P>
<P>
   1) BILL NUMBER: Y2K
</P>
<P>
   The House on Wednesday approved, 236-190, a bill that would
protect businesses from class action lawsuits and punitive damages
in the case of Year 2000 computer failures. Supporters said there
needs to be legislated limits on such cases to protect businesses
from major financial loss. Opponents said it would bar consumers
from bringing merited lawsuits and recouping losses suffered as a
result of the Year 2000 computer bug. A ``yes'' vote favors the
bill.
</P>
<P>
   VOTE : 1
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   The attendance record tracks the cumulative attendance of
members to date when they are physically present for roll call
votes.
</P>
