<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-FAMILY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: STILL UNABLE TO PROCLAIM `THIS IS MINE' 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DAVID GONZALEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Celia Angel was growing up in Mexico, she was
orphaned by her fifth birthday and sent to live with relatives who
treated her more like a servant than kin. Maybe that's why she
tried giving her 11 children the tenderness she never received. And
maybe that's why she relished the affection her children and
grandchildren gave her on Mother's Day.
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday, most of her children visited her, but only after
she had spent a few hours selling tamales on the street. She has to
work and people have to eat, including herself. That hasn't changed
much in the nine years since Mrs. Angel, 60, came to the United
States and moved to East Harlem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things are neither bad nor good,'' she said quietly, inside
her apartment on Sunday morning. ``But moving ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   What was different this year was who wasn't by her side. Her
daughter, Alma Gonzaga, is confined to a Bronx psychiatric ward, a
frequent stop for the young woman who has suffered from
schizophrenia and violent outbursts. Absent, too, were Alma's two
children. Alma's infant daughter, Manuela, was placed in foster
care after Alma tried to jump off a bridge in September. Her son,
Pedro Jose, was placed in foster care when he was born in February.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Angel has attended many hearings in Family Court, hoping to
have her grandchildren given to her, or at least to another of her
daughters. But the authorities said they were worried about Mrs.
Angel's ability to protect the children from Alma.
</P>
<P>
   ``What does the judge want for these children?'' Mrs. Angel
asked. ``They do not have a home they can say is theirs. I had that
experience. I was an orphan who could not say, `This is mine.'
Because of the experiences I suffered as an orphan, I do not want
that to happen to my grandchildren.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest twist in the case happened late last month at a
hearing before Judge Harold Lynch of Bronx Family Court. Mrs. Angel
was there, along with Ilze Earner, a social-work administrator in
East Harlem who has been helping the family at the request of
officials from the Mexican Consulate, which often assists Mexicans
in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Earner said that a lawyer for the city's Administration for
Children's Services admitted in court that the agency had
mistakenly thought it had an open case against Mrs. Angel, stemming
from an incident in which she left Alma alone with her infant
daughter while Mrs. Angel attended to a medical emergency in
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not like a bad credit report and she didn't get her
Amex card,'' Ms. Earner said this week. ``Kids are languishing in
foster care. Do we think this is a good thing?''
</P>
<P>
   Leonora Wiener, the spokeswoman for the Administration for
Children's Services, said that a misunderstanding occurred, but
officials with her agency were still worried that Mrs. Angel had
endangered the child by leaving her with Alma. She said that other
family members, including relatives of the children's father, who
is in jail on a parole violation, are being considered as
guardians.
</P>
<P>
   Andrea Naso, the spokeswoman for St. Christopher's, the
foster-care agency responsible for the children, said the agency
wanted to ensure that the children would be in a safe and
comfortable home. ``The court wants a choice to see the children
are cared for,'' she said. ``I don't think we have any concerns as
far as that goes.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Earner fears that investigating the paternal relatives
will only create more paperwork, more delays and more time in
foster care for the children. She knows that she risks the judge's
ire by talking about the case, since he reprimanded her in court
for having spoken to this columnist last month.
</P>
<P>
   Now she wants a lawyer to do the talking for her: She has
enlisted Norman Siegel, executive director of the New York Civil
Liberties Union, who plans to meet with Mrs. Angel on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This needs to be talked about,'' Ms. Earner said. ``This is a
real problem affecting the poorest, most vulnerable families in
this city. Who is allowing them to speak and say it is wrong?''
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday, before she went out to sell food, Mrs. Angel
refused to accept that her own childhood destiny would befall her
grandchildren. She said Alma would remain institutionalized. In
effect, Mrs. Angel would forsake her own child to save two others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their father is in jail, their mother is in a hospital and
nothing has happened to improve this situation,'' she said. ``You
see, I still have two cribs waiting for the children. I am waiting
for the judge's conscience to soften. Now it is in God's hands. And
the judge's.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
