<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-TOBACCO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: STRUGGLE OVER THE TOBACCO SPOILS  
(DW) 

</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Saturday, May 15:
</P>
<P>
   The dispute between Gov. George Pataki and Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani over how to divide New York state's share of the
multi-state settlement with the tobacco industry works to
everyone's disadvantage. The fight, now in the courts, could delay
the state's receipt of $306 million in tobacco money for 1999 and
even hold up the $800 million the state is expected to receive in
2000. There is no reason the two sides cannot find a middle ground.
</P>
<P>
   The fight might also delay tobacco payments to other states
because the settlement requires that 80 percent of the 46 states
involved, accounting for at least 80 percent of the money, receive
final approval of the settlement from their state courts if any
money is to be disbursed this year. Since New York state will
receive almost 13 percent of the nationwide settlement, or about
$25 billion in the first 25 years, its timely approval is
important.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Dennis Vacco, then New York's attorney general,
decided that state government would get 51 percent of the proceeds,
New York City 26 percent and all other counties 23 percent, using a
formula based on population and Medicaid expenditures.
</P>
<P>
   The city makes a solid argument that the formula fails to fully
compensate it for what it must spend to care for Medicaid
recipients with smoking-related diseases. A state judge, however,
approved the formula, and the city has appealed the decision. Erie
and Westchester Counties have also appealed, but their claims are
considered easier to resolve.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki can end the court fight and get the money flowing by
accepting a fair compromise. The Giuliani administration had agreed
to a sensible deal with Vacco that would have given New York City
about $700 million more than the $6.7 billion it now expects to
receive over the next 25 years, an amount that would bring the city
closer to covering its tobacco-related health costs. Pataki
rejected that proposal. Now the current attorney general, Eliot
Spitzer, who came to the issue as a neutral party, is trying to get
the two sides to reach a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki has already shown poor instincts on how to use the
tobacco money. He has proposed spending the bulk of it in the first
five years on state debt reduction, leaving little for new health
initiatives and anti-smoking programs that could help reduce future
spending on tobacco-related disease. At the very least, he should
strike a compromise that would get the funds flowing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-14-99 2200EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
