<SLUG> BC-NY-COMMUTER-TAX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI AND VALLONE SEE A BUDGET TANGLE IF THE COMMUTER TAX ENDS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ABBY GOODNOUGH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After predicting for months that budget negotiations
would be quick and relatively painless this year, city officials
are now warning that the state Legislature's plan to repeal the
commuter tax will seriously hinder the process, forcing Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani and the City Council to prepare for the potential
loss of up to $360 million in annual revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani and City Council Speaker Peter Vallone both said this
week that if the Legislature pushed through the repeal, they might
have to scale back or even abandon their own tax cut proposals _
the largest of their respective tenures _ which they have touted as
ways to share the city's $2.1 billion surplus with its residents.
In recent weeks, the Democratic speaker and the Republican mayor
had cheerfully predicted that their most daunting task would be
agreeing on which taxes to cut.
</P>
<P>
   Now it seems that Albany will decide for them, eliminating a tax
that suburban residents who work in the city have paid since 1966.
While commuter tax revenue is only a tiny fraction of the city's
$35 billion budget, officials in the Giuliani administration say
the proposed repeal is an egregious example of state lawmakers'
tampering with the city's finances.
</P>
<P>
   ``How is New York City going to successfully manage its money if
Albany, on a whim, can repeal a tax that is an important source of
revenue?'' said Robert Harding, Giuliani's budget director. ``We
are being forced to move away from targeted tax cuts and meet
somebody else's idea of how we should govern our city.''
</P>
<P>
   The pending repeal would affect only New York state residents,
who represent 58 percent of those paying the commuter tax. But
lawmakers in neighboring states have already said they would sue to
force New York to cut the tax for all commuters. If the suit
succeeded, the city would lose $360 million annually. Otherwise,
the loss from New York commuters would be $210 million.
</P>
<P>
   Independent budget monitors said Friday that either way, the
city could absorb the revenue loss because the economy was so
strong. But they said the commuter tax was sensible and important.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the biggest hole in the world,'' said Diana Fortuna,
the president of the Citizens Budget Commission. ``But it's just a
shame, because it will probably knock out some tax cuts that would
be much more beneficial.''
</P>
<P>
   Harding and other city officials said that if the Legislature
made good on its promise to repeal the commuter tax next week, the
mayor and the Council would struggle to meet their goal of adopting
a budget by June 5. They would have to readjust revenue estimates
and shuffle spending priorities, which could lead to more haggling
between the two sides, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The budget process has been going on for five months, we're
getting into the final stretch, and now this major hurdle has been
thrown in front of us,'' said Thomas McMahon, the director of the
Council's finance division. ``Having significantly less resources
will require both sides to reassess our priorities.''
</P>
<P>
   But state Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver, a Manhattan Democrat,
questioned why the proposed commuter tax repeal would complicate
budget negotiations, when all Giuliani and Vallone had to do was
relinquish part of their own tax cut proposals. The mayor has
proposed $405 million in tax reductions, while the speaker's tax
cut package is worth more than $700 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mayor and the Council speaker both have proposals to take
away more money than this,'' Silver said in an interview. ``It may
make it harder for them to impose the tax cuts they want, but they
have clearly allocated money for tax cuts in their fiscal plans.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders in the state Senate were the first to propose
ending the commuter tax, hoping that it would help a Republican
Senate candidate from Rockland County win a special election later
this month. But they privately expected that the State Assembly,
which is dominated by New York City Democrats, would block the
plan.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Silver surprised everyone by announcing that the
Assembly would support the repeal. Two influential Assembly
Democrats, Roberto Ramirez, the Bronx party leader, and Clarence
Norman Jr., the Brooklyn party leader, declined to say Friday how
they would vote, but they expressed little opposition to ending the
tax.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Shelly needs the votes, he usually gets the votes,'' Norman
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
