<SLUG> BC-NY-TRANSIT-DEMAND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK CITY TRANSIT UNION'S DEMAND COULD LEAD TO STRIKE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Raising the possibility of a strike on New Year's
Eve, the president of New York City's largest union is calling for
a 30 percent raise over three years in coming contract talks with
the Metropolitan Transportation Authority.
</P>
<P>
   Willie James, president of Local 100 of the Transport Workers
Union, said he was driving a hard bargain because the local's
33,000 bus drivers and subway workers had accepted a small wage
increase in their current contract and because the MTA has a budget
surplus of nearly $400 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since there is a big surplus, since everyone is flush with
money, we want them to give us a substantial wage increase,'' James
said. ``We deserve it. We helped turn this place around.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though state law bars public sector workers from striking,
James warned that when the union's contract expires on Dec. 15,
there could be a walkout that would tie up the city on New Year's
Eve.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to use a strike _ it would be horrible,'' James
said. ``But I'm not ruling out anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Transit workers last walked out in 1980, in an illegal 11-day
strike. The union was fined $650,000, and strikers were fined two
days' pay for each day they were out.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Kelly, a spokesman for the MTA, declined to comment on the
union's demands, saying the agency did not want to do its
bargaining in the news media.
</P>
<P>
   But Diana Fortuna, president of the Citizens Budget Commission,
a corporately financed watchdog group, said the union's call for a
10 percent raise three years in a row was excessive.
</P>
<P>
   Then, echoing earlier statements about municipal labor by Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani, she said, ``We can't afford to grant raises to
these workers without getting productivity increases in return.''
</P>
<P>
   James said his demand for a 30 percent raise was reasonable _
members of his union earn about $39,000 a year on average before
overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's outrageous,'' he said.`` We've already
increased productivity. We are totally responsible for bringing the
system back.''
</P>
<P>
   In sending a strong warning to the MTA before negotiations begin
this fall, James, like many other labor leaders in the city, is
talking tougher than he was just a few years ago, when there was a
budget deficit and large layoffs were threatened.
</P>
<P>
   Some labor experts said James' demand for a 30 percent raise
could embolden other union leaders to make similar demands, while
other experts dismissed James' demand as merely an opening bid.
</P>
<P>
   In the union's current three-year contract, workers received a
single 3.75 percent wage increase, a lump sum averaging $800 and a
supplementary pay increase of $200 to $500 for the 30 percent of
workers with at least 15 years of experience.
</P>
<P>
   James said that he also wanted an improved health plan and a
decrease in employee-paid pension contributions.
</P>
<P>
   He said union members were working harder than before, even
though buses and subways were running less frequently.
</P>
<P>
   ``It creates a lot more stress for our members,'' he said,
``because when people are waiting for buses or subways a longer
time, they don't take out their anger at the MTA, they get angry at
the first body they see, and that's a bus driver, subway motorman
or conductor.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
