<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MALCOLM-X-DIARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALCOLM X'S BULLET-RIDDLED DIARY FOR SALE, AS OWNERSHIP IS
QUESTIONED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Calif.)   (bl)  
 By KEVIN FLYNN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ City officials began investigating Friday how the
bloodied, bullet-riddled diary of Malcolm X, which was in his coat
pocket when he was assassinated 34 years ago, got into the hands of
a private collector who is now auctioning it off in California.
</P>
<P>
   The red, mock-leather diary was People's Exhibit 60 at the trial
of three men convicted in the February 1965 killing of the black
Muslim leader, and officials said they had believed it was still in
storage alongside the paperwork and other evidence from the case.
But an unidentified private collector, who says the diary was sold
by the Police Department about seven years ago during a purge of
old files, has arranged to sell the pocket-size book later this
month.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials said it was not customary to sell the personal
effects of a murder victim. Such items are usually returned to
family members, Inspector Michael Collins, a police spokesman,
said. Officials said they did not know why the diary had not been
returned shortly after the trial to Malcolm's widow, Betty Shabazz.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, in an effort to determine what had happened, they began
going through the remaining files on the case, which are in a
warehouse in Brooklyn as part of the Municipal Archives. The
archives took possession of the case files from the Manhattan
district attorney's office in 1993, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The files contain autopsy reports, shell casings and mangled
bullets, but all that remains as evidence of the diary is an empty
envelope, marked ``1965 Red Diary with Three Bullet Holes,'' said
Kenneth Cobb, director of the archives.
</P>
<P>
   ``At one time it was part of this case file,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer representing the estate of Dr. Shabazz, who died in
1997, said the family would like to block the California auction,
which is scheduled for May 27.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their reaction is that they are shocked that something that
represents so intimate a part of their father's last moments would
find its way to an auction house on the West Coast,'' said the
lawyer, Joseph Fleming.
</P>
<P>
   The 146-page diary contains the phone numbers of many of
Malcolm's friends and associates. One page carries the notation
that Malcolm was scheduled to attend a meeting at Brown University
several days after his death during an appearance at the Audubon
Ballroom in upper Manhattan's Washington Heights, said the auction
house handling the sale, Butterfield &AMP; Butterfield of San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The diary has three bullet holes and some blood stains, said
Vanessa Hardy, a book specialist with the auction house. ``It's an
incredibly shocking item,'' said Ms. Hardy, who estimated it would
sell for as much as $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hardy said a private collector had approached her company
within the past few months with a letter of provenance indicating
that the book had been bought from the Police Department between
1991 and 1993, when, according to the letter, the police were
purging their evidence files. The purchase was made by one
collector, who then sold it to the collector currently represented
by Butterfield &AMP; Butterfield. Ms. Hardy declined to identify either
collector, saying such disclosures are against company policy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
