<DOCNO> NYT19990514.0443 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 22:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8054 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-1STLD     05-14 0557
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALLIES SAY ASSIGNING BLAME SHOULD WAIT FOR INQUIRY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: Story rewritten throughout.)  (lb) 
 By ELIZABETH BECKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After Belgrade charged that a NATO warplane had
fired on refugees in the southwestern Kosovo village of Korisa,
Pentagon officials said Friday that NATO warplanes were attacking
in the general area around Korisa, but that they had no evidence so
far that any of the planes had been near the village.
</P>
<P>
   Both Pentagon and NATO officials said they were reluctant to try
to say who was to blame in Korisa, where at least 60 died, until an
investigation was complete.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's good reason to be cautious about the Serb
reports,'' said Kenneth Bacon, the Pentagon spokesman. ``I would
just urge you to be careful with those reports; don't rush to
judgment. NATO is in the middle of investigating this now, and as
soon as they finish, we will have something to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials said they did not want to repeat the mistakes
made last month after NATO warplanes accidentally hit a refugee
convoy in southeastern Kosovo. At first NATO officials denied
responsibility for the bombing, on April 14. Then, after a series
of gaffes, they had to retract their statements and admit that NATO
jets had hit two convoys.
</P>
<P>
   Italy also questioned NATO on Friday about hundreds of
deactivated bombs that have been found in fishing nets in
international waters in the northern Adriatic Sea.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the NATO air fleet engaged in the campaign in Kosovo are
stationed at Italian bases. The Italian government has been
receiving complaints from fishermen operating out of the port of
Chioggia, south of Venice. Residents of Chioggia have also
complained that bombs are washing up on their beaches. Kosovo lies
across the Adriatic, to the southeast.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials confirmed on Friday that ``in rare cases'' pilots
unloaded bombs into the Adriatic. This happened, they said, when a
technical malfunction of the plane made it unsafe to land with the
ordnance still on board.
</P>
<P>
   ``We make sure by overflying the area first to see there is
nobody there, and then these weapons are jettisoned there,'' said
Maj. Gen. Walter Jertz, a NATO spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Jertz said that the jettisoned bombs would not explode, because
they would have been crippled by the malfunction.
</P>
<P>
   Belgrade's early accusations that NATO had attacked Korisa
included suggestions that NATO had used cluster bombs. The
description later changed to ``laser-guided'' missiles.
</P>
<P>
   NATO and Pentagon officials defended in principle their ability
to use cluster bombs, which can leave undetonated ``bomblets''
littered across a landscape that will act like land mines. The
bombs drew criticism last week after a strike on the market in Nis,
in which Belgrade said 15 people were killed.
</P>
<P>
   The NATO and Pentagon officials said that the weapons are as
accurate as other gravity bombs and remain effective against
targets like troop concentrations, airfields and other large
military targets.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. John Jumper, commander general of U.S. Air Forces in
Europe, emphasized that cluster bombs have the same accuracy as
other bombs that are not precision-guided weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't mean mistakes don't happen,'' the general added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
