<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 22:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8057 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-SILVERBULLETDAY-N     05-14 0249
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-SILVERBULLETDAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SILVERBULLETDAY WINS AGAIN  
(DW) 

</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Silverbulletday, the filly who was scratched from
the Preakness after she drew an outside post position, gave a
commanding performance from the inside post position Friday as she
won the Black-Eyed Susan Stakes for her eighth straight victory.
</P>
<P>
   It was the 11th time in 12 starts that Silverbulletday had won,
solidifying her standing as the best filly in the country. She
easily outran Dreams Galore by two lengths, came within
three-fifths of a second of the Pimlico track record for a mile and
one-eighth and broke the record for the Black-Eyed Susan by
two-fifths of a second.
</P>
<P>
   She was no surprise to the public, which bet her down to 1-9
while her closest rival in the field of seven, The Happy Hopper,
went off at 8-1. Silverbulletday lived up to her reputation. She
moved smartly in front at the start, opened up on the far turn,
drifted out a bit in the homestretch and held off a late rush by
Dreams Galore.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Stevens, who rode Silverbulletday, said, ``I so much wanted
to run this filly in the Preakness.'' He said that he tapped her
when the gate opened, and added: ``She went on; she kept going and
she exploded. It makes the hair stand up on the back of your
neck.''
</P>
<P>
   Silverbulletday ran the mile and 1/8 in 1:47 4/5, breaking the
record set by Imaginary Lady in 1989 and nearly matching the track
mark set by Private Terms in another race in 1989. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-14-99 2230EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
