<SLUG> BC-NY-CABBIE-DISARM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOUNDED CABBY DISARMS MAN AND TURNS HIM OVER TO POLICE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By KIT R. ROANE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A Brooklyn livery cab driver whose head was grazed by
a passenger's bullet Thursday night disarmed the gunman, chased him
down and made a citizen's arrest, police said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The driver, Phedro Desprez, 37, turned the attacker over to two
rookie officers walking their beat nearby. The suspect, identified
by the police as Lewis Oswin, 19, has been charged with robbery,
assault and criminal possession of a weapon, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   Explaining that he had emigrated from Haiti eight months ago and
had to support his wife back home, Desprez said he had little
choice but to fight off the man when the gun was pulled shortly
after 11:30 p.m. Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had $89 in one pocket and 60 in the other, and I was in a
panic when I saw the gun,'' he said, while resting Friday at his
Flatbush home. ``I had to protect myself. My head was bleeding, but
you have strength in that situation.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the account given to the police by Desprez, he was
driving through the Brownsville section around 11:15 p.m. when two
girls flagged him down on the corner of Thomas S. Boyland Street
and Hegeman Avenue. But when Desprez pulled over, the girls called
over three men standing on the other side of the street, who also
got into his car and began giving him directions.
</P>
<P>
   After he dropped the girls off at Lenox Road and Kings Highway,
the three men told him there would be one more stop. But they kept
giving him different directions as he drove a circuitous route
through Brownsville.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked them if they were looking for a club and they said no,
that it was a house,'' said Desprez, scratching at a white gauze
bandage wrapped about his head. ``Then this man put his hand in his
pocket and pulled out a gun. The guy said he was going to kill
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Desprez was grazed by a bullet to the right side of his head as
he fought with the gunman over control of the pistol in the front
seat of the moving car. Desprez said that he was able to wrest it
free only after his cab ran into several parked cars on East 96th
Street.
</P>
<P>
   The two other men jumped out of the cab when it finally rolled
to a stop near Willmohr Street. Although Oswin also tried to flee,
he stopped when Desprez leveled the gun at him.
</P>
<P>
   According to the police, the two officers walking their post
happened upon Desprez, who dropped the pistol and explained what
had happened. The officers quickly arrested Oswin and sent Desprez
to Brookdale Hospital Medical Center, where he was treated and
released.
</P>
</TEXT>
