<SLUG> BC-HATE-CRIMES-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPROMISE ON HATE CRIMES BILL COLLAPSES IN TEXAS SENATE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY WALT 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A compromise on a hate crimes bill pushed at the
11th hour by Gov. George W. Bush collapsed Friday night in the
Texas Senate as Republicans refused to sign off on it.
</P>
<P>
   The failure to resolve a rancorous partisan split primarily over
whether gays and lesbians and other specific groups should be
offered special protections under the bill has effectively killed
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas has had a rather ignoble history as it relates to race
relations and a rather ignoble history as it relates to sexual
orientation,'' said Sen. Rodney Ellis, the Houston Democrat who is
the Senate sponsor of the bill. ``All is not well in the wild, wild
West.
</P>
<P>
   ``I assume this bill is dead for this session, but don't be too
sure. Miracles happen every day ... if it's too hot for you this
session, don't worry I'll be back,'' Ellis vowed.
</P>
<P>
   House Bill 938, carried successfully in the House by Rep.
Senfronia Thompson, D-Houston, had taken on huge symbolic
significance. It was named the James Byrd Jr. Hate Crimes Act in
memory of a black East Texas man who was chained to a pickup and
dragged to his death last summer. A white supremacist has been
sentenced to die for the crime and two other white men are due to
stand trial.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd's family has been lobbying for the measure, along with a
coalition of civil rights groups _ from African-Americans, gays and
lesbians to Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Last week President Clinton challenged the governor to push the
bill through the Texas Legislature. At the same time, socially
conservative groups have been opposed to it.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's dramatic end came after a morning prayer vigil and
impassioned speeches by Democratic lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only reason this bill is not passing is because of
presidential politics and Republican primary politics,'' said Sen.
John Whitmire, a Houston Democrat. ``We have to rise above politics
today. We have to rise above presidential politics today. Bush and
his party are dead wrong on how they are handling this issue.''
</P>
<P>
   By midday, Democrats learned that compromise language that had
been offered the night before had come from the governor's office,
even as Bush has publicly refused to take a position on the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Within the past two days, we offered some ideas in an effort
to break the stalemate on this sensitive issue,'' said Bush
spokeswoman Karen Hughes.
</P>
<P>
   After the efforts cratered, Sen. David Sibley, R-Waco, the chief
Republican negotiator, said, ``It is with the encouragement of the
governor of the state of Texas that we embarked on this effort.
Anybody that says leadership was lacking just doesn't know what
they were talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's role in trying to broker a deal late this week only
became known to most Democrats, including some of the key
negotiators, at midday Friday. Bush has repeatedly said only that
he would ``consider'' any hate crimes bill that comes to his desk
and he has doggedly refused to take a public position on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, no other Senate work was getting done Friday, and an
estimated 200 House bills died in Senate committees as time ran out
for legislation. There is little more than two weeks for bills to
pass both houses, with the session ending at midnight May 31.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Ken Armbrister, D-Victoria, chairman of the Senate
committee that wrangled with the bill for more than a week, said
Bush's compromise had suggested a way that the Senate could
eliminate the hot-button protections for gays and lesbians.
</P>
<P>
   The new wording, he said, adopted language from the federal Hate
Crimes Statistics Act that the governor's father signed into law as
president in 1990 &UR; . &LR;  The law refers to reporting requirements that
the attorney general tabulate crimes related to prejudice based on
race, religion, ethnicity or sexual orientation. But the law itself
apparently doesn't state those categories.
</P>
<P>
   Gearing up for the possible death of the bill, Senate and House
Democrats, their staff and supporters of the measure first held a
prayer vigil in the Capitol Rotunda instead of reporting to the
floor for the 10 a.m. call. Once they got to the floor, Senate
Democrats launched into a series of impassioned personal privilege
speeches.
</P>
<P>
   By noon, without having acted on a single piece of legislation,
the Senate had recessed into political caucuses. The day dragged on
as teams of Democrats and Republicans, occasionally including Lt.
Gov. Rick Perry, scurried in and out of meetings, writing and
rewriting the proposal. They were still at it nine hours later.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day Sen. John Whitmire, D-Houston, blamed
Republicans in general and Bush in particular for the stalemate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I beg you, governor, to get involved in this issue as you do
in tax reform,'' Whitmire said to hoots and applause at the Rotunda
prayer vigil. ``I ask that the lieutenant governor give us a vote
on the Senate floor. Get the leaders or our caucus and help.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
