<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALAXY SEEKING MISSING PIECES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA -- As Galaxy coach Sigi Schmid continues to say the
ship is holding strong -- he's not about to say it doesn't lack
deficiencies.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles misses post-up striker Carlos Hermosillo, it's been
unable to create the counters that made them so effective last
season and midfield playmaker Mauricio Cienfuegos needs to be more
involved in the attack.
</P>
<P>
   Other than that and their lack of a scoring punch, the Galaxy
(4-4, 6 points) is fine as it prepares to face Tampa Bay (3-4, 7
points) at the Rose Bowl this evening at 7:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, previously winless Kansas City (1-7) handed the
Galaxy a 2-1 defeat. It was the first loss for Schmid since he took
over the club last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously I'm not happy about losing, but when you look at the
game and look at the domination of the game, it wasn't a total
loss,'' Schmid said of the Galaxy's loss to the Wizards. ``We
created 11 corners, that means we're going forward. We had more
shots and more shots on goal than they did. So, from the standpoint
of being dangerous, I think we're getting there.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, only five goals in eight games?
</P>
<P>
   ``If we go six and seven more games and have the same results
then we have a real problem,'' said Schmid. ``But I'm confident
it's going to be better this weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   Schmid has the team working on finishing more than anything
else. But with strikers Welton, Clint Mathis and Cobi Jones all
small, finesse finishers, the Galaxy lacks size up front.
</P>
<P>
   And Hermosillo doesn't return from Mexico until next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can use some size up there for sure,'' said Schmid. ``Last
year the Galaxy countered against teams. This season teams are
taking away that countering space from us. They're dropping back.
And when a team takes away countering space, you need someone who
can hold the ball under pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   Cienfuegos, meanwhile, has been caught defending more than
distributing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Against Kansas City last week he got stuck back-tracking,''
said Schmid. ``We have to get him the ball in offensive
positions.''
</P>
<P>
   Against the Mutiny, Los Angeles needs to control the midfield,
particularly against Tampa Bay's Carlos Valderrama and Mauricio
Ramos.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you give those two time and space they can hurt you ...,''
said Schmid. ``If we can force those midfielders to defend, it will
be to our advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   GALAXY INFO BOX
</P>
<P>
   Today's game: Tampa Bay (3-4, 7 points) vs. Galaxy (4-4), Rose
Bowl, 7:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Television: None.
</P>
<P>
   Radio: KTNQ 1020-AM (Spanish); KRLA 1110-AM (English).
</P>
<P>
   Series history: First meeting this season; Galaxy leads
all-time, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
   Galaxy update: Except for a lack of a scoring punch, the Galaxy
didn't play that badly in last week's 2-1 loss to Kansas City. But
how is this for scoring comparisons? After eight games last season,
the Galaxy had 26 goals and five multiple-goal games. After eight
games this season, it has only five goals and no multiple-goal
games. Ouch. Clint Mathis, who has split time on the front line and
at midfield, returns to the lineup after serving a red-card
suspension. Former UCLA All-American striker Seth George, a
second-round college draft choice by the Galaxy last winter, is
expected in training camp next week. George had been training in
Germany, after signing a temporary contract with 1860 Munich of the
German Bundesliga.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay update: The Mutiny is 0-4 at the Rose Bowl, but is
going for their fourth consecutive victory after reacquiring
midfield playmaker Carlos Valderrama from Miami. Tampa is coming
off a 2-1 victory over MLS champion Chicago. Striker Musa Shannon,
the MLS Player of the Month for April, leads the club with five
goals and an assist.
</P>
<P>
   By Fred J. Robledo
</P>
</TEXT>
