<SLUG> BC-NY-POLITICAL-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITY COUNCIL REMATCH BREWS  
 WAITING IN THE WINGS  
 A POLITICAL CLUB WITH A TWIST 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JONATHAN P. HICKS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With elections for the state Legislature and Congress
a year away and New York City's next major municipal races a year
after that, 1999 is likely to be a pallid year in local politics.
But a heated rematch is shaping up in one corner of the city, a
City Council district that includes the center of Staten Island and
a slice of Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   In a special election in February, James Oddo took 53 percent of
the vote in a three-way race and won the seat vacated by John
Fusco, who had been elected Staten Island's surrogate, a judicial
position. By law, another election must be held later this year,
and Oddo, a Republican, is likely to face his major rival in that
earlier race: John Sollazzo, a Democratic district leader who ran
against Fusco for City Council in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Although Sollazzo received only 40 percent of the vote in the
special election in the 50th Council District, he said he was
convinced that he would do better this fall in the rematch. ``It
was a special election, and only 13 percent of the voters came
out,'' Sollazzo said. ``But this time we have more time to prepare
and we will have a larger turnout. This time we will have a strong
candidate at the top of the ticket.''
</P>
<P>
   Sollazzo referred to the race for Staten Island district
attorney, which will coincide with the City Council election. In
that race, the incumbent, William Murphy, a Democrat who beat the
Staten Island borough president, Guy Molinari, four years ago, will
face Catherine DiDomenico, a Republican lawyer who is counsel to
Vito Fossella, the U.S. representative.
</P>
<P>
   Although defeating an incumbent like Oddo is usually an uphill
battle, Staten Island Democrats suggest that this year's council
race represents their most fertile opportunity in years.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a tradition in politics that says that the best time
to beat an incumbent is his first time out,'' said Robert Gigante,
the chairman of the Democratic Party on Staten Island. ``Jimmy Oddo
has only been a councilman for a couple of months. Bill Murphy's
coattails will be helpful. It will be enough to pull this off.''
</P>
<P>
   Oddo said he had not begun thinking about the election. ``For
me, the best campaign strategy is to focus on doing my job,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Waiting in the Wings
</P>
<P>
   It is relatively rare for a member of the state Assembly to give
up his seat, particularly in a district where he is virtually
assured of re-election. So even a hint that an incumbent will
retire is enough to bring out potential successors.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Samuel Bea, 66, a Democrat who represents a district
in the northeastern section of the Bronx, says he has not decided
whether to seek a third term next year. But there is rampant
speculation in his district that he might retire from the Assembly
at the end of this term.
</P>
<P>
   That has inspired a number of politicians to say they are
contemplating running for the Assembly seat. One potential
candidate is Carl Heastie, 31, a Democratic state committeeman and
a budget analyst in the office of City Comptroller Alan Hevesi.
Heastie is a close political ally of state Sen. Larry Seabrook, a
dominant political figure in the district.
</P>
<P>
   Another potential candidate is Joey Jackson, 32, a lawyer who is
chairman of the Bronx Democratic County Committee. Jackson has
close ties with Assemblyman Roberto Ramirez, the Bronx Democratic
Party chairman. Another is Lethia Williams, a schoolteacher who is
heavily involved in civic organizations in the district.
</P>
<P>
   But the most prominent possibility is City Councilman Lawrence
Warden, 54, who has represented the district since 1992 and is
barred by term limits from seeking re-election to the council in
2001. ``With term limits in place now, I have to keep options
open,'' Warden said. ``It's certainly something I'm looking at.''
</P>
<P>
   All of that has the potential to create tension in the ranks of
the Northeast Bronx Democratic Club, of which all the prospective
candidates are members. Warden angered many club members in 1997
when he endorsed Mayor Rudolph Giuliani for re-election.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Sam does decide to retire, it will be quite an
unpredictable situation in our area,'' Seabrook said. ``There are a
lot of people who would like to be in the mix. It's going to be
interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   A Political Club With a Twist
</P>
<P>
   Typically, political clubs make their central mission the
advancement of a single party's candidates. Occasionally, however,
there are exceptions.
</P>
<P>
   One such anomaly is the new Caribbean and American United
Political Club, in the northeast Bronx. Hugh Beckford, one of its
leaders, said the organization would support both Democrats and
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not necessarily advocating for any political party,''
Beckford said. ``We will support candidates who are advocating what
is in the best interest of the community.''
</P>
<P>
   Another goal, he said, is to register a large number of
immigrants to vote in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the club does have aims that are decidedly traditional.
The club is considering running candidates from its ranks.
</P>
<P>
   Beckford himself, the director of a social-services agency in
the Bronx called Caribbean and American Family Services, said he
was considering running for office, although he was uncertain which
position.
</P>
<P>
   While the new organization could well provide some political
competition for Seabrook's club, which is the dominant Democratic
group in that section of the Bronx, the state senator dismissed
that possibility. ``To the extent that they will work for
Democratic victories,'' he said, ``we won't have any problem.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
