<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fire kills 11 racing horses in Ohio
 &HT;    By Margo Rutledge Kissell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Willard Miller stared into the charred rubble
where 11 harness racing horses died Thursday night after fire raced
through a barn at the Greene County Fairgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   The Jamestown man lost three horses in the blaze, including a
2-year-old colt who showed great promise and was to race for the
first time June 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the best thing I ever had. He was the kind you dream of
having,'' said the teary-eyed Miller, for whom the loss was as much
personal as financial.
</P>
<P>
   The state fire marshal spent Friday sifting through the rubble
but has not yet determined what caused the fire. Investigators have
not ruled out arson and are following possible leads, said Xenia
fire Lt. Jeff Leaming, who serves on the Greene County Fire
Investigation Task Force.
</P>
<P>
   Xenia fire Chief David Price set a preliminary damage loss
estimate at $700,000 and said a final amount would not be
determined until fire officials talked to all of the owners who
lost trotters and pacers in the fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a horseman's worst nightmare,'' said Virgil Wallace,
president of the Greene County Harness Horsemen's Association and
member of the fair board.
</P>
<P>
   As a few harness racers took their horses through the paces on
the nearby track, a backhoe dug a large hole in the infield where
the carcasses were buried. The large grave was just behind a
headstone memorializing 38 horses who died in a fire in an adjacent
horse barn in June 1984.
</P>
<P>
   That barn had been rebuilt and became threatened by Thursday
night's fire, whose flames leaped into the air about 30 feet away.
</P>
<P>
   Flames spread quickly through the 37-year-old barn filled with
hay and straw. Xenia firefighters who responded to the scene within
two minutes of receiving the first 911 call at 8:18 p.m. found the
structure engulfed in flames.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fire was coming out both ends of the barn
</P>
