<SLUG> BC-SUMMIT15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Aggressive trade policy called for at summit
 &HT;    By John Murawski
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CORAL SPRINGS, Fla. _ Speaking at the Florida Economic Summit on
Friday, Gov. Jeb Bush outlined some of his favorite economic
policies, including property tax cuts and universities raising
money by having professors do corporate research.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more you can connect research to the real world, the more
synergy you'll see,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   The summit is convened under state law three times a year, with
Friday's meeting being held at the Radisson Resort in Coral
Springs. It brings together lawmakers, economic development
officials, business people and chamber of commerce representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Summit discussions included Florida's role in international
trade. Sixteen panelists agreed that Florida's commitment to
international trade is eclipsed by the state's spending on
promoting tourism.
</P>
<P>
   ``This state ought to have an international trade policy
equivalent to a country,'' said Mike Fitzgerald, president of
Enterprise Florida's International Trade and Economic Development
Unit. ``We have one of the largest economies in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   As other panelists warned that Florida will lose out to other
states in the race to attract foreign trade, Rep. Carlos Valdes
(R-Miami) suggested the state create a new agency to promote
international business.
</P>
<P>
   But panelist Dick Nunis, an Enterprise Florida board member,
chastised Valdes for his proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you looking for another job?'' Nunis asked. ``We've had
too many organizations.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Rudolph Bradley (D-St. Petersburg) told Nunis his comments
were insulting.
</P>
<P>
   Though outnumbered, Nunis, who recently retired as chairman of
Walt Disney Attractions, refused to apologize.
</P>
<P>
   The three-times-a-year economic summit might soon be history. A
bill to reorganize Enterprise Florida, the state's business
promotion agency, would reduce the meeting requirement to once a
year. The bill has passed the legislature and is awaiting the
governor's signature. As recently as 1996, the law called for four
meetings a year.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's director of tourism, trade and economic development, J.
Antonio Villamil, said it's better to have small meetings dedicated
to focused topics, such as space or transportation, rather than
three general meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
