<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALMON HAS BEEN HERE BEFORE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ANDREW BAGGARLY  
 San Bernardino County Sun  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ Tim Salmon glanced down at his fiberglass-wrapped left
wrist, then looked up at the reporters encircling him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man, I've been here before,'' the Angels right fielder said
with sad smile.
</P>
<P>
   It was the worst kind of deja vu. For the second consecutive
year, Salmon was breaking out toward a monster season when injury
stopped it. Last year, a torn ligament in his foot landed him on
the disabled list for two weeks in May and hobbled him the rest of
the year. This time, a badly sprained wrist was the culprit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've become an expert on my foot and it looks like I'm going
to become an expert on my hand now, too,'' Salmon said.
</P>
<P>
   Salmon admitted he was shocked when results of an angiogram
showed a slight tear in the wrist, meaning it had to be immobilized
and would keep him out at least four to five weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought they'd poke around a little bit and say, `OK, you're
day-to-day.''' Salmon said. ``I was shellshocked. I wasn't able to
comprehend what they were telling me. My wife said, `Hey, you took
that news pretty good.' Well, I was dazed.''
</P>
<P>
   Salmon was batting .347 with a team-leading seven homers and 25
RBI when he injured the wrist on May 4 while attempting a sliding
catch. He's finally shed the slow-starter label. Now if he could
just make it through May without landing on the DL.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather have the slow starts and be healthy,'' Salmon said.
</P>
<P>
   Protecting Mo: Angels manager Terry Collins said he has no
reservations about leaving Garret Anderson in the cleanup spot
until Salmon returns.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson was hitting .301 entering Friday's game, and his seven
home runs are more than he usually has this early in the season.
But is he enough of a threat to keep opponents from pitching around
Vaughn?
</P>
<P>
   In typical fashion, Anderson said he won't change his approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter where I hit in the lineup,'' he said in a
flat voice. ``If you're a run producer, you drive in runs. You
either know how to do it or you don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Total body workout: Second baseman Randy Velarde said the
discomfort in his lower back is still there, though it's tolerable.
</P>
<P>
   Velarde started for the fourth consecutive game Friday after
missing five with a bulging disc.
</P>
<P>
   Velarde has a Mr. Olympian physique and spends more time in the
weight room than most players. Not enough time, as it turns out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did weight training for every part of the body, but I
neglected the small muscles of the spine and it caught up to me,''
Velarde said. ``If you don't take care of the small muscles, the
big ones take over and it causes instability.''
</P>
</TEXT>
