<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-METROSTARS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METROSTARS LOOK TO REGAIN SCORING TOUCH 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Scoring only one goal in the first four games at home is not
what the MetroStars had in mind in their attempt to lure soccer
fans to Giants Stadium. The MetroStars will enter Saturday night's
game against the Miami Fusion without having scored a goal in the
last 280 minutes of action at home.
</P>
<P>
   The primary reason for the MetroStars' lack of offensive
production is the absence of Tab Ramos, their most creative
midfielder, who has not played since the opening game of the season
because of an injury just below his right knee.
</P>
<P>
   Without Ramos in the lineup to provide quality service to
Eduardo Hurtado, the team's premier striker, the MetroStars (3-4)
have been starved for goals. And they may stay that way until Ramos
returns or until the team acquires its last foreign player. Ramos
assisted Hurtado on two goals in the opening-game victory in Miami
on March 20. While Ramos was missing the rest of the games, Hurtado
has one goal _ and that came from a penalty kick.
</P>
<P>
   The MetroStars have scored two other goals, by Mike Petke and
Nansha Kalonji, for a grand total of three in their last six games
_ not counting shootout goals, of course.
</P>
<P>
   After Thursday's practice at the team's training facility at
Kean University in Union, N.J., Ramos said that his injury was more
than nerve trauma below his right knee, as had been announced, and
that it also included a partial tear of a tendon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't find out that two-thirds of a tendon was torn until
four weeks later when I had an MRI,'' Ramos said after working
mostly on his own at Thursday's practice. ``I can kick the ball
with force now. I started doing that yesterday. But it bothers me
when I use the inside of my foot.''
</P>
<P>
   For about three weeks after his injury Ramos was in severe pain
every time he tried to kick the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt good when I started kicking with force yesterday,''
Ramos said Thursday. ``But I have no idea when I'll be ready to
play. They tell me I have to be patient. I will start working with
the team next week, and once I'm 100 percent I'll start playing a
little here and a little there before I can play a full game.''
</P>
<P>
   Without Ramos, it is becoming imperative for the MetroStars to
acquire the last foreign player they are due by the league. The
MetroStars have given the league a list of five players to choose
from, but their first choice appears to be Florin Raducioiu, a
29-year-old Romanian striker who plays in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   The MetroStars are in a desperate need of another striker to be
paired with Hurtado on the attack. Coach Bora Milutinovic has tried
Roy Myers of Costa Rica and Mark Chung as Hurtado's partner without
much success. Both are midfield playmakers rather than strikers.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night's game against the Fusion (3-5) will also serve
as a qualifier for the 1999 US. Open Cup. The winner will
automatically advance, while the loser will have to finish among
the league's top scoring teams to qualify for the next round.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
