<HEADER>
A8193 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN     05-14 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RICE WANTS MORE HELP FROM LAKERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A rout at the hands of the Houston Rockets left a bad
taste in the Lakers' mouths Thursday night. But they can clear
their palates with a simple culinary formula.
</P>
<P>
   Just add Rice.
</P>
<P>
   How do you know? Just ask the man.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like I've always been saying,'' Glen Rice said, ``we got
back to that standstill (stuff) out there. And if you look at the
second half, all I basically was doing was forcing up (3-pointers).
And that's not what I'm about, man.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice missed 8 of 13 shots in the Lakers' Game 3 playoff loss to
Houston, and that's not what he's about either. It was his worst
game in weeks.
</P>
<P>
   But Rice said _ and teammates agreed _ it was the Lakers'
stagnant offense that stunted his shooting performance. It's a
trend they need to reverse immediately to win Game 4 today and
close out the best-of-five series.
</P>
<P>
   When the Lakers took off on their recent six-game winning
streak, it was largely due to better player movement in their
offense, with plenty of screens set for Rice, who isn't comfortable
standing still waiting for shots.
</P>
<P>
   But the Lakers wilted under the Rockets' defensive pressure
Thursday and strayed from their game plan _ and lost for the first
time in seven games. It also left Rice hoisting up bad shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason we were going so well is we were moving the ball
around. We had the floor spread and we had guys running off
screens, and that's in my opinion what this team needs to do,''
Rice said.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Kurt Rambis agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did a good job taking us out of our sets, and we made a
lot of mistakes in terms of where we were supposed to get the ball
and who we were supposed to get the ball to,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And if the Lakers help Rice with movement and screens, they'll
help themselves handle Scottie Pippen. With Rice standing still,
Pippen expended no energy fighting past screens, and he was able to
conserve energy on defense. Presto, Pippen gets aggressive on
offense and scores 37 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got to keep that man tired,'' Rice said. ``If we allow him
to do what he did (Thursday) night, it's going to be a tough Game
5.''
</P>
<P>
   He meant Game 4, but if the Lakers don't adjust quickly, they'll
be facing elimination in Game 5 back in L.A.
</P>
<P>
   With a 2-1 lead in the series, the Lakers were far from
panicking Friday, but there was a clear sense the Rockets had put a
dent in their psyches with the 102-88 win. After all, the Lakers
hadn't lost since April 26 _ a 22-point loss to Houston. Since
then, they'd looked unbeatable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels like we hadn't lost in a while, so it felt kind of
awkward, it felt a little weird being in that situation,'' Kobe
Bryant said. ``But we just have to respond come Saturday....
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the formula for winning basketball, we just have to do
it every night. We just have to adjust well to their pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   They have to adjust to their aggressiveness as well. Allowing
the Rockets a 12-rebound advantage, and 19 offensive rebounds, is a
sure-fire formula for losing. But it's not every night that Charles
Barkley grabs 23 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a little upset with ourselves,'' Bryant said, ``because
we didn't go out there with the energy that we needed.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets, seemingly on the verge of collapse just days ago,
not only stayed alive in the series, they breathed new life into
their self-confidence. They now know the maligned Pippen can win
games and the Rockets can frustrate the Lakers' once-overpowering
offense.
</P>
<P>
   That's all a veteran team with three superstars needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to put them away. You don't want to give this team
any life, because they've done it before in the past,'' Bryant
said.
</P>
<P>
   Emotionally, the Lakers said they were unaffected. They exuded
their usual L.A. cool in the face of the Houston humidity. The only
overwhelming feeling was restlessness.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're anxious right now, we can't wait until (Saturday),''
Bryant said. ``We want to get out there and play. I think today is
like the slowest day in the world, because we're all anxious to get
out there and kind of get this thing over with.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
