<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 23:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8197 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT     05-14 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: ONE CRUISE ENDS, ANOTHER BEGINS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Pat Riley stood on a Carnival cruise ship in 1995 and
was introduced as the Miami Heat's $30 million Moses; the visionary
who would lead the team from the humiliation of losing to the NBA's
Promised Land.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, Miami is trying to avoid its own period in the
wilderness _ trying to avoid being eliminated by the Knicks for the
second straight year. After Friday night's 87-72 victory, the Heat
have a chance in Game 5 Sunday to avoid a humbling first-round
exit. Once again Friday night, Riley pulled a rabbit out of a hat.
</P>
<P>
   Riley's program, his credibility, will be on the line Sunday.
When he took over in Miami, Riley could have told the people he
could walk on water and they would have believed him. Today they
might ask, ``Can we see?''
</P>
<P>
   When he was asked what the significance of a lost series would
be, Riley said, ``Major.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a winning team; we're building a good program down
there,'' he said. ``But this isn't good at all.''
</P>
<P>
   You'd like to think that a game is a game, a series a series.
But the venom that surrounds this series underlines the credibility
at stake. Less so for Jeff Van Gundy of the Knicks, who is in the
beginning of his head coaching career, than for Riley, whose best
work is behind him.
</P>
<P>
   A year after he was introduced in Miami, Riley lost Juwan
Howard, the Washington forward he was trying to sign as a free
agent. Riley felt Howard could have put the Heat over the top.
</P>
<P>
   The league negated the deal, saying the Heat did not have room
under the salary cap to sign him. The league charged that incentive
bonuses in the contracts of Tim Hardaway and P.J. Brown should have
been counted against the salary cap by Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Riley was counting on getting Howard, and to make room for him,
Riley got rid of, among others, Kevin Willis, now playing well in
Toronto; Glen Rice, a tremendous weapon for the Lakers, and Matt
Geiger, playing well at center in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   The Heat are left with a wagon whose wheels have been run off.
For the Knicks, losing this series wouldn't be any more cataclysmic
than what this season has already been. Factions formed, causing
divisions and rancor that spilled over from the front office to the
locker room. The president of the team was demoted, and an ongoing
debate developed over whether Van Gundy should stay or go, or
whether the Knicks should walk or run.
</P>
<P>
   Even a series victory over Miami would bring the Knicks back to
where they were last season, when they defeated Miami, three games
to two, in the first round. The Knicks have not gone beyond the
second round since 1993-94.
</P>
<P>
   In Miami, there has never been a debate over Riley's status.
It's exalted. Period. He is Moses, though a loss to the Knicks may
prompt some of the bolder members of the flock to wonder if Riley
really knows where he is going.
</P>
<P>
   Riley has been associated with the NBA for 32 years: as a
journeyman player, a broadcaster, an assistant and then a head
coach. In that time, he has been a part of six NBA titles.
</P>
<P>
   Riley's credibility bankroll is hefty, but a loss to the Knicks
would cost him a big chunk of it. Regardless who wins, this series
will bring a four-year-old drama full circle. Riley left New York
as the loser, more or less, in a struggle that saw Ernie Grunfeld
emerge as the winner and team president.
</P>
<P>
   Now Riley, as president of the Heat, is at risk of being
defeated by players Grunfeld brought to the Knicks; Riley is losing
with players he brought to the Heat: Brown, Hardaway, Alonzo
Mourning and Dan Majerle.
</P>
<P>
   Riley quickly points out that Miami's pilgrimage is just
beginning. The Knicks played their first season in 1946-47 and
didn't win their first championship for 23 seasons. They have not
won a championship in 26 years. Beyond that, Madison Square Garden
has been part of New York's sports culture since 1879, this actual
building since 1968.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami franchise and Miami Arena _ which taxpayers paid for _
are 11 years old. Now Riley must persuade the public to buy into a
new arena, the centerpiece of a slick, 70-acre complex near the
Port of Miami. Plans for the complex include the expansion of the
port that benefits the Carnival Cruise Lines owned by Micky Arison,
who also owns the Heat. The chief architect of the new arena's
financial plan is P. Anthony Ridder, chairman of Knight-Ridder,
which owns The Miami Herald.
</P>
<P>
   Riley is Arison's Moses, but you wonder after a series like this
that exposed so many flaws and weaknesses whether Riley will suffer
the same fate _ lead the Heat and their followers to the Promised
Land but never cross into it with them. Lots of holes to fill and
lots of seats to fill. For the time being, the Heat is nearing the
wilderness and Van Gundy is out of the woods. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-14-99 2319EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
