u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-HEAT-ART-N     05-14 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-HEAT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS ARE UNABLE TO EXTINGUISH THE HEAT'S FLAME 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a startling turnabout, the Miami Heat used the
3-point touch that had deserted it in Game 3 and overwhelmed the
New York Knicks during a 41-15 run in the second half Friday night
at Madison Square Garden to win Game 4, 87-72, and force a deciding
game Saturday afternoon in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Such a scenario seemed unthinkable in the third quarter, after
the Knicks held a 62-58 lead. The Heat's desire took over as it
weathered a 22-5 run. Scrambling for loose balls and rebounds, it
made up an 11-point third-quarter deficit and rallied to take the
lead, 67-64, on a 3-pointer from a suddenly resurgent Tim Hardaway
with seven minutes 57 seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Hardaway, who had all but disappeared in this
three-of-five-games series because of a sore knee and suspect
confidence, delivered another 3-pointer off a drive-and-kick by
Terry Porter, who caught Charlie Ward off his guard. Porter
penetrated and found the open Hardaway, who drilled the 3-pointer
to give the Heat a 74-66 lead with 5:23 left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   After a turnover by Larry Johnson on his drive to the basket,
Porter was left open in transition for his 3-pointer to provide the
Heat with a 77-66 lead with 4:10 left. That lead ballooned to 19
points with three minutes left.
</P>
<P>
   During that same stretch, the Knicks were 2 for 10 with 6
turnovers. All that had gone right for them in Game 3 went terribly
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Hardaway finished with 14 points, and Alonzo Mourning had 16
points and 14 rebounds. Porter chipped in with 16 points off the
bench.
</P>
<P>
   Allan Houston and Ward scored 12 each for the Knicks, who shot 2
for 13 in the fourth quarter and were outscored, 29-10.
</P>
<P>
   The way the momentum swung from the second quarter into the
third was hauntingly familiar for the Heat. As its shots ricocheted
off the rim, the Knicks took the misses and overwhelmed Miami in
transition. The Knicks trotted off on a 22-5 run from the second
quarter into the third on the wings of 3-pointers from Ward and
Johnson to take a 51-40 lead with nine minutes left in the third.
</P>
<P>
   In Game 3, the Knicks broke open the game with a 32-2 run. But
just as this run approached that kind of roll, Ward had to leave
the game. He dived for his own turnover and banged the left side of
his head into the knee of Dan Majerle with 9:49 left in the third.
Ward went to the locker room, where he had medical glue put on the
cut near his left eye.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks missed him as the Heat did something it did not do in
Game 3: Miami rode Mourning and mounted a comeback to pull within
4, 51-47. A 3-pointer by Johnson stopped the Heat's minirun with
6:30 left. But this game was not going to be decided as quickly and
as easily as the previous blowouts in this series.
</P>
<P>
   The tension was thick as both teams went tit for tat as the
third quarter wound down. Each time the Heat inched within 3 to 5
points of the Knicks, there was Houston to hit a jumper or a free
throw.
</P>
<P>
   Voshon Lenard tossed up a 3-pointer as the shot clock ran and
that pulled the Heat within 2 points with 50 seconds left in the
third. But an active Latrell Sprewell sprang between two Heat big
men and came up with a rebound and put-back to give the Knicks a
62-58 lead after three quarters.
</P>
<P>
   The Heat came out like a team desperate but not out of control.
Methodically it carved a 7-point lead early in the second quarter
by sinking the 3-point shot that had escaped it in Games 1 and 3.
But just as in Game 3, the Knicks found a way to take the edge off
the Heat before the first half closed.
</P>
<P>
   In Game 3 it was Sprewell who came in and stirred his team. This
time it was Ward, who hit all three 3-pointers he attempted in the
first half and put his body in peril to bring the Knicks back to
life and help provide a 44-40 lead before the break.
</P>
<P>
   With 4:56 left in the second quarter, Ward drove the lane,
careened off the chest of P.J. Brown, crashed to the floor and
brought the fans to their feet. He hit one of two free throws. Two
possessions later, with the shot clock running down, he took off in
front of Hardaway and nailed a 3-pointer to tie the game, 37-37.
</P>
<P>
   After the Knicks overwhelmed the Heat in Game 3 with a 12-0 run
to close out the first half, they provided an encore with a 15-5
run. The half was capped when Johnson missed a 3-pointer, gathered
his rebound and went in for a layup at the buzzer.
</P>
<P>
   As it has throughout the series, the Heat started out executing
its game plan well. Although Mourning, Brown and Majerle found foul
trouble early and were on the bench more often than not, the Heat
rediscovered the cold-blooded shooting of the limping Hardaway.
</P>
<P>
   He had made just one of his first 15 3-point attempts in this
series, but found his groove in the face of Childs. He dribbled in
front of Childs, pulled up and hit two consecutive 3s in the first
quarter. Earlier in the day, Hardaway was fined $5,000 for verbal
abuse of officials and refusing to leave the court in a timely
fashion after his ejection from Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   Miami coach Pat Riley also dusted off another 3-point artist.
Lenard, whose playing time in this series had been limited to a
cameo in the blowouts, delivered as well. The Heat, finding success
from 3-point range, took a 25-24 lead after the first quarter and
extended its lead to 7 points early in the second.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
