<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-PHILLIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS BLUNT PHILLIES, 7-3 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ They had stumbled into Philadephia, reeling and
wrung out, insisting they were not worried about their slump but
slipping behind the streaking Phillies in the standings all the
same. But like fireworks that illuminate even the heaviest clouds,
the New York Mets' hitters unleashed a bombardment that lifted them
to a 7-3 victory Friday night over the Phillies.
</P>
<P>
   Combined with another disciplined outing by Masato Yoshii, the
victory jolted the Mets out of the doldrums that had engulfed them
during their 2-4 slide in Arizona and Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   John Olerud, Robin Ventura and Edgardo Alfonzo all hit home runs
_ Olerud's and Ventura's were both two-run shots in the first
inning _ to boost the Mets to a 5-1 lead by the third. Olerud's
blast was only the 14th that ever reached the upper deck of
Veterans Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Yoshii, who had pitched six shutout innings in each of his last
two starts, had allowed only a solo inside-the-park homer by Bobby
Abreu to that point and seemed firmly in control of the game,
allowing just one other runner to reach second base and getting
ahead on most hitters. His fastball was regularly in the '90s, an
uptick that Manager Bobby Valentine has attributed to a slight
change in Yoshii's mechanics. With the new success has come an
increased aggressiveness and confidence from the pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I go up there, I'm trying to be as aggressive as
possible,'' Yoshii said. ``I'm pitching the same as usual. Nothing
has changed.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Mets added another run in the top of the fifth inning,
Phillies starter Chad Ogea was gone, the former Met Yorkis Perez
was trying to prevent a blowout and Valentine was leaning back on
his bench in satisfaction. The Mets scored the run thanks to the
leadoff hitter Roger Cedeno, who showed the speed of a sprinter in
stealing four bases Friday night. He hit an infield single, then
stole second, advanced to third on an Alfonzo fly ball and scored
on Olerud's sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine has given Cedeno, who is filling in for Rickey
Henderson and has 14 stolen bases, the green light to go whenever
he gets on base. Like Cedeno, the Mets read all the signs correctly
Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Speed and power, that was all our runs,'' Valentine said. ``It
was a well-balanced attack, guys hitting the ball hard and Roger on
the bases.''
</P>
<P>
   But starting pitching has given the Mets fits this season, and
in the bottom of the fifth, Yoshii flirted with disaster. He
yielded a leadoff homer to pinch hitter Dave Doster, whose shot hit
the left-field foul pole. Three batters later, Scott Rolen sent a
2-2 pitch against the left-field scoreboard to narrow the Mets'
edge to 6-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made a couple of mistakes and they hit the foul pole,''
Valentine said of his starting pitcher. ``He was fabulous, making
pitches, keeping them off stride. He came up big. When he keeps the
ball down, he's a good major league pitcher.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentine let Yoshii bat in the sixth, and his pitcher redeemed
his decision in the bottom half of the inning. Yoshii struck out
Ron Gant, got Abreu to ground out and forced Mike Lieberthal to pop
up to Olerud. It was all Valentine could ask of his starter, and
better than the Mets' manager has received recently from the rest
of his rotation. In six innings, Yoshii gave up three runs on five
hits _ the three solo homers did the damage _ with two walks and
four strikeouts. The pitcher who two weeks ago was battling for his
job baffled a team that went 5-1 on its recent road trip while
hitting .336 with 15 home runs and 44 runs scored.
</P>
<P>
   ``He worked hard on his mechanics,'' Valentine said. ``He knows
when he has it. And he flaunts it when he does.''
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ BOBBY JONES will start Monday after he threw Friday and
reported no problems after his session. Jones has had soreness in
his elbow and tingling in his fingers, but he was pleased with his
performance in a series of tests the team gave him. ``That eased my
mind,'' Jones said. ``There's still a little swelling, but nothing
drastic.'' RICK REED will pitch Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Mets purchased the contract of pitcher PAT MAHOMES from
Class AAA Norfolk. To make room for Mahomes on the 40-man roster,
the Mets transferred outfielder JAY PAYTON to the 60-day disabled
list, retroactive to opening day. At Norfolk, Mahomes was 4-1 with
a 3.49 earned run average in six starts. In 382/3 innings, he
allowed 38 hits, 17 runs (15 earned), with 12 walks and 24
strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   _ RICKEY HENDERSON, hampered by a strained right knee, ran in
the outfield Friday and will likely be ready to play Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   _ Pitcher JOSIAS MANZANILLO will accept his assignment to
Norfolk while reserving the right to dispute the assignment.
Manzanillo told the Mets he had a sore right elbow, but general
manager STEVE PHILLIPS says Manzanillo didn't mention it until told
of the assignment.
</P>
<P>
   _ Entering the game, the Mets led the National League with a
.989 fielding average. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
