<HEADER>
A8220 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-VOTE15-COX     05-14 1273
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-VOTE15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Election airlift grounded for South Florida Israelis
 &HT;    By Douglas Belkin
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Israelis in South Florida hoping to cast
their vote for the next prime minster Monday afternoon had their
cut-rate round-trip tickets to Israel yanked hours before they were
set to depart in what is either a massive display of
disorganization or distrust by the politically motivated parties
that arranged the flights.
</P>
<P>
   The hotly contested race for prime minster between conservative
incumbent Benjamin Netanyahu and Labor Party Leader Ehud Barak was
expected to draw between 10,000 and 15,000 Israeli-Americans back
to the Middle East to vote.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli political parties desperate for an edge had heavily
subsidized the flights. Prices for round-trip tickets that normally
sell for up to $2,000 were cut by as much as 90 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But on Thursday and Friday, as flights were supposed to depart
from Miami, many were canceled either because organizers overbooked
the charters or because rival political factions believed members
loyal to the opposition party had bought seats to vote for the
wrong candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they realized there was too much risk in taking
people,'' said Avi Tansman, who is from a suburb of TelAviv and has
lived in Boca Raton for ten years. ``They don't know us and it's
much easier to go to Brooklyn and take the masses (who support
Likud).''
</P>
<P>
   Said an Israeli-born doctor who lives in Boca Raton and whose
flight was canceled Friday afternoon: ``I think they were just
overwhelmed. They had too many people who wanted to get on those
flights.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the flights were organized in numbers never before seen,
the phenomenon the Israeli press dubbed the ``election airlift'' is
not entirely new. In the 1996 election, several thousand, mostly
ultra-Orthodox right-wing Jews from Brooklyn flew to Israel to back
the Likud Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hasidim have always gone over in a small number and some
Israelis, particularly people who served in wars have gone,'' said
Bill Gralnick, South-Central Florida Director of the American
Jewish Committee. ``It's never been significant, but in the last
couple of elections there has been a big influence of American
money and more and more of a media ripple effect.''
</P>
<P>
   Israelis use U.S. strategies
</P>
<P>
   Part of that ripple effect has come from Israeli politicians
employing American strategies and American strategists, Gralnick
said. For instance, James Carville, President Clinton's campaign
manager, is running Barak's campaign, using a strategy of
repetition, focus and simplicity that was nowhere to be found in
Israeli political campaigns of 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure to get the most effective strategists has
intensified this year in the wake of Netanyahu's upset victory in
1996. Netanyahu defeated Shimon Peres by 29,457 votes out of about
3 million. The expatriate population began to be understood as
critical. Strategists, desperate for any additional edge, began to
look abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Israeli community, there has been a buzz about this for
a while,'' said Chuck Reddy, the executive director of the
nonpartisan Florida-Israel Chamber of Commerce. ``As the issue of
Jerusalem comes up and the debate gets more intense, people are
following it. They say, `I was going to go home in July anyway,
instead I'll go in May.'''
</P>
<P>
   There are approximately 300,000 Israelis living in America and
30,000 in South Florida, according to estimates by the Florida
Israel Chamber of Commerce. Thousands of others are expected to fly
from Europe, most notably from Germany and France.
</P>
<P>
   At stake, according to observers of Middle Eastern politics, is
the posture of the Israeli government toward the peace process with
Palestinians, and by extension, the stability of the region.
</P>
<P>
   ``Virtually every Israeli living here has family in Israel,''
said Itzhak Asher, a Boca Raton sculptor and dual citizen who said
he will be flying to Israel in June to vote in the predicted runoff
between Netanyahu and Barak. ``This is our only way to make our
voices heard.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Americans, Israelis living abroad are not allowed to vote
through absentee ballots unless they are away on official
government business. And unlike Americans, who rarely muster an
electoral turnout greater than 50 percent, nearly 80 percent of
Israelis of voting age traditionally cast ballots.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets sold out for weeks
</P>
<P>
   Round-trip tickets from Miami that typically cost $1,000 have
been discounted to $765 by the government-run airline, El Al,
according to El Al sales representative John Balcer of Miami.
Politically backed charters have been advertised for as low as
$180. The catch is tickets generally are for flights that arrive
the day of or the day before the election, and return two or three
days later. Tickets went on sale in March and April and have been
sold out for weeks according to travelers and representatives from
El Al, which flies from New York; Newark, N.J.; Chicago; Los
Angeles; Miami; Baltimore and Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   Though most people know that the subsidy is coming from the two
largest political parties through Kesher on the left and Chai
L'Yisrael on the right, the groups advertise in Jewish and Hebrew
publications that the fares are for any Israeli registered to vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hear about these trips through friends,'' said Sam Ballen,
a Boca Raton lawyer who holds dual citizenship but will not be
returning to Israel to vote because he waited too late to book a
flight. ``All you need to get a ticket is a passport and to be
registered, but it's understood who is sponsoring the trips.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the two groups, political analysts say Chai L'Yisrael has
chartered more flights and raised more money to subsidize them.
Kesher offered flights for $450 and Chai L'Yisrael for under $200.
</P>
<P>
   `Maybe they identified me'
</P>
<P>
   Until a few days ago, the election seemed almost certain to
result in a runoff to be held in June but a surge by Barak in the
polls late this week shook the confidence of Netanyahu's supporters
and may have added to the cancellation of trips from Miami and for
good reason.
</P>
<P>
   Tansman, for instance, bought a ticket for $195 from Miami to
Tel Aviv on a Likud-linked charter but he is an ardent Barak
supporter. ``Maybe they identified me, maybe they got overwhelmed
because Netanyahu is behind in the polls. At this point, it's
confusion.''
</P>
<P>
   Reservation line overwhelmed
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the answering machine at the toll free number for the
Chai L'Yisrael reservation line sounds almost comically overwhelmed
and repeated several times: ``If you have made a reservation, we
will contact you shortly. Please be patient. We will contact you
shortly. Please do not call this number again. We will contact you
shortly.''
</P>
<P>
   The election airlift strategy, which has been widely reported in
the Israeli press, has angered some Israelis who feel voters living
abroad are not invested in their country, do not know what's going
on and should not be allowed to vote if they do not live there.
</P>
<P>
   Asher, 53, acknowledged the anger but is adamant about his stake
in the election. A veteran of three wars, Asher said he reads three
Israeli papers once a week, lives in Israel for five months a year
and speaks to his two daughters in Caesarea three times a week.
</P>
<P>
   `Too much at stake'
</P>
<P>
   ``There is too much at stake,'' said Asher, who said he plans to
vote for Barak. ``I really want to make sure that my small voice
contributes to the issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
